<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEALING NOT A CRIME _ HONEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Imagine the conversation with Jimmy Sheckard, if
Sheckard were alive and not rolling over in his grave because of
the sad state of the Los Angeles Dodgers' running game.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy, how many bases would you steal if you were playing today?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard to say a number. But I'd lead the Dodgers in steals,
that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd only lead the Dodgers? Not the whole National League?
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the Dodgers. Hey, I'm 121 years old!''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Sheckard was a 67-base stealer at the turn of the LAST
century, a little Brooklyn outfielder who dueled with Honus Wagner
and Frank Chance for the league lead. The Dodgers' long tradition
of footspeed and daring began with him.
</P>
<P>
   It continued with Pete Reiser, Arky Vaughan, Jackie Robinson and
Pee Wee Reese. It peaked with Maury Wills, Davey Lopes and Steve
Sax. It lived on in Eric Young and Raul Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   It has died with the 2000 Dodgers. The numbers say they couldn't
steal a base if you gave them a ski mask and a getaway limo.
</P>
<P>
   The six Dodgers who have batted leadoff this season have stolen
13 bases, total. That's how many Wills swiped in a week. The rest
of the Dodgers have stolen 36.
</P>
<P>
   The team ranks 13th in its 16-team league in steals. It's on its
slowest pace since the 1989 team that had just said goodbye to Sax
and lost Kirk Gibson for most of the year with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Two things the Dodgers could always do, decade after decade, it
seemed. They could pitch. And they could run.
</P>
<P>
   The decline of their pitching has been beaten to death. What of
their running?
</P>
<P>
   Last season they were second in the major leagues with 167
steals. Davey Johnson, reared in the pitching-and-three-run-homers
philosophy of Earl Weaver, forced himself to manage more
aggressively than usual, seeing the need to manufacture runs.
</P>
<P>
   Then Young (51 steals) was traded to the Chicago Cubs and Raul
Mondesi (36) was traded to the Toronto Blue Jays. Then Devon White
(19) went on the disabled list in May.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has gone back to waiting for the three-run homer. And
while Gary Sheffield and Eric Karros have made that strategy look
good so far, you wonder if it's the answer for a team that plays
half its games at Dodger Stadium, never before a home run hitters'
park.
</P>
<P>
   As on many topics, you can find different thinking on this in
the Dodgers braintrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think bases are stolen to give yourself an advantage. Just
to steal to be stealing doesn't make a whole lot of sense to me,''
said Jim Tracy, the coach who is managing the team while Johnson is
hospitalized with an irregular heartbeat. ``I think it (depends on)
the type of ballclub you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Malone, the general manager, knew he was giving up speed
when he traded away Young (to improve the defense) and Mondesi (to
improve the clubhouse atmosphere). But Malone didn't envision the
collection of statues that takes the field these days in the
uniform of Robinson, Wills and Lopes. Only Shawn Green (15 steals),
Todd Hollandsworth (9) and Mark Grudzielanek (8) are on pace to
match their 1999 totals.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, a one-time 25-steals man, got his second during the
Dodgers' 8-6 loss to the Pittsburgh Pirates Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a matter of philosophy,'' Malone said this week.
``Davey and I talk about it a lot. Davey doesn't want to give away
outs (risking having runners thrown out). That's Davey's
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers are 21-11 when they steal at least one base, 7-6
when they attempt at least one steal but fail, and only 19-28 when
they don't attempt a steal. They're averaging nearly 7 runs a game
when they steal, only 4 when they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Their record when they steal is better than their record when
they homer (39-27).
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that they seem to be looking for opportunities
to run.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the Dodgers led the Pirates 5-3 with two out in
the bottom of the seventh inning. Adrian Beltre and Chad Kreuter
singled to bring up Kevin Elster. Tracy said later that he had left
the decision whether to steal up to Beltre. The interim manager was
willing to risk an out that would take the bat out of Elster's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre broke for third, and Pirates reliever Marc Wilkins, in
his haste to get the ball to the plate, bounced it for a wild pitch
that got Kreuter to second. After Elster walked, Jim Leyritz
singled home Beltre and Kreuter for runs that turned out to matter
in a 9-6 Dodgers victory.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre's steal was the kind of aggressive move the Dodgers have
made too rarely this season, one of those ``little things'' they
keep talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll see more of that in the second half. I think
we're just going to do everything we can to win ballgames,'' Malone
said.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, in case they've forgotten, it is possible to hit a
lot of home runs and steal a lot of bases in the same season. Jimmy
Sheckard led the league in both, but that was 97 years ago. These
days the Dodgers might not be able to sign him, so trade him to
Florida instead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
