<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS CAN'T SEE THE LIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ By the time you read this, Mike Judd will be gone,
back to Albuquerque after getting scorched Tuesday afternoon in the
big-league sun.
</P>
<P>
   His one-day Los Angeles Dodgers teammates, however, are still
here, left wondering where the momentum went in an 8-6 loss to the
Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   They had won the first two games of the series to move into
third place and had extended the Pirates' losing streak to six. But
Jeff Shaw isn't the only one who has had trouble closing out teams
this season. The Dodgers haven't swept a three-game series since
May 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we didn't sweep,'' acting manager Jim Tracy said. ``But we
did take two of three. I'll take that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodger Stadium crowd of 34,872 had trouble buying four
errors, which could have been five when Gary Sheffield lost John
Vander Wal's eighth-inning liner in the sun. Vander Wal was
credited with a double, but the boos told a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who has become one of the team's most popular
players, leads the majors with 32 homers, but he got an earful,
too, just like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who are only 22-22 at home, loaded the bases in the
seventh but didn't score. The eighth might have been even more
painful after reserve catcher Paul LoDuca opened with a single. The
Dodgers had the heart of their order coming up, but Sheffield,
Shawn Green and Eric Karros couldn't get LoDuca past first.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had a built-in excuse of having to turn to a minor-
leaguer to fill the spot of suspended Carlos Perez, who despite his
own problems this year has an ERA under three in his last five
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Judd, who has failed in brief callups the previous two years,
impressed pitching coach Claude Osteen warming up in the bullpen.
That all changed when Judd walked Warren Morris to open the first,
then hit Jason Kendall and gave up a three-run homer to Wil
Cordero. The Pirates added two more in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a good arm, I don't know how long it is going to take
to get over this hump and have a little more confidence in
himself,'' Osteen said. ``A couple of times Paul came back to the
bench after an inning and said, `When he gets ahead of the hitters,
they aren't hitting him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It looked like Judd might get bailed out when the Dodgers scored
six runs in the third.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. The Pirates went back on top in the fifth when
Morris walked and Kendall homered to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home runs happen,'' Tracy said. ``The problem is putting guys
on base before the home runs. That's what put us in a hole. At one
time they had seven runs on four hits. There's the answer to this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca, who caught Judd in the minors, said the early runs shook
the pitcher's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that he wanted to do well and maybe he put too much
pressure on himself,'' LoDuca said. ``But this guy is going to win
some games in the big leagues. He has too good a stuff not to.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for the team, which opens a two-game
series tonight against Colorado, the team that took back third
place Tuesday by routing Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had two six-run innings in this series. The first
led to a victory Sunday night, but Tuesday's only brought more
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who has been battling a slump the past month, had a
two-run double off Pirates starter Todd Ritchie. Green just made
contact on a 1-2 breaking ball to stay alive, then drove the next
pitch, sailing it over Vander Wal's head in right.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the inning, Karros had a two-run single and shortstop
Kevin Elster gave the Dodgers a 6-5 lead with a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   It was Green, though, who made Tracy smile. After an exciting
first two months with the team, Green has gone into a tailspin.
Earlier this month he had an 0-for-17 slump and entered Tuesday's
game just 3 for 20 on the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   But he had a game-tying RBI single against the Angels last week
in an extra-inning, come-from-behind victory. Monday night, he had
a triple. And even though he was thrown out attempting an
inside-the-park homer, the crowd gave him a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be there for us,'' Tracy said. ``It doesn't happen
overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Or in the afternoon sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
