f a BC-HEASTER-KAN &LR;      07-19 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Big Tobacco a victim of big injustice  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ The $145 billion punitive-damage award against
cigarette makers exposes tort law for the fraud it has become.
</P>
<P>
   This case is, pure and simple, a grotesque example of legal
immorality. It represents a legal lynching.
</P>
<P>
   A Philip Morris executive defined the crux of the problem by
noting that those making ``informed choices about smoking should
not be rewarded for choosing to smoke.'' Speaking on behalf of
former smokers unwilling to be a party to legal larceny, I think
he's absolutely right.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force behind this shameful perversion of tort law is
the big lie holding that manufacturers misled smokers concerning
smoking's health risks. Many of those seeking to get into Big
Tobacco's deep pockets may have told themselves this lie so often
that they actually believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever ills tobacco causes, its bad ends cannot justify the
legal looting of the tobacco industry. Big Tobacco is in the very
legal business of producing something demanded by hundreds of
millions of people throughout the world. Despite this, it is denied
the basic constitutional protections afforded even the most heinous
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, anyone who has ever smoked has been reminded
constantly that ``coffin nails'' and ``cancer sticks'' may be
terminally bad for them. My paternal grandfather, a heavy smoker
who died at 75 in 1950, tried to warn me off cigarettes many times
with the admonition, ``Jerry, these things will kill you.'' His
frequent coughing-wheezing fits underscored his message.
</P>
<P>
   Granddad's warnings were ignored, because although smokers know
the risk, they decide the trade-off of enjoyment provided by
tobacco is acceptable. Nearly all, it's safe to say, do so thinking
they are bulletproof.
</P>
<P>
   As if this weakness wasn't bad enough, Americans rejected the
concept of personal responsibility for their actions. Once enough
of the population could agree that nothing was ever the fault of
the individual, the tobacco companies became ripe for the
demonization that would justify their looting.
</P>
<P>
   The winning lawyer announced piously at a victory news
conference that ``this isn't about money,'' but this is precisely
what it's about. It's not about justice or righteousness. It's
about money.
</P>
<P>
   Only money's lure could cause smokers to accept the
rationalization that tobacco causes all their maladies. The human
body is a complex mechanism. Some people smoke their entire lives
without resulting disease or debilitation. Some live lives of
abstinence and still die of ailments routinely associated with
tobacco use.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the legal system has been perverted to the point
of pretending not only that virtually all smokers suffer
afflictions caused exclusively by tobacco use, but also that all
these plaintiffs are blameless victims in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Society, meanwhile, pretends the money comes from the ``evil''
tobacco companies. In fact, the industry is merely a transfer agent
for its customers, who are paying more and more for their smokes.
</P>
<P>
   So, as long as we're so eager to abuse the legal system in
pursuit of ill-gotten gain, here's a new wrinkle to consider: Why
shouldn't smokers sue those involved in tobacco lawsuits for the
economic damage suffered by skyrocketing cigarette prices?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
