<SLUG> BC-EURO-KAN </SLUG>
  
 American Century Investments invests in Euronet Services  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ The venture capital arm of American Century
Investments has invested $6 million in Leawood-based Euronet
Services Inc. through a private purchase of Euronet stock, the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Euronet operates a network of automated teller machines, mostly
in Europe. Euronet, which is publicly owned, sold a 4.9 percent
stake to American Century Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Henry, co-founder and chief operating officer of Euronet,
said the company didn't need to raise the cash but valued the
strategic link to American Century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategic value of their investment far outweighed the
dollar value of their investment,'' Henry said. ``We were not in a
desperate need for that cash.''
</P>
<P>
   American Century, the Kansas City-based mutual fund company,
created American Century Ventures earlier this year. Its mission is
not merely to make financial bets. It invests in companies in which
American Century sees a strategic gain, such as using and helping
to further develop those companies' products or services.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Mulcahy, vice president of American Century Ventures, said
the company is interested in Euronet's global distribution in
financial services and particularly its wireless applications.
</P>
<P>
   Euronet's ATM network offers transactions beyond cash
withdrawals, transfers and account balances. It also recently
introduced Arrowz Wireless Banking, which allows customers to
access banking information with their mobile phones, and Arrowz
Event Messaging.
</P>
<P>
   American Century Ventures has made 10 such investments,
including one in RecordsCenter.com, which is based in Kansas City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
