</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVEREST-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Everest Connections to begin area cable construction today  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANAS CITY _ Everest Connections Inc. today will begin building
its fiberoptic network to provide cable TV, local and long-distance
telephone service, and high-speed Internet connections in the
Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   The company said construction of the network will begin today in
Lenexa and expand to Kansas City next month. An Everest executive
said it should have its first Lenexa subscribers by October and its
first Kansas City customers by November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beginning construction is a milestone for us,'' said Steve
Gaul, Everest's general manager for the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   Construction comes three months after Everest announced that the
Kansas City area would be its first market. Subsequently, the
company has decided to also enter the Minneapolis and Tulsa, Okla.,
markets. UtiliCorp United Inc., the international utility and
energy trading company based in Kansas City, is an Everest partner.
</P>
<P>
   The start of construction for Everest is another indication that
the Telecommunications Act of 1996 is beginning to bear fruit. The
federal law made it easier for competitors to enter the business
against such companies as Southwestern Bell and Time Warner Cable.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Anderson, vice president of UtiliCorp Communication
Services, a UtiliCorp subsidiary, said Everest and another
UtiliCorp affiliate eventually will give consumers in much of
western Missouri a choice of cable TV services and a wider choice
in telecommunications and high-speed Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Everest has not released prices for its services but has said
they will be competitive and save customers of its full package 20
percent to 30 percent compared with today's prices for such
services.
</P>
<P>
   Another company _ Digital Access Inc. _ has similar plans to
offer a bundle of cable TV and telecommunications services to
Kansas City area consumers. But Digital Access executives have
scaled back the company's original plans to serve the entire area
because, they have said, it's not profitable for two companies to
build networks in the same neighborhoods and seek the same
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it will concentrate initially on Johnson County. A
Digital Access spokesman said Tuesday that no date has been set to
begin construction but that it is continuing with its plans _
including building in Lenexa.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, Lenexa is still a go,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Everest and Digital Access have received franchise agreements to
offer telecommunications in Lenexa, which has a separate
application process for cable TV. Everest so far has a franchise
agreement to offer cable TV and telecommunications in Kansas City
and cable TV in Mission.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have other franchises pending. Everest is seeking
agreements in Kansas City, Kan.; Leawood; Olathe; Merriam; Mission
Hills; Overland Park; Prairie Village; Shawnee; Westwood; Blue
Springs; Grandview; Independence; Lee's Summit; and Raytown.
</P>
<P>
   The Mid-America Regional Council has been working with area
cities to standardize franchise agreements. That work should be
done by mid-August and is expected to speed the issuing of
franchise agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Katerndahl, a manager for the council, said one issue that
had emerged was whether companies should build extra underground
conduit and sell the additional space to other companies who want
to enter the market. Such a provision in a franchise agreement
would limit disruptions on area streets caused by construction.
</P>
<P>
   Above ground, some utility poles have no more room to string
cable. In those cases, bigger poles would have to be installed, and
some cities have concerns about their appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are issues, but I don't think there are big obstacles
here,'' Katerndahl said.
</P>
<P>
   Gaul, of Everest, estimates it will take eight months to wire
Lenexa. As customers are wired, they will be offered the full
bundle of cable TV, telecommunications and Internet services.
Construction should begin in Mission late this year or in early
2001.
</P>
<P>
   It will take up to three years to complete work in Kansas City.
Construction will begin in southern and midtown Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Everest's area network will have 11,000 miles of cable and take
three to five years to complete. Plans call for Lawrence and
Leavenworth to be included, he said.
</P>
<P>
   UtiliCorp is also a partner in Kearney's ExOp. ExOp offers cable
TV, telephone and Internet service in Kearney and is building a
system in Platte City. ExOp will be building systems in other towns
with populations of less than 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Everest has bought a building at 9669 Lackman Road in Lenexa,
which will house the company's primary telecommunications and cable
TV equipment. It's from that location that construction starts
today. The building has 20,000 square feet of space.
</P>
<P>
   It also has leased 12,000 square feet of administrative office
space at 4740 Grand Ave. in Kansas City. Those offices will be
filled in the fall. In the meantime, it will have a temporary
office in the same building beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Everest, which is based in St. Louis, will have 60 to 70 area
employees by the end of the year and eventually 300 employees.
Those figures don't include people building the network.
</P>
<P>
   Par Electrical Contractors Inc. will be building the network.
Construction will start slowly but will eventually employ 500 to
750 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about this,'' said John Wilson, president of
Par.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
