<SLUG> BC-RACE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Police introduce program to eliminate racial profiling  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Under the white glare of public scrutiny, police
chiefs in Johnson County's two largest cities stepped into the
bright lights of a news conference Tuesday and made a frank
admission: We're human.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we are all human with human frailties, perceptions,
experiences, which set the stage for the possibility of biased
decision-making,'' Overland Park Police Chief John Douglass said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglass and Olathe Police Chief Art Mabry, as well as a host of
watchdog organizations, formally introduced Operation Vanguard to
the public on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under way since July 1, Operation Vanguard is designed to root
out race-biased decisions made by individual police officers who
unfairly single out minority motorists. It also provides training
to challenge officers to dispel old-school police tactics that
trade on stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it to our communities and the people who live, work and
travel through them to do everything we can to ensure that their
contacts with the police are fair, equitable and appropriate,''
Douglass said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 17 days of data collection, 530 Vanguard reports
have been filed in Olathe: about 30 a day, 10 per shift.
</P>
<P>
   Mabry says he'll use the data to spot behavior trends and the
potential need to step up cultural sensitivity training. So far, he
says, nothing in the data alarms him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very confident that our officers do not deliberately
racially profile,'' Mabry said. ``But if somebody was to ask me to
statistically prove that, I have nothing tangible to lay my hands
on. The data will answer these questions, one way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Data will be reviewed periodically, perhaps once a month, and
shared with other police departments through the Johnson County
Police Chiefs' and Sheriff Association, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That group met Tuesday and issued a news release supporting
race-profiling studies. The release said law enforcement officials
have an ethical and moral responsibility to ensure ``consistent
treatment to every member of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Operation Vanguard news conference, Henry Gueary III,
president of the Olathe chapter of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, said: ``We hope this serves as a
wake-up call to the issue of racial profiling. Our feeling is there
is nothing to fear because eventually (data collection) will be
required by law.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Gueary's office logged 38 complaints of racial
profiling. This year 16 reports have been called in to the Olathe
chapter, with the summer peak season half-complete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 0043EDT &QL; 
