r a BC-BUCKS-KAN &LR;      07-19 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCKS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Foundations commit money to `giant steps' for KC area  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY _ Kansas City's two largest
foundations announced a dual commitment Tuesday of at least $150
million toward areawide development and beautification ideas known
as the ``10 Giant Steps,'' which were unveiled during Kansas City's
150th birthday last month.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The steps range from specific projects, such as creating ``the
world's largest river fountain'' and developing a network of
bicycle trails, to more general subjects, such as improving
life-sciences research and upgrading cultural facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the Ewing Marion Kauffman Foundation and the
Hall Family Foundation represents the first funding commitments for
the 10 ideas. The foundations' contributions will not be in
addition to the millions of dollars they already give out. Rather,
Tuesday's announcement means that part of the Kauffman and Hall
foundations' annual spending will be more tailored toward the 10
steps' projects and subjects.
</P>
<P>
   There's no sense yet, however, of which initiatives will get
done first.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, this is underlining our existing commitment to the
community and tying it to the KC150 work,'' said Dave Lady, the
Kauffman Foundation's senior vice president and chief financial
officer. ``It's broader than one grant. It's more of a focus
area.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kauffman Foundation, created from the wealth of
pharmaceutical entrepreneur Ewing M. Kauffman, concentrates on such
issues as education and youths. It intends to focus on two giant
steps that correspond to those issues _ early-childhood care and
life-sciences research.
</P>
<P>
   Early-childhood care is a longstanding issue in Kansas City,
with government agencies and civic task forces repeatedly calling
for more day-care programs and better-paid caretakers. The
life-sciences initiative is an attempt to build upon the creation
of the Stowers Institute for Medical Research, scheduled to open
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, both the Kauffman and Hall foundations already are
linked in raising funds for a $300 million, dual-stage downtown
performing-arts center, which fits into one of the 10 initiatives,
upgrading cultural facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall Family Foundation's further commitment is more open to
any of the 10 steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think each one of the steps has merit and each one needs to
be explored,'' said Bill Hall, president of the Hall Family
Foundation. ``We're not discounting any of the ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hall foundation, created from the family of Hallmark Cards
founder Joyce Hall, has made sizable gifts to such civic endeavors
as the renovation of Union Station and the expansion of Children's
Mercy Hospital. It also routinely gives to neighborhood-improvement
ventures and fund-raising campaigns for fountains.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hall indicated the foundation probably could be counted on
to favor the river fountain and the step aimed at ``livability
standards'' for such things as reducing crime and cleaning up
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some new ideas that we would not undertake except
for the fact that they came out of the giant steps,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two foundations gave out roughly $75 million last
year. By comparison, their commitment to the 10 steps works out to
$75 million for each foundation. But Hall and Lady additionally
said that each foundation probably would spend more on the ideas
during the next decade; the announced $150 million figure merely
corresponded to KC150.
</P>
<P>
   The giant steps themselves _ besides a fountain, bike trails,
cultural facilities, early-childhood care, life sciences and
neighborhood ``livability standards'' _ also included: painting
bridges over rivers in different colors, putting up colorful
welcome signs at the region's main entry points, creating a school
curriculum on local history, and promoting the region's image as a
family vacation destination.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these steps are being worked on already, such as bike
trails. Others are high on other civic agendas, such as
life-sciences research with the Civic Council of top local
executives. And some are traditionally the work of government, such
as painting bridges.
</P>
<P>
   The steps were conceived by a group of civic leaders involved in
Kansas City's 150th birthday celebration. The group was led by
Arthur S. Brisbane, publisher of /{The Kansas City Star/}; Michael
Carter, chairman of Carter Broadcast Group; and Carol Marinovich,
mayor of the Unified Government of Wyandotte County and Kansas
City, Kan. However, the group left no blueprint for how its 10
steps should be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   With the foundations now committing their funds, Brisbane said
the leaders would ``regroup'' and serve as a ``catalyst'' for the
10 steps. The intention is to get other community agencies behind
the effort, then track progress of the steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy and enthusiasm with which these ideas were brought
forward is exciting,'' Hall said in a statement accompanying
Tuesday's announcement. ``We look forward to working with a variety
of community groups and organizations to translate some of these
ideas into reality and to continue to make our community a more
vibrant place to live and work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
