<HEADLINE>
GRUDZIELANEK SHAKY BUT EXPECTED TO START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers second baseman Mark
Grudzielanek has gained back two pounds from the 10 he lost while
missing more than a week with a viral infection. But the true test
of his condition comes tonight when he returns to the starting
lineup against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek is trying to find his legs after striking out all
three times he batted during the series with the Pittsburgh
Pirates. He has said he will need five more days to be 100 percent,
but progress remains slow.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's 8-6 loss, Grudzielanek came up with the bases
loaded in the seventh and two outs and took a called third strike
from left-hander Jason Christiansen to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, he told the club he could hit but was still rocky
and had to be reminded by the home-plate umpire when he struck out
in the seventh. He remained in the game at second and also fanned
during the Dodgers' six-run eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, he stranded six base runners in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is getting better, but it is still going to take some
time,'' said Jim Tracy, who managed his third game in place of
ailing Davey Johnson. ``This thing really has taken a lot out of
him and there is no rushing him back too quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, who batted .326 in 123 games last year as the
team's shortstop, came into Tuesday's game hitting .301 with five
homers and 31 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   __ More Davey: Johnson remained in the hospital for a third day,
undergoing tests for an irregular heartbeat. ``I talked to him last
night and he sounded pretty good,'' Tracy said. ``He was in good
spirits, but you could tell how much he wants to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is expected to return to the club before the end of the
home stand, which runs through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Spring-training update: The Vero Beach, Fla., City Council
and Indian River County Commission will meet Monday to consider a
memo detailing a $19 million public buyout that would keep the
Dodgers training there for at least 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is only designed to outline where the money will be
spent and does not seal the deal in favor of Vero Beach. The club
still is considering an offer from Las Vegas, which is putting
together plans for a spring complex that will accommodate six
major-league teams.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers hope to have a decision by September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just a process document and doesn't get us any closer to
getting the deal done,'' Dodgers vice president Derrick Hall said.
``These are just broad-range parameters that have been agreed upon
with all of the fine detail still needing to be worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The money will be spent to renovate Holman Stadium, surrounding
practice fields and locker rooms. Among the issues under review are
details about parking and concession revenue.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick hits: Dodgers reliever Antonio Osuna took over for
starter Mike Judd and pitched a season-high three innings. Osuna
allowed two hits and an unearned run. . . . The Dodgers scored 22
runs in the series, the most by the team in a three-game set since
May 19-21 when they swept the Florida Marlins. . . . Pittsburgh
starter Todd Ritchie, who won a club-high 15 games last season, did
not get out of the third inning Tuesday, allowing nine hits and six
runs. . . . Former Dodgers reliever Roger McDowell (1991-94) was a
clubhouse visitor before the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
