   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DAMS (Pioneer, Calif.) _ The future of the Pacific Gas and
Electric hydropower system, a complex of 174 dams on 17 river
systems that is the largest privately held collection of dams in
the world, is at stake under current plans for its pieces to be
auctioned off to the highest bidder by sometime next year. That
specter had prompted a coalition of environmental groups and
outdoorsmen to demand that any sale be tied to arrangements
intended to ease the toll being inflicted on California's rivers.
By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ADOPTED-MONKEY (New York) _ The saga of Cookie Flikshtein has
stirred tumultuous feelings on both sides of the fight. To the
Flikshtein family and an outraged army of their neighbors, Cookie
is a beloved _ albeit simian _ member of the family. She may be a
monkey, they admit, but she has adjusted enough to the human
condition to spend most evenings eating Rocky Road ice cream and
watching the nightly news. The state agrees that Cookie is no
ordinary primate, but not because of her human characteristics. She
is a Diana monkey, an endangered species. As such, she deserves
special care, and the state, after a protracted court battle, has
successfully argued that Cookie should be taken from the Flikshtein
home and placed in a special animal rescue program at the Detroit
Zoo. By Alan Feuer.
</P>
