   GARLIC-FARMERS (Undated) _ Ray Bradley, one of about 20 farmers
selling new garlic at New York City's Greenmarkets, came to farming
through haute cuisine's back door, as a chef in some of the city's
top restaurants. By Deborah Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVE-OILS (Undated) _ In a world awash in olive oil, it is hard
to imagine a new one that could merit singling out. But several
olive oils, and one innovative grapeseed oil, are worthy of the
attention of the serious cook. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   SORBET (Undated) _ A good sorbet should taste like an extraction
of its main flavor, and nothing else. There are almost no
limitations on flavors; they can be summer fruits like peaches,
blackberries and nectarines, or spices, chocolate, herbs or
spirits. Some chefs have recently taken to making almost-ice-cream
sorbets with fromage blanc, sour cream or even goat cheese. All of
them are able to stand out without compromise. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ The column: Cooking basil-crusted loin
of lamb with Michel Richard, the chef and owner of Citronelle in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: On cooking sorrel
chicken. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The weekly wine column: On the San
Francisco International Wine Competition, which featured wines from
16 countries and 22 U.S. states.By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
