<SLUG> BC-SPAM-BILL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOUSE PASSES RESTRAINTS ON JUNK E-MAIL  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to shrink the rising heaps of unwanted
clutter in everyone's electronic in boxes, the House almost
unanimously approved legislation Tuesday to crack down on
unsolicited commercial e-mail known as spam.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which passed 427 to 1, would help halt repeated
electronic solicitations from advertisers, permitting consumers and
Internet service providers (ISPs) to sue advertisers for as much as
$500 per unwanted e-mail, up to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Courts could triple that amount in certain cases and award
attorneys fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most annoying thing about the Internet is junk e-mail,''
said Rep. Heather Wilson, R-N.M., who sponsored the bill. The
Constitution, she said, ``guarantees a right to commercial free
speech, but there is no right to force us to listen to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The single ``no'' vote was cast by Ron Paul, a Texas Republican
with strong libertarian leanings. A similar bill is under
consideration in the Senate, but has not moved out of committee
despite broad bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   The popular spam crackdown is part of a continuing drive in
Congress to write rules for the Internet _ an effort that spans
everything from attempts to ban Internet gambling to sorting out
such hugely complicated and controversial issues as digital
copyrights and access to high-speed ``broadband'' communication
networks.
</P>
<P>
   But even on an issue as seemingly simple as banning spam,
lawmakers found themselves trying to sidestep a thicket of basic
conflicts _ in this case between privacy and free speech _ that
have complicated Washington's efforts to update the nation's legal
infrastructure for the Information Age.
</P>
<P>
   While the spam crackdown passed nearly without dissent, the
measure took more than a year to draft after earlier versions
brought complaints from free-speech advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was about the 50th draft,'' said Wilson spokesman Kevin
McDermott. ``It went through a lot of reworking to get to a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than ban spam outright, lawmakers were careful to draw a
narrow bill that essentially allows consumers to simply ``opt out''
of further solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhat to my surprise, given all the not-very-good laws I've
seen, this one seems pretty solid,'' said Eugene Volokh, a law
professor at the University of California at Los Angeles who
specializes in cyberspace issues and free speech. ``It's suitably
narrow. It merely requires that the sender provide an opt out.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires advertisers to include a valid return address
in all commercial e-mails and prohibits further transmission after
a recipient objects.
</P>
<P>
   Senders must label all advertisements ``in a manner that is
clear and conspicuous'' and clearly provide a method for recipients
to refuse any further solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson cited estimates saying that more than a third of
unsolicited commercial e-mails are pornography. And at
congressional hearings, Federal Trade Commission official Eileen
Harrington testified that spam is rife with false information and
extravagant claims, calling spam the ``fraud artists' calling card
on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill could prove a boon to ISPs, which said that spam
campaigns can overwhelm their systems and slow service, costing
them $1 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would permit ISPs to prohibit anyone from using
their systems to send unsolicited commercial e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, the nation's largest ISP, estimates that up to
30 percent of its traffic coming from outside its system consists
of spam.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson cited a small ISP in her state of New Mexico,
Albuquerque-based Associated Information Services, which complained
of being inundated with anywhere from 400,000 to 2 million junk
e-mails a day, clogging traffic and in some cases causing system
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Steven Fox told Wilson his business is being
``spam-bombed,'' causing delays in client e-mails and preventing
some from even connecting to the service.
</P>
<P>
   If an ISP is working with spammers _ say by collecting a fee
from advertisers who send spam _ the measure would require the
provider to give its subscribers the option of not receiving such
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Like other legislation that gives ISPs a safe harbor from
litigation over activity that takes place on their systems, the
bill would protect ISPs from any spam lawsuits involving their
networks.
</P>
<P>
   The bill stopped short of a ban on spam to avoid trampling on
commercial free-speech rights and to protect consumers who do want
to receive unsolicited commercial e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers nixed earlier ideas for a central government
clearinghouse where consumers could register to prevent unsolicited
mail _ seen as a potentially dangerous depository of information
that could be misused by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The law does not apply to all unsolicited commercial messages,
which taken literally could include sending job resumes to
employers or asking friends if they are interested in buying a used
car.
</P>
<P>
   The measure resembles earlier laws aimed at mitigating the
unwanted side effects of older technologies, from automated
telemarketing calls to junk faxes. Volokh said the bill follows
Supreme Court precedent that allows Congress to limit commercial
solicitations on the grounds that there exists ``no right to press
even good ideas on an unwilling listener.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure would pre-empt 16 state anti-spam laws, including
California's, which has been challenged in court as a violation of
the Constitution's protection of the free flow of interstate
commerce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
