<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-TAX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SENATE PASSES GOP TAX CUT FOR COUPLES  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate approved a measure Tuesday to cut taxes
for married couples by $248 billion over the next 10 years, setting
up an election year showdown with President Clinton over how to
spend the growing budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Triumphant Republicans heralded the 61-to-38 vote as a step
toward eliminating the much-maligned ``marriage penalty,'' a quirk
in the tax code that causes many married couples to pay more in
taxes than they would if they remained single.
</P>
<P>
   Warning Clinton that Democrats will pay a political price if he
makes good on his veto threat, GOP leaders pushed through the bill
in time for it to be on the president's desk before the Republican
National Convention later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the bill goes far beyond providing relief for
couples who pay a marriage penalty and accused Republicans of
trying to reward their wealthiest supporters. They noted that
billions of dollars in relief also would be directed to those who
currently enjoy a tax benefit from marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he will veto the bill, unless Republicans agree to
a $250 billion companion measure to provide prescription drug
coverage to Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``By itself, I will veto this bill,'' Clinton said in a
statement from Camp David. ``The marriage penalty bill put forth by
the majority in Congress is one part of a fiscally irresponsible,
poorly targeted and regressive tax plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote came less than a week after the Senate approved a
measure eliminating the estate tax over the next 10 years. Later
this week, the House of Representatives is expected to pass
legislation expanding tax breaks for contributions to retirement
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the tax cuts represent a cornerstone of the GOP's
election year strategy to return a sizable portion of the federal
budget surplus to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office released new figures Tuesday
that estimate the budget surplus will be $2.17 trillion over the
next 10 years, up from the $838 billion estimate in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these families have contributed to the record surplus
that we have in Washington,'' said Sen. William Roth, R-Del., the
Finance Committee chairman. ``They deserve to get some of it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   As a political matter, Republicans hope to convince voters that
Democratic intransigence is all that is standing in the way of
meaningful tax cuts. Within hours of the Senate's vote, 10
Republican governors distributed statements applauding the
legislation and calling on Clinton to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, including Clinton, have advocated smaller, targeted
tax cuts and called for using the bulk of the surplus to pay down
the debt and expand social programs. Democrats have been more
receptive to tax cuts as estimates of the surplus rise.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Democrats joined 53 Republicans in supporting the marriage
tax measure, including California Sen. Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if Congress only passes into law one piece of
tax reform legislation this year, it should be the marriage penalty
relief,'' Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein also supported a more limited Democratic tax cut
proposal that failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providing marriage penalty relief is a matter of common sense,
fairness and decency,'' Feinstein said. ``Couples should not be
penalized by the tax code simply because they are married.''
</P>
<P>
   California Sen. Barbara Boxer voted against the GOP measure,
while supporting a Democratic alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``marriage penalty'' arises, among other reasons,
because of the combined income of two wage earners pushing a couple
into a higher tax bracket. Republicans estimate about 25 million
couples pay more income tax than they would if they were single,
averaging about $1,400 in ``marriage penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some glaring, unfair provisions in the tax code, and
this is one of the most offensive,'' said Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would address the problem by boosting a couple's
standard income tax deduction so it is equal to double that of a
single taxpayer. In 2000 dollars, that would be an increase from
$7,350 to $8,800. The bill also would expand the 15 percent and 28
percent income tax brackets and make changes in the earned income
tax credit for married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the changes go far beyond alleviating the tax
burden on married couples, amounting to a giveaway to the wealthy.
Combined with the GOP plan to eliminate the estate tax, Democrats
said 43 percent of the cuts would go to the wealthiest 1 percent of
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., called the
Republican plan ``another reckless tax scheme that favors the
wealthiest Americans and leaves little money for the issues that
Americans care most about.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats offered an alternative that would allow married
couples to choose to file together or separately, whichever was in
their financial interest. Democrats said their plan would wipe out
the ``marriage penalty'' for all couples earning less than
$150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than costing $248 billion over 10 years, Democrats said
their measure would have cost $54 billion. The Senate defeated the
measure by a 50-to-46 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate must reconcile its bill with a House version passed
last week. The House version is approximately $70 billion smaller.
Congressional leaders are expected to send a final version of the
bill to the White House this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict right now the president will sign this bill,'' Lott
said, ignoring Cliton's veto threat, ``because it will be very hard
to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be clear, very clear, Mr. President. Are you
for eliminating the marriage penalty tax or not?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
