<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEEN-MUM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LAST ROYAL SERVES BRITAIN WITH CLASS  &HT;     By LEAH GARCHIK 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In merry modern-day England, where a notable number of Windsors
have been caught with knickers down or hands out, Her Majesty Queen
Elizabeth the Queen Mother is the human tea cosy of the family:
pleasant, plump, predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unwieldy formality of her official two-queen title _
chosen specifically by her when her daughter became Queen Elizabeth
II _ the 99-year-old Queen Mum seems to relish being Britain's most
cuddly royal, never varying from the twinkly-eyed grandmotherly
image so carefully crafted over the years. Before she celebrates
her real 100th birthday on August 4, Wednesday's official pageant
in London will allow her family, 12,000 invited guests and 7,000
participants (pilots flying by, a 1,000-person choir, scores of
marchers and drummers and float riders) to give official thanks to
the one in their midst who has never flagged in the greatest royal
duty of all: waving at the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   If her daughter sometimes shows more interest in corgis than
people, and her son-in-law flashes embarrassing bursts of temper
and racism, and the generation those two begat chases after sex and
commercial success in ways unthinkable in prior years, the Queen
Mother never slips. She is always there, in floral print or baby
blue or pearly pink with matching hat, nodding, smiling, pivoting
her forearm and flapping her palm from side to side in the
direction of the hoi polloi.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Royalty Personified
</P>
<P>
   Like Queen Victoria, who was on the throne the year the Queen
Mum was born, she knows her job, and she does it without griping.
She is the only royal to personify the value of royal reputation,
which as the new century begins, seems to be the only remaining
virtue of the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The Windsors can't make foreign policy, and they don't dare
venture opinions on social questions. They are there, simply, as
icons. And while the Queen Mum has served superbly as a sort of
human ornament, there are always people who think that figurines
are nothing but dust collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, as the cries of anti-royalists have grown louder
in the United Kingdom, so have whispers about the old lady. She
never once opened a door, says iconoclast mischief-maker
Christopher Hitchens in Vanity Fair, nor pulled a curtain. But such
were the ways of aristocrats in the castle in Scotland in which
Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon was raised.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MUM19 (61639 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  She was the spoiled child of the middle-aged Earl and Countess of
Strathmore, and her childhood nickname was ``Princess.'' She
rejected her future husband's first two proposals of marriage and
only acquiesced after it was clear she would be unable to attract
his older brother, who it seemed was the man who would be king.
</P>
<P>
   It's said she was a domineering wife. Most people thought
``Bertie,'' Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon's husband, was an introverted and
weak-willed milquetoast. But when his brother threw away the throne
for love and Bertie became King George VI, it was his strong wife
who bucked him up, insisted he take lessons to rid himself of a
speech impediment and gave him the strength to lead during wartime.
</P>
<P>
   There are critics who point out now that both Elizabeth and the
King were fans of Neville Chamberlain's policies of appeasement
toward Nazi Germany, but World War II was the setting for the
royals' finest hour. The Queen Mother permanently placed her
portrait in the nation's lockets when she risked her children and
herself by refusing to escape to safety and insisting on standing
her ground in London.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, she was accused of ruining the life of her
younger daughter, Princess Margaret, by thwarting Margaret's love
affair with Capt. Peter Townsend, a divorced man. Ironically, her
own husband had become king as a result of his brother's love for a
divorced woman. In public, her resentment of the Duke and Duchess
of Windsor never wavered (some said because she jealously believed
that the former king was more popular with the public than her
husband, who took the throne when he left). Her unforgiving
attitude toward the Duke may have caused her to be so hard on
Margaret, whose sanctioned marriage to Anthony Armstrong-Jones
ended in divorce, followed by much public profligacy.
</P>
<P>
   Some even blamed the Queen Mother for encouraging the unhappy
marriage of Diana and her grandson, Charles. Diana was the
granddaughter of the Queen's lady-in-waiting, Lady Fermoy, and it
was said the older royal saw herself reflected in the younger one.
</P>
<P>
   They both seemed eager to please, putting on shows of
flirtatious warmth and naivete. The public and crowds adored them.
But while the Queen Mother's husband was willing to bask in the
accolades accorded his beloved wife, Charles was jealous of his
wife's popularity. Although the Queen Mother's marriage held, and
Diana's didn't, both women made use of personal magnetism to hold
on to public affection long after their blue-blood husbands, by
death and divorce, were out of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MUM19 (61639 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Critics' ``accusations'' _ the Queen Mother likes the horses; she
likes more than the occasional slug of gin and tonic; she's partial
to jokes and candy and an army of aging gays she employs as
servants _ seem strangely Victorian. A hundred years ago, these
``perversions'' would have been scandalous; nowadays, her secret
fondnesses make her all the more lovable.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, as if she knows that she's the last of the
thoroughly adored Windsors, she hangs in there. She's very much
aware that she's the family member least splashed by the mud of
scandal and least criticized for failing to acknowledge real issues
of modern life. Everyone knows she's of another age; she's happy to
be there up on the balcony acknowledging the tributes.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the royals, she seems to have understood and accepted the
duties of the position, one of the few left in the world where
looking like you can do the job is the essence of performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
