 I'LL PASS ON THE MALIGNANT BURGER  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If I was a meat-eater (he wrote, smugly), I
would be tempted to peek under the bun and the pickle next time.
Looking for, you know, funny stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Federal food inspection authorities have ruled that it's safe to
eat animals with cancer, tumors and open sores. Mix 'n' match.
</P>
<P>
   Those defects will be classified as ``aesthetic problems.''
Please pass the pork chops and the Clearasil.
</P>
<P>
   I had a good chuckle over this news story with my next-door
neighbor, Upton Sinclair. OK, Upton is dead, but his 1906 book,
``The Jungle,'' was a muckraking expose of the American meatpacking
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair wouldn't bother to write that book today, because who
cares if the meat people are tossing floor-sweepin's into the
sausage? That's only the tip of the tumor. And it's all legal.
</P>
<P>
   The new ruling has to make the meat inspectors' job easier. What
meat could possibly be rejected?
</P>
<P>
   MOVING ON to less tasteful stuff:
</P>
<P>
   Famed screenwriter Joe Eszterhas has written a book, ``American
Rhapsody,'' released Tuesday, a fact-fiction stew about the
Clinton-Monica stuff.
</P>
<P>
   One character in the book is Willard, who is Bill Clinton's
manhood.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Drudge Report, there will be an audio
presentation of the book, and the voice of Willard will be comedian
Bill Maher.
</P>
<P>
   This from the Drudge Report: ``President Clinton has privately
expressed disappointment in Maher playing his penis, the senior
adviser said.''
</P>
<P>
   Which causes reader Gar Smith to wonder, ``Who did the president
want to play his penis? Sylvester Stallone? Arnold?''
</P>
<P>
   No, Schwarzenegger is a Republican; it's doubtful he would play
the role sympathetically.
</P>
<P>
   BAD TASTE in every item today? That was not my intention, but
sometimes the best-laid plans of mice and men wind up as items
about men eating mice.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's New Yorker magazine was a fascinating article,
seriously, on the squirrel-brain eaters of rural Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The meat is sweet, but the brain is to die for. Literally, some
medical researchers fear.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; this  &LR; week's New Yorker, I swear: ``The Joy of Rats ...
South China Delicacy.''
</P>
<P>
   In next week's issue, I'm guessing: ``Cockroach crunch cookies:
High protein from low places.''
</P>
<P>
   I'M A NAZI. That's what Larry Ellison's Sausalito-based
motoryacht Izanami spells backwards.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get inatizi, Lizzy. Izanami is a mythological goddess,
one of two beings who created Japan. She wound up being stir-fried
to death in a volcano.
</P>
<P>
   More Larry boat stuff: The 192-foot-long Izanami isn't Ellison's
biggest boat. That would be his 234-foot Eco.
</P>
<P>
   When Ellison bought Eco, he turned one deck into a basketball
court. He also races yachts and plays guitar in his own blues band.
Ah, to be filthy rich and 15 forever.
</P>
<P>
   WE'LL EACH grab two legs and make a wish:
</P>
<P>
   From the Carmel Pine Cone's ``Police and Sheriff's Log'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Sky Ranch Road residents both claim ownership of the same
rottweiler.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a story worth watching. This could develop into the sequel
to Elian.
</P>
<P>
   FINEST NAME ever for a toy: Irritating Stick.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Irritating Stick is not an actual stick, but a video game.
It's based on a Japanese game show where contestants take a giant
electrical rod and maneuver it through a metal maze, trying to
avoid shock.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be confused with today's column theme: Irritating Shtick.
</P>
<P>
   YOU KNOW you're old when ... they tell you you're too old for an
old folks' home.
</P>
<P>
   Ethel Schneider of Walnut Creek and a friend motored off
recently to check out a retirement home near Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   The receptionist at the home informed Ethel and her friend that
there is a waiting list, and the home does not accept anyone unless
they can move in before their 85th birthday, ``and obviously you
two don't qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   Durn, and it seems  &LR; seemed like such a warm-hearted place.
</P>
<P>
   THE MAILBAG: ``I always start at the back of the paper, skipping
most of the columnists except Miss Manners and Top of the Sixth,
and I look forward to your Forty-Nine Stories, or even that daily
goo you painfully dredge up.'' (Eleanor Peterson)
</P>
<P>
   Give us this day ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
