<HEADER>
A6275 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-CSU-TEACHERS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-19 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSU-TEACHERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CSU MAY UNIFY TEACHER PROGRAM ENTRY STANDARDS  &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The California State University is working to simplify its
admissions and transfer process for education students to help the
state in its push to get 250,000 new secondary and elementary
school teachers in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We urgently need teachers, so we are trying to eliminate the
barriers that frustrate people and discourage them when they
apply,'' said Arthurlene Towner, dean of CSU Hayward's education
department.
</P>
<P>
   Admission standards for the 21 campuses offering teacher
preparation now require varying grade-point averages for students
from different disciplines. And requirements for students who share
the same major can vary from campus to campus. All this makes it
difficult for students applying to teaching programs at more than
one university within the system.
</P>
<P>
   Trustees for CSU, which trains 60 percent of the state's
teachers, will consider a proposal at their meeting at CSU
headquarters in Long Beach Wednesday to establish uniform GPA
requirements for admission to education programs across the system.
</P>
<P>
   They also will weigh a proposal to increase the number of
transferable community college education courses.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, only transfer credits from a single, generally
three-unit, course _ Introduction to Education _ can be applied to
a CSU program. The change would allow up to six units from
education courses to be applied to a teacher preparation program at
CSU.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a great deal of attention put on this issue,
and we are big players. We are trying to facilitate that production
of teachers for the classrooms,'' said Thomas La Belle, provost and
vice president for academic affairs for San Francisco State
University. ``Each one of the CSU campuses has been relatively
autonomous, and this brings them together.''
</P>
<P>
   The actions are part of a move by the system to make the
admissions and graduation process easier for all students. Last
year, it aligned its course requirements with the University of
California's admission standards to ensure incoming freshmen and
transfer students could be eligible for both systems with one set
of courses. To further reconcile with UC's requirements, they will
vote Wednesday to lower the minimum number of units required for a
bachelor's degree from 124 semester units to 120, and to count only
college preparatory classes to calculate GPAs for admission.
</P>
<P>
   The latest effort to ease access for those seeking teaching
credentials comes as the state has about 34,000 teachers in
classrooms on emergency credentials and is struggling to attract
and retain enough new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The CSU system has added an online teacher credentialing program
and increased the flexibility of its teacher preparation programs.
It has also incorporated the fifth-year credentialing program into
the bachelor's degree on many campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one of those things in and of itself doesn't amount to a
whole lot, but each one contributes to expediting the process,'' La
Belle said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Commission on Teacher Credentialing requires that
those seeking acceptance to teacher preparation programs have
grades in the upper half of all students. But there are multiple
ways to calculate who is in that upper half, said David Spence,
CSU's executive vice chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, each campus sets separate GPA requirements for each
discipline. Under the new system, admission to all teaching
programs would be based on a common GPA, which will be determined
by the chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   The new requirements would not lower academic standards because
applicants with GPAs in the top half would still be chosen, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some educators worry that students in the most rigorous fields
such as mathematics and engineering _ where it is difficult to get
top grades _ may be excluded from teaching programs, he said. But,
he added, campuses will be allowed the flexibility to make
exceptions in individual cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a high standard,'' he said. ``California needs
teachers and needs them to be prepared in a quality way. Part of
that has to do with the kind of people we admit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
