<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW--BROTHERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BROTHERS SEEM BORN TO BE BUSINESSMEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY PETER SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2000 San Francisco Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A case could be made that entrepreneurs are
born, not bred.
</P>
<P>
   The Case brothers, for example, have come a long way from their
lemonade stand in Hawaii. Dan Case heads Chase H&AMP;Q, the investment
bank that recently became part of Chase Manhattan Corp. Brother
Steve heads America Online, which is about to merge with Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Sandler is longtime co-chief executive officer of Golden
West Financial Corp., the Oakland holding company for World Savings
and Loan, and her brother, Bernard Osher, headed the venerable
Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield auction house, which was bought by eBay
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Other local examples of sibling CEOs include the Dibachi
brothers. Yesterday, Farid Dibachi officially launched Arzoon, a
San Mateo B2B e-commerce company that lets rail and other freight
customers procure and track shipments involving more than one mode
of transportation. Meanwhile, brother Farzad is founder and CEO of
Niku Corp., a Redwood City developer of Internet software that
allows law firms, ad agencies and other professional services to
automate many of their services.
</P>
<P>
   Both brothers spent their early years in Iran, where their
father, a microwave engineer, helped build the country's first
ground satellite station.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, when Farid was 16 and Farzad 14, the family moved to
the United States. Both brothers were drawn to technology. By the
time he was 20, Farid not only had an undergraduate degree from the
University of Tennessee but also a master's degree in mechanical
engineering from Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Then Farid went to work for Hewlett-Packard for about six years,
picking up a second master's degree in electrical engineering along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he left HP to become vice president of engineering for
a small electronic test equipment company ``to get acquainted with
how small businesses run,'' he said. Two years later, he launched
his first startup, Wavetron Microsystems, in the basement of his
San Carlos house.
</P>
<P>
   Wavetron did well selling digital signal-processing hardware and
software to military contractors. But by 1995, Farid was talking
with his younger brother about pioneering the development of an
``information appliance'' _ a low-cost computer, with all functions
built into push buttons on the casing that was as simple to use as
a microwave oven.
</P>
<P>
   Farid sold Wavetron for millions of dollars to SBS Technologies
and co-founded Diba with Farzad, who previously was senior vice
president of Oracle and helped lead the development of its
multimedia database and networking products.
</P>
<P>
   After just 18 months, the two brothers sold their fledgling
company to Sun Microsystems for an estimated $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Farzad quickly went on to found Niku, which means ``do-gooder''
in Farsi. The Redwood City company went public in February at $24
per share and quickly soared to $105. Even after slipping back to
$33.75 in the recent Internet stock retrenchments, Niku still has a
market value topping $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While Farzad was building his second startup, Farid took a
two-year sabbatical from the entrepreneurial rat race. ``I was
burned out after seven years and all the emotional ups and downs,''
he said. ``I decided to spend time with my family, pick up golf,
sit on some boards but never do another startup.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never'' turned out to be a short time. In September, Farid got
excited by the idea for an online service that would help
businesses navigate the very fragmented transportation industry and
allow them to arrange freight shipments by truck, rail, plane or
ship from a single access point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entrepreneurial spirit is like a virus,'' Farid said.
``It's not something you can really get rid of.'' He named his new
venture Arzoon, which means ``inexpensive'' or ``good value'' in
Farsi. The startup doesn't have the value of Niku yet, but Farid is
working to match his younger brother's most recent success.
</P>
<P>
   Arzoon has raised $34 million from private investors, including
J.&AMP;W. Seligman and Co., Venrock Associates and a venture capital
fund of Thomas Weisel Partners. In May, it also received financing
from four strategic partners _ the Union Pacific, CSX, Norfolk
Southern and Canadian Pacific railroads.
</P>
<P>
   RETIREMENT PLANNING: The U.S. Small Business Administration, the
U.S. Department of Labor, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and Merrill
Lynch announced yesterday that they are launching a Web site in
August to help small business owners develop appropriate retirement
plans for their employees. The site will be called
 &LR; selectaretirementplan.org &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's tight labor market, more and more business owners
are recognizing the need to offer retirement plan benefits to their
employees, both for retention and recruitment,'' said SBA
Administrator Aida Alvarez. ``However, many business owners have
been deterred from doing so because of the lack of educational
resources and the difficulty of deciding on which plan to adopt.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Web site will answer questions about plan contribution
flexibility, record-keeping, administrative responsibilities and
overall business advantages. It will also guide users to specific
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Grow a Business appears every Wednesday in The Chronicle. Send
small-business tips, comments and questions to
 &LR; entrepreneurs &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com,  &LR; or to Peter Sinton, Grow a
Business column, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
