r f BC-APPLE--PROMISE-SFCHRO     07-19 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE--PROMISE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 APPLE LEADERS PROMISE TO DAZZLE AT MACWORLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Apple Tuesday reported quarterly revenues that were a
shade below expectations, but profits were solid and both company
officials and analysts said new products to be announced today
should push sales growth back onto the fast track.
</P>
<P>
   For its third fiscal quarter, which ended July 1, the Cupertino
Mac-maker posted sales of $1.83 billion. Compared with revenues of
$1.56 billion in the same period last year, sales were up 17
percent, but they fell short of the $1.9 billion analysts had
predicted after lowering their estimates from an original target of
$2 billion for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Net profits for the quarter added up to $200 million (55 cents
per share), compared with $203 million (60 cents) during the same
three months last year. But the figures for both years included
significant gains from investments rather than operations _ mainly
sales of shares in ARM Holdings, a British chip designer.
</P>
<P>
   When those gains are excluded, net profits for the most-recent
quarter totaled $163 million, up a whopping 43 percent over the
comparable figure last year. On a per-share basis, earnings without
the investment gains were 45 cents, 29 percent higher than a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm OK with this,'' said Daniel Kunstler of J.P. Morgan
Securities in San Francisco. ``We've grown accustomed to upside
surprises from Apple, and this time there wasn't so much pizzazz,
but we'll deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple shares, which were recently split 2 for 1, closed at
$57.14, down $1.06, in regular trading yesterday. In after-hours
trading, they slipped further, to below $55.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, Fred Anderson, Apple's chief
financial officer, cited three factors to explain why profits held
up well despite the revenue shortfall: Component prices during the
quarter fell below expectations; the company's product mix shifted
slightly toward its higher-margin ``professional'' products; and
the percentage of sales through Apple's online store rather than
dealers hit a record 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, gross margins for the quarter were 29.8 percent,
well above industry norms.
</P>
<P>
   The lower-than-anticipated revenues resulted from a slowdown in
sales of the iMac, the company's consumer- and education-oriented
model, and a preference on the part of education buyers, who are
especially important during the third quarter, for the
lowest-priced iMac, which lists for $999. IMac sales for the
quarter were just shy of 450,000 units, out of the company's total
volume of 1.016 million units.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson blamed the iMac slowdown on the fact that Apple hasn't
introduced new models in nine months, but he said that would change
today, when company chief executive Steve Jobs delivers the keynote
address at the East Coast edition of Macworld Expo, the semiannual
Mac trade show, in New York. ``I think you'll be impressed,'' he
told analysts, adding that the company has ``a very strong pipeline
of products'' and that new models will be introduced more
frequently during the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Anderson declined to provide specifics about the
new models, but Apple watchers expect the new iMacs to come with
faster processors and graphics, new color options and improved
keyboards, mice and audio. ATI Technologies, the Montreal company
that supplies graphics chips to Apple, yesterday briefly posted a
press release boasting that its latest chips will be included in
new iMac and PowerMac models to be announced at the Expo.
</P>
<P>
   Mac rumor sites on the Web have also been abuzz with speculation
about a ``cube Mac,'' a new cube-shaped model without a built-in
screen, and accompanying audio components made by Harman Kardon. .
During the past week, several sites that had posted reports about
the cube removed them after receiving messages from Apple lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers had predicted that the previously promised
``public beta'' version of Mac OS X, a major overhaul of the
company's operating system software, would be released this week.
But in yesterday's conference call, Anderson said the beta is
``still on target for release in the late summer,'' with the
``first customer release'' still set for January.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party developers are also expected to announce a variety
of new programs and peripherals for the Mac today. Topping the list
will be Microsoft Office 2001, a new Mac edition of the popular
productivity suite.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
