r f BC-WELLS--PROFITS-SFCHRO     07-19 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS--PROFITS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HEALTHY PROFITS FOR WELLS FARGO
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY SAM ZUCKERMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Wells Fargo's second-quarter profit climbed 12
percent, fueled by rapid loan growth, higher fee income and robust
venture capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, the largest bank based in the West, said Tuesday that it
earned a record $1.04 billion (63 cents per diluted share) in the
three months ending in June, as most of its consumer and commercial
businesses operated in high gear. In the 1999 second quarter, the
bank earned $931 million (55 cents).
</P>
<P>
   The bank boosted revenue to $4.56 billion in the quarter, up 11
percent from a year ago, a solid showing in an industry in which
top-line growth is typically in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   After the report, Wells shares fell $1.31 to $42.06 amid a broad
retreat in bank stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The bank took its current form in 1998 when Minnesota's Norwest
Corp. bought San Francisco's Wells, took its name and moved its
headquarters here. The new Wells has largely avoided the loan
problems and sluggish profit gains that have dogged some other big
banks, including several that went through megamergers a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very steady quarter, with high-quality earnings,''
said Joseph Morford, an analyst with the brokerage Dain Rauscher
Wessels. ``Wells is the dominant bank in much of the West and
that's the fastest-growing area of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank has not stumbled in its big merger or in several
smaller purchases because it has taken a cautious approach to
combining the old Wells and Norwest.
</P>
<P>
   The two banks had sharply different styles in the retail
marketplace. Wells favored telephones, ATMs and computers for
reaching customers, while Norwest stressed more traditional branch
banking.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Wells has converted about 70 percent of the products and
computer networks of the two banks to common systems, Chief
Executive Officer Dick Kovacevich said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the profit jump in the second quarter stemmed from a
twenty-fivefold surge in gains from venture capital investments to
$320 million. The bank also had hefty increases in deposit, trust
and investment account fees.
</P>
<P>
   Wells' outstanding loans jumped 21 percent to $135 billion, with
strong gains in both the consumer and commercial portfolios. The
bank said it had a slight increase in problem loans, which stayed
below 1 percent of total credits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the bank added some 100,000 online customers per
month, passing the 2 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   The only area of the bank that reported a lower profit was the
mortgage business, which felt the effects of rising interest rates.
Mortgage originations dropped to $18 billion from $23 billion a
year ago, trimming earnings in the business 7.5 percent to $62
million.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
