r f BC-SCHWAB--EARNINGS-SFCH     07-19 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB--EARNINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SCHWAB EARNINGS AND ACCOUNTS UP
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Charles Schwab Corp. reported second-quarter
earnings precisely in line with Wall Street expectations Tuesday,
but its stock shot up on news that the company added a whopping
400,000 customers during a tumultuous period for the brokerage
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco discount broker said its operating income for
the quarter ended last month rose 16 percent to $199 million (14
cents per share) from $171 million (12 cents) in the year-earlier
quarter. Revenues surged 25 percent to $1.4 billion from $1.12
billion.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the leading market indicators were down sharply,
Schwab's stock jumped $1 to $38.25. It has gained more than 50
percent in less than eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Smith, an analyst with Chase H&AMP;Q in San Francisco, said the
addition of 400,000 new accounts _ bringing the total to 7.2
million _ ``is a good indicator of how well Schwab is doing in this
competitive market'' and ``bodes well for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that a lot of investors and prospective investors sat
on their hands last quarter because of the wild volatility and
steep plunges in stock prices that began in April.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the only sour disclosure in Schwab's report was the
fact that the average commission per trade during the second
quarter slipped to $36.65 from $40.12 in the first quarter,
continuing a trend that has persisted for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab customers have been steadily increasing the percentage of
trades that they place online, where commissions are lowest. In
addition, Smith noted, Schwab has lately scaled down the
commissions it charges its most-active traders and also has reduced
commissions for financial advisers.
</P>
<P>
   David Pottruck, president and co-chief executive of Schwab,
noted that 4.1 million of Schwab's 7.2 million accounts now place
at least some trades online _ a 46 percent gain from a year ago.
Online trades accounted for 81 percent of all trades last quarter,
compared with 67 percent in the year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its operating results for the second quarter
exclude an after-tax total of $61 million in charges stemming from
its acquisitions of U.S. Trust Corp. and CyBerCorp Inc.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; alouis &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
