r f BC-PILLSBURY--MERGER-SFC     07-19 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILLSBURY--MERGER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECHNOLOGY DRIVING LAW-FIRM MERGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY CAROL EMERT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite the dot-com bust, technology is the
catalyst in the planned law-firm merger of San Francisco's
Pillsbury Madison &AMP; Sutro with New York's Winthrop, Stimson, Putnam
&AMP; Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   The combination, announced Monday, will give Pillsbury a sizable
presence in New York, where it can pursue securities underwriting
as well as mergers and acquisition work for its Bay Area tech and
other clients, Marina Park, the firm's managing partner, said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Pillsbury, founded in 1874, operates a small New York
office with just one partner and two or three associates.
</P>
<P>
   Winthrop, founded in 1868, also gives Pillsbury a significant
overseas presence, with offices in London, Tokyo, Hong Kong and
Singapore. Half of Winthrop's revenues come from outside of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Winthrop, meanwhile, will be able to tap into Pillsbury's
technology business. Winthrop ``has a very strong capital and
finance practice and a nascent technology practice that they very
much want to grow,'' Park said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is expected to be finalized by year end. The combined
firm, which will be called Pillsbury Madison, will have some 860
lawyers and 16 offices. As measured by combined 1999 revenues, it
will be the second-largest law firm in the Bay Area and the
18th-largest in the United States, according to American Lawyer, a
trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Park said she expects Pillsbury Madison to become the largest
Bay Area law firm by 2001, barring any mergers by its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury has been building its technology practice since 1991,
when it opened a Menlo Park office specializing in intellectual
property. That office later moved to Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Pillsbury expanded its intellectual property business
by merging with a boutique firm, Cushman Darby &AMP; Cushman of
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the ability to serve those clients on a global
basis,'' said Park. Tech companies ``as well as our Fortune 500
clients, are going global very rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm's technology clients include dot-coms WebEx and
Support.com and Kinera, a maker of ``unified messaging'' software.
Kinera is just a few months old but is already asking for legal
advice as it plans a global expansion, Park said. ``A lot of
Silicon Valley companies are global just by their very nature,''
Park said.
</P>
<P>
   For Fortune 500 clients such as Chevron, the New York office
will allow Pillsbury to handle projects that require loans, such as
for building large power plants overseas. Typically those deals are
handled out of New York or London.
</P>
<P>
   The Winthrop merger is a key step in an ongoing effort by
Pillsbury to boost its revenues and its reputation. During the
1990s, the firm was plagued by lackluster revenues, high staff
turnover and a reputation as being somewhat sleepy.
</P>
<P>
   Park and Chairwoman Mary Cranston were put in charge in January
1999 with the mandate to turn things around. They immediately
raised the number of hours associates and partners are required to
work and tilted compensation more heavily toward the firm's biggest
rainmakers.
</P>
<P>
   They also formulated a vision statement and a strategic plan
that included boosting the firm's New York and overseas presences.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the firm's total revenues rose to a healthy $252.6
million, which translates into compensation per partner of
$506,000. Winthrop's compensation per partner is similar, about
$520,000.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's goal is to be among the top 25 percent of law firms
in terms of per-partner revenue. ``So far, we're ahead of that
target for this year,'' Park said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
