<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-PETTY-TEX     07-19 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PETTY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KYLE PETTY TO DRIVE SON'S CAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In rolling tribute to his late son, NASCAR driver Kyle Petty
plans to replace Adam Petty as permanent driver of the No. 45 car
in the Busch Grand National Series later this summer and take the
entire team to the Winston Cup ranks beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Petty's return to the BGN series fulltime, scheduled to
begin at Darlington Raceway on Sept. 2, signals a major
restructuring at Petty Enterprises. Petty, 40, will relinquish his
seat in the No. 44 Hot Wheels Pontiac Grand Prix, which is
scheduled to be driven for the final 11 races of the season by
former Cup regular Steve Grissom.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty, 19, was killed while practicing his Busch car at New
Hampshire International Speedway on May 12. The first
fourth-generation athlete in any sport, Adam Petty made his Winston
Cup debut at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth on April 2. He was
scheduled to graduate to the Cup ranks fulltime beginning in 2001,
and carry on the family legacy begun by NASCAR pioneer Lee Petty
and seven-time Cup champion Richard Petty, Kyle's father and Adam's
grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a doubt that a Petty should be driving that
\RNo. 45\S car. I'm just taking up space,'' Kyle Petty said
yesterday afternoon. ``Adam's accident happened on a Friday. On
Monday, I went to his shop and talked to his entire group. From
that day forward, that was Adam's car and Adam's team. We never got
the opportunity because of the accident to do what we wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's a personal thing. I want that car to succeed. We
want to take the 45 car and win races with it, so I can prove _
probably to myself _ that I gave Adam everything I could have given
him so that if things had worked out, he could have won races.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty's No. 45 BGN Chevrolet Monte Carlo is sponsored by
Sprint, and the long-distance telephone company will continue next
year when Petty Enterprises switches manufacturers to the Dodge
Intrepid R/T.
</P>
<P>
   Petty also announced that Mattel's Hot Wheels brand would end
its primary sponsorship of the No. 44 car at season's end, although
the toymaker plans to continue as a major associate on the Cup cars
Petty Enterprises will field for Petty, John Andretti and Grissom
beginning in 2001. Grissom currently drives the No. 43 Dodge for
Petty Enterprises in the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series. He will
compete in both series through the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of eight Cup races, Kyle Petty first drove Adam's BGN
car at Dover, Del., on June 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a better race car driver, I'd probably be running
better right now,'' said Petty, who scored a fifth-place finish at
Nazareth Speedway on Sunday. ``To run fifth, it makes you feel like
you can run a race car again.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty also said that driving Adam's car has helped him
emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the car, we haven't changed anything, no matter
how strange that sounds,'' Petty said. ``It still says `Adam Petty'
on the car \Rroof\S. It's still Adam's seat, Adam's steering wheel.
For me to get in the car and sit in the same seat and drive with
the same wheel and look out the window ... I know he's been there
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound strange, but with the loss we've experienced, it
makes me feel so much closer to him. For me, that's comforting.
That's helping me, and I cherish it right now.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
