<SLUG> BC-FBN-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSIVE TACKLE WILLIAMS A HOLDOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ It just wouldn't be a Cowboys training
camp without a little strife.
</P>
<P>
   All the positive vibes of the first day of ``Camp Campo'' were
interrupted yesterday by an old-fashioned holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran offensive tackle Erik Williams didn't report with the
rest of the team Monday and was still nowhere to be found when the
Cowboys took the field for practice yesterday at Midwestern State
University.
</P>
<P>
   A source said Williams' absence is rooted in his desire to
restructure his contract. Williams, 31, is signed for two more
years. He is scheduled to make $1.9 million in 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' agent, Alan Herman, was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said the situation is disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erik Williams is obviously not here; we're real disappointed
that he's not here,'' Jones said. ``What his status is and where we
go from there will just have to evolve. That's an internal matter
and we'll see how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the 10-year veteran is subject to being fined up to
$5,000 for each day he misses.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, however, said he has not decided if the Cowboys would
levy a fine against Williams at this point. And while he was
disappointed, he also said he was not surprised by the the player's
absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we basically counted heads yesterday, we thought he might
be a late arrival, but then we started visiting with his agent and
realized he wouldn't be here,'' Jones said. ``I had a good visit
with him last week and we were aware of the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Williams' issues have more to do with his status and
future on the field than money. Jones, however, refused to
elaborate any further.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my understanding that he is mulling his professional
options,'' the owner said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who made the Pro Bowl for the fourth time last season,
had been slowed during the off-season after elbow surgery to remove
bone chips. The 6-foot-6, 311-pounder, however, is fully recovered
and has been cleared by doctors for training camp.
</P>
<P>
   While Williams does have two years left on his contract, there
has been some speculation that this could be his last with the
team. Solomon Page, last year's second-round pick, is considered
the team's right tackle of the future. If the Cowboys cut Williams
after the 2000 season, they would only have to eat $1.4 million in
pro-rated signing bonus money.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while Williams' holdout is putting a hitch in the
Cowboys' plans for this season, it is giving them a glimpse of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Page, who was expected to replace Everett McIver at right guard,
replaced Williams in the starting lineup at tackle yesterday.
Free-agent signee Jorge Diaz, who started in Tampa Bay the past few
years, played right guard. Veteran backup Tony Hutson will
alternate with Diaz at guard in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Page will know both spots,'' offensive line coach Hudson Houck
said. ``But right now, we're looking at it like he is going to be
our right tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo downplayed Williams' holdout, terming
it a business decision, and said that he would not consider it
anything major unless Williams is out for a few weeks. However,
like Houck, he said he has a lot of confidence in Page.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Solomon Page,'' Campo said. ``I like him a lot. He may
be the best athlete of the whole group on the offensive line. He is
very talented. He is going to have to come to the front. I'm
confident he will be able to step in and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Page said he would like to see the Williams' situation resolved
because ``Erik is a friend of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he did not hide his personal excitement about returning
to his ``natural position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't bother me,'' Page said. ``I'm a natural tackle. I
don't expect to have any problems at tackle.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
