r s BC-FBN-COWBOYSOFFENSE-TE     07-19 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS </SLUG>
 OFFENSE-TEX 
Cowboys' swift wide receivers at the center of offensive attack 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Troy Aikman liked what he saw yesterday.
What he saw was Joey Galloway or Rocket Ismail running under balls
that Aikman lobbed to open areas in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams will have to honor the speed we have this year,'' Aikman
said at the start of training camp for a third consecutive summer
at Midwestern State University. ``Teams will have to decide on how
they want to play us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys plan to use training camp as an open-air laboratory
to create an offense resembling what the Cowboys used during their
Super Bowl years, with modifications such as the ones implemented
last season by the Super Bowl champion St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge in this training camp is to really get this
thing going offensively,'' said Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, who
invested handsomely this off-season to add speed to the offense,
namely speed receiver Galloway and tight end Jackie Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway, who signed a seven-year, $42 million deal, including a
$12.5 million signing bonus, is one of the fastest players in the
NFL. Harris is a wide receiver in a tight end's body. Both players
are part of what should make the Cowboys more difficult to defend
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is going to change the most about this offense is,
hopefully, we're going to be a little more unpredictable than we've
been,'' said head coach Dave Campo, the former defensive
coordinator who is using his past to make suggestions that should
make the Cowboys more problematic for opposing defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be times when we're more of an
off-the-seat-of-our-pants operation, which puts pressure on the
defense,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who turns 34 in November, is the centerpiece of
offensive coordinator Jack Reilly's offense.
</P>
<P>
   After two seasons in New England, Reilly and Ernie Zampese have
returned as offensive coordinator and offensive consultant,
respectively. Virtually the entire offense was put in during two
minicamps and two quarterback schools this off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The old offense with a new look is designed to take advantage of
Aikman's ability to read defenses and hits spots. Now the ``spots''
are simply moving faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously have a real deep threat now,'' said Aikman,
referring to Galloway and Ismail, and Harris running the big-play
routes down the middle that haven't been seen since Jay Novacek
retired three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has found a comfort zone with Ismail, who is starting his
second season with the Cowboys, although he is still adapting to
Galloway's speed. It's easy to underthrow both of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey is a flyer,'' Aikman said. ``If we keep throwing into the
wind like we did today, I'm not going to have an arm by the end of
training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo sees the addition of Harris and rookie running back
Michael Wiley, who will compete with Chris Warren for the job of
third-down back, as important keys to success ``because there is
going to be some double-coverage on those wideouts, I can promise
you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman is coming off what he admits to be a ``disappointing''
season, both from a team standpoint (8-8) as well as individually
(17 touchdowns, 12 interceptions, two concussions). Physically,
though, Aikman is fine. He hasn't even talked to a neurosurgeon
since November.
</P>
<P>
   Learning the offense and adjusting to his new offensive
teammates now have his total attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be naive in saying that we'll be where we
eventually want to be when training camp is over \Rug. 18\S,''
Aikman said of the pass offense. ``But I certainly believe we'll be
where we need to be to at least be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   When the games begin (July 30 vs. Pittsburgh), Reilly will call
the plays. Zampese, 64, will provide the expertise, serving purely
in a consulting role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernie Zampese is a tremendous asset because he has seen
everything that you can see in the NFL,'' Campo said. ``Plus,
there's a calming effect that Ernie has with Troy.''
</P>
<P>
   And, after all, this training camp is about Aikman and the
offense. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
