<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6288 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PERRY--ENTREPRENEUR-S     07-19 1499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERRY--ENTREPRENEUR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EYE FOR ONLINE OPPORTUNITIES LED TO SUCCESS FOR VENTRO FOUNDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY PETER SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE SENIOR WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ David Perry, the 32-year-old founder and chief
executive of Ventro Corp. in Mountain View, helped invent the
business-to-business online marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Like many pioneering entrepreneurs, Perry didn't start off with
a grand vision. But he had the intelligence, fortitude and
competitive spirit to spot opportunity when it arose and then do
something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when Perry was simultaneously studying for an
MBA degree at Harvard University and heading a biotech startup, he
saw a huge opportunity for industries with lots of buyers and
sellers to eliminate inefficiency and make more money by handling
procurement online.
</P>
<P>
   Today, this is a major part of the B2B market that analysts
project could be worth between $2.7 trillion and $7.3 trillion
within four years.
</P>
<P>
   Perry's company seeks to serve a big chunk of it, and Wall
Street was enthusiastic, at least at first.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, the company went public under its previous name,
Chemdex, and soared from its offering price of $15 to a peak
$239.81 in late February. Since then, it has gone into a tailspin
along with many other Internet infrastructure companies and
dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ventro's stock is trading at $23.25 a share, and Perry's
approximate 5 percent slice of the company is down from more than
$500 million to a mere $51 million. But Perry remains upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Arkansas in a house with concrete floors and two
years ago had a negative (net worth) of $200,000,'' he said. ``I
try not to run the company by the stock price.''
</P>
<P>
   Becoming a successful entrepreneur takes an ability to roll with
the punches and the plunges.
</P>
<P>
   Perry did not originally plan to land in business at all. He
attended the Air Force Academy but a serious shoulder injury not
only knocked him out of varsity football, it dislocated his chances
of becoming a fighter pilot.
</P>
<P>
   So Perry switched to the University of Tulsa in Oklahoma,
studied chemical engineering and went to work for Exxon. By age 26,
he was managing a $200 million piece of the Benicia oil refinery in
the East Bay. Then it occurred to Perry that because the oil
business was growing at what he jokingly calls ``a blistering 11/2
percent-a-year pace,'' it would be wise to jump into higher-growth
high technology.
</P>
<P>
   However, companies such as Intel and Cisco would not give him
the same management responsibilities he had at Exxon, where he had
a couple hundred people reporting to him. So he went to Harvard to
earn an MBA degree and make himself more marketable.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to studying entrepreneurship, Perry wanted more
hands-on experience. So he teamed up with two Harvard and
Massachusetts Institute of Technology scientists to write a
business plan for a biotech company.
</P>
<P>
   While his partners worked on ways to create tests for HIV and
other viruses that would show the degree of infection rather than
just indicate positive or negative, Perry handled the business
side. That entailed working 15 to 20 hours a week negotiating
equipment and real estate leases, hiring employees and managing
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Virogen's goal of revolutionizing viral testing was not
commercially feasible, it dawned on Perry that going through
catalogs to find and buy chemical agents, beakers and thousands of
other supplies was inefficient. The process and paperwork were
similarly tedious for the buyers of Virogen's initial products.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on his experience at the biotech startup with his
classroom insights into the Internet, Perry envisioned an online
marketplace that might connect more than 5,000 suppliers with
250,000 life scientists who buy materials for pharmaceutical and
biotech firms as well as government and academic labs.
</P>
<P>
   Perry's new enterprise, dubbed Chemdex over beers in his Boston
apartment, started in mid-1997. It received early financing from
Genentech founder Robert Swanson, who died last year, and venture
capital firms CMGI and Bay City Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Chemdex charges a 2 to 12 percent fee per transaction. Its
customers include major pharmaceutical, biotech and academic
customers including Bristol-Myers Squibb and SmithKline Beecham.
</P>
<P>
   With one market up and running, Perry began looking at how he
might get more bang for the buck out of Chemdex's experience and
investment of more than $100 million in technology. It turned out
that the template for the life sciences products industry could be
used to transform the business supply chains of other industries
that are characterized as ``fragmented'' for having many suppliers
and differently priced products.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large number of buyers and sellers is a good sign of
inefficiency,'' said Perry.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Chemdex established a holding company called Ventro
Corp. to provide e-commerce software and other services to Chemdex
and its growing lineup of other online marketplaces.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Chemdex, Ventro has started five operating
companies: Amphire Solutions to serve operators, distributors and
suppliers of the $150 billion U.S. food service market; Broadlane
and Promedix for hospital and medical supplies and services;
Industria Solutions for the fluid processing (oil to shampoo)
market; and Ventro Life Sciences to serve Europe's scientific
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health care, food services and life sciences are non-sexy
industries,'' said Perry. ``But tens of billions of dollars of
goods are bought and sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ventro was one of the first companies to develop B2B
infrastructure services, it is not alone. Hardly a day goes by
without news of a new online buying consortium such as Johnson &AMP;
Johnson banding together with Baxter International and other
providers to create a health care marketplace or Ford, General
Motors and DaimlerChrysler starting an exchange for the automotive
industry.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 600 online marketplaces and thousands more
anticipated in the next few years, Perry acknowledged that ``the
current B2B landscape looks like a game of 6-year-olds playing
soccer, with everyone crowding the ball and no obvious strategy for
getting the ball into the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he believes B2B e-commerce is unlocking
significant value for buyers, sellers and companies such as Ventro
that bring them together. Perry is not the only believer in his
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perry was one of the first to see the opportunity for online
exchanges for buyers and sellers in fragmented industries,'' said
venture capitalist Brook Byers of Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers,
who succeeded Swanson as Ventro's chairman. ``When he started, B2B
was not in the lexicon.''
</P>
<P>
   AMR Research recently ranked Chemdex, which generated nearly all
of Ventro's $23 million revenues in the first quarter, as the No. 2
net marketmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Group analyst Lisa Williams is confident Ventro will be a
survivor. ``They are first mover in many markets. They don't have
all their eggs in one basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they are not just putting up marketplaces to see if people
will come; they have backing from people with authority in each
supply chain they go after,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is keen on Ventro. David Hines, president of
Avalon Research in Boca Raton, Fla., believes B2B marketplaces such
as those offered by Ventro and rival SciQuest are not much
different from electronic catalogs provided by companies such as
Fisher Scientific. ``We question what value is added,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hines also is concerned that Ventro's vendors have nonexclusive
contracts that allow them to create competing electronic solutions.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, he feels that Ventro and others distort the market
potential by talking about the dollar value of all sales
transactions instead of their fees from those deals. ``It's like
Realtors talking about the value of the houses they sell rather
than their commissions.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines' bottom line: ``The business model is unlikely to produce
a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry and his backers disagree. They say &UR;  &LR; Ventro not only will
be profitable but has plenty of cash. Although it has cumulative
operating losses of about $150 million, it has close to double that
in cash reserves.
</P>
<P>
   On the golf course, Byers said that Perry always likes to
``swing for the green'' and that he takes the same approach in
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aggressive,'' Perry agrees. ``My philosophy is to hit
away; it's easier to correct on the short distances.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ventro already serves industries with total sales of
$500 billion, Perry is aiming much higher. ``The gross domestic
product _ all goods and services _ is our potential market,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pausing for a second, he amends that: ``Actually, it might be
bigger. We have international aspirations as well.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
