<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6289 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAYCOLUMN-TE     07-19 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYES OF TEXAS, FOOTBALL WORLD STILL ON AIKMAN
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Was Troy Aikman really that busy in the
off-season? Did he use his power and influence to mastermind the
firing of Chan Gailey? Did he demand a return to the Norv Turner
offensive system? Did he strong-arm Jerry Jones on getting
free-agent receiver Joey Galloway signed?
</P>
<P>
   As those questions were asked yesterday, Aikman stood in the
middle of the practice field at Midwestern State University, and a
smile spread across his sweaty face. It wasn't, however, a ha-ha
kind of smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not exactly amused,'' Aikman said, ``but more like amazed.
None of it is accurate. But I do understand why some people might
feel that way, although I obviously don't like my name being
associated with something like Chan being fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, it's there, although voices within the Cowboys'
hierarchy say that among players who have the ear of Jones, and
among key assistant coaches, Aikman's private comments on Gailey
were basically nonexistent compared to the others.
</P>
<P>
   But Aikman became the lightning rod the day Jones held the press
conference to fire Gailey in January. Jerry dumped the hot rivet in
a certain lap when he said he wanted to return to an offense that
Aikman was comfortable with. What were people supposed to think,
particularly when Aikman went a week without publicly attempting to
defuse what Jones had said?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, however, the quarterback was in shock for that week after
hearing Jerry link him directly to the firing. ``I was watching at
home on TV, I heard that, and I wanted to kick in the screen,''
said Aikman, smiling again and shaking his head. Then again, he
shouldn't have been surprised _ the owner and the quarterback
always have had a close relationship. Jerry rarely makes a major
personnel move at Valley Ranch without somehow connecting Aikman to
it. And with or without Troy's approval.
</P>
<P>
   But for those keeping score at home, that's two consecutive head
coaches at Valley Ranch supposedly done in by the muscle of Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize as much as anybody, how disruptive to our football
team the firing of head coaches has been,'' Aikman said. ``It is
the one area where you have to have stability, and we've been just
the opposite. I know there were reasons behind what happened to the
three previous head coaches since I've been here. But if we are
ever going to get back to where we need to be, this has to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   It was interesting that Aikman was nowhere to be seen or heard
when Jones went looking for a new head coach. His respect for the
two in-house candidates, Dave Campo and Joe Avezzano, kept the
quarterback very neutral. But it was also a given that with either
of the assistants, or even if a longshot candidate from the outside
had been hired, that the old offense was coming back. Aikman admits
he thought that was very important.
</P>
<P>
   So now, here the Cowboys are, in training camp again, and
attempting to follow a football theme that Campo coined as the
third head coach in four summers: ``An old plan for a new future.''
</P>
<P>
   It also comes with the territory that the Campo era is opening
with a noose attached to Aikman's neck, more so than even with the
new head coach.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a flood of media opinions that Aikman is on the
spot as never before in his career. Why? Because Jones supposedly
has given him everything he wanted _ Gailey gone, the old offense,
the quality receiver, etc. Therefore, Aikman must now reverse a
career that has been trending downward the past few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It's silly stuff, actually. When has there not been pressure on
Aikman, going all the way back to the beginning of the Jimmy
Johnson regime when many of us thought Johnson wanted Steve Walsh
as his quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   Same ol' story for all quarterbacks _ no one receives more blame
when things are going badly, or more credit when things are going
well. But that goes double when your name is Aikman and your team
is the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard it, and I've read it about all the new pressure on
me, and my response is ... well, actually it'd be best if I not
give my response to that,'' Aikman said. ``But what have people
been watching all these years if they think that? Yes, the pressure
is immense. But is that new? I accept it. I don't try to dodge
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another twist is that while the Cowboys have been regarded as a
fading team the past three seasons (and have performed as such),
the negative on Aikman is he's not what he has been at QB. So is
that him, or is that the talent around him, or both?
</P>
<P>
   One way or the other, answers will come this season. And so will
either blame or praise, making it nothing more than another typical
season for Aikman. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 0109EDT &QL; 
