<HEADLINE>
YOUNG PITCHERS GET CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With Esteban Loaiza going to the bullpen and
Mark Clark released, manager Johnny Oates said Ryan Glynn and Matt
Perisho will be given every opportunity to establish themselves as
major-league starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want them looking over their shoulders or to feel that
one bad pitch is going to get them sent to the minors,'' Oates
said. ``Certainly they're going to be evaluated, and at some point
we have to see improvement. But I'm not basing my opinion on one or
two outings; it will be 10, 15 _ and in some cases _ 30 outings.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates also said going with Glynn and Perisho instead of Loaiza
does not mean the Rangers are giving up on the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us the best chance to win now,'' Oates said. ``We
gave the veterans a chance first, Clark and Loaiza. Now we're going
to see how this works. I don't see it as an experiment; it gives us
a chance to win right now and will enable to make decisions at the
right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Davis stays in the bullpen as the second left-hander but
Oates said, ``I'll make sure I see enough of him, too.''
\Nsubheds:Loaiza accepts move Esteban Loaiza accepted his move to
the bullpen without complaint yesterday, although he knows there's
a good chance he could be traded within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do anything about it,'' Loaiza said. ``I can't be
upset because I know I've been struggling. We'll just see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, who irked Johnny Oates by being late to the clubhouse
Monday, said he doesn't want to be traded but admitted it's a
strong possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here, and I like it here,'' Loaiza said. ``But I
really can't do anything about it; that's not my decision.'' OLIVER
BEFORE PERISHO
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates has decided to pitch Darren Oliver tomorrow
against the Anaheim Angels and move Matt Perisho back one day to
pitch against the Seattle Mariners. Both are left-handed, but Oates
wants Perisho to pitch against Seattle's predominately
right-handed-hitting lineup. Left-handers are hitting .389 off him
this season, and right-handers are hitting .253. Oliver, who will
face the Angels' predominately left-handed lineup, has been tough
on left-handers in the past, but they're hitting .338 off him this
year and hit .325 off him last year. MARTINEZ WANTS TO STAY
</P>
<P>
   Count outfielder Dave Martinez among the Rangers' potential free
agents who want to be back next year. Martinez has been with three
clubs this season and six in his 15-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it here,'' Martinez said. ``I think this team is going
to be fine. It's just a young team that needs a little time to
develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, acquired June 9 from the Chicago Cubs, has been
platooning in right field with Chad Curtis and went into last
night's game hitting .259 with the Rangers. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   -- Reliever John Wetteland fulfilled a boyhood dream yesterday
when he met Giants Hall of Famer Willie McCovey and got his
autograph. Wetteland, who grew up in North California, said, ``The
only two autographs I wanted growing up were McCovey and \RNolan\S
Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Frank Catalanotto entered yesterday's game with eight
pinch-hits, second most in the American League and the most by a
Rangers player since Geno Petralli had eight in 1992. The club
record is 12, set by Bill Stein in 1980 and tied by Kevin Reimer in
1990. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
