<SLUG> BC-INTEL--EARNINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INTEL PROFITS UP DESPITE CHIP DELAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY DAN FOST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a booming tech market, you can always count
on Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest chipmaker reported record revenues for the
second quarter Tuesday, with net income soaring 79 percent to $3.14
billion (45 cents per share).
</P>
<P>
   Intel said revenue will continue to rise. If there was anything
to darken the sunny picture the company painted Tuesday, it was
that the Itanium chip _ which will ultimately supplant Intel's
flagship Pentium processors _ will be further delayed and won't
start selling until the fourth quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Joseph Osha of Merrill Lynch and Co. said the delay
should not hurt the big picture for Intel. ``Nobody thought Itanium
would do much for them this year,'' Osha said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's biggest challenge lies in merely meeting the demand for
its products, as the growth of the Internet fuels a seemingly
insatiable appetite for high-powered computer chips. Santa Clara's
Intel and its chief rival, Advanced Micro Devices of Sunnyvale, are
both showing signs of robust financial health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel's way out in front. It'll take AMD a long time to catch
them,'' Osha said. ``At this point, both companies are trying to
keep up with demand.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Intel chief executive Craig Barrett said the
implementation of new manufacturing technology will allow Intel to
squeeze more chips out of a single silicon wafer, which ``will
allow us to substantially increase second-half supply to help us
meet this anticipated strong demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the three months that ended July 1 was $8.3 billion,
up 23 percent from the second quarter of last year, when the
company reported revenue of $6.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A significant part of the strong revenue jump came from interest
and other income _ essentially, $2.34 billion in gains on
investments, mostly the sale of stock in Micron Technology.
</P>
<P>
   But Intel also shipped a record number of microprocessors, as
well as record amounts of flash memory _ the chips used in wireless
devices such as cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's stock this year has reflected its leadership in a
healthy business climate. Before yesterday's numbers were released,
Intel shares closed at $143, down $3.31. Earlier in the day, the
stock hit a 52-week high of $147.50.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Dan Fost at  &LR; fostd &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
