<SLUG> BC-GLF-BURCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE CHAMPION SAW TIGER'S PROMISE EARLY
</HEADLINE>
 REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hail him as a visionary. Discount his comment as premature
hyperbole. Either stance, at this juncture, is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   But don't accuse Peter Thomson, a five-time British Open
champion, of piling on in the rush to project Tiger Woods as the
youngest golfer to complete a career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 24, can capture his fourth major championship at this
week's British Open. If he hoists the claret jug Sunday on the Old
Course in St. Andrews, Scotland, Woods will have won each of golf's
major titles one time. He will join Ben Hogan, Jack Nicklaus, Gene
Sarazen and Gary Player as the only players to hit for the cycle in
professional golf.
</P>
<P>
   By doing so, he would fulfill the predictions of countless Tiger
praisers who have overloaded the bandwagon since Woods won the U.S.
Open by a startling 15 strokes June 18. And he'd make a prophet of
Thomson, who uttered these words in 1997:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would win every time on the Old Course at St.
Andrews,'' Thomson said after watching Woods finish 24th in the
1997 British Open, his first professional appearance at golf's
oldest major championship. ``Better get a bet down on him for 2000.
I could see him going around in 64 every day. I think he'll win by
a mile.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Thomson's sentiment is the prevailing one in
professional golf circles. If Woods plays St. Andrews with the same
focus and flair he exhibited last month at Pebble Beach Golf Links,
he'll make Thomson's observation the most valuable potential
investment tip since Bill Gates alerted friends he was launching a
computer software venture called Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Roll back the calendar to the summer of 1997, when Woods began
retooling his swing and triggered a stretch where he won one PGA
Tour event in 17 months, and you could have gotten 100-1 odds
against him winning the 2000 British Open. Maybe 200-1. Now, he's
an even-money proposition, with 12 victories in his past 22 starts
at tour events. He's won two of the past three majors.
</P>
<P>
   And he's clearly smitten with the notion of a slam-clinching
victory at St. Andrews, the course where the first documented round
of golf was played in 1552.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no better site to have it occur than at the home of
golf,'' Woods said. ``That's where it all started. Every person who
has ever played the game has wanted to win a British Open at St.
Andrews ... If I could somehow be fortunate enough to play well and
get that claret jug, it would be a good feeling. That's something I
would love to have happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win major championships in the same year at Pebble Beach
and St. Andrews, it doesn't get much better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The topper, of course, would be achieving a career grand slam _
and golf immortality _ at 24, two years younger than Nicklaus. For
anyone else, surpassing the Golden Bear would rank as a daunting
mental stumbling block. For Woods, it's par for the course.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, at 24, already has 20 victories on the PGA Tour.
Nicklaus, at the same age, had 12. Woods has won major
championships by 15 and 12 strokes, two of the three biggest
landslides in golf history. Nicklaus never lapped an elite field by
more than nine strokes, his winning margin at the 1965 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Woods has shown a flair for the dramatic while
dominating professional golf for the past 14 months. That's why St.
Andrews _ with its wide fairways, driveable par-4 greens and
unmatched history _ seems the perfect backdrop for Woods to etch
his name into golf lore by becoming the fifth player to complete a
career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first shot is fired at the 2000 British Open, there
is a thick air of inevitability about its outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Tiger doesn't win at St. Andrews, there should be a
stewards' inquiry,'' said Sir Michael Bonallack, former
administrator of the Royal &AMP; Ancient Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger is playing better than he ever has,'' said Butch Harmon,
Woods' instructor. ``His swing ... is pretty easy to tweak if
something goes wrong. If he plays good golf, he's going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If history unfolds at St. Andrews, remember that Peter Thomson
told you so. And he did it three years before the rest of the golf
world joined the chorus.
STANFORD GRANTS FATHER'S OFF-THE-CUFF WISH TO CADDIE AT OPEN
</P>
<P>
   Steve Stanford considers himself living proof of a time-honored
adage: Be careful what you wish for because you just might get it.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Stanford wished himself into a caddie's vest for
tomorrow's opening round of the U.S. Women's Open at the Merit Club
in Libertyville, Ill. That is where his daughter, TCU graduate
Angela Stanford, will make her debut in an LPGA Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about 500 people who would do a better job for her
than I would,'' Stanford said. ``But I remember once, when she was
young, she asked, `If I ever make it, what would you want?' I
mouthed off and said, `I'd like to caddie one time at the U.S.
Open.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, he gets his chance. His daughter wouldn't have it any
other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to do it ... for a lot of emotional reasons,'' said
Angela Stanford, whose Open gallery will include several friends
and family members, as well as longtime instructor Amy Fox. ``He
helped me get started in the game. He always made sure I had
options and did the right thing. He talked me into seeing Amy. I
thought it would be neat for him to be inside the ropes with me at
my first Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties agree this will be a limited engagement. Steve
Stanford described both himself and his daughter as
``hard-headed,'' which could make for a combustible combination.
Because of that, Angela said the two will huddle before tomorrow's
opening round to define the caddie's role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, he still sees me as a 12 year old. We're going to
have to have a little talk about that,'' said Angela Stanford, 22,
a member of the U.S. team that won the 2000 Curtis Cup, the Ryder
Cup equivalent for women's amateur golf.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Stanford nodded and laughed. He vowed to let Angela call
the shots at the Merit Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll offer her advice, but she's the boss,'' he said. ``I'll
carry the bag. I'll give her the yardage. But she'll make the last
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties, in turn, figure to leave the Open with a
once-in-a-lifetime experience.
CHIP SHOTS Open overlap With 52 weeks available on the calendar,
why would golf's big cigars pick the same one to contest both the
British Open and the U.S. Women's Open?
</P>
<P>
   Good question.
</P>
<P>
   Simple answer: Scheduling conflicts at the Merit Club in
Libertyville, Ill., site of the Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   Originally selected to play host to the event in 1999, officials
at the Merit Club requested a switch to 2000 when the 1999 PGA
Championship was booked at Medinah (Ill.) Country Club, another
course in suburban Chicago. Their wish was granted. In selecting
dates for 2000, tournament officials sought at least a two-week gap
from the Western Open (July 6-9), the PGA Tour's annual stop in the
Chicago area.
</P>
<P>
   Based on available dates at the Merit Club in 2000, that made
this week the best option, even though it coincides with the
British Open. U.S. Golf Association officials characterized the
overlap as a one-year aberration and said steps will be taken to
prevent future overlaps. SPECIAL OPPORTUNITY
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lopez, 43, said she hopes to make the most of a special
exemption into the U.S. Women's Open field granted by USGA
officials. Lopez will be making her 20th career appearance at the
Open, where she has three runner-up finishes but no victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had to qualify for the Open, so I was flying around
the house when they told me about the special exemption,'' said
Lopez, an LPGA Hall of Famer with 48 career victories. ``For me,
missing the Open just wouldn't be right. I need to be there. And I
plan on being more prepared for this tournament than any I've
played this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez finished second at the 1997 Open, the only time in the
past four years that she's survived the 36-hole cut. As for her
chances to win this week, two months after gall bladder surgery,
Lopez said: ``The older you get, the less chance you have to do it.
If I never win an Open, I would have to say something would be
missing in my career. But it's not in God's plans if it doesn't
happen, and I just have to accept that.''
LPGA GOLDEN MOMENTS June 6, 1999
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate the LPGA Tour's 50th anniversary, the
Star-Telegram will feature a significant moment in tour history
each week this season.
</P>
<P>
   Juli Inkster rolled to a five-stroke victory at the U.S. Women's
Open, posting the lowest total in relation to par (16 under) of any
player in tournament history. With rounds of 65-69-67-71, Inkster
broke even-par 72 each day at Old Waverly Golf Club in West Point,
Miss.
</P>
<P>
   By finishing at 16-under, Inkster established a record for
lowest finish in relation to par of any player at a U.S. Open,
men's or women's. Tiger Woods set the men's mark June 18 at Pebble
Beach Golf Links, where he shot 12 under and won by 15 strokes.
Hale Irwin bettered both totals July 2, winning the 2000 U.S.
Senior Open by finishing at 17 under.
</P>
<P>
   Both Inkster and Woods will be in the spotlight this week.
Woods, 24, seeks to become the youngest player in history to
complete a career grand slam by winning the British Open. Inkster,
40, will defend her U.S. Women's Open title at the Merit Club in
Libertyville, Ill. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
