<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN'S OPEN EXHIBITION NO SLAM DUNK FOR JORDAN
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIBERTYVILLE, Ill. _ He reigned as ESPN's top athlete of the
20th century. But Michael Jordan was no match for three U.S.
Women's Open competitors in a three-hole exhibition yesterday at
the Merit Club.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan posted the highest score on each hole during the
competition, with Jordan and teammate Nancy Lopez losing all three
holes to Laura Davies and Meg Mallon in a best-ball match. Davies
birdied all three holes.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the Jordan-Lopez team came to a birdie was on the
first hole. Lopez missed a 3-foot birdie attempt after Jordan
hooked a drive into the woods and picked up his ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need much humbling. I know I'm a hack,'' said Jordan,
a member of the Merit Club. ``I got beat by everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, president of basketball operations for the Washington
Wizards, said his best round at the course was a 69, but that came
``three years ago, when I didn't really have a job.''
</P>
<P>
   As for a pretournament favorite, the NBA legend identified
defending champ Juli Inkster, rather than any of yesterday's
playing partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a putter's course,'' Jordan said. ``I would pick Juli
right now. When she gets that putter straight, she can shoot some
low numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster expressed surprise at receiving the nod.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm honored,'' Inkster said. ``I didn't even know he knew who
I was.'' STANFORD OPTIMISTIC
</P>
<P>
   Angela Stanford, a TCU graduate, said she was pleasantly
surprised by how crisply she struck the ball yesterday in her
initial practice round at an Open venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary. I don't like to be hitting it this good this early
in the week,'' said Stanford, 22, an amateur who is making her Open
debut. ``There's too many days left in the tournament for things to
change. But that's a good situation to deal with. I like the fact
that I'm hitting everything solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, an All-American who won four college tournaments
during the 1999-2000 season, practiced yesterday with two-time Open
champ Hollis Stacy and two teammates from the 2000 U.S. Curtis Cup
team: Carol Semple Thompson and Robin Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford said she liked the Merit Club layout (6,540 yards, par
72), which plays to her strength as a long hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fairways are pretty generous, bigger than I expected,''
Stanford said. ``And the greens are holding, at least for now. I
really like it. I think I can do well here.'' ROUGHER ROUGH
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year's event, when unseasonably cool temperatures in
Mississippi prevented the rough from filling in at Old Waverly Golf
Club, fairways at the Merit Club are ringed by thick, 3-inch rough.
Karrie Webb, a five-event winner this season on the LPGA Tour,
predicted the winning score would not be better than 6-under par.
That's 10 strokes higher than Juli Inkster's 16-under total in
1999, a tournament record.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Davies concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to keep it out of the rough,'' Davies said. ``It's
hard to deal with. I tried to move the ball out of the rough
\Ryesterday\R, and it really grabbed hold of my back. It got my
attention.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
