<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS MIGHT LOSE FREE-AGENT GUARDS DAVIS, BUCKNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The agent for Mavericks free-agent guards Greg Buckner and
Hubert Davis said yesterday that his clients might be better served
by leaving Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kauffman said Davis is entertaining several multi-year
offers and Buckner would prefer not having the Mavs match his
three-year offer from Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the league leader in 3-point shooting last season, signed
a six-year deal for $4.2 million with the Mavericks three years
ago, with an opttion to leave after the third season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a deal under market value because that's all the
Mavericks could do back then,'' Kauffman said. ``Hubert waited for
this day with the understanding that he would be rewarded. Now that
looks like it's out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs are offering Davis a one-year deal at $3.5 million.
Davis is in the market for a three- or four-year contract starting
at Sacramento, Boston and New Jersey are among the teams that have
shown interest and Celtics coach Rick Pitino is scheduled to visit
with Davis today.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Mavs' deal is for more this season, Kauffman said
Davis is looking for the security of a longer contract. Kauffman
said he did understand the Mavs' dilemma regarding Davis. The Mavs
could be up to $19 million under the salary cap next season and are
hesitant to sign their free agents, such as Davis and Gary Trent,
to long-term deals.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the promises made to Davis were in the previous ownership.
Kauffman is expected to talk about Davis' situation with new Mavs
owner Mark Cuban today.
</P>
<P>
   With Buckner, the Mavs have the right to keep him by matching
Vancouver's three-year, $2.5 million tender offer. After Buckner
signs the offer sheet, the Mavs have 15 days to match it or the
team will lose him. The first day free agents can sign is Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mavs' glut of guards, Kauffman said the second-year's
guard development is better served with the Grizzlies, where
minutes figure to be more plentiful. Kauffman wouldn't confirm that
the Mavs offered Buckner a two-year deal at the NBA minimum, but
the agent did say the Buckner wasn't happy with the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great situation in Vancouver,'' Steve Kauffman said.
``They stepped up and went after him.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
