<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6297 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-GONZALEZCOLUMN-TE     07-19 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE LABOR WAR RAZES BASEBALL, ENJOY WHAT A CARPENTER HAS BUILT
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One does not have to be Nostradamus to foresee dark days ahead
for the sport of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations of Major League Baseball's blue-ribbon
committee _ increased revenue sharing and luxury taxes and other
measures that could curb the free-spending habits of some teams _
aren't likely to pass muster with the union, even if commissioner
Bud Selig can convince the owners to go along.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, another labor war looms. At this time next year,
the stories surrounding baseball will focus on the possibility of a
strike by the players to pre-empt an off-season lockout by the
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon to a ballpark near you: no baseball.
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason to savor this season, to relish every
unexpected Chicago White Sox victory, every Randy Johnson
strikeout, every Mark McGwire home run (so just where will the big
guy end up on the all-time list when the next strike/lockout forces
him into premature retirement?).
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason to appreciate the feel-good stories of the
year, to thrill at every Andres Galarraga smile, every Kerry Wood
pitch, every Geraldo Guzman victory.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, perhaps the casual fan _ an endangered species to be sure if
there's another work stoppage _ isn't familiar with Geraldo Guzman.
An introduction is in order.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman was a carpenter in his native Dominican Republic less
than two years ago. Monday, he pitched eight shutout innings in the
Arizona Diamondbacks' 7-0 victory against the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a shot in the arm,'' Diamondbacks manager Buck
Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   And not just for a team struggling to hold on to a tenuous lead
in its division. A story like Guzman's _ a story of perseverance,
of overcoming odds, of unlikely success _ provides a lift for an
entire industry that's all too often dragged down by matters of
money.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, who should give a bonus to their entire
scouting department, have uncovered several overlooked gems. Closer
Byung-Hyun Kim signed out of Korea. Reliever Vicente Padilla signed
out of Nicaragua. Slugger Alex Cabrera signed after a season with
the China Trust Whales in Taiwan's Chinese Professional Baseball
League. Productive first baseman Erubiel Durazo signed out of the
Mexican League.
</P>
<P>
   None of those stories, though, can match Guzman's.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman was signed by the Montreal Expos in September 1989, when
he was 16, and pitched decently in two seasons in the Dominican
Summer League. But he sustained a shoulder injury, and was released
after the '91 season.
</P>
<P>
   He went into carpentry, an honorable profession, and figured
that would be his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really think I would be back in baseball,'' Guzman
said.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't play baseball for the next six seasons, but, in 1997,
Diamondbacks part-time scout Rafael Mena convinced him to pitch in
weekend pickup games. Junior Noboa, the club's Latin America
coordinator, like what he saw and arranged for Guzman to play in
Taiwan in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona then signed the pitcher to a minor-league deal, and,
after Guzman pitched well in the Dominican Winter League, the
Diamondbacks decided to protect him on the 40-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman began the season at Double-A El Paso, and was promoted to
Triple-A Tucson in June. He made it to the majors July 6. Pitching
for a first-place team in front of more than 36,000 fans in
Houston, the erstwhile carpenter held the Astros to one run in
eight innings of a 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where he's come from, from what he's had to overcome, I
don't think he would consider this pressure,'' Showalter said.
``Getting through what he's gotten through to get to this point is
a lot more pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Guzman, 27, throws a hard, sinking slider and a lively fastball.
He has allowed only one run in 16 innings. Monday, he struck out
nine, walked three and allowed only two runners to reach second. He
retired 13 of the last 14 batters he faced and threw 70 of his 108
pitches for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   After the club built a big lead, he nailed down the victory.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great story.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman will have time to relive it by reading his scrapbook
during the next strike. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
