<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS IGNORE WRITING ON WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Right fielder Orlando Palmeiro will run through
walls for his Anaheim Angels teammates, as he tried to do Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The problem he had was that the wall didn't give, Palmeiro hit
the ground hard and Ruben Rivera rounded the bases with an
inside-the-park home run that allowed the San Diego Padres to tie
the game with two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Garret Anderson didn't trail the play, making it
possible for Rivera to circle the bases. But the Angels benefited
from a misplay by Padres right fielder Eric Owens one inning later
and managed to escape with a 3-2 win in 11 innings before 21,835 at
Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After Owens misplayed Troy Glaus' two-out, 11th-inning blooper
into a triple, Padres closer Trevor Hoffman threw a wild pitch and
Glaus scored the winning run. Al Levine (2-2) pitched a scoreless
10th and 11th to earn the win for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wild finish to what had been a relatively quiet game,
thanks to Angels starter Ken Hill and Padres starter Brian
Tollberg. Hill gave up one run and four hits in six innings;
Tollberg gave up two runs and four hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took a 2-1 lead into the bottom of the ninth and were
on the verge of winning it, considering closer Troy Percival
appeared unhittable. He struck out Bret Boone and Ben Davis with
overpowering fastballs. Strike three to Davis was clocked at 98
mph.
</P>
<P>
   Percival got ahead on Rivera 0-2 with two fastballs, then threw
another that Rivera was able to hit to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro raced back on the ball, but instead of playing it off
the wall and holding Rivera to no more than double, he tried to
make a heroic catch. He crashed into the wall and fell hard onto
the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to get it, but it carried a little more
than I thought it would,'' Palmeiro said. ``When I hit the wall, I
had no idea where (the ball) was.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson failed to back up the play from his center-field spot,
making his move to the ball only after Palmeiro hit the ground.
Palmeiro eventually retrieved the ball himself and threw it to
cutoff man Benji Gil, whose throw home to catcher Bengie Molina was
too late to get Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Anderson's failure to back up Palmeiro even more
notable was that only last week the center fielder failed to back
up Tim Salmon in right field on a ball hit off the wall in right by
the Dodgers' Adrian Beltre. Beltre ended up with a triple and
eventually scored the winning run in the 10th inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that happened and I'll learn from it,''
Anderson said. ``If I was the reason we went extra innings; I'll
take the blame for it. I'm not going to make excuses. If we had
lost the game, I would take the loss on my shoulders. There was a
lot of finger-pointing last year, but that's not going to happen
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't get on somebody for not being where he should be,''
Percival said of Anderson. ``He knows it. If I throw a curveball in
the dirt, the game's over. You start finger-pointing and it gets
right back at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia spoke with Anderson about the play but also praised
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Garret's played excellent center field in his first
full season out there,'' Scioscia said. ``There are going to be
plays he has to learn to react to. He has to experience things. He
gets good jumps on the ball and he's done a good job coordinating
things out here. There are going to be plays (where) he has to make
adjustments, and he will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
