A6303 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-2NDLD-W     07-19 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DELAYS TRIP TO REMAIN AT PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs top of story for updating about Clinton's decision to stay at
talks another day)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ In an effort to finalize a Middle East peace
accord, President Clinton has delayed his trip to Japan by one day
and will stay at Camp David with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, the White House
announced just after midnight on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton now plans to leave for a summit meeting in Japan of the
seven leading industrial nations on Thursday morning, giving him at
least another 24 hours to urge the two leaders to come to an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The chief White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said the
president believed that delaying his departure was in the best
interests of the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations, described as increasingly intense and heated,
were still going after midnight, the third straight night of very
late talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still at it,'' a White House spokesman, P.J. Crowley,
said at 12:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to stay at Camp David appeared to reflect the up
and down twists of the talks. On Tuesday, it seemed that the
impossible might be possible: an agreement on all the issues,
including Jerusalem. At other times, the temperature fell to the
more sober expectation of a modest agreement and a second meeting
before Mr. Arafat's Sept. 13 deadline for declaring a Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
   The Haaretz newspaper in Israel reported in its Wednesday paper
that negotiations were focused on what the paper described as a
package of American-mediated proposals on the ``core issues of
borders, refugees and Jerusalem.'' The paper said Arafat had yet to
approve the proposals, implying that Israel had.
</P>
<P>
   The article said that under these proposals Jerusalem would
remain united under Israeli sovereignty, that major settlements on
the West Bank would be annexed by Israel and that Palestinian
refugees could return to Israel only for family reunifications and
without Israel accepting any responsibility for their original
expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the account said, Israel would agree to ``broad
autonomy'' for Palestinians in East Jerusalem, and to accept some
one hundred thousand Palestinian refugees into Israel. According to
this report, Israel could end the summit meeting with a ``partial
accord,'' which would include its recognition of a Palestinian
state.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment on the report from negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the Israeli delegation have called home in the
last 24 hours, leaking news that the question of Jerusalem had been
under discussion since Monday and hinting at progress on this most
intractable issue.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Arafat was reported to have called his headquarters
in Gaza and told his aides to spread the word that he was
considering packing his bags and leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides were playing to their constituents, and preparing
public opinion for posssible outcomes. Arafat, presumably, was
showing that he was not going to give up on his long-held stance
that East Jerusalem must be the capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the same script, Barak was demonstrating that he was
a man of reason, and was prepared as Israel television reported
Tuesday night to make ``unprecedented steps'' toward the
Palestinian position on Jerusalem. If an agreement were not reached
on the future status of Jerusalem, Barak would be able to say that
he had tried his best and that the Palestinians were unmovable.
</P>
<P>
   But that Jerusalem was on the table was itself progress over the
seven-year time line of negotiations between the Palestinians and
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was astonished by the degree of progress in the last few
hours,'' said an Israeli who was in contact with the delegation by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Only several months ago, Jerusalem was a virtually taboo subject
in back-channel talks in Stockholm, where the top negotiators of
Arafat and Barak met and made progress on a variety of issues.
These included what might constitute the territorial boundaries of
a Palestinian state and what would be the fate of the 3 million
Palestinian refugees scattered across the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   But on Jerusalem, there was only generalized talk in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports attributed to Israeli officials, the
Israeli delegation at Camp David was presenting a plan that would
incorporate the Israeli bedroom communities that are now a de facto
part of the capital into the legal entity of Jerusalem. Among the
West Bank settlements near Jerusalem being mentioned are Maale
Advmim and Givat Zeev.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for areas populated by Palestinians, such as
Beit Hanina and the Shuafat refugee camp, to be placed under
Palestinian control. The moves together would provide more
demographic balance in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But this version of a solution for Jerusalem leaves unanswered
the top concerns of Arafat, who has insisted all along that East
Jerusalem, annexed by the Israelis in the 1967 war, should be the
capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   From the Palestinian point of view, the Israeli plan does not
deal with the heart of the matter: it leaves under Israeli
sovereignty the Old City of Jerusalem, home of the main religious
sites of Judaism, Islam and Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been reports that Arafat has stood firm on
Jerusalem, insisting that no agreement can come out of these
negotiations without Palestinian control over the Al Aqsa Mosque
and the Church of the Holy Sepulcher.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, stood studiously above the
fray on the issue of Jerusalem. He did not utter the word Jerusalem
or mention any of the other substantive matters, such as
Palestinian refugees or the boundaries of a new Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, through the release of bits of minutae on who was
meeting with whom or who was not meeting with whom, he depicted
Clinton as a president waiting to do some down-to-the-line
persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   Now into the eighth day, the negotiations have produced a
roller-coaster of emotions, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go through various emotions, ranging from moments where
you see promise, to moments where the only thing you see is
frustration,'' Lockhart said. ``Not only the president, the leaders
and all the delegations, have run the entire range over the last
eight days.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that the technique of ostentatiously threatening to walk
out has been used in the past _ Anwar el Sadat of Egypt packed his
bags at Camp David 22 years ago, and Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel
did the same at Wye, Md., three years ago _ Lockhart was asked if a
similar approach had been made this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I know of,'' Lockhart said. ``It would be a long
walk. You've got to go all the way down the mountain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 0125EDT &QL; 
