<HEADER>
A6305 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f BC-AMWEST-AZR &LR;      07-19 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
  
AMWEST &HT;    BC-AMWEST-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    AMWEST 3-MONTH EARNINGS FALL 21%(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By PETER CORBETT(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Some of the pain America West passengers have been
feeling lately is finally being felt by the airline.
</P>
<P>
   America West on Tuesday reported a 21percent drop in profits for
its second quarter, largely because of soaring fuel prices and
problems maintaining its planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem in two words is maintenance reliability,'' Douglas
Parker, the Tempe-based airline's president, said in a conference
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not delivering to the gate reliable aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline, with the worst reliability record of the 10 major
U.S. carriers, escaped the quarter without the series of
cancellations that stalled passengers in February and earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   But pressure on the airline's profits may not abate for the next
few months: jet fuel prices remain high and monsoon weather
typically disrupts flights during summer storms.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, more than 40percent of America West's flights were
delayed, in part due to storms at its Phoenix and Las Vegas hubs.
On-time results only improved a few points in August.
</P>
<P>
   America West's competitors appear to be faring better.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines said Tuesday that earnings surged
13percent, and Southwest Airlines reported a 21percent jump in
profits. Both companies said an increase in passengers offset
higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed that America West didn't show sustained
improvement in operations yet,'' said Brian Harris, who follows the
airline industry for Salomon Smith Barney in New York. ``It's the
same thing that plagued them in the first quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   That is driving away many higher-paying business travelers who
can't depend on America West, according to airline industry
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   More business travelers would flee America West for a more
reliable carrier if they weren't so hooked on its frequent-flier
miles, said John Andrews, owner of Global Travel Management in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, overall bookings remain strong and are in
line with industry trends.
</P>
<P>
   America West filled 73.7percent of its seats in April, May and
June, up 4.7points from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   America West flew 96.1percent of its flights during the quarter,
up from 95percent in the first quarter. The industry average is
98percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel costs are the biggest cloud on America West's horizon. Fuel
expenses were up 57percent in the second quarter, to $83million,
and ticket surcharges did not come close to offsetting the higher
jet fuel costs, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   A $30million increase in fuel expenses in the second quarter
accounted for about 40percent of the company's $75.4million
increase in operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, second-quarter net income declined to $33.5million,
down $8.8million from a year earlier. Earnings per share of 91
cents were 2 cents higher than analysts' estimates. The earnings
included a gain of $6.2million, or 17cents a share, from the sale
of a stake in the Leisure Co., a vacation package business.
</P>
<P>
   America West's revenue was up 9.1percent in the second quarter,
to $604.8million.
</P>
<P>
   The company saved $6million in fuel costs in the quarter by
hedging, or locking in lower fuel prices in advance.
</P>
<P>
   But it decided against much hedging the rest of this year
because there weren't any bargains on the market, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   America West has partial hedging positions on 17percent of its
fuel purchases in the third quarter and 5percent in the fourth
quarter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That could prove costly if prices don't moderate. Crude-oil
prices, an indicator for jet fuel prices, could level off or
decline as oil nations begin to increase production.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said America West must do a better job of preventive
maintenance and be more efficient in repairing aircraft. The
airline is in the midst of an industrywide safety audit by the
Federal Aviation Administration after a review of Alaska Airlines
maintenance following a January crash.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of America West closed down 50 cents on Tuesday, at
$17.75.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Peter.Corbett(a)Arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republic.com or (602) 444-4815.
</P>
</TEXT>
