<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6307 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-DOMESTIC-AZR &LR;      07-19 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMESTIC-AZR </SLUG>
  
The Phoenix City Council quietly and unanimously passed a policy
giving health and life insurance benefits to the families of
same-sex and heterosexual unmarried partners beginning Aug. 1. &HT;    
 &HT;    BC-DOMESTIC-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    A QUIET VICTORY FOR GAYS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By PAT KOSSAN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - The last time the Phoenix City Council ruled on an
issue involving homosexuality, it faced a crowd of 3,000 warring
citizens monitored by police in riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   This time, nobody noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Which, some say, was exactly the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Aug. 1, same-sex and heterosexual unmarried partners
of city employees will for the first time be eligible to share city
health, life and other insurance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded benefit was contained in city union contracts that
the council unanimously, and quietly, passed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the city's Gay and Lesbian Employees Association,
unable to get a majority of council members to publicly
support &UR; domestic-partner benefits, said they finally turned for
help to the city's unions, representing about 8,300 of the city's
12,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Most union benefits are routinely extended to non-union
employees to save the city extra administration costs. All five
unions negotiated the domestic-partner benefits into their two-year
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Was this part of a strategy to keep this whole thing quiet?
</P>
<P>
   No, said Michael Ingersoll, assistant personnel director .
</P>
<P>
   Not really.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had that effect. It made it easier for everyone to deal
with,'' he said. ``But I wouldn't call it a deliberate effort to
depoliticize it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not at all what we did,'' said Mayor Skip Rimsza, who
called the new benefits a way to compete in a tight job market.
``It's just part of a modern labor contract. It's not tied at all
to a gay and lesbian issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kelly Armstrong, a city accountant and founding member of
the Gay and Lesbian Employees Association, has a different take.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terribly political,'' he said. ``We didn't want it to
turn into another debacle.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he wanted to avoid a repeat of the 1992 meeting
where City Council members, two wearing bulletproof vests, faced
off with 3,000 citizens at the Phoenix Civic Plaza over the city's
effort to include sexual orientation in its internal
anti-discrimination policy.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, council members approved the addition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a city policy issue, and a public debate was
appropriate, while this is a wage and benefit issue,'' said Vice
Mayor Doug Lingner, who wasn't on the council in 1992. Lingner said
domestic-partner benefits weren't a high priority with the council,
but were important to many union members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lets employees know we are listening to them,'' Lingner
said.
</P>
<P>
   The successful pairing of Phoenix's gay and lesbian employee
group with the unions ``will have wide-reaching effects,'' said
Armstrong, who expects more cities to begin using unions to aid in
passing similar measures and prevent political headaches for
elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps by keeping the heat off them,'' he said, ``and the
issue out of their laps.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the Phoenix Firefighters Association said they
didn't care about politics, they care about their members and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our members were in a situation where their dependents
and domestic partners were not covered for medical and dental and
some surplus life insurance,'' Capt. Tim Knobbe said. ``That's why
we supported it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was simply an idea whose time had come to Phoenix, Ingersoll
said. Phoenix competes in a market filled with municipalities,
including Tempe, Tucson and eight other Western cities, along with
many private companies, that already offer domestic-partner
benefits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the city approved domestic benefits for 45 employees, 26
of them to cover heterosexual partners and 19 same-sex partners, at
a cost to the city of $170,000.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify, partners must sign a notarized statement annually
that they have lived together for at least a year, are not related
and are financially interdependent, such as owning joint checking
accounts, mortgages or leases.
</P>
<P>
   Tucson has provided domestic-partner benefits to same-sex
couples since 1997. About 15 to 25 of its 5,000 employees sign up
each year at a cost to the city of about $25,000, Tucson officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe started providing benefits to same or opposite-sex
domestic partners last year, a spokeswoman said. Of about 15,500
employees, 23 employees and one retiree take advantage of the
policy, at a cost to the city of $52,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Pat.Kossan(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8960.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
