<HEADER>
A6317 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HEAT-SUMMER-LADN     07-19 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-SUMMER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT IS HERE TO STAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRENT HOPKINS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The San Fernando Valley paid up Tuesday for a
summer of cool temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Chatsworth broke a 2-year-old record when thermometers hit 105
degrees, an afternoon high that was shared by Woodland Hills.
Northridge reached 102. At the University of Southern California,
where Los Angeles' official temperature is recorded and shared with
the rest of the world, the temperature gauge topped out at 87.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotter weather seems more noticeable because it's been
cooler lately,'' said Bruce Rockwell, a meteorologist with the
National Weather Service. ``But, in fact, we have days all the time
like this during the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this summer.
</P>
<P>
   June saw only a few temperatures that were slightly above the
normal average of 86 degrees. July has actually seen temperatures
nearly 10 degrees below the normal 95 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only halfway through the summer,'' Rockwell said. ``A
lot can happen in the next two months.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not good news for some.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the heat,'' said Marcy Liu, who owns Liu's Won Moo
Hapkido studio in Northridge. ``We've got to keep the air
conditioning on all the time, so my electricity (bill) is going to
be huge this month.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief won't be coming soon. Temperatures in the Valley are
expected to reach the 90s to lower 100s for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a bad thing for people who work outdoors,''
said Brian Budworth, 22, of Glendale, while seeking cool comfort
from Foster's Old Fashioned Freeze in Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely opposed to all this hot weather,'' he
deadpanned before breaking into a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people opposed to the heat are hitting the beach. Chuck
Moore, a lifeguard at Zuma Beach, said the temperatures there have
averaged about 65 degrees during the day, drawing thousands.
</P>
<P>
   For Moore, the working climate is a breeze. Not so for Mark
Dennett, who's working on a supermarket construction project in
Encino and building up a heat immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pain to work outside right now. Once you get outside,
you build up a tolerance, though,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Daily News Staff Writer Orith Goldberg contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 0259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 02:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6318 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u v BC-ELIMINATE-HERB-SALES-     07-19 0027
</HEADER>
