<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 07:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6369 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i PM-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0719-C     07-19 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 PM-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0719-COX &HT;    CLINTON DELAYS JAPAN TRIP, TAKE MIDEAST SUMMIT TALKS INTO
OVERTIME
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Casting crucial Mideast peace talks into extra
innings, President Clinton scrubbed a scheduled visit to Tokyo
early Wednesday, hoping to push Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
the final painful steps toward an accord to end their 52-year-old
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned to go ahead with a second leg of his long
planned trip to Japan, leaving Washington Thursday morning, a day
later than he was originally slated to depart.
</P>
<P>
   The decision buys Clinton up to 24 additional hours to try to
wrest a peace agreement from a Camp David peace summit that
stretched into its ninth inconclusive day early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials announced the schedule change at 12:30
a.m. (ET) Wednesday, as Clinton and top U.S. diplomats pressed
forward with marathon talks between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still at it,'' National Security Council spokesman
P.J. Crowley told reporters at 12:30 a.m. (ET).
</P>
<P>
   With the long-term adversaries still at odds over issues
centered on territory, security, the future of Jerusalem and the
question of Palestinian statehood, Clinton determined that
extending the negotiations for one more day offered the best chance
for a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president regrets that he will have to delay his trip to
Japan for one day,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said in a
prepared statement issued from Camp David, five miles from this
Catoctin Mountain hamlet. ``The president believes this is in the
best interest of the Mideast peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had been due to arrive in Tokyo Thursday afternoon for a
bilateral meeting with Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   After cancelling that leg of his trip, Clinton planned to leave
Washington Thursday morning and go directly to Okinawa _ the
southernmost island in the Japanese archipelago _ in time for what
had always been the main event of his visit: the annual summit of
the leaders of the so-called Group of Eight democratic powers.
</P>
<P>
   As negotiations intensified at Camp David late Tuesday, Lockhart
said Clinton's mood has swung with the atmospherics inside Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like all of them, you go through various emotions ranging from
moments where you see promise to moments where the only thing you
see is frustration,'' Lockhart said. In a word, though, he
described Clinton as ``determined,'' to broker a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Israeli radio was reporting Wednesday morning that
Barak is preparing to leave the Camp David summit talks despite
President Clinton's 24-hour delay. The radio report quoted a senior
Israeli source.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak is preparing to return home at the soonest moment after
it became clear to him that the Palestinians are not a true partner
for peace,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many rumors swirling around the tension-filled summit
for eight days, however, the source's comments could not be
confirmed here Wednesday. The participants have been operating
under a strict news blackout, broken only briefly by Clinton
himself in an impromptu interview with a New York newspaper on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between Arafat and Barak have run so high that, in
eight days of talks, the two men have held just two direct,
one-on-one meetings, the last of which was Saturday. Since then,
they've encountered each other only informally, at a meal, for
example, with others present and seated between them.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart stressed, though, that the lack of direct talks between
Barak and Arafat doesn't mean the negotiations have stalled. Much
can be done to narrow the gaps between them, said Lockhart, by
using Clinton as an intermediary and a buffer to preserve what
diplomatic goodwill still exists between the Israeli and
Palestinian sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 52 years of debate behind them, so the atmosphere at
times has been tense,'' said Lockhart. ``But they are still working
at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
