<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6438 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN20-COX     07-19 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stage 4 water law: Get lost, newcomers
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With Austin residents using a record-setting
amount of water and putting a strain on the city's distribution
system, we present for your consideration Kelso's Stage 4 Mandatory
Water Conservation Program.
</P>
<P>
   Under Stage 4, people who have lived in Austin less than five
years will have to move to another town on days corresponding with
their home addresses.
</P>
<P>
   If the last digit of your house number is three or six, you'll
have to move out of Austin on Tuesday, so call Mayflower
immediately. Those with house numbers ending in four or five have
to leave Wednesday. Zero and nine have to go Thursday, and one and
eight have to be out of town on Friday. Two and seven gotta go
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The city regrets the inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   City officials realize this isn't fair, especially since so much
gas has been blown up your skirts by the city and the Chamber of
Commerce to get you newcomers to move here. You came here after
much huffing and puffing by the city about what a great place this
is to start up a business. Some of you may have even been offered
tax incentives to sucker you into moving here.
</P>
<P>
   Well, we're sorry that we can't keep up with your demands, but
that's just too darned bad. We just can't get enough water out
there to accommodate the growth. Oh, we'll have this mess fixed in
a couple of years. Improvements to the city's water system should
make mandatory watering restrictions a thing of the past by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what? This is 2000. So come back in two years.
Meanwhile, pack the minivan, get your sorry butt out of here and go
somewhere else. I understand Buffalo is nice this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   We'd also like to apologize to you about the roads. You may have
noticed that while we didn't have the water treatment capacity to
serve y'all, we also didn't have enough roads built to service
y'all, either. We just didn't plan ahead. We know it. Boy, are we
sorry. But there's not much we can do about it except tell you to
split. Call us when you get there.
</P>
<P>
   Stage 5, incidentally, is expected to start in a couple of
weeks. Stage 5 is really ugly. You don't even want to hear about
Stage 5.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I'm just kidding about Stages 4 and 5, and right now
we're really in Stage 2 of water rationing in Austin. Under Stage
2, you can water your yard every five days, determined by your
address.
</P>
<P>
   But the really fun part is that if you see watering abuses, you
can call the city at 512-499-2199 and turn in your neighbors.
There's nothing quite as satisfying as ruining somebody's day with
a simple self-righteous phone call to the authorities, is there?
You know that jerk whose kid is learning to play the trombone about
10 feet from your bedroom window? Here's your chance to fix his
horn.
</P>
<P>
   There's probably some old trout living on a fixed income on your
street who is a little nearsighted and therefore is watering about
three inches into the road. Go ahead. Turn her in and make her life
miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you could always call 499-2199 and ask them if they
have Prince Albert in a can.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at 512- 445-3606 or at
jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6439 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN20-COX     07-19 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courting revival of city hub
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1850, the people of Montgomery County, Ohio invested the
staggering sum of $100,000 to erect what U.S. Magistrate Judge
Michael Merz calls the ``finest remaining example in the nation of
Greek Revival Temple-style architecture in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's what Merz would call foresight.
</P>
<P>
   In this century, it seemed that every 30 years or so, somebody
talked about tearing down the Old Court House. In 1968, a developer
proposed tearing down the building and putting a gas station in its
place.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's what Merz would call lack of foresight.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, farsighted city leaders stepped in, preventing the
kind of catastrophe that left Merz's mother crying on the steps of
Steele High School before her alma mater met the wrecking ball in
1955.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a BP station instead of the Old Court House. Here was
the site where Ohioians listened to an address by Abraham Lincoln,
rallied after the Great Flood, sold war bonds during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Merz thinks the Old Court House should be restored to its
original grandeur: ``You don't let the front steps of your house
deteriorate. You make them sparkle.''
</P>
<P>
   Merz, who is president of the board of trustees of the
Montgomery County Historical Society, is spearheading the
save-the-courthouse movement, a creative partnership of county
officials and the Historical Society. ``It is one of a kind in the
nation,'' Merz said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hackett, director of the historical society, called Merz
the ``sparkplug'' of the drive to restore the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Merz is so passionate about the Old Court House because
he understands that buildings do have soul, do have character.
``Having spent a good deal of my career in the Public Safety
Building, I know you don't require good architecture to provide
good public service,'' Merz told the Montgomery County Commission
on Tuesday afternoon. ``I'd describe that architecture as 1950s
Greyhound station.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps fearful of committing any further architecture crimes,
commissioners speedily approved the Partnership for History plan,
agreeing to spend up to $3.7 million on the courthouse and $200,000
on a feasibility study on the conversion of Memorial Hall into a
regional history museum, while continuing to serve as a memorial to
veterans. The county initially will spend $1.7 million on
structural repairs, while the Historical Society will launch a $2
million fund-raising drive to finance restoration of the interior.
</P>
<P>
   It's a partnership that has folks on both sides of the aisle
equally excited. ``This is my favorite project, something you don't
generally get to do _ the restoration of a building that is
timeless,'' said assistant county administrator Jim Dinneen.
``We're not restoring it as a museum, but as a center of
government, a live building.''
</P>
<P>
   A place for visiting dignitaries, swearing-in ceremonies,
state-of-the-city addresses, naturalization proceedings. A
community gathering place, once again, instead of merely a
community landmark. ``If you asked people to take a pushpin and
find the center of Dayton, they would pick Third and Main,''
Dinneen said. ``Yet very few go inside the courthouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Merz looks around him and sees millions being invested in the
baseball stadium, the RiverScape riverfront development, the
performing arts center. ``Here we have a gem in the middle of the
city,'' he said. ``How can we spend millions on these other
projects and let the courthouse sit in the heart of the city and
not improve it?''
</P>
<P>
   A good question _ and one that he has challenged all of us to
consider.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's what I call foresight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
