<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6458 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN20-COX     07-19 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida jury's verdict a reminder to Big Tobacco of its own
mortality
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big Tobacco may still own the Republican majority in Congress,
but the unregulated days of this deadly industry are numbered.
</P>
<P>
   No one believes that the tobacco industry will have to pay the
historic Florida verdict _ $12.7 billion in actual damages and
$144.8 billion in punitive damages to an unidentified half million
smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco stocks hardly flinched at the verdict, which will either
be sliced to the bone or, more likely, thrown out altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the tobacco companies once again walk away without
shelling out a single red cent, the industry took an old-fashioned
behind-the-barn whipping at the hands of a six-member Miami-Dade
County jury.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors sat through two years' worth of testimony. They
decided on the largest damage award in U.S. history in only five
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the verdict was stunning but not nearly as important
as the message the jurors sent to the tobacco executives and their
protectors in Congress: Tobacco bullies can be beat.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry has always enjoyed a privileged status
among other American businesses. It produces a legal product that
cripples and kills hundreds of thousands of Americans annually.
</P>
<P>
   No other product, including all illegal drugs lumped together,
comes close to killing as many citizens as tobacco. Yet this highly
addictive and deadly pro- duct not only remains free of government
regulation, it actually is subsidized by order of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Congress did the tobacco industry its biggest favor in 1965 when
it ordered cigarette packages to carry warning labels.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry wanted Congress to do this because the
warning labels made the industry bullet-proof in court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, tobacco industry executives stuffed more money into the
pockets of their congressional protectors and walked away with even
stronger warning labels. The labels were designed to usurp the
ability of Americans harmed by highly addictive tobacco products
from receiving damage awards. Plaintiffs could not easily claim
that they were not warned.
</P>
<P>
   Drug pushers should get Congress to put warning labels on
cocaine and heroin and make their products legal. That should solve
the drug problem. The only difference would be that cocaine and
heroin have never come close to killing and maiming as many
Americans each year as tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida jury sent a message to Congress and Big Tobacco that
warning labels on cigarettes do not inoculate the industry from
liability.
</P>
<P>
   This verdict coupled with several other court decisions in the
past several years indicates that public resentment over the
tobacco industry's history of deceit and arrogance has reached a
critical mass. The tide has shifted. That means Big Tobacco may
lose its traditional clout in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing what we know now, it's inconceivable that Congress would
permit the legal sale of tobacco if the product was just now
discovered and offered for sale to the American public.
</P>
<P>
   No lawmaker would dare support the sale of a product described
by medical scientists as more addictive than cocaine and more
deadly than world war.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, tobacco should not now be made illegal.
Prohibition was a disaster. There's no need to repeat that mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida jurors said they wanted to send a message even if
their verdict is overturned. They succeeded. The tobacco industry
can no longer push plaintiffs and jurors around.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the day is coming when protecting Big Tobacco will be a
political death sentence in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
