<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS20-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: FILE 1 of 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of money did the Wimbledon tennis tournament
winners receive?
</P>
<P>
   A: Pete Sampras, the men's singles champion, won 477,500 pounds
(about $723,500, depending on currency exchange fluctuations).
Venus Williams, women's singles champion, won 430,000 pounds
($651,500).
</P>
<P>
   Todd Woodbridge and Mark Woodforde, men's doubles winners, each
received 195,630 pounds ($297,000). Serena Williams and Venus
Williams, women's doubles winners, each won 176,070 pounds
($266,800). Donald Johnson and Kimberly Po, winners of the mixed
doubles, each received 83,100 pounds ($126,000).
</P>
<P>
   Total prize amount for Wimbledon's millennium championships was
8,056,480 pounds (about $12.2 million).
</P>
<P>
   Information online:
www.wimbledon.org/about/championships.htmlprize.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did Camp David get its name?
</P>
<P>
   A: Established in 1942 by President Franklin Roosevelt and known
initially as Shangri-La, the presidential retreat was renamed by
President Dwight Eisenhower in 1953 for his grandson, David
Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The death and career of actor Walter Matthau were well
covered by the media, but I never saw anything about his family.
Was he ever married? Any children?
</P>
<P>
   A: Matthau was married twice, first in 1948 to Grace Geraldine
Johnson, with whom he had two children, David and Jenny. They were
divorced in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 21, 1959, he married actress Carol Wellington-Smythe
Marcus, said to be the inspiration for Truman Capote's character
Holly Golightly in ``Breakfast at Tiffany's.'' They met when
Matthau starred on Broadway in ``Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter?''
She played a small role in it, acting under the name Carol Grace.
They had one son, Charles, who directed his father in a few TV
movies and the 1996 feature film ``The Grass Harp,'' which also
starred Jack Lemmon.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that a couple was detained at
Hartsfield International Airport in Atlanta because the woman
discovered a pistol in a carry-on bag and reported it to airport
police. The couple had flown to Atlanta from Little Rock, Ark. I
never saw any mention of how the bag got through security in Little
Rock in the first place. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Security guards in Little Rock made Alison Reed walk through
the security checkpoint twice, but never checked her bag, Reed told
police. Security officials at the Little Rock airport wouldn't
answer questions about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, a University of Arkansas student, and her husband, Jason
Combs, had just gotten married and were on their way to Cancun,
Mexico, via Atlanta when the incident occurred in May. After
reporting her discovery of the gun, Reed was held at the airport,
then jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Reed told officers the gun belonged to her mother, Tommie Reed,
since the bag also belonged to her. Her mother, who confirmed that
information with police, said she used it to shoot snakes at the
family farm.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Reed was dropped the next day after her
appearance in Municipal Court, and the newlyweds continued on to
Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I depend a good deal on closed-caption TV. How does it work?
Sometimes the words appearing on the screen are far behind the
spoken words, and there are many spelling errors. Do humans type in
the words, or is it done with computers that decipher speech?
</P>
<P>
   A: Several methods are used to provide subtitles, or printed
dialogue, for hearing-impaired viewers. When programs are
prerecorded for later broadcast, captions are typed into a computer
and added to the videotape before broadcast. If a script is
available, captions also are typed in advance for programs that are
broadcast live, and then are added to the TV signal during
broadast.
</P>
<P>
   For live ``real time'' broadcasts with spontaneous dialogue, the
dialogue is recorded by a ``stenocaptioner'' on a shorthand machine
linked to a computer. The computer produces encoded subtitles.
Unlike normal typists, stenocaptioners can write entire words or
phrases with a single hand motion known as a ``stroke.'' A
``misstroke'' won't have an incorrect or missing letter, but can
have entirely different words or phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Missing or dropped letters also can be the result of
transmission problems or poor reception.
</P>
<P>
   Information online: www.robson.org/capfaq/.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did cowboy-western actor Gabby Hayes ever win an Academy
Award?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Nor was he ever nominated for an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was surprised to learn that Elvis Presley had a twin
brother, although the brother died at birth. Was he a fraternal or
identical twin?
</P>
<P>
   A: Identical. Jessie Garon Presley was stillborn on Jan. 8,
1935. Vernon Elvis and Gladys Presley had no other children.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Both the play and the movie about Buddy Holly indicated that
his wife, Maria Elena, was pregnant at the time of Buddy's death.
What has beome of either her or the child?
</P>
<P>
   A: In a 1998 interview with the London Daily Telegraph, Maria
Elena Santiago Holly said she lost the child two days after Holly
died in a plane crash in Iowa on Feb. 3, 1959. Eventually she
married again and had three children by her second husband, but
continued to use the name Holly ``for reasons of the estate.''
</P>
<P>
   She told the interviewer that she operates an office in Dallas
from which she guards Buddy's image and name. She said she even
helped push through a Texas law that prevents the defamation of a
deceased celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Although she doesn't own the publishing rights _ Paul McCartney
has those _ nor the recording rights to Buddy's songs, she shares
royalties from the 50 songs Buddy Holly wrote, and the 50 or more
that he sang. Even so, ``I'm not rich, rich,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is sweet vermouth a red wine, a colored white wine, or a
liqueur?
</P>
<P>
   Daily Telegraph, Millis said Deutch had done enormous damage to
American intelligence capability through his ``incompetence.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, U.S. News &AMP; World Report said in its ``Washington
Whispers'' column that Millis had called Deutch the ``first-,
second-, and third-worst'' CIA director.
</P>
<P>
   Millis, 47, was found dead of an apparent gunshot wound June 4
in a motel room near Washington. A spokesman for the Fairfax City
(Va.) police said officers were called to the motel because a man
was threatening suicide. When they arrived, they found Millis'
body.
</P>
<P>
   Deutch is a controversial figure. His successor as CIA chief,
George Tenet, stripped Deutch of his CIA security access because
Deutch allegedly violated rules on safeguarding classified
material.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
