 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I get the absolutely correct time? When I try to
set my antique clocks by TV, I find there's at least a minute's
difference on various channels.
</P>
<P>
   A: Call this number for the master clock at the U.S. Naval
Observatory: 202-762-1401.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In weather reporting, I often see and hear references to a
``trace.'' Can you define that? How many ``traces'' make up an
inch?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the intensity of rainfall is too slight to be measured,
it's called a trace. So there's no way to judge how many traces
make up any measurable amount, because it cannot be measured.
</P>
<P>
   Other rain terms are more definitive. A ``light rain'' is more
than a trace, but less than 0.10 inch (2.5 millimeters) per hour. A
``moderate rain'' falls at rates from 0.11 to 0.30 inch (2.8 to 7.6
millimeters) per hour. A ``heavy rain'' falls faster than 0.30 inch
per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you list the U.S. presidents who were related to one
another, and the nature of their relationship?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the book ``Facts About the Presidents,'' John
Adams and John Quincy Adams _ father and son_ were the most closely
related presidents. Others: William Henry Harrison was the
grandfather of Benjamin Harrison; James Madison and Zachary Taylor
were second cousins.
</P>
<P>
   The book adds that genealogists have shown that Franklin Delano
Roosevelt was remotely related to 11 former presidents, five by
blood and six by marriage (names or relationships not outlined). He
also was a fifth cousin of Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why would a Russian be on the Tour de France racing team
sponsored by the U.S. Postal Service? Can you list all members and
their countries? Also, are team members paid?
</P>
<P>
   A: The team has 20 members, 11 of whom are Americans: Frankie
Andreu, Lance Armstrong, Dylan Casey, Tyler Hamilton, George
Hincapie, Marty Jemison, Kenny Labbe, Levi Leipheimer, Kevin
Livingston, Kirk O'Bee and Christian Vande Velde. The others: Jamie
Burrow (England); Julian Dean (New Zealand); Viatcheslav Ekimov
(Russia); David George (South Africa); Benoit Joachim (Luxembourg);
Patrick Jonker (Netherlands); Steffen Kjaergaard (Norway); Cedric
Vasseur (France); and Stive Vermault (Belgium).
</P>
<P>
   They are full-time professional athletes and employees of
Disson, Furst and Partners, a sports marketing firm in Sausalito,
Calif., said Margot Myers of the Postal Service. The slight
exception is Labbe, who is a letter carrier, but he also is paid by
Disson Furst when he races.
</P>
<P>
   Riders are selected to provide ``the best possible talent for
the team'' regardless of nationality, Myers added. ``We want the
riders who will get us the best results.''
</P>
<P>
   Disson, Furst negotiates contracts with the riders and pays
them. Contracts aren't public information, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service pays an annual fee to Disson, Furst and
Partners to be the title sponsor of the team. That amount isn't
made public either, Myers said. Other sponsors include Nike,
Yahoo!, Volkswagen, Trek (bicycles), Thomas Weisel Partners
Merchant Banking, Visa, Gatorade and various equipment suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Information online: http://www.uspsprocycling.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recall reading years ago about scientists seeding clouds in
an effort to produce rain. Whatever happened with that? Is it a
possibility to combat the drought in the Southeast this year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Research with cloud seeding began in the late 1940s after
World War II and continues today, but results have been
inconclusive, said Raymond Ban, senior vice president of
meteorology operations at the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Early experiments used dry ice crystals and, later, silver
iodide particles, he explained. The theory was that these particles
would serve as nuclei upon which water droplets would freeze, get
heavier, then fall, melt and produce rain. Recent experiments have
used nitrates or other chemicals that attract water so that even
when the humidity is relatively low, water droplets would condense
on the particles and produce rain.
</P>
<P>
   While there's some evidence that seeding may enhance rae
selected ``for their significance in American history as well as
for their aesthetic value,'' and cites as a reason for their choice
``the diversity of the designs.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has had 27 official flags and one unofficial
one (not including variations both official and unofficial found in
the arrangement of stars), according to ``The Flag Book of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of skier Jill Kinmont, an Olympic hopeful who
was in an accident some years ago that left her a quadriplegic? Two
movies in the '70s told her story, but I haven't seen or heard
anything about her lately.
</P>
<P>
   A: Kinmont was a 1956 Olympic contender in the slalom when she
suffered a tragic fall that ended her athletic career. But it
didn't end her life.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has said she suffered depression after the
accident, she was able to turn her life around and began a new
career as a teacher at Bishop Union Elementary School in her
hometown of Bishop, Calif. She retired in 1996, but continues to
volunteer at the school.
</P>
<P>
   She also continues her hobbies, a vegetable garden and painting,
and has become locally well known for her art. Her husband, whom
she married in 1976, frames her works.
</P>
<P>
   The movies about her were ``The Other Side of the Mountain''
(1975) and ``The Other Side of the Mountain, Part 2'' (1978). In
both films, Marilyn Hassett portrayed Kinmont.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The government of South Korea is issuing a medal to veterans
of the Korean War. Do you have any details? How do we apply?
</P>
<P>
   A: South Korea originally offered the Korean War Service Medals
in 1951 to all United Nations forces serving in Korea and adjacent
waters, but at the time U.S. law prohibited members of the military
from wearing medals issued by foreign governments. (DD-214 or
DD-215). National Guard members must provide their statement of
service equivalent (NGB Form 22). Applications will be accepted
through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Air Force Personnel Center, 1-800-558-1404; or
online at www.afpc.randolph.af.mil/awards; or write HQ AFPC/DPPPRA,
550 C St. West, Suite 12, Randolph Air Force Base, Texas
78150-4714.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ABC-TV recently broadcast Peter Jennings' ``The Search for
Jesus.'' Is a videotape available for purchase?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Call 1-800-225-5222 to order the two-hour documentary. A
spokeswoman said the cost is $34.95 plus $4.95 for shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The media always refers to the Confederate ``battle flag.''
Was there a national flag for the Confederate States of America,
and a separate ``battle flag''? Or was there only one flag?
</P>
<P>
   A: There were several Confederate flags.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars and Bars, adopted in 1861, had white stars for the
seven seceding states in a circle within a blue square at the upper
left of the flagu know?
</P>
<P>
   A: Friends of Allison was the name of the organization founded
by Alvin and Arline Atlas of Bethesda, Md., to fund bone marrow
testing. Their daughter, Allison, died of leukemia in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If something happens to a president-elect after election day
but before he takes office, what then? Is there another election?
</P>
<P>
   A: What would happen in this scenario is uncertain, according to
the National Taxpayers Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Electoral College is technically the official method our
political system uses to select a president. While the election
occurs in November, the Electoral College doesn't meet until near
the middle of December. During that time period, the issues of
disability and succession become murky, said the NTU's Pete Sepp
and Jerry Terry.
</P>
<P>
   The 25th Amendment and associated statutory law provide for
orderly succession if a president dies or declares his incapacity
to serve. Statutory law also addresses instances where a party's
bona fide nominee for president dies or becomes disabled between a
convention and a general election.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Ellis Katz, professor emeritus of political
science and fellow of the Center for the Study of Federalism at
Temple University, ``No provision is made for a disability that
occurs between the general election and the general meeting of
electors. At this time, the only constitutional solution is elector
discretion.'' This would seem to dissuade the holding of another
election, said the NTU.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's International Information Programs Web
site _ www.usinfo.state.gov/usa/infousa/politics/eleccol/katz.htm _
has posted Katz's commentary.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
