<HEADER>
A6475 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-FOOTBALL-HNS &LR;      07-19 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOOTBALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MILLER `SERIOUS' ABOUT `MNF' ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It's late in the fourth quarter, the Miami
Dolphins trail by two but are marching into New York Jets
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, sit down and shut up. Dan and Al have it covered.
</P>
<P>
   But say the same two teams are playing, and the Jets are beating
up on the Fish by four-plus touchdowns in the third, then Mr.
Miller, the stage is yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might be the place,'' Miller said recently. ``I don't
think I'm the most savvy guy about doing a football broadcast, but
I know when you got a game that's cooking, the last thing you want
to be is like the guy who is trying to score humor points. They
will crucify you for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, 38-6, beginning of the fourth quarter, everyone is going
to bed _ maybe I can try my act.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, there is never a dog game on ``MNF.''
</P>
<P>
   With just two weeks to go until the Hall of Fame Game and the
first preseason ``Monday Night Football'' telecast, the
reconstituted ABC crew gathered before the Television Critics
Association. It was an interesting but telling blunder that the
first question from a critic was directed to the ``cast.''
</P>
<P>
   It's show time.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a joke. By all accounts, the comic Miller has been
in intense training camp sessions with Al Michaels and fellow
newcomer, Hall of Fame quarterback Dan Fouts, practicing by calling
games from tape.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone involved with the telecast, from executive producer Don
Ohlmeyer on down, insists that Miller is not there just to provide
comic relief. Rather, ``Dennis will give us an attitude,'' which is
what Ohlmeyer also hopes to get from Fouts and fellow newcomers
Melissa Stark and Eric Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Miller insists that while he comes with a fan's perspective and
a comic's wit, he is not going to be lobbing endless punch lines.
Nor will he be lost by the complexities of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's football _ it's not like I'm on the medical channel,''
Miller said. ``I just don't want to convey that I'm going to be the
court jester. My prime directive is to be an integral member of a
three-man booth.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Miller is not treating this ``Monday Night Football'' gig
as a joke. He is 46, looking to go mainstream, and incredibly
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very serious about this _ very,'' said play-by-play man
Michaels, whose job will be to serve as traffic cop and know when
to go to Fouts (himself having a pretty decent sense of humor) or
Miller. ``He wants to do this perfectly ... he knows when he has to
be out (there); he has a great sense of timing.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for dropping obscure cultural references, Miller said he
will not dumb down for ABC. But the man known for launching F-bombs
on his HBO show ``Dennis Miller Live'' is prepared to go network:
Expect to hear him say ``Golly!'' a lot. Here's a hint: It's a code
word.
</P>
<P>
   He is counting on you knowing what he means.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
