</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6496 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-LONDON-CULTURE-$ADV22     07-19 1660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-CULTURE-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A NEW MULTI-RACIAL, MULTI-CULTURAL LONDON FACING
MULTI-CHALLENGES
 &HT;    (1200&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 23 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Take a walk in Brixton.
</P>
<P>
   Four miles from the gray postcard propriety of Westminster,
Brixton is a riot of noise and color.
</P>
<P>
   It pulsates with hefty bass riffs and reggae rhythms dancing
from knee-high speakers on the sidewalks outside CD stores and
appliance shops. In the borough's lively street market, you hear
the melodious sounds of Yoruba, Shona, Arabic, Spanish _
occasionally even English.
</P>
<P>
   The market's shops and stalls offer London's best Afro-Caribbean
and African fare _ plantains, caramel-colored smoked fish,
thermo-nuclear peri-peri sauce and yams. The air smells of scorched
coffee, limes and coriander.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, bright red double-decker busses _ the symbols
of familiar London seem drab in Brixton _ pass through, a reminder
that the heart of the Anglo-Saxon universe is a 10-minute commute.
</P>
<P>
   No less than Parliament House with Big Ben and Churchill's
statue, however, Brixton now is a part of the fiber of modern
London, a city rapidly being redefined by its ethnic variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multiracial London is coming of age, and it is this that is
igniting such energy, buzz and creativity,'' wrote Yasmin
Alibhair-Brown, a columnist for the Independent newspaper and
author of Who Do We Think We Are: Imagining the New Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation started at the end of World War II, when
Britain began accepting a substantial number of immigrants from
countries that for the most part had been colonies.
</P>
<P>
   Most settled in London's boroughs. Today, nearly 25 percent of
Londoners are from non-white minorities. In boroughs such as
Brixton, the percentage of non-whites is 40 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Wilson, a Brixton resident, came to London in 1952 from
Spanish Town in the hills above Kingston, Jamaica. Wilson, an
electrician, has raised children and now grandchildren in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still Jamaican,'' he says, buying a pair of fresh chickens
for his wife to grill. ``But these young ones, they are Londoners _
not Englishmen, mind you, but Londoners.''
</P>
<P>
   People here insist that London is no melting pot, as immigrants
don't shed their cultural identities in the process of
manufacturing a new one. Nor is London seen as a multicultural
mosaic on the order of Toronto or Chicago, which have ancient,
separate and sheltered ethnic neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In London, things are more fluid. With notable exceptions, few
neighborhoods could be called ``Little Delhi,'' ``Little Jamaica,''
or ``Little Lagos.''
</P>
<P>
   The Evening Standard perhaps said it best when it described
London as an ``ethnic kaleidoscope _ always shaking into a new
pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   This sprawling city of 8 million has 33 distinct ethnic
communities speaking 300 languages. One central London school
recently reported that its 800 students speak 79 languages at home.
At school they are unified in their struggle with English.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of this multi-ethnic seasoning is palpable. In fact,
the favorite food in Britain no longer is fish and chips or
steak-and-kidney pie _ it's curry.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon has sparked a wave of creativity matched only by
the bell-bottomed Carnaby Street revolution of the mid '60s that
introduced wide belts and frilly Edwardian suits to millions of
American closets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other place in the world like this city today,''
London musician Aki Navaz said recently in The New York Times. ``I
used to look through the windows at the white world. Now I know
that white kids are looking through mine, wanting to join in with
this energy.''
</P>
<P>
   London even has become a cultural center for other cultures. In
June, the best and brightest of ``Bollywood'' - the Indian version
of Hollywood - flocked to the Millennium Dome for the Indian
version of the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   With Britons, ``Bollywood'' takes a backseat only to Hollywood.
A new 30-screen cineplex is dedicating six screens to Bollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Three Bollywood movies, known as extravagant productions of epic
lengths and lavish musical interludes, entered the United Kingdom's
top 10 list this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mambo Sharman, one of the Bollywood awards organizers, said he
was amazed at this trend. ``Often I go past a cinema in London and
look at the queues for Bollywood films and there are as many white
faces as Indians,'' he said in a recent interview. ``It makes me
feel guilty for not going as often as I should myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Madame Tussaud's, the venerable British waxworks museum, soon
will add its first ever Bollywood display. And Andrew Lloyd Webber,
the superstar British musical machine with a keen sense of the
popular, is preparing to stage Bombay Dreams, a new musical set in
Bollywood.
</P>
<P>
   While it is an exaggeration to say non-whites now dominate the
London entertainment scene, the ethnic variety is nevertheless
remarkable. A number of black and Asian comedians _ notably Nina
Wadia and Meera Syal _ have become household names.
</P>
<P>
   Many young Britons are plugged in to Fun-Da-Mental, a
multiracial group that plays a fusion of Persian jazz, rap and
hip-hop. The music produced by these hip, young musicians as well
as the established Jazzie B of Soul II Soul reflects a mix of
original cultures shaken but not stirred in the traditions of
London.
</P>
<P>
   The British cutting edge is layered with artists such as Steve
McQueen, the black Turner Prize winner whose haunting film The Bear
has received praise at the new Tate Modern museum.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   These changes have not come comfortably to all Britons.
</P>
<P>
   David Irving, the historical writer and accused Holocaust
denier, earlier this year said he spoke for many of his countrymen
when he expressed longing for the days when Britain was more
British.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could go to Heathrow airport, take a 747 and fly back
10 hours later to find England as it used to be,'' he said during
his libel trial against Emory University professor Deborah
Lipstadt. ``I can't say I applaud uncontrolled colored immigration.
I regret the passing of old England.''
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party has found political capital in attacking
what it describes as a flood of immigrants from Asia and Africa,
with the implied threat to British culture and institutions if the
torrent isn't stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair's Labor government has responded by
tightening immigration rules. It has become so difficult to enter
Britain that a thriving black market has emerged in trafficking
immigrants. Last month, 58 Chinese immigrants were found dead in
the back of a vegetable truck where they suffocated while being
smuggled into Britain.
</P>
<P>
   For all the worries about immigrants, Britain remains very white
_ 94.6 percent white, according to government statistics. Away from
London and other large cities such as Birmingham and Manchester,
non-whites are rare. About half of all the non-whites in Britain
live in London.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, blacks _ mostly from the Caribbean _ constitute 1.6
percent of the population. Pakistanis, Indians and Bangladeshis _
generally lumped together and called Asians _ constitute about 2.7
percent. The balance includes Chinese and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, because the minority population is much younger than the
white population, the government estimates that in 20 years, the
percentage of non-whites in British society will double.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the predictable tensions over change, blacks and Indians
often say they believe for the most part they have been accepted _
if not embraced _ by whites.
</P>
<P>
   When Rasshied Din started in business a few years ago, he was
warned not to use his own name because the English would think he
was a ``second-hand sari salesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Din Associates is now the seventh-largest design consulting firm
in the country with a client list that features retail and fashion
heavyweights such as Tommy Hilfiger and Selfridges.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as the 1980s, Din was a pioneer. ``People would call
up and say, 'Oh, you speak English,' as if they were surprised,''
he said. ``It seems strange looking back, but you have to remember
that this was before there were any prominent Asians in business or
in the arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the changes, race doesn't occupy the august station in
British society or politics that it holds in the United States. For
many Londoners, it is a topic like sex and religion, best not
discussed over the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   That may be changing. A strong minority vote was essential to
Ken Livingstone's election in May to become London's first elected
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone now represents the largest base of constituents in
the country, potentially elevating the agenda of London minorities
to national importance.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Hall, a respected black intellectual, believes Britain is
becoming more like the United States in its racial dynamics _ if
perhaps in a gentler, more civil fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Britain going to accept its diversity and become more
humane? We don't yet know,'' he said. ``Yes, things are better in
some ways, but a lot of people feel left out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there's no going back in the fundamental change in the
nature of London, making the city a unique and fascinating
experience, said Trevor Philips, a black politician and social
critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hum of London's streets cannot be replicated,'' Philips
wrote recently. ``It's the sound of a hundred cultures softly
clashing, sometimes melding, occasionally grating uncomfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.blink.org.uk, http://www.asian-online.co.uk,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cre.gov.uk
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
