</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6499 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WAITER-SFCHRON &LR;      07-19 3345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAITER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 MAY I TAKE YOUR ORDER: What it's like to be a waiter in
San  Francisco   By Robin Davis  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  HELP WANTED: High-end restaurant with national 
 reputation seeks waiter/waitress. Fine dining experience 
 necessary. Excellent interpersonal skills, food and wine 
 knowledge a must. Excellent tips, flexible schedule. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; HELP WANTED: Small fast-paced mid-priced restaurant seeks &LR; 
 &LR; waiter/waitress. Serving experience a plus, but we'll train the &LR; 
 &LR; right person who's motivated and wants to learn about food and &LR; 
 &LR; wine. Great tips, flexible schedule. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; HELP WANTED: Unpretentious corporately-owned restaurant seeks &LR; 
 &LR; servers. Some experience a plus, but we're looking for hard &LR; 
 &LR; working team players. Good tips, flexible schedule, fun &LR; 
 &LR; environment. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
If you've ever considered getting a job waiting tables, there may
be no time liked the present. The roaring economy has drained the
pool of restaurant workers, leaving owners and managers struggling
to fill positions (see related story,  &UR; SERVICE &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen workers are hard to come by, but trained servers are
even more scarce. Think anyone can be a waiter? No way, say
managers and restaurant owners. They may be able to train anyone
who walks in the door on the technical side of service, but it
takes much more than that to be a top-notch server.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if technical service is perfect, that's only half the
battle,'' says Doug Washington, general manager of Jardini &LR; e &LR; re in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Diners want more from servers than just putting food on the
table. Some want to engage them in conversation; others want to be
left alone. Still others are there for a romantic evening with
their date or to close an important business deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans don't know what they want from service,'' says Ruth
Reichl, editor-in-chief of Gourmet magazine. Gone are the days of
formal French service as well as what Reichl calls the ``Hi, my
name is Bob'' style of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good restaurants are trying to come up with a style that is
American, but there are no rules for it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That also means that restaurateurs have to spend more time
training even experienced servers. What works at four-star Aqua,
for example, would never fly at Delfina, a more casual Mission
District spot that receives high marks for service.
</P>
<P>
   At Aqua, where many of the main courses go for $30 or more, the
rigorous training includes written tests on food, wine, service and
the computer system, in addition to days spent shadowing long-time
waiters. General manager Jean-Claude Persais likens the training _
which can take up to two weeks _ to boot camp.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, fast-paced Delfina, where such dishes as the
Niman Ranch steak and french fries is only $15, spends about three
days training new servers. The first day, trainees ``run'' the
food, delivering it to the table. The second day they follow an
experienced waiter, and on the third day they're set free in a
small section of the restaurant. Owners Anne and Craig Stoll work
with them throughout the process to make sure they know the menu
and wine list.
</P>
<P>
   All of this for a job which, in the public's eye, demands little
respect and isn't considered a legitimate career.
</P>
<P>
   Lifelong waiters are a rarity, and most who've been doing it for
years admit they didn't plan it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd have asked me when I was 20 if I'd still be doing
this, I would have said no,'' says Doug Uyeno, a waiter at
Jardini &LR; e &LR; re. But after 11 years, he's still waiting tables, and
thinks it will remain his career.
</P>
<P>
   Helen O'Byrne, who's been a server at Aqua for six years, also
plans to remain a server for as long as she can. She's a graduate
of the hospitality program at Columbia University and kept saying
that waiting tables was just temporary. Now? ``I say I'm a server
at Aqua with pride and conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   And she's rewarded for it. By no means is being a waiter easy
money, but the pay is good _ servers even at more casual places
like Pasta Pomodoro or Houston's can make $100 a shift. At
top-of-the line establishments, some waiters pull in $60,000 a
year, or more. Waiters also have the benefit of flexible schedules
and they have their days free.
</P>
<P>
   But what's it really like? We spent time at three very different
restaurants, all of which have great service. The following
vignettes tell what the restaurant looks like from the waiters'
point of view, what they see and hear, how they work with the
kitchen and how they feel at the end of the night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; AQUA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the usual tsunami at 6:30, but the red flag is still
in effect,'' says Bryan Philon, a manager at Aqua's daily 5 p.m.
staff meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He's not giving a weather report. He's telling the staff to
expect a slower than normal start for the four-star restaurant that
evening. But be ready. Anything can happen. Tonight the staff
expects to serve 240 customers.
</P>
<P>
   Servers listen _ finishing their ``family meal'' of hot dogs,
mashed potatoes, toast and salad _ while the managers discuss the
night ahead.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Jean-Claude Persais takes over, his gentle
French accent belying his message, which is strictly business. He
quickly lists the VIPS dining this evening and what they're like _
``very particular, spends a lot'' and ``a regular at Charles''
referring to Charles Nob Hill, another restaurant in the Aqua
group.
</P>
<P>
   Persais has already covered this information with chef-owner
Michael Mina, in the manager's meeting. Mina noted which  &LR; amuse &LR; 
 &LR; bouche &LR;  and complimentary middle course he sent to each VIP on
their last visit so he won't send the same ones tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Persais goes through menu changes, and then Mina brings out the
special for the night _ thin slices of hamachi with a sticky rice
and fermented black bean cake. He explains the dish, listing each
ingredient and the cooking process. As the servers take notes, they
also discuss the best way to describe the dish to diners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what are the components?'' Mina asks. The servers list
them, tossing around various descriptors.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about `paillard?' '' asks waiter Bob Davis. Mina doesn't
like it. ``Carpaccio?'' Good. They'll call it hamachi carpaccio.
</P>
<P>
   Aqua's staff goes through this extensive prelude every night.
Mina knows it's a lot of pressure for the staff, but Aqua is one of
the best restaurants in the Bay Area, if not in the country.
Service is key _ this year Aqua's service earned a prestigious
James Beard Foundation nomination. That kind of success brings high
expectations from customers, and Mina makes sure he gives his staff
every tool they need to meet those expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aqua is the kind of place I have to gear up for all day
long,'' says Davis, who's been waiting tables here for seven years.
Before a shift, he works out and gets focused. ``The stakes are
high here. I can't cruise through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, things start well for him. He has a large party plus
smaller tables in his section in the back of the dining room. ``I
really, really like everyone I'm waiting on right now,'' says the
boisterous man with white, spiked hair. His jovial laughter and
that of his customers rings through the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Davis thinks most customers come in to enjoy themselves, and
he'll go out of his way for them. On the other hand, he says, if
they treat him like a servant, he'll act like one, leaving his
personality behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of times people don't understand how much they
participate in the process,'' Davis says. ``I have a role. They
have a role. It's best when everyone understands that.''
</P>
<P>
   Server Helen O'Byrne has a more difficult time this evening, but
says she thrives on the challenge. Her first table, a party of six,
moved to her section because they didn't like the first location.
Then, one of the diners spills his wine. The staff can see these
people aren't happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have to make sure it turns around,'' she says with a
smile and a gleam in her eye.
</P>
<P>
   She goes to work. The sole woman at the table is obviously
hosting the party. O'Byrne concentrates on her, frequently using
the phrase ``for you.'' When she asks to order the John Dory from
the tasting menu as an a la carte entree, O'Byrne goes to the
kitchen and asks Mina. ``The chef will be happy to do that for
you,'' she says when she returns.
</P>
<P>
   Servers at Aqua don't spend much time in the kitchen. That's
Mina's exclusive territory. He stands before the line, reading
orders spurting out from a small printer. The staff behind the line
waits. Like a conductor, he brings them to attention _ ``Listen
up'' _ orchestrating the meal for every table, deciding which
 &LR; amuse bouche &LR;  to send, when to send the appetizer. He works with
two expediters, one on either side, and another staff member who
walks through the dining room and reports to the kitchen which
tables have finished a course, and whether it's been cleared and
reset for the next one.
</P>
<P>
   Mina checks every plate. He also eyes the plates that come back
to see what's been eaten and what hasn't. That will be information
for tomorrow's waiters' meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Managers and runners come through the kitchen, but servers come
in only on a ``two-minute warning'' _ which means the entrees will
be ready to deliver to the table in two minutes. They also visit
the kitchen if a table is moving slowly through a tasting menu, or
if a customer has a special request or a problem.
</P>
<P>
   After most of the tables have their entrees, Mina walks through
the dining room to see how the ``first turn'' is going _ the time
between when the first round of guests are leaving and the second
set is coming in. It's a crucial time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good night,'' he says. He can tell how the servers
are feeling by the table maintenance. If they're rushed or
panicked, Mina will see wine and water glasses unfilled or a napkin
left unfolded when a guest gets up for a moment. But not tonight.
It looks good.
</P>
<P>
   O'Byrne knows it's a good night, too. The unhappy guests who had
been moved to her section left her a generous tip. But she says
it's more than the money. She turned their experience around and
made them happy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DELFINA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A night at Delfina starts with side work _ all the little
details required to set up a dining room. When the restaurant
doubled its seats from 35 to 70 a few months ago, the staff and
owners discussed whether to bring in bussers and let them do the
set up. They decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   Bithiah Rosales, who has waited tables at the restaurant for two
years, says it gives her a sense of ownership to do the work
herself. Setting up is a chatty time, with music a little louder
and servers busy with tasks such as polishing silver and glasses
and rolling the strips of cheesecloth used to wipe the edges of the
plates before they go out of the kitchen. Periodically one of the
servers will call out a time-check so everyone knows how much time
is left before opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no lollygagging,'' says Rosales, a petite dark-haired
live wire.
</P>
<P>
   Like Aqua's staff, servers at Delfina go through a nightly
pre-opening ``line-up.'' But at this smaller, less formal
restaurant, the process is much more casual. Waiters gather at the
bar with owners Anne and Craig Stoll. Craig goes through the menu,
skipping over the regular items but explaining anything new or
something he's changed.
</P>
<P>
   He'll list all of the ingredients, usually down to salt and
pepper, then explain how the dish is made. Some servers take notes;
others just nod their understanding.
</P>
<P>
   They discuss some dishes more than others. Should they put a
description of the  &LR; ribollita &LR;  on the menu? No, the waiters say;
the customers will still need an explanation. Should the menu
specify that the pastas aren't entree-size? The waiters agree to
remind the customers of that if they order pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Craig also throws in little quizzes. ``And what's a &LR; i &LR; oli?'' he
asks in a singsong voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garlic mayonnaise,'' the staff replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``So why don't we call it garlic a &LR; i &LR; oli? Because that would be
redundant, right?''
</P>
<P>
   He goes through the specials. Tonight there are just six quail
appetizers. He also has a small amount of an octopus salad he's
created that he'd like to try out. Does one waiter want to try to
sell them all or should they open it up to the staff? Sometimes, if
there are just a few orders of a special, they'll give it to only
one waiter to make sure it doesn't get oversold. The staff decides
they will all sell them.
</P>
<P>
   Craig brings out an example of a cheese course plate so the
staff can taste it. He explains that it's a Cabrales, a crumbly
blue-veined cheese made by Cowgirl Creamery in Point Reyes. ``Try
to sell it with port,'' Craig suggests. The staff nods, thinking
about how well that would go with this pungent cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Nightly wine tastings are also part of the line up, so they
taste a Ridge Lytton Springs Zinfandel while Anne explains changes
to the wine list.
</P>
<P>
   It's a few minutes before the restaurant opens. The staff rushes
to put on their aprons and the women put on lipstick. Now it's
5:30, and customers are already lined up for the tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a turn-and-burn restaurant,'' says Anne. ``We don't like
to rush customers. At the same time, we have three seatings so it's
important to keep things moving along.''
</P>
<P>
   The volume created by three seatings, or ``turns,'' helps the
Stolls keep prices reasonable. It also means the staff of five
waiters and two assistants have to be on the ball from the minute
the door opens until the last diner leaves.
</P>
<P>
   While Aqua keeps all of their VIP information in a computer,
Delfina relies on its staff. If Anne spots a VIP, she writes a code
on the board at the kitchen entrance: T14-Ken &AMP; Teresa. Ken and
Teresa are at table 14.
</P>
<P>
   Servers are also responsible for pacing the meal at each table,
telling Craig when to fire an order. How do they know?
</P>
<P>
   Rosales says customers let you know in many ways. If someone
keeps looking at his watch or if groups aren't communicating at a
table, they're probably in more of a hurry. Sometimes, it's just a
feeling. ``It took me a solid six months to perfect firing,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   By 6 p.m., every seat is filled. By 7 p.m., Anne will need some
of these tables for the next turn. She has a few tricks to keep
things moving. For example, sometimes when she sees a table
finishing entrees, she turns to the kitchen and fires chocolate
cakes, even if they haven't been ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take 10 minutes to bake,'' she explains. ``I'd rather
waste the cakes than have the customers sit and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   How many cakes does she waste in a night?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one or two. Everybody loves chocolate cake,'' she laughs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HOUSTON'S &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Houston's _ a mid-priced Texas-based chain specializing in
steaks and burgers _ doesn't leave anything about service to
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Instructions for servers at each of its branches, including the
one in San Francisco at The Embarcadero, specify:
</P>
<P>
   _ Appetizers and drinks must be on the table within two minutes
of ordering.
</P>
<P>
   _ Entrees must be served within 10 to 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Servers must wear cotton/polyster blend clothes as uniforms.
No 100 percent cotton. Clothes must be professionally cleaned,
preferably by the company that Houston's recommends so the look
will remain consistent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Any hair clips worn must be black or brown. No banana clips.
</P>
<P>
   Sound extreme? Consider this: While Zagat Survey ratings
generally show that service nationwide lags two points behind food,
nine of the 14 Houston's that are rated in the survey score only
one point below food or are even with food. In San Francisco, the
service rating surpasses the food _ food is 18 points; service is
19, placing it in the ``good to very good'' category.
</P>
<P>
   With 46 restaurants nationwide, the company has had time to
perfect a system that works. It starts with the hiring process. The
first step is a standardized cognitive abilities test that
determines whether the candidates fit the company's profile of a
waiter. Once hired, an extensive training process begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get people who say, `Eight days of training? Forget it!'''
says Nikki Smith, assistant manager of the San Francisco branch.
But then, she says, Houston's knows they're not right for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a six-year Houston's veteran, started work at the San
Francisco branch three months ago, after moving from Texas. She
likes the company because what it states as ``life goals'' matches
her own _ professionalism, positive mental attitudes, aim to
please, teamwork and a commitment to quality.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also talks about training servers on ``wow moments'' and
``the blanket of warmth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds like a cult,'' she laughs. ``We're a weird
group.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing weird about the good service they provide.
</P>
<P>
   The servers begin their shift by signing up for the daily chores
that need to be done before opening. The ones who get in earliest
get to pick their favorite jobs. The last one has to make cheese
toast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why no one likes to do it,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, many of the servers help finish up the cheese toast
to be sure the restaurant is ready for lunch. Today is especially
important. Smith just got a message that George Beale, Houston's
president and principal owner, will be in. She looks panicked for a
brief moment, but quickly resumes her composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I run the place like he's always standing there,'' she says
pointing to the corner, ``everything will be fine.'' Still, she
whispers to the servers that he'll be coming.
</P>
<P>
   At 11 a.m. she peers through the glass doors. ``Papa's here,''
she whispers under her breath. But Beale just floats through the
restaurant, talking on his cell phone. One of the servers hands him
a cappuccino. He's gone almost as quickly as he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   As at Aqua and Delfina, the staff gathers for a pre-service
meeting. Houston's, which has names for everything, calls them
``preshift huddles.'' But the meetings are perfunctory and very
brief, while at Aqua and Delfina they're longer and detailed.
</P>
<P>
   Smith looks over each of the waiters. ``Button the top button,
please,'' she says, gesturing to one of the men. ``Shoes look
good.''
</P>
<P>
   She talks briefly about the food, but since the menu changes
very little it's more like a refresher course. What sauce goes with
the artichoke? Tell me about the Hawaiian rib-eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yum-yum, right?'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The minute customers start filing in, the system that makes
service at Houston's work begins.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who walks in the door is greeted within seconds. Each
of the waiters has just three tables, whereas most restaurants have
stations of five or more. There are no bussers or runners, but
everyone backs everyone else up. Smith takes food to tables if a
server has his or her hands full. She answers the phone if one of
the hosts can't get to it.
</P>
<P>
   As orders come in to the kitchen, one manager handles the salad
station, another the grill. They call out times to the kitchen _
how long an order has been in, how much time they have left before
they're over the allotted time.
</P>
<P>
   If the food won't be done in time, the waiter will do a ``fly
by'' _ walking by the table to see if the customers seem
particularly anxious for the food _ or will do a ``table call''
where they explain that the food will be a little late.
</P>
<P>
   As lunchtime progresses, the pace picks up but the quality of
service never slows. By noon, the restaurant is filled; by 12:30,
customers are waiting for a table. Houston's doesn't take
reservations, so the staff doesn't have to be concerned with
``turns'' like at Aqua and Delfina. Besides, the system is designed
so customers are in and out in 25 to 30 minutes at lunch, and 45
minutes at dinner, based on a three-course meal.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Bettencourt, a seven-month Houston's employee, believes
in Houston's system. ``There's not a morning that the alarm goes
off that I think I don't want to go to work,'' she says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
