<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6500 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-POTPOURRI-SFCHRON &LR;      07-19 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 Wine Potpourri: Tips to Keep in Mind When Dining With Wine  By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Poor wine service in a restaurant can help ruin an
evening out. The whole experience can be a minefield of strange
wine names, off-the-scale prices and service that's either too
friendly and casual or too stuffy and condescending.
<P>
   At the table, expect to be handed the wine list along with the
menu. It's smart business for the restaurant and it gives you a
chance to choose wine and food together. A quick assessment of the
list will send up any red flags that trouble with wine service
might be minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   Is the wine list manageable or is it so cumbersome you feel like
you're at the gym lifting weights? Are the wines listed in an order
that makes sense and is easy to read? Is the print large enough and
clear enough so you don't have to ask for a flashlight? Does the
restaurant offer wines by the glass?
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly _ and this is a blazing red flag _ are the
wines priced in concert with the menu entrees? Or, is every wine of
interest more expensive than the most expensive entree? There
should always be a range of prices so all budgets can be
accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees on what's right or fair when it comes to
pricing wine in restaurants. In general, most wine professionals
agree that twice the retail price is fair for a bottle of wine in a
restaurant. But that formula doesn't take into consideration older
wines that are hard to find and often are priced differently.
</P>
<P>
   Here are two things you can expect from good wine service:
</P>
<P>
   _ The attention and speed of wine service will be different if
the server is doing both wine and food. It's not always the case,
but a sommelier's sole job is to help the diner select the wine,
then serve it.
</P>
<P>
   _ No matter who the server is, expect the wine you've chosen to
be displayed for verification and opened at the table. The person
hosting the meal, male or female, should receive the wine list,
order the wine and get the first sip to determine the soundness of
the wine.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; If all of your expectations are met, tip the wine server.
Sommeliers make their money based on how much wine they sell and
how well they serve the wine to diners.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reading the Numbers &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the claim by many consumers that their budget rarely
exceeds $20 for a bottle of wine, MFK Research reports that
California wines priced over $25 are hot items.
</P>
<P>
   The research division of Motto Kryla &AMP; Fisher LLP, a U.S. wine
industry management and research consultant, says that wine sales
in that price range exceed 3 million cases annually, with a value
of more than $1 billion. Further, the category is growing at 25
percent per year.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers can be confusing, especially as the global wine market
constantly changes. In March, Motto Kryla &AMP; Fisher announced that
U.S. table wine exports were flat in 1999 both in volume and
dollars. Now, along comes the Wine Institute, stating that U.S.
wine exports for 1999 were up 2 percent from the previous year, to
$548 million. WI further said that California wine shipments to the
rest of the United States were up 3 percent, representing an
increase for the sixth consecutive year. The reason, according to
the Wine Institute _ is the strong U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Rabbit &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago I rambled on about Stupid Wine Tools, the kind of
gadgets that make money for someone else by providing you with a
piece of useless junk _ for example, double-winged corkscrews with
a screw that's more like a wood auger.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came the Rabbit. It's a new cork-pulling machine that
looks vaguely like a rabbit, with the precision gear positive
motion that eases corks out of bottles in seconds. The Rabbit is
clamped securely to the top of the bottle, then with one downward
motion to drive the screw into the cork, followed by a second
upward motion, the cork is out of the bottle faster than you can
say Gew &LR; u &LR; rztraminer. With the smooth mechanism and the
user-friendly cushioned rubber handle, The Rabbit is a cross
between the lever Screwpull and an OXO kitchen tool.
</P>
<P>
   The Rabbit is available at Beverages &AMP; More and Sharper Image
stores and catalog. Prices range from $70 to $80.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One of the simplest-to-use cork removers is curiously called the
Ah-So wine opener, which sells for about $20. There are no moving
parts or gears _ just a loop handle attached to two metals prongs,
one slightly longer than the other. Simplicity, however, doesn't
mean it is easy to use for some people.
</P>
<P>
   But once you get it down, the Ah-So can out-pull just about any
cork remover. Here's how. Insert the longer of the two prongs into
the tight space between the cork and the bottle. Using a rocking
motion, while gently pushing the Ah-So downward, move the long
prong down until the shorter prong can be inserted between the cork
and the bottle. Now, using the same gentle rocking motion, work the
prongs downward until the base of the Ah-So is flush with the top
of the bottle. Then, with a slight twisting motion, pull the cork
out of the bottle. The key is rock, don't push. It takes a little
practice but the Ah-So is slick and fast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
