<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 Working Cook: Neighborhood Restaurant Inspires a Dish Worth 
 Waiting For   By Tara Duggan  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  My neighborhood Chinese restaurant, Eric's in Noe
Valley, always has a line out the door and at least five cars
double-parked, hazard lights flashing, out front to pick up
take-out.
<TEXT>
<P>
   People don't line up for traditional things like the wonton
soup; what they want are the California-influenced dishes like beef
with portobello mushrooms and my favorite, the shrimp with mango,
which is stir-fried with a bit of hot chile pepper and sprinkled
with cilantro. The balance of spicy and sweet is just right, and
it's fresh-tasting without a heavy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Since I eat at Eric's all the time, I couldn't help being
influenced by this simple dish and came up with my own version,
Curried Prawns with Mangoes, which has the addition of curry.
</P>
<P>
   Curry powder is, of course, one of the original easy-cook
inventions. What's really important, though, is that you don't just
shake it into a sauce or you'll find yourself with a grainy, raw
flavor. It's always better to saute dried spices like curry powder
in fat before adding them to your vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The Grilled Chicken Breasts with Corn, Tomato &AMP; Mozzarella Salad
is a simple way to capture the flavors of summer in one dish. It
depends on high-quality seasonal produce and fresh mozzarella. If
you find the ripest summer tomatoes, which are acidic and full of
flavor, you might not need to add any lemon juice or vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   The Sweet Potato Empanadas with Ancho Cream have a subtle
filling of creamy potatoes, golden raisins, crunchy pumpkin seeds
and a bit of fresh goat cheese inside a flaky crust. Ancho chile
paste provides mild, smoky heat.
</P>
<P>
   If you like, prepare the filling ahead of time, which takes
about the same amount of time to prepare as it does to roast the
potatoes. This works well as a make-ahead recipe, because you can
just take one or two empanadas out of the freezer at a time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CURRIED PRAWNS WITH MANGOES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Serve this dish with steamed jasmine rice.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons oil
</P>
<P>
   21/2 teaspoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 pound peeled and deveined shrimp
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 large, medium-ripe mango
</P>
<P>
   Handful cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1/2 lime
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large saute pan or wok over low heat. Add the
curry powder and saute for 5 minutes, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the shrimp with 1/2 teaspoon salt and a few pinches of
pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Chop the onion and mince the jalapeno. (Discard jalapeno seeds
before mincing if you prefer a mild dish; leave in the seeds for a
spicy curry flavor.) Add the onion and chile to the pan, increase
the heat to medium and saute until the onion is tender, about 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   As the onion cooks, dice the mango (see note) and roughly chop
the cilantro. Increase heat to high, then add the shrimp and mango
to the pan. Stir-fry until the shrimp just turn pink. Stir in the
cilantro then add a squeeze of lime juice. Season to taste with
salt.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  An easy way to chop mango is to hold the fruit upright
on a cutting board with a narrow side facing you. Using a large
knife, cut the fruit in half about 1/2 inch from the center, just
around the seed. Repeat with the other side. Score the flesh in
each half into squares, then push each half inside-out so it looks
like a hedgehog. Then cut off each square.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 215 calories, &LR;   &LR; 24 g protein, 14 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 7 g fat (1 g saturated), 172 mg cholesterol, 437 mg
sodium, 3 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; GRILLED CHICKEN BREASTS WITH CORN, TOMATO &AMP; MOZZARELLA SALAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless, skinless chicken half-breasts (7 or 8 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 ears fresh yellow corn, husked
</P>
<P>
   Few basil sprigs
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ripe summer tomatoes (may substitute cherry tomatoes)
</P>
<P>
   7-ounce piece high-quality fresh mozzarella
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Fresh lemon juice or champagne vinegar, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   If using a grill, prepare coals before beginning preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Start a large pot of water boiling that will eventually hold the
corn.
</P>
<P>
   Season the chicken breasts on both sides with salt and pepper.
Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Have ready a large bowl of ice water that will eventually hold
the corn.
</P>
<P>
   Drop the corn into the boiling water and blanch until
crisp-tender when pierced with a knife, about 2 minutes. Drain and
immediately plunge into the ice water.
</P>
<P>
   Mince the basil. Dice the tomatoes (or cut the cherry tomatoes
in half) and dice the mozzarella; pieces should be slightly larger
than the corn kernels.
</P>
<P>
   Begin grilling the chicken breasts (or place on a seasoned grill
pan over high heat); cook about 5 minutes per side, until the
chicken is no longer pink in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   While the chicken cooks, cut the corn kernels off the cobs and
transfer to a large bowl. Add the tomatoes, basil and mozzarella.
Add the olive oil and season with salt and pepper. Toss lightly and
taste. Add a drizzle of lemon juice or vinegar if the salad needs a
little boost of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the chicken into strips.
</P>
<P>
   Using a slotted spoon, portion the salad onto plates and arrange
chicken strips on top.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 370 calories, &LR;   &LR; 40 g protein, 17 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 16 g fat (8 g saturated), 106 mg cholesterol, 279
mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SWEET POTATO EMPANADAS WITH ANCHO CREAM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You may prepare the filling ahead of time and store it in the
refrigerator for a few days. To freeze, wrap the unbaked empanadas
(without egg wash) with a layer of parchment paper between each.
Defrost overnight in the refrigerator, then brush with egg wash and
bake as directed. Allow a few extra minutes in the oven in case the
empanadas are still cold in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Filling
</P>
<P>
   21/2 pounds sweet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 ancho chile peppers (see note)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raw, unsalted green pumpkin seeds (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   Topping
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups (12 ounces) Mexican crema or sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon or lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   To Assemble
</P>
<P>
   Two 17.3-ounce packages frozen puff pastry dough, defrosted
according to package directions
</P>
<P>
   Two 51/2-ounce packages fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Line a baking pan with
foil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the filling:  &LR; Pierce the sweet potatoes with the
tines of a fork, then place them in the foil-lined pan. Bake for 45
minutes to 1 hour, until tender when pierced with a knife.
</P>
<P>
   While the sweet potatoes are baking, place the ancho chiles in a
bowl and cover with the boiling water. Cover the bowl with plastic
wrap and let soak for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large skillet, then crumble in the oregano and
saute briefly. Add the onions and saute over low heat until very
tender, 15 to 20 minutes. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the chiles, reserving the soaking water. Pull off stem
ends and shake to remove most of the seeds. Coarsely chop the
flesh, then place in a food processor. Add about 1 tablespoon of
the soaking water and puree. Add more soaking water as needed to
form a thick paste. Set aside. Reserve 1 cup of the chile-soaking
water; discard remainder.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pumpkin seeds in a heavy, deep skillet over medium
heat. After a few minutes they will start popping. Allow most of
the seeds to pop, shaking the pan and stirring often so they don't
burn, about 10 minutes total.
</P>
<P>
   When the sweet potatoes are done, remove them from the oven.
Reduce the oven temperature to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the potatoes and cut into large dice. Add to the onions,
along with the pumpkin seeds, 2 tablespoons of the ancho paste, 1
cup chile-soaking water and the raisins. Cook over low heat to
incorporate flavors, about 5 minutes. Season with salt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The topping:  &LR; Combine 2 tablespoons of the ancho paste with the
crema and lemon or lime juice; stir to blend well. Season with a
bit of salt and set aside. ( &UR; Note: &LR;  There may be a little ancho
chile paste left after making this recipe.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble: &LR;  Select a plate or lid that is about 4 inches in
diameter; this will be your guide to cutting out the dough circles.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully unfold 1 piece of the defrosted puff pastry and place
on a lightly floured work surface. Roll out the dough to about an 8
x 12-inch rectangle. Place the lid or plate on the top corner of
the dough and cut around it with a small, sharp paring knife.
Repeat, cutting out 6 circles in all.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly beat the egg in a small bowl, then stir in the milk.
Using a pastry brush, paint a thin band of egg wash around rim of
each circle. Place a few tablespoons of the filling across the
center of each circle, then about 1 tablespoon of the goat cheese.
Fold each pastry in half, then press down into a half circle (you
may need to remove some filling to close). Using a fork, crimp the
edges together.
</P>
<P>
   Place the empanadas on a parchment- or foil-lined baking sheet,
brush tops with egg wash and bake at 375 degrees for about 20
minutes, until golden. Repeat with the remaining dough.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the empanadas hot or warm, topped with a spoonful or so of
the chile-cream topping.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 24 empanadas; serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  If you can't find green pumpkin seeds (also called
pepitas), substitute sliced almonds. Ancho chiles are deep-red
dried poblano peppers with a sweet, smoky flavor. Both pumpkin
seeds and ancho chiles are available in Latino markets and in some
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER EMPANADA (without topping): &LR;   &LR; 325 calories, &LR;   &LR; 7 g protein, &LR; 
 &LR; 41 g carbohydrate, 16 g fat (5 g saturated), 15 mg cholesterol, &LR; 
 &LR; 56 mg sodium, 6 g fiber. &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; TOPPING, PER TABLESPOON: &LR;  34 calories, 1 g protein, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 3 g fat (2 g saturated), 6 mg cholesterol, 7 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
