<HEADER>
A6507 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SERVICE-SFCHRON &LR;      07-19 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERVICE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 SF Restaurants Face Service Crisis in Face of Dot-Com Onslaught   By Robin Davis 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; A crisis is looming at Bay Area restaurants. In a
region where eating out is a way of life, restaurateurs are
struggling to find servers and line cooks. For Northern California
diners, that struggle translates to higher tabs and poorer service.
<P>
   With unemployment at an all-time low, many businesses are in the
throes of labor woes, but perhaps none as much as the
labor-intensive restaurant industry, a linchpin of the local
economy. In San Francisco, restaurants made up 23 percent of the
city's taxable sales in 1998, the latest year for which figures are
available, according to the California Board of Equalization.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is twofold, industry experts say. Not only are more
people who once worked in restaurants being drawn into other
fields, but more restaurants are opening _ more than 400 in San
Francisco alone in 1999, according to the San Francisco Department
of Health, which licenses them.
</P>
<P>
   As with many other businesses, restaurant servers are fleeing to
dot-coms, say general managers and restaurant owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my cocktail servers left, and she joined a startup,''
says Umberto Gibin, general manager of the Grand Cafe in San
Francisco. And not to be a programmer or an executive. ``She's a
receptionist. But she makes $37,000 a year with stock options and
she works 9 to 5.'' That's a hard deal for restaurants to beat.
</P>
<P>
   For a city that's considered one of the best culinary
destinations in the country, quality is now on the line. For
diners, it's the decline in service that is the most apparent and
the most frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, The Chronicle has received more
complaints than ever from diners who think their dinners have been
ruined by poor service. Complaints range from poor pacing of the
meal _ one person's entree being brought out so late that the rest
of the party had finished eating _ to being forced to wait at the
bar long after a promised reservation time.
</P>
<P>
   Other diners simply feel neglected by servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to request menus. We had to request wine. We had to
inquire about dinner three times, and once the meal arrived, we had
to ask for silverware _ at which time the waiter went around the
table asking each person if they would like both a fork and a
knife, or just needed one or the other,'' says Tracy Skytt of San
Francisco of a recent dining experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eating out is a lot more than seared foie gras or lavender
creme brulee,'' wrote one woman in her 20s who eats out frequently.
``Gracious service will always impress us more.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jackie Kleinman of San Francisco, who has dined out in the
Bay Area two to three times a week for the past 23 years, had good
service at a restaurant recently, she was so surprised that she
realized how jaded she's become about dining out. ``I've lowered my
expectations,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of feeling is bad news for Bay Area restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Reichl, editor in chief of Gourmet magazine and an observer
of the national restaurant scene, says she isn't surprised. ``More
restaurants are opening, and restaurants are stealing entire staffs
from one another,'' she points out. ``It's no wonder service is a
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, complaints about service are at an all-time
high. In Zagat Survey ratings nationwide, service is the No. 1
complaint of more than half of the respondents. On average, service
lags about two points below food quality on the survey's 30-point
scale.
</P>
<P>
   An online survey conducted by Consumer Reports and published in
this month's issue shows the same degree of dissatisfaction. When
asked for their pet peeves about dining out, more than 700
respondents listed rude and bad service as the top two complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, too, note a dramatic drop in service quality. In the
more than 100 restaurants The Chronicle reviewed in 1998, the
number of restaurants earning three stars for service (considered
excellent to extraordinary) just about equalled the number of
restaurants with service below two stars (considered fair to poor).
But last year and for the first half this year, restaurants in the
fair-to-poor service category outnumbered those with excellent or
better almost 2 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Customers are also feeling the restaurant labor squeeze in the
form of higher menu prices as wage increases are passed on. Kathy
King, general manager at top-rated Boulevard, says labor costs have
been rising steadily since the restaurant opened in 1993. But in
the last year, it's gotten worse. In that time, she says, her labor
costs jumped 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Galle, director of operations for LuLu Inc., which runs
LuLu and Azie in San Francisco and Zibibbo in Palo Alto, says the
three restaurants are paying as much as 30 percent more now for
labor than they did just three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   All this translates into higher menu prices. According to the
Zagat Survey, which rates hundreds of restaurants throughout the
country, the Bay Area last year became the second city in the
nation, after New York City, to top the $30 mark for an ``average
meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Although restaurateurs are aware of the problem, many are
overwhelmed by just trying to fill empty positions. Kirk Webber,
co-owner of Cafe Kati in San Francisco, says the floor staff he
initially hired when he opened almost 10 years ago stayed for six
years. In the past three years, he's gone through three complete
staff changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our servers can make $50,000 to $60,000 a year,'' he says.
``But for the first time, it's hard to find a server.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone. A glance at the Help Wanted ads from recent
Sunday newspapers shows many restaurants hiring for line cooks and
sous chefs, but just as many looking for managers, servers and
bussers.
</P>
<P>
   Aqua, for example, runs an ad in the Sunday Examiner-Chronicle
almost every week for managers, servers, greeters, bussers and
bartenders. The House of Prime Rib, Stars and many others also have
been advertising for wait staff.
</P>
<P>
   Many restaurants are discouraged not only by the low number of
applicants, but also by the quality of the applicants. Galle of
LuLu Inc. received several applications when she advertised for a
general manager for high-end Azie, but most weren't qualified for
high-end restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``One had managed a fast-food franchise. Another was a security
guard,'' she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Some restaurants resort to poaching staffs from other
restaurants. In itself that's nothing new, but restaurant workers
say it's more prevalent than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all go out to dinner and if we find someone phenomenal,
we'll leave a business card,'' says Gibin at Grand Cafe.
``Everybody is looking for servers, bartenders, bussers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the highest-end restaurants have a revolving door of
servers. At Aqua, one of the Bay Area's five four-star restaurants,
waiters can make $60,000 a year or more, according to Stewart
Halstead, who handles hiring for Aqua and Charles Nob Hill in San
Francisco and Pisces in Burlingame. But even though they may make
more than the kitchen staff, they have a higher rate of turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Many servers say the reasons are the physical demands of the job
and the little respect it offers in the eyes of the public.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Hearne, who has waited tables at Jardini &LR; e &LR; re in San
Francisco since it opened three years ago, doesn't mind waiting
tables, but says he'd rather have a writing job. ``There's no
future in waiting tables. The money is good, but if I don't set up
my own retirement, I'll end up being a 60-year-old waiter who can't
do it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite working at two Bay Area restaurants that are highly
regarded for service and being paid well for it, Bob Davis of Aqua
and Bithiah Rosales of Delfina says they believe that others don't
respect them for being servers. It's the idea of being treated as a
servant.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, servers traditionally have little power and no
career path. That leaves most servers waiting tables until they
find their ``true calling''; until they finish school and put their
degree to work; or until they're discovered as the next great
artist, writer or actor.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mina, chef-owner of Aqua and Charles Nob Hill, Pisces
and Aqua in Las Vegas, explains that his kitchen staff is easier to
hire because he can offer them prestige and a future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask if they want to be chefs of their own restaurants, and I
only hire people who want to be chefs,'' he says. Line cooks at
Mina's restaurants immediately command respect from their
colleagues. ``When they're ready to go, I help them find a job,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   But he can't do that for servers. ``Saying you work at Station
Two at Aqua doesn't carry the same respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sheinfield of the Zagat Survey notes that television
celebrity chefs like Emeril Lagasse and Bobby Flay went a long way
toward validating working in a kitchen. But there's no such thing
as a celebrity waiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A parent might say, `My son cooks at a restaurant,' but no one
says, `My son's a waiter,' '' says Sheinfield. ``It's a prestige
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
