<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV09-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV09  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: PORK SALTIMBOCCA; POTATOES, TOMATOES AND
BASIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, Aug. 9, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's 20MINUTE-MENUS. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of 20MINUTE-MENUS _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pork and sage are natural partners and before we had ever heard
of pork tenderloin our mothers and grandmothers were using sage in
stuffing for pork roasts.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out pork and prosciutto are natural partners, too,
though the idea of making little pork ``sandwiches'' stuffed with
prosciutto and sage comes from the famous Italian dish saltimbocca,
which is made with veal. It is not an old traditional Italian dish
but one that may have been invented in more recent years in Italy
that became very popular over here.
</P>
<P>
   Today's pork, like veal, has a mild (some might say bland) taste
and the strong flavors of the sage and of the prosciutto, which
also adds salt, turn pork tenderloin into something so delicious I
would happily serve it to company. It is certainly appropriately
named: saltimbocca means jump into the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   At this time of year you have to take advantage of the great
tomatoes and the basil, which is much more pungent than the basil
that is available from hothouses in the winter. The vegetables are
simply prepared because when they are fresh they don't need a lot
of fussing.
</P>
<P>
   PORK SALTIMBOCCA
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces pork tenderloin
</P>
<P>
   4 very thin slices prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   Bunch sage to yield 8 large sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons Marsala
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash and dry the pork and cut into eight slices crosswise.
Cover with wax paper and pound slices until they flatten a little.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place a thin slice of prosciutto on each of four slices. Wash
and dry sage leaves and place two sage leaves on each of the four
slices. Cover them with the remaining four slices of pork and press
to seal.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat a nonstick pan large enough to hold the pork packages
until it is very hot. Reduce heat to medium high and add the oil.
Saute the pork on both sides until it browns. Reduce heat to medium
and continue to cook 3 to 5 minutes longer until pork is almost
cooked (the inside is not red).
</P>
<P>
   4. Add the Marsala and continue cooking until it thickens
slightly. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   POTATOES, TOMATOES AND BASIL
</P>
<P>
   9 ounces new potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil spray
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces whole onion or 5 ounces chopped, ready-cut onion (1 1/3
cups)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 large ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil to yield 1/3 cup tightly packed basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Turn oven to 450 degrees. Scrub but do not peel potatoes. Cut
into 1/8-inch-thick slices. Spray a cookie sheet with oil. Arrange
potatoes on cookie sheet with as little overlapping as possible.
Spray again and place in the middle of the oven and roast until
potatoes are golden on the bottom, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile chop onion coarsely. Heat nonstick skillet large
enough to hold the onion and tomatoes until it is very hot. Reduce
heat to medium high and add oil and onion. Saute the onion until it
begins to soften and color.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mince the garlic, wash, trim and slice tomatoes about
1/4-inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add the garlic to the onion and saute for 30 seconds. Add the
tomatoes and cook over medium low heat 5. Turn the potatoes and
continue roasting about another five minutes until they are done.
</P>
<P>
   6. Wash and cut the basil leaves coarsely and when potatoes are
cooked add to the onion-tomato mixture with the basil. Stir and
season with salt and pepper and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prepare potato-tomato dish through step 2.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare pork dish through step 2.
</P>
<P>
   Continue with potato dish through step 3.
</P>
<P>
   Continue with pork dish through step 3.
</P>
<P>
   Finish potato dish.
</P>
<P>
   Finish pork dish.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil spray
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces pork tenderloin
</P>
<P>
   4 very thin slices prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   Bunch sage (eight large leaves)
</P>
<P>
   9 ounces new potatoes
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces whole onion or 5 ounces ready-cut onion
</P>
<P>
   2 large ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil (1/3 cup tightly packed)
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 597 calories, 19 grams total
fat, 4.1 grams saturated fat, 101 milligrams cholesterol, 235
milligrams sodium, 53 grams carbohydrate, 6.4 grams fiber, 42 grams
protein.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
