<HEADER>
A6535 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MUSIC-DOUG-SAHM-HNS &LR;      07-19 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DOUG-SAHM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COUNTRY, ROCK OR JUST PURE DOUG SAHM? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM BEAL Jr.  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ He went by several names, depending on his mood
and whether he was up to wearing a wrestling mask.
</P>
<P>
   At one time he was Little Doug. Then he was Sir Douglas, Doug
Saldana, Wayne Douglas, Samm Dogg the masked musician and, in some
circles, just Doug. He might even have had a few more aliases.
</P>
<P>
   But he also was always Doug Sahm, the hyper-kinetic Texan from
San Antonio who, according to his longtime Sir Douglas Quintet
partner Augie Meyers, ``could get on a mental horse and ride off in
seven different directions at once.''
</P>
<P>
   That line also describes Sahm's musical pursuits. He started his
career as a kid country phenomenon and went on to play rock 'n'
roll, blues, Tex-Mex, more country and combinations thereof.
</P>
<P>
   When the man died in November, he left a country album in the
can. The 12-cut disc, ``The Return of Wayne Douglas,'' has been on
and off of release lists for months. The Tornado-label collection
was supposed to hit the streets this week.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Sahm was fond of revisiting his own songs
while he paid tribute to the people who influenced him. He did just
that on ``Wayne Douglas.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahm-book chestnuts such as ``Beautiful Texas Sunshine,''
``Cowboy Peyton Place,'' ``Yesterday Got in the Way,'' ``Dallas
Alice'' and ``Texas Me'' are reprised here, alongside Leon Payne's
``They'll Never Take Her Love From Me'' and Bob Dylan's ``Love
Minus Zero/No Limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahm weighed in with a few new tunes, ``Oh No! Not Another
One,'' ``You Was for Real,'' ``Huggin' Thin Air,'' ``I Can't Go
Back to Austin'' and ``I Don't Trust No One When It Comes to My
Heart,'' co-written with Clay Blaker.
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for pure country through and through, it is
not here. To be sure, Sahm could honky-tonk with the best, and he
does so on the Payne cut and ``Huggin' Thin Air,'' but, just as he
was never content staying in one musical bag, old Wayne Douglas,
even when he was playing country, let his freak flag fly.
``Yesterday Got in the Way'' rocks, while ``Cowboy Peyton Place''
conjures up the ghosts of Austin's glory days.
</P>
<P>
   A Doug Sahm country album is not your daddy's country album nor
is it your alt-country album. What Sahm did best, and what he did
on ``The Return of Wayne Douglas,'' is gather a bunch of
like-minded, top-flight players together in a comfortable recording
studio, set a mood and let things rip.
</P>
<P>
   Recorded at Cherry Ridge Studios in Floresville, Texas, which is
owned by Tommy Detamore, the steel guitar ace who works with Blaker
in the Texas Honky Tonk Band, the disc features an interesting
array of musicians: Meyers and Ronnie Huckaby playing keyboards,
Detamore, fiddler Bobby Flores, guitar wizard Bill Kirchen, drummer
Dan Dreeben, David Carroll thumping the upright bass, Blaker on
guitar, Sahm's son Shawn contributing background vocals and Sahm
playing guitar, singing and telling stories.
</P>
<P>
   The result is near-patented Doug Sahm musical feast, a South
Texas hippie country album that twangs without mercy while
two-stepping in tie-dye without apology. And it ends with Doug's
outgoing answering machine message. You can't dance to that, but
you will play it more than once.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Jim Beal Jr. by e-mail at jbeal(at)express-news.net)
</P>
