<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MUSIC-SUPREMES-HNS &LR;      07-19 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SUPREMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A SUPREME PREFERS TO TALK ABOUT THE GROUP'S OLD DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HECTOR SALDANA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Singer Mary Wilson, the only other original
Supreme on the planet besides Diana Ross, isn't an I-told-you-so
sort of person.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, her comments could be juicy right about now as Ross'
ill-fated, faux Supremes ``Return to Love'' tour is being called
the biggest flop of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, 56, is mum on the subject _ to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name wasn't on it, and I just want it clear that it wasn't
my fault for the tour not happening,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As the only member of the Supremes from beginning to end, Wilson
is not shedding any tears (or gloating) over the cancellation of
Ross' so-called reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts are that it was not a Supremes reunion,'' she said.
``Once Cindy (Birdsong) and myself are not there, it cannot be a
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we were asked to be a part of it, but it seemed that we
were only asked, but really not wanted. They did not even try to
meet us halfway in terms of having us on the tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, Ross was guaranteed $20 million. Wilson and Birdsong
were offered a comparative pittance, and when they finally agreed
to accept $3 million each, Ross allegedly pulled the plug on the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   So Wilson doesn't want to talk about those Supremes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem talking about the (real) Supremes,'' joked
the author of the 1986 best seller, ``Dream Girl: My Life As a
Supreme.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the old days, Wilson said, ``Florence (Ballard),
Diane and I knew we were good.'' She rankles at being called a bit
player or background singer and reminded that the late Ballard
actually had the best voice of the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson kept the group going until 1977 and the hits continued,
albeit less often. Singer Jean Terrell took over Ross' spot. ``Up
the Ladder to the Roof,'' ``Stoned Love'' and ``Floy Joy'' were
late-period Top 10 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Motown is preparing a 40th anniversary Supremes box set, but
like the reunion tour ``it could have been done better,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things that happened in the studio, that
without me telling them, they won't have,'' she said. ``Just like
an awards show, the audience will see what's presented but the real
show was behind the scenes _ what was going on before we went out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson called Berry Gordy's liner notes for the upcoming project
``very one-sided.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very funny to me because he mentioned Diane throughout
the entire piece, but everyone else is just `The Supremes.' He
never mentioned our names. To me, that's so funny. How can you talk
about the Supremes and not mention us?''
</P>
<P>
   The music will stand on its own apart from the politics, she
said, and include unreleased tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly speaking, I don't think there was anything in the
vault that could have been a hit, but there are some wonderful
songs there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, everyone recorded together, the band and the
singers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to go down right, otherwise you'd stay there all day
doing one song,'' Wilson recalled. There was little science to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. We went in there and we just sang,'' she said
with a giggle.
</P>
<P>
   The Supremes evolved from the Primettes (``sister group'' to the
Primes, that became the Temptations) and included pals Barbara
Martin and Betty McGlown. Stardom wasn't MTV-instant.
</P>
<P>
   From 1959 to 1963, the Supremes toured and recorded but didn't
hit big. ``We did a lot of work and a lot of shows. We prepared a
lot before we became famous. By 1964 (when `Where Did Our Love Go'
hit No. 1), we were well seasoned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, people will have an instant hit, do a video and they've
never even worked on a stage.''
</P>
<P>
   She describes her early days at Motown as ``major fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the fun was, before it became a big business. Big
business does take away the fun,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute you start making money and the minute other people
start telling you you're great is when it breaks down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said she survived with a foundation of home, faith, love
and friendship. ``I had good values and I was able to weather the
storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson had a not-so-subtle message for pop divas _ get real.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that you're not so hungry for all this love and adulation
that people give you, that you start believing it. When you start
believing your own press, that's it. We used to call it, back at
Motown, getting a big head.''
</P>
<P>
   She jokes that she would ``kill for a voice like Aretha Franklin
or Gladys Knight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a great voice. I'm a great performer. I've always
been a great performer. Even when I didn't know what I was doing
because I enjoyed being up there,'' she said of her role in the
Supremes.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson doesn't close the door on a real Supremes reunion.
``Obviously, Florence could never be there for a real reunion, but
there's a chance that it could happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Where did the love go? It's still there, Wilson believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know. I feel because there was so much accomplished,
so much love, that it was not just an ordinary thing. I think this
was something that was made in heaven, honestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can only happen when that comes back together. Once that's
realized _ and if we're still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it have to be a high-dollar, mega-hyped tour? No, Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be for Diane and I to get together and say, `Girl,
let's forget all this business and what folks think. Let's just do
it for us.' And it could be done any kind of way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once that happens, it can be done. I leave the door open for
that, and that's really all I can say. It would be that simple. It
is that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wilson visits San Antonio on Thursday as a spokeswoman for
``Value Your Heart,'' a heart disease and hypertension education
and screening program, supported by the National Council on Aging
and sponsored by the Methodist Healthcare System.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hypertension is a silent killer, especially for
African-Americans,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
