<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6547 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-THOMSON-SETTLE-BOS &LR;      07-19 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMSON-SETTLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON FIRM AT CENTER OF PLAN TO BRING NET SPEED TO TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ When a Hong Kong investment manager buys stock from a
broker in Tokyo, chances are the deal passes through an old brick
mill on Boston's waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, about half the world's stock trades are processed right
at Fort Point Channel, at Thomson ESG, a unit of Thomson Financial
Corp. It is an arcane, behind-the-scenes business that handles the
tangle of communications among brokers, big investors, and banks
every time a trade is placed. And it's at the center of a push to
complete trades faster _ in one day instead of three _ by 2002. As
recently as 1995, trades settled, with money and securities
officially changing hands, in five days.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Draper, a spokeswoman for the Securities Industry
Association in New York, which is working on the so-called T(plus)1
guidelines, observed that ``this is going to require a major
overhaul.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Internet is part of the answer.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Thomson ESG is hammering out final details of a
plan to merge with its rival, a branch of New York's Depository
Trust &AMP; Clearing Corp., an institution set up and owned by
financial services firms to settle their trades. ``We each wanted
to get into each other's marketplace,'' Thomson ESG chief Howard
Edelstein said. Instead, they're aiming to develop a new system
together.
</P>
<P>
   ESG stands for electronic settlements group, a misnomer because
the company does everything but the actual ``settling.'' Call it
what you will, it claims $100 million in annual revenue and has
been growing 40 percent annually for the past five years, as global
trading volumes have mushroomed.
</P>
<P>
   The group embraced this unsexy but lucrative niche of
post-trade, presettlement services after the market crash of 1987.
Big investors suddenly saw the costly potential for errors and
dishonest maneuverings during three days of limbo in an environment
where most trade confirmations were done with phone calls,
scribbled faxes, or telexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were still primitive,'' Edelstein said. After Thomson
created a kind of electronic-message clearinghouse, he said, ``You
couldn't walk away from a trade'' by pretending the confirmation
hadn't arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson first marketed its system as a money-saver for
institutional investors. The dozens of faxes and calls required for
every trade could cost $10 to $12, Edelstein said. Thomson charges
brokerage firms 20 cents to $1 per trade; investment managers
essentially get the service for free.
</P>
<P>
   But the system did more than save the fees. It cut out some of
the grinding monotony of processing trades and saved employees
time. And it saved vast amounts of money by reducing human errors.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments said in 1993 that, in two years, the system
had cut its internal trading error rate 83 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Thomson's system has become the industry standard.
Being neutral helped: Thomson manages no money and has no trading
desk. The group handles 1.5 billion shares a day, roughly half of
US trading volume, plus a quarter of trades overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 10 years after changing the way the industry worked, and
gaining a virtual monopoly, Thomson needs to change to stay at the
forefront. T(plus)1 is looming on the horizon. And a competitor is
emerging, called the Global Straight-Through Processing
Association. It is being backed by many of the same institutions
that are members of the Depository Trust &AMP; Clearing Corp., who are
hoping to create some competition for the business.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the DTCC. Together, Thomson and the New York group will
have 15,000 clients, including top Wall Street brokers, money
managers, and custodian banks. The new system, to be rolled out in
2002, will even further reduce the back-and-forth among investors,
brokers, and bankers, Edelstein said. The communications between
the parties will become even more automated, ending the need for
them to tack message after message onto a cumbersome file.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is likely to be rife with culture shock, however. The
DTCC literally houses most of the nation's stock and bond
certificates, the pieces of paper behind shares of Microsoft Corp.,
for instance, that most investors never see or hold in their hands.
Many employees have been there 20 or 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson ESG, though, has a dot-com culture, complete with brainy
engineers, chic, open offices, and yes, a foosball game room.
Edelstein is a zealot of the Myers-Briggs personality test and
cares immensely about management skills. The group he runs was
launched with venture capital from parent Thomson Financial, which
owns many data and service providers.
</P>
<P>
   ESG's merger partner has been updating its sleepy image. But its
environment is still one of bad cafeteria sandwiches and ugly
conference rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein, deep into the seventh year of the longest stint on
his resume, is brimming with energy to tackle the challenge. He'll
be chief executive of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the arch-competitor of most of these people,'' he said.
``I have a whole lot of fence-mending to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He's already started. In May, he flew about 20 top managers from
ESG and DTCC to Paris. From there, they boarded a train to
Amsterdam. They took up the entire car next to the bar car for five
hours of meetings and casual conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to go slow,'' Edelstein said. He's not making
light of the need to bridge the culture gap to make the deal work:
``If we do it wrong, we'll have our heads handed to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
