<HEADLINE>
CDS-TO-CAPITAL PRESERVATION SWAP MAY HIKE YIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife retired in May. We feel we have too many funds and
need to get our act together. Our combined Social Security amounts
to $21,000 and we feel we need another $25,000 to $30,000
additional income per year, as we intend to travel and enjoy life.
What would you recommend to safely return 8 percent to 10 percent
on our investments _ or are we dreaming?
</P>
<P>
   V.B., Newport Beach, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It seems to me that one end of that 8 percent to 10 percent
range of returns is probably attainable, while the other end may be
a bit in the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Returns of 10 percent are what a reasonable person can expect
from a long-term investment in an all-stock portfolio, and stocks
are anything but safe, particularly at or toward the end of a bull
market of unprecedented duration and strength.
</P>
<P>
   Second, while you do not break out percentages of many of your
investments, it seems likely that if your wife has more than 91
percent of her 401(k) money (and more than 70 percent of your
combined savings) in a capital preservation fund, then your
appetite for risk is limited.
</P>
<P>
   The fund you cited is not a retail fund, so I can only guess
that it's either a money market or a conservative bond fund,
probably yielding in the 5 percent to 6 percent range. Your
expectations for total portfolio returns as it is now constituted
should probably be in the 7.5 percent range. That would represent
an annual return of nearly $41,000 from the portfolio, which
certainly would support the rate of withdrawals you contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   But if you suspect your withdrawals are likely to be at the
$30,000 end of your estimate, that would leave you with only
$11,000 a year being shoveled back into the principal account, one
of whose primary purposes is capital growth to offset the inflation
of the later years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   So I suggest this: Examine the capital preservation fund,
checking to see how its investments are made and what the actual
yield is. If your total returns are smaller than the 7.81 percent
currently available from CDs (discussed in more detail in the next
letter) I would swap that investment for CDs, which would deliver
the desired $30,000 income stream and leave the returns of all of
your other holdings to be reinvested for capital appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   The move to the CDs could be done with a rollover to a
traditional IRA. The money from your wife's lump-sum distribution
could be added to the fund accounts _ preferably at the stock end
of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage of those moves is that you can then view
everything but the CDs as long-term investments. With that in mind,
I'd rather see you replacing fixed-income funds such as the
Oppenheimer Limited-Term Government and Strategic Income funds and
the Van Kampen Limited-Maturity Government fund with either
balanced or stock funds. (But if you feel you have as much stock
market exposure as you can enjoy, I don't want to urge you into
heavier exposure; I am confident in the likely long-term returns
from stocks, but am less sanguine when it comes to short- and
intermediate-term prospects.)
</P>
<P>
   As for simplification of your portfolio, you are to some extent
limited by investments in funds with sales charges, either in class
B shares where you will pay a fee upon sale, or class A shares in
which you already have paid fees to enter the fund family.
</P>
<P>
   The investment in which your moves should be most limited is
your wife's IRA. Since all of the Oppenheimer funds she holds are
class B shares, you would owe a redemption fee if you transferred
to any investment outside the Oppenheimer fund family. But what you
could do to simplify that part of the portfolio and maintain
roughly the same asset allocation you now have is to tally what
percentage of your Oppenheimer holdings are invested in stock and
what percentage are on the fixed-income side. You could then swap
all of the stock shares for Oppenheimer Total Return and all of the
Fixed-Income shares for Oppenheimer Strategic Income shares. That
move would cut out three of the funds. If you feel that by drawing
your income stream from CDs or your capital preservation holding
allows you to be comfortable with more stock, you could give the
Total Return position a heavier percentage than you currently have.
</P>
<P>
   You would not have the same penalty within your own IRA, since
you have class A shares, which carry up-front loads. But since you
have already paid an up-front price to get into these fund
families, I suggest that you consider looking at options within the
same fund families for consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My CD is bringing me minimal returns and I don't know what
investment to make without risk. I got stung badly in the stock
market about 20 years ago and since have been fearful of investing.
I don't care if I deplete my money before I pass on, but I am in
fairly good health.
</P>
<P>
   J.C., Swampscott, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You need to move from your ``minimal-return'' CDs to
``maximum-return'' CDs. Shopping around for CDs is critical. For
example, the average yield for a five-year CD of $100,000 or more
was 6.45 percent entering this week; the best rate, offered by
Capital One FSB of Virginia (1-800-564-7426) was 7.81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At that rate, your savings would bring you an annual income
stream of $23,430, and you would need only $14,614 of it to
supplement your other income. This would mean you could plow nearly
$9,000 a year back into your savings, which is a good thing, since
you will need to keep the balance growing to protect against future
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to become daunted when seeking out the nation's best
CD rates. The main source I use is the data bank page of the Sunday
New York Times Business section, which lists the three institutions
with the highest rates for various kinds of CDs and their telephone
numbers. Now, before you call the banks, remember the difference
between the best rate and the average rate works out to $4,080 a
year for you, so the patience you need will be rewarded. In my
experience, the busiest telephone lines in the nation on a Monday
morning must be those of the institutions that show up at the top
of the lists. Be patient. If the entire process of moving your
savings to a top-yielding CD takes you half a day, you would be
getting about $1,000 an hour for your time.
</P>
<P>
   The second caution I would take is to put little more than
$100,000 in any single institution. Putting in $100,000 gets you
the ``jumbo'' rate, which is usually a few hundredths of 1 percent
higher than the rate for CDs under $100,000, and will give you
$100,000 worth of FDIC insurance on your savings.
</P>
<P>
   And many sites online list CD rates. The one I have bookmarked
is at www.bankrate.com/brm/rate/
</P>
<P>
   dep_home.asp, and it provides much the same information found in
the newspapers _ and a great deal more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I read your article on the use of the ``step-up'' rule when
inheriting stock. Does the same rule apply to stock in my 401(k)
account?
</P>
<P>
   J.H., Anaheim, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Alas, it does not. You have to remember the money that went
into your 401(k) was only tax-deferred, and the tax bill will
eventually come due _ even in the event of the death of the owner
of the 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   The rate at which the money must be withdrawn form a 401(k)
involves not only some fairly complicated IRS rules, but also the
provisions within the particular 401(k) plan in which you are
enrolled. For that reason, rather than provide you with
generalities, I suggest you speak with the administrator of your
401(k) plan, who can tell you what the options would be for the
person inheriting your account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
