<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SCHERER, JOURNALISM MATTERED, NOT STAR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ray Scherer, who died this month, was a lanky, amiable reporter
for NBC News. At the White House for decades, one of his favorite
assignments was in 1953, covering Harry Truman's return from the
White House to Missouri and the family house in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   What's the first thing you plan to do, Scherer asked the former
president. ``Carry the grips to the attic,'' Truman replied. Ray
chuckled and noted: ``Life was a lot simpler then.''
</P>
<P>
   Former White House occupants were on their own with no Secret
Service protection; the imperial ex-presidency did not exist. Also
simpler was the role of reporters. When ``the media'' meant ``the
press,'' ink-stained wretches were on the sidelines, not in the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters have historically been unpopular, mostly because of
their reporting zeal. But a bigger media problem of late is not
reporting, but the lack of reporting experience. David S. Broder,
who has reported a story or two, has commented on the need for
American institutions to draw clear, bright lines between each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to recognize that sticking to your own business makes
for a healthy society,'' Broder wrote. ``My own field of journalism
would benefit from remembering that. The career lines of journalism
_ the honorable tradition of working up from a night police beat to
more important assignments _ have been blurred by the increasing
tendency to import `stars' from the political and entertainment
worlds and give them high-profile media jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Equally insidious is the tendency to make journalists behave
as if they were politicians, putting them onto TV panels where the
premium is not on reporting and analysis but on argumentation and
put-downs. We have plenty of politicians who are skilled at
soundbites; journalists are poor substitutes for candidates and
officeholders on these staged debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``But more important, when we abandon our real work of gathering
news and helping make sense of it, we leave a void.''
</P>
<P>
   The night police beat? Talking to cops? Writing obituaries?
Making sure that facts are organized and accurate? These efforts do
not demand the IQ of a neurosurgeon or an astrophysicist. But many
talking heads are too fastidious for such grubby tasks. They might
choke and blanch at the reality of life and death.
</P>
<P>
   Television changed the seating arrangements of press and
politics; cable television has made it a nonstop circus. As the
media begin to gather in Philadelphia for the Republican National
Convention, numbers prove that ``media'' is a plural noun.
Convention arrangers expect 2,066 delegates. Their guess for the
size of the delegation from every medium: 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the media mob invading Philly will be schedulers,
footmen, valets, hairdessers, haberdashers, cosmeticians, and
taxidermists ministering to that peculiar pygmy tribe known as
``talking heads.''
</P>
<P>
   I know whereof I speak. In several well-paid turns as a talking
head at conventions, I was astonished at the daily muster of a
producer, a chauffeur, a researcher, and someone to carry my grips.
A researcher for an occasional two-minute gabfest? It seemed
superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   In the pre-cable era, televised sages actually shared their
reporting notes with viewers. Many talking heads today have never
reported, have never interviewed someone who didn't want to be
interviewed, never felt the fresh air of rejection. Their
perspective is that of a propagandist for cause or candidate, not
someone with a skeptical attitude toward power.
</P>
<P>
   Historians, professors, and those with specialized knowledge
infuse panels with actual facts. But political handlers and spin
doctors are easier to find, happy to advertise themselves and their
past or future clients, and eager to fill a programming void with
propaganda. Pundit smackdowns are unappetizing, uninformative, and
alas, omnipresent. Without them, cable television would be a test
pattern and a buzzing sound.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
