<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE BLANKETY-BLANK CONSPIRACY AGAINST HILLARY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Let's see, what kind of names was I calling
people in 1974? It's hard to recall, but I'm sure I was saying
something to the effect of ``blankety-blank Nixon.'' And yes,
``Nixon'' was a cuss word, a very powerful one in years gone by.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton stands accused of having called the
manager of her husband's losing 1974 campaign for Congress a
``blankety-blank Jew blankety-blank.''
</P>
<P>
   The blankety-blank in question happens to be a Baptist, but
still it's a powerful accusation against someone running for Senate
in New York, and it comes at a time when her husband the president
is negotiating with Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because Republicans who should know better, like Sen.
Trent Lott of Mississippi, repeated the charge, Hillary Clinton
took time to strongly deny that she used anti-Semitic language. In
the past, she has freely admitted she has a bad temper and there's
plenty of testimony she has used obscene language, but who the
blankety-blank hasn't?
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a different matter to use the word ``Jew'' as an
adjective in a compound blankety-blank construction. Then it's
almost always a slur. I don't know Hillary Clinton personally, but
some of my best friends (pardon the expression) are Jewish friends
of hers. I can't imagine she'd say such a thing, especially about a
Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary may swear like a Marine gunnery sergeant on occasion,
but she's notoriously precise.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Fray, the Baptist and former campaign manager who accused
the first lady of making the anti-Semitism slur, claimed at one
point that his father was Jewish, and later that he had one
great-grandmother who was Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   This guy can't even choose which of his forebears was a member
of the chosen people, and we're supposed to believe his charge
against Hillary?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I'm half-Catholic, yet no one has ever called me a
papist or even a half-papist, or whatever slurs are made against
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   All people may be created equal, but ethnic slurs aren't, and
their power changes with time, place and social circumstance. The
word ``Nixon'' has lost most of its power, and I believe I can get
away with printing the word ``papist'' in a non-derogatory way,
although we'll see when the letters arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Some ethnic slurs, or slurs associated with sexuality, can even
(or only) be used as terms of solidarity among members of that
ethnic group, as we're all aware.
</P>
<P>
   Other words, like ``Jew,'' can be uttered with hate, as it all
too often has been and still is. But the word is also spoken with
pride by Jews, and frequently with admiration by non-Jews. But I
doubt if you can get away with it in a phrase with cuss words, even
if you are Jewish. Like a lot of non-Jews nervous about the
volatility of language, I've always been more comfortable with the
word ``Jewish.''
</P>
<P>
   In American working-class contexts, some ethnic slurs are often
traded between members of various groups as jokes and ritual
insults, and given and taken only partly hurtfully. Archie Bunker,
a guy who could never get on TV in this age of PC, comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '70s I worked in a meatpacking plant in New Haven,
Conn., not far from where Hillary Clinton attended law school. Even
in those times of racial tension, the black guys and Italian guys
regularly insulted each other's heritage, but gingerly because of
the presence of large, sharp knives.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some ethnic slurs can be used anywhere or any time
with no fear, words like ``WASP,'' ``white guy'' and even
``honky,'' a pretty odd word. Maybe it's because it's widely
perceived that white guys, particularly WASPS, are in charge, even
though there are more WASPs in Appalachia than there ever were in
the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   We just have to grin and bear it, and if anyone calls me a
``blankety-blank WASP blankety-blank,'' he won't be invited over
for Bloody Marys again.
</P>
<P>
   As with all language, the meaning of potentially hurtful words
is a product of context, intent and language users' knowledge of
each other, as much as anything found in a dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   We have some knowledge of those making the charges against
Hillary Clinton. The words ``blankety-blank Jew blankety blank''
ascribed to her by Fray and his wife Mary were printed in a new
book by a former National Enquirer reporter named Jerry
Oppenheimer. Fray himself has previously spread rumors that Hillary
is a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   You can't tell me the words in that book weren't intended to be
hurtful in the context of a campaign in New York, where a good many
voters are Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Most New York voters, even those who aren't fans of Hillary,
probably don't believe she has ever uttered that anti-Semitic slur.
She probably does have the capacity, and the reason, to call Fray a
``blankety-blank blankety-blank.''
</P>
<P>
   The real blankety-blanks in this are the Republican politicians,
like Trent Lott and Hillary's opponent, Rick Lazio, who are playing
the anti-Semitic canard as a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   I'd call them ``blankety-blank Republican blankety-blanks,''
except I'm still registered as one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
