<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6561 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-19 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS BITE TO THE CORE OF APPLEBEE'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is Applebee's and why are people saying those nasty things
about it?
</P>
<P>
   Applebee's, as you may know, is a chain restaurant whose slogan
is ``America's Favorite Neighbor.'' It is the uncrowned king of
what is called the ``casual-dining concept.'' It is the largest
such chain, with $2.3 billion worth of sales at 1,198 locations.
The management estimates that the United States could accommodate
1,800 Applebee's before reaching some kind of saturation point, so
all I can say is: brace yourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Who has been trashing Applebee's? For starters, the satirical
magazine The Onion cruelly mocks the Hartford Applebee's in the
current issue, with its tongue-in-cheek expose ``Area Applebee's a
Hotbed of Machiavellian Political Maneuvering.'' There is no
Hartford Applebee's just as there is no Boston Applebee's; the
``neighborhood'' in the trademarked name ``Applebee's Neighborhood
Grill &AMP; Bar'' inevitably refers to a mall-like Shopper's World or
the scenic Cranston (R.I) Garden City Shopping Center, two
locations where I recently ate.
</P>
<P>
   Applebee's has likewise been fricasseed in a recent collection
of food essays by Sallie Tisdale called ``The Best Thing I Ever
Tasted.'' Tisdale, a contributing editor for Harper's, is an
Intellectual, so naturally she disdains Applebee's. And yet her
vicious, drive-by firebombing of the Overland Park (Kansas)-based
chain has more than a grain of truth to it.
</P>
<P>
   The interior decoration is indeed quite cloying. The
agglomeration of Life magazine covers, old license plates and
'40s-era movie studio glossy photos that festoon the Applewalls is
known in the restaurant business as ``non-chain decor.'' But the
decor is uniform across all the sites. ``Applebee's decor is
history written by people who have never studied history,'' Tisdale
writes. ``But they know a lot about marketing.'' Inter alia, she
takes a pot shot at Applebee's chief executive, Lloyd Hill, who
``isn't really a restaurateur'' but . . . ``a businessman.''
Imagine that! In terms of offhand slander, I might have mentioned
that the chain was once part of W.R. Grace, famed for bringing good
things to many neighborhoods, or that the company's stock price is
lower today than it was five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What about the food? It's the Model UN on quaaludes: Oriental
Chicken Salad; Tijuana ``Philly'' Steak Sandwich; Aztec Chicken
Salad; Jambalaya Pasta and so on. ``World food principles gone
mad,'' Tisdale writes. ``The food is not good, but not bad . . .
Applebee's purpose is inoffensiveness.'' In this, it succeeds
magnificently. On Sunday night, I ordered Applebee's new specialty,
``Santa Fe Stuffed Chicken.'' My solicitous and, yes, friendly
waitress kept asking me if it tasted ``too spicy.'' I didn't have
the heart to say it tasted like something NASA might feed the
astronauts on Cinquo de Mayo from festively decorated tubes.
</P>
<P>
   By way of establishing my credentials, I should say that in
addition to Cranston and Framingham, I can recall eating at
Applebee's in Newton and Manchester, N.H., within the past year.
I'd like to say something (itals)nice(unitals) about Applebee's,
because my family and I used to enjoy eating there. That was before
my children crossed the threshold of gastronomic innocence and
realized that deep-fried chicken fingers and french fries for $2.79
are no bargain, nutrition-wise nor pocketbook-wise. And before I
realized that heaping plates of onion rings and ``supreme'' nachos,
seductive as they are, might not be Dad's best friends, either.
</P>
<P>
   So here is the sum total of nice things I can say about
Applebee's: They serve liquor, which is a medically approved muscle
relaxant/depressant that can be safely imbibed in times of stress.
The portions are generous. I paranoiacally poured their 16-ounce
beer into a laboratory beaker, and it measured 17 ounces. The staff
is quite chipper _ and who doesn't like chipper? And their food is
better than Bickford's or Denny's, which is faint praise indeed.
But the International House of Pancakes they will never be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
