<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6564 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-NBC-REALITY-BOS &LR;      07-19 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-REALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC TRIES TO COPE WITH `REALITY' CRAZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, CALIF. _ Actress Allison Janney, in her guise as press
secretary C.J. Cregg of ``The West Wing,'' was ``briefing'' TV
critics Tuesday about NBC when Megan Mullally of ``Will &AMP; Grace''
popped up in the back of the room with a pressing question.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in the banshee-on-helium voice that makes her socialite
character, Karen, so indelible, Mullally explained that her NBC
sitcom could really use one of those hot ``reality'' programs as a
lead-in.
</P>
<P>
   So how about scheduling ``Survivor'' just before ``Will &AMP;
Grace''? No can do, she was told, ``Survivor'' isn't on NBC.
Mullally persisted: ``Big Brother,'' then? Nope. ``How about that
`Millionaire' show?'' Uh-uh. ``Making the Band?'' Sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Hands on hips, Mullally demanded: ``Is there any reality
programming on this network at all?'' Told there was not, she
declared: ``Well, somebody's going to get their ass fired!''
</P>
<P>
   Never let it be said NBC doesn't have a sense of humor about the
quandary in which it suddenly finds itself. The craze of this
summer is ``reality TV,'' and the Peacock Network has been caught
flat-footed while its rivals bask in high ratings, media attention,
and bushels of advertising dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality programming is definitely here to stay,'' conceded
NBC's top programming executive, Scott Sassa. ``It's not just a
fad: It's a trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't as aggressive as we should have been in this area.
It's an area we definitely have to pursue . . . The public has
spoken, and they want some of these shows.''
</P>
<P>
   How far is NBC willing to go in search of a blockbuster? This
far: The network is in serious negotiations for an American version
of a Dutch reality show called ``Chains of Love,'' in which a woman
is chained to four men, then chooses one each day to be cut loose
until she is left with the one to whom she is most attracted.
</P>
<P>
   With a straight face, NBC Entertainment president Garth Ancier
called it ``a relationship show.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just NBC: Whatever restraints there once were on
network television seem to be coming loose. As the Globe reported
Tuesday, ABC has proudly announced a new marketing campaign for its
sitcom, ``Norm,'' that will verbally accost viewers in public
restrooms. Via an audio device affixed near urinals in New York and
Los Angeles, the voice of actor Norm McDonald will be heard making
such wisecracks as ``Hey, watch your shoes!'' and ``Oh, my God,
look at the size of that thing!'' ABC also plans to leave messages
on viewers' home answering machines, urging them to watch a new
sitcom, ``Madigan Men.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks' willingness to go to such extremes suggests two
things: that bottom-line pressures have made them desperate, and
that they believe there is more promotional and ratings upside from
such stunts than there is public-relations downside.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa, who said after being named president of NBC West Coast
last year that his priorities were more family programs and less
sex on NBC, said Tuesday that he believes the public has changed
its view of what is acceptable on television. ``This is just a
thing you have to adapt to,'' he said. ``It's the way the world has
changed.'' He insisted that the image of NBC _ a network identified
with such smart, Emmy-winning shows like ``Frasier,'' ``ER,'' ``Law
&AMP; Order,'' and ``Friends'' _ will not suffer from a move toward
reality programs like ``Chains of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not diminish the level of quality'' of NBC's sitcoms
and dramas, he said. ``But we cannot ignore the level of interest
in these kinds of (reality) shows.''
</P>
<P>
   That extends to advertisers, who once turned up their noses at
programs like Fox's ``Cops,'' according to Ancier, a former Fox
executive, but now are willing to pay premium rates for spots on
``Survivor'' or ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware of NBC's interest in getting on the scoreboard, dozens of
producers have made pitches for new reality programs, including
knockoffs of ``Survivor'' that are set on buses or trains, and even
one that featured people eating sheep's eyeballs, according to
Sassa.
</P>
<P>
   As he sifts through prospective programs, Sassa is apparently
feeling heat from his bosses, Jack Welch, chairman of NBC's
corporate parent, General Electric, and NBC president Robert
Wright. Both have reportedly complained about the network being
left behind in the reality-TV stampede. In a lighthearted reference
to the situation, Janney opened the mock press conference Tuesday
by saying: ``Today is Tuesday, July 18, making this the 23rd day in
a row that Scott Sassa has not been fired.''
</P>
<P>
   As Sassa and Ancier play catch-up in the reality race, even one
of their top stars admits she's hooked on a CBS show. ``I'm
obsessed with `Survivor,' '' said ``Will &AMP; Grace'' star Debra
Messing Tuesday. ``The house thing (``Big Brother'') is weird, but
`Survivor' rocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS-0720     07-19 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS-0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIAN PARLIAMENT DEALS POLITICAL WIN TO PUTIN
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian President Vladmir Putin's promise to strengthen
federal government moved one step closer to reality Wednesday, when
the lower house of parliament approved key laws curbing the power
of regional governors.
</P>
<P>
   Putin introduced the legislation to change the structure of the
country's political system, saying the bills were necessary to
establish the rule of law in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The measures will strip governors of the right to sit in the
upper house of parliament, called the Federation Council, and take
away their right of immunity if they are charged with breaking
federal laws.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors of the laws described the vote as another step
towards authoritarianism in the country, and warned it would put
still more power in the hands of an already-strong president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an attempt of a constitutional coup,'' said Andrei
Piontkovsky, director of the Center for Strategic Studies, a think
tank. ``It's a well thought-out plan being carried out in tandem
with a fight against the oligarchs, to remove powerful
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Duma's 363-35 vote _ which overcame a Federation
Council veto _ comes after the government instigated a series of
high-profile tax evasion cases against the small group of powerful
Russian businessmen known as ``the oligarchs,'' who are seen as the
most influential politicians in the country besides the governors.
</P>
<P>
   Duma legislators who voted for the package of bills Wednesday
said it was a step in the right direction to make Russia's
parliament a more professional body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the president has separated regional leaders
from the Federation Council and wants to make it a professional
body is very important. The governors are too strong and too
dangerous,'' said Yelena Mazulina, deputy from the liberal Yabloko
Party, which sits in opposition to Putin's parliamentary bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's predecessor Boris Yeltsin created the country's
post-Soviet Constitution, which outlined a distribution of federal
powers between the president and the two-chamber parliament. The
Duma, the lower house, is comprised of nationally elected
officials, while the upper house, the Federation Council, is made
up of governors, who are elected locally.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have long characterized Russia's regional leaders as
bureaucrats who run their territory like medieval fiefdoms, due to
a lack of federal oversight and a strong legislative branch of the
federal government. The governors control how federal funds
allocated to their region are spent, they give tax breaks or
declare a company bankrupt at whim, and they can give _ or deny _
permits for media outlets to work locally.
</P>
<P>
   This autonomy has led to the passage of regional laws that often
conflict with federal laws, a situation Putin has declared many
times, must come to an end so that the country ``would remain
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The Duma's passage of the compromise law means governors will
give up their seats in the Federation Council by February 2001. The
governors will hand-pick their replacements, who will be subject to
dismissal by a vote in their regional parliament. Mazulina said she
hopes this situation will be replaced by direct elections for
council deputies within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.pravetelstvo.ru
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS-0720     07-19 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS-0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIAN PARLIAMENT DEALS POLITICAL WIN TO PUTIN
