<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6567 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      07-19 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAZY-MAKING HOLLYWOOD; TITO THE GREAT; GRAFFITI HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Hollywood really crazy? Well, of course, Hollywood is crazy _
Kevin Costner, with his no-acting, can't-buy-a-hit self, is still
making movies, isn't he? That, however, is not one of the 100
reasons Movieline supplies as proof positive that Hollywood types
are as wacky as a bag o' cats. Basically, the feature is just an
excuse for its writers to make snarky comments about stars, and to
show that their magazine isn't really becoming just another
sycophantic celebrity rag. There are obvious potshots such as
Whitney Houston's ongoing marriage to Bobby Brown (No. 85), and
Woody Allen dumping Mia Farrow to marry her adopted daughter,
Soon-Yi Previn (No. 51). And there's more information than anyone
needs about the things stars do to stay pretty, such as Shania
Twain's use of something called Bag Balm, intended to numb cow's
udders during milking, as a face moisturizer (No. 40). Some of the
items aren't so outlandish _ who can blame Jennifer Lopez for
bringing her own sheets during hotel stays because she refuses to
sleep on anything with a thread count of less than 250? But the
list really cranks up with such gems as Mira Sorvino's absurd
portrayal of Marilyn Monroe in a cable movie (No. 77) and Jennifer
Love Hewitt's ill-advised turn as Audrey Hepburn in a recent TV
movie (No. 78), and the frightening revelation that Cindy Crawford
intends to make more films (No. 90.) Wow, can you imagine what
would happen if she and Costner ever teamed up? Oh, the horror!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you get right down to it, there isn't much to distinguish
Latina from numerous other magazines out there targeting young
women. Yes, it's geared for Hispanic women, but really, it's just
the same parade of fashion, beauty, health and relationship tips.
But if you have the patience to wade through such airy features
about whether a summer romance will still burn hot come autumn, and
the unappreciated elegance of the ponytail, there's one piece worth
checking out in the August issue _ a tribute to Tito Puente. Before
Santana, before Ricky Martin, before Marc Anthony, there was
Puente, the great, Grammy-winning musician and composer, who died
in May at 77. It was Puente introduced the joy and magic of Latin
music to the masses a half-century ago. Instead of a straight
appreciation essay about the man they call ``the earliest
gatekeeper of the Latin-music garden of earthy delicias,'' they
allow their readers to reminisce about Puente, and their letters
speak volumes about how his music touched their lives. Says one
reader, ``When my four older brothers would get ready to go to the
Hollywood Palladium to see Tito and (fellow Latin music icon) Celia
Cruz, his music would be playing, and the family would somehow
start dancing, and the house would be the happiest place on earth.
Thank you, Tito, for the music of your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the current Latin stars for whom Puente paved the way,
India, is featured in the same issue. She discusses how she became
successful in an industry which once believed women couldn't sell
salsa music, and also criticized her ample curves as a turn-off.
(She has since lost weight, although she says she did it for
herself, not record sales.) She also speaks frankly about an
abusive relationship, and how surviving it strengthened her and
influenced her music. ``People think I hate men because of my
lyrics, and it's just not true,'' she tells writer Juan M. Mendez.
``I don't hate men. I love men! What I hate is discrimination of
any kind. What I hate is domestic violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Stress bills itself as ``hip-hop's only story telling magazine
for, by, and about its readers,'' which is another way of saying
it's not The Source or XXL. While it isn't as well known as those
magazines, it's steadily making a name for itself as an alternative
for news and views among hip-hop heads. There's a great piece by
Supriya Pillai about WERISE, an acronym for Women Empowered through
Revolutionary Ideas Supporting Enterprise.'' Formed last year in
New York, WERISE is an organization, collective, and production
company formed to support the creative efforts of women artists.
What's refreshing about the organization is its open to all women
regardless of race, religion, sexual orientation, age or ideology.
``We are only as strong as we are represented,'' says co-founder
Rozz Nash. A hip-magazine writting about a womanist/feminist
collective _ imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue, there's the story of Fuzz One, one of New
York's best known ``subway bombers,'' or graffiti writer, written
by Fuzz One himself. He's been using New York's subway cars as his
personal canvas since the 1970s, which was the height of the
hardcore graffiti movement. The story is written in a loose,
non-linear style, and Fuzz has some interesting stories as one of
the few white graffiti writers to get respect among the hardest of
the hard. But what makes the piece are the photographs of his work,
some of which are stunning. Is graffiti vandalism? No doubt. But it
was such a part of the subways, and made them so distinctive, that
those graffiti-proof cars now rattling through NYC just don't look
right without the aerosol inspiration of such spray-paint gods as
TAKI 183, TURK 62, and FUZZ One.
</P>
</TEXT>
