<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6570 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINESCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-19 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUTINE &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CONTACT: VERONICA BUCIO AT 713-220-7733
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    GREEDY, `GODLY' AND ONLINE GAMBLING
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're old enough and from the Bible Belt, you may recall the
days when an unholy alliance of Baptists and bootleggers would team
up on the same side in wet-dry elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptists certainly didn't want Demon Rum being purveyed, and
the bootleggers certainly didn't want anyone but their illicit
selves purveying it.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of thing is happening again in Washington even as we
speak.
</P>
<P>
   The ``godly'' and the great big gambling interests are ganging
up to try to ban most forms of wagering on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of cyber-casinos seems to be cutting in on the
gaming gravy train, and the folks in Las Vegas and Atlantic City,
as well as other fixed-site palaces of chance that have sprung up
around the country, want to put an end to the cheeky competition.
</P>
<P>
   Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. Inc. reported recently that Internet
gambling generated $1.2 billion in revenues last year and would
grow to $3 billion by 2002. An exponential boom is in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet gambling industry is amenable to many of the same
strictures that govern casinos, including regulation, even
taxation, but those offers were not good enough for proponents of
an outright ban.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to outlaw Internet gambling has given rise to one of
the more amusing and expensive lobbying fandangos of the current
congressional session.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner are most evangelical Christian groups and the
casino lobby, as well as others who stand to be hurt financially by
Internet gambling, such as liquor stores that do a big business in
government-run lottery tickets. On the other side are the Internet
industry, the gambling sites, libertarians and, in some cases, the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Some improbable legislative contortions have ensued.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the influential and well-heeled pari-mutuel
interests won an exemption in the main House version of the bill.
They're worried about declining attendance at the track and are
happy to parlay their action into the ether. By some accounts, the
exemption actually expands the Internet gambling opportunities for
these folks.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, governors wanted an exemption to explicitly
allow Internet sales of lottery tickets, but they failed to get
one.
</P>
<P>
   Is this sinking in? The folks who run horses and dogs got their
way. The governors did not. What is wrong with this picture?
</P>
<P>
   A general ban on Internet gambling passed the Senate on a voice
vote last year.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Monday night, the House voted 245-159 for a ban,
including the pari-mutuel exception. But the measure was being
considered under a procedure that required a two-thirds vote,
meaning the proponents were 25 votes short.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote pointed to the scramble of party allegiances and
ideologies the issue has produced.
</P>
<P>
   In favor of the ban were the unlikely duo of Rep. Sheila Jackson
Lee, the hopelessly knee-jerk Democrat from Houston, and Rep. Dick
Armey, the neo-Neanderthal Republican from the Dallas area. Voting
``no'' were such arresting combos as Reps. Bill Archer, R-Houston,
and Barney Frank, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the strong House support, advocates of the ban
vowed to press on and seek another vote when only a simple majority
would be required. But problems of legislative scheduling,
including the need for what could be a protracted House-Senate
conference on a final measure, make prospects for the proposed ban
uncertain at best.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a lot easier discussion if governments had never
succumbed to the allure of gambling. Then lawmakers might be able
to make some morally defensible argument that gambling is a
deleterious activity that should be strictly regulated and taxed,
if not outlawed outright.
</P>
<P>
   But that horse is way out of the gate. States now count on huge
rakes from gambling enterprises that they regulate (horses, dogs,
casinos) or run themselves &QL; 
(lotteries).
</P>
<P>
   Further, enforcement of a ban would be nightmarish. Most
gambling sites are, not surprisingly, run from off-shore _ Antigua,
St. Martin, Latin America _ meaning that policing of a U.S. ban
would be problematic at best.
</P>
<P>
   If the Justice Department were really interested in cracking
down on the gambling sites, it could move under the Wire
Communications Act of 1961, which was passed to ban sports betting
over the telephone. But the government lawyers, unlike the
antigambling zealots on Capitol Hill (and their greedy casino
friends), remember Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
