<HEADER>
A6576 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELYCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-19 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUTINE &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CONTACT: VERONICA BUCIO AT 713-220-7733
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NO DENYING HO-HUM OF CONVENTIONS
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh wow. Bulletin. Bulletin. This just in:
</P>
<P>
   As an indication of how riveting the major political parties'
national presidential nominating conventions are expected to be,
ABC News has gotten the National Football League to agree to change
the starting times of two Monday night preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   This, we are told, means the network will be able to devote an
hour _ a whole hour _ of primetime coverage to each of the opening
nights of the Republican and Democratic conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, ABC planned only to provide prime-time coverage of
the GOPers on July 31 and the Dems on Aug. 14 during the halftimes
of the NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   Then, ta da, ABC learned some folk of news value were expected
to speak on the opening nights of these incredibly choreographed
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Golly, of course the network could have had no idea speakers
such as Colin Powell and Laura Bush and President Clinton and
Hillary Clinton were tapped to speak on the opening nights of their
particular conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Wanta bet?
</P>
<P>
   The only real thing at question in ABC's sort-of-last-minute
scheduling finagling is: What, at the near last minute, made the
network honchos decide Americans actually might like a glimpse of
the national political conventions' opening nights?
</P>
<P>
   This is not a particular gig at ABC. Its rescheduling just
presented itself as an especially bright example of the public's
general perception of modern political conventions and their trend
to long-winded dreariness. Certainly, CBS and NBC hardly are going
to fill their airwaves with hours of convention coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, were it not for PBS' plan to provide virtual
gavel-to-gavel coverage, non-cable television subscribers across
the country would have no chance to see anything but awfully edited
presentations of the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's really quite nice to learn PBS now can be seen by
non-cable subscribers almost everywhere in the United States,
neither is this a particular gig at all those Americans who won't
watch much of the conventions even without the excuse of not having
the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, for that matter, is this a special gig at the parties for
finding themselves spreading what has become, at best, a one-night
show into a four-night speakathon.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, some of us will like hearing all sorts of political types
speak to halls filled with usually tackily outfitted delegates who
often like to talk and visit with one another far more than they
like to listen to those on the podium.
</P>
<P>
   But, that's politics and that's fair _ especially when you
realize those rude roars are heard only by the poor speakers, not
those hearing the word on sheltered television microphones.
</P>
<P>
   The one speech that really counts and that most are interested
in hearing at any political convention is the acceptance speech by
the nominee. That's pretty much as it ever has been and ever shall
be.
</P>
<P>
   In the talk about the conventions that came before most of us,
the one thing that dominates is the nominating process. For
example, there are those who can describe with vivid recall the
votes at conventions in the 1950s. Ask them about any speeches _
including the acceptance ones _ and, usually, your answer is heavy
silence and blank faces.
</P>
<P>
   It's not television's fault _ the major networks who carry too
little and the cable networks who try to fill too much air time.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the political parties' fault. Their leaders would be
fools to pass up such golden opportunities for party pep rallies
and any exposure to the general public they can get for their
candidates, their campaigns and, hey, even their kind-of basic
political philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the fault of newspapers, which have the luxury of
filling their pages with reports and observations of events and
intrigues that television _ even most delegates _ never could find.
</P>
<P>
   It's not even the fault of political columnists _ ragtag and
otherwise _ who analyze and pontificate, lecture and share, find
merit in and scorn the worth of today's political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   It's no one special's fault, but maybe we all ought to work
together to change from the kind of national nominating conventions
that served the purpose of their names to the post-primary
conventions of today which, in truth, are not nominating but
acceptance conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, even political junkies recognize some things political
are nothing but awfully ho hum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
