<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6579 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-19 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TABLE-HOPPING IN SAN FRANCISCO AND NAPA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- San Francisco and Boston: often compared, but
really a continent apart. A recent visit, in the chilly month of
June, provided a few more comparisons and some notable differences.
The city by the bay is a food town extraordinaire and has been for
ages, fueled by the ever-ready supply of California's bounty; its
restaurants are filled with a combination of fervent local diners,
tourists, and convention goers. And then there's Napa, where the
ribbon of Route 29 that snakes from the town of Napa through St.
Helena and on past Calistoga can only be compared to Route 6 on the
Cape. Once on, there's no escape as the traffic crawls ever so
slowly north.
</P>
<P>
   Some notes from the far side of the country:
</P>
<P>
   We arrive at Gary Danko's at 5:30 on a Friday evening, the only
reservation my sister-in-law could wangle by calling weeks ahead of
time. One of the hottest high-toned spots in town, this place has a
dining room that looks like a supper club _ cool, shuttered, and
mirrored, in subdued colors. It's definitely not in the mold of the
big, dramatic palaces now in vogue; not a fish tank or water wall
in evidence. It's named for the chef, a moniker that sounds a
little like an auto parts store.
</P>
<P>
   The room starts to fill up, though, so the slight twinge of
paranoia one feels at being so unfashionably early dissipates
quickly. And the staff, beautifully outfitted in dark suits, is
gracious and chatty. Anyway, by that time we're deep into
deciphering the prix fixe menu, which takes some concentration. A
diner can order three, four, or five courses for prices ranging
from $51 to $70; each portion is adjusted depending on how many
courses are ordered. It's fun to mix and match this way, we decide,
choosing several appetizers, adding an entree, pondering the cheese
course versus dessert. But it sounds chaotic for the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Maitre d' and co-owner Nick Peyton explains later in a phone
interview that the flexible prix fixe came from his frustration. At
many restaurants, he thinks, the ``choices are few and the rules
many.'' This method, he and Danko decided, is more
``user-friendly.'' And, he insists, careful handling means that
dishes don't go astray. No, no one has ever ordered four courses of
desserts, either _ ``although they could if they wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Danko's cuisine reminds me a little of Michael Schlow's at
Radius: the same voluptuousness, the same intensity of flavorings,
all with a classical underpinning in sauces and combinations.
Glazed oysters with a thin, creamy stew of leeks and salsify slide
down the throat luxuriously. A terrine of foie gras boasts crunchy
brioche toast points and a bright lemon chutney. Snapper fillet is
hard-seared at the edges, a brilliant contrast with the creamy
flesh. Danko is superb at game birds, preserving the fine delicacy
of tiny quail and making a masterpiece of a fat squab permeated
with allspice, cinnamon, coriander, and other Moroccan spices. The
bird is stuffed with couscous and, when cut into fat slices,
resembles an intricate sculpture of rosy skin against pale yellow
grain, over a bed of cumin-scented carrots.
</P>
<P>
   We graze through our varied courses, liking everything we taste.
We stop short for the impressive cheese cart and slow only slightly
at desserts, the better to appreciate the richness of chocolate
souffle with a chocolate sauce and one of vanilla, enchanting the
child in all of us, and to savor the warm apricot tart. The meal is
delightful, and I'd have to say the philosophy of varying the
portion sizes works _ you leave happy but not stuffed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Napa Valley draws hordes of visitors these days, and we
meander up for two days over a holiday weekend. Big mistake,
trafficwise. So we stick to the back roads and smaller wineries.
</P>
<P>
   Napa restaurants are almost always packed _ wine tasting can
make one hungry. Bistro Jeanty, lively, boisterous, and very in
right now, squeezes my husband and me into a table wedged against
the back wall. The women next to us are drinking pink cosmopolitans
through the meal, an odd sight in a French bistro in the heart of
wine country. We eat terrine de lapin (rabbit pate), beet and mache
salad, cassoulet. All the food is great, very authentically French
bistro, as though we've been transported to Lyons. Another bistro,
Bouchon, owned by French Laundry star Thomas Keller and his
brother, has also opened in the valley. This seems odd too: robust
French frites and pieds de cochon (pigs' feet) in the heart of
Cal-Ital.
</P>
<P>
   We all have our favorites, though, and mine in Napa is Terra, a
St. Helena restaurant owned by husband and wife Hiro Sone and Lissa
Doumani. Sone, the chef, and Doumani, who oversees desserts, met at
Spago, where they both worked, and 12 years ago opened this 90-seat
place in an old stone building. Perusing the menu reveals no
prevailing style or cuisine. Some dishes sound Italian, some
French, many appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's food that we like to eat,'' says Doumani in a later phone
interview. The couple matches ingredients to the climate of the
valley, she says, eschewing any particular style, the benefit of
having one's one restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The individuality is certainly part of the appeal. Cauliflower
soup is so simple _ cauliflower, cream, peekytoe crab, and a little
American caviar _ that chef Sone is amazed when people order one,
finish it, and order another. Pure and elemental in flavor, cool
and smooth, the soup is fantastic; we don't order a second, but we
think about it.
</P>
<P>
   The grilled quail is fine but can't match the beauty of a plate
of spaghettini with tripe, tomatoes, and white beans. Although I've
always pretended to like tripe, some versions of it feature too
much tomato sauce and tough strands of tripe; the Chinese style is
almost always too chewy. This is pared-down tripe gently handled,
the strips tender, discreetly tossed among the beans and bits of
roasted tomatoes. The dish is comforting rather than spectacular,
sustaining rather than overwhelming. It cements my admiration for
Sone's cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As we get ready to leave Terra, the manager, Tim Mosher, asks if
we'd like to take the rest of our bottle of pinot noir with us.
It's a pleasant surprise, as the two of us rarely finish a whole
bottle and have gotten used to squandering the last third or so,
rather than drinking more than safety allows.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, alcohol laws and restaurant practices differ greatly
from state to state; Terra's practice would be verboten in
Massachusetts, where having an open bottle in the car could get you
hauled in. Mosher's view is that it's much safer to take the wine,
rather than feeling obliged to drink it all.
</P>
<P>
   Wine is a big deal, of course, in Napa and all over California.
Although most restaurants have impressive wine selections, it's
fairly common for diners to bring bottles along with them. Not an
eyebrow is raised when one of our party brings a French burgundy to
Gary Danko's, though a $25 corkage fee is charged.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Liquor Licensing Board spokesman explains that the
practice isn't allowed here because the city issues licenses on a
``public need'' basis. If bottles were brought in, the city would
lose its control over alcohol consumed. Not to mention upsetting
the earning potential of those getting a liquor license.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
