<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LOFTY GOALS BEHIND `LAUGHABLE' LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Stephen Barnett, a law professor at the
University of California at Berkeley, says Julia Hill ``ought to be
laughed out of court.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, Barnett argues: ``The idea of living in a tree
doesn't belong to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. How naive of Hill in this day and age to sue a big
Internet service provider and its even bigger ad agency for
allegedly imitating her likeness and profaning every personal and
public thing for which she stands.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, such idealistic sensitivity should be expected from
a person who re-adopted her childhood nickname of ``Butterfly'' and
spent two years living all alone on a fragile wooden platform atop
a 200-feet-tall, old-growth California redwood.
</P>
<P>
   This is a person who named the tree ``Luna.''
</P>
<P>
   And swears she still feels the 1,300-year-old giant's spirit
deep within her own heart.
</P>
<P>
   We are not exactly talking about the most normal, practical
human being on Earth here, now are we?
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Hill climbed down from her tree in Humboldt County on
Dec. 18, packs of people _ for and against the movement to save
old-growth redwoods in Northern California _ have been waiting for
her to make another kind of descent.
</P>
<P>
   Into the realm of the co-opted and the sell-outs.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and handsome like Luna, and the daughter of an Arkansas
preacher, Hill is only 26 years old. But already she is a
bigger-than-life symbol to thousands.
</P>
<P>
   To some, she's a born-again mystic, a young woman who climbed a
threatened tree for what she thought would be a few weeks of
protest, and ended up learning some eternal truths about life and
the cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   To others, she is an environmental hero, whose dangerous,
self-sacrificing effort to spare one old tree from clear-cutting
raised awareness of the entire movement.
</P>
<P>
   To still others, Hill is an airy-fairy activist wannabe, a
woman, according to columnist Alexander Cockburn, whose ``fiery
anti-corporate rhetoric'' has been ``replaced by banal spiritual
homilies and indifferent poesy.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, as Hill told the Associated Press earlier this
year:
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has an opinion, a demand, a request, a feeling, a
thought, you name it, about me and what I'm doing with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Although people are waiting (eagerly or fearfully) for her moral
descent, Hill has so far stayed her course. In a society that
constantly whipsaws between its desire for hope and its incurable
cynicism, she has managed to walk an excruciatingly narrow
tightrope of do-gooder celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   She has done this, it seems, by holding sacrosanct the integrity
of her name and the benevolent wisdom she believes Luna imparted
during their 738-day cohabitation.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when Hill saw a print ad for OmniSky, a Palo Alto-based
Internet and e-mail service provider, she felt violated.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ad does not use her name, it shows a young woman
with long dark hair like Hill's, sitting on a small wooden platform
high up in a redwood tree. Using OmniSky, she's asking a man at the
base of the tree to come up and give her - a sponge bath.
</P>
<P>
   In her lawsuit in U.S. District Court in San Francisco, Hill
alleges that OmniSky, its parent carrier, AT&AMP;T, and the company's
ad agency, TBWA Chiat/Day have ``severely and irreparably harmed
Ms. Hill and the movement she has come to symbolize.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, the suit says the ad is ``completely antithetical to
Ms. Hill's values, and (is) profoundly injurious and destructive of
the sanctity of her peace, happiness, and feelings, as well as her
privacy, identity and her life's work.''
</P>
<P>
   The aim of Hill's suit is to force OmniSky and the other
companies to stop running the ad, turn it over to her and destroy
all copies. She is also asking for unspecified damages that,
according to a spokesman, would be used _ as are profits from her
recent book _ for Hill's environmental activities, not for her
personal gain.
</P>
<P>
   Since news of the suit broke last week, legal experts like
Stephen Barnett have weighed in. Most share the Berkeley
professor's dim view, if not of the suit itself as ``laughable,''
at least of Hill's chances of winning.
</P>
<P>
   As one entertainment industry attorney, Harley Williams of Los
Angeles, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Does a picture of a woman sitting in a tree have a secondary
meaning that says, `That's Julia'? It seems unlikely to me, but
she'll get significant publicity for herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, so far, is the same thing as saying Hill will get a
significant amount of public attention for her cause: Luna and
everything that giant old redwood represents.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
