u l BC-SUMMER-JOB-BOS &LR;      07-19 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-JOB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING' LA VIDA LOONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGAWAM, Mass. _ It's another sunny summer day deep inside Looney
Tunes Movie Town at Six Flags New England. Way off to one side of
the amusement park, between the Speed Trap kiddie ride and the
Subway food stand, about 125 squinting patrons have gathered in
front of a small stage. They're sporting tank tops, T-shirts,
halter tops, shorts, sandals, sneakers,
</P>
<P>
   and various degrees of sunburn.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole DiDomenico is ready for them. Indeed, the 19-year-old
college student must be ready for them five times a day, five or
six days a week, from Memorial Day through Labor Day. That's nearly
400 times that she'll portray either Sylvester the cat or Foghorn
Leghorn the rooster, dancing and prancing her way (a soundtrack
provides the characters' voices) in a heavy, oversize costume
through a 25-minute performance of the Chevy Venture Looney Tunes
Rockin' Road Show. Before waving good-bye to the small crowd, she
always lumbers to the front of the stage to silently touch and
cuddle many of the kids who've been watching, some of whom warily
pose beside her while their parents capture the Kodak moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like I've (itals)already(unitals) been in 400
shows,'' DiDomenico declares wearily after a recent performance.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she's complaining. As summer jobs go, this one beats
working down at the Meriden Square Shopping Center, nearer to her
home in Berlin, Conn., where she labored last summer. (It pays
more, too: $7 an hour vs. $6.75.) ``I'm dancing, I'm sweating, and
I'm losing weight,'' DiDomenico says. ``This isn't sitting indoors
behind a counter and saying, `Can I help you?' over and over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, it's a job that DiDomenico can't admit to, at least not
publicly. In order to reinforce the illusion that a 6-foot cat or a
7-foot rooster is real, she can never be seen by outsiders (or
photographed) while getting into or out of her costume. She must
always refer to Sylvester and Foghorn in the third person, as in
``Sylvester is a very unlucky cat'' or ``Foghorn is very much into
himself.'' In fact, she can't even say she ``plays'' a role, but
must instead insist that she ``helps'' her characters perform in
the same way that, say, 16-year-old Sean Hatcher ``helps'' Bugs
Bunny and 20-year-old Christina Fletcher ``helps'' Daffy Duck on
the Looney Tunes stage. So if you ask her if it's hot inside a
rooster suit, she'll reply earnestly, ``Don't worry. Foghorn is
very comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even ``helping'' makes a nice addition to a resume,
especially for a dance performance major at Hartford Conservatory
who began taking lessons at age 3 and is now being paid to be
onstage for the first time. ``It could be valuable if I ever wanted
to work at, like, Disney,'' points out DiDomenico, who drives about
80 miles round-trip to work each day. And just maybe, she reasons,
it could eventually help her to land her dream job: a role in the
musical ``Cats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have to be on Broadway,'' she adds hastily. ``It
could just be a tour of America. Even if it just toured
(itals)Connecticut,(unitals) I wouldn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Six Flags New England will do. The 235-acre
park, an impressive and continuing makeover of the former and
frumpy Riverside Amusement Park, employs over 3,000 seasonal
employees, according to a spokesperson. About 600 of these are
recruited overseas, but most of the rest, like DiDomenico, come
from the Connecticut River valley. They're ride operators,
maintenance workers, games overseers, food servers, parking
attendants, security guards, sales and marketing interns, ticket
takers, performers, and EMTs. So important are young seasonal
workers to the park that it has been granted a temporary waiver
permitting 16- and 17-year-olds to remain on the job until 11 p.m.,
rather than until the 10 p.m. deadline mandated by Massachusetts
child-labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that stage performers have a certain status
among park workers, DiDomenico, who works an 11 a.m.-to-7 p.m.
shift, hardly has a star painted on her dressing room door. She and
the four other cast members of the Looney Tunes show, the eldest of
whom is 21, reach their small shared quarters via a corridor that
also provides access to a public men's room. Their major amenities
are a small freezer, a tiny sofa, a boombox, and a single shower.
``Anyone who comes to visit us sits on the floor,'' says
DiDomenico, who got her job here after two auditions. (``I cried.
My father cried.'')
</P>
<P>
   Her duties, meanwhile, don't end with her performance. Cast
members must frequently wash down the stage and pick up trash
around the low red benches on which the audience hunkers down.
Between performances _ always wearing their bright blue park
shirts, name tags, khaki shorts or pants, and white shoes and socks
_ they are encouraged to attend other park shows and to provide
exaggerated enthusiasm. For DiDomenico and her co-performers, that
often means hooting at the five-piece Dixieland Express (``They're
the (itals)ooooonly(unitals) live music in the park,'' she
laments), after which the two groups of young performers try to
figure out how to kill time until their next shows:
</P>
<P>
   ``You wanna hang in our dressing room?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah. You wanna hang in our dressing room?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The major alternative is the Caf, a.k.a. Wabbits, a well-hidden
and Spartan employee cafteria that features decidedly non-park food
prices ($1.25 hamburgers! 75-cent french fries!) and where the
major decoration is a sign telling workers what to do if they
encounter a lost child. Employees are not allowed to partake of the
park's rides during working hours, although they do receive a free
admission pass once a week. And shopping within the park, even with
a 35 percent employee discount, isn't a particularly attractive
option when you're making $7 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sure you don't wanna hang in our dressing room?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah. You sure you don't wanna hang out in (itals)our(unitals)
dressing room?''
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, only 185 shows until Labor Day, right? Meanwhile,
DiDomenico's summer job will help pay for a new Hyundai, a cell
phone, and clothes down at the mall. ``It's been a fun summer and
I've met a lot of new people,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``But next year,'' adds the former high school swim-team
captain, referring to Six Flags' water park here, ``I think I want
to be a lifeguard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
