<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6585 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOUSE-FANS-0720-COX     07-19 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-FANS-0720- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COX &HT;    Adding a bathroom exhaust fan good way to lower humidity in the
house
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Around the Miami Valley we have fairly mild
summers temperature-wise, but it gets seriously uncomfortable when
the humidity is high. If you can lower the humidity inside your
house during the cooling season, you can raise the thermostat on
your air conditioner and still feel cool.
</P>
<P>
   That's why adding a bathroom exhaust fan or a range hood that
exhausts outdoors is a good investment for saving energy. Today
we'll concentrate on bathroom fans, but installing a range hood is
not much different.
</P>
<P>
   The two most important issues in deciding between two bathroom
exhaust fans are capacity and noise levels, and both are easy to
compare.
</P>
<P>
   When you visit a store to shop for exhaust fans, you'll find
most of them are marked with a CFM number such as 80 CFM or 120
CFM. This represents the number of cubic feet of air the unit moves
per minute.
</P>
<P>
   The larger the bathroom, the larger the CFM number required. A
100 CFM fan can handle a bathroom of about 90 square feet (9 by 10
feet), for example.
</P>
<P>
   The fan package will also be marked with a sones number
indicating how loud or quiet the unit is. A fan rated 1 sone makes
about as much noise as a whisper, and some fans are rated as low as
0.5 sone.
</P>
<P>
   Most moderately priced fans fall in the 2.5 to 5 sones range. A
fan above about 6 sones is likely to produce a drone that will
become very unpleasant after a while.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've decided how much capacity you need and how much
noise you're willing to tolerate, you can start shopping for other
features such as lights, heaters and automatic controls.
</P>
<P>
   Several local home-improvement stores carry plain,
ceiling-mounted fans delivering about 130 CFM and producing about
2.5 sones for about $75 to $100, not including installation
hardware. Such units have a plastic cover and no lights.
</P>
<P>
   Add a light and a night light and the price increases about $30
for the same power. Replace the plastic with wood and brass for
another $10 or so.
</P>
<P>
   Some exhaust-fan units come with built-in heaters to help warm
the bathroom. The heater units readily available at local stores
have electric heaters using about 1,200 to 1,600 watts, which means
they'll need to be placed on a hefty circuit (about 20 amps) or
they might trip breakers or blow fuses.
</P>
<P>
   The fans with heaters also tend to devote less power to moving
air, so their ratings drop toward the 70 CFM to 90 CFM range. They
sell for about $100 to $200, with the wood and brass models at the
high end.
</P>
<P>
   A check of local stores found no fans with automatic controls .
Automatic fans come equipped with motion detectors to turn on when
someone enters the bathroom or humidity detectors to turn on when
the humidity in the bathroom rises.
</P>
<P>
   Stores can order such models for about $215 to $350. But even
without automatic controls, it's a simple matter to turn a fan on
and off with a wall switch.
</P>
<P>
   Putting in an exhaust fan requires what I call second-tier
do-it-yourself skills; it's harder than entry-level jobs like
replacing a light switch but easier than building a room addition.
</P>
<P>
   Fan installation requires some carpentry and wiring skill, plus
the use of a reciprocating saw, a tool most people don't have lying
around. You'll also probably need to climb on the roof and remove
some shingles.
</P>
<P>
   The best place to install an exhaust fan is on the ceiling of
the bathroom, but that is only practical for the do-it-yourselfer
if the area above the bathroom is accessible, as in the floor of an
attic.
</P>
<P>
   Start the installation by opening the package the fan comes in,
reading the instructions carefully and doing an inventory of parts
and materials.
</P>
<P>
   Most fans don't come with exhaust pipes, roof vents and wall
switches, so you'll need to determine what materials you'll need to
finish the job. Kits are available that promise to include all
you'll need to vent the fan through the roof or through a wall, but
you probably can buy the parts for less by shopping for individual
components in the vent-pipe aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Take the main housing of the fan into the attic and lay it next
to an attic floor joist over the position you want the grille in
the bathroom below. Mark the outline on the ceiling and cut along
the lines. The best way to make a clean cut is to drill holes at
the corners of the outline and cut along the lines with a hand
jigsaw or wallboard saw.
</P>
<P>
   Hold the fan housing in place over the opening and have an
assistant in the bathroom below attach the grille facing to the fan
housing. Attach the housing to the joist in a position that lets
the grille sit flush against the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   If your fan has a light or heater, you'll have to install boards
on either side of it to hold back the attic insulation. Insulation
resting against a hot fan housing is a fire hazard.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is wiring. You'll have to run an appropriate
electrical cable into the box and attach it to the house's power
supply at a wall switch. If you're not sure how to do that, it's
probably a job best left to a professional electrician.
</P>
<P>
   The next phase is providing a path for the moisture-laden air to
be pushed outside. Allowing the fan to simply blow its air into the
attic can cause moisture problems there, and failing to vent a fan
outside violates most community building codes.
</P>
<P>
   From the underside of the roof, select a spot near the fan
housing for the exhaust pipe to poke through the roof. Pick a spot
next to a rafter so you'll have something to anchor the vent to.
</P>
<P>
   Mark a circle large enough to accept the vent tailpiece next to
the rafter. Cut it out with a reciprocating saw. Attach a clamp to
the rafter just inside the hole to hold the tailpiece in place.
</P>
<P>
   While on the roof, remove shingles but not the roof paper from
the area where the vent cover flange (a protective metal plate)
around the vent will go. Stick the tailpiece through the hole and
clamp it in place. Attach the vent cover to the tailpiece and apply
roofing cement to the bottom of the flange before nailing it in
place with roofing nails.
</P>
<P>
   Run a length of flexible exhaust hose from the outlet on the fan
housing to the tailpiece of the vent. Wrap the hose with pipe
insulation to reduce condensation that could drip and damage the
fan motor.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, take the electric line you ran into the fan housing
earlier and attach it to the motor, making sure first that the line
is not live.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't get at the fan from above, you can follow a similar
series of steps and mount a fan high on a wall and vent it through
the wall directly to the outside.
</P>
<P>
   As mentioned earlier, installing an exhaust fan is a fairly
complicated project, and the instructions that come with your fan
may not be clear enough for you to finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   The best source I've found for extra advice on this job is the
book ``Home Improvement 1-2-3: Expert Advice From the Home Depot.''
You can find it at the public library.
</P>
<P>
   Contact James Cummings by e-mail at jamescummings(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
