u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     07-19 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDS ANSWER THE FERVOR FOR TECH STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Putnam Investments launched a brand-new technology mutual fund
this week. MFS Investment Management recently introduced a
technology fund and a global telecom fund. In September, Fidelity
Investments will roll out two new select funds, one for the
wireless industry, one for the networking business.
</P>
<P>
   Raise your hand if you spot a trend here.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is not just a sector anymore. It is an asset class,
and people can't get enough of it.
</P>
<P>
   In the first five months of the year, more than one out of every
three dollars that went into mutual funds found its way into
technology funds, according to FRC, a Boston company that tracks
mutual-fund flows. A big chunk of that money went to Janus, the
Denver mutual fund company, which boasts a family of tech funds.
</P>
<P>
   The other fund companies are suffering from Janus envy, and
their response has been a predictable one. Practically every major
fund group, including some that have never sold anything but fully
diversified funds, has hopped on the technology bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Among those that have created or filed to create new tech funds
are Pioneer, Neuberger &AMP; Berman, Oppenheimer, Franklin, and Charles
Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of feedback from the people who sell our funds,
asking for a technology offering,'' said David Oliveri, a spokesman
for MFS, explaining his firm's decision to get into the technology
fund business. Putnam heard the same thing from its brokers.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to blame investors for their single-minded pursuit of
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want performance,'' said David O'Leary, president of
Alpha Equity Research. Technology has had performance in spades.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: The Nasdaq Composite index, which is technology-heavy,
last year was up 86 percent. Even with the big sell-off this
spring, many tech stocks are hitting new highs.
</P>
<P>
   When Lipper Inc. recently ranked the top mutual funds of the
past 10 years, the first four funds on the list were Fidelity
select funds that invest in technology: Select Electronics, Select
Technology, Select Computer, and Select Developing Communications.
All were up at least 1,400 percent over the 10-year period. The
best funds over the past one year, three years, or five years are
also technology names.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks account for 34 percent of the total value of
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, up from 7 percent in 1989. Said
O'Leary: ``Who is to say that in five years, the number won't be up
to 50 percent?''
</P>
<P>
   Given their mad dash to technology, you might guess that
investors don't own much technology in their regular mutual funds.
Nothing could be further from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   At Putnam, for instance, popular growth funds like Voyager,
Vista, and New Opportunities have anywhere from 45 percent to 60
percent of their money in tech stocks, according to the company's
Web site. At Fidelity, both Retirement Growth and Aggressive Growth
have 65 percent of their money in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Asking for more technology on top of that is a bit like asking
for french fries with your french fries.
</P>
<P>
   Burt Greenwald worries that investors may wind up with
indigestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry was built on the tenet that you should diversify
your risks,'' said Greenwald, a mutual fund consultant in
Philadelphia. ``The thinner you slice the baloney _ to high tech,
to telecom, to wireless _ the more you are increasing the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Benz, a senior analyst with Morningstar Inc., which
tracks the mutual fund business, makes a similar point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most investors would be better off with a regular growth
fund,'' she said. ``They will have plenty of exposure to
technology, plus the manager has the flexibility to go elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Benz makes one more point: With a big-name growth fund,
investors are likely to get experienced money managers. On the new
pure-tech funds, the managers are more likely to be no-name
rookies.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what? No one cares. Technology has become a religion,
with a large group of faithful followers. Those disciples believe
in technology _ and they don't want to hear about risk and
diversification.
</P>
<P>
   So far, their faith has been handsomely rewarded, and sticking
with technology, even during difficult times like this spring, has
proved to be a wise course.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund companies have little choice but to give investors
more technology funds. The alternative is to watch the money flow
out the door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
