<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6588 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CHURCHES-WOMEN-ART-BO     07-19 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHES-WOMEN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 BARRIERS BEYOND THE CHURCH DOOR FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This has been a summer of symbols for women of the cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it was the African Methodist Episcopal church, which
elected the Rev. Vashi McKenzie of Baltimore to be the first woman
bishop of a black Protestant denomination.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks earlier, the nation's largest Protestant
denomination moved in the opposite direction, declaring that women
should not serve as pastors in Southern Baptist churches.
</P>
<P>
   And just last Thursday, the Episcopal Church started
disciplinary action against three dioceses that have refused to
ordain women even though the denomination has allowed women priests
for 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   Since the women's movement propelled the first major wave of
women into Protestant seminaries 30 years ago, women ministers have
made some remarkable advances, including ascending in Massachusetts
to the top posts of three denominations.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to scholars and clergy, women still face
obstacles that have come to be known as a stained-glass ceiling.
Women in ministry, on average, earn less money and have less
prestigious assignments than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appointment of one person to high liturgical office does
not mean the barrier is down at all,'' said Edward C. Lehman, an
emeritus professor of sociology at the State University of New York
at Brockport. ``Even though denominational executives try to to say
the system is equal for men and women, in practice it doesn't work
out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Women now make up an estimated 11 percent of clergy nationwide,
and 31 percent of students preparing for ordination at graduate
schools of theology. The Unitarian Universalist Association is the
first denomination in which women make up more than 50 percent of
ministers; at the historic Andover Newton Theological School in
Newton, Mass., women make up 60 percent of the student body.
</P>
<P>
   And women in New England have achieved some lofty positions. The
United Methodist Church's top regional administrator is a woman,
Bishop Susan W. Hassinger; so is the top official of Massachusetts'
American Baptist Churches, the Rev. Linda Spoolstra. And the Rev.
Margaret G. Payne of Shelburne, Mass. will be installed as bishop
of the New England synod of the Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America in September.
</P>
<P>
   The Rt. Rev. Barbara C. Harris, the No. 2 official in the
Episcopal Diocese of Massachusetts, was the first woman to become
an Anglican bishop, and Virginia S. Harris is the top official of
the lay-led Christian Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   But at the level of churches, differences persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really trying hard in many more liberal denominations .
. . and we need to celebrate that, but the problem is there is
still an inner, unnamed desire to have men lead,'' said the Rev.
Jan Powers, pastor of North Congregational Church in North Amherst,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Research studies over the last several decades, conducted by
universities and within denominations, confirm that impression.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 79 percent of United Church of Christ pastors are
men, but the majority of associate pastors are women, and women are
more likely than men to fill positions overseeing religious
education, music, and youth programs. And women in the UCC earn
less money than men in the same positions.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics from the Presbyterian Church (USA) show a similar
pattern _ a higher percentage of men as senior pastors, and a
higher percentage of women in junior positions.
</P>
<P>
   An official of the American Baptist Churches believes women are
losing ground. The American Baptists have been ordaining women for
130 years, but the official said some churches are now hiring males
pastors ordained in other denominations rather than female American
Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am seeing increasingly large numbers of women entering
seminary, and many of them are graduating with honors, but they are
not getting placed,'' said the Rev. Valentine B. Royal, director of
American Baptist Women in Ministry. ``I would say that we have lost
ground. It's reverting to the old boys club. People don't even feel
compelled to interview women anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   That pattern was confirmed by Paula D. Nesbitt, a sociologist at
the University of Denver and author of ``Feminization of the Clergy
in America,'' who researched the Episcopal Church and the Unitarian
Universalist Assocation and concluded that the more women entered
the ministry, the fewer prestigious opportunities were available to
them. Instead, Nesbitt says, women clergy wind up in in part-time,
low-paying, or junior jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last 30 to 40 years, there has been a proportional
diminishment of opportunities to get into high-level leadership
positions,'' Nesbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The picture for women is bleaker outside mainline Protestant
churches. Roman Catholics, Greek Orthodox, and Orthodox Jews do not
ordain women; women also do not lead Muslims in worship.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelical churches have a mixed history; the Southern Baptists
recently made clear their reluctance to see women as pastors, but
just last week a prominent Pentecostal official responded by urging
churches to allow women in leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Reform and Conservative Jewish semiaries are ordaining
increasing numbers of women rabbis, but most preside over small
congregations. The most prominent exception is Rabbi Emily Lipoff
of Temple Ohabei Shalom in Brookline, Mass., one of only two rabbis
in the country heading a large congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Women ministers say they must combat a number of stereotypes:
that they will have more trouble balancing work and family than a
man, that they will be less adept at handling financial and
administrative decisions, and that many people, when visualizing a
pastor, see a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a reluctance to seeing that women have the
intellectual capacity to make hard decisions on employment
practices and property issues,'' said the Rev. Carol M. Flett,
rector of St. Peter's Episcopal Church in Weston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Judith L. Rhodes of Emmanuel Church in Boston's West
Roxbury neighborhood said women must prove their abilities in
managerial areas where men are assumed to be strong. Rhodes calls
the Diocese of Massachusetts ``extremely welcoming'' to women, but
says ``I do think there are not as many opportunities in larger,
wealthier parishes for women as rectors as I'd like to see.''
</P>
<P>
   In the historically black Protestant denominations, progress has
been particularly slow. The handful of women who head black
churches in Massachusetts have small congregations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always known that women maintain and sustain our
churches, but this has been one place where our leadership has been
firmly men,'' said the Rev. Gloria White-Hammond, co-pastor of
Bethel AME Church in Boston. ``Smart white men went a lot of
different places, but this was a place where a smart black male,
when he couldn't go to law school or medical school, went.''
</P>
<P>
   Every woman minister interviewed for this story said women have
made more progress in Massachusetts than elsewhere, and each
praised her own church hierarchy for trying to ensure fairness. But
each woman also had stories of ways in which they were treated
differently based on gender _ usually by having the work-family
balance or their administrative faculties questioned, but sometimes
by outright discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several jobs I didn't get far in because the
churches were looking for men,'' said the Rev. Rebecca Brown, an
interim minister at Second Congregational Church in Winchester,
Mass. But Brown said she found other congregations that were happy
to employ a woman, and that in general, ``we're doing great.''
</P>
<P>
   Women in ministry can't turn to the courts _ a tactic used by
women in other professions _ because churches are exempt from
antidiscrimination laws. And in many denominations, ministers are
hired by congregations, not assigned, limiting the ability of
leadership to force change.
</P>
<P>
   The American Baptists are testing one strategy: asking
congregations to accept resumes that do not reveal gender.
</P>
<P>
   Other denominations appoint female interim ministers to
congregations wary of women leaders, hoping their fears will be
assuaged. This strategy worked for Flett, who became rector of a
Burlington, Mass. church that wanted a man but changed its mind
after working with a woman on a temporary basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's often a powerful indigenous reluctance to accept women
in ministry, but often if the first woman minister is an interim,
and they start to like her, then things start to change,'' said the
Rev. Paula J. Fletcher of United Church in Clinton, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
