<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DEADLY-MOSQUITO-ART-B     07-19 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEADLY-MOSQUITO-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNTING A WINGED MENACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRATHAM, N.H. _ On a recent morning, a blond woman in
camouflage picked her way through ripe-smelling farmland toward a
trap she had set the night before, its nylon now shuddering with
the weightless bodies of mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Tricked by a stream of carbon dioxide they had mistaken for a
mammal's breath, they had been sucked by the tiniest of fans into a
cone-shaped net where they trembled together, whining.
</P>
<P>
   Some mornings, Sarah MacGregor has found as many as 8,000
mosquitoes crowded inside the bag, in a pile so dense that they
give off the distinct scent one of her staff describes as
``meaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days, their corpses would be packed in dry ice, mailed to
Boston and painstakingly analyzed, on the infinitesimal,
needle-in-a-haystack chance that the mosquitoes of Stratham are
carrying the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   James Stuart's dairy farm is 300 miles from New York City, where
seven people died last summer after the mosquito-borne virus
mysteriously surfaced for the first time on this continent. Crows
and hawks have not fallen out of the sky in New Hampshire,
supplying clues about where the virus is dwelling, as they have in
New York and New Jersey this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But as late summer approaches, and mosquitoes rise by the
millions out of salt marshes, scientists all along the East Coast
are racing to find the virus in insects or animals before human
cases show up.
</P>
<P>
   (Officials are already scrambling to spray parts of New York
City, Long Island and Westchester County after announcing Monday
(July 17) that the virus had been found in mosquitoes, Associated
Press reported this week.)
</P>
<P>
   Experts predict infected mosquitoes will already have scattered,
making them more difficult to kill. There is no cure for West Nile
encephalitis, which is fatal in 3 to 15 percent of human cases.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah MacGregor and her corps of women in hip boots are a
distant outpost in the search for the virus, and her anxiety about
it is mixed with the eagerness of the mobilized volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first mosquito bite I got this year, I looked at it and
thought, `Could this be the one?' '' said MacGregor, who began
working in mosquito control 21 years ago, fresh from the University
of New Hampshire's entomology program. ``I've worked my whole
career to help battle a public health emergency. So it's
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for the West Nile virus, sustained at a low boil all
winter, has lurched back to life as the height of mosquito season
approaches. After 20 years in the business, MacGregor knew enough
to give a shudder at noon last Sunday, when _ based on the
staggering number of larva she had found in water samples around
Stratham _ millions of them pulled their stalky, black-and-white
legs out of the marsh and balanced themselves precariously on the
water's surface. For an hour, they sat on the marsh hardening their
exoskeletons in the sun, then embarked on a life spent blindly
seeking moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Around noon, a craving for protein came over the fertilized
females, who took to the air in search of a stream of warm breath
and what scientists refer to as a ``blood meal.''
</P>
<P>
   The project of controlling mosquitoes has met with skepticism
from the public ever since 1912, when John B. Smith, New Jersey's
state entomologist, tried to convince state lawmakers to require
local programs _ and was roundly ridiculed for it, as if he had
proposed abolishing bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was regarded as exceptionally radical,'' said Wayne Crans,
director of mosquito research at Rutgers University in New Jersey.
``One of the comments (from lawmakers) was, `Why not a law to
exterminate potato bugs?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But that skepticism was not in evidence last year, after 63
nonfatal and seven fatal cases of West Nile encephalitis were
reported in the New York City area. Humans can contract the virus
only through the bite of a mosquito, which in turn contracts the
disease from a ``reservoir'' such as wild birds or livestock. Last
year's human victims described initial symptons as mild and
flu-like, and most were not seriously ill. But a few developed
encephalitis, a sometimes fatal swelling in the brain or spinal
column.
</P>
<P>
   So far, this summer has provided only a trickle of information
about where the virus is living, despite a $7.7 million program for
surveillance of wild birds, chickens, livestock and mosquitoes in
the 17 states and two cities targeted by the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   In February, an infected red-tailed hawk fell dead from a tree
in Westchester County. In March, officials at the CDC announced
that the virus had been found in mosquito larva that had survived
underground through the winter, so the outbreak would not _ as had
been hoped _ die out with the end of mosquito season. Three crows
were found infected in New Jersey and New York in June. And by last
week, the number of infected birds found had climbed to 13,
scattered among New York's Suffolk, Weschester and Rockland
counties, as well as Bergen County in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Although mosquitoes are the only creatures known to transmit the
virus, not one infected mosquito has been found yet this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have found it,'' said Crans. ``The crows are trying
to tell us something. They're saying, `You're looking in the wrong
place.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's outbreak was confined to New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut, but public health officials say it is possible that by
August, infected birds may migrate from New York City to the south
coast of Massachusetts. Rhode Island and Connecticut were also
singled out by the CDC as potential danger spots. The three
northern New England states were not designated danger spots, but _
like states as far away as Washington State _ are all applying for
federal funds to test their mosquitoes for disease. MacGregor,
whose company, Dragon Mosquito Control, has a contract with the
state, hopes to see the present surveillance program increased
tenfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could be healthy on Saturday and by the next Friday on
life support in the hospital,'' she said. ``It's not just a pest.
It could kill your parents. That's very scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The testing process itself is labor-intensive. Once mosquitoes
have been collected, they are sorted by species and grouped in
pools of as many as 50 mosquitoes, said John Anderson, director of
the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station, which this summer
will double the 65,000 insects it tested last year.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen in glass tubes at a temperature of minus 80 degrees, the
mosquitoes are suspended in liquid along with tiny glass beads and
sand-like grinding material, then spun at high speed using a
machine called a vortexer, so the mosquitoes' individual cells have
been broken down. Finally, the lab injects the mosquito parts into
host cells, which are incubated in the hope that any viruses living
within it show themselves, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Once scientists find infected mosquitoes, they can urge
residents to take special precautions against insect bites, and
state officials can decide whether to use pesticide, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   In a field whose experts still sometimes estimate mosquito
populations by counting human complaints, the probability of
finding small numbers of infected mosquitoes, especially in states
with small programs, remains daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with orders of magnitude that are well beyond
public health's ability to sample in a way that would make you feel
that we are doing an exact job,'' said Christopher Mores,
supervisor of arthropod-born virus supervision for the
Massachusetts Department of Public Health, which has screened
mosquitoes for diseases like Eastern Equine Encephalitis for 40
years. But ``if someone can come up with a better'' method of
tracking the disease, ``good luck,'' he added. ``We can't just wait
for humans to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   What people have to remember in the face of these odds is that
``there are no antiviral agents,'' Anderson said. ``There is no
cure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
