<HEADER>
A6596 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-19 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     INVESTORS SHOULD CONSIDER MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SHANNON BUGGS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Vicente Fox won the Mexican presidency, citizens who voted
for him knew the place to celebrate was at the feet of nation's
capital's most famous landmark, the Angel of Independence on
Reforma Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Investors knew better.
</P>
<P>
   The real place to party in Mexico City was in the financial
district, at the Bolsa Mexicana de Valores, the country's stock
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the election the bolsa jumped more than 6 percent.
But since then, the index has been in a holding pattern. Although
there is good reason to be excited about the potential impact the
election will have on the economy, investors realize significant
changes are a long way off.
</P>
<P>
   The historic election ended 71 years of rule by the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, which is known by its
Spanish-language initials PRI, and revived international interest
in Mexico's markets.
</P>
<P>
   But before individual investors rush to chase that rally, they
must consider the risks that shape the Mexican economy.
</P>
<P>
   Elections in Mexico typically are followed by major crashes in
the Mexican financial markets. So far, it appears Mexico will avoid
that curse this year. But even if the economy remains stable
through the presidential transition, investors can't count on big
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot forget about the fact that embedded in the
investment decision is the possibility there could be a
devaluation,'' says Rafael Bello, a Latin American analyst with
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``A country like Mexico is not going to
guarantee stellar performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is still considered an emerging market.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of reasons for that, not the least of which is
debilitating poverty that engulfs large chunks of the population
and prevents the government from collecting enough in taxes to
sustain social programs that could raise literacy rates and income
levels.
</P>
<P>
   This economy still depends on state-run companies that
monopolize the nation's electric, petroleum and other top
industries. On the campaign trail, Fox promised to bring more
competition and foreign investment to Mexico, stopping short of
committing to privatization. But it may take him his entire
six-year term to make good on that.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force behind Mexico's recent prosperity is exports.
More than 80 percent of Mexico's goods and services are sold to the
United States, with Canada and European nations trailing far
behind. So, if the U.S. economy slows, the Mexican economy will
also pull back.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of that can be seen now. At the end of the first
quarter, Mexico's economy grew 7.9 percent, and it's on track to
end the year at 5.2 percent, says Joyce Chang, head of global
fixed-income research at Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's emerging status is also a reflection of the high
volatility in its markets.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Mexico's bonds were listed as junk bonds by the
nation's top rating companies. Now its bonds are considered
investment grade by one of the rating companies, and the other is
expected to up its rating of Mexico to investment-grade by year's
end.
</P>
<P>
   The improved ratings can be attributed, in part, to the free
market reforms started by outgoing President Ernesto Zedillo, whose
six-year term ends on Dec. 1. Fox has the difficult job of
maintaining Zedillo's fiscal discipline while shepherding reforms
in the tax system, courts and schools through political land mines.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this will happen overnight, so if you choose to
invest in Mexico at all, consider it to be a long-term proposition
rather than a short-term one.
</P>
<P>
   So, how can investors take advantage of the political changes,
the credit upgrade and the improved economy?
</P>
<P>
   One of a handful of possibilities is stock in Mexican companies
or U.S. companies with Mexican operations, but the risks and
returns cover a wide range.
</P>
<P>
   The most efficient way to bet on all of Mexico is to buy either
closed-end country funds or international index funds.
</P>
<P>
   Closed-end country funds are mutual fund investment companies
with a fixed number of shares that can be bought and sold on stock
exchanges at a discount or for a premium.
</P>
<P>
   There are two for Mexico _ Mexico Fund, on the New York Stock
Exchange under the ticker MXF, and Mexico Equity and Income Fund,
which trades as MXE on the same exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But closed-end funds have fallen out of favor with many
investors, mainly because their prices have been stagnant or
falling. Their one-year returns range from 54 percent on the Mexico
Equity and Income to 2 percent on the other.
</P>
<P>
   What is in vogue, however, are international index funds _ stock
portfolios that mimic performance benchmarks and are traded like
stock on the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   These funds are also called WEBS, an acronym for World Equity
Benchmark Share. They are designed to trade in line with their net
asset values, so discounting is not as much of a problem. Also,
there is not as much active managing with WEBS than with closed-end
funds, which may produce more stable results and fewer expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Ishares' MSCI Mexico Index tracks Morgan Stanley Capital
International Mexico index and trades under the symbol EWW.
</P>
<P>
   But with so few choices, it is still a big risk to invest solely
in Mexico. You may want to hedge your bets by buying Latin America
funds, such as the Merrill Lynch Latin America or the T. Rowe Price
Latin America funds.
</P>
<P>
   But before you shift any of your money into a Mexico or Latin
American fund, make sure you are not getting caught up in a wave of
hype.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully assess if such an investment matches your risk
profile, asset allocation and financial goals. If you don't, the
next downturn in the Mexican economy could sink your portfolio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
