<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Sharyn Wizda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Yes, the world of those under 20 can be
inscrutable to those over 30. But if you're looking for a peek
inside the inner sanctum, you might get a clue on the big screen
starting Friday, when director Amy Heckerling's latest film,
``Loser,'' opens. Heckerling (who happens to be 46) seems to have a
knack for capturing the trappings of teen-dom. Check out her
filmography:
</P>
<P>
   First, there was ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High'' (1982), which
showcased Southern California proto-slacker hip _ remember
Spicoli's checkerboard Vans? The skinny ties and cabbie's cap of
Mark ``Rat'' Ratner, who also shoved his sport jacket sleeves up to
the elbow? Dude! (Let's not forget ``Aloha, Mr. Hand.'')
</P>
<P>
   Then came ``Clueless'' (1995), a fluffy ``Emma''-inspired
confection with short pleated cheerleader skirt suits, omnipresent
cell phones, throwaway references to Christian Lacroix and Calvin
Klein, and a high-school argot that quickly was absorbed into the
mainstream _ ``As if!'' and ``That is so five years ago!''
</P>
<P>
   What does ``Loser'' have in store? The movie reteams ``American
Pie'' co-stars Jason Biggs and Mena Suvari (here, looking
suspiciously like a Meg Ryan Mini-Me circa ``Addicted to Love'') as
young college students in New York. Looks like sooty eye makeup and
bed head are on the ``In!'' list for fall. Potential additions to
teen-speak: ``Skotch'' (pronounced ``scootch''), meaning ``a little
bit,'' as in, ``Turn it down a skotch''; saying, ``Dust!'' instead
of ``Bye!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
