<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-MONTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CELEBRATING AMERICA'S DIVERSE BEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GRIFFIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Institute of Brewing Studies, along with brewers' guilds
across the country, has declared July to be the first American Beer
Month.
</P>
<P>
   I laughed when I first heard that because when I was growing up,
America arguably produced the worst beer in the world. When I was
9, my beer-fancying uncle visited us from Germany, and after too
many failed experiments, he finally refused to drink anything but
Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed with the explosion of microbreweries and the
growth of independent brewers, who take extraordinary care with
their product.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in terms of both experimentation and mimicry of established
international styles, American beers are largely among the best in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   To help you celebrate the rest of American Beer Month, here are
a few U.S. brews of all varieties and styles worth a mug or two.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Steam Beer has been around for ages, and had we known of
its existence back in the early '70s, my uncle's vacation might not
have been so sobering. This fresh hop brew contains no additives,
which may explain its unique flavor and champagne-like fizz.
</P>
<P>
   Boulder Amber Ale comes from the Rockies, as the name implies,
and has the expected roasted caramel aroma with a crisp hop finish.
Maybe it's the mountain spring water that elevates above the norm
(but, then again, Coors boasts the same thing).
</P>
<P>
   Celis White, out of Austin, Texas, is a great wheat beer with
touches of citrus and coriander in a true Belgian style.
</P>
<P>
   Stoney Creek Vanilla Porter offers bittersweet flavors of
roasted coffee and chocolate, both typical of porters. Then it adds
the boldness of vanilla to create a multilayered treat that could
serve as a dessert substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Redhook ESB is a personal favorite just to kick back with after
a hard day at work. It started life as a winter ale, but its
dryness is welcome any season of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Pete's Wicked Ales may have become victims of their own success,
and their attempts at diversifying the lineup don't always work
(can anyone say Strawberry Blonde?). But the tart citrus tone to
the Summer Brew makes it always welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Star Brewery, of San Antonio, produces a fine array of
beers, each as rich as its Texas-themed name and the legend it
bears on the side of the bottle. Start with a Wildcatter's Stout or
a Vigilante Porter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact John Griffin by e-mail at jgriffin(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
