<HEADER>
A6622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHINA-BANK-500&AMP;ADD-NY     07-19 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BANK-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE BANKS TO EVENTUALLY CONTROL INTEREST RATES, OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China's chief central banker said Wednesday that
Chinese banks would be empowered to set their own lending and
deposit rates within the next three years, an important step toward
opening the country's tightly controlled financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Most interest rates in China are currently set by the central
bank, one of many mechanisms used by the government to keep a firm
grip on the currency and keep foreign investors out of domestic
stock and bond markets. That policy has served the country well:
while currencies collapsed around the region during the Asian
financial crisis that began three years ago, China's currency, the
yuan, remained steady, and its economy chugged along largely
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   But China has long said it is committed to liberalizing its
financial system as part of a transition to a market-based economy.
A convertible currency, or one that can be freely bought and sold
for other currencies, would make it easier for foreign investors to
do business here and allow Chinese companies to raise money abroad.
It would also increase China's influence in the global economy,
where the country wants to be a major power.
</P>
<P>
   Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China, said
there is still no timetable for making the currency fully
convertible. But he told reporters at a news conference here that
loosening restrictions on interest rates, allowing them to move up
and down based on market forces, would take place over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first step is to liberalize interest rates on foreign
currency deposits and lending,'' Dai said. ``The next step will be
to liberalize rates on rural credit, and then in urban areas we
will start by expanding the floating band of lending rates,'' he
said. Interest rates on bank deposits would be allowed to float
last.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major step forward in improving the efficiency of
the economy,'' said Dong Tao, an economist with CS First Boston in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that China must first clean up its banking
system, which is riddled with bad debts, before allowing the kind
of competition that floating interest rates would bring. With
non-performing loans estimated to exceed 40 percent of the
portfolios of some banks, unleashing market forces too early could
quickly lead to costly bank failures or even trigger the kind of
financial crisis that China's strict financial controls are
designed to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank now sets lending and deposit rates, and all
banks are state owned, so there is little true competition between
them. The interest rate controls also allow the central bank to
manage demand for the currency, which it has kept artificially
pegged for years at around 8.28 yuan to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The country has recently begun a partial recapitalization of its
major banks through the creation of asset management companies that
are supposed to take some of the bad loans off those banks' books.
But the program is making slow progress.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dai said the central bank would also support the restructuring
of the country's banks into shareholding corporations that can
later go public, something that would increase their capital and
force them to adopt more efficient and transparent management.
</P>
<P>
   Further steps to open the country's financial markets remain
more distant, he said. For example, he said no decision had been
made to allow foreign investors to buy Chinese stocks, which are
denominated in local currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rationale for these constraints is that some enterprises
are not sufficiently self-disciplined, the depth of the Chinese
capital market is not sufficient, and we are not sufficiently
capable of supervising the securities market,'' Dai said.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners are currently restricted to a small number of shares
denominated in foreign currency that are not available to domestic
investors. The segregated market keeps foreigners from acquiring
control of China's listed companies.
</P>
<P>
   And it insulates China's stock markets from the sudden outflow
of capital that has triggered crises in other developing economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be happy if I could convert the yuan into U.S. dollars
when I go to New York to attend meetings, but now I think there is
a long way to go,'' said Dai.
</P>
</TEXT>
