<HEADER>
A6625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CONVENTION0717-COX-1S     07-19 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION0717-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Fixes first graf.
 &HT;    Politics goes hi-tech By Bob Keefe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Democratic party's 4,368 delegates arrive
here for their convention beginning Aug. 14, they'll plan meetings
with each other online using an Internet scheduling system.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Staples Center, where the convention will be held,
they'll chat by Internet phones and by e-mail from computer kiosks
throughout the building.
</P>
<P>
   And back home, folks can keep in touch with them and watch every
second of the gathering live with Web cameras linked to the
convention's extensive Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to politics, Y2K style.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to show that they're in tune with today's dot-com world _
and along the way possibly reach potential voters who typically get
their information online instead of CNN _ organizers of this year's
political conventions are touting and tapping into technology like
never before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be the most technologically advanced,
Internet-savvy political gathering in history,'' said Terry
McAuliffe, chairman of the Democratic National Convention
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country in Philadelphia, organizers of the Republican
National Convention are no neophytes either.
</P>
<P>
   When the Republican convention starts July 31, staffers will
send regular e-mail updates to ``Dot- Com Delegates'' who register
with the GOP Web site. Visitors to the site can also take virtual
tours of the convention or order coffee cups and T-shirts
emblazoned with the convention's logos.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from the first political conventions in the
1830s, when a few hundred delegates gathered in smoky saloons in
Baltimore and Harrisburg, Pa., to draft party platforms and elect
nominees who sometimes didn't even attend.
</P>
<P>
   Today's party organizers say they're using technology _
specifically the Internet _ to reach more people, to get more
opinions and increase involvement in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   But it's about much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   With television networks devoting less time to covering
conventions, party organizers are turning to the Internet to get
their message out 24-hours a day, seven days a week. And _ perhaps
most importantly to them _ they can do it without any media
scrutiny or public comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outreach possibility much, much better than they've
ever had,'' said Michael Margolis, a professor of political science
at the University of Cincinnati who co-authored the book ``Politics
as Usual: The Cyberspace 'Revolution' '' earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they're all interactive and everything _ but most
people don't realize that anything they see and any of the choices
they make (on a Web site) can be controlled by the Webmaster
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another reason why the political conventions are so
into technology: Because so is much of the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to show that you're dot-com literate,'' Margolis
said. ``You want to show the world that you know this is where
you're supposed to be _ or else it would look like you're out of
step or out of touch.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Staples Center in Los Angeles, Democrats are leaving no
doubt that they know technology.
</P>
<P>
   After chatting with each other on Internet phones and by e-mail,
delegates will cast their votes at interactive kiosks throughout
the convention floor. While doing so, they can watch video feeds on
computers featuring behind-the-podium interviews or the latest
analysis by C-SPAN. Election.com, the private company that managed
the Arizona Democratic presidential primary earlier this year _ the
first legally binding political election held over the Internet _
will tally the votes. Results will be sent to the Democratic
convention's Web site and around the world immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Naz Nageer is the computer whiz who is in charge of making sure
it all goes smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Nageer, who formally was director of technology
at US Web in Los Angeles and before that worked as a computer
programmer at Time Warner Inc., is the convention's director of
technology.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several months, he has overseen redesign of the
group's Web site (dumping the red-white-and-blue _ ``too stale,''
he said) rounded up the equipment and supervised wiring of
everything to the Staples Center to make sure it all works.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got quite a bit of fiber (optic line) in there, and
we're using just about all of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Nageer has been busy preparing the technology, other
Democratic Convention officials have been busy getting the word
out. Advertisements and other paraphernalia urge Web surfers to
``Participate in America's Democratic eConvention.'' Tuesday, the
group is planning what it claims is the first-ever Internet press
conference for a political convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really all about access,'' said convention Chief
Executive Lydia Camarillo. ``Technology is one of the key ways of
reaching people today.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the Internet and other technology really prompt more
people to get involved with politics and vote?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not, says Margolis, the political science professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are ordinary people who aren't interested in politics in
the real world, who aren't interested in watching this on
television _ why are they suddenly now going to go the Democrats or
the Republican's Web sites and start getting involved?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
