r d BC-INTERNET-FOOD-HNS &LR;      07-19 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     E-FOOD IS BEING SERVED, AT THE CLICK OF A MOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EMILY SPICER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet-savvy food lovers know that just about any
diet-breaking, high-calorie delight you can imagine is only a
mouse-click away.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Web also offers foods to help you stay on your diet
and lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the traditional diet-plan foods. These sites claim their
nuke-'em-and-eat-'em fare is just as convenient as the little boxes
stacked in supermarket freezers _ and better-tasting. That means no
temptation in the candy aisle, and all that pesky thinking is done
for you: They count the calories, design the meal plans, prepare
your food and restrict the portions.
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do is eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the total answer to everybody's weight loss
problem,'' said Hilton Davis, owner of Diet-to-Go, one of the
companies selling on the Web. ``We provide a healthy meal plan, and
if you stick to it, and don't eat too much else, you should lose
weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis started Diet-to-Go in the mid-1980s with fresh entrees
sold in Washington, D.C.-area supermarkets. After a few more
incarnations, the company went on line in October 1999
(www.diettogo.com). Since then, Diet-to-Go has been preparing about
10,000 meals a week for about 800 customers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The food is shipped in a large, two-compartment (frozen and
fresh) box. Everything is insulated in Styrofoam and chilled on
packs of dry ice.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can choose several meal plans of 1,000 or 1,600
calories a day, from one to three meals a day, for three to seven
days a week. Prices range from $8.50 to $99.95 per week. Prices do
not include shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Another such company, Healthy Meal Express, www.healthymeal.com,
got its start with a health scare. In 1996, 39-year-old pharmacist
Joe Martinez learned he had diabetes. He tried modifying his diet
to control the disease, but became frustrated with the options
available in packaged foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was low in fat, it was high in sugar,'' Martinez said.
``If it was low in sugar, it was high in fat.''
</P>
<P>
   So Martinez started preparing his own healthful foods to go,
giving them to his pharmacy clients. He started selling on the Web
in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While the foods were developed for diabetics, Martinez says they
are appropriate for anyone. His company has started offering a high
protein/low carbohydrate meal plan. Meal plans offer 1,000 or 1,800
calories a day, from one to three meals, five or seven days a week.
The food is shipped chilled, not frozen. Prices range from $49.95
to $159.95 a week, not including shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Another Web site, www.zoneperfect.com, caters to Zone dieters
who don't have time to prepare the carefully calibrated meals the
diet requires. Through the Web site, customers can order six meals
for $26.50, 12 for $59.95.
</P>
<P>
   The ZonePerfect meals became available about two and a half
years ago, and the company now ships about 7,000 meals per week.
</P>
<P>
   While each company says the food tastes better than the frozen
variety sold at supermarkets, customers care more about convenience
and safety.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Delgado, a 40-year-old teacher from El Paso, Texas, said
she has lost nine pounds in the five weeks she has been eating
Diet-to-Go meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not small portions,'' she said. ``I am so satisfied.
I don't believe I'm eating only 1,000 calories a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Ellis, a two-year customer of Healthy Meal Express, says the
Web meals helped keep his overeating and diabetes under control. In
his first year, Ellis lost 120 pounds and his diabetes went into
remission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It played into my own personal weaknesses,'' said the
51-year-old Wisconsin business consultant. ``It was like, `This is
it, dude. This is all you get to eat for the week.' I was
determined I would stay inside the box. And then a couple of times
I wanted to eat the box,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I learned to eat in healthy portions and got past the
mental hunger, I was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Farr, a dietitian in San Antonio, said these types of
eating plans are ideal for people such as Ellis and Delgado, who
are too busy to cook and need help in learning to eat smaller
portions.
</P>
<P>
   But she cautions that there are other diet-related problems not
solved by prepared food.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bigger issue is where we eat, fast food vs. home, and why we
eat. Because we don't always eat from hunger,'' she explained,
adding that counseling is sometimes needed and a package on the
Internet doesn't deal with these issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quick and fast. That's good. But it's not that
satisfying, so you will probably get other foods already in the
home to supplement it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Emily Spicer by e-mail at espicer(at)express-news.net)
</P>
