A6627 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-RELIGION-VASHTI0720-C     07-19 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-VASHTI0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AME Bishop McKenzie delivering keynote speech at Wilberforce
 &HT;    By Khalid Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILBERFORCE, Ohio - Scarcely two weeks after she shattered the
``stained-glass ceiling'' that kept women out of the Episcopacy of
the African Methodist Episcopal Church, Bishop Vashti Murphy
McKenzie returns to Ohio on Tuesday to deliver the keynote speech
at the Third Episcopal District Christian Education Congress 2000
at Wilberforce University.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day retreat is sponsored by the Dayton District of the
AME church and is designed to cultivate the lives of Christian
youth through Bible study, training sessions, worship services and
recreational activities. The education congress runs from Tuesday
through next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The last time McKenzie visited the Miami Valley, she was being
heralded as one of the brightest lights in the AME constellation.
</P>
<P>
   When she returns, the 53-year-old cleric will be recognized as a
pivotal figure in church history after becoming the first woman to
assume the position of bishop in the 213-year legacy of the AME
church.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Fredrick Wright, pastor of Dayton's Wayman Chapel AME
Church, said McKenzie's speech was arranged on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the conclusion of our General Conference in Cincinnati
our (Dayton District) bishop had to be reassigned.'' Wright said.
``Our new bishop, Robert Vaughn Webster, was able to persuade
Vashti to come and preach before the congress after she was elected
bishop.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who served as a delegate at the Cincinnati conference,
says the election of McKenzie, who sits on the Wilberforce
University board of trustees, was a good choice for the future of
the AME church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bishop McKenzie is a very skilled and focused individual. She
is very energetic and determined to accomplish a lot of things.
She's a gifted preacher but she's also a gifted administrator who
raises the level of people around her,'' he said. ``I think she's
going to add a tremendous touch to the church and do some
magnificent things.''
</P>
<P>
   Educational Congress 2000 expects to attract more than 300
participants, many of whom will be housed on the Wilberforce
campus. Registration fees are $100 for registrants living
off-campus and a $145 on-campus fee. Admission to McKenzie's
keynote speech is free.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Khalid Moss at kmoss(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
