<P>
   DISABILITIES-SURVEY (Washington) _ Nearly 10 years after the
signing of the Americans with Disabilities Act, a survey shows that
the disabled continue to lag behind the rest of society in
employment, income and access to health care. The act, signed July
26, 1990, by former President George Bush, banned discrimination
against such people. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-IMMIGRANTS (Washington) _ Major Hispanic groups voice
frustration with Congress' focus on legislation to bring more
high-tech foreign workers into the country. Unless Republican
leaders do more for immigrants already here, the GOP will be
targeted at the polls this year by Latino voters, the Hispanic
organizations warn. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CHOICE (Washington) _ Republican pro-choice advocates secure
a promise from Republican Platform Committee Chairman Tommy
Thompson that he will consider allowing open discussion as
committee members write the abortion plank at the GOP convention.
Pro-choice Republicans say they will fight to change the party's
plank opposing any abortion, but conservatives say their chances
are nil. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Washington) _ President Clinton, unlike some of
his predecessors, is savoring his last months in office. The
president doesn't rage against the dying light. Instead, he's ever
more nostalgic about his waning tenure in the White House. He has
often said that ``even the bad days are good'' in the presidency _
and he quips that he has had his share of bad days. By HELEN
THOMAS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
