   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-ADVISER (Washington) _ The trail that led Peter Swire to
the White House as President Clinton's chief adviser on privacy
matters began in the 1970s when he worked the computers at his
family's furniture stores in Albany, N.Y. There amid the La-Z-Boy
recliners and living room sets, he was inspired when his father,
Bill Swire, charged headlong into the computer era. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Now that Supreme Court
appointments are an issue in the campaign, we should recall a
lesson from history: It is not unusual for a president to become
disenchanted with a Supreme Court justice he has nominated for the
high bench. With independence and life tenure, justices are free to
move in any direction they choose. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
