<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-ONLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAVOR AN UNUSUAL WINE? CHECK THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I wanted to serve an Alsatian champagne at a
party we were hosting during the December holidays. There was a
problem, though. None of the wine stores I went to carried
sparkling wine from that region of France, which produces some of
my favorite white wines.
</P>
<P>
   I had no trouble finding numerous Alsatian sparkling wines when
I started shopping with my computer, however. When I entered one
Web site, wine.com, there were a half-dozen of the wines priced
under $15 with thorough descriptions of each one.
</P>
<P>
   This led to a new, far more appealing problem: Which ones did I
want? I resolved that dilemma by selecting a couple of bottles of
three different styles, plus another half-dozen different sauvignon
blancs from the Loire Valley that I had never seen in area wine
stores. A week or so later, my shipment arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Buying wine has never been easier, I decided. Wine.com offers up
to 20 percent discounts on case purchases, similar to most stores,
and the fast-growing company periodically offers free shipping.
Point, click and sip.
</P>
<P>
   There is a catch, however. The New York Liquor Authority has not
approved wine.com's method of operation, meaning either I or the
company may have violated the law with our transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to buying wine on line, a world where politics is at
play and the rules and regulations can trace their roots to the
bygone era of Prohibition. A world where dot.com quickly leads to
dot.why?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, each state sets its own laws for buying wine via
the Internet. In New York, it is illegal to buy wine directly from
an out-of-state winery. However, if you want to purchase wine from
a New York winery with a Web site, that's perfectly all right.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? You have every right to be.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas McKeon, counsel to the state Liquor Authority, says the
state has approved some Internet wine merchants such as
wineshopper.com and evineyard.com, which use the traditional
three-tier (sale, distribution and delivery) method for wine
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   New York also gives its blessing to Windsor Vineyards, a
California winery that sells its product only by direct mail (its
wines are not available in stores). Why? Because Windsor has
established a sister winery in the Hudson Valley, which acts
primarily as a recipient for sales from California to New Yorkers.
Since the shipper has a New York address, the transactions are
legal.
</P>
<P>
   As for wine.com, which first sent my shipment to a liquor store
in Rochester, which then sent the order on to me, McKeon is less
clear. ``We're talking to wine.com right now. I'm not saying
they're not approved,'' he said. ``We've been talking with them for
a few months. I'm not prepared to comment on if a resident who buys
wine from them is breaking the law.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think New York state's 151 wineries are opposed to direct
sales from wineries in California and other locales, as well as
direct sales from Internet sites, think again.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Randy Kuhl, a Republican from Hammondsport, deep in
the heart of Finger Lakes wine country, believes that allowing
direct interstate sales from wineries would be a boon to New York
wineries. Countless sales go unfilled when tourists visit wineries
in New York but can't have the wines shipped to their homes in
other parts of the country, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhl was the leading proponent of a 1995 bill that would have
liberated interstate shipments from wineries in New York and from
out-of-state wineries to New Yorkers. The bill was approved by both
the Senate and Assembly, but was vetoed by Gov. George Pataki, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   One of those lobbying hard for Pataki to veto the bill was
Michael Long, chairman of the Conservative Party, which supported
Pataki in both of his successful races for governor. Long, it so
happens, owns a liquor store on Long Island, according to Kuhl.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesalers call direct shippers ``bootleggers.'' Wineries and
e-commerce sites call wholesalers ``state-sanctioned monopolies.''
They both want a piece of the $1 billion direct wine business.
</P>
<P>
   Direct sales are an economic concern to wholesalers,
acknowledged David Dickerson, a spokesman for the Wine and Spirits
Wholesalers of America. But he said it's really a local tax and
policy issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want a free and open marketplace for alcohol,''
Dickerson said. ``They want licensed operators and to be able to
crack down on illegal activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The wholesalers group has given its support to wineshopper.com,
an Internet site funded by Amazon.com and others that allows
consumers to order wines that go through the wholesale system and
often end up at a retailer where buyers have to pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   The illegal activities the wholesalers decry include the
potential of minors with credit cards ordering wine or liquor
direct. The wine industry thinks that argument lacks credibility.
Minors, they counter, have easier, cheaper ways to buy alcohol than
to order it by phone or computer, wait a week to get it and pay
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later this three-tier structure is going to come
down. The consumers aren't going to allow it,'' Kuhl says. ``The
liquor distributors have a monopoly and they want to control the
whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   James Tresize, president of the New York State Wine &AMP; Grape
Foundation, describes Internet wine sales as a ``complicated and
evolving'' issue. ``It takes a lot more time to change things in
the wine industry because there are so many restrictions and
regulations,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, such as California and Washington, have reciprocal
agreements allowing the direct shipment from wineries to consumers.
New York, however, has never made a similar pact with other states.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for wine on the Internet will probably never replace
the pleasure of browsing in a well-stocked store and discussing
selection with a knowledgeable merchant.
</P>
<P>
   Your local liquor store also enjoys other advantages over the
Internet: There are no shipping charges (which usually amount to
about $20 per case), and there is the immediacy of having the wine
in your hand the moment you have paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even some neighborhood stores realize that the need to be
accessible on the Internet, too. Craig Allen, president of All Star
Wine &AMP; Spirits in Latham, N.Y., is redesigning his store's Web site
and working on ways to ship wines out of state. He predicts that
All Star's sales from the Internet, which currently account for
just 1 to 2 percent of the store's business, will mushroom to 15
percent within the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Buying wine on line is similar to catalog shopping: you don't
leave your house. Also, the selection at wine.com, the site I'm
most familiar with, is impressive, better than most wine stores.
</P>
<P>
   It's an alternative I'm glad to have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
