<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON HATES TO LEAVE HIS JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, unlike some of his predecessors,
is savoring his last months in office. The president doesn't rage
against the dying light. Instead, he's ever more nostalgic about
his waning tenure in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Some presidents chafed and resented the goldfish-bowl living
they endured in the White House, though they actually had a lot of
privacy and protection.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson referred to the presidency as ``the splendid
misery.'' Harry Truman called the White House ``the crown jewel in
the penal system,'' and he likened himself to a prisoner. He called
the White House ``the loneliest place in the world.'' Lyndon
Johnson dubbed it ``lonely acres.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton is loath to leave. He has often said that ``even the
bad days are good'' in the presidency _ and he quips that he has
had his share of bad days. In fact, Clinton has hardly known a day
in the White House when he was not being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Robert Ray, successor to Kenneth Starr, is
trying to pick up on the unfinished Whitewater and Monica Lewinsky
business. Still hanging over Clinton's head is the Little Rock
panel studying his possible disbarment based on his deposition in
the Paula Jones sexual harassment case.
</P>
<P>
   If the impeachment left any scars, it did not mar his joy of
holding the highest office in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Last May when he was presented a crystal apple by a teachers'
organization and named honorary ``Teacher of the Year,'' Clinton
said: ``I generally believe presidents should not receive awards
because the job is award enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Diane Rehm of radio station WAMU, an
affiliate of National Public Radio, Clinton said: ``I love this
job. I'd do it forever if I could.'' He added that while in the
job, he was trying ``to squeeze every last drop out of every minute
I've got to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   While others moan and groan about the ``awesome burden,'' as
Johnson did, Clinton seems to wallow in it. He also told Rehm he
will miss the position ``terribly,'' and added: ``I love this work.
I just love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's yearnings were also shared by a recent Republican
predecessor _ Ronald Reagan, who often indicated in his last year
in office that he would have loved a crack at a third term.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, Reagan was barred from his dream by the 22nd
Amendment, which limits presidents to two terms. This
constitutional ceiling was pushed through by Republicans in the
aftermath of Franklin D. Roosevelt's four terms in office.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Johnson renounced reelection in 1968 as a result of
the bitter divisions in the country over the Vietnam War, he waited
in the wings, hoping for a draft at the Democratic National
Convention in Chicago. But that political gathering turned into a
debacle that made a Johnson comeback impossible.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Clinton hates to turn over the presidential reins, he
is dedicated to keeping his hand in the party's business. He is
starring in almost weekly fundraisers to build up the coffers for
Vice President Al Gore and other Democratic hopefuls. That is more
than can be said for Johnson, who did not go all out for Vice
President Hubert Humphrey until the last few weeks of the
presidential race in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   President Dwight D. Eisenhower was lukewarm in his support of
Vice President Richard Nixon in the 1960 contest when Nixon ran
against John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The icing on the cake for Clinton is the satisfaction of knowing
that at least one pollster, John Zogby, thinks if Clinton did run
again, he would win.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
