<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6669 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-OLYMPIC-SYDNEY19-COX     07-19 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIC-SYDNEY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four years later, globe-trotting Atlantans still wear Olympic
rings
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ It's Friday night, and the musky aroma of
Australian manhood saturates the Oaks, a pub on the north side of
Sydney Harbour that's as big as a Wal-Mart. Mobs of men are
standing around talking rugby over schooners of beer. Some are
furiously working the slot machines everyone calls ``pokies.''
Others are charring slabs of meat on a barbecue pit out in the
courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   There's something odd about the round table by the door. Not
only does it include several women _ eating pizza, no less _ but
some of their accents sound rather alien in this setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I left Atlanta,'' one of them says, ``my mover
asked, `What's the deal with Sydney? It seems like we've been
moving everyone to Sydney.'''
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Sydney, of course, is the Olympics. Four years ago
tonight, Muhammad Ali lit the caldron that signaled Atlanta's star
turn on the world stage. For some Atlantans, it wasn't enough. At
least 200 veterans of the 1996 Games have moved on to Australia to
be part of the first Olympics of the 2000s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a pretty tight group,'' says Carol Isbister, one of
several Atlanta alums around the table at the Oaks. She's working
in Olympic hospitality, as she did in '96, and has been here long
enough to get used to the Australian fondness for cute nicknames.
Carol has become ``Kazzar.'' Her fiance, Michael Rolnick, an
Atlanta native who manages Olympic communications for Ansett
Australia airlines, has become Mick.
</P>
<P>
   This year marks the first time in almost a century that the
Games have gone from one English-speaking nation to another. The
Sydney organizers have taken advantage of the coincidence, hiring
some 50 people who worked with the Atlanta Committee for the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Former ACOGers are running Sydney's broadcasting operation and
several of its venues, including the largest one, Stadium
Australia, the 110,000-seat arena where the five-ring circus will
begin Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Isbister, have gravitated to Sydney to work for
private companies or Olympic sponsors or as independent
consultants. Her employer alone, Carlson Marketing Group, is
sending 100 former Atlanta Olympic workers to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the Atlanta veterans are enjoying the beautiful
setting, the welcoming warmth of their Australian colleagues and
the excitement of staging another Olympics, there have been
complications.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Australians are every bit as proud as Americans
and don't always take kindly to outside criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Sydney Morning Herald ran a story about the
Atlantans headlined ``The U.S. Cavalry.'' One of them _ a Canadian,
as it turned out _ said she found local waiters and cabbies to be
rude. The paper ran letters for days telling the Yanks to go home
if they didn't like it. The story created such a fuss that the
Sydney Organising Committee for the Olympic Games (SOCOG) canceled
a Fourth of July party planned for its hired hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The e-mails were flying,'' says Milton Cockburn, SOCOG's media
relations manager. ``But that's the only problem we've had because
of the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers have had to make many cultural adjustments, from
sticker shock at the price of an apartment to not being able to
find baseball box scores or good Tex-Mex food.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney looks and feels deceptively like a U.S. city _ Seattle or
San Diego comes to mind _ but it most certainly isn't. Some have
found, for instance, that Australians move to the hum of a
different didgeridoo when it comes to conducting business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are slower,'' says Ann Michele Worrall of Game Plan
International, a company that brokers Olympic housing. ``There's an
almost Latin mentality of `manana, manana.' Except here, it's `no
worries.'''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been her biggest frustration, though. Worrall, who
also handled housing during the '96 Games and the 1998 soccer World
Cup in Paris, had trouble following the Australian accent when she
moved here 18 months ago. Meetings between her French clients and
Australians looking to rent to them could get embarrassing. ``I'd
understand the French just fine,'' she says, ``but I'd have to ask
the Australians to repeat themselves four or five times.''
</P>
<P>
   The sometimes condescending attitude toward women is another
irritation. ``Women definitely have a more secondary role here,''
says Sherry Spurlin, who worked at the Atlanta whitewater course
and manages a similar venue outside Sydney. ``These guys call me
`mate,' and I'm like, `Come on, I'm not your mate.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Spurlin's closest friends in Sydney are Australians.
When one of them, a kayaker, barely missed qualifying for the Games
this spring, she hurried to his weeping wife and daughter and
hugged them like they were family.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the Atlantans have become a bit Aussie in their
months here. Ed Hula, who made a name for himself as a radio
reporter covering the '96 Games, sold his house in Georgia and
rented a three-room flat overlooking the Sydney Harbour Bridge. He
and his wife, Sheila, edit an Olympic newsletter, Around the Rings,
riding ferries around the harbor like Sydneysiders and
enthusiastically partaking of the native seafood. Much to their
amusement, their 14-year-old son, Ed, has developed an embryonic
Australian accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I luuuuv rugby,'' he says, tossing a fat, oblong ball at his
father and then rushing him. ``He makes a good tackling dummy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dad remains loyal to American football. A Florida State grad, he
ran up a huge phone bill listening to his Seminoles win the
national title on the Internet. ``I was probably the only person in
Sydney who cared,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   After the Games, many of the Atlantans plan to return home. A
few want to move on to the next Olympics in Salt Lake City or
Athens. Some plan to hang around Australia and see more of the
country they've been too busy of late to explore.
</P>
<P>
   One local enthusiasm the Olympic workers have managed to find
time for is surfing. Quite a few of them have ventured onto nearby
Bondi Beach to take lessons. Reed Draper, a Sandy Springs, Ga.,
native who is special events manager at the athletes village,
admitted to his instructor that he was concerned about sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, mate,'' the teacher assured him, ``I've been out here 17
years, and I've seen only two of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day brought news that a 9-foot man-eater had been
caught at Bondi. Draper quietly retired his surfboard and resumed
his landlubber duties at the village. After all, he has an even
bigger adventure coming up: His wife, Laurie, is due to give birth
to their first child during the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Draper says, ``should add a little challenge to our
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1511EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6677 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-AID-$ADV23-C     07-19 1910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-AID-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLOMBIA HOPING NEW U.S., EUROPEAN AID WILL HELP CURB FLOW OF
ILLEGAL DRUGS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With COLOMBIA-FARC-$ADV23.
 &HT;    EDs: U.S. aid funding chart information attached at end of
story.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 23, And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRES ESQUINAS, Colombia _ The flood-swollen Orteguaza River
slices through the Colombian lowlands, its dirty brown water
straining at banks that give way to swampy clumps of thick forest
and patches of cleared land.
</P>
<P>
   Bright green coca plants and poppy fields dot many of the
clearings, verdant cash crops in a land of hunger and war.
</P>
<P>
   This remote territory in Colombia's far south has become ground
zero in the escalating conflict against narcotics traffickers, and
Marxist rebels who have tapped the drug trade as a major source of
revenue to fuel their 36-year-old insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the cocaine and heroine grown here is destined for the
United States, which recently approved a $1.3 billion aid package
to help Colombia fight its drug war. Colombian pilots will fly a
fleet of 60 U.S.-supplied helicopters, providing security and
transporting forces that will wipe out remote drug laboratories and
fumigate illicit crops from low-flying crop dusters.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the high-tech U.S. technology, the Amazonian
headwaters of southern Colombia are a primitive, hostile region.
There are few towns, fewer roads and thousands of square miles of
dense green growth perfect for hiding illegal operations _ and
enemies. The muddy brown streams are ideal for transporting
contraband.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rivers are the super highways here,'' said General Mario
Montoya, head of a new Colombian anti-narcotics task force. ``They
carry everything they need for the production of cocaine on those
rivers. Ten years ago, there was very little coca here, but today
this area has the highest concentration of coca production in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics fear the jungle _ and Colombia's tortured landscape of
leftist guerrillas, right-wing paramilitary groups, drug barons, a
questionable military and rancorous domestic politics _ may swallow
up the American aid, drawing the U.S. further into a quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made a profound and dramatic shift in focus from
supporting a police force in a friendly country to supporting an
army engaged in a civil war,'' said Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash.,
shortly after Congress approved the aid package. ``I wonder how
long it will be until we read the first news story of some of this
equipment showing up in the hands of rebels.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials insist the aid is strictly for fighting drugs,
not to help Colombia fight its civil war. But Montoya admits that
in the remote wilds, the two are often intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FARC, with all its guns and all its evil, is involved in
the drug trade,'' he said, referring to the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia, the nation's largest and oldest guerrilla
group. ``If the guerrillas are involved in drug trafficking, as we
know they are, we're going to attack them.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombia, a nation of 39 million, supplies an estimated 80
percent of the world's cocaine. It is also a growing source of
heroin. Both drugs are worth billions on the streets of America and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   There are no accurate figures on how much the country's
guerrillas gain by taking a cut from the poor farmers who grow the
crops and the traffickers who process and smuggle it, but some
Colombian newspapers have cited figures in the hundreds of
millions.
</P>
<P>
   With the guerrillas and drug lords so powerful, Colombian
President Andres Pastrana stunned the nation 18 months ago by
starting peace talks with the FARC. To show his goodwill, he
ordered Colombian troops out of a Switzerland-sized chunk of the
nation that has become de facto FARC territory.
</P>
<P>
   But the peace talks have since stumbled without much real
progress, and Pastrana's popularity has plummeted. Many Colombians
fear he has given the guerrillas too much without getting anything
in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guerrillas are terribly strong because they have so much
money from drug trafficking,'' said Eduardo Gomez, who retired from
the Colombian military and now works in Bogota, the capital. ``We
have no confidence in our institutions. The money from the U.S.
will be wasted, because our army, our police and our government are
corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimates on FARC strength range from 17,000 to 22,000 soldiers
in the field, but they are only one of the warring forces in
Colombia. Another guerrilla group, the Army of National Liberation
or ELN, has some 5,000 soldiers, while right-wing paramilitary
groups, which also take tribute from drug traffickers, have an
estimated 7,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's military _ the army, air force and navy _ has about
120,000 personnel. It also has a reputation for corruption and
human-rights abuses, with many observers citing close ties between
army officers and the paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana has named his bold new strategy for saving the country,
``Plan Colombia.'' The U.S. aid - which will mostly fund military
equipment, but also provides money for crop substitution and other
social programs _ will be supplemented by more than $600 million
for social programs that Pastrana recently obtained from European
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through his four-year term in office, however, Pastrana
has been hamstrung by a corruption scandal and bitter relations
with the national congress. He recently appealed to Colombians to
be more positive, saying, ``I'm tired of the bad news that does not
let us see and construct a better country for all.''
</P>
<P>
   But it will take more than a positive attitude to vanquish
Colombia's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that Plan Colombia will escalate the war on both
sides,'' said Marco Alberto Romero, a political scientist at
Colombia's National University. ``If the guerrillas resist this
first campaign, the logic will be that the U.S. will increase its
aid and become more committed to the Colombian conflict. It's a
very complicated problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Romero believes the focus should be on providing more
opportunity for the rural peasants who grow the coca and poppy. The
peasants now have no alternatives, and wiping out their only cash
crop by fumigation could foul the environment, sicken the poor
farmers and create a new wave of internal displacement within
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have regional consequences,'' he said. ``The drug
trafficking affects the whole Andean region. This could lead to the
breakdown of the peace talks in Colombia, but also could trigger an
arms race. Already both (the FARC and the government) are building
up their forces even as they are participating in the peace
talks.''
</P>
<P>
   On the front lines, Gen. Montoya downplays the criticism and
confidently predicts victory.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent briefing for reporters complete with slides,
tapes of radio conversations among drug traffickers and maps laying
out the alignment of forces, Montoya said the new U.S. aid _
especially a fleet of about 30 sophisticated Blackhawk helicopters
_ will tip the balance in favor of his 3,000-man force in the
southern region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get the helicopters, we can really go to work,'' he
said. ``They will give us the element of surprise and mobility. We
will move in and immediately neutralize the crops.''
</P>
<P>
   Boats patrolling the rivers to intercept cocaine shipments, as
well as the supplies of gasoline, cement and chemicals needed to
convert the coca leaves into cocaine will augment the force.
</P>
<P>
   The only role for U.S. troops _ no more than a few hundred at
the time _ will be to train the Colombian pilots and soldiers, and
help operate sophisticated surveillance equipment the U.S. will
send, he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   There are reports that the guerrillas may have _ or will soon
obtain _ surface-to-air missiles or other advanced weapons to shoot
down the helicopters. Critics also warn that the drug farmers and
traffickers will simply move elsewhere once the Colombian offensive
picks up steam.
</P>
<P>
   But Montoya remains upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``These groups will try to defend their operations because there
is lots and lots of money involved in narco-trafficking,'' he said.
``But we're prepared militarily for this fight. We're in this for
the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams' E-mail address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Colombia:
</P>
<P>
   www.latnic.utexas.edu
</P>
