u i BC-DIGITAL-DIVIDE-530&AMP;AD     07-19 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-DIVIDE-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCUSSIONS ON ERASING DIGITAL DIVIDE BETWEEN RICH AND POOR
NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A group of high-technology executives urged the
wealthiest nations Wednesday to take action to erase a growing
digital divide resulting from the economic chasm separating the
developed and developing worlds.
</P>
<P>
   The perception that the world is increasingly being divided into
information technology haves and have-nots is among the topics that
the seven leading industrial nations and Russia will take up at
their annual summit meeting, which begins Friday in Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   A task force established by the World Economic Forum, a policy
organization made up of many of the world's largest corporations
that meets annually in Davos, Switzerland, presented on Wednesday a
series of policy proposals on the issue to Japan's prime minister,
Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   The task force, including the chief executives of Sony Corp. and
Toshiba Corp., Japan's two largest consumer electronics firms,
proposed a set of principles including telecommunications and
Internet deregulations, universal access to education and
technology training, as well as support and financing for small
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, prepared at the request of the Japanese government
at the Davos meeting, also includes ideas like the creation of a
Peace Corps-style volunteer group, the Global Digital Opportunity
Corps; the establishment of local technology community centers; and
the establishment of e-chambers of commerce to support
technology-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese high-technology executives said Wednesday evening that
Mori planned to announce at the summit meeting that Japan would
commit $12 billion in loans and $3 billion in Overseas Development
Assistance funds over five years to information-technology
initiatives in the developing world. The move is intended to prompt
similar commitments from other countries to integrate developing
nations into the world's expanding digital infrastructure, a
Japanese executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Mori, who acknowledged this week that he is a computer novice
and has only recently learned how to use a mouse, appeared
Wednesday afternoon with an international group of high-technology
executives to underscore his nation's commitment to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to make this an information technology discussion,
mainly focusing on the developing nations,'' Mori said. ``This
digital divide issue is a crucial matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of a global digital divide has been seized on in the
past year by corporate executives eager to prove they are socially
responsible. But there is disagreement over what the divide
represents and how permanent it is.
</P>
<P>
   A number of economists and technologists believe the world
income gap created by the industrial revolution may still be the
fundamental dividing line between rich and poor nations rather than
the question of access to technology.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the task force said that the digital divide should
not overshadow the traditional issues that define rich and poor
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not a digital divide, said Richard Li, chairman
and chief executive of the Pacific Century Group. ``It is an
education divide, and information technology is only a conduit to
promote education.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sony's chairman, Nobuyuki Idei, acknowledged that his company
had struggled with its own internal digital divide and had been
slow to deploy information technology among its workers. ``This is
a good indication of the problems that will confront us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Schwab, the founder and chairman of the World Economic
Forum, said in an interview this week that he believed that
inexpensive digital wireless technology systems would increasingly
spread in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally feel that a breakthrough is coming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said on Monday that information technology holds
promise for creating economic opportunity as well as improving
access to health care and education. But they noted that while
there are now an estimated 332 million people connected via the
Internet around the world, only 1 percent live in Africa. And less
then 5 percent of the computers connected to the Internet are in
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   The officials would not offer any U.S. commitment or pledge of a
specific dollar amount to help bridge the digital divide. But they
said they would welcome such proposals from other nations at the
summit meeting and from the U.S. private sector.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference here Wednesday afternoon, members of the
World Economic Forum task force appeared sensitive to the issue of
self-interest on the part of the large corporations backing
significant financial investment in high-technology spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about self-interest,'' said Vernon J. Ellis,
international chairman of Andersen Consulting. ``There is nothing
wrong with self-interest, as long as it is enlightened long-term
self-interest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
