<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6686 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-SMALL-TOWN-BROKER-HNS     07-19 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-TOWN-BROKER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BROKERAGE BANKS ON BIG GROWTH IN SMALL TOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BILL DAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARBLE FALLS, Texas _ Three years ago, during one of the bull
market's brief but sharp downturns, Edward Jones stockbroker Hugh
D. Reed took a call from one of his clients, an elderly widow. She
was making sure he had not suffered too many losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her I was fine,'' Reed said. ``She wasn't asking if she
was OK, she was asking if I was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed's grin widened. ``The next day, she brought me a plate of
cookies.''
</P>
<P>
   How many investors bake cookies to console brokers during market
drops? Not too many. But if they do, they probably bake them for
Edward Jones brokers, whose 5,700 offices are sprinkled throughout
America's small towns, suburbs and neighborhoods. Another 1,000
brokerages have sprouted in Canadian and British towns.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-growing company _ it has added 15 percent more brokers
every year since the early 1980s _ has never wanted high-rise
boiler rooms in urban areas. Instead, they're in neighborhood
shopping centers or professional buildings, close in proximity and
spirit to their clients.
</P>
<P>
   Where Edward Jones has been supremely successful, though, is in
the countryside. Its philosophy of catering exclusively to
individual investors and small businesses led Fortune magazine to
dub it ``the Wal-Mart of Wall Street.'' Edward Jones goes, to put
it simply, where the clients are.
</P>
<P>
   Reed is a perfect example. He has been a broker in Marble Falls,
a small but prosperous Texas town 90 miles north of San Antonio,
for eight years. He believes, with a fervency approaching religion,
that by being in his clients' community, he can serve them better.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly a relationship business,'' he said from behind
his small but ornate blond-wood desk. ``You become a member of the
family. We have educated a lot of kids and grandkids, and
transferred a lot of businesses from the original founders to the
next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, sets Edward Jones apart from other brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   If there is anything the company's St. Louis-based executives
want you to know about Edward Jones, it is the differences.
</P>
<P>
   First, there are the offices. Not only are they spread
throughout rural areas _ Texas alone has 700, up from 100 a decade
ago _ all of them are staffed by one broker and one support person.
</P>
<P>
   When an area has enough business to support another broker,
Edward Jones doesn't add one to the office. Instead, a separate
branch is opened. There are no supervisors or branch managers; each
broker is responsible for business development.
</P>
<P>
   This gives Edward Jones brokers much greater freedom, and helps
the company attract entrepreneurs. ``We get people who really want
their own office and command of their own ship,'' said Edward Jones
managing partner John Bachmann.
</P>
<P>
   The company also distinguishes itself from others through its
conservative investment philosophy. ``Everyone says that,'' Reed
said. ``No one says, `We're wild and crazy.' But I have found
through the years that I do not take on every client or potential
client who comes to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He told the story of a man who came into his office one day,
plopped a $100,000 check on the desk and said, ``Let's play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally had to tell him, `I'm not the right broker for
you,''' Reed said. ``You need someone who will trade four times
today and three times tomorrow, and that's not who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed has a tactic for instances when he can't talk a client out
of something risky. He produces a letter documenting his
disapproval, and asks the client to sign it. It's a seldom-used
strategy, but it almost always works.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Jones discourages customers from dabbling in penny stocks
by not compensating brokers for trading stocks under $5 per share.
It shies away from the lucrative investment-banking business. And
most different of all, it pushes no proprietary investments on
clients because it doesn't have any.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is so different, Edward Jones can't grow simply by
buying another brokerage. The pieces would not fit together. So
Bachmann, who has been in charge since 1980, masterminded a
growth-through-expansion strategy that will give the company 10,000
brokerages by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The big numbers aren't just about stoking partners' egos. ``If
you take a market like San Antonio, we may or may not be
(advertising) on TV or in the newspaper, because we may or may not
be on a scale where we can afford that,'' Bachmann said. ``We need
that scale or we run the risk of being irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is starting to wake up to just how relevant Edward
Jones is. Merrill Lynch has experimented in opening branches in
small towns; one is less than a mile up the street from Reed's
Marble Falls office.
</P>
<P>
   Bachmann shrugged this off. He compares Edward Jones to
Southwest Airlines, another business that found a successful niche
and has held off imitations from competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do one thing well, we're not going to do other things,'' he
said. ``We're not going to serve institutions. We don't have house
brands, period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of people have tried to emulate our model, but unless
they're willing to do those tradeoffs, they won't have the success
we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1523EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
