<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-WILSON-BOS &LR;      07-19 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WILSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIAN WILSON SAYS HIS SONGS SPEAK FOR THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the annals of pop music, the Beach Boys' ``Pet Sounds'' rates
on many Top Ten lists of all time. It was the precursor to the
Beatles' ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band.'' The masterwork
of Beach Boys genius Brian Wilson, it set studio standards for
years to come. And it is now being performed on tour, complete with
a 55-piece orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my wife and managers asked if I'd like to do it, I said
sure,'' says Wilson. ``And when they told me if I'd be happy using
a symphonic orchestra to do it, I also said sure. So we got it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kick. I love that album anyway, and in front of an
orchestra, it's even better. The songs speak for themselves,''
Wilson says in a recent phone interview from the road. He is
playing some other Beach Boys hits too, so the show is not all
drawn from one album.
</P>
<P>
   Released in 1966, ``Pet Sounds'' was almost a Brian Wilson solo
record in that he used studio musicians and only brought the rest
of the Beach Boys in on it later. The album includes ``God Only
Knows,'' ``Wouldn't It Be Nice,'' ``Caroline, No,'' and ``Sloop
John B.'' Wilson wrote the music and co-wrote the lyrics with Tony
Asher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was smoking dope back then _ and believe it or not, it
helped me to write. It did,'' says Wilson. ``The songs came pretty
quickly _ they took about two hours each. We just poured them out
of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   What took more time _ and is the reason ``Pet Sounds'' is hailed
as groundbreaking _ is the care that Wilson took in stacking the
vocal parts to achieve a lush sound, as well as including
experimental sounds made by such objects as bicycle bells, teacups,
and Coca-Cola cans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The album was made very cautiously and carefully,'' says
Wilson. ``But it turned out fantastic. We took each song one at a
time, then we finally got it all mixed and were flipped out by it.
We really flipped. We thought it was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the motivating factor behind the music, he says,
``We wanted to make a special love album for people. The voices
were the love, and the instrumentation, I guess, was the
excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the exotic sounds on it, Wilson recalls, ``My drummer had
a kit called Soundmakers. And we looked through his kit and we
found a bicycle thing and teacups and stuff. It was just a
fantastic trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, a ``Pet Sounds'' boxed set came out, featuring
a new stereo remix of the album. Wilson says, ``I got a chance to
hear it, but I'm deaf in my right ear, so I can't appreciate
stereo.'' (He blames his hearing loss on touring in the early
years.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the boxed set, he says, ``I wasn't involved in it. It was
all done by Capitol Records.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Wilson has forsaken major record companies to form
his own indie label, Brimel, chosen by combining the first three
letters of his name and the first three of his wife, Melinda, with
whom he has had two children in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The label's first release is the new Wilson concert CD, ``Live
at the Roxy Theatre,'' recorded in Los Angeles last year and
available only on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Internet, does Wilson like to surf it?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he admits, ``my wife handles that end of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
