<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENNISMILLER-ANTIJOCK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENNIS MILLER BLOCKS CRITICISM AS HE TACKLES `MONDAY NIGHT' ROLE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MIKI TURNER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ With his small frame and scruffy appearance,
he doesn't look the part. Plus, there's nothing on his extensive
resume to suggest that he's even qualified for the job. Yet when
comedian, talk show host and pitchman Dennis Miller faced a
skeptical group of TV critics at the group's annual media tour
Sunday at the Ritz Carlton Hotel &AMP; Spa, America's most irreverent
funny man didn't fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who was hired by producer Don Ohlmeyer last month to
join ABC's Monday Night Football broadcasting team, was as steady
as any armchair quarterback as he fielded questions about his
``odd'' hiring, his qualifications and the role he'll play when he
joins longtime MNF announcer Al Michaels, analyst Dan Fouts and
on-field reporters Eric Dickerson and Melissa Stark.
</P>
<P>
   When you consider the pedigree of his MNF colleagues, all of
whom are either ex-jocks or longtime sports broadcasting pros,
Miller's hiring seems pretty risky. After all, even though Miller,
46, has earned five Emmys for HBO's ``Dennis Miller Live,'' he has
never called any kind of sporting event and has never played the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, however, is hopeful that the Saturday Night Live alum's
acerbic ``common-man'' appeal will add just the right touch to its
storied Monday-night franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we've tried to assemble is a group of people who
have different skills and different life experiences,'' Ohlmeyer
said. ``We've got two Hall of Famers and the best play-by-play
announcer in the business. I think people will be surprised at
(Miller's) knowledgeability in terms of football. Also, what Dennis
brings is that he looks at life a little bit askew and he looks at
football a little bit askew.''
</P>
<P>
   With his MNF debut two weeks away, Miller concedes that he still
has a lot to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not ready to go right now,'' Miller said. ``I've got
two weeks and I'm going to use every second of it. I'm trying to
lay in as much information as I can. I'm just reading a bunch of
statistics and player biographies. I'm just trying to pull it all
in on a deeper level. And then when I get to the game, I'll just,
you know, try to comment on the game.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ohlmeyer explained it, Fouts will pick apart the x's and o's,
Dickerson and Stark will get up close and personal with the
players, Michaels will call the plays and Miller will. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, it's football,'' Miller said with a hint of
condescension. ``I've never played the game, but it's not like I'm
on the medical channel with Denton Cooley. I can comment on a
football game. If somebody at home goes, `He never played,' well,
you know, a lot of people didn't play the game. I'm not going to
try and comment on, you know, the inner stuff (it takes) to go
across the middle with a defensive back careening at your spine.
But I watch football as much as anybody. I can comment on a team
and tell (people) what I think are their strengths and
weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   And he won't, repeat won't, be in the booth for comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want to convey that I'm going to be the court
jester out there because, indeed, football is a different arena,''
Miller says. ``These people don't want me to be some manic
jokesmith out there. I'm going to talk football. If I see a chance
for a humorous shot, I'm going to take it here and there, but my
prime directive is to be an integral member of a three-man group
talking about a football game. And I think I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As do, for that matter, his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we brought Dennis in (for an audition), not only did we
get Dennis Miller as Dennis Miller (the comedian), we got from him
some of the most perceptive analysis of the game itself that I've
ever heard,'' Michaels said. ``He came in from a different angle.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Dickerson: ``I think it's a good thing, and I think all the
players that play now even think it's a good thing because it adds
a comedic side. The NFL is not all about being comedic, but some
funny things can happen in the National Football League.''
</P>
<P>
   After the news conference, Miller demonstrated his football
knowledge by offering a prognosis of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dunno, I don't think it's their year, quite frankly,''
Miller said. ``I think Michael Irvin is a loss. He was a bit of an
iconoclast and a weird guy, but certainly a gamer and it can't help
to lose him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind Jerry Jones. I like the way he makes money. I
like his approach to the game. People always go, `He just wants to
buy a championship,' like that's a bad thing. I've always thought
that's a good thing. I think he makes a mistake when he goes into
the draft room and commandeers that situation. I don't think his
picks over the years have proven that he's as an astute judge of
talent as he is a judge of finances. I'm picking the Rams.''
</P>
<P>
   And with his HBO show _ now in its seventh season _ going on
hiatus next month until January, Miller will have plenty of time to
hone his broadcast skills. Although not one typically for
self-doubts, Miller admitted he does have some apprehensions about
his new gig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have show-business apprehensions, but they're not real-life
apprehensions'' he said. ``It's just show-business pressure. I
don't feel that much pressure. If I do well they'll rehire me and
if I do it poorly they'll fire me. I'm at peace with that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
