<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SAKS-RENOVATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAKS MAKEOVER: SALES SPACE UP, AS IS CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)  (EDS: Hyphen in `Saks-Fifth' in 2nd graf is cq) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``To our friends up the avenue, who have done things
decidedly new, we extend a cordial greeting, a bravo of approval, a
sincere salutation and a hearty hand-clasp.''
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1924. The avenue was Fifth. The welcoming
advertisement was placed by Russeks, ``An Institution of Paris
Fashion,'' at 36th Street. And the newcomer was Saks-Fifth Avenue,
between 49th and 50th streets.
</P>
<P>
   Russeks is long gone. So are most of the big Fifth Avenue
retailers: B. Altman, Arnold Constable, Best &AMP; Co., Bonwit Teller
and De Pinna. That leaves Saks with the task of restoring the
character of its landmark building without freezing the store in
time, especially a time that is 76 years past.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many stores that have the wonderful bones this
building does architecturally,'' said Christina Johnson, the
president and chief executive of Saks Fifth Avenue. ``We have the
challenge of marrying this company's incredible legacy to the
relevancy needs of the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost halfway through a five-year, $100 million renovation,
from the top floor to the basement (sorry, ``concourse level''),
Saks has already picked up an extra 40,000 square feet of selling
space by moving the alterations, wrap and pack, receiving and fur
storage departments out of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Saks executives are turning their attention to the main
floor. Its good bones have been lost to an accumulation of visual
clutter and physical obstructions like sales islands pushed into
the aisles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have a clear shot when you're in the store,'' said
Stephen B. Joseph, vice president for corporate store planning and
design, who is working with the architectural firm Tucci, Segrete &AMP;
Rosen Consultants. ``Clear sight lines and clear circulation are
very important.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the renovation of the main floor, scheduled for 2002,
sales islands will be pulled back four or five feet to the line of
the columns along the main aisles. ``When you walk into Saks Fifth
Avenue, you'll see this grand boulevard,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The men's department at the rear of the floor will be moved
upstairs, freeing space for cosmetics, jewelry, handbags and
accessories. A ring of smaller, almost self-contained selling areas
will be created around the perimeter, framed by pilasters with
acanthus-leaf capitals that complement the existing columns.
</P>
<P>
   New chandeliers and sconces will be added, as will some kind
molding, perhaps trompe l'oeil, to give the ceiling an added sense
of depth.
</P>
<P>
   The men's department will be consolidated on the sixth floor and
the seventh floor, which is under renovation. The third floor, home
of high-end design, will be renovated next year, with a shallow
barrel-vaulted ceiling along the main axis, leading to windows
overlooking the Channel Gardens of Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   As unlikely as it seems, the top two floors at this prime
location were once occupied by workrooms. These were supervised in
the 1930s by Joseph T. Cukor, a cousin of the movie director George
Cukor, and were described by Fortune magazine as ``bursting with
girls stitching diligently over long tables spread with rippling,
exotic fabrics, with wacky designers, grave-faced fitters, blinking
tailors and mannequins lolling about waiting for fittings.''
</P>
<P>
   Saks was designed by Starrett &AMP; Van Vleck in Renaissance Revival
style. The 10-story limestone and brick building has chamfered
corners, two-story-high pilasters and setbacks above the seventh
floor. The architects virtually replicated this design at the
Garfinckel store in downtown Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The hyphen in Saks-Fifth Avenue distinguished it from an older
Saks &AMP; Co. store on Herald Square. The Saks-34th Street building
still stands, altered beyond recognition and now known as Herald
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Horace Saks merged his business with Gimbel Brothers in 1923,
permitting him to finance construction on Fifth Avenue. More
recently, Saks was owned by Batus Inc., a unit of BAT Industries of
Britain, and then Investcorp, a Bahrain-based investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Saks was acquired two years ago for $2.1 billion by Proffitt's
Inc., which changed its name to Saks Inc. The company, based in
Birmingham, Ala., operates 357 stores.
</P>
<P>
   The headquarters of the Saks Fifth Avenue division, which has 61
stores, occupy 16 floors of the Tower 49 skyscraper at 12 East 49th
St. The store has 650,000 square feet, but executives will not
disclose how much of that is given over to sales.
</P>
<P>
   Edward M. Calabrese, senior vice president and creative director
of Tucci, Segrete &AMP; Rosen, contrasted the renovation of Saks with
the general transformation of Fifth Avenue into a ``mall-like,
homogenized'' environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much has been obliterated,'' he said. ``Putting things back
and giving a building back its sense of architecture will be very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bottom line is that they're also looking at the
size of the investment. It's one of the last luxury department
stores in the United States. It's them and Neiman Marcus. They
don't want to make any mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
