<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROP EVERYTHING FOR THESE COOKIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dale McClelland e-mailed looking for a recipe for snowdrop
cookies that ``ran a number of years ago. They are rolled in
powdered sugar while hot and have nuts and spices in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Our electronic library database goes back about 10 years. I
could find nothing there on snowdrop cookies. However, through the
magic of the Internet, which has a worldwide base of recipes, I
found what I think is the recipe Dale wants at www.cookierecipe.com
_ a fabulous site that is part of www.allrecipes.com. And for
chocolate lovers (if it's not chocolate, it's not worth eating),
here's a similar recipe from the same Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia W. Snowden saw our request for fire-and-ice pickles and
sent along her recipe. Duh. I had no idea that these were the same
pickles that we run the recipe for every holiday season and call
Christmas pickles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SNOWBALLS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 4 dozen
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ground pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   7/8 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter and white sugar. Add nuts and vanilla. Blend in
flour and salt and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Form dough into small balls and bake on ungreased cookie sheet
for 8 to 10 minutes until barely brown. Coat in powdered sugar
while still hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cookie: 51 calories, 3 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, trace protein, 5 milligrams cholesterol, 25
milligrams sodium, 61 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   SNOWY PECAN COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 5 dozen
</P>
<P>
   4 (1-ounce each) squares unsweetened chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups white granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   Combine chocolate squares and oil in saucepan and place over low
heat until chocolate is melted.
</P>
<P>
   Cool and pour into mixing bowl. Add sugar, eggs and vanilla,
mixing until well blended.
</P>
<P>
   Sift dry ingredients together and gradually add to chocolate/egg
mixture, stirring well.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in nuts, cover and place dough in refrigerator overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees and grease cookie sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Shape dough into small balls, about 1 inch in diameter. Roll in
powdered sugar and place about 2 inches apart on cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 84 calories, 4 grams fat, 10
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 14 milligrams cholesterol, 46
milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-AND-ICE PICKLES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 gallon
</P>
<P>
   2-ounce bottle Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 gallon dill pickles (not kosher)
</P>
<P>
   5 pounds sugar
</P>
<P>
   8-10 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons whole mustard seed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 red bell pepper, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Drain pickles in colander. Slice pickles in 1/4-inch-thick
slices and layer them in original jar along with the sugar: dills,
sugar, dills, sugar. When the jar is about half full, add Tabasco
sauce, garlic, mustard seeds and red pepper slices. Layer remainder
of pickles and sugar. Let jar sit unrefrigerated for 7 days,
turning container from top to bottom every day.
</P>
<P>
   Note: You may not be able to fit all the pickles and sugar in
the jar. Save the ingredients; by the next day, the sugar will be
dissolved, making room for the rest of the pickles and sugar. Put
in smaller jars for gifts to friends. Also makes a great relish for
salads.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 12 calories, 0 fat, 3 grams
carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 73 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Request:
</P>
<P>
   Sue Simnacher Tood of Haltom City, Texas, would love some of the
recipes for dishes that were served at the now-closed St. Joseph
Hospital cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was an RN there (Bee Simnacher) and I worked briefly
in the business office circa 1968-70. Employees would line up to
wait in line to get in, and the glorious smells would drive you
crazy. Then, sadly, they decided to have food purchased outside for
the cafeteria. I remember the Ritz cracker pie, the carrot salad,
and oh, the Mexican food!''
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone help?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
