<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-19 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ANOTHER TASK IN PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: in reference to aabalone((red)) in 10th graf, change
double parentheses to single brackets; aabalone, three a's lower
case, is CQ)  
 By LISA BELKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you read this I will be on vacation. But that doesn't mean
I won't be working. I'll have my laptop with me, and, with luck,
I'll be able to tap into my e-mail. After all, this column has to
be edited.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I have a tradition of working while playing. It
began on our Hawaiian honeymoon, when Bruce spent the plane ride
reading medical journals and I was awakened at an ungodly hour by
The New York Times' magazine section so I could answer questions
from a fact checker.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the memorable summer on Block Island, off Rhode
Island, when I had to finish the final draft of a book and Bruce
had a grant application due. We were sharing a rental house with
Bruce's sister and her husband, and, between the four of us, we'd
brought four cell phones, three laptops and a fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   This does, I admit, seem to go against the basic meaning of the
word ``vacation,'' and I realize that other couples handle things
differently.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Seibel, for instance, is an assistant U.S. attorney who
refuses to even think about work while on vacation. Her staff, she
says, knows that she wants to be called only ``if the safety of the
republic is in question,'' and, thankfully, that hasn't happened
yet. But Seibel's husband, Dr. Barron Lerner, is a self-diagnosed
work addict. A physician and medical historian at New York
Presbyterian Hospital, he feels that time spent away from work is
time spent worrying about work piling up _ in other words, only by
working can he relax.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before laptops, Seibel and Lerner would venture to
Cape Cod, Mass., for just a week at a time because she grew
agitated if he worked and he grew agitated if he didn't. Then, with
the coming of the e-mail era, they agreed to be daring and try a
two-week vacation, but first they established some carefully
crafted ground rules. He was allowed to work. But only during one
of the two weeks. And only at night after their two children were
asleep. ``You have to do what fits each person's desires and
neuroses,'' Lerner said.
</P>
<P>
   It is an evolving compromise. There is some question, for
instance, about whether e-mails fall under the
no-work-during-daylight clause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regard that as work, absolutely, but he regards it as an
activity of daily living,'' Seibel said.
</P>
<P>
   And there are varying interpretations of what counts as vacation
literature, too. Lerner is hoping that the new 581-page biography
of the legendary physician Sir William Osler ``could qualify as a
beach book.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Wiggin, founder of aabalone((red)), a consulting and
marketing communications firm in Darien, Conn., sees vacation as a
badly timed interruption of work. In the old days, she says, she
would spin herself into a frenzy in the hours before V-Day, trying
to tie up all the loose ends at work and at home. Now she takes
what she calls the dot-com.mom vacation, which means scheduling her
family's departure 24 hours ahead of her own, then spending that
full day ``at warp speed,'' working virtually nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to cook, eat, answer the telephone or be
sociable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that ``every tiny bit of work is done'' means she can
put that work aside for a while, and on her most recent trip, a
family reunion in New Hampshire, she ``decided not to even plug in
the brand new rocket ship PowerBook from which I had hitherto been
inseparable.'' The dot-com.mom approach is effective, she cautions,
only if you apply it on the other end, too _ leaving vacation a day
before everyone else and spending 24 hours excavating your desk.
</P>
<P>
   I can't see that either of these solutions will work for us.
Wiggin's plan, for instance, requires a marriage in which only one
spouse has an over-enmeshed relationship with work.
</P>
<P>
   At our house we would spend so much time jockeying to be the one
who stayed home that I don't think we'd ever actually leave on our
trip. Because the disturbing fact is, neither of us really minds
taking some work along. The laptop doesn't mar our vacation so much
as it permits us to take one. If I could not have finished my book
on Block Island, I couldn't have gone to Block Island. How lovely,
then, that technology allows me to work in a hammock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
