<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6727 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-INDIAN-AUTHOR-HNS &LR;      07-19 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-AUTHOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOT-SELLING AUTHOR FROM THE RESERVATION NOT AT ALL RESERVED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At age 33, with two novels, two short-story
collections, nine books of poetry and a screenplay to his credit,
Sherman Alexie is not only one of America's hottest authors, he is
unique among Indian writers in having attained pop-culture fame.
There is a Sherman Alexie fan club. He has a Web site. Strangers
recognize him everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a peculiar thing,'' Alexie said. ``I think it's a
combination of being a writer and the movie (the 1998 independent
film 'Smoke Signals'), but being Indian has made me original and
eccentric enough to give me a level of recognition that's beyond
the actual number of books I sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, ``this is a camera-conscious culture, and I'm
good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie is wrapping up a 32-city national tour promoting ``The
Toughest Indian in the World'' (Atlantic Monthly Press, $24, 283
pages), his new, best-selling short-story collection.
</P>
<P>
   Alexie is a Spokane-Coeur d'Alene Indian, reared on the Spokane
Reservation, a handsome, robust athlete _ a shooting guard _ and
not afflicted with false modesty. ``I'm one of those players I used
to make fun of, but I'm still better than 90 percent of the players
on most (basketball) courts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indian-ness, in all its facets, is his subject. He goes at it
with energy, imagination, originality, irreverence and wit,
although _ and he admits it _ his efforts sometimes flop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Toughest Indian in the World'' is a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the strongest stories are sure bets for ``Best of . .
.'' anthologies.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Saint Junior,'' an over-the-hill, overweight Indian
basketball player and his wife celebrate their unlikely but abiding
love story even as he tosses up air balls on a snow-packed outdoor
court.
</P>
<P>
   In the title story, an assimilated journalist surprises and
mystifies himself by having a sexual encounter with a bare-knuckled
Indian boxer who makes his living fighting the toughest fighters on
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   In ``One Good Man,'' which Alexie calls the best story he has
ever written, a young Indian man cares for his dying diabetic
father, whose feet have just been amputated.
</P>
<P>
   The two drive to Mexico, aiming to fulfill the father's dream of
removing himself from colonial America, but their car and the old
man's wheelchair break down just north of Tecate, and they can't
hitch a ride.
</P>
<P>
   ```Do you believe in God?' I asked my father.
</P>
<P>
   ```God has lots of potential,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ```When you pray,' I asked him, 'what do you pray about?'
</P>
<P>
   ```That's none of your business,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laughed. We waited for hours for somebody to help us. What
is an Indian? I lifted my father and carried him across every
border.''
</P>
<P>
   Other stories in the collection reach for profundity and fall
short (``The Sin Eaters'') or border on the juvenile (``Dear John
Wayne'').
</P>
<P>
   But all crackle with humor and irreverence, and they have bite.
Alexie does not romanticize ``the rez,'' nor Indian-ness per se.
(``It was Indian scouts who had helped white people kill Sitting
Bull, Geronimo, and every other Indian warrior in the world.'')
</P>
<P>
   He tells Indian secrets. In ``Class,'' he writes: ``Velma, my
dark-skinned mother, was overjoyed by my choice of mate. She'd
always wanted me to marry a white woman and beget half-breed
children who would beget quarter-bloods, and so on and so on, until
simple mathematics killed the Indian in us.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``One Good Man,'' the father offers this advice: ``Son, if
you're going to marry a white woman, then marry a rich one, because
those white-trash women are just Indians with bad haircuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie says he had a drinking problem from ages 18 to 23, and
alcohol is a significant factor in several of his stories. Summing
up the life histories of his siblings, the narrator of ``One Good
Man'' says ``we were teacher, truck driver, logger, accountant,
preacher and guitar player. Our biggest success: We were all alive.
Our biggest claim to fame: We were all sober.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no alcoholism in this book. All the Indians are sober
or never drink,'' he said. ``Most of the characters in my books
never drink or are recovering. Most people don't notice that.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the critical acclaim for ``Smoke Signals,'' Alexie said
that the film is regarded as a business failure by the film
industry. It was made for $1 million and earned $8 million, but
despite the terrific profit margin, the numbers were too small to
impress the industry's major players, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So now ``I'm working on studio screenplays, getting lots of
money for movies I know they'll never make. . . . It provides me
with security,'' he said. As a practical matter, ``all the success
of 'Smoke Signals' has done is it's guaranteed me that I can get
meetings with people. That's not a small thing, but it hasn't
guaranteed me money to make another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexie, who describes himself as ``a binge writer _ I work 12
and 14 hour days for weeks at a time, and then I don't work for
weeks at a time'' _ is at work on what he calls ``an urban novel''
about politics.
</P>
<P>
   He is hitting his stride. ``My vocation and my avocation is
writing. It's what I prefer to do above all else,'' he said.
``Publishing is nice, and I love the life, but if they stopped
publishing me tomorrow, I'd still be doing it. If I was bad at it,
I'd still do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
