<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-POE-HOUSE-DEMOLITION-     07-19 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POE-HOUSE-DEMOLITION-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYU RAPPING ON POE'S DOOR, SOON TO BE NEVERMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Behind the landmark Judson Memorial Church, which
frames the sky south of Washington Square Park through its ornate
campanile, there is a quaint, if somewhat dilapidated, block of
mustard and red brick houses.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists say two historic treasures reside on this
unassuming Greenwich Village swath: a house where Edgar Allan Poe
once lived and a town house renovated by McKim, Mead &AMP; White.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the summer, the stretch of four-story to six-story
buildings on West Third Street between Thompson and Sullivan
Streets will most likely be gone.
</P>
<P>
   And, to the dismay of city preservationists and neighborhood
groups, it may be replaced by a 13-story building for the New York
University School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Village and preservationists have long
criticized university construction projects that they considered to
be insensitive to the scale and historic character of the area, and
a handful of NYU projects under way this year had already added
fuel to residents' complaints.
</P>
<P>
   But the law school's plan to erect a 13-story multipurpose
building on West Third Street, which preservationists argue will
eviscerate a part of the Village's heritage and replace it with a
tower that will obscure views of the Judson Church, has inflamed
tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're transforming Washington Square and changing the
neighborhood's character by constructing buildings that are huge
and really unattractive,'' said Aubrey Lees, a member of the
Committee to Save Washington Square, a neighborhood group.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the city's leading preservation groups, like the
Municipal Arts Society and the Landmarks Conservancy, as well as
the Mystery Writers of America, have written to the law school,
pleading with administrators to reconsider their plans. And the
groups have tried to protect the buildings by seeking landmark
designations. But residents of the buildings have been told to be
out by July 31, and university officials said demolition could
begin posthaste.
</P>
<P>
   University administrators argue that the new buildings are
critical to the school's survival. ``These decisions we are making
are not window dressing,'' said John H. Beckman, a spokesman for
the university. ``They are part and parcel of a plan that began 30
years ago when NYU took a good hard look at itself and realized it
couldn't survive as a commuter school. What you're seeing now is a
latter part of that process.''
</P>
<P>
   John Sexton, dean of the law school, said the new building on
West Third Street will include needed faculty offices, classrooms
and student lounges. He said the school is reaching out to
neighbors to come up with a mutually acceptable plan.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build a building that belongs in the neighborhood,
that looks good in the Village, and we will do so in consultation
with the community,'' Sexton said. ``But we do not accept the views
of preservationists who say nothing can ever change.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   NYU told its neighbors at community board meetings in December
that it would build on West Third Street, shortly after the law
school purchased the Judson House, a Greek Revival town house on
the corner of West Third and Thompson, from the Judson Church for
$3.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Peter Laarman, senior minister of the church, said the house had
become a financial burden, costing about $17,000 a year to
maintain. The church sold the house to the university because the
law school promised to give the church space in the new building,
and to consult with congregants on the building's design. ``The
proposed structure maintains the open sky behind the church
itself,'' Laarman said, ``and it won't be a disaster by any
means.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In February, the university began meeting with neighborhood
groups and preservation advocates to discuss the project and
present design sketches. But many of the people who attended the
meetings said that the discussions began too late because officials
had already decided to tear down the historic structures.
</P>
<P>
   One of the buildings to be razed is the little red brick house
at 85 W. Third St., where Poe lived in 1844 and 1845.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1844, Poe moved into two rooms at the back of 85
Amity St., now West Third.
</P>
<P>
   During his stay there the American Review published his poem
``The Raven,'' to international acclaim. He also helped to start
and edit the Broadway Journal, a New Yorker of its day. And he
began writing one of his most noted short stories, ``The Cask of
Amontillado.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Poe lived close by several literary salons, like the Waverly
Place home of Anne Charlotte Lynch, who held soirees with guests
like Ralph Waldo Emerson and Herman Melville.
</P>
<P>
   Poe, who sometimes gave readings of his new works at such
gatherings, alienated himself from the Village literary crowd when
his unflattering portrayal of its members in ``The Literati of New
York'' was published in 1846. But by then he was ensconced in the
country, in the Bronx in a small cottage that would become a city
landmark.
</P>
<P>
   Some Poe scholars argue that the house on West Third Street is a
more important site. ``Scholars across this country have been
enormously anguished about losing this house,'' said Burton R.
Pollin, a professor emeritus of City University who has written 12
books on Poe.
</P>
<P>
   But New York University's resident Poe scholar, Kenneth
Silverman, who wrote ``Edgar A. Poe: Mournful and Never-Ending
Remembrance'' (Harper Collins, 1991), said the house had been
significantly altered in the 154 years since Poe lived there.
</P>
<P>
   The lower exterior of the building, he said, only vaguely
resembles its 19th century counterpart, as the stoop was removed
and the entrance shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate to have anyone go by there today and say, `Now, I
have an idea of how Edgar Allan Poe lived,''' Silverman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton said he ``finds it hard to take seriously any claims that
this building is special.'' He said he suspects preservationists
are using the Poe house as an excuse to halt construction.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Other preservation groups, like the Society for the Architecture
of the City and the Landmarks Conservancy, have focused their
energies on saving the Judson House. Originally three separate
Greek Revival houses, the buildings were merged and redesigned in
the 1890s by McKim, Mead &AMP; White, which also designed the Judson
Church.
</P>
<P>
   David Garrard Lowe, an architectural historian who wrote
``Stanford White's New York'' (Watson-Guptill, 1992), said the
house is a perfect example of colonial revival, the architectural
style that the novelist Edith Wharton admired in her writings about
the Village.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Poe scholars asked the city's Landmarks
Preservation Commission to designate the Poe house as a landmark to
protect it from demolition, but after considering the
documentation, the agency declined to hold a hearing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week, the New York state Office of Historic Preservation
announced that it had determined that the Judson House was eligible
for listing in the state and national registers of historic places.
But such a designation would not necessarily protect the house from
demolition.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton said the architects of the new building, Kohn Pedersen
Fox, are still considering preservationists' concerns. ``But,'' he
added, ``the fact of the matter is that it is literally impossible
to maintain those buildings and go along with our program.''
</P>
<P>
   The West Third Street project is the second NYU building plan
that has chafed some university neighbors this year.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the school completed demolition of the modernist
Loeb Student Center, built in the 1950s on Washington Square South,
to make way for the Helen and Martin Kimmel Center for University
Life, designed by Kevin Roche, who has designed several recent
additions to the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   The old student center, Beckman said, was an embarrassment
because it could not even accommodate half the students' requests
for club meeting spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Some neighborhood groups fought Kimmel, which will be wider at
its base and at its top than its predecessor, but the same height.
One group, the Committee to Save Washington Square, filed suit in
New York Supreme Court to try to halt construction until the
university studied the impact it might have on the Village. The
case was dismissed and is under appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime neighborhood residents say the planning for the student
center has been reminiscent of that of a building across the street
_ the Elmer Holmes Bobst Library, a red sandstone hulk on
Washington Square South. The library was built in the 1960s despite
widespread neighborhood protest.
</P>
<P>
   Construction has also irked some neighbors at Union Square,
where the university built a 14-story dormitory last year, and
where another 18-story dormitory is going up now.
</P>
<P>
   The chief complaint with all these projects has been that the
school does not adequately solicit neighborhood participation in
the planning process.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call us in after the process has gone beyond where they
can make substantial changes,'' said F. Anthony Zunino, president
of the Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation.
Referring to West Third Street, he said: ``That whole street has
become institutionalized all the way from Broadway to the end of
the park, except this one block. They are destroying the scale of
the neighborhood every time they tear down part of the Village.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Washington Square neighborhood was first developed in
the 1830s it became fashionable for its Federal and Greek Revival
homes, most of them just a few stories high. The district had ``a
kind of established repose which is not of frequent occurrence in
the other quarters of the long, shrill city,'' wrote Henry James,
who grew up there, in his 1881 novel, ``Washington Square.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckman said that although the university has met with
neighborhood groups and preservation advocates, it is not required
to consult with its neighbors on the developments because the
construction is within legal zoning limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we had a desperate need for space, we did not seek
any variances so we could build higher,'' he said. ``We completely
understand that we live in a neighborhood which has an interest and
a stake in the architecture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
