<HEADLINE>
FIRST ACADEMY AWARDS `SHOW' WASN'T SUCH A BIG DEAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ How many people attended the first Academy Awards show,
and was it broadcast? _ A.A., Stephenville, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ An audience of 250 attended the first awards
presentation for the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences on
May 26, 1929.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, which was brief and received little fanfare, was
held at the Roosevelt Hotel in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no big deal in 1929, even for the motion picture
community,'' UPI Hollywood reporter Vernon Scott writes. ``At that
time, the winners were known in advance of the banquets.''
</P>
<P>
   The event, which was not broadcast on radio until a year later,
was hosted by Douglas Fairbanks and director William C. de Mille.
The Best Picture award went to ``Wings,'' Best Actor to Emil
Jannings and Best Actress to Janet Gaynor.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Where can we get a tape of the song ``Barefoot Boy?'' _
J.H., Mineral Wells, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ That song is included on folk singer John McCutcheon's
1980 album, ``Barefoot Boy With Boots On,'' which was rereleased in
1998 and is currently in print.
</P>
<P>
   You can order it on CD directly from McCutcheon by calling (804)
977-6321 or visiting the Web site www.folkmusic.com.
</P>
<P>
   McCutcheon, a six-time Grammy nominee, is scheduled to perform
in Dallas Sept. 30 at the Winfrey Point building on White Rock
Lake. For ticket information, call (972) 622-7283 or visit the Web
site www.whiterocklake.org.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Where can I write to Jerry Seinfeld? _ M.D., W.
Brookfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ Write to him in care of Creative Artists Agency, 9830
Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, Calif. 90212.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old comedian married public relations executive
Jessica Sklar, 28, in December and they expect their first child
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the U.S. Postal Service began issuing a ``Seinfeld'' TV
show stamp as part of the Celebrate the Century collection for the
1990s. The 33-cent stamp features an illustration of Seinfeld's
apartment.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
