<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Place for God: A Guide to Spiritual Retreats and Retreat
Centers'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Timothy Jones &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Image Books/Doubleday, $14.95'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Are you looking for a place where you can have some down time,
away from cellphones, e-mails, work ... even friends and relatives?
Is your spirit weary? Then maybe what you need is a ``spiritual
vacation,'' as author Timothy Jones so aptly describes a sojourn in
a retreat center.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Place for God'' is a useful guide to retreat centers across
the United States and Canada. More than 250 locations _ convents,
hermitages and spiritual guest houses _ are cataloged.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of the book is devoted to an exploration of
retreat-taking, providing useful insights based on the author's
experiences. Is it right for me? How can I make it a meaningful
experience? How much will it cost?
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the book consists of listings of various centers,
divided by state. Each comes with pertinent information such as
e-mail addresses, religious affiliation, location, accommodation
and points of interest (some retreat houses offer gyms and gift
shops).
</P>
<P>
   Jones provides an excellent map and guide. Although many
listings indicate that people of all faiths are accepted, it's a
pity that he does not include a single non-Christian center _ and
there are dozens he could have selected. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Amrita Shlachter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``God of the Possible &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Gregory A. Boyd &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Baker, $12.99) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does God really know ``everything?'' Gregory A. Boyd's answer is
``no.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the stake ready yet. The Minnesota
minister-theologian makes an interesting _ and, most important,
Bible-based _ case for his views in ``God of the Possible.''
</P>
<P>
   What is the nature of the future? Is it settled and therefore
completely known by God? Or is it partly settled and partly open to
change (because it hasn't happened yet), and therefore not fully
knowable by anyone _ in the same way that a square circle is
intrinsically impossible?
</P>
<P>
   Boyd argues that the latter view _ the ``open view of God'' _
better fits a Bible that frequently speaks of the deity as changing
his mind, regretting a situation or being disappointed. The book
critiques the classical view, outlines the open view and considers
its practical effects, and works to answer objections and
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd has set himself a difficult task. But at the very least,
``God of the Possible'' competently sets forth his side and proves
that this theory is not biblically out of court from the
beginning. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
