<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6741 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     07-19 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUSTICES OFTEN AT ODDS WITH PRESIDENTS WHO APPOINT THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 23)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that Supreme Court appointments are an issue in
the presidential campaign, it is challenging to try to match recent
justices with the presidents who selected them.
</P>
<P>
   The results will prove surprising. When presidents and
presidential candidates vow that they will not subject prospective
justices to a ``litmus test'' on a highly volatile issue such as
abortion, they are perverting the truth.
</P>
<P>
   They know that when they begin considering Supreme Court
candidates, they will face tremendous pressure from liberal
feminists on one side and staunch conservatives on the other.
</P>
<P>
   In a July 9 television interview, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson,
who is chairman of this year's Republican platform committee, said
that George W. Bush need not be bound by the platform declaration
that only anti-abortionists will be named to the federal judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a Catholic opponent of abortion, also pointed out that
a president is not committed to a position by the platform and
could select a pro-choice running mate. The field includes
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, New York Gov. George Pataki and New
Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush knows that he would incur the wrath of the right wing
if he were to pick a pro-choice individual as a running mate or a
nominee to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Democrats. Al Gore would bring the wrath of
pro-choice liberals down on his head if he were to nominate an
anti-abortion person to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years we have heard a great deal about the kinds of
individuals who should be named to the nation's highest tribunal.
We, therefore, have anticipated that a resolutely conservative
president, like Ronald Reagan, would appoint only those who shared
his ideology while a more liberal president, such as Bill Clinton,
would pluck justices from the ranks of his philosophical allies.
</P>
<P>
   Let us look at the current crop of justices and some from the
past to see if we can match them with the presidents who nominated
them.
</P>
<P>
   The three most consistently conservative members of the current
court are Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas and Chief Justice William
Rehnquist. It would seem logical to believe that all three were
elevated to the high court by Reagan, the most consistently
conservative president of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But that judgment would be incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Scalia was nominated by Reagan. Thomas, however,
was named by a moderate conservative, George Bush, father of the
current GOP presidential hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist was appointed by Richard Nixon and promoted to chief
justice by Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Who then nominated David Souter and John Paul Stevens, both of
whom are considered to be liberal justices? Was it Lyndon Johnson,
John Kennedy or Jimmy Carter?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is: None of the above. Souter was chosen by the same
George Bush who selected Thomas. Stevens was named not by a liberal
Democrat but by a moderately conservative Republican, Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Kennedy and Sandra Day O'Connor, who are regarded as
``swing votes,'' joining the conservatives on some issues and the
liberals on others, were named to the Supreme Court by Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer, key members of the
court's liberal bloc, are more easily identified with the president
who chose them: Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A president may vow to appoint only individuals with whom he is
philosophically compatible. But a president may not know the basic
ideology or the degree of independence of a judicial candidate he
nominates for confirmation by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Senate has approved the president's choice and the
justice has begun a lifetime tenure on the court, there is nothing
the president can do to control the way that justice votes on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three justices appointed by Theodore Roosevelt, the
president expressed repeated exasperation with Oliver Wendell
Holmes Jr., one of the truly great justices of all time. The reason
was that Holmes sometimes voted against Roosevelt's position on
critical issues.
</P>
<P>
   Woodrow Wilson, a visionary progressive, named three justices,
two of whom were at opposite ends of the political spectrum. One
was the brilliant Louis Brandeis, the first Jewish member of the
court and a giant among justices. Another was James C. McReynolds,
a vehement anti-Semite and political reactionary.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``Justices and Presidents,'' Henry J. Abraham wrote
that ``McReynolds, continuing to manifest his violent temper and
abrasive nature on the bench, not only became a member of the
anti-New-Deal Four Horsemen; he turned into their loudest, most
cantankerous, sarcastic, aggressive, intemperate and reactionary
representative.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the memorable lines of Dwight D. Eisenhower was that he
had made two mistakes as president and ``both are on the Supreme
Court.'' His reference was to Chief Justice Earl Warren and
Associate Justice William Brennan, who in the eyes of other court
observers, are among the greatest.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Constitution became the law of the land in 1789,
successive justices have sought to adjust its dictates to new
generations of Americans. Sometimes they succeed, and sometimes
they fail.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for a president to become disenchanted with a
justice he has nominated. With independence and life tenure,
justices are free to move in any direction they choose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6744 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DEALER0720-COX     07-19 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEALER0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Career as a Las Vegas blackjack dealer hard way to make an easy
living
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ She's standing at a blackjack table at The Mirage
Hotel, expertly dealing the cards and chatting with patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Her name tag reads ``Nancy'' and ``Dayton, Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They want customers to know where we're from because it's an
icebreaker,'' explains Nancy Potasky Stein, who's been a Las Vegas
dealer 16 years. ``It gives them a chance to say they're also from
Dayton or Columbus or Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in tuxedo shirt and bow tie, short black skirt and
teal-and-black vest decorated with a palm-tree design, Stein has
worked her way up to the top of a profession she calls fun and
exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard way to make an easy living,'' Stein says. ``I like
it because it's a people job.''
</P>
<P>
   That's obvious on this particular morning as a patron steers her
wheelchair up to Stein's table.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know my mother passed away,'' the woman confides as Stein
begins to deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a local who always came in with her mother,'' says Stein
later. ``I knew right away when I didn't see her mother that
something was wrong. I have a lot of repeat customers; you get to
know their whole life stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Her clients come from around the world and speak a variety of
languages. Her workplace is one of the strip's most elaborate
hotels, housing novelties ranging from Siegfried and Roy's gorgeous
snow-white leopards and white tigers to a ``live volcano'' that
erupts every half hour.
</P>
<P>
   On her way to work, she passes live dolphins and sharks, a
tropical rain forest, palm trees and loads of orchids.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as glamorous as it might appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You stand on your feet all day and sometimes you have to put
up with obnoxious people,'' Stein says. ``But, overall, people are
basically nice _they're out having a good time, they're on
vacation, they're relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   So how did a local girl end up cutting the chips in Las Vegas?
</P>
<P>
   It all started when her dad opened an auto painting shop in Las
Vegas and his daughter began accompanying him to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I might want to be a dealer,'' said Stein, then 24,
who had attended the University of Tampa and always worshipped the
sun. ``I had never picked up a deck of cards in my life!
</P>
<P>
   ``My father had a friend who had a dealers' school and he said
you could earn a good living,'' she remembers. Today, according to
Stein, dealers earn between $20,000 and $80,000, primarily in tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actually paid just minimum wage,'' Stein explains,
adding that dealers prefer the type of tip in which the player
makes a bet for the dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dealer might average between $120-$160 a day in tips plus
their salary,'' says Stein, who deals in two areas _ a low limit
$5,000 pit and a high limit ($5,000-$10,000) pit on weekends. Stein
works six hours a day, with 20 -minute breaks each hour.
</P>
<P>
   Employee cafeterias provide another perk: Casino employees eat
whatever they like free of charge when they're on duty. There are
also complimentary tickets to shows to be had.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, who has always dealt blackjack_ the nation's most popular
casino game _ says dealing isn't as easy as it looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You practice by pitching cards into a hat for hours,'' she
says. ``You learn to deal out of a shoe, how to cut the chips, what
the payoffs are.''
</P>
<P>
   Though dealing had traditionally been a man's profession, by the
time Stein attended dealers' school, women were dealing as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was all by myself, scared but excited,'' she recalls.
``Everyone said I'd be back in Dayton in six months.''
</P>
<P>
   After completing the course, neophyte dealers get their feet wet
by working at downtown casinos as apprentices, then move to the
strip.
</P>
<P>
   Stein practiced at El Cortez, then went to the Horseshoe .
</P>
<P>
   ``Every casino has a different costume,'' says Stein. ``At the
Horseshoe, we wore jeans and a bolero and cowboy boots.'' She
worked her way up to the Golden Nugget, the old MGM, then moved to
the prestigious Mirage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you're interviewed by the casino manager, other
times you are auditioned _ they watch you deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein suffered a temporary setback at the age of 30 when she was
diagnosed with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a fighter,'' she says. ``I kept my apartment here but
went back to Dayton for the chemo and radiation.''
</P>
<P>
   She credits her dad with encouraging her to become a dealer when
she expressed interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll earn a good living and meet a nice Jewish boy,'' he
assured her.
</P>
<P>
   Both predictions have come true. At 43, Stein met and married
Howard Stein, a pit boss at the Bellagio hotel. It was a first
marriage for both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to get married but I was very picky,'' says
Stein.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Stein says his wife is an excellent dealer who's lots of
fun, always upbeat and brings out the best in others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of dealers out here who are stone-faced and
don't talk, and you might as well go to a machine!'' he says.
``When you gamble most people lose money because that's what Las
Vegas is built on. People aren't exactly happy when they lose but
the hurt isn't so bad when you're with Nancy because you're having
fun. She gets everybody involved _ the people at the table are all
interacting with one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein says Las Vegas has changed dramatically since she arrived
20 years ago. Then, she says, the town was known for cheap
all-you-can-eat buffets; today, gourmet restaurants abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``And all the concerts come here now,'' Stein says. ``Las Vegas
is a good value for a vacation and now people bring their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite Las Vegas acts currently include ``O,'' a Cirque du
Soleil show performed on a stage of water at the Bellagio;
impersonator Danny Gans, who performs at The Mirage, and
``Mystere,'' another Cirque show at Treasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   Any gambling advice?
</P>
<P>
   ``Come knowing that gambling is for entertainment only,'' she
advises. ``Come to have a good time. Pick up a strategy card if
you're a novice ... it will tell you when to split, when to double
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``And don't spend more than you can afford to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Meredith Moss at meredithmoss(at)coxohio.com or at
225-2440.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
