<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1S     07-19 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Wednesday, July 19, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Editors &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: PEACE-TALKS and CLINTON-JAPAN.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEACE-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ President Clinton, delaying his
departure for an economic summit in Japan, meets with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat in an effort to salvage the Middle East peace
talks. But There are indications that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak has decided to stop the talks and return home. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JAPAN (Washington) _ President Clinton`s decision to cut
short a planned Trip to Japan and stay on at the Camp David peace
talks will bolster impressions that the administration does not
take its Asian ally seriously, Japan watchers say. And by shuffling
his schedule, Clinton is doing little to help the political
fortunes of his Japanese host, embattled Prime Minister Yoshiro
Mori. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   DISABILITIES-SURVEY (Washington) _ Nearly 10 years after the
signing of the Americans with Disabilities Act, a survey shows that
the disabled continue to lag behind the rest of society in
employment, income and access to health care. The act, signed July
26, 1990, by former President George Bush, banned discrimination
against such people. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-IMMIGRANTS (Washington) _ Major Hispanic groups voice
frustration with Congress' focus on legislation to bring more
high-tech foreign workers into the country. Unless Republican
leaders do more for immigrants already here, the GOP will be
targeted at the polls this year by Latino voters, the Hispanic
organizations warn. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CHOICE (Washington) _ Republican pro-choice advocates secure
a promise from Republican Platform Committee Chairman Tommy
Thompson that he will consider allowing open discussion as
committee members write the abortion plank at the GOP convention.
Pro-choice Republicans say they will fight to change the party's
plank opposing any abortion, but conservatives say their chances
are nil. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Washington) _ President Clinton, unlike some of
his predecessors, is savoring his last months in office. The
president doesn't rage against the dying light. Instead, he's ever
more nostalgic about his waning tenure in the White House. He has
often said that ``even the bad days are good'' in the presidency _
and he quips that he has had his share of bad days. By HELEN
THOMAS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-ADVISER (Washington) _ The trail that led Peter Swire to
the White House as President Clinton's chief adviser on privacy
matters began in the 1970s when he worked the computers at his
family's furniture stores in Albany, N.Y. There amid the La-Z-Boy
recliners and living room sets, he was inspired when his father,
Bill Swire, charged headlong into the computer era. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Now that Supreme Court
appointments are an issue in the campaign, we should recall a
lesson from history: It is not unusual for a president to become
disenchanted with a Supreme Court justice he has nominated for the
high bench. With independence and life tenure, justices are free to
move in any direction they choose. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already
filed.)
</P>
</TEXT>
