<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-EXECUTIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIME OF MY LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   Fred Mouawad is chief executive of Mondera.com, an Internet company
offering luxury goods; this was written with Jobert E. Abueva.  
 (eds; in 2nd graf `trial biking' is CQ; not `trail')  
 By FRED MOUAWAD   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An hourglass sits on my desk. It symbolizes my extreme
sensitivity to time. I like to pit myself against the clock to see
how fast I can complete a task or project. I've been called a speed
fiend. I own a Ferrari and a Porsche back in Geneva where the speed
limits are higher.
</P>
<P>
   I enjoy outdoor sports like trial biking, a kind of motocross. I
also jet ski and scuba dive. My mother disapproves of my choices in
sports. She always worries whether I'll return in one piece.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a boy, my family spent three weeks every summer on a
yacht sailing the Mediterranean. Once, I finished reading all the
books I brought on board in one week. I did not want to play
Monopoly with my brothers. I found it boring. I made my father
redirect the yacht to the nearest island so I could stock up on
more books. I have been reading self-improvement and business books
since I was 13. I suppose I'm not much fun to be with on vacations.
</P>
<P>
   I was born in Lebanon but constantly traveled because of my
parents. At the age of 6, I started attending boarding school in
Geneva. My brothers soon joined me. Our mother called us every
other day, more so than anyone else's parents. It was embarrassing.
One day she would be in Paris, then Riyadh, then Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   I studied business administration at Pepperdine University, but
I couldn't wait to own my own business. In my sophomore year I
bought a local travel agency and tried to produce a low-budget
movie. The agency took off, but the writer never finished the
script for the movie. I knew I had to improve my success rate.
</P>
<P>
   After school I sold off the agency and went to work for my
father. I come from four generations of jewelers. My first
assignment was to manage our Thailand operations where we
manufactured jewelry. I enjoyed the autonomy of managing 215 people
until my father came into town.
</P>
<P>
   Family businesses are a real challenge. I made changes to the
organization that my father vetoed. I had to learn to manage my
emotions around him. I also knew then that I would break away from
the family business.
</P>
<P>
   I went to Harvard Business School but left after a year to start
a venture capital firm. I went back to trading gems, this time over
the Web. I still have more than 120 Web designers working for me in
Bangkok. Soon afterward, I also opened a pizza chain in India and a
coffee chain in Thailand. My venture capital fund also invested in
pharmacy chains in Argentina and in other e-commerce ventures in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   My brother Paschal and I founded Mondera in Manhattan. We
thought: Where better to locate it than in the diamond district of
the world's fastest city? Being on the Internet is a never-ending
race against time. I work 16-hour days and sleep six hours a night.
I sleep in on weekends. My friends constantly remind me to slow
down.
</P>
<P>
   During a charity auction at Cannes last May, I had bid on a
massage by Heidi Klum, the model. I was up against James Caan and
Kenneth Branagh. I was the last remaining bidder at $31,000. I
intend to redeem my prize. I simply need to make the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
