<HEADLINE>
GENS X AND WHY COLLECT FOR FUN AND PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release July 19, 2000.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's TRENDS-NEXTGEN column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of TRENDS-NEXTGEN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Generations of kids have collected baseball cards and comic
books. Today's Gen Xers and Whyers have branched out.
</P>
<P>
   Many young people take collecting very seriously. They're not
just in it for fun.
</P>
<P>
   As an avid 16-year-old Swatch collector told an interviewer for
my company, Youth Intelligence, ``I don't even wear the watches,
but I know they'll be worth money some day, and that's why I buy
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, collecting supports the need to be viewed as an
individual that pervades so many of this generation's activities.
Young people love things that make them feel special and unique. As
a 14-year-old collector of vintage bowling shirts explained, ``All
my friends look the same and dress the same For me, my shirts are
totally special and no one else can buy one like it. It says a lot
about me.''
</P>
<P>
   So what are these savvy collectors saving? Here are some of the
things that are hot.
</P>
<P>
   BEANIE BABIES
</P>
<P>
   What started as a cuddly toy has become a hot commodity. Today,
Beanies can be bought at auction on eBay and ``collecting'' them
has turned childhood fun into a serious preoccupation. As one savvy
12-year-old New York collector told Youth Intelligence, ``I think
if I just had all these stuffed animals it would seem kind of
babyish, but I'm getting them so I have a complete collection. I
don't play with them, but I know all their names and how much each
one is worth.''
</P>
<P>
   CONCERT TEES
</P>
<P>
   Think Bay City Rollers rather than Backstreet Boys. Young people
are enthralled by 1970s music. But unlike other hoarding hobbyists,
those who are grabbing the T-shirts are actually wearing them. As
one 21-year-old from Los Angeles explained, ``I think music in the
past was more real, more legit. When you wear an old shirt from a
concert you're really connecting with the past and rejecting some
of the commercial music of today.''
</P>
<P>
   HALSTON/PUCCI/GUCCI/VALENTINO
</P>
<P>
   Designers _ and designs _ of the 1970s are also all the rage,
from handbags to halter tops. Young people want anything that seems
to have a history. A 26-year-old from Los Angeles commented, ``I
think collecting clothes is cool. There's so much disposable
fashion these days but you know that designers like Halston or
Gucci are still so cool.''
</P>
<P>
   WATCHES
</P>
<P>
   These days, time is more precious than ever, so it should be no
surprise that watches are treasured. From vintage Hamiltons and Tag
Heures to more modern Swatches and even Casio G shocks, watches are
ones to watch. Some trendsetters are even donning multiple watches
_ partly because they like to collect them and partly as a fashion
statement.
</P>
<P>
   LUNCH BOXES
</P>
<P>
   With pictures of everything from the Dukes of Hazard to Smurfs,
lunch boxes are the hottest portables to stockpile. As one
18-year-old devotee from Chicago explained, ``I suppose part of it
is I wish I had the days of having my mom pack a lunch I mean that
never happened but it just seems like a part of childhood I totally
missed out on.'' More practical collectors suggest otherwise. As
one said, ``Lunch boxes are super durable and really reflect our
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   HELLO KITTY/JAPANESE ANIME
</P>
<P>
   The kitty character just won't disappear. Her more serious
sisters (Princess Mononoko and countless others) may be bought as
kitsch now but may be keepers for later. As one 19-year-old Kitty
collector from Austin, Texas explained, ``Anime is the future of
animation, and I think it will change a lot over the next 20 years.
In the future people will be really interested to see how it all
started, so I find comic books or things on the Internet that I can
buy and keep.''
</P>
<P>
   HOT IN THE FUTURE: Manolo Blahniks
</P>
<P>
   These high-priced high heels seem to be selling like they were
already in limited supply. Women gush about how gorgeous they are
and will look for any excuse to buy just one more pair. But whether
you consider them overpriced or even gaudy, their craftsmanship is
undeniable, and 20 years from now, our bet is that teenaged girls
will scrounge in their grandmas' closets hoping to find a pair of
these shoes, even if they don't fit.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR
</P>
<P>
   Two-way pagers
</P>
<P>
   Piper Perabo (actress)
</P>
<P>
   Rimless sunglasses
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
