<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-POLITICS-680&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNING LABOR PARTY AGAIN TARGET OF INFORMATION LEAKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For the second time this week, a damaging memo from
Prime Minister Tony Blair's inner circle has been leaked to major
newspapers and caused acute embarrassment to his government as it
struggles to keep its once-high popular appeal from continuing its
present swoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current situation is serious,'' said the confidential
message published Wednesday and written by Philip Gould, the
government's pollster. ``The New Labor brand has been badly
contaminated. It is the object of constant criticism and, even
worse, ridicule.''
</P>
<P>
   The note echoed many of the concerns raised in a secret memo
written by Blair that found its way into newspapers Monday. That
message, composed on the prime minister's own computer, reflected
his anxiety that New Labor, as he calls the party he recast from
its old socialist model, was losing touch with ordinary voters and
was failing to persuade them that it shared their worries over
crime, the family, defense and patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   The first leak caused distress at 10 Downing St. because it
portrayed Blair as a politician consumed with short-term popularity
gains rather than as a reformer with a long-range vision, the image
he and his handlers like to put forward.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's disclosure upset Labor strategists because of its
timing, coming right after Gordon Brown, the chancellor of the
exchequer, announced a $65 billion cash injection into public
services intended to put the Conservatives on the defensive as
attention focuses on the national election expected next year.
Newspapers changed their front pages late Tuesday night to
accommodate the leaked story and subordinated the coverage of the
new investments, Labor's first good news in months.
</P>
<P>
   In his own leaked message, dated April 29, Blair complained that
the government was perceived as weak on crime, asylum seekers,
defense and family issues. ``It is bizarre that any government I
head should be seen as anti-family,'' said the prime minister,
whose wife, Cherie, was eight months pregnant at the time with the
couple's fourth child.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government _ and this even applies to me _ are somehow out
of touch with gut British instincts,''he wrote. He called for a
series of tough ``eye-catching initiatives,'' concluding, ``I
should be personally associated with as much of this as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould's memo, written in May, said: ``The government has been
drifting and growing almost monthly weaker and more diffuse. Above
all else, I have a sense of a government which started with great
strength but has seen that strength ebb away and erode as the
months and years have passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair has asked Sir Richard Wilson, the Cabinet secretary, to
try to find the source of the leaks. Scotland Yard detectives can
be called in if a serious suspect emerges, but past investigations
of this kind have proved fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the memos were given to the chief political
correspondents of The Times of London, a major broadsheet, and The
Sun, the best-selling daily tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Blair government has been dogged by six other leaks in the
past three months. They ranged from an internal note from Britain's
ambassador to Japan to Foreign Secretary Robin Cook about Britain
and European monetary union to a request from Blair to his staff
researchers for ``killer facts'' he could use to defeat the
Conservative leader, William Hague, in the weekly Prime Minister's
Questions debate in parliament. They also included two other Philip
Gould strategy warnings about Labor's losing ground to the Tories
on populist issues like law and order and the handling of asylum
seekers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   All the leaks have benefited the Conservatives, and Labor
officials accused the party of being behind the disclosures. But
the Conservatives' chairman, Michael Ancram, said he believed they
were being orchestrated by dissidents within the government. ``This
latest leak is a further indication of the bitter internal war that
is raging in the heart of the Labor government,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the past months, Blair has seen the 20-point lead his
government steadily held over the Conservatives since coming to
power in 1997 fade to single digits. The most recent canvas, an ICM
poll published in The Guardian newspaper on Tuesday, showed Labor
only seven points ahead of the Tories, and Gould's memo predicted
it could soon go down to five.
</P>
<P>
   While those figures are worrisome to the government in light of
how recently they had been much more favorable, they still reflect
a higher popularity rating for the Blair government than any
British government has ever recorded after three years in office.
Labor gained a majority of 179 seats in parliament in the May 1997
election, and its current poll numbers would still translate into a
comfortable majority of 127.
</P>
<P>
   Gould, 50, is one member of the five-man group associated with
the creation of New Labor that also includes Blair; Brown; Peter
Mandelson, now the Northern Ireland secretary; and Alastair
Campbell, the prime minister's chief spokesman. He is a former
advertising man who was brought into the party in 1985 by
Mandelson, then the communications director, to equip it with
modern marketing and media techniques and give it a brand
identification that would be acceptable to the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   He regularly tracks attitudes through his focus groups that aim
to find out what people think in greater depth than opinion polls
do. He distills their comments into the phrases used to guide
strategists in coming up with policies that respond to public mood.
Critics of New Labor have complained that this approach favors
image over substance, and that the public has consequently lost
faith in the party as one without any convictions of its own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
