<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-CRITIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WEAPONS INSPECTOR BECOMES A CRUSADER FOR ENDING IRAQ
SANCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN WECHSLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELMAR, N.Y. _ It has been more than two years since Scott
Ritter walked away from his job as chief of a U.N. weapons
inspection team in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left, he spent a good part of a decade in that
country, sometimes standing toe-to-toe with angry high-ranking
Iraqi army officers refusing to show him what he wanted to see,
sometimes with automatic rifles pointed at him, held by a shaky
Iraqi soldier with his finger on the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 39-year-old former Marine is worlds away from that
life. Now actively campaigning against sanctions because he
believes Iraq is no longer a threat, Ritter recently moved his
family from Hastings-on-Hudson in suburban New York to a two-story
colonial in the Albany suburb of Delmar. There, he hopes to put
down roots for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest decision he's recently faced was what color to paint
the living-room wall (they settled on ``ripe-corn yellow,'' which
reminded his Georgian wife Marina of her East European home). On
Saturday, he spent the evening with friends to celebrate his
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   But two years after he left Iraq, Ritter is poised to go back.
This time, it will be with the blessing of the Iraqi government.
Though Ritter was once accused by Iraq of spying _ ``falsifying
facts'' and ``inventing lies,'' the Iraqis said _ he is now welcome
there, as his mission has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of looking for hidden weapons, Ritter wants to show the
world (and the United States in particular) that the United Nations
sanctions against Iraq are doing much harm and little good.
</P>
<P>
   The trade blockade, he says, has caused the death of 1.5 million
Iraqi citizens and done nothing to bring an end to Saddam Hussein's
reign. Ritter hopes to film a documentary in Iraq showing that,
from a military perspective, the country no longer has the
technology to make weapons of mass destruction and, therefor, is no
longer a threat to anyone but its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think sanctions are a horrible tool,'' said
Ritter, author of ``Endgame: Solving the Iraq Problem Once and For
All,'' and a frequent speaker on college campuses and on National
Public Radio. ``I don't think my country should be carrying out a
policy that kills 500,000 children (from malnutrition and lack of
medical care). And that's what we're doing today.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his background, Ritter seems like the last person who
would be pushing for an end to the sanctions that have crippled
this Middle Eastern country.
</P>
<P>
   The product of a military family, he spent his childhood moving
from Michigan to Hawaii to Turkey to Germany. After graduating from
Franklin and Marshall College in Lancaster, Pa., he joined the
Marines and eventually became a weapons inspector in the Soviet
Union, where he also met his wife.
</P>
<P>
   When Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990, Ritter went to Saudi Arabia to
help determine where Iraq was hiding its SCUD missiles. His team of
Marines had no luck finding the elusive weapons, but that didn't
keep the U.N. from hiring Ritter, at war's end, to lead a weapons
inspection team specializing in concealment.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be an easy job. One time, when Ritter and his team
drove through a checkpoint to inspect a Baghdad facility, a jittery
Iraqi soldier panicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He jumped out, cocked his weapon and pointed it at me,''
Ritter recalled. ``The only thing that saved me was an Iraqi
colonel who jumped out and stood in front of me. I owe my life to
that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But spending up to 220 days in Iraq each year gave Ritter a
perspective he could not get from his U.N. office in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``You realize they're human beings,'' he said. ``Iraqis are
wonderful people. They have a great culture and a lot of history.
Unfortunately, they're ruled by a brutal dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Ritter says his inspections revealed evidence
that Iraq had made both chemical and biological weapons before the
Gulf War. But the weapons themselves were ruined, destroyed either
during the war or by the Iraqis themselves when it was clear they
were losing.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, Ritter said he has found no viable weapons, which is
not to say the Iraqis haven't tried to get some. It was also clear,
Ritter said, that weapons inspectors were being used by the CIA and
the military to get information about Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter left his job Aug. 26, 1998. In December, Iraq threw all
arms inspectors out of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
