 ART ADV.: Photos with OIL-SQUEEZE and CHURCHES-WOMEN, and a photo
and graphic with DEADLY-MOSQUITO are being transmitted to NYT Photo
Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHURCHES-WOMEN (Undated) _ The AME church has selected its first
female bishop ever, Vashti McKenzie of Baltimore. But women in many
faiths still face a ``stained glass ceiling'' -- limits to how high
they can climb the church heirarchy. By Michael Paulson. 1490
words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   DEADLY-MOSQUITO (Stratham, N.H.) _ As epidemiologists all over
the country look anxiously forward to high summer _ when the
deadly, incurable West Nile Virus is likely to strike again via
mosquitos _ scattershot checking methods are the only methods
around. By Ellen Barry. 1370 words. PHOTO; GRAPHIC: 25 picas x 5.5
inches, ``West Nile virus.''
</P>
<P>
   ROMANIAN-ADOPTEE (Burlington, Vt.) _ Michael Stamatis was born
in Romania and was adopted by a Vermont couple. Now 17, he is
accused of sexual assault and is being prosecuted as an adult.
Outraged Romanian officials warn Vermont that the case could affect
American adoption of Romanian children. By Adam Pertman. 1500
words. (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) -- Despite what appears to be a
growing trend to reduce the wall that separates church and state,
American Jews remain staunchly opposed to any mixing of religion
and public life. By Michael Paulson. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN-COLUMN (San Francisco) -- For Ray Scherer, journalism
mattered, not star power. By Martin F. Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: David Nyhan and Derrick Jackson are writing on local
topics; their columns will not move.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-JOB (Agawam, Mass.) _ It's quite a summer job for college
student Nicole DiDomenico: Five times a day, five or six days a
week, she'll portray either Sylvester the cat or Foghorn Leghorn,
dancing and prancing in a heavy, oversize costume through a
25-minute performance at Six Flags New England. By Nathan Cobb.
1120 words.
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) -- Why is Applebee's being fricasseed
these days? By Alex Beam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-NBC-REALITY (Pasadena, Calif.) -- Why did NBC miss the boat
on reality programming? By Don Aucoin.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Movieline supplies 100 reasons as
proof positive that Hollywood types are as wacky as a bag o' cats.
By Renee Graham.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD (d) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-COLUMN (San Francisco) --The city by the bay is a food town
extraordinaire, fueled by the ever-ready supply of California's
bounty. By Alison Arnett. 1290 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THOMSON-SETTLE (Boston) _ A little-known unit of Thomson
Financial processes about half the world's stock trades. And it's
at the center of a push to use the Web to complete trades faster _
in one day instead of three _ by 2002. By Beth Healy. 970 words.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-SQUEEZE (Undated) _ As trucking and airfreight carriers pass
higher fuel costs on to customers through surcharges, economists
say higher oil prices may soon begin seeping into the cost of
everything from a cell phone to a box of golf balls. By Kimberly
Blanton. 1600 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Fund companies are rolling out
brand-new technology funds. Why? Because, as Willie Sutton once
said of banks, ``That's where the money is.'' By Steven Syre and
Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCE-HOOKER (Undated) _ Investor has a problem: too many
funds. By Kenneth Hooker.
</P>
