<SLUG> BC-CIR-MARBLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNUCKLING DOWN IN THE WORLD OF MARBLES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va., Md., N.J.)  (Circuits)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marvin George plays for fair.
</P>
<P>
   George, a soft-spoken postal worker from Bridgeport, W.Va.,
reasons that the youth of West Virginia would be well served if
they played more marbles and if their parents and teachers held
more marble tournaments. A dozen years ago, when his daughter won a
local tournament, he began to talk teachers and principals into
sponsoring local events. As executive director of the West Virginia
Marble Shooters Association, he now runs two statewide tournaments,
one for children 14 and under and one for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't play for keeps in our tournament,'' George said. ``We
provide the marbles to our kids and we play for points.'' The
winners get scholarships up to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   George's marble site, www.marbles.net, gives the rules of
Ringer, the most popular tournament marbles game, and leads to his
two tournaments and a third one in Maryland. The Mountaineer
Marbles Tournament, for children only, was held last week in
Beckley, W.Va. George has sponsored eventual champions in the
National Marbles Tournament (www.blocksite.com/wildwood), a
77-year-old event held in Wildwood, N.J., each Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia was the center of U.S. marble making during this
country's golden age of marbles, roughly 1920 to 1960. Those days
are gone. Next door to George's town, in Clarksburg, the police
routinely shoo away or arrest entrepreneurs and collectors who try
to sneak onto the torn-up former factory floor of the Akro Agate
Co., looking in old drainpipes and digging around the grounds for
corkscrews and Popeyes and sparklers and fluorescents (from uranium
salts) and other rare marble varieties. Akro Agate closed in 1951
and the building was razed three years ago. Asia and Mexico have
taken over machine-made marbles, and today there are only a handful
of U.S. marble companies.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer children play marbles today, even in West Virginia, than
during the golden age, George acknowledged. ``The experts say it's
because of television and Little League and different organized
sports,'' he said. ``It's my belief it's because adults don't want
to organize tournaments anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But marbles have had a curious resurgence caused in part by the
Internet. Colorful Web sites have spurred interest in marble
collecting, and the Internet is full of advertisements. The
collecting interest, in turn, has led to specialty marble making
and to a pickup in organized marble tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   The two worlds of marbles, playing and collecting, are both
represented at MarbleCollecting.com (www.blocksite.com), whose
operator, Robert Block, writes about marbles and holds online
marble auctions. Its reference section includes lists and links to
rules for different games, major tournaments, a Frequently Asked
Questions page with the history of marbles, a bibliography and an
archive of articles from the Marble Mania newsletter. There are
sections on marble auctions, shows, local clubs, bulletin boards
and membership information for the Marble Collectors Society of
America.
</P>
<P>
   On the site, you learn that marbles have been found in Egyptian
tombs and North American Indian mounds, and that William Blake
painted three boys playing marbles for his poem ``The Schoolboy.''
You can also learn how to make a marble by hand, which, the site
says, is now being done by 50 U.S. artisans.
</P>
<P>
   The sites reveal marbles' fascinating contributions to the
American language. Steelies. Cat's eyes. Aggies. No histing. No
hunching, either. Playing for keeps and playing for fair. Slipses.
And remember to knuckle down. Besides Akro Agate's varieties, there
are the classics made by Marble King of Peyden City, W.Va. _
Bumblebees and Wasps and Rainbows and Spider-Men and Tigers and
Green Hornets. Not to mention Swirls, Peerless Patches, Christmas
Trees and Golden Rebels by Peltier Glass Co. of Ottawa, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   George isn't particularly interested in promoting marble dealers
or marble shows at his tournaments, although he is grateful to them
for promoting interest in the game. ``The two worlds don't really
mix,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids, especially the elementary school kids, they need to know
about winning and losing and what it's like to lose, and what it's
like to practice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
