<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLER-RELEASED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGE CRITICIZES BONUS PROGRAM FOR CUSTOMS AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal judge has knocked more than two years
off a drug smuggler's sentence and sent him home to Australia
because U.S. customs agents who worked on his case in San Francisco
got cash bonuses from the government for drug seizures.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker first denounced the bonus
program in a 1998 ruling, saying it created ``perverse law
enforcement incentives'' for unreasonable searches and detentions.
</P>
<P>
   In the new ruling, made public Tuesday, Walker was particularly
concerned that the program had not been disclosed to Michael Wayne
Sanderson's attorney until after his trial and conviction in
December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That information ``would have been another arrow in (the
defense's) quiver during plea negotiations'' and for trying to
discredit the agents' testimony, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which still exists, offers small cash awards, in
the neighborhood of $100 to $200, to customs inspectors for
``superior achievement'' in enforcement activity, including drug
seizures.
</P>
<P>
   The Customs Service had no immediate comment on Walker's ruling,
but has previously described its program as performance incentives,
not bounty-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   The program received a vote of confidence last week from the
U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals, which denied a new trial to two
men convicted in another San Francisco smuggling case. The court
said the Customs Service incentive program, which was not disclosed
to the defense until after trial, was ``a system of rewards for
legitimate and diversified job performance and not a payment for
testimony,'' although some of the awards appeared to be based on
prosecutions that ended in convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson, described by Walker as a low-level participant with
no previous criminal record, faced a sentence of 6 1/2 to eight
years under federal guidelines. Instead, the judge sentenced him to
four years and three months, the time he had already spent behind
bars, and freed him to return to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 12 customs employees who testified for the prosecution,
Walker said, eight had received bonuses for drug interception,
including two who were rewarded for their work on Sanderson's case.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said he wasn't determining that disclosure of their role
would have led the jury to acquit Sanderson, only that concealment
had subverted the defense position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
