u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     07-19 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB PRODUCT IMAGES CAN LIE LIKE A RUG 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ours is a family besotted with catalogs. But don't get me wrong.
We welcome the dozens of catalogs _ J.Jill, Pottery Barn Kids,
French Country Living, House and Home, you name it _ that land in
our mailbox every day. In fact, one of us, who shall remain
unnamed, takes so much pleasure in browsing catalogs that he makes
a point of rummaging through the recycling bins at the post office
for discarded catalogs that the direct marketers failed to send us
for some reason.
</P>
<P>
   But we seldom actually order from catalogs because we know that
pictures can, if not lie exactly, then pleasantly distort. On the
rare occasions that I break down and buy something from a catalog
that is not a tried and true piece of clothing or cookware, I am
invariably disappointed, usually by its quality.
</P>
<P>
   So more often than not, we simply covet.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I share a special longing for rugs. We own very
few because we know a good rug when we see it, which invariably
means we can't afford it. But this past spring we decided to break
down and buy an area rug to cover a large section of our living
room floor.
</P>
<P>
   The rugs we found in the pages of our catalogs were certainly
enticing.
</P>
<P>
   But our distrust of the pictures and prices sent us into actual
rug stores. We grew depressed as we made our way through the racks
of hanging rugs because we couldn't afford the lovely hand-hooked
ones and we didn't want the ones made of synthetic fibers.
</P>
<P>
   Then one evening, inspiration struck. ``You know, I've seen some
beautiful rugs up on the Web,'' my husband said in a casual, steady
tone.
</P>
<P>
   Eureka!
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, I went straight to the computer. Rug
merchants, it turns out _ perhaps to no one's surprise but my own _
have taken their wares to the Web with a vengeance. I spent an hour
clicking my way from area rug to area rug, Web site to Web site. I
found every imaginable size, material, pattern and motif for sale
at sites like Area Rugs Unlimited (www.arearugsltd.com) and Area
Rugs For Less.com (arearugsforless.com).
</P>
<P>
   By that evening, I had collected bookmarks for about a dozen
rugs, and I showed them to my husband. One of them, the Retro-Gold
rug from the Vintage collection at AreaFloorRugs.com
(areafloorrugs.com), caught his eye. Its squares of muted old-world
golds, rusts and blues would be a perfect complement to our newly
upholstered couch. The size was perfect. The site told us that we
were getting a $675 rug for $385. I ordered it.
</P>
<P>
   I was thrilled with my smart purchase. I struck up a friendly
e-mail exchange with Paul, a customer service agent at
AreaFloorRugs.com. Every time I sent him an e-mail message, Paul
responded at once. We were headed for vacation and needed to time
the shipping of the rug so it didn't arrive while we were away, and
Paul went out of his way to accommodate the request. If he was a
robot, he was one of the more impressive feats to come out of
automated customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Paul's diligence, the rug arrived according to plan a
few weeks later. We hauled it up the stairs, ripped through the
heavy plastic wrapping and unrolled it onto the waiting floor.
</P>
<P>
   What we experienced next is best described as consumer shock.
Instead of the subtle hues we anticipated, the colors were closer
to neon. A clown lying on our floor would call less attention to
himself . The loud colors were only accentuated by the rug's
glossy, plasticine look and feel, which was not unlike Astroturf.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Kmart special,'' my husband said, crestfallen.
</P>
<P>
   I was angry, but not with AreaFloorRugs.com. After all, the site
had faithfully described the rug as being of ``super heavy weight,
high pile, 100% Continuous-filament, Delustered, Velvet-Set
polypropylene to provide years of durable splendor.'' If I had seen
the word ``polypropylene'' buried in the description, I was too
seduced by the other words to take much notice. And blame lay with
no one but myself for failing to decode the phrases ``natural
luster'' and ``quaint antique charm.'' AreaFloorRugs.com should
give that wordsmith a raise.
</P>
<P>
   I was angry with myself. I castigated myself for thinking that a
digital photograph reproduced on my old computer monitor would be
true to the real thing. As anyone who has been around computers for
a few years can tell you, colors vary from one computer to the
next, as monitors are not calibrated to the same schemes. I knew
this. My husband knew this. Why had the healthy skepticism we held
for the catalogs failed to kick in when we turned to the Web?
</P>
<P>
   I am not alone when it comes to getting something slightly (or
very) different from what I think I have purchased online. One
friend recently used an online agency to rent a villa in France,
only to arrive and find that the house lacked such basics as a
telephone line. And the husband of a colleague told me his story of
ordering what he thought was a side table for his office. Instead,
he ended up with a miniature version of what he thought he had
bought. Still, he kept it. (``It's a designer table, very nice,''
he explained, ``but only 10 inches tall.'')
</P>
<P>
   But that rug had to go back.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, in the meantime, was sending me solicitous e-mail notes.
Had the rug arrived? Was I happy with it?
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of days, I was too mortified to respond. I wanted
to spare his feelings. After all he had done to shepherd my order
along, the rug seemed as much his as mine. When I finally
responded, I chose my words carefully: ``The rug arrived. It is a
bit disappointing, not what we had envisioned from the photo we saw
online.'' I refrained from asking him if he had any idea how
hideous this object was. Instead, I inquired politely about the
return policy.
</P>
<P>
   Paul wrote back immediately, of course. He was disappointed by
our disappointment. But he minced no words about the return policy.
Yes, we could return it, but we would have to pack it up ourselves
and pay for the shipping. We would also be charged a restocking fee
of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The work that would be required to send back the rug was
daunting. I let it slip and grew distracted by other things. We
decided to live with the rug, partly because we knew we'd never
find the time to return it, partly because we knew it was an object
lesson for us about the perils of purchasing items sight unseen on
the Net, where it is easy to be completely deceived about scale,
color and texture.
</P>
<P>
   Now, every time we open our front door we are greeted by the
sight of our Internet purchase.
</P>
<P>
   But we've grown used to it. I'm even beginning to like it, to
appreciate its finer qualities. When our elderly cat loses her
lunch on the rug, for instance, it's like cleaning Teflon. And
we've learned our lesson, a lesson that has blurred some
distinctions. When I told my husband the other day that I planned
to write about the rug, he responded, ``Didn't we buy that from a
catalog?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
