<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6771 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX     07-19 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENTED ARTISTS, UGLY BELIEFS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I have to get myself up and going in the morning, I might
listen to Roxy Music, Django Reinhardt, the Tractors, Graham
Parker, Monster Magnet or any number of others.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the upsides to being single: There's nobody to
complain.
</P>
<P>
   So the other morning I'm in an Eminem mood; don't know why, just
am. I take out his first CD, pop it in, and it suddenly hits me:
Should I be listening to this?
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Detroit rapper is catching a lot of flak
(justified, in my mind) for his new CD, ``The Marshall Mathers
LP,'' which contains numerous derogatory references to homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   With my hair still wet from the shower and a lunch to be packed,
7:30 a.m. is probably not the best time to be debating my
foreseeable future with young Mr. Eminem. Heck, I can hardly
remember my name for the first hour I'm awake.
</P>
<P>
   But the question remains: At what point are a performer's lyrics
so opposite to what a fan believes that the fan decides to quit
listening? How about what a performer says in interviews or does in
private life?
</P>
<P>
   It's a quandary. After all, buying musicianss CDs and/or going
to see them in concert is, in a sense, endorsing what they say and
subsidizing their lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   I'm helping, in small ways, to help Bono pay for that mansion,
to enable Art Alexakis enjoy his hobbies and plan for retirement,
and to maintain the upkeep of the Supersuckers' equipment. And so
on. And so are you, if you buy CDs by U2 or Everclear or the
'suckers or pay to see them in concert.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's a real easy call. I don't, for example, buy CDs
by white-supremacist bands.
</P>
<P>
   But far more often, the line is fuzzy.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Clapton, Elvis Costello and Motorhead leader Lemmy have all
made dumb remarks in the past: Clapton about immigrants coming to
England, Costello about Ray Charles, and Lemmy about the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   You might assume that Clapton and Costello are racist and that
Lemmy was in denial about the true scope of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean I throw out my CDs by these guys? Clapton and
Costello have both apologized for their remarks, and both said they
were drunk when they made them.
</P>
<P>
   And Lemmy sounded more poorly educated and naive than
anti-Semitic in his recent interview with ``Q'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Are remarks by well-known artists just blips on the radar screen
or revealing insights into what they really believe? Does it cast a
negative light on all their music?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not defending any of the dumb things these guys said, but am
I, on a certain level, an apologist? I still enjoy the music these
guys make. I can't say that their actions and words make their
music irrelevant to me.
</P>
<P>
   And consider this: What if, tomorrow, Eminem met with gay
leaders, realized how horrible some of his lyrics are, and then
apologized profusely and promised never to perform the offending
songs again? And kept his word.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long shot, but stranger things have happened.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder about this a lot these days _ not as a journalist, but
as a fan. To me, Eminem is very, very good at what he does: His
delivery and lyrics are among the best in hip-hop, immediately
identifiable and among the most popular. He's not handling stardom
well in some ways, and he's got some growing up to do, but he is
talented.
</P>
<P>
   Does that matter, given some of the hateful things he says?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure. And I wonder what other people say about this,
where they draw the line. At what point do people stop buying an
artist's music because it is offensive?
</P>
<P>
   That recent morning I changed my mind and listened to Django
instead of Eminem. For whatever reason, standing there in my living
room, hair still wet, lunch still unpacked, I wanted to hear
something else. Maybe it just had to do with a desire to hear some
great, swinging jazz guitar playing instead of some hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe it didn't. I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
