<HEADER>
A6773 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-AMERICANRHAPSODY-REVI     07-19 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICANRHAPSODY-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BOOK MAKES WONDERFUL KINDLING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JEFF GUINN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``American Rhapsody'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Joe Eszterhas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Squalid fiction/nonfiction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $25.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``American Rhapsody'' makes literary history. Since the first
prehistoric man or woman scratched graffiti on cave walls, nobody
anywhere has written a worse, more disgusting book than this
prurient garbage by screenwriter/novelist Joe Eszterhas.
</P>
<P>
   It's not actually that bad. It's worse. But my vocabulary fails
me.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, ``American Rhapsody'' is Eszterhas' take on Bill
Clinton, Monica Lewinsky, Sharon Stone, Richard Nixon and other
high-profile representatives of an era that, to put it charitably,
probably will not be looked upon with great admiration by our
descendants. In a whiny ``Author's Note'' before the book's assault
begins, Eszterhas explains that he wrote ``American Rhapsody'' as a
reflection ``about a generation, my generation, which, in some
ways, even though it was entrenched in power, creeping up on sixty,
was still struggling to find itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas says his own fame, earned by writing scripts for
``Showgirls,'' ``Jade'' and ``Basic Instinct'' _ the last of which
included the erotically charged scene in which Sharon Stone crossed
her legs and instantly became a media sensation _ frazzled him to
the point where he simply had to take time off to rediscover
himself. His vacation coincided with the Lewinsky scandal. Watching
it all on TV and reading the books about it, Eszterhas decided that
he and Bill Clinton probably had a lot in common, including
overactive libidos and fond memories of drugs. So Eszterhas wanted
to write a book that told the whole sordid story _ about Bill
Clinton, about Monica Lewinsky and about who we modern-day
Americans have become.
</P>
<P>
   But how to do it? Well, Eszterhas' solution is this: Ninety-five
percent of ``American Rhapsody's'' 432 pages are in a normal
typeface. This signals, he says, writing that is ``sometimes
interpretive, but based on well-researched facts.'' Which
translates as, ``I'm making most of it up, but within the bounds of
libel laws.'' Occasionally, there are chapters in bold type, which
offer Bill Clinton or Lewinsky or Bob Dole or Al Gore or Hillary
Clinton scatalogically ruminating on their lives. These, Eszterhas
claims, are written by a nasty imp inside the author: ``The writing
is fictional and his,'' he writes, ``starting with well-researched
facts but blasted through and transformed by his hallucinatory
dreams.'' Translation: really obscene made-up stuff that, presented
even marginally as fact, could get Eszterhas sued.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a little fact, lots of projections on who did and
said what and why, and occasional scenes and ruminations that are
so disgusting and far-fetched that only the mindlessly sex-obsessed
will read them completely (i.e., the same folks who think
``Showgirls'' was quality entertainment).
</P>
<P>
   The last chapter of ``American Rhapsody'' is the pornographic
nadir of the book: a happy soliloquy from Bill Clinton's, well,
you-know-what. I wish I were making this up.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the ``what'' of ``American Rhapsody.'' You've been
warned, so read it at your own peril.
</P>
<P>
   But now for the ``why,'' which is harder to pin down.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf is a reputable publisher, much admired in
literary circles. But it is also an imprint of Random House, which
is part of a megamedia conglomerate, and profit-seeking naturally
dictates what it prints and distributes. ``American Rhapsody'' is
trash, but why it is published trash is sadly simple: The publisher
believes that lots of people will buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they will. But ``American Rhapsody'' isn't just trash
fiction, it is a gruesome assault on common sense. It takes
voyeurism to an extreme level in the name of ``understanding'' who
we are. Yeah, and Larry Flynt publishes ``Hustler'' magazine to
protect Americans' First Amendment rights. .MDBU/.MDNM/ (Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
