r l BC-SILENT-RETREATS-TEX     07-19 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILENT-RETREATS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETREATS USE SILENCE TO EMPHASIZE THAT STILL, SMALL VOICE FROM
WITHIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JAIME JORDAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In a high-tech, high-volume world, finding
quiet time away from the hustle and bustle can be a chore.
</P>
<P>
   But more and more spiritual leaders are urging their
parishioners to seek out silence, whether in spiritual retreats or
simply in a quiet place in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Jesus) said, `Come away with me to a quiet place,' I
think that's one of the key invitations to silence,'' said the Rev.
Mark Cannaday, rector at St. Alban's Episcopal Church in Arlington,
Texas. ``Jesus frequently went away to pray, and that's motive for
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept of speaking to God through silence may seem
contradictory at first, Cannaday said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Silence speaks.' It seems almost nonsense, but of course it
isn't, because silence has a different voice. It's still and it's
small,'' he said. ``It refers back to that experience that Elijah
had in the Old Testament, that God doesn't speak in the whirlwind
or in the storm. Mostly God speaks in that still, small voice that
comes in silence, that comes while I, or we as a group, are
silent.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the power of silence.
</P>
<P>
   And so, as the pace of the world picks up, more clergy are
urging parishioners to seek God not only in churches, but also to
participate in retreats during which they seek to empty themselves
in the presence of God and wait in silence for a word from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our society, it's just so important to stop,'' said Vicky
Caudell, who schedules silent retreats at the Mount Carmel Center
for Spirituality in Dallas. ``As long as we're standing around and
we're doing the talking to God, he can't get through. We have to
slow down and get silent so he can talk to our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the premise for silent spiritual retreats, said Sister
Dorothy Powers, director of children's catechesis at the Catholic
Center in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The basic format, although it varies depending on the retreat
center, is set up so that lay people meet with a retreat leader for
30 minutes to an hour a day to help them reflect on their life and
where God is in their life. The retreat leader gives the lay people
Scripture to reflect upon as the day is continued in silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, people who go on a silent retreat are at a point in
their lives where they're ready to do some interior spiritual
journeying to deepen their relationship with the Lord to make sense
of their lives,'' Powers said. ``The variety of reasons are as
great as the variety of people who go.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowing down, quieting one's self can be an abrupt change for
many who aren't used to silence, Cannaday said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like being detoxified, I would guess. The truth
is that you have to kind of physically let yourself calm down. It
would be like having a hectic day. Everything has been chaos, so
when you sit down, you're still sort of moving.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mount Carmel Center for Spirituality facilitates that
slowing down as much as possible, Caudell said. Although located in
the southwest corner of Oak Cliff, a Dallas neighborhood, the
monastery occupies 45 secluded acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an oasis of quiet in the midst of Dallas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Retreats can last from one day to eight or more days, Powers
said. They range in price from a free-will offering for a day visit
to a couple of hundred dollars for a week's stay, retreat leaders
say.
</P>
<P>
   And they are becoming more sought out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the hectic pace of life is probably making people more
aware of the need for periods of quiet reflection, just to get your
sanity back,'' Powers said. ``I think there's a spiritual hunger or
thirst in everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Many North Texas worshippers travel as far as Houston, San
Angelo, Mississippi or Louisiana to retreat centers, Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are opportunities close at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Prince of Peace Lutheran Church in Arlington has been putting
the power-of-silence concept into practice for 21/2 years, senior
pastor Tom Schleuter said.
</P>
<P>
   The church started having Friday-evening watch services, which
last from 9 p.m. to 9 the next morning. Some people stay a few
hours; others stay the whole 12. In essence, it is the practice of
being silent and seeking to be in God's presence.
</P>
<P>
   Schleuter said prayer and watching are interchangeable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prayer to me is just a time of just everyday, all-the-time
communication with the Lord,'' he said. ``Some people think I have
to be on my knees, folding my hands, closing my eyes.'' But sitting
quietly in God's presence is also a form of prayer, Schleuter said.
</P>
<P>
   Schleuter said he would recommend silence to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what people find is ... how extremely and
extravagantly loved they are by God, because they are focused on
him and they find that he is ultimately focused on them. He loves
you. That brings everything else in your life into perspective,''
Schleuter said. ``You begin to see your life from God's perspective
instead of, `I can't get control of my life, I'm so busy.' '' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
