<HEADER>
A6776 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     07-19 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIREN CALL OF THE WIRELESS NET 
</HEADLINE>
   By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asking whether you need wireless Internet service for your
handheld computer is like asking about the sound of one hand
clapping. Just trying it out and seeing whether you like it is more
practical. But then, when it comes to shiny new gadgets, I've
always followed the path of buy first, ask questions later.
</P>
<P>
   After testing wireless modems and Internet services for Palm
organizers from both OmniSky and GoAmerica.net, I can see what all
the fuss is about. (Those opting for Microsoft's PocketPC platform
aren't out of the wireless loop either: Cell-phone connectors and
the recently announced wireless service packages from GoAmerica and
Aether Systems provide similar freewheeling possibilities.) I've
used the wireless Web connection for only a couple months, but I am
seriously hooked. I may not need it, but I like it.
</P>
<P>
   Although I live in New York, a major coverage area, I don't work
in sales, and I haven't yet had to buy plane tickets when I was in
a cab on the way to the airport, firing off e-mail messages as I
went. But when I was out and about on a recent Friday night with
the OmniSky modem in tow, I was able to check on the flight of a
friend flying in, keep tabs on the score of the New York Liberty
game, reply to e-mail that had just arrived and check bids on Ebay
auctions. It may seem rather frivolous, but the fact that I didn't
have to go home to my computer but could work these tasks into the
dead spots of my evening saved me time that I could use later for
other nefarious purposes, like reading a book or watching ``Wallace
&AMP; Gromit: The Wrong Trousers'' on DVD.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless service also saved my sanity and let me keep in
touch with my editors when I was cooling my heels in June in the
Manhattan Criminal Court building's jury assembly room, doing my
civic duty. Incorporating the OmniSky product into my daily routine
was similar to working my first Pilot 5000 into my daily life back
in 1996. Once I remembered that I had the darned thing, it became,
for better or worse, an appendage.
</P>
<P>
   Adding an external modem to the Palm is not the only option for
wireless connectivity. Web-enabled cell phones have been around for
months, and Palm Inc. recently announced plans for a software
product called the Palm Mobile Internet Kit. It is supposed to let
Palm users worldwide (with III's or later versions) connect
wirelessly to the Internet using mobile phones or Palm-compatible
modems. The company says the kit should be available later this
year for less than $50.
</P>
<P>
   There is also, of course, the company's Palm VII, which offers
built-in wireless access and streamlined Web content from its own
service plan; users of the Palm mobile kits can enjoy the same
service. For those who already own a Palm organizer or who don't
want to buy a Palm VII, there are a couple of other enticing
options.
</P>
<P>
   OmniSky began offering its wireless modem and Internet service
package to Palm V and Vx owners in May, and its customized modem
module for Handspring Visor devotees is due this fall. GoAmerica
recently revamped its service and offers its own modem and access
package for many types of Palm organizers, including the Palm
Professional, the Palm III series and the Palm V series.
</P>
<P>
   Taking into account the monthly cost and the coverage and
content offered, OmniSky comes out ahead in my book. OmniSky's
Minstrel V modem (made by Novatell) clips neatly to the back of the
slim Palm V organizer. Even though the modem doubles the thickness
of the Palm, the service more than makes up for the added weight of
the modem and antenna with a wealth of wireless features. Users can
check their e-mail on as many as six accounts. They can also browse
more than 1,000 Web sites streamlined for wireless surfing, and
they can explore other sites around the Net as well.
</P>
<P>
   OmniSky, which mainly uses AT&AMP;T's wireless network, is not
available nationwide. It is concentrated around major metropolitan
areas, particularly on the East and West Coasts.
</P>
<P>
   The company suggests that you have 1.4 megabytes of RAM free on
your palmtop before using the OmniSky package, and the Palm V comes
with a total of 2 megabytes. Two megabytes is probably enough for
most people, who probably use only the organizer's standard
functions, even with the OmniSky programs installed. I am one of
those users, though, who insist on toting around a ton of
space-eating Palm shareware programs, along with electronic copies
of documents like the New York City subway map and the Tao Te
Ching. (I like to think of those two as somehow complementing each
other in the realm of daily urban life.)
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy my shareware cravings and need for space, I have been
using a Palm Vx, with its beefy 8 megabytes of RAM. After I
installed OmniSky, I also got a Palm Telnet program from the
PalmGear H.Q. Web site (www.palmgear.com) so I could log in and
read postings from my favorite online community, New York's
technologically old-fashioned but always entertaining Echo bulletin
board
</P>
<P>
   When you sign up for the OmniSky service, the company ships you
the modem and a CD-ROM with all the software you'll need to set
everything up, including the modem driver for the Palm. While you
run the installer program, you'll be asked to configure your POP3
e-mail accounts, including the omnisky.net address that is made
available for you.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The installer program on the CD also provides the Palm with a
huge amount of useful links in stripped-down ``Web clipping'' form,
with the links organized under category headings. These groupings
include Finance (Etrade, Fidelity and others), Travel (Travelocity,
BizTravel, MapBlast and more), News and Sports ( ABCNews, Yahoo,
MSNBC and others), Shopping, Living and Local Events. Once
installed, the software works with your Palm's address book _ it
will pop your e-mail address right into place when you are
composing a message.
</P>
<P>
   GoAmerica's latest product and plan for Palm devices, while not
as versatile as OmniSky's, has many of the same basic features and
links, and it offers owners of older Palm models the same addictive
wireless options. The addition of the modem to a Palm III makes it
a little unwieldy, but navigating the service itself is easy. And
the on-screen graphics displaying the modem's connection progress
are more informative than OmniSky's are.
</P>
<P>
   After you install the software and tap the GoAmerica icon on the
Palm screen, a new screen will pop up with two self-explanatory
icons: Go.Web and Go.Mail. You can also configure existing POP3
mail accounts for the Go.America service.
</P>
<P>
   The modem usually costs $299, but the company is offering $100
off the price if the user will sign a one-year contract. The
service costs $49.95 a month for unlimited use or $9.95 a month for
the first 25 kilobytes of data. Details can be found at
www.goamerica.net.
</P>
<P>
   A GoAmerica module for the Handspring Visor is under
development, and the company also offers a variety of wireless
options for pagers, smart phones and laptops.
</P>
<P>
   The OmniSky modem usually costs $299 as well, but the company is
holding a half-price sale on the device through the end of August
for people who sign six-month contracts for the monthly service.
Unlimited usage is $39.95 per month. OmniSky's unlimited use plan
is cheaper than the unlimited plan offered by Palm for the Palm
VII, which costs $44.99. More information is available at
www.omnisky.com.
</P>
<P>
   The OmniSky installer software is designed for use with Windows
95, 98, 2000 and NT, but I was also able to coax the files onto the
Palm with a Macintosh G3 running Virtual PC 3.0. GoAmerica's
installer CD is also for Windows only.
</P>
<P>
   One quibble I have with the clip-on modems from OmniSky and
GoAmerica is that there's no pass-through port incorporated into
the modem design. That means you can't attach an external keyboard
or other additional hardware device at the same time because the
modem is camped out in the HotSync port. For users who need to
enter a lot of text while maintaining the wireless connection, the
Palm VII has the edge here.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the modem and the monthly service plan from either
company is a bit of an investment, but if you need constant access
to your e-mail or a constant flow of data into your hand, wireless
service is well worth a look, especially if you already own a Palm
device. I found it worth the price for the convenience and
flexibility it offers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know it's a guilty pleasure, but I think my Internal
Rationalization Module will keep those feelings at bay until the
early adopter's Next Big Thing becomes everyone else's Thing to
Have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
