<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6778 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-VISAS20-COX     07-19 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HISPANIC, BUSINESS LEADERS IN TUG-OF-WAR OVER VISAS BILL
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX and MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hispanic leaders and high-tech employers both
called on Congress Wednesday to pass stalled legislation to create
more visas for highly skilled foreign workers. But that's where the
agreement ended.
</P>
<P>
   Technology executives, saying they are desperate for workers,
want a ``clean'' bill that does just one thing: expand the H-1B
visa program to allow more computer-savvy workers into this country
for up to six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``An enormous number of jobs are going begging in the United
States,'' said William Archey, president of the American
Electronics Association, a trade group. ``There is an extraordinary
need for the high-tech industry to have an increase in the H-1B
visa program.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a separate press conference on Capitol Hill, a coalition
of groups involved with Latin American immigration issues said
Congress should approve H-1B legislation only if it:
</P>
<P>
   _ Allows as many as 2 million undocumented immigrants who have
lived in the U.S. since 1986 to apply for legal residency.
</P>
<P>
   _ Permits immigrants who qualify for visas to remain in this
country while awaiting resolution of their cases.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gives immigrants from El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras and
Haiti treatment equal to that given to Cubans and Nicaraguans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unconscionable that U.S. senators and representatives
would fast-track the H-1B visas without considering other
immigration policies that have been pending for years,'' said
Marisa J. Demeo, regional counsel for the Mexican American Legal
Defense and Educational Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But tech executives said Latin American immigration issues
should be considered separately because the need to hire skilled
workers, such as computer programmers and engineers, is so urgent.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Congress temporarily expanded the H-1B program's
annual cap from 65,000 to 115,000 visas per year. The cap falls to
107,500 in fiscal 2001, which begins Oct. 1, and to 65,000 a year
later. This year, employers used up the entire year's quota in six
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a genuine urgency to the passage of H-1B
legislation,'' said Rhett Dawson, president of the Information
Technology Industry Council. ``The lifeblood of the (technology
industry) is human capital.''
</P>
<P>
   To help industry, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, has been pushing a
bill to boost the annual limit to 200,000. Though passed out of
committee months ago, the Hatch bill still has not been put to a
full Senate vote because of disagreements over amendments.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, a similar bill, sponsored by Rep. David Dreier,
R-Calif., also is languishing amid partisan wrangling over
amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats insist that fairness demands that the immigration
amendments be attached to the H-1B legislation. But critics say
Democrats are trying to force Republicans to vote against Latin
American immigration provisions in order to get political
ammunition for this November's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the issue has become politicized,'' said Harris
Miller, president of the Information Technology Association of
America. ``And we all know it's a political year. We're here to
urge the House and Senate leadership to take the politics out of
this process.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Information Technology Association of America, www.itaa.org
</P>
<P>
   Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund,
www.maldef.org
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail address is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
