<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6780 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      07-19 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT PERFECT, BUT ALMOST REEL ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Pam and Robin, who used to fish
off Bodega Bay, Calif., appreciated the character of Linda, the
other boat captain in ``The Perfect Storm.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``She wasn't Hollywood blonde with a lot of cleavage,'' says
Pam.
</P>
<P>
   Robin nods. ``She even had chapped lips, like someone who spent
real time out on the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   The two friends, who used to be captain and crew when they
fished for salmon, sat watching the summer's big movie adventure
and grabbing for each other's hand and squeezing hard. In that,
they were no different from much of the audience. But their
appreciation was more real than imagined.
</P>
<P>
   They were horrified, delighted and not just a little bit
nostalgic for a life that was so thrilling Pam says she's never
found a job to match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I ever heard any fisherman talk poetically like
Billy (George Clooney) in the movie,'' says Pam, ``but I remember
once going down past Point Reyes, staring at that beautiful
shoreline from the flying bridge and feeling so lucky and thinking
there was no better feeling in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I watched the movie it made me sad that there can't be
more things in life that get a person's adrenaline up like that.''
</P>
<P>
   I think that's why no matter what the critics think of the film,
it hooked so many of us computer-dependent zero-tolerance
dress-down-on-Friday people. This is what some real life people do
when they go to work. They put on worn flannel shirts and get fish
guts under their fingernails and are lucky if they suffer only
chapped lips. Some also die on the job, but there's an edge to the
life that is tantalizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being out there in the ocean is reality,'' says Robin. ``It's
like childbirth. It's very humbling. You are in an environment
where something bigger is in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin and Pam talk about a stomach-wrenching storm that hit them
one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly things just change,'' says Pam. ``The sea can be flat
calm and then turn into total chaos.'' She thinks the waves that
day might have gotten to 15 to 20 feet. Robin says they were big,
though nothing like the Sierra-sized mountains of water in the
movie. Still, she adds, ``When you're in a little boat and out in a
storm, every big wave looks like one of those waves.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam, who was steering, says, ``I actually thought about putting
on my survival gear and yelling to Robin to get her's on, but we
couldn't take a second to stop. It was like a big washing machine
of giant waves, one on top of the other. In a storm like that the
water gets frothy and green, almost luminous.''
</P>
<P>
   They, too, had trouble with the flopper out in rough seas. In
the movie the flopper is that big hunk of metal that looks like an
anchor flailing against the wheel house and which Billy, in a
superhuman move, cuts off with a blow torch while being pitched
around like a bucking bronco.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened with us,'' says Pam, ``is the chain broke that
holds the outrigger pole down which allowed the flopper to swing
loose. It's what you normally count on to give the boat balance,
but in this case it turned into a weapon and could have cut a huge
gouge in the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin had to go out by herself and pull the flopper in.
Normally it took the two of us in a standing still boat in good
weather to maneuver the thing. I have no idea how she did it alone.
She just became very strong. And saved our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently landlocked, Robin is a teacher and raises exotic
garlic. Pam makes arty picture frames out of old earrings and
political buttons. The next boat she's going on is a cruise ship to
Gibraltar.
</P>
<P>
   But when they talk about their fishing days they dimple like
Clooney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't ever want to do it again. Seeing that movie made me
realize how lucky we were to survive,'' says Robin. ``But there is
such excitement and anticipation when you're out there. You never
knew what will happen each day.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam says, ``Not only do you get to be out in nature, but what
you achieve is your own doing, no one else's. That's a good
feeling. But it's a hard way to make a living because there's so
much red tape and restrictions. I'm too chicken to go through a
hurricane for the sake of fish, but I understand going out in nasty
weather because you have a boat payment due.''
</P>
<P>
   They never got badly hurt. They never fell in, except for a
couple of embarrassing mishaps at the dock. They never got rich.
But they were luckier than the friends who never made it back to
port.
</P>
<P>
   They don't call themselves fisherwomen. ``Fisherman is a word
for what you do. It has nothing to do with gender,'' says Robin.
</P>
<P>
   Gentler than most of the critics, they rolled their eyes at only
a couple of movie scenes. ``I don't know about diving into that
kind of a sea to rescue someone with all your clothes on and having
the boat right there to swim back to,'' says Pam.
</P>
<P>
   But they thought the music-to-fish-by was realistic. ``Every
time we stopped the boat and started to fish we played either the
Rolling Stones or Bob Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said we caught more fish with Dylan.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
