<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6782 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-POLITICAL-CONVENT     07-19 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-POLITICAL-CONVENTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF TV'S JUST NOT ENOUGH: CONVENTIONS ON THE NET
</HEADLINE>
 By REBECCA FAIRLEY RANEY c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Political conventions were once smoky back-room affairs. Then
they became television events. Now they have moved to the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally many major news organizations are offering extra
coverage online. But in addition, the major political parties and
independent Web producers are offering novel ways to follow the
conventions online.
</P>
<P>
   Many Internet experts say that at this point in history, the use
of the medium may be like the use of television at conventions in
the 1950s, when networks were still learning what the cameras could
do.
</P>
<P>
   The online experiments with convention coverage are ``kind of
like 3-D glasses at the movies,'' said Larry Purpuro, deputy chief
of staff for the Republican National Committee. ``It's for the fun
of the experiment,'' he said, ``but they're not so fun to use.''
Purpuro is director of the party's e.GOP project, an effort to
apply Web-based technologies to the committee's communications,
fund-raising and organizing activities.
</P>
<P>
   Purpuro said that for party leaders, the Internet meant ``a
tremendous opportunity for us to collect a lot of interest that can
be developed and enhanced post-convention.'' The Republican
convention will be held from July 31 to Aug. 3 in Philadelphia.
After the convention ends, Purpuro said, the party can get in touch
with people who have sent in their e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   For many Web site producers outside the parties, the conventions
present an opportunity to test different methods of telling a story
and tapping the public's interests.
</P>
<P>
   During important speeches, producers at America Online will
offer chats and instant polling to subscribers. The idea is to
provide an outlet for discussion and debate to individuals who are
more interested in politics than their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's other people who are interested in it, not necessarily
the people you live with,'' said Kathleen deLaski, director of
political and government planning for America Online. ``That's the
large part of the audience'' for America Online's political
services, she added.
</P>
<P>
   AOL will produce a chat show every evening for both conventions.
Unlike traditional media outlets, in which editors set the agenda,
AOL will poll its members each day on what the topic of the show
should be.
</P>
<P>
   The service is also offering ``delegate diaries,'' daily reports
from delegates that will describe what the convention is like for
the average delegate and put the procedures of the conventions into
easily understood terms.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dozens of Web sites that plan to offer coverage beyond
traditional news, a common idea is to use the Internet to augment
the programs offered by the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest problems the parties face when organizing
conventions is deciding whom to include on the speaking schedule.
FreedomChannel.com, a nonpartisan site (www.freedomchannel.com),
doesn't face the same time constraints, so it will offer video
clips of prominent political figures who are not scheduled to speak
at the convention. For example, the group is working to arrange a
speech from Jeb Bush, the governor of Florida and a brother of
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people want to speak at the conventions who never get
to the podium,'' said Daniel Manatt, media director of
FreedomChannel.com, which is based in Washington. ``So we want to
offer an unlimited amount of time on our Web site. The whole idea
of the Internet is that it's limitless.''
</P>
<P>
   Video clips of the conventions will not be hard to find on the
Web. Two Internet companies not affiliated with major news
organizations have secured skyboxes at both conventions: AOL and
Pseudo Programs Inc. The skyboxes, which provide overall camera
coverage of the convention floor, are usually reserved for
television networks.
</P>
<P>
   For Pseudo Programs, which has a Web site at www.pseudo.com, the
central feature of the convention coverage will be the use of
360-degree cameras. The cameras show whatever surrounds them, and
the company's presentation online will allow members of the
audience to choose their own views rather than depend on a
perspective chosen by a photographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really giving people the opportunity to sit in the
control box,'' said Jeanne Meyer, senior vice president of Pseudo
Programs. The conventions will give ``a huge illustration of what
we can do,'' she said, ``that we're not just television squeezed on
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The company asked Democratic and Republican groups to nominate a
few members to cover the convention. In keeping with its
audience-driven theme, the company is letting its viewers select
the people who will be sent.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are also planning to use a 360-degree camera to
provide nonstop video coverage on their Web site,
www.dems2000 &QC; .com. Party officials hope that the camera will give
``a free and open perspective'' on their convention, which will run
from Aug. 14 to Aug. 17 in Los Angeles, said Peter Ragone, a
spokesman for the Democratic National Convention Committee. The
Democrats want to offer extensive detail on the Internet about
issues, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you happen to be a person whose chief interest is the
environment,'' he said, ``we have the ability to talk in depth and
in length with the voter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have collected the opinions of some members of the
public online through a so-called interactive platform. By the
deadline earlier this month, 460 people had submitted ideas
electronically, and party officials said some of their ideas might
be included in the party's platform.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua King, vice president of external affairs for
SpeakOut.com, which built the interactive system for the party,
said: ``Is this 460 more people than would have participated
otherwise? Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are offering the public the opportunity to
become ``dot-com delegates'' through their convention site at
www.gopconvention.com. By signing up at the site, the Internet
``delegates'' will be able to see exclusive interviews with
convention participants, receive updates from state delegations by
e-mail, get a convention screen saver and send their opinions about
convention events.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the conventions online may well depend on how
well the parties steer members of their audiences into their
electronic dens at important moments.
</P>
<P>
   Experience has shown that major news articles and splashy events
are the most likely factors to drive the public to political Web
sites. So campaigns and political groups would do well to be
prepared to steer traffic from the convention sites to related Web
sites while the interest is high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to see how well prepared the parties are to catch a
wave,'' said Professor Michael Cornfield, director of the Democracy
Online Project at George Washington University. He said it would be
interesting to see if either party posted Web site addresses _ for
their own convention sites or related sites _ on their stages.
</P>
<P>
   By driving traffic to their own Web sites, Professor Cornfield
said, the parties can build ways to keep in touch with supporters
at a time when voters are interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political scientists will tell you,'' he said, ``that
post-convention bounce really matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
