<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6783 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MDK2-GAME-NYT &LR;      07-19 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MDK2-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING IT UP, AND LAUGHING ABOUT IT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)  (Circuits)  
 By PETER OLAFSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MDK2 made me smile. Not quickly, not broadly, and usually not
for very long, but my reflection in the monitor screen did
occasionally grin back at me for a second or two, and that was
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   It had been years since a game made me smile _ let alone laugh _
with any regularity. I suspect that is a byproduct of the decline
in the late 1990s of the adventure game, the genre best equipped
for pure storytelling and for the exquisite timing that humor
requires. Infocom made me laugh reliably with its text adventures
throughout the 1980s, and its spiritual heir, Legend Entertainment,
made me laugh with its text-and-graphic adventures in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   I have fond memories of trying to get some mundane object from
an uncooperative, monosyllabic sailor in LucasArts' Secret of
Monkey Island. The more I tried, the more he said no. The more he
said no, the more I tried. I could barely stay in my chair for
laughing _ both at myself for my inane persistence and at the game
for responding in such detail.
</P>
<P>
   That was 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In MDK2, the Canadian game developer BioWare, which showed in
1998's Baldur's Gate that the role-playing genre still has a pulse,
demonstrates with a joyful mix of action and whimsy that games can
still find subtle ways to amuse us.
</P>
<P>
   Like Shiny Entertainment's original MDK from 1996, MDK2 is not
conventionally funny. (Indeed, when it tries to be conventionally
funny, as it does in the animations between its 10 levels, it is
the least effective.) Rather, it makes me feel funny, the way I
felt after I had sneaked a couple of sips of my dad's Budweiser
when I was a kid. Around the third level, through the accrual of
minor but telling details, I found MDK2 had kicked me into a kind
of giddy reverie.
</P>
<P>
   That's no mean achievement. Comedy is especially risky in an
action game. To paraphrase John Le Carre's George Smiley: If you
make your enemy look too foolish, you lose the justification for
taking him on.
</P>
<P>
   At the game's start, the victors of MDK have no sooner toasted
their success than they discover that the aliens they thought
vanquished have returned. A mine crawler _ a surface-chewing lawn
mower operating on a planetary scale _ has appeared in Edmonton,
Alberta. (A small in-joke: BioWare is based in Edmonton.) So Kurt
Hectic, hero of the first game, goes back into action, diving from
the orbiting Jim Dandy spacecraft while dodging missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Like its predecessor, MDK2 adopts the over-the-shoulder,
third-person view familiar from the Tomb Raider games. It preserves
the level structure: Corridors link stadium-size chambers,
typically with a locked door at the far end that is opened by
finding and disabling a series of devices. You will still find
subgames that range from directing a tropical fish through pipes to
avoiding flying debris. And you'll undertake the conventional
business of collecting weapons and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But while the pieces will seem familiar, the whole is not quite
conventional. Kurt remains an unlikely hero. In his form-fitting
coil suit and pointed helmet, he looks as though he should be
competing in the Tour de France rather than saving the planet. When
he pops open the threadbare parachute that permits him to glide
through the immense levels, it looks as though someone has pulled
back his suspenders to give them a nasty snap.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the weapons are rather extravagant. One type of grenade
opens a black hole that sucks in everything around it _ especially
useful when a resilient enemy absolutely, positively has to be
removed to someplace else. The enemies do not all behave like
normal, preternaturally aggressive enemies. Some of them appear to
be waving at me. And in all honesty, Kurt didn't so much dive from
the Jim Dandy as fall from it.
</P>
<P>
   The original MDK was an all-Kurt affair. (The K in the title
stands for Kurt.) Here, he handles only every third level, sharing
the spotlight with Max (the M) and Dr. Fluke Hawkins (the D). Max
is a six-limbed, cigar-chomping robotic dog who can operate a jet
pack, fire up to four weapons simultaneously and destroy a
formidable array of scenery.
</P>
<P>
   As you would expect of a scientist with spectacles and a crown
of white hair, Dr. Fluke Hawkins is not much of a fighter. But he
possesses a gift for invention: With found items in each hand, he
can sometimes combine them to create something new. It's a skill
that emphasizes chasing down objects and experimentation and gives
his levels a distinctly adventure-game feeling. For instance, the
hand dryer retrieved from the spaceship lavatory and some pipes
come together as a leaf blower; it sends the giant enemies
occupying the leafy lounge bouncing into the maw of a giant, toothy
plant on loan from ``The Little Shop of Horrors.''
</P>
<P>
   But MDK2 tends to celebrate its humor in small touches, from the
quiet ``ding'' of the machines that recharge Max's jet pack to the
distressed body language of aliens in the sights of Kurt's sniper
scope to the little neon labels that appear above the weapons and
supplies. The enemies you shoot sometime collapse in extravagant
fashion, first spinning around on one foot, as though they are
auditioning for a part in a corny western. And advancing through
one room requires that Kurt take the stage and dance to entertain
aliens in the balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, few of these little scenes are worth more than a
flutter of a comic eyelash. But taken together, they put the player
just slightly off balance _ not so wobbly as to jeopardize MDK2's
premise, but wobbly enough to enjoy it at a new, silly level. At
one point, controlling Max, I stumbled across a wall panel that
looked like a false front. I had Max do what he does best _ shoot
it _ and the wall panel shattered, only to reveal another wall
panel. And behind that one, another.
</P>
<P>
   That went on for about seven layers, but it never became
repetitious. Rather, it made a joke of the repetition, recalling in
tone the curtains and doors in classic cartoons that open to reveal
another portal, and in its comic persistence, that uncooperative
sailor in Monkey Island a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   I had to smile, and I did.
</P>
<P>
   MDK2, published by Interplay; for Windows 95 and 98, and Sega
Dreamcast; $34; for teen-agers and adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
