<HEADER>
A6789 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GOLF-BROPEN0720-BISHE     07-19 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-BROPEN0720-BISHER-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite his best efforts, Montgomerie still not the favored
figure
</P>
<P>
   By Furman Bisherc. 2000 Cox News Service ST. ANDREWS, Scotland -
Poor Colin Montgomerie. He would like so to be popular. To be
greeted with standing ovations by tournament galleries, like a rock
star. Chanting his name. Everybody's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good old Monty,'' they'd say, ``our national idol. Every
Scot's personal hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as ``Mrs. Doubtfire,'' the derisive name pinned on him by
some sarcastic member of the British press. Or as ``Glasgow Fats,''
before he went on a diet and came forth a trim figure. He is no
trencherman as in Lee Westwood, who said, ``I'm a golfer, not an
athlete. I don't need to be super-fit.''
</P>
<P>
   With Monty, it's not so much condition as it is an urge to be a
favored figure. Yet, there are his old-maidish responses to
applause, the lips pursed into more a grimace than a smile. The
quick shift from smile to frown, as at the mention of the name
``Tiger Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   As you have surmised, golf has come home again for another
British Open at the manger of the game, the Old Course at St.
Andrews. Montgomerie was in for his pre-championship news
conference. Third question, no more than three minutes into the
inquisition, when the question came out of the pack, ``Are you
trying to say Tiger is not quite the favorite everyone might
think?''
</P>
<P>
   Monty bristled. There it was again, Tiger, Tiger, Tiger. ``First
American question, American question about Tiger Woods,'' voice
dripping with sarcasm. ``I never said he wasn't experienced, for
God's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a Scot, you'd suspect that Montgomerie would look upon St.
Andrews as home ground, even with all the liberties the Royal &AMP;
Ancient has taken with this hallowed old relic. New and more severe
bunkers. ``They outdid themselves on the bunkers,'' Jack Nicklaus
said. ``They are very, very different.''
</P>
<P>
   The length has been stretched out, not that in this warm, quiet
weather and interstate fairways any professional should feel
constricted. ``Everybody will be a long hitter here,'' Nick Faldo
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a very, very different Open,'' Nicklaus said.
</P>
<P>
   After Montgomerie came away from being ``pipped'' again, as they
say it over here, at Loch Lomond, he was asked about the Open. ``I
can hardly wait to play the great old course again,'' he said in
the driest of tones. Never would you have expected Colin
Montgomerie not to show proper respect for the course held highest
in world esteem, guarded on the left by grouty old structures and
on the right by St. Andrews Bay.
</P>
<P>
   A flash peek at his record in Opens played here and you find
incriminating evidence. In 1990, he finished 48th. In 1995, he
never finished. Two rounds of 75, missed the cut and went home.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie has tried so hard to be liked in the United States.
He'll even say such a thing as, ``The American Open is my favorite
tournament. It is set up the way a major championship should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Heke nothing we've ever seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees the Old Course set up in such a way as to protect its
chastity. ``The winner will be someone who does not attack every
pin. You will need to play safe some of the time,'' none of that
reflecting on the bombarding game that Woods plays.
</P>
<P>
   For the past seven years, Montgomerie has been the dominating
player on the European Tour. This year, he has dropped to third
place, behind Darren Clarke, who got a head start in World Match
Play, and Els. Still, Scottish punters are collecting strong behind
Monty at 14-1, second choice with Els and Westwood, behind the
pressurized Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you are fed up with people talking about Tiger Woods,''
it was put to him as the conference ground down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I am,'' Monty said. ``Next question.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-CORSON-NYT     07-19 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CORSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM CORSON, 74, A MARINE NEARLY COURT-MARTIALED FOR BOOK ON
VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ William R. Corson, a retired Marine Corps
lieutenant colonel who was an expert on revolution and
counterinsurgency and was nearly court-martialed for writing a book
venting his disillusionment over the Vietnam War, died on Monday at
a hospital in Bethesda, Md. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Corson lived in Potomac, Md. The cause of death was emphysema
and lung cancer, his wife, Judith, said.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1968, Corson was just back from a tour in Vietnam and
working in the Defense Department, looking forward to retirement.
He spent much of his spare time hunched over a typewriter at home,
working on a book he would call ``The Betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   Corson had never believed in the ``domino theory'' that one
Communist takeover would lead to another, and he had long thought
that the struggle in Vietnam was more about nationalism than
Communism, his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher, W.W. Norton, planned to publish the book on July
1, the day after Corson's retirement became effective. But the
colonel ran afoul of a regulation requiring officers to submit
statements on public policy for official review before making them
public.
</P>
<P>
   Unpersuaded by his argument that the regulation should not apply
to him because he would be a civilian when the book came out, and
that his manuscript violated no national-security laws in any
event, the Marine Corps delayed his retirement and moved to convene
a court-martial. As the debate grew heated, the Corps dropped the
court-martial, and Corson retired a month later than planned.
</P>
<P>
   The book condemned the assumptions that had led the United
States into a quagmire. ``The politicians saw in Vietnam, or so
they thought at the time, a chance to pull off a cheap victory
against the Communists,'' he wrote. ``When their initial judgments
about Vietnam were found to be in error, there was no way to
confess their error, without risking defeat at the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Corson argued that the American-backed Saigon government was
inept and corrupt and out of touch with the people.
</P>
<P>
   William Corson became familiar with Southeast Asia as a young
officer. After Korean War service, he learned Chinese at the Naval
Intelligence School in Washington. In the late 1950s he was
stationed in Hong Kong, and in 1962 he was assigned to the office
of the Secretary of Defense. From 1964 to 1966, he taught a course
on communism and revolution at the Naval Academy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, he was sent to command a tank battalion in Vietnam, a
country he had been studying since it was a French colonial
possession. In 1967, he was named head of the Combined Action
Program, in which Marines aided South Vietnamese militia in
villages. Corson's superiors praised his ability to win the
confidence of the Vietnamese. Had he decided to remain in the Corps
instead of retiring, he seemed destined to wear the eagle of a full
colonel, perhaps even the star of a brigadier general.
</P>
<P>
   His career path had been unusual. Born in Chicago, he spent much
of his early childhood with his grandparents after his mother and
father divorced. As a teen-ager, he preferred wandering and odd
jobs over the classroom. Then he got a job at the Chicago Daily
News, whose publisher, Frank Knox, saw something in him.
</P>
<P>
   Knox, who later became secretary of the Navy, who was on the
board of the University of Chicago and helped the young man get a
scholarship there.
</P>
<P>
   William Corson enlisted in the Marines in World War II and
fought in Guam and Bougainville in the Pacific, rising to sergeant.
After the war, he returned to the University of Chicago and got a
degree in mathematics. He received a master's in economics at the
University of Miami and re-entered the Marine Corps in 1949 as an
officer. Years later, he got a doctorate in economics from American
University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the Marines, he taught history at Howard
University in Washington for a year and wrote several books on
national security issues. He also served as compliance director of
the Price Commission, the agency created in 1971 as part of
President Nixon's attempts to stabilize the economy and hold down
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Corson is survived by their three sons,
Adam, Zachary and Andrew, all of Potomac; two sons from an earlier
marriage, Christopher of Silver Spring, Md., and David of
Greenville, S.C.; and five grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unpleasantness surrounding his retirement, Corson
remained a Marine at heart, up to a point. ``I could kill you in
eight seconds,'' he boasted to an interviewer a year after leaving
the Corps. ``But I don't have the instinct for that sort of thing
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
