<HEADER>
A6793 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS20-COX     07-19 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini-reviews
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison, Sonia Murray, Pierre Ruhe and Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs From an American Movie _ Vol. 1: Learning How to Smile''
</P>
<P>
   Everclear. Capitol. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   When Capitol releases an Everclear best-of, it'll be a beautiful
thing. Each of the trio's albums has a handful of great tunes and
some clunkers. This is no exception. There's at least one-third of
a very good album here, but a couple of the most entertaining
moments owe a debt to other artists. ``AM Radio'' is a big slab of
goofy fun that pays tribute to the 1970s, incorporating a chunk of
Jean Knight's ``Mr. Big Stuff.'' The stomping ``Now That It's
Over'' contains musical allusions to both Led Zeppelin and the
Beatles. There's one moment that should have remained someone
else's, though _ a well-meaning but icky cover of Van Morrison's
``Brown Eyed Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More about Everclear:www.everclearonline.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Country Grammar''
</P>
<P>
   Nelly. Universal. 17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Nelly's ``Country Grammar'' came up and surprised the musical
world when the St. Louis rapper's first album debuted higher than
the much more hyped Lil' Kim follow-up. Clearly, those caught off
guard by Nelly's No. 3 entry onto the pop charts hadn't listened to
his album, because it both predicts and details his imminent
success _ over and over again. In fact, the main difference among
his songs is which luxury car hip-hop's first prominent bluesman
claims to be driving _ a Range Rover in the insistent title track,
a Hummer in the quirky, Playstation-sounding ``Tho Dem Wrappas''
and a Mercedes on the menacing ``For My,'' with fellow twanger Lil'
Wayne. All of ``Country Grammar'' is revved up on St. Louis pride
and original music, but too often it stalls when it comes to
subject matter and hooks.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Nelly and Universal Records:
www.universal.com. and www.nelly.net
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``White Pony''
</P>
<P>
   Deftones. Maverick. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Put Metallica, Radiohead and Fugazi in a blender with a dash of
Smashing Pumpkins, garnish with a twist of trip-hop, and you have
the Deftones cocktail. The alternative metal quintet's third album
barrels out of the speakers with the force of a runaway train, but
the band has a firm grip on the handle. The rampaging riffs are
grabbers, but the abstractly creepy lyrics and the inventive sound
painting of Stephen Carpenter's guitars and DJ Frank Delgado's
turntablism make them stick. You'll bang your head, but it won't
feel empty while you do it.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More about Deftones:
</P>
<P>
   deftones.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   Mahler Symphony No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, Yoel Levi, conductor. Telarc.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Gustav Mahler's Symphony No. 1 is Yoel Levi and the ASO's latest
installment in the composer's symphonic cycle _ they've already
released Nos. 4 through 7. In Mahler 1, Levi inserts the original
second movement, ``Blumine,'' making this a five-movement work. As
in the rest of the cycle, the playing here is exacting, limpid and
subtle, with pure horn calls, crisp, dry-eyed cello statements and
explosive percussion. It's almost a textbook display of orchestral
refinement, captured in Telarc's vivid sound. Levi's interpretation
is a bit generic _ there's room for a thousand touches of
personality in this music, left unexplored _ but for overall sound
and style, this recording is hard to beat.
</P>
<P>
   _Pierre Ruhe
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on the ASO and Levi's Mahler cycle:
www.telarc.com/classical
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BLUES
</P>
<P>
   ``Royal Blue''
</P>
<P>
   Koko Taylor. Alligator. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s, Koko Taylor has used a winning formula: Work
with great musicians, play barnburners, add raunch _ and top it
with the bluesiest growl this side of Howlin' Wolf. Now 64, the
queen of the Chicago blues is joined on a rockin' set by B.B. King
and Kenny Wayne Shepherd. Time has neither smoothed Taylor's voice
nor dulled her libido: ``When you check my oil, check it nice and
slow,'' she sings in a voice that could make a dipstick salute. The
highlight is the one departure: ``The Man Next Door'' features only
bluesman Keb' Mo' on steel guitar and harmonica _ and one of the
most expressive voices the blues has yet produced.
</P>
<P>
   _Don Melvin
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Koko Taylor and Alligator Records:
www.alligator.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
