<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-LAWSUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES OF COLUMBINE VICTIMS SUE SCHOOL OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ky., Miss.)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The families of three victims of the shootings last
year at Columbine High School have sued the school principal,
teachers and a security guard, charging that they knew the two
killers' propensity for violence and took no steps to intercede.
</P>
<P>
   Had they done so, the families said in complaints filed on
Monday with the Jefferson County District Court, the killings of 12
students and a teacher and the wounding of two dozen others might
never have happened. The lawsuits expanded charges previously filed
by the families against members of the Jefferson County Sheriff's
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an awful lot of information that was made available
by these perpetrators,'' James A. Cederberg, a lawyer representing
one of the families, said, referring to the shooters, Eric Harris
and Dylan Klebold. ``At some point, the message has got to be
received. These kids were up to something that was a threat to
everybody else at school. So how could it all have fallen through
the cracks?''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Jefferson County School District said that
none of the employees of Columbine, including principal Frank
DeAngelis, had any prior knowledge ``about the horrible plans or
the tragic actions'' of April 20, 1999. The spokesman, Rick
Kaufman, described the Columbine defendants as ``dedicated staff
members who have demonstrated time and again their commitment to
the care, safety and well-being of students and staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Charges against school officials after a mass shooting are not
unusual, and in at least two other cases, families of victims said
that the shooters had exhibited a similar tendency toward violence
as the Columbine lawsuits suggest.
</P>
<P>
   After a teen-age boy shot and killed three fellow students and
wounded five others in West Paducah, Ky., in 1998, victims'
families sued 30 school officials, including school board members,
teachers and a principal. In Mississippi, a school district was
sued after a 17-year-old student killed two classmates in 1997 at
Pearl High School.
</P>
<P>
   If the latest lawsuits involving Columbine employees are any
different, it may only be because, as the three new complaints
charge, the two killers provided more than casual evidence of their
interest in violence.
</P>
<P>
   The families of Isaiah Shoels, who was killed, and of Richard R.
Castaldo and Mark Taylor, who were wounded, said that in a class
taught by Garrett Talocco, a defendant, Harris showed videotapes he
had made that showed him and Klebold using guns to enact ``revenge
shootings'' of other Columbine students.
</P>
<P>
   In a creative writing class taught by Judy Kelly and a
psychology class taught by Tom Johnson, both defendants, the
complaint said that work by Harris and Klebold reflected ``hatred,
anger, possession and use of firearms, and the desire and intent to
kill and injure others.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits also charge that a sheriff's report discussing
Harris' Web site, on which he wrote about bomb-making and threats
of violence, had been forwarded to Neil Gardner, a deputy assigned
to Columbine as a security officer but that Gardner, who was also
named as a defendant, took no action.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of all these incidents, the families said DeAngelis
should have been aware of problems with Harris and Klebold and
responded in a way that could have prevented the attack. The
families said that, as principal, DeAngelis was ``responsible for
the overall operation and safety of the school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
