A6795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GAY-SCOUTS20-COX     07-19 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-SCOUTS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEGISLATORS SEEK TO END FEDERAL TIES TO BOY SCOUTS
 &HT;    420&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A group of Democratic House members says President
Clinton should resign as honorary head of the Boy Scouts of America
because of the group's policy against homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawmakers also said at a Capitol news conference
Wednesday she was introducing legislation to revoke the Boy Scouts'
federal charter.
</P>
<P>
   The largely symbolic actions come in response to a recent
Supreme Court decision upholding the Boy Scouts' right as a private
organization to exclude homosexuals as leaders and possibly as
members.
</P>
<P>
   In a July 13 letter to Clinton, 11 Democratic House members said
that ``in order to disavow this policy of intolerance, as well as
to clarify any misconception of implicit presidential approval, we
urge you ... to resign as honorary head of the BSA.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremonial position has been held by every president since
William Howard Taft in 1910, said Gregg Shields, a spokesman for
the Boy Scouts of America. ``We appreciate their support,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been tied up in Mideast peace negotiations at Camp
David, Md., and hasn't reviewed the request from his fellow
Democrats, said Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important role, but it has been pushed aside by bigger
issues,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The same legislators also want Congress to repeal the
84-year-old federal charter for the Boy Scouts, said Rep. Lynn
Woolsey, D-Calif. She introduced a bill Wednesday to strike the
scouts' ``honorific'' charter granted to ``organizations with a
patriotic, charitable or educational purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a symbolic act,'' Woolsey conceded. But she said it would
``send a message that the Congress of the United States does not
support intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the Boy Scouts to be available to all boys,''
regardless of their sexual orientation, Woolsey said at the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Shields said the Boy Scouts is among many federally chartered
groups recognized by Congress as ``patriotic societies'' that
restrict membership to certain people. Other such groups include
the Catholic Veterans, Jewish War Veterans U.S.A., and Vietnam
Veterans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an honor to be a congressionally chartered
organization,'' he said, and the Scouts have strived ``to live up
to that honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey said that time is running out on the current
congressional session and that any action on the bill would be
dependent on the Republican House leadership. However, she promised
to bring it up again in the next Congress, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The congresswoman was joined at the press conference by former
Eagle scouts who said the values they learned in scouting help them
later to come out as gay men.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts, along with his family and church, ``helped me
develop my own moral compass,'' said Graham Segroves, who attained
the Eagle rank in Knoxville, Tenn., and now works for the National
Gay and Lesbian Liberation Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Segroves said he is dismayed that national Boy Scout leadership
``says a gay man like me cannot be a positive role model'' for
members.
</P>
<P>
   Congress approved a federal charter for the Boy Scouts in 1916,
six years after the organization was founded.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in a 5-4 vote that the
Boy Scouts can bar homosexuals from serving as troop leaders. The
ruling may also permit the group to reject gay boys as members.
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey said she doesn't dispute the court decision but
disagrees with the Scouts' anti-gay policies. ``We're not saying
that the Boy Scouts are bad,'' said Woolsey, whose grown son is a
former scout. ``We're saying that intolerance is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the recent Supreme Court decision which
effectively allows the BSA to exclude homosexual males from its
leadership and potential membership, we are deeply concerned that
the office of the president, in its capacity as honorary head of
the BSA, is seen as giving implicit approval to this
self-proclaimed intolerant policy,'' the legislators wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 11 liberal Democrats who signed the letter to Clinton
was Rep. Cynthia McKinney of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Boy Scouts of America: www.bsa.scouting.org
</P>
<P>
   Scouting for All: www.scoutingforall.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
