<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0720-COX     07-19 2008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Running mate decision nears finish line
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush said today he hasn't yet decided on a running
mate but would soon. ``I will start notifying people,'' he said
without elaborating. He said his top criterion for picking someone
to share the ticket remains ``whether we can work together for the
good of the nation.'' Those most frquently mentioned as potential
running mates are Govs. Frank Keating of Oklahoma, Tom Ridge of
Pennsylvania and George Pataki of New York; Sens. Fred Thompson and
Bill Frist, both of Tennessee; and Rep. John Kasich of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   A WITNESS FOR THE PROSECUTION
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before Kansas City-area law enforcement personnel
today, Al Gore upped the ante in his self-described bid to be ``a
law enforcement president'' by proposing to hire 10,000 new
prosecutors in communities nationwide. His proposal is modeled
after President Clinton's grant program to put 100,000 new
community police officers on the streets _ the COPS program, which
Gore has proposed expanding by 50,000. Crime is this week's main
focus for Gore, although he appears preoccupied by the Texas budget
and its shortfall of at least $610 million, due, state officials
say, to underestimated Medicaid costs.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING THE ATTACK TO FOE'S HOME FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is going to San Antonio Thursday to take aim at the
state's newly projected budget shortfall that critics warn may be
growing daily. Gore took a few preliminary shots today, blaming the
projected shortfall _ now officially put at $610 million _ on
George W. Bush mixing unwarranted tax cuts for the rich with
inadequately funded programs for the poor. ``How Governor Bush has
run Texas is relevant to the judgment the American people will make
as to how he would run the country if they ever gave him the
chance,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   THEY'LL ALL BE UPDATING THEIR WEB SITES NOW
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush will promote his new and improved Web site _
www.georgewbush.com _ in a new television ad, using fast-paced
music and tilted camera angles. The ad will begin running in the
San Francisco-San Jose and New York City markets on Friday. The
only talking in the ad is a video clip of Bush declaring that he's
running for president. The site will allow users to download
event-specific posters or placards for campaign events, listen to
live Internet ``radio shows,'' and enter ``fun and humorous''
contests. Bush joked that modern day technology could even play a
role in who he chooses as his running mate. A new qualification for
his partner, he said, would be ``whether they have a good Web
page.''
</P>
<P>
   LET'S SEE IF THOSE NEEDLES JUMP OR STAY LEVEL
</P>
<P>
   The man who accused Hillary Clinton of making an anti-Semitic
slur is willing to take a lie detector test or truth serum to prove
he's telling the truth. Paul Fray has accused Clinton of calling
him a ``Jew b------'' during an argument in 1974 in Arkansas. ``If
she does not have any recollection of it that's not my problem,
it's hers,'' Paul Fray said in an interview broadcast today on
ABC's ``Good Morning America.'' Fray said he does not think she is
anti-Semitic: ``It was a spur-of-the-moment thing.''
</P>
<P>
   KEEP FISHING FOR AN ANSWER
</P>
<P>
   At his brief news conference in Austin today, George W. Bush
took a swipe at opponent Al Gore for declining to take a clear
position on whether to breach Snake River dams in the Pacific
Northwest to save salmon. The administration's top environmental
officials were testifying before Congress today to make the case
that it isn't necessary at this time to take such drastic action
despite pleas by environmentalists. Business interests oppose
breaching the dams. Gore, in Kansas City, Mo., was asked about
Bush's criticism and he refused again to take a definitive stand.
``I'm going to review it carefully,'' he said, adding that he
believes all sides need to talk.
</P>
<P>
   STRIKE WHILE THE CONVENTION IS HOT
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Philadelphia city workers are threatening to strike
July 25 _ a week before the Republican convention _ if their union
and the city can't agree on a contract by then. A strike could mean
piles of uncollected garbage all over the city just as thousands of
people come to town. Herman ``Pete'' Matthews, president of the
blue-collar District Council 33 of the American Federation of
State, County and Municipal Employees, said he's seen little
progress in three weeks of talks and that he hopes that setting a
strike deadline will put pressure on city negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   TORRICELLI TO TRENTON?
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, whose fund-raising prowess propelled him
into Democratic leadership in his first Senate term, said today he
hopes to become New Jersey's next governor. Torricelli said he
admires a governor's ability to ``get things done'' and that he's
tired of fighting for incremental change. At the same time, he
would not have to give up his Senate seat while running for
governor next year. His Senate term expires in 2002. Republican
Gov. Christie Whitman is barred from seeking a third term.
</P>
<P>
   CALL GOING OUT FOR MCCALL
</P>
<P>
   In what labor leaders are calling a powerful signal that they
intend to support state Comptroller Carl McCall for governor in
2002, nearly all of New York's top union officials are holding a
fund-raiser for him Thursday in Manhattan. Officials said it was
far too soon for them or their unions to make formal endorsements,
but several of them told the New York Times that they intended the
event to be taken as an early sign of their sympathies. ``We'd
elect him tomorrow,'' one prominent union leader said.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER HEALTH PLAN FROM HILLARY
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton presented a plan to extend health insurance to
millions of Americans, including 1.1 million New Yorkers. Her plan,
which hews closely to the one proposed by Al Gore, could not be
further in details and scope from the ill-fated program she helped
to mastermind in 1994. Among other things, it would, expand an
existing government program to insure children, and steers clear
from visions of insuring the entire nation in one blow.
</P>
<P>
   HIT THE GROUND RUNNING
</P>
<P>
   In the first six weeks after he abruptly entered the Senate
race, Rick Lazio spent $1.58 million on TV advertising, and sought
to bolster his candidacy by hiring several political consultants
who had worked on John McCain's campaign. His latest campaign
records filed with the Federal Election Commission show that Lazio
collected $4.99 million in donations from April 1 through June 30.
He spent a total of $2.32 million, and his campaign now has $6.19
million in the bank, including money left over from his House
races.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK VOTE INCREASING
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans were the only race or ethnic group to defy the
trend of declining voter participation in congressional elections,
increasing their turnout at the polls from 37 percent of potential
black voters in 994 to 40 percent in 1998, according to a new
Census Bureau report. Nationwide, overall turnout by the voting-age
population was down from 45 percent in 1994 to 42 percent in 1998 _
about 3 million fewer voters _ the report said.
</P>
<P>
   AFTER COVERDELL, A DEMOCRAT?
</P>
<P>
   The death of Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell means Georgia likely
will be represented by two Democrats in the Senate _ at least for a
few months. Under Georgia law, Democratic Gov. Roy Barnes can
appoint an interim replacement until a Nov. 7 special election.
Barnes has said it is ``inappropriate'' to discuss any appointment
so soon after Coverdell's death.
</P>
<P>
   THE RUSSIANS ARE COMING!
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to improve relations with the Republican Party and learn
how to build a political party, emissaries from Russian President
Vladimir Putin's political faction plan to attend the GOP
convention in Philadelphia. Rep. Curt Weldon (R-Pa.), who is
arranging the trip, said the group will be led by Boris Gryzlov,
head of the pro-government Unity group in the Russian parliament.
``They want to cover both bases,'' Weldon explained. ``I've told
the Russians, don't put all your eggs in either party's basket.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG AD BUY FOR PRIESTS
</P>
<P>
   A national group of Roman Catholic priests, saying they want to
expose Christian politicians who support abortion rights as false
prophets, began an ad today aimed at making opposition to abortion
the top issue for voters. Priests for Life took out a full-page ad
in today's New York Times, and plans TV spots in selected markets
next month. ``Voters are free to elect whom they choose. But to be
free, one has to be informed of the implications of one's choice,
including the moral and spiritual implications,'' said the Rev.
Frank Pavone, head of the New York-based group.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD TIME TO BE A FATHER
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are retooling and bringing back a TV ad that stars Al
Gore as son and then father, a biographical montage that emphasizes
the importance of fatherhood. The heartwarming spot was originally
made for Father's Day, but it ran for only four days. Strategists
felt it was an effective demonstration of Gore's ideas on
fatherhood and of him as a person, and will begin airing it again
Thursday. George W. Bush discussed the importance of fathers
earlier this week, but Democrats said that's just a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE STATE, BIG DIVISION
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island Republicans split over George W. Bush and John
McCain will be heading for separate hotels at the GOP convention.
Eight of 10 delegates backing McCain have rejected the party's
official choice of accommodations in Philadelphia, deciding instead
to stay just over the border in New Jersey. Some defecting
delegates say they'll save about $100 per night. But others say
they're making a statement that they're as independent as the man
they support.
</P>
<P>
   SO OK, GUYS, COOPERATE
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the Democratic attack against his record as
governor, George W. Bush told state legislators from across the
country that Texas is an example of good government _ ``a template
for change in Washington. We have put the public's interests
first.'' Bush said civility and bipartisanship, two traits missing
in Washington, flourish in Texas. ``In order to get anything done
... there has to be a new spirit and attitude in Washington, an
attitude you find in your states _ an attitude of cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   HIS TURN IN THE SPOTLIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party's Ralph Nader took advantage of his newfound
media attention Tuesday, speaking before a full house of
journalists and supporters at the National Press Club in
Washington. Nader said he would raise gas taxes and replace Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. He also took issue with Rep.
Barney Frank (D-Mass.), the openly gay congressman who has said Al
Gore would be a better supporter of civil rights than Nader. Said
Nader: ``I've been an advocate for civil liberties and civil rights
when he was trying to figure out how to play soccer in elementary
school, and I don't need to be lectured by him about this.''
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL INCLUSIVENESS? YOU CAN BET ON IT
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party, moving to head off any threat to George W.
Bush's message of racial inclusiveness, has repudiated a Washington
state GOP resolution calling for the elimination of American Indian
tribal governments. ``We are writing to assure you we reject this
resolution and everything it stands for. ... The elimination of
tribal governments is not an option,'' said a letter sighed by GOP
national chairman Jim Nicholson and Sens. John McCain of Arizona
and Ben Nighthorse Campbell of Colorado, the only Indian in the
Senate. Both political parties have sought donations from tribes
with successful gambling casinos.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
