<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SMOKE0720-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY:
</P>
<P>
   Kick butts by regulating Big Tobacco
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry is like a cockroach. Whacked by a 2-by-4 or
hit with a $145 billion verdict, it still won't die.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict that the record-breaking judgment in a Florida
class-action suit against five tobacco companies will either be
reduced by an appeals court or paid off through higher cigarette
prices. Then it will be business as usual for this renegade
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco belongs under the control of the federal Food and Drug
Administration, but so far that hasn't happened. The industry has
fought off government oversight and curried influential allies
through generous campaign contributions. As a result, conglomerate
Philip Morris faces more stringent regulation of its Kraft macaroni
and cheese than its Marlboro cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the FDA, cigarette makers would be compelled to disclose
the contents of cigarettes and all potential health effects. FDA
regulation would end the industry's insidious practice of
advertising to kids and would force companies to address the damage
caused by their product.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of regulation has allowed cigarette companies to
conceal their in-house research on the deadly nature of their
product. In its massive verdict against the industry, the Florida
jury recognized and punished that callous disregard for human life.
</P>
<P>
   Yet elected officials still seem intent on rewarding tobacco
companies for their deadly deceit. Many states, including Georgia,
have passed laws designed to shield the industry from its sins and
insulate it from public outrage. Those laws were spurred by Big
Tobacco's $246 billion settlement with the states in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That settlement did not decimate Big Tobacco. On the contrary,
revenues and profits rose in its aftermath, fueled by a 45-cent
rise in the cost of a pack of cigarettes. Nor will this $145
billion verdict bury the industry, despite what Big Tobacco
attorneys insist. If the appeals court upholds the judgment,
cigarette manufacturers will increase prices again and continue to
prosper. Cigarettes cost almost nothing to produce and are so
addictive that smokers will pay whatever is demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Big Tobacco does not need Georgia lawmakers fretting over its
well-being and legislating special protections. It's true there are
fewer tobacco jobs in the United States, but that's because the
industry put its profits ahead of its patriotism in opting for
cheaper overseas production and labor.
</P>
<P>
   As long as there are 46 million smokers in the country, there
will be profitable cigarette companies. Those companies ought to be
regulated.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
