<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6801 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-ESHOPPING-TEX     07-19 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ESHOPPING-TEX </SLUG>
 
 EDS: Has sidebar, TRAVEL-ESHOPPING-CHART 
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Travel researched and booked on the Internet is one of the
fastest-growing segments of the Web. But does that mean it's more
efficient, easier, and cheaper than the old-fashioned method of
phone calls and travel agents?
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, I would have argued vigorously that it
is. After all, I've found some great last-minute air fares on Web
sites; I've also gotten a couple of hotel deals and a steal on a
flight to Europe, booked months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   But then I spent a couple of days conducting a little
experiment: trying to book a cruise, a weekend in Las Vegas, and a
Cancun vacation through the most popular Web sites and through
traditional travel agents. And _ surprise _ the two methods turned
out to be a draw.
</P>
<P>
   As with everything else done online, the big plus is
convenience; you can order airline tickets or book a hotel in the
middle of the night or while wearing a mud mask and fuzzy slippers.
If you're lucky, and flexible on your destination and travel dates,
you can find some astounding deals.
</P>
<P>
   But is it faster?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   Cheaper?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   More frustrating?
</P>
<P>
   Often.
</P>
<P>
   Still, travel is a popular topic on the Net, with more than
1,000 commercial Web sites devoted to the subject. More than 52.2
million people used the Internet for travel planning in 1999, an
increase of 54 percent from the previous year, according to a
survey by the Travel Industry Association of America. The same
report said that 16.5 million people booked travel online in 1999,
an increase of 146 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So it's worth taking a look at how best to use these resources.
</P>
<P>
   For this test case, I visited three large all-purpose sites,
Expedia, Travelocity and Travelscape, which was recently purchased
by Expedia. I also called three local travel agents, chosen at
random, to whom I had never spoken previously. (I didn't identify
myself as a reporter until afterward.)
</P>
<P>
   My goal was to find the best deal on three vacations: a
seven-day Caribbean cruise; a three-day weekend in Cancun, Mexico;
and a three-day weekend in Las Vegas. I asked for moderate but nice
lodgings _ not the Ritz but not a Motel 6 _ for two people. The
trips were to be taken during the first two weeks of December.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened?
</P>
<P>
   Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   I spend a fair amount of time online and had visited each of the
sites in question, so I expected this to go quickly. Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Using the high-speed T1 Internet connection through my office
computer _ much faster than the 56K modem on my laptop at home _ I
still spent a lot of time watching pages load and then having them
crash or lock up. Sometimes, this was in the middle of a search,
forcing me to start over. What I expected to accomplish in an hour
or two ended up taking a large part of a day.
</P>
<P>
   I also realized that although the Web may be great for
last-minute deals, like the Internet specials the major airlines
offer on weekend flights, it's another thing when you're trying to
find specific destinations at a specific time. Sometimes, search
engines brought up great packages that weren't available on the
dates I needed. Other times, prices were a couple of hundred
dollars higher than I'd been quoted at other sites or by an agent.
</P>
<P>
   Each site was reasonably efficient and, best of all, offered
pictures and details about hotels and cruise ships, letting you see
what you were getting into. But each had its quirks:
</P>
<P>
   Travelocity had some of the best graphics on its hotels, and it
was easy to compare packages, but it seemed most likely to crash at
an inopportune time.
</P>
<P>
   Expedia, too often, just wanted to give links to other sites
that varied greatly in quality of information offered; sometimes
you couldn't book online at these sites but were given a phone
number to call.
</P>
<P>
   Travelscape's search engine produced relevant results fastest,
but in a plain-Jane format; it offered fewer options and doesn't
sell cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents:
</P>
<P>
   Even using agents that I'd never used before, I got quotes
immediately after I explained what I was looking for. (One took the
information and called me back within 30 minutes with prices and
specifics; the others kept me on the line while they looked.) All
three said they had been to the destinations in question and would
refer me only to properties they knew. The prices, for the most
part, were equivalent to or better than what I found on the
Internet, sometimes for the same properties.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drawback, of course, is that you don't see the
properties; to get brochures, you need to visit an office or wait
for materials to be sent to you in the mail. (One agent referred me
to the Internet to look up hotels he'd recommended.) And unless you
know and trust the agent, you might be suspicious as to why a
certain hotel or cruise line is being recommended over others; is
it really the best option, or is the agent getting some kind of
financial incentive to sell it?
</P>
<P>
   The experiment did reinforce one valuable lesson: As with any
major purchase, it pays to do your research before whipping out
your credit card. And it's wise to use every tool at your disposal.
Traditional travel agency or Internet travel site? At this point,
the smart traveler uses them all.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
