A6804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GRASS0720-COX     07-19 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRASS0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drought has us holding our ground, not working it
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Financed in part by the harvest and sale of one
of my kidneys, we recently upgraded to House 2.0. It's in a nice
neighborhood with big trees, two Ford Expeditions in every garage
and lush, expertly groomed lawns that appear to be tended with the
assistance of Paul Mitchell hair care products.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, I have no business being there, so I secretly
applauded the city's edict over the weekend to impose mandatory
watering restrictions because it enables me _ in the guise of being
a good, environmentally proper Austinite _ to ignore the lawn, to
watch this magnificent green space turn to brown and eventually,
sometime next month, burst into flame. For someone as impaired as I
when it comes to lawn care, this is liberating.
</P>
<P>
   Burn, baby, burn, I say.
</P>
<P>
   The old neighborhood _ small yards, 10-year-old Volvos, no
garages _ was different. Mowing there appeared to be strictly
optional, and watering was a suburban extravagance. The people next
door had a great lawn, but it was Xeriscaped, festooned with
greenery that (unlike, oh, turf grass) was meant to grow in these
parts. The primary user of the back yard was our large, profoundly
stupid dog, and I get all misty when I think about the dry,
neglected grass crunching under her clumsy paws. Not watering led
to not mowing, which led to a lot more time devoted to more
worthwhile pursuits such as beer. Not that I didn't try for a
while. In addition to making a steadfastly half-hearted effort at
keeping the lawn together, I planted basil. It died. So did the
jalapenos. The rosemary just sort of sat there, too proud to
succumb but too neglected to grow, which I'm told is what it
ideally does. Potted plants committed suicide on the way home from
the greenhouse rather than subject themselves to our deadly
combination of indifference and incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   Those were, I now realize, the salad days, except without the
salad. Then the yard got so ugly we had to sell the house and move.
</P>
<P>
   The greenery around the new place struck both my wife and me
when we toured it. That great back yard with more than a dozen
trees. The Mexican oregano. The plants in pots and the shrubs out
front. This is a great yard, and we will take care of it, we
resolved. I even spent several minutes seriously weighing the
benefits of gas vs. electric weed whackers. In a few hours after we
closed on the place, however, the back yard looked like Sherman had
just marched across it and the oregano drooped in defeat. The
corners of the front yard, where we couldn't quite position the
sprinkler to hit, turned the color of Kansas wheat.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the neighbors' lawns continued to look like
picture postcards from County Cork.
</P>
<P>
   Then the mandatory restrictions kicked in, and with them a kind
of reverse competition. A well-kept, painfully green lawn suggests
a home where the husband works in a dull but dependable trade, the
wife answers the door in June Cleaver heels and the kids never talk
back to their parents. This is not anywhere near my life (I don't
work, my wife only wears heels to the beach and my three-year-old
teaches me cuss words) and I see no reason to compel my lawn to lie
for me. The goal now is not who has the greenest lawn, but whose
will die most quickly. In this, we're off to a smashing start. The
neighbors are brown with envy. Wait'll I put the washing machine
and the pit bull in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   One of the enduringly baffling qualities about life in Central
Texas for me, a non-native (my wife is from here _ what's your
excuse?), is why people spend so much time working their ground,
attempting to keep things alive that simply weren't meant to grow
here. Allow me to note that, a) it's much too hot to be outside,
and b) despite what you hear from well-meaning horticulture
professionals with no financial motivation for telling you
otherwise, absolutely nothing is meant to grow here. True, there's
the Xeriscaping movement, the success of which, I suspect, is due
to animal sacrifice or something, and said movement has made
inroads among enlightened yard-diggers, but far too many of us
spend excessive water, money and time trying to keep our greenery
green. This makes lazy people such as myself feel terribly
inadequate, but not so inadequate as to effect a behavioral change.
I mean, ``The Simpsons'' are on every night.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful lawns are the domain of the overly socialized. But if
this fine drought holds for a few more weeks, the new place ought
to look a lot like home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the uth smoking by driving up cigarette
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Rep. Bill Archer,
R-Tex., said the gray-market provision was eliminated from the
trade bill because it would have opened the door to numerous tax
amendments when it reached the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal with the bill was to create a non-controversial bill
devoted entirely to trade,'' Archer said. ``While I do not think
the gray-market act is controversial, this committee has worked on
this trade bill for over two years and we did not want it to be
subject to tax amendments once it is on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer said he hopes to take action on the proposal later this
session.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would have banned the sale of cigarettes labeled
``For use outside the U.S.'' and would have required the
destruction of all gray-market cigarettes that are seized by the
federal government. It also would have prohibited the
re-importation of previously exported cigarettes except for returns
to their original manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
