<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6809 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-TECHNOLOGY-MAP-NY     07-19 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TECHNOLOGY-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROJECT GIVES SMALL NONPROFIT GROUPS A BIG-TIME MAPPING TOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MELISSA P. McNAMARA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Matthew Bregman, the Brooklyn Academy of Music's
development director, initiated a marketing plan to spur
neighborhood real estate development for use by the performing
arts, he searched for a way to project accurate images of the
borough's landmarks, potential sources of financing and residential
areas lacking access to the arts. He found the solution in the New
York Public Interest Research Group's computer mapping software.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting the project to BAM's board without visual aids would
have been ineffective, Bregman said. ``It's kind of like if you
tried to play chess without a chess board,'' he said. ``The visual
difference is extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the research group, known as NYPIRG, began the
Community Mapping Assistance Project (www.cmap.nypirg.org) to
provide customized computer mapping services to nonprofit groups
like the Brooklyn Academy of Music. The Web-based program generates
detailed maps using sophisticated Geographic Information Systems
software. Since the project's inception, NYPIRG has been engaged in
more than 250 projects for almost 100 nonprofit clients.
</P>
<P>
   Although many federal government agencies and for-profit
corporations regularly use Geographic Information Systems software
to present statistical data visually, nonprofit organizations do
not often rely on the costly software mapping programs because
those groups lack the financial and highly specialized technology
personnel resources, Steve Romalewski, CMAP's technology director,
said. NYPIRG's service fills this need by providing the technology
that can plot an organization's data and provides
computer-generated maps, graphs and reports tailored to the needs
of New York state's nonprofit groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``These maps are not just a convenience,'' Bregman said. ``It's
a necessity to have this technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit organizations use the GIS mapping technology primarily
to facilitate their advocacy wrk. The United Hospital Fund of New
York, for example, uses the technology on its Web site to display
the locations of ambulatory care sites, hospitals and nursing homes
(www.uhfnyc.org). By entering a ZIP code, people can find phone
numbers and other information to get the help they need, said
plained Amy Cohen, the United Hospital Fund's technology editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to return to our site when they see how easy it is
to find these locations for their elderly family members,'' Cohen
said, ``and it's easily accessibly for volunteers who want to help
out in local centers.'' The Web site receives 400 to 500 hits per
month.
</P>
<P>
   CMAP also serves as a political tool for nonprofits lobbying for
increased political or financial support by creating digital images
of an organization's membership, demographic patterns and
legislative districts. Interactive sites that use the CMAP
technology include Who Represents Me? New York City residents can
enter their address to find representatives at the federal, state
and city levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Council Finder is extraordinarily helpful. Lobbyists in
the nonprofit community could spend two hours just to locate the
right people to contact and to find out who your representative
is,'' Bregman said.
</P>
<P>
   Converting data from a raw statistical database into a visual
image makes it easier for nonprofit groups to find sources of
financing. The mapping software also helps advocacy groups mobilize
public opinion. Arnold Cohen, president of the Partnership for the
Homeless, a nonprofit that operates homeless shelters in New York
City, uses maps on the organization's Web site to show lobbyists
which representatives to focus on to increase New York City's
financing of homeless shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a detailed map, we can see our network of 140 shelters
sprinkled throughout the boroughs,'' Cohen said, ``which makes us
more informed when we speak to congressional or City Council
representatives. We also see where there are gaps in our network so
we can push for more funding.''
</P>
<P>
   On its own Web site, CMAP creates maps that draw on its
databases of research stored during the past 10 years from NYPIRG's
environmental and consumer projects. Once the figures are converted
to digital form, nonprofit organizations can translate the numbers
into vivid visual displays that increase public awareness. The
visual images of demographic and income patterns retrieved from
1990 census data enable some organizations to examine the locations
of social service centers. Similarly, a Top 21 Dirty Power Plants
in NY link on CMAP's Web site draws users from NYPIRG's
environmental research projects to a map with the location of power
plants and emission reports for each plant.
</P>
</TEXT>
