<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKIN' MIGHTY PRETTY:OKLAHOMA CITY'S REDEVELOPMENT IS INCREASING
ITS TOURISM TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
 OKCITY KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 TIM JANICKE  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because I-35 is the mother road for many of us around Kansas
City, The Kansas City Star decided to explore its length _ 1,593
miles _ this summer. Watch for the stories in Travel each week
until Sept. 3. For more pictures from Oklahoma City or to read
earlier stories, log on to www.kcstar.com//fyi//fyi.htm. Look for
the I-35 Odyssey icon.
</P>
<P>
   Next week: See every kind of lighter imaginable in Guthrie,
Okla.
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ I'm going to let you in on a little secret.
Oklahoma City is gettin' hip. That's right, Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Used to be that a lot of Kansas Citians saw Oklahoma City as a
bottleneck in their race to get to Texas. Now it's becoming a
place, not just to slow down, but to stop.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons is Bricktown.
</P>
<P>
   Once a decaying, 20-block warehouse district on the southeast
corner of downtown, Bricktown was named for its brick sidewalks and
streets. Revitalization began in the mid-1990s, and now there are
restaurants and bars, the Southwestern Bell Bricktown Ball Park and
a canal with water taxis, as well as other attractions and
businesses. That's right, in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, sophisticates such as we here in Kansas City don't
give much respect to Oklahoma City. We'd rather point to our
Country Club Plaza, Westport, the River Market or any of a dozen
plans on the drawing board that we think are going to elevate us in
the eyes of tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But Oklahoma City's $700 million downtown renovation is going to
put it on the map, too. A renovated convention center adjacent to
Bricktown and three new downtown hotels are expected to
dramatically increase the number of conventions there. That's
right, in Oklahoma City. In the beginning
</P>
<P>
   Bricktown Brewery manager Jim Cowan marvels at the explosion of
restaurants and bars in the area since 1992, when the first brewpub
in the state opened in Bricktown. Now there are 18, with more
planned or under construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last year we seemed to be on the verge of a boom,''
said Cowan, who also is president of the Bricktown Merchants
Association.
</P>
<P>
   A theater complex and 20,000-seat downtown arena, both slated to
open in 2001, will be magnets that will draw more people to
Bricktown, Cowan said. He hints that Oklahoma City will make a
strong bid for the Big 12 basketball tournament once the new arena
opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last trigger (of Bricktown development) will be the movie
theater project that is close to starting construction,'' he said.
The complex will have 20 regular movie screens plus a 3-D IMAX
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Across from the brewery stands Chelino's, with by far the best
Mexican food I found on my nearly two weeks this spring exploring
I-35 _ and that includes Laredo, Texas, hard by the Rio Grande,
where I began this I-35 odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Chelino's has a main level plus has two upstairs dining rooms
and three outside terraces. It's huge. For me, the chicken fajitas
made the trip worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Chelino's outside terraces overlook the Bricktown Canal, where
water taxis glide day and night. The canal, which connects to the
North Canadian River south of downtown, was built for the taxis. A
taxi pass will let you get on and off the taxis all day; hours vary
from late morning until 11 p.m. and later on weekends, holidays and
during special events. A narrator describes points of interest
along the way. Brick paths line both sides of the canals for
pedestrians. You could ride the water taxis for transportation, but
most attractions in Bricktown are no more than three or four blocks
from one another. Could be crowded
</P>
<P>
   So far business bustles some days, then lags on others, Cowan
said. When the theaters open next year, he thinks crowds will
increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the weekends things are fantastic,'' he said, ``but the
crowds are event-driven. When we have an arena football game, when
we have the RedHawks (the Triple-A baseball team), then Bricktown
is covered up. If we have a Wednesday night in the summer with no
baseball, football or conventions, you don't see as much activity
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southwestern Bell Bricktown Ballpark anchors the southeast
corner of Bricktown, and its brick-dominated architecture blends
nicely with the brick streets and sidewalks. Completed in 1998, the
park seats 15,000 and draws more than 650,000 fans each year to see
the RedHawks, a farm club of the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a message here if you read between the lines. Call ahead
if you want to make sure there's a place to park and room in the
restaurants to eat.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, at 9 p.m. July 1, a Saturday, my family pulled off
I-35 on our annual trip to see my in-laws in Texas. Bound for
Chelino's, we threaded our way through Bricktown. The streets and
parking lots were packed with holiday revelers. We opted to pass on
through and stop on the way back, after the holiday. By the
afternoon of July 5, we found it easy to park and found plenty of
places to sit in Chelino's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fourth of July is the biggest weekend down here,'' Cowan
said. ``We have a history of fireworks displays and parades, stuff
that's pedestrian-friendly. Last year (on the Fourth of July) we
marked the opening of the canal.'' The renaissance
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City's revival was born of despair, said Sara Atkins,
an economic development officer with the Greater Oklahoma City
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes back to 1993 when we were trying to get a major
airline, and we didn't get 'em,'' she said. The mayor then, Ron
Norick, decided to call the airline to find out why it stiffed OKC,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So anyway, Ron calls them up and says, `How come you didn't
choose us?' They said, `Quite frankly, we don't think your city is
that attractive.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron said, `We're going to have to invest in ourselves.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Norick went to the taxpayers for a sales tax increase. The
$350,000, raised over 5 years, is being matched by private funds,
Atkins said. The money goes for several projects, of which
Bricktown is currently the most visible. Two other Oklahoma City
business districts, Automobile Alley and Stockyards City, were
included in the same renovation project. Both will cater primarily
to business tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Some Bricktown buildings are still under renovation. The old
Santa Fe Depot, for instance, will be completed next year, but is
already serving as an Amtrak station with trains going south to
Fort Worth and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bricktown is a dining and entertainment draw, many
tourists stop in Oklahoma City to visit the memorial that
commemorates one of its greatest tragedies. The Oklahoma City
National Memorial, on the north side of downtown, was dedicated
April 19 of this year, at the site of the bombing of the Alfred P.
Murrah Federal Building on April 19, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The design features a reflecting pool and 168 chairs, one for
each of the bombing victims who died. Atkins, a survivor who was
working in the adjacent Journal-Record Building during the blast,
said the new memorial is ``absolutely beautiful at night.''
Vacation time?
</P>
<P>
   To the vacationer, Oklahoma City used to be nothing more than
truck stops and gas stations, interspersed with motels. You might
eat or get gas, and if you were tired, you might sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But now there's Bricktown, too, a welcome respite. You might not
plan a week's vacation here, but there's enough to keep you busy
for a day or two. According to Chamber of Commerce estimates,
Bricktown drew 4 million people last year. The chamber projects 3
million additional customers by 2002, after the arena and theater
openings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to be down here, to have people have Oklahoma
City on the map when they think of tourism.'' Cowan said.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, Oklahoma City. OKLAHOMA CITY INFO: Farm club
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma RedHawks, who play baseball at the Southwestern
Bell Bricktown Ball Park, are a Triple-A farm club for the Texas
Rangers. Taxi please
</P>
<P>
   More than 250,000 people showed up last summer to see the
dedication of the Bricktown Canal and the inaugural voyages of the
Bricktown Water Taxis. Conventions double
</P>
<P>
   The Myriad Convention Center, adjacent to Bricktown, added
100,000 square feet of convention space to it existing structure in
1999. Convention bookings there doubled to 111 conventions in the
year 2000. Sports fans
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma Wranglers arena football team and the Oklahoma City
Blazers hockey team of the Central Hockey League each draw an
average of 9,000 fans to their games at the Myriad center. Fill 'er
up
</P>
<P>
   Motorists in Oklahoma City paid as little as $1.31 for unleaded
gasoline last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
