</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL COVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL-SERVICE _ Awaiting details of the funeral arrangements
for Sen. Paul Coverdell, and any word on his replacement. Bush may
attend. (Fosket, etc. , Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL-PROJECTS _WASHINGTON _ A look at what projects
Coverdell was working on and what happens to his role at the
Republican National Convention. (Eversley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COVERSENATE _ WASHINGTON _ An official day of remembrance hasn't
been designated yet, but tributes poured forth on the Senate floor
Wednesday morning for the late Sen. Paul Coverell (R-Ga.). A vase
of white roses sat on his Senate desk, now coverd in black.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL-MEDIA _ Piedmont hospital's announcement that the
media reports were wrong and Coverdell was alive (though he had
died 10 minutes before) was a huge media disaster for the hospital
and spokeswoman Nina Montanaro. We'll try to trace how that
happened, and what the hospital will do in the future to prevent
those kinds of blunders, plus include what the networks plan to do
on funeral coverage for the senator. (Jubera, Druckenmiller,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COVERDELL-STROKE _Trying to get the doctors/hospital to talk to
us about Coverdell's treatment, which may be impossible given that
the family must grant permission for that to happen. But we'll try
to get docs to talk about how people with his condition are
typically treated and how important it is to get to the hospital
immediately, not wait three weeks like he did. Doctors probably
could have saved him, perhaps with interventional radiology to shut
off the bleeding aneurysm _ one of the specialities at Piedmont.
We'll try to reach Dr. Lou Jacobs, who specializes in that, and
other doctors who might comment on the difficulty of treating the
kind of stroke Coverdell had. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DALEY _ NASHVILLE, Tenn. - William Daley formally takes control
of Vice President Al Gore's presidential campaign as its overall
chairman this week. But how will Daley, a product of the
rough-and-tumble politics of Chicago, work with Donna Brazille,
Gore's street-tough campaign manager from Louisiana? (Shepard, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-SENATE _ With the unexpected passing of Georgia's senior
Senator, speculation is already rampant over who'll run for the
seat in November, and who, if anyone, Barnes will appoint to the
seat. Everyone from Zell Miller to Johnny Isakson has been
mentioned. But nobody's talking much on the record yet out of
respect for Coverdell. Still, as one wonk said, don't be surprised
if potential candidates are buttonholing people at Coverdell's
funeral. (Chapman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GREY-MARKET _ WASHINGTON _ In a setback for states with tobacco
settlements, a proposal to ban the sale of ``gray market''
cigarettes was eliminated from a trade bill Wednesday. (O'Dell, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-SCOUTS _ WASHINGTON _ A group of liberal House Democrats on
Wednesday sent a letter to President Clinton asking him to step
down as honorary head of the Boy Scouts of America. The group also
introduced legislation to revoke the Scouts' federal charter _ a
symbolic action _ following a Supreme Court ruling that the
organization could bar homosexuals. (Dart, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIANS _ WACO, Texas _ It's up in the air as to whether the
fifth issue in the Branch Davidians' wrongful-death lawsuit _
whether FBI agents fired at the Davidians on April 19, 1993 _ will
be heard. Houston attorney Mike Caddell indicated last week that he
was dropping the issue. A representative of Waco's federal court
said it has not been contacted by the other attorneys for the
plaintiffs yet on whether they want a hearing. (Waco
Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
