tobacco case pints to the disconnect between the public and elected
officials, who are bent on giving tobacco breaks and protections.
(The Atlanta Constitution) 8. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ U.S. Magistrate Judge Michael Merz, who is
president of the board of trustees of the Montgomery County
Historical Society, is spearheading a save-the-courthouse movement,
a creative partnership of county officials and the Historical
Society. ``It (the courthouse) is one of a kind in the nation,''
Merz said. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ Even if the tobacco companies once again walk
away without shelling out a single red cent, the industry took an
old-fashioned behind-the-barn whipping at the hands of a six-member
Miami-Dade County jury. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ With Austin residents using a
record-setting amount of water and putting a strain on the city's
distribution system, we present for your consideration Kelso's
Stage 4 Mandatory Water Conservation Program. (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
