<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ Ken Medernach is on to something. With killer
heat and drought, gardening isn't much fun. Meanwhile, Ken has
found a way to enhance just about any growing space: those still
looking good, as well as the many that are dying and dragging and
flagging. He goes to his basement workshop and creates all sorts of
copper pieces, including statuary, garden torches, tomato cages,
fountains and birdbaths with recycling pumps _ and whatever else
his clients' imagination might come up with. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PONDS _ Like the estimated 9 million homeowners with ponds
across the country, Dick and Joann Kochs have the fever and warn it
can be contagious, too. If you don't believe them, they say, try
visiting some of the 50 metro-area ponds this month and next on the
Atlanta-based National Pond Society's 12th annual tour.
``Pondering,'' as the hobbyists call it, reels in most converts by
whetting their appetites with examples of what can be done. It must
work because the number of water gardening enthusiasts grows by 30
percent annually. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-FANS _ If you can lower the humidity inside your house
during the cooling season, you can raise the thermostat on your air
conditioner and still feel cool. That's why adding a bathroom
exhaust fan or a range hood that exhausts outdoors is a good
investment for saving energy. Today we'll concentrate on bathroom
fans, but installing a range hood is not much different. (Cummings,
Dayton Daily News) 25. WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is James Cummings' Nuts &AMP; Bolts column
</P>
<P>
   GRASS _ Ode to the joy of grass or joy of not watering, or
