<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-PORTERWAGNER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wagoner rolls again
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bless his pea-pickin' heart. Porter Wagoner, the last living,
rhinestoned relic of the Grand Ole Opry, has made a new album that
is as naive and untarnished as Grandma's Sunday china. No, he still
can't sing all that well. And the simplistic arrangements and
melodies here sound like Wagoner, 72, hasn't turned on the radio in
35 years. In fact, most of the tunes are so literal and trite they
could have been in the soundtrack of Robert Altman's searing
indictment of country music, the movie ``Nashville.'' (Remember
Karen Black's ``Rolling Stone (Gathers No Moss)''?) But in today's
country music, Wagoner's outing is like a big spoonful of cowpeas _
simple, familiar and satisfying. Whether it's a song about missing
the spring nesting of bluebirds (``Watching Eagles Fly'') or
childhood memories about a kid down the street nicknamed
``Scooter'' (``House on Mulberry Street''), the tunes are as
wistful and heart-warming as old black-and-white photos in a
scrapbook. If you are looking for the kind of scratchy country
music that will have you crying in your beer in spite of uneven
quality, here it is.
</P>
<P>
   `The Best I've Ever Been'
</P>
<P>
   Porter Wagoner. Shell Point Records. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : More on Porter Wagoner:
www.country.com/gen/music/artist/porter-wagoner.htm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
