<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6819 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-NINEYARDS20-COX     07-19 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-NINEYARDS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hit-man comedy wholly satisfying a `The Whole Nine Yards' from
Willis
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a comedy with a body count and familiar mafia premise, but
with enough twists to overcome its familiarity. Bruce Willis stars
as a hit man who moves next door, incognito, to henpecked dentist
Matthew Perry. As in ``The Sixth Sense,'' Willis doesn't seem to
mind playing genial straight man to his cast mates: Perry, Patricia
Arquette and Kevin Pollack. The movie's high point is Amanda Peet's
giddy performance as a dental technician who wants to make a very
unusual career change.
</P>
<P>
   `The Whole Nine Yards'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For the official movie site:
www.thewholenineyards.net/
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Angela's Ashes'' (R) _ A finely made adaptation of Frank
McCourt's popular memoir of growing up poor in Ireland that's
almost too stately for its own good. Fans of the book will enjoy
seeing their favorite parts re-created onscreen. Others, who don't
have the memory of McCourt's lyrical prose whispering in their
heads, might wonder what all the fuss is about. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ride With the Devil'' (R) _ Worth the ride. Ang Lee's
fervent, oddly gallant film about the fringes of the Civil War may
be too scattered for some. Like the skirmishes between the
pro-South Bushwackers and the pro-North Jayhawkers, the movie is
random, sprawling and piecemeal, with Quantrill's Raid on Lawrence,
Kan., providing the blood-soaked centerpiece and moral fulcrum. But
others may find it a sublime contemplation on the warring factions
of the American nature _ settling scores vs. settling down. Grade:
B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The War Zone'' (R) _ Actor-turned-director Tim Roth has
created the most Bergman-esque movie since the great Ingmar Bergman
stopped making movies. On the desolate coast of Devon, a seemingly
normal family is beset by secrets and lies that lead to total
breakdown. The teen son (Freddie Cunliffe) suspects his father (Ray
Winstone) is having sex with his older sister (Lara Belmont). A
brutal, challenging film that asks you to take a risky journey.
Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Ninth Gate'' (R) _ This major disappointment from Roman
Polanski stars Johnny Depp in a tale of old books, the devil and a
gateway to satanic powers. Imagine one of those seasonal Halloween
horror houses, but designed by librarians. And what do you get at
the end of the trek? The spectacle of a bunch of rich twits in
black robes, play-acting a satanic mass. Grade: D +
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``What Planet Are You From'' (R) _ It's ``I Married a Stand-Up
From Outer Space.'' A strangely desperate and unfunny comedy about
a galactically equipped alien and his mission to breed with Earth
women. Poor Annette Bening plays one of the women; Garry Shandling,
who also co-wrote and produced this mess, is the R-rated
extraterrestrial. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Stephen Whitty, Newhouse News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Big Tease'' (R) _ A slight bit of silliness about a
Glasgow hairdresser (Craig Ferguson) who thinks he's been invited
to compete in a stylist competition held in L.A. Ferguson is
pleasant enough, and there's good work by Frances Fisher, Mary
McCormack and David Rasche as L.A. types. But for the most part,
the satire is tepid, and the movie more often than not takes the
low-comedy road. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rosetta'' (R) _ When the grim teenage heroine gets thrown
into a muddy pond in this Belgian flick, you'll want to cheer.
Teenage Emilie Dequenne won the top acting award at Cannes for her
deeply annoying performance as a teenager who will do anything it
takes to get a job and get away from her trailer-park life. It's a
slice-of-life flick that mistakes gloom for artistry. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Isn't She Great'' (R) _ Isn't great. Or even good. Bette
Midler plays ``Valley of the Dolls'' author Jacqueline Susann, but
the movie is neither biography nor burlesque. It can't decide if
its main character is great, or a gargoyle. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Diamonds'' (PG-13) _ Kirk Douglas plays an aging boxer and
stroke survivor who convinces his estranged son (Dan Aykroyd) and
loving grandson to drive to Reno, where he stashed some diamonds 60
years ago. The bonding road trip is excruciating, and a visit to a
brothel (run by Lauren Bacall) is almost unwatchable. But then
there's Douglas, game, courageous and still with a legend's sheen.
Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) O N T H E W E B : For upcoming video release dates:
www.comingsoon.net/videos.htm
</P>
<P>
   PIERRE VINET/Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   pictured: Bruce Willis and Matthew Perry in ``The Whole Nine
Yards''
</P>
<P>
   PIERRE VINET / Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Willis (left) and Matthew Perry star in ``The Whole Nine
Yards.''
</P>
