<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6820 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL20-COX     07-19 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `X'actly what we need: Superheroes
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``X-Men,'' the comic phenom that had been roaming around the
``in development'' film beat for almost a decade, has finally made
it to theaters. Its long-term success or failure could mean life or
death for similar comic book projects such as ``Spider-Man,''
``Black Panther'' or ``Sgt. Rock.'' Frankly, I'm still waiting for
the long promised movie version of ``The Fantastic Four'' (the
Invisible Girl would now be the Invisible Woman, i.e., any female
over 40).
</P>
<P>
   But while we're waiting to find out whether the others will make
it to film, here are a few lesser known comic-inspired characters
you may want to check out on video. And not one of them wears a
cape.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Swamp Thing'' (1982): Made my heart sing. This scrappy
little flick brings the DC Comics half-veggie hero to oozy life
with metaphysical philosophy intact and the merest touch of camp
(the relentlessly straight-arrow dialogue, the comic-panel-style
wipes). Evil scientist Louis Jordan (``Gigi'') wants good scientist
Ray Wise's (``Twin Peaks'') secret formula. He leaves Wise for dead
in a swamp where the formula and whatever's been lying around in
the bog for eons (Jimmy Hoffa?) combine to turn him into something
that looks like a cross between the Creature From the Black Lagoon
and the Pillsbury Doughboy with a weak sphincter. Director Wes
Craven went on to fame, fortune and fingernails with his
``Nightmare on Elm Street'' series.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Phantom'' (1996): Since it's fast-paced and
kid-friendly, I'm not sure why this cleverly put-together update of
the old Phantom comic strip never made it big in theaters. Maybe a
Jar Jar Binks would've helped. Created as sort of the thinking
man's Tarzan in 1936, the Phantom wore a mask and a long purple
body stocking instead of a loincloth. And instead of elephants and
an ear-splitting yell, he depended on his wits and a carefully
cultivated superstition, i.e., that he was immortal when, in fact,
his was a 400-year-old father-to-son dynasty. Set in the '30s and
globetrotting back and forth between the Phantom's jungle home and
an art deco Manhattan, the movie is especially notable for its
cast. Billy Zane, who later chased Leo around the sinking Titanic
with a gun, plays the Phantom; Kristy Swanson, the original Buffy
the Vampire Slayer, is a fearless heiress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Li'l Abner'' (1959): Not exactly in the superhero vein, but
certainly cartoonish. This adaptation of a '50s musical based on Al
Capp's satirical comic strip about the denizens of Dogpatch USA may
not be a classic, but its bold set design and art direction make it
seem like the Sunday funnies come to life. Plus, there's a fine
Johnny Mercer score. Designated the most useless place on earth,
Dogpatch is set to become a testing site for atom bombs unless the
inhabitants can find something necessary. Sort of the way the
National Historic Landmark registry works. The stars, Peter Palmer
and Leslie Parrish (Daisy Mae), never went anywhere, but Julie
Newmar became a cult icon thanks to her rendition of Stupefyin'
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Darkman'' (1990): Leave it to Sam Raimi to do it backwards
and get it right. While everyone else was rifling through their old
comics for the next ``Batman,'' Raimi simply created his own comic
book character: a horribly scarred scientist (Liam Neeson) who uses
the experimental synthetic skin he created to wreak vengeance on
the thugs who blew up his lab and ruined his life. Raimi knows the
pulp heart of comic-book love. His movie is brain-poundingly
violent, operatically emotional, and _ rather like ``X-Men'' _
obsessed with the existential angst of being a superpowered freak.
Look for Oscar winner Frances McDormand (``Fargo'') as the female
lead.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more about comics:
www.comicmuseum.com/default.asp
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
