<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6822 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE20-COX     07-19 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Having fun with form and function
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ken Medernach is on to something. With killer heat and drought,
gardening isn't much fun _ though it surely will be again.
Meanwhile, Ken has found a way to enhance just about any growing
space: those still looking good, as well as the many that are dying
and dragging and flagging.
</P>
<P>
   He goes to his basement workshop and creates all sorts of copper
pieces, including statuary, garden torches, tomato cages. Fountains
and birdbaths with recycling pumps _ and whatever else his clients'
imaginations might come up with.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Ken showed off his wares at home in Atlanta (a sign on
the gate says, ``Warning _ Strange Dog''), where he grows a
demonstration garden of copper, seeded and nurtured by the
companionable characteristics of form and function. Gardeners
always have valued the pairing of those traits, seen in so many
plants. How beautiful the form and flowers of the peach tree, the
plum, apple and cherry. How tasty their fruit. Okra's sumptuous
yellow blossom, recalling its lovely cousin, hibiscus, gets outdone
only by the taste of those fine pods sliced and fried in cornmeal.
That's function for you.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at Ken's tomato cage, I thought, this would look good in
my garden even if I had my usual short crop of squirrel-devastated
'maters. Similarly, his spiral sprinkler of copper tubing adds zip
and flash even if it's standing dry half the time because of the
drought-imposed cuts in water usage. Ken says he tells gardeners
that, when they buy sprinklers these days, they're ``serving art.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Ken is doing. A 15-year building contractor (also
a buddy with a serious gift for cooking and martini-making), he has
loved metal art and craft since the 1950s, when he held an
after-school job in a Savannah welding shop. Over the years, Ken
has worked mostly with copper but also with steel, wood and stone.
His art, which provides a calming counterpoint to the hassles of
building and remodeling, began asserting itself dramatically about
a year ago, when Ken, mentored by metal artist Ivan Bailey, spent
more and more time working with the copper sheets, tubing and pipe,
using heat, anvil, hammer, band saw and snips to make the metal
what he wants it to be. He first set up on a concrete pad outside,
but when a pignut hickory began throwing down on him, ``I figured
I'd have to move inside or wear a hard hat.'' No, wife Meg and
daughter Erin don't bend and pound metal; ``they kibitz.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many who have seen a pastime grow into a passion, Ken
nurtures a hope for his metal sculpting: ``to at some point make a
living at it and stop being a building contractor.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the appeal of copper?
</P>
<P>
   An avid gardener, Ken likes the metal's aging process,
describing it in ways he might talk about the changes in a shrub or
tree as it matures, grows great bark, changes appearance with the
seasons: ``Copper enhances itself, taking on a rich brown patina
that becomes mahogany. After many years _ it could take up to 20 _
it turns green.''
</P>
<P>
   As garden material, copper gets beautiful competition from
bamboo. But, says Ken, the reeds are good for a mere season or so,
while ``copper is virtually forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Long enough for all the down-pressed, heat-struck,
drought-stricken gardens to recover their form and function. I
hope.
</P>
<P>
   For information, on Ken Medernach's copper tomato cage, call
404-875-5905.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
