r l BC-PONDS20-COX     07-19 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PONDS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlantans find one cool hobby in water gardening
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dick and Joann Koch thought they were fixing a drainage problem
eight years ago when they hauled huge rocks into their Marietta,
Ga., back yard.
</P>
<P>
   The rocks solved their erosion woes all right but also laid the
foundation for a hobby about which they've grown passionate _ water
gardening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love it. It just becomes a part of you,'' Joann said of the
two earthen ponds and waterfall her husband built.
</P>
<P>
   Like the estimated 9 million homeowners with ponds across the
country, the Koches have the fever _ big time _ and warn it can be
contagious, too.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe them, they say, try visiting some of the 50
metro-area ponds this month and next on the Atlanta-based National
Pond Society's 12th annual tour. ``Pondering,'' as the hobbyists
call it, reels in most converts by whetting their appetites with
examples of what can be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every pond creates another pond with visitors and neighbors,''
said Roswell, Ga., resident Alan Sperling, whose pond, along with
the Koches', is on tour.
</P>
<P>
   He should know. Sperling founded the National Pond Society 11
years ago after growing desperate for help in locating supplies and
advice. He was living in Acworth at the time and ran a newspaper ad
asking people to share their pond knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got about a thousand calls,'' said Sperling, a retired
engineer. With that kind of response, he organized the nonprofit
group and started a newsletter, which evolved into a magazine,
Pondscapes, published from his home office. Membership now totals
more than 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The number of water gardening enthusiasts, which Sperling said
grows by 30 percent annually, has skyrocketed in recent years as
improvements are made to pond products and hobbyists discover the
benefits of relaxation and family activity.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years, the pond society's members were 50 and
older; today, most are 30 to 35. The vast majority own water
gardens with aquatic plants and fish _ from large earthen ponds to
lined pools and even just containers, Sperling said. A small
percentage tend strictly to Japanese koi ponds.
</P>
<P>
   Another group devoted to the hobby, the International Waterlily
and Water Gardening Society, has members, including commercial
suppliers, in 30 countries. Ironically, its U.S. offices are in
Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   So why so much interest in the Atlanta area?
</P>
<P>
   First, the mild climate allows for all types of gardening nearly
year round _ lucky for Atlantans, who love their yards. Second,
gardeners, like gracious Southerners, know the value of sharing
information and ponderers are among the most willing, Sperling
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You meet the most fabulous people with ponds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As proof that pondering is contagious, Sperling estimates there
are some 5,000 ponds within a five-mile radius of his Roswell home.
</P>
<P>
   There, he and his wife, Madalyn, have created a marina-like
setting along a steep embankment on Loch Highland Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a master plan for the site because everybody
who visited us contributed by saying, 'Can you imagine if you did
this, or did that,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a series of gray wooden decks, stairs and bridges,
lined with rope bannisters, that meanders several water features.
They begin with a pool, created by Mystic Ponds &AMP; Waterfalls, where
the boards in one bridge are spaced far enough apart so that water,
accented with lights, is visible at night.
</P>
<P>
   From the pool, a waterfall built from rock spills into a gentle
stream. ``My wife and I hauled in 11 tons of rock by rolling each
one of them down the hill,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Farther downhill, Sperling split the stream in two _ not an easy
feat. It then feeds into an L-shaped water garden, filled with gold
fish and plants.
</P>
<P>
   Raised storage bins along the deck's edge not only hide the
pond's mechanics but make for handy benches for enjoying the shady
setting. ``Observation, if you hang around a pond, is the best way
to manage it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Koch picked out his spot early on when he and his wife
built their pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I just sit,'' he said, pointing to one of the
rocks _ all hand picked _ he hauled in with heavy equipment.
</P>
<P>
   It all started when his next door neighbors attempted to build
their house on a rocky site. They needed to get rid of the rock,
and the Kochs were battling erosion along a kudzu-covered ravine
that flows past their house.
</P>
<P>
   Dick , a computer consultant, used the rocks to build two
earthen ponds _ each 20 by 60 feet and 3 feet deep _ connected by a
waterfall. Pumps circulate the water from a spring at the top of
the hill into the first pond, then over the waterfall and into the
lower pond, then finally a spillway that empties into the
Chattahoochee River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being earthen ponds, they're never really crystal clear, but
we like the natural look of them,'' said Joann, retired from the
hotel food industry.
</P>
<P>
   She spends most days gardening along the embankments, lined with
river birches, rhododendron, ferns and colorful impatiens, while
her husbands maintains the ponds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't enjoy something like this, it can become a chore,
said Dick, who drains the ponds to about one foot every spring to
clean them.
</P>
<P>
   That requires moving some 100 fish, including three koi about 2
feet long, which Dick wraps in towels for a quick but precarious
transfer from one pond to the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``What started as a maintenance project is now a major hobby for
us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention a beautiful setting that's a far cry from that
kudzu-ensnared ravine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're out here you don't realize you're sitting almost
in the middle of the city,'' Joann said of the site, where a family
of mallards has taken up residence. ``It's like you're way up in
the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's another benefit _ that one thing that keeps spawning
more ponderers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be able to help other people get started,'' she
said. ``By visiting ponds, they see it's something they, too, can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   National Pond Society
</P>
<P>
   Tour of Ponds
</P>
<P>
   When/Where: 9 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturday _ 20 ``west side'' ponds,
East Point, Marietta, Roswell, Kennesaw, Canton, Acworth; 9 a.m.-6
p.m. July 29 _ 20 ``east side'' ponds, Duluth, Lawrenceville,
Lilburn, Conyers, Ellenwood; 8 p.m.-midnight Aug. 26 (Night Tour) _
10 ponds, Roswell, Marietta
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $10.50 for minimum two.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 770-643-0112 or visit the NPS Web site at www.
ponds(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Points to ponder
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Site your pond close to your house to enjoy the sights and
sounds from indoors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make your water garden at least 18 inches deep _ more if you
plan to include Japanese koi. Deeper ponds may require fencing.
Check your local zoning laws for pools and fences.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For safety's sake, don't consider a pond if you have children
under 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't rush when building a pond. Have a plan but first get to
know the site by working it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't forget electricity when considering costs. For a basic
pond, count on a liner costing about 80 cents a square foot; pump,
$100; filter, $200; rocks, $175 a ton. Other costs include plants,
fish, hardscaping, lighting, outdoor furniture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Visit ponds; research products before launching construction.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use pond water, which is recirculated, to water lawns and
plants.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Start small when adding fish (four to six), regardless of pond
size, until you get used to caring for them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Control algae by providing the right conditions _ the right
types and number of plants, few fish, little sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Source: National Pond Society
</P>
