<SLUG> BC-BUYERSEDGE-BUGS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The buzz on bugs
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's that? Butterflies in the punch bowl? A trail of ants
across the picnic plate? Bugs atop the napkins?
</P>
<P>
   Such pests are usually the uninvited guests at summer
gatherings, but this year they are the life of the party _ or at
least the partyware.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bugs, butterflies and dragonflies are on everything from
glasses to dishes to napkins,'' said Suzanne Williamson, author of
``Entertaining for Dummies'' ($19.95, I.D.G.) and consultant to
Rich's. The whimsical winged things just seem to go with the more
casual summer entertaining atmosphere, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Real bugs are likely to be a part of a porch party anyway. And
the drought is driving many pests indoors. Why not also invite
inside buggy napkin rings or bumble bee votives? And if the
lightning bugs aren't providing enough twinkles, just string up a
set of dragonfly patio lights.
</P>
<P>
   We found everything from colorful bee-themed tumblers at
Wal-Mart to a red-checkered tinware plate with a trail of ants
painted across it at Metropolitan Deluxe in Virginia-Highland.
Paper plates splattered with images of bugs and captions of ``eek''
and ``gross'' (also at Metropolitan Deluxe) are sure to get the
guests buzzing.
</P>
<P>
   And at Watershed in Decatur, we found a clever dragonfly made of
pantyhose stretched around a wire hanger frame and painted green
that can be attached to anything from the edge of the table to a
centerpiece flower arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson said the critters can even be used creatively for
more formal table settings. ``I love the juxtaposition of engraved
linens, bone china, sparkling crystal and a few bugs painted on
tabletop pieces,'' she said. ``To carry the bug theme further, use
branches and leaves for a centerpiece and large-leaf-patterned
linens, and serve chocolate-covered ants with coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   And the best part _ the bugs won't bite.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
