r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP20-COX     07-19 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Watermelon rind suitable for specialties
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While waiting for watermelon time, we set aside a request from
Bessie Jo Britt of Decatur, Ga., for her long-lost recipes for
watermelon rind preserves and pickles like her mother made.
</P>
<P>
   These timeless instructions for using otherwise-castoff rinds
were preserved in our files. They have been published many times
and undoubtedly will be again on some future hot summer day.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Watermelon
</P>
<P>
   Rind Pickles
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 5 pints
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 3-4 hours, plus overnight
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 1 1/4 hours, plus processing time
</P>
<P>
   3 quarts (about 6 pounds) watermelon rind, unpared
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup salt
</P>
<P>
   3 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts (about 2 trays) ice cubes
</P>
<P>
   9 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   6 cinnamon sticks, 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, thinly sliced, with seeds removed
</P>
<P>
   Pare the peel and all pink edges from the watermelon rind. Cut
into 1-inch squares or fancy shapes as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Mix salt with 3 quarts of cold water. Cover prepared rind with
this brine. Add ice cubes and let stand 3 to 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Drain; rinse in cold water. Cover with cold water and cook until
fork tender, about 10 minutes. Do not overcook. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, vinegar and water. Tie cloves and cinnamon sticks
in a clean, thin white cloth. Add to sugar mixture. Boil 5 minutes.
Remove spice bag and set aside. Pour syrup over the watermelon
rinds; add lemon slices. Let stand overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Heat watermelon in syrup to boiling and cook slowly for 1 hour.
Sterilize canning jars. Pack hot pickles loosely into clean, hot
pint jars. To each jar, add 1 piece of stick cinnamon from spice
bag; cover with boiling syrup to 1/2 inch from top. Remove air
bubbles. Wipe jar rims. Adjust lids. Process 10 minutes in a
boiling water bath.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon : 46 calories, trace protein, no fat, 12 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 297 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Watermelon Rind
</P>
<P>
   Preserves
</P>
<P>
   Fills 6 half-pint jars
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 5 1/2-6 1/2 hours, divided
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 45 minutes, plus processing time
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 quarts prepared watermelon rind
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts cold water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   4 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   7 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 thinly sliced lemon
</P>
<P>
   Trim green skin and pink flesh from thick watermelon rind; cut
into 1-inch pieces. Dissolve salt in 2 quarts water and pour over
rind; let stand 5 to 6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Drain, rinse and drain again. Cover with cold water and let
stand for 30 minutes. Drain. Sprinkle ginger over rind; cover with
water and cook until fork tender. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   To make preserves, sterilize canning jars. Combine sugar, lemon
juice and 7 cups water. Boil 5 minutes; add rind and boil gently
for 30 minutes. Add sliced lemon and cook until the melon rind is
clear. Pack hot preserves into hot jars, leaving 1/4-inch head
space. Wipe jar rims and adjust lids. Process 5 minutes in a
boiling water bath.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 45 calories, trace protein, no fat, 11 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 87 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Request
</P>
<P>
   A Jonesboro, Ga., woman is looking for a cake made with fresh
kiwis.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
