<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find itemsBy Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My sister in Chicago gave me a great candle made by Trapp
Private Gardens. It really smells terrific! My favorite scent is
Rejuvenating Rain. Where can I purchase more of these candles here
in Atlanta? My sister's suitcase is getting heavy bringing me
candles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Debbie Baugher, Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We didn't have to burn the candle at both ends to find this
particular brand. Trapp Private Gardens candles, which are made in
Kansas City, Mo., are available at Hodge Podge, 970 Piedmont Ave.
N.E. (404-874-6037), Lemon Grass in Phipps Plaza (404-760-0503) and
the Mole Hole stores in malls throughout Atlanta. Candles range
from about $4 for the votives, lasting 15-20 hours, to $20 for the
signature perfume candle (in photo), which lasts 45 hours. To
achieve total scent saturation, each candle is infused with a
bottle of perfume, says a company representative. There are 16
scents available, including Guava Mango, Lily of the Valley,
Essence of Gardenia, Orange-Vanilla, Summer Flowers and Cool
Cucumber.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Ricola Pearls _ tiny mints that you can put
under your tongue, to refresh your mouth. They disappeared several
months ago, and I would appreciate it if you could locate a source.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia A. Herman, Lawrenceville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We have a few pearls of widsom for you. A spokeswoman for
Ricola U.S.A., Pamela Hehl Dalessio, says that she does not
``currently have a store location in Atlanta.'' She adds, ``our
mints are widely distributed in metro New York, California and
Hawaii. But we have just gone through a packaging update and are
preparing to increase distribution throughout the rest of the
country.'' You can buy the mints on the Internet at
www.providentinc.com. Or call 215-364-4515. A box of 25 mints is 89
cents. Sugar-free Ricola mints are made from natural herbs grown in
the Swiss mountains. Each little mint _ called a pearl because of
its shape _ has 1.5 calories and comes in peppermint, spearmint,
orange-mint, lemon-mint and menthol eucalyptus.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have combed Atlanta's food markets in a vain attempt to
find finnan haddie. This salted, smoked and dried haddock is a New
England staple and assumes gourmet proportions when properly
prepared. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Lee Palermo,
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: You will soon be savoring finnan haddie, which takes its name
from Finon in Scotland, where it was developed more than 100 years
ago. And haddie is the Scottish term for haddock. We reeled in your
finnan haddie ($6.99 a pound) at Harry's Farmers Market, 1180 Upper
Hembree Road, Alpharetta (770-664-6300). Publix at the Peach, 2868
Peachtree Road N.W., and Cub Foods, 2625 Piedmont Road N.E., will
special order this fish for you. While haddock is naturally white,
finnan haddie is dyed before smoking to give it a characteristic
tawny/amber color.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a WWII Air Force veteran and am looking for a CD or
cassette recording of military bugle calls, from reveille to taps.
Any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   _ George Reid,
</P>
<P>
   Lawrenceville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: At ease, solider. We found your request. Army Surplus Sales,
342 Peachtree St. N.E. (404-521-2227) has the tape of America's
Bugle Calls for $11.99. It includes 58 of the most famous military
bugle calls, including Reveille, Morning Colors Sequence, First
Call, Attention, To the Colors, Carry On, Assembly, First
Sergeant's Call and Taps. Surplus City, 2906 Buford Highway, Duluth
(770-497-4906) can order this tape for $13.95. A CD is $17. Or
order on the Web: www.militaryrecordings.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: During a recent vacation in Florida, I purchased several
packages of Kool-Aid Slushies mix, which makes for a refreshing
summertime treat. I have searched for this product at local grocery
stores but have not had any luck finding it. Please help.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott Morrow, McDonough, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another Slushies request: I am looking for Kool-Aid
Slushies. All flavors are excellent, especially the lemonade. Last
year I could find the mix in grocery stores. But now I am having
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lida Moulder, Palmetto, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Mix it, freeze it, serve it! That's how Kool-Aid describes
Slushies, its seasonal soft frozen beverage mix. We discovered the
icy treat mixes _ in lemonade, cherry and grape _ at the Wal-Mart
in Snellville, 2135 E. Main St. (770-979-2447). Other Wal-Mart
stores also stock this product. A 5-ounce package is 96 cents. Each
packet makes about four 1-cup servings; each serving contains 140
calories but no fat or cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
