<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, July 20, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-VISAS _ WASHINGTON _ Putting pressure on Congress, a
business coalition hosts a news conference Wednesday to urge the
Senate to act on a bill to allow more visas for foreign high-tech
workers. At the same time, a coalition of major Hispanic
organizations and the Congressional Hispanic Caucus will urge that
``Latino fairness'' issues be included in the bill. (Garcia, Cox
News Service) 25.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EARNINGS _ After two consecutive money-losing quarters,
Coca-Cola rebounded to earn $926 million, or 37 cents a share, in
the second quarter. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 20.
</P>
<P>
   GENPARTS-EARNINGS _ Atlanta-based Genuine Parts Co. is releasing
its second-quarter earnings results Wednesday. One interesting
aspect to note is their Internet launch and how well it has done so
far. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 12.
</P>
<P>
   UPS-EARNINGS _ UPS reports earnings. (Hirschman) 10.
</P>
<P>
   IACOCCA _ Lee Iacocca is back in the business world more than 20
years after he rode high as CEO of Chrysler. Now he's pushing a
butter substitute called Olivio. We've got a short one-on-one with
him
</P>
<P>
   plus a report about his new gig. also a box or sider: Iacocca
talks about the biz world today. (Owers, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   DOW _ Disappointed investors dumped the shares of Internet
stocks that failed to meet overly optimistic expectations for
second quarter results, sending all major stock averages lower
despite good news elsewhere in the market. ``It's the Super Bowl
syndrome,'' said John Eade, director of research at Argus Research
in New York. ``The reality never lives up to the hype.'' (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-UNION _ The pilot unions at Delta Air Lines' two regional
subsidiaries are seeking to merge with the carrier's main pilot
union. They say their members are at a disadvantage in pay and
career issues as separate entities, because the Delta union wants
tighter controls on the types of planes the subsidiaries fly.
(Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REC-ROOM _ Dot.com companies that are trying to attract _ and
keep _ younger employees who grew up playing PlayStation and
Foosball are outfitting their offices with all manner of games and
entertainment. From built-in ``frisbee breaks'' to impromtu
ping-pong tournaments we talk to these fun junkies to find out if
this is any way to run a business. (Harris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
