<HEADER>
A6829 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-JERSEY-GOV-NEWHOUSE &LR;      07-19 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERSEY-GOV-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY DEMOCRATS ABANDON MCGREEVEY BID FOR GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, July 18, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With photo of Veronica McGreevey (NNS6). 
 By RON MARSICO and JOE DONOHUE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ On the campaign trail this spring, Democratic
U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine repeatedly implored whoever was
listening to support Woodbridge Mayor Jim McGreevey for governor
next year.
</P>
<P>
   His comments at a Democratic Party confab in Atlantic City in
early May were typical. ``You can make certain Jim McGreevey is
that governor.''
</P>
<P>
   That was then.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., abruptly entering
the gubernatorial fray, Corzine -- like various other Democrats who
were behind the Woodbridge mayor just a few days ago -- has
recalled his endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's remaining neutral and focusing on this year's race,''
said Tom Shea, Corzine's spokesman, this week. He said his boss was
attending a family event and was unavailable for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very close to both of them. He just doesn't want to
distract attention from what he's trying to accomplish this year,''
Shea said. Corzine has issued a memo urging his staff to remain
neutral.
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey, who has enlisted his mother and other family members
in an all-out counterattack, said he was unfazed by news that
Corzine was shifting to neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our most important task is to secure Mr. Corzine's election as
the next U.S. senator. Unfortunately, gubernatorial politics are
now distracting us from the primary charge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine is but one on a growing list of prominent Democrats who
have hedged on previous commitments to McGreevey, turning what some
considered a sure-thing primary into a wild Democratic scramble.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, state Senate Minority Leader Richard Codey, a
Democrat who has been a strong McGreevey backer, would say only,
``I expect to be conferring with my chairman and other county
leaders sometime in the very near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Janiszewski, Hudson County executive and county party
leader, previously has said he is reconsidering his endorsement.
Thomas Giblin, Democratic State Committee chairman and Essex County
chairman, who had been backing McGreevey, said he would convene a
meeting of local party officials to reassess the situation.
</P>
<P>
   While McGreevey, who narrowly lost the governorship in 1997,
says he is in the race to stay, supporters of Torricelli are trying
to create the impression of a juggernaut behind the senator's bid
to wrest away the party's nomination. Many are buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like Poland,'' said one Democrat of the Torricelli
offensive against McGreevey. ``It was blitzkrieg. There was some
opposition. But it was mopped up relatively quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey denied his campaign was in panic mode even though his
supporters were working a frantic pace trying to keep his campaign
from collapsing. McGreevey has even had family members lighting up
the phone lines on his behalf for the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Ronnie McGreevey, Jim McGreevey's mom, calling,'' said
Veronica McGreevey, working her way through a list of Essex County
Democratic committee members Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know we came so close in '97, within one point, right?
Jim's been working all up and down the state for three years. We're
asking for your support. We want to take back the Statehouse
together. What do you think about that?''
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey's sister, father and fiancee have all been calling
local-level Democrats since late last week in what McGreevey called
a ``stepped-up'' phone campaign following the emergence of the
Torricelli threat. McGreevey said the team has made more than 2,000
calls in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   The calls have been made out of the office of Gary Taffet, an
insurance executive who formerly served as McGreevey's chief of
staff and currently heads his political operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's (Torricelli) a great senator,'' said Veronica McGreevey.
``We're putting in a junior senator, Corzine. We need to keep a
senior senator in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning his deferential tone of the past few days, McGreevey
took a swipe at Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Governor's Office is not simply a matter of one person's
ambitions or political interests. It ought not be about political
gamesmanship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey said he remains ``confident'' while citing strong
support statewide among labor officials, elected officials,
grass-roots organizers and clergy members.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Fran Fiore, staff representative of Communications Workers of
America Local 1040, which has 10,000 members, said a number of
locals met last week and voted to continue to back McGreevey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much our position that Jim McGreevey had our
support last time (in 1997), and he'll have our support again,''
Fiore said.
</P>
<P>
   While both McGreevey and Torricelli supporters claimed to have a
majority of county Democratic chairmen in their camp, clear
divisions were emerging.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming what most had assumed, South Jersey Democratic leader
George Norcross said Camden, Burlington and Gloucester counties,
which produce 82 percent of the region's votes, all will be backing
Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``People view Torricelli as a lock. And that's what's driving
this more than anything else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not since Brendan Byrne has a statewide candidate been drafted
for governor, and Bob Torricelli is being besieged by those who
want him to lead this party to victory,'' Norcross said.
</P>
<P>
   But Chuck Chiarello, Atlantic County chairman, said he intends
to remain with McGreevey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have loyalty and respect for Jim McGreevey, and I'm sticking
with Jim. I've been part of a commitment to Jim from Day One --
back when it wasn't even fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't have some loyalty, I don't think you have much
credibility in politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most other party leaders tended to praise both prospective
contenders and acknowledged divided loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Torricelli, Union County chairwoman Charlotte
DeFilippo said, ``Love him dearly, he's a great senator. But I'm
behind Jim McGreevey. Union County has been with and intends to
stay with McGreevey. He's a party builder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My phones have been ringing off the hooks from both sides,''
said Thomas Pankok, the Salem chairman. ``I'm really thinking
seriously of taking a neutral position and just staying out of it.
I think I'm to the point now where I'm just going to refuse to talk
about it to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ron Marsico and Joe Donohue are staff writers for The
Star-Ledger of Newark, N.J. Star-Ledger staff writers David Kinney
and Alexander Lane contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
