<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAY ATTENTION TO VOLTAGE AND FREQUENCY ABROAD
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I'm moving to Europe and wish to take my computer with me.
Will I have a problem with the computer because of the different
electrical standards overseas?
</P>
<P>
   A: Different European countries have different electrical
standards, so find out ahead of time what the voltage and frequency
rates are for your new home. Most computers of recent vintage,
especially laptops, should be able to handle it.
</P>
<P>
   Most electrical current in the United States operates at 110 to
120 volts, with a frequency of 60 hertz, while other parts of the
world use 220 to 240 volts and varying frequencies (usually 50
hertz in Europe). Ireland, for example, operates at 220 volts, 50
hertz.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a Windows-based PC, check the back of the computer
for the voltage switch that leads to the computer's power supply,
inside the case. You will probably see a switch that will let you
manually select either 115 volts for use on U.S. electrical systems
or 230 volts for use with European standards.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer states that the majority of its Macintosh
computers that were manufactured after the Macintosh SE model in
1987 are ``universal'' and can handle currents between 100 and 240
volts, and 50 to 60 hertz. To determine whether a Mac is indeed
universal, look at the machine's FCC identification label for its
voltage requirements, or refer to the technical specifications
section of the user's manual. Some Apple machines have a manual
voltage selector that allows you to choose 110 or 220 volts.
</P>
<P>
   Your monitor, printer and other devices may not be so versatile,
so refer to the electrical specifications in the documentation that
came with your equipment. If the country you're moving to uses a
line frequency other than 50 to 60 hertz, make sure your devices
are flexible, or ``frequency independent,'' to ensure proper
performance. Apple says most of its products are indeed frequency
independent, but double-check before using any particular device.
If you have lost the manuals that came with your Mac, Apple has a
searchable Tech Info Library at til.info.apple.com.
</P>
<P>
   PCs running Windows, DOS, OS/2 or other operating systems are
made by a wide range of different companies, so refer to the
manufacturer's technical specs for your machine. Most computer
makers will have that information in the tech support area of their
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   You can get a voltage converter for around $30 to $40. And you
will probably also need a plug adapter (or a set of them) for your
various power cords.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I use a different keyboard layout for my computer besides
the American one? Is there a system setting to change, or do I have
to buy a program and a new keyboard to do that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both the Windows and Macintosh operating systems will allow
you to substitute foreign-language keyboard layouts. For Windows
98, go to the Start menu, then Settings and Control Panel, then
double-click on the Keyboard icon. Click on the Language tab, then
on Add. Pick your choice from the pop-up list.
</P>
<P>
   For the Macintosh, go to the Apple menu to Control Panels and
select Keyboard. You will see a list of languages. Check the one
you wish to use. If you don't see the additional keyboards, you may
need to install the files from your operating system's CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   The accents, alphabet and punctuation for many languages,
including Danish, French, Norwegian, Spanish and German, are
usually readily available. If you need a language that you don't
see listed, check with your operating system's maker for additional
language kits. Appropriate keyboards (or inexpensive letter
stickers to use with yourU.S. model) are available, and you can
find a good supply of foreign-language hardware and software at
www.worldlanguage.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
