<HEADER>
A6840 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-CHEM-HAZARDS-1     07-19 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEM-HAZARDS-1,000&AMP;ADD-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISHAP AT CHEMICAL-WEAPONS INCINERATOR UNDERSCORES PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednesday, July 19, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With photo of Veronica McGreevey (NNS6). 
 By BRENT HUNSBERGER  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It began with a jammed feed-chute gate deep within the country's
only working chemical-weapons incinerator.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six hours of repairs, an inexperienced furnace
operator, whose boss felt the event ripe for a little on-the-job
training, became overwhelmed by a series of automatic system
shutdowns his work manual didn't cover.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, nobody told him about the sock of sarin-laced trash
workers left atop the chute after cleaning it. Hours later, his
superiors discounted alarms and ordered him to keep relighting a
furnace, even as the sock's deadly fumes had been sucked through
hundreds of feet of pollution controls into Utah's cool desert air.
</P>
<P>
   The leaks the night of May 8 and 9 likely amounted to two drops,
traveled only 8 feet and posed no risk to 32,000 residents near the
Tooele Chemical Agent Disposal Facility, said U.S. Centers for
Disease Control officials.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials emphasize the leaks occurred during an unusual
repair and don't reflect normal operations. They insist that new
safeguards being built into three similar incinerators throughout
the United States -- in Umatilla, Ore.; Pine Bluff, Ark.; and
Anniston, Ala. -- would have prevented the leak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we can do is retrain and once again
re-emphasize an overall safety culture,'' Army spokesman Greg
Mahall said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Utah environmental officials have shut down Tooele -- its
fifth such closure in four years -- until the Army puts new
safeguards in place. Congress plans a hearing on the matter later
this year. And in Oregon, state regulators have demanded assurances
that the Army apply recommended fixes to the Umatilla Chemical
Depot before it burns 221,000 munitions filled with 3,000 tons of
sarin, VX and mustard agents. Construction delays have pushed the
start date to 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the incident shows how highly engineered systems can
malfunction in unthinkable ways, overwhelming humans trying to
respond and endangering surrounding populations. One noted
organizational sociologist says even with operator retraining,
other accidents will undoubtedly surprise Army officials as they
fire up the three other incinerators.
</P>
<P>
   ``These systems are not very safe,'' said Charles Perrow, a Yale
University sociologist and author of the book ``Normal Accidents:
Living With High-Risk Technologies.'' ``And I would not want to
live near one.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarin, or GB, is essentially a human pesticide, like everyday
organophosphates that eliminate insects and weeds. Sarin assaults
the nervous system and a fraction of a drop, inhaled, can kill. In
1995, a doomsday cult unleashed sarin in a crowded Tokyo subway,
killing 12 and injuring more than 5,000. But in wind and heat, it
disperses quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Tooele, built 30 miles southwest of Salt Lake City at the
Deseret Chemical Depot, was designed to destroy nearly half of the
nation's chemical-weapons stockpile. It has incinerated 5 million
pounds of agent since 1996. Two of its four furnaces were online on
May 8, the night of the leak, processing fencepost-like M-56
warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The night's events were detailed in four separate investigations
by the Army, the CDC, the Utah Department of Environmental Quality
and the incinerator's operator, EG&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   Just before a 5:30 p.m. shift change, a tipping gate began
sticking inside a 2-by-2-foot metal chute where agent-laced rocket
parts fall into a rotary kiln. Workers left the problem for the
next 12-hour shift, whose manager was the least experienced at
Tooele, and whose regular control-room supervisor had the night
off.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 8, two workers donned masks and full-body vinyl
suits to enter the hot, sarin-laced room and free the gate.
Eventually, they cleaned it using up to 100 gallons of water.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:37 p.m., just before leaving, they set a one-pound bag of
agent-laced fiberglass atop the upper gate of the chute, expecting
it to drop into the furnace upon restart.
</P>
<P>
   In the control room, the furnace operator, using a dozen
computer screens, tried to bring temperatures back up to normal.
Certified for the job only three months earlier, this was his first
experience with an ``upset condition.'' His supervisor thought it
would be a good experience. But his procedure booklet didn't cover
the unusual repair job. And nobody had said anything about the
lingering bag of sarin-laced waste above the kiln.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the feed-chute washdown had generated a large cloud
of steam in adjoining furnaces, causing temperatures and air
pressure to drop. The steam inundated an air-flow meter hundreds of
feet downline until it malfunctioned and automatically shut down
the furnace and an adjoining afterburner.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers call this a ``lock-out.'' It required a system purge,
which pumped more cool air into the furnace. Internal pressures
began fluctuating wildly, veering off the operator's gauges.
Temperatures inside the afterburner, usually 2,100 degrees,
plummeted to 1,160 degrees. Eventually, pressures fell so low, it
created a vacuum, sucking air through the afterburner in under two
seconds. That was too quick and too cool to burn the sarin gases
being drawn off the sock.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:26 p.m., the first of three alarms inside the facility's
100-foot chimney sounded. But the control-room supervisor either
discounted or misunderstood them. Instead, he ordered the operator
to again relight the furnace. The plant site manager, thinking it
another false alarm, unmasked the site.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after midnight, the alarms sounded again. By now, an
onsite lab confirmed the first alarms: GB had escaped the stack at
3.5 times the allowable limit.
</P>
<P>
   There were other problems, too. The Army didn't tell Tooele
County officials of the leaks for four hours, violating an
agreement between the two agencies. Workers failed to immediately
check highly sensitive air monitors lining the depot's perimeter.
When they did six hours later, they didn't take all possible
readings, rendering the results from one monitor, which detected a
trace of GB, uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, over the previous month, 33 false alarms rang inside
Tooele's stack, nearly a dozen for unknown reasons. Those false
alarms, investigators later concluded, led supervisors to discount
warnings the night of the leak.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Army and EG&AMP;G officials cite the root cause of the leaks as
operator and management error. But Utah and CDC officials note that
the same feed chute had jammed before, in part because the liquid
sarin inside the rockets has unexpectedly gelled, sticking to
rocket parts and incinerator walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chute design stinks,'' said Sue Oliver, who monitors the
Army's demilitarization program for the Oregon Department of
Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   Perrow, who led a presidential probe into the Three Mile Island
accident, called the events leading up to Tooele's leaks a classic
example of the unintended consequences of complex industrial
systems. Parts inside these ``tightly coupled'' systems have prompt
and major impacts on others, he says. When things go wrong -- the
jammed feed chute and the drenched flow meter, for example --
operators cannot fathom them quickly enough. Their intervention
usually only makes things worse, Perrow says.
</P>
<P>
   He suspects similar crises will arise at the three other
incinerators.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they designed (the incinerator), they never thought of
these two complexities,'' Perrow argued. ``There are thousands more
they never thought of. When they get it running again, there's
going to be another thing.''
</P>
<P>
   (Brent Hunsberger is a staff writer for The Oregonian of
Portland, Ore.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
