<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6848 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CHICKEN-DELIGHT-TEX     07-19 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-DELIGHT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICKEN SOUP FOR ALL SOULS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By LISA DAVIS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First came the fanciful fowl of ``Chicken Run.'' Then three
chickens were awarded to one of the tribes on ``Survivor'' (alas,
they were promptly eaten). Now comes the chicken coop on ``Big
Brother'' (alas, even the hens have no privacy). And let's not
forget the food fight being waged by Chick-fil-A and Burger King
over Chick's contention that Burger King's ``save the chickens''
and ``eat a Whopper'' ad is a rip-off of its 5-year-old ``Eat mor
chikin'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With both sides crying fowl, it seems that in pop culture, the
chickens have finally come home to roost. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHY DID THE CHICKEN CROSS THE ROAD?
</P>
<P>
   Buddha: If you ask this question, you deny your own chicken
nature.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Seuss: Did the chicken cross the road? Did he cross it with
a toad? Yes! The chicken crossed the road, but why it crossed it,
I've not been told!
</P>
<P>
   Ayn Rand: It was crossing the road because of its own rational
choice to do so. There cannot be a collective unconscious; desires
are unique to each individual.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Leary: Because that's the only kind of trip the
Establishment would let it take.
</P>
<P>
   Machiavelli: The point is that the chicken crossed the road. Who
cares why? The ends of crossing the road justify whatever motive
there was.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Sanders: I missed one? _ From www.randomchicken.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE CHICKEN HALL OF FAME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Little
</P>
<P>
   Little Red Hen
</P>
<P>
   Foghorn Leghorn
</P>
<P>
   Super Chicken
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Chicken of the Sea
</P>
<P>
   Rooster Cogburn &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE YEAR OF THE ROOSTER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rooster is one of the 12 astrological signs in the Chinese
calendar. The next year of the rooster rolls around in 2005. Folks
born in a rooster year are observant and forthright, conservative
at heart, although they do like to preen. Famous roosters:
Confucius, Wagner, Verdi, Rachmaninoff and Katharine Hepburn. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN CLICHES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Playing chicken
</P>
<P>
   Chickened out
</P>
<P>
   Cocksure
</P>
<P>
   A cock-and-bull story
</P>
<P>
   Bad egg
</P>
<P>
   Nest egg
</P>
<P>
   Egg on your face
</P>
<P>
   No spring chicken
</P>
<P>
   Mad as a wet hen
</P>
<P>
   Flown the coop
</P>
<P>
   Don't count your chickens before they're hatched
</P>
<P>
   Don't put all your eggs in one basket &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHICH CAME FIRST, THE CHICKEN McNUGGET OR THE EGG McMUFFIN? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Answer: The McMuffin debuted in 1972, 11 years ahead of the
McNugget.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want there to be no peasant in my kingdom so poor that he is
unable to have a chicken in his pot every Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Henry IV, king of France from 1589-1610  &QL; 
MIKE THE HEADLESS CHICKEN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's true what they say about running around like a chicken with
your head cut off. On Sept. 10, 1945, in Fruita, Colo., Lloyd Olsen
decapitated a young chicken for dinner, but the hearty fowl refused
to die. Impressed, farmer Olsen fed him with a medicine dropper,
and Mike lived another months, sans head, becoming quite famous.
Today, there's an annual headless chicken festival in Fruita. Don't
believe it? It's documented at www.miketheheadlesschicken.org. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FANCY CHICKENS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chickens are descended from the wild red jungle fowl of India,
where they were first domesticated about 5,000 years ago. Although
supermarket chickens have had any interesting traits bred out of
them, there are many fanciful breeds to occupy chicken enthusiasts.
A sampling:
</P>
<P>
   Sultan: very fanciful, with long feathers shooting up from head,
tail and feet
</P>
<P>
   Brahma: very colorful and stately
</P>
<P>
   Polish: looks like a chicken wearing a Phyllis Diller wig
</P>
<P>
   Appenzeller Spitzhauben: The national breed of Switzerland,
black and white with bright red cockscomb
</P>
<P>
   Black rosecombs: pure black bird with bright red comb, white
spot on cheek Sources: Smithsonian magazine, www.feathersite.com  &QL; 
SOUL FOOD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sales of ``Chicken Soup for the Soul'' books topped $100 million
last year (as well as inspiring several parodies, including
``Chicken-Fried Steak for the Soul''). Which of the following is
NOT a real title in the series?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Chicken Soup for the Cat- and Dog-Lover's Soul''
</P>
<P>
   B. ``Chicken Soup for the Golfer's Soul''
</P>
<P>
   C. ``Chicken Soup for the Country Soul''
</P>
<P>
   D. ``Chicken Soup for the Co-Dependent Soul''
</P>
<P>
   E. ``Condensed Chicken Soup for the Soul''
</P>
<P>
   (The answer: D. ``Chicken Soup for the Co-Dependent Soul'')  &QL; 
THE BIG CHICKEN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An architectural landmark in Marietta, Ga., (just north of
Atlanta and hometown of Newt Gingrich), the Big Chicken is a
56-foot-tall metal fowl with movable beak and eyes. It was built in
1963 for a local ice-cream parlor, which has since become a KFC
franchise. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DEM DRIED BONES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turn a chicken carcass into a model apatosaurus or T-rex with
help from paleontologist Chris McGowan's books ``Make Your Own
Dinosaur Out of Chicken Bones'' (HarperCollins, $13) and ``T-Rex to
Go'' (HarperCollins, $14). &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE CHICKEN PLANT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Echeverias _ succulent plants native to Texas and parts south _
are commonly called ``hen-and-chickens'' because of the way new
little plantlets develop in clusters around the mama plant. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOW TO HYPNOTIZE A CHICKEN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lay the chicken on its stomach, then move your finger in a
straight line away from its beak. ``This induces total sensory
overload in the chicken's two-volt brain, putting him/her/it under
for anywhere from 15 seconds to 30 minutes.'' _ From ``The Straight
Dope'' by Cecil Adams &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tired of fast-food chicken? Try a couple of these homemade
recipes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson Davis' Southern Chicken &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that Jefferson Davis. This is his very own recipe:
</P>
<P>
   Cut a chicken into serving portions. Cook in a pressure cooker
for about 20 minutes to tenderize. (OK, they DIDN'T have pressure
cookers in the days of the Confederacy. They steamed the chicken in
a cast-iron pot with the lid held down by cast-iron bars. Same
result.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove chicken from pressure cooker and dust lightly with fine
cracker crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Put four heaping teaspoons of butter _ not margarine or oil _
into a large frying pan and melt over medium heat. Pan-fry chicken
until light brown. Turn the pieces frequently. This will take about
5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove and serve at once, while good and hot. _ From ``Bull Cook
and Authentic Historical Recipes and Practices'' by George Leonard
Herter and Berthe E. Herter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The following recipe is from ``Bless the Cook'' by Bessie
Munson, legendary Fort Worth cook and restaurateur. She also spent
some time in Hollywood catering for the likes of Loretta Young, and
was food director for Camp Waldemar, near Kerrville. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BESSIE MUNSON'S CHICKEN STEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 stewing chicken (5 pounds) cut up &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 small onions, cut in half &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 whole cloves &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons paprika &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups carrot slices, cut diagonally in 1/2 inch pieces &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups celery slices, cut diagonally in 1/2 inch pieces &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 package (10 ounces) frozen peas, unthawed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flour &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Place chicken in 4-quart Dutch oven. Add water, onions and
seasonings. Bring to a boil. Cover; simmer for 2 1/2 to 3 hours or
until chicken is tender. Remove bay leaf and cloves. Add vegetables
and bring to a boil. Cover; simmer for 15 to 20 minutes or until
vegetables are tender. Drain and reserve broth. Skim off excess
fat.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 3 cups broth into saucepan. (If necessary, add water to
measure 3 cups.) Gradually add milk to flour, stirring until
smooth. Add to hot broth; bring to a boil over medium heat,
stirring constantly until gravy is thickened. Pour gravy over
chicken and vegetables. Heat thoroughly. Sprinkle with paprika
before serving, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
