<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TO BRING CAMPAIGN INTO BUSH TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAYTOWN, Mo. _ Sensing an opening in reports of Texas budget
troubles, Vice President Al Gore is scrambling his schedule for a
detour into Bush's backyard Thursday to make his point in person.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has spent the week unveiling anti-crime initiatives
between attacks on what he says is the governor's fiscal
irresponsibility, will be in San Antonio in the afternoon. There,
he will criticize Bush's handling of the economy, which Gore said
will see a shortfall this year, reducing the state's surplus from
$6.4 billion to about $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was not previously scheduled, but the Gore campaign
hopes to capitalize on news reports suggesting that Texas's fiscal
situation has worsened over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers continue not to add up,'' said Gore spokesman
Chris Lehane, referring to Bush's budget. ``It's become a major
issue in the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign maintains Gore has exaggerated the shortfall,
and that the state has more than ample funds to cover its expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent several weeks on a ``Progress and Prosperity'' tour,
traveling the country to herald the administration's success in
producing record federal budget surpluses, and promising more of
the same. In recent days, he has also gone on the attack, seizing
on the shrinking Texas surplus to chip away at a record of which
the governor is very proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Governor Bush has run Texas is relevant to the judgment
the American people will make as to how he would run the country if
he ever gave them the chance,'' Gore told an audience of about 100
law enforcement and government officials gathered at the Raytown
City Hall to hear his crime policies. ``Especially since he is
calling for the same priorities that gave Texas its budget
shortfall: unaffordable tax cuts for powerful interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also spoke of some additional anti-crime notions Wednesday.
He proposed to add 50,000 more police officers, and 10,000 new
prosecutors, to the nation's justice system, to increase the number
of state and local prosecutors by a third. He also proposed
targeting so-called crime ``hot-spots'' by making grants to those
areas, to pay for police overtime, and to improve communications
between local and federal law enforcement authorities. Raytown,
currently in the grip of a methamphetamine epidemic, is one such
``hot spot.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the Gore crime proposals, like everything else he has
brought up in recent days, were laid against the backdrop of Bush's
state budget.
</P>
<P>
   You can't improve crime-fighting ``if your policies would leave
no money for cops and prosecutors, in order to cut taxes for
powerful interests and the wealthy,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters of the San Antonio visit as part of an
answer to a completely unrelated question. During a brief visit to
a playground at the Richard C. Green Sr. Family Center _ at which
Gore tossed children into the air and had a long conversation with
two little girls about their dolls, and about Henry, their
troublesome classmate _ Gore was asked whether he agreed with the
Clinton Administration's opposition to the removal of four dams on
the Snake River, in the Pacific Northwest. Environmentalists have
pushed for the dams' removal, to recover salmon runs in the region.
Bush believes the dams should be retained.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, closely associated with environmental causes, was
noncommittal Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to bring all the parties together for a solution
that protects the environment and doesn't harm the economy,'' Gore
said. ``I'm going to review it carefully. What's needed is to bring
all the stakeholders together.'' Then he segued into his
announcement of the San Antonio stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the Vice President is always welcome to Texas,''
said Bush spokesperson Dan Bartlett. ``But Texans won't appreciate
his continued misrepresentations and distortions of the record in
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Governor Bush will be in Texas Friday, Bartlett said, but in
Austin, not in San Antonio. He said the governor has no plans to
head elsehwere.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll give (Gore) a big Texas welcome,'' Bartlett said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he added: ``In one way or another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
