u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-DUVAL-BOS     07-19 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-DUVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL SAYS HE'S MISUNDERSTOOD BY THE PRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ The warm afternoon had given way to a
gray chill, spectators made their way toward the exits, and vendors
began closing up shop at the Old Course. Seemed like a perfect time
to start playing a few holes of golf, so there was David Duval
strolling down the first fairway at 5:15 Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   On a long list of charming aspects to St. Andrews, the fact that
you can get in 18 holes after dinner ranks near the top. Yet it
seemed surprising to see Duval out that late, given the fact that
most of his colleagues already had played 18, hit balls, putted,
and gone to get some rest as they prepared for the 129th British
Open.
</P>
<P>
   But Duval has his own game plan, even if it's not in his nature
to be big with specifics. After all, he reasons, his intentions
seem to get twisted and misunderstood. An example is the perception
that he has a genuine dislike for the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' said Duval, who knows the misconception
comes from problems he had with the media (mostly European) at last
year's British Open at Carnoustie. The course was a brutal setup,
Duval said. And even though his colleagues echoed those sentiments,
it was Duval who took the brunt of the beating in the papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disillusioned with what transpired in the papers,
obviously,'' said Duval. ``Not with the Open itself. The
championship itself is second to none.''
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that he wants to do well in this major, Duval
played in the Loch Lomond last week in Glasgow, a tournament that
ended Saturday and allowed for an early arrival here. He played St.
Andrews Sunday and Monday, played a little Tuesday night, and was
back at it Wednesday. And it's all business, said Duval. This isn't
a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of feel like when I'm at a golf tournament, I'm there
to work and golf,'' said Duval, explaining why he didn't bring his
fishing equipment to Scotland. ``I'm not there to fish. I do enough
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also thinks he's done enough talking when it comes to the
topic of his winless streak. Duval's last trip to the winner's
circle came in April 1999, and while he hasn't had to declare
bankruptcy, he said it has been frustrating _ not so much that he
hasn't won, but because his play has been good enough for
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm driving it pretty good,'' said Duval. ``I
think I'm in the top five for hitting greens in regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves?
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting. The putting has been lacking.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Duval ranks 168th on the PGA Tour in putts per round,
mind-boggling for a guy who is a fairways-and-greens machine.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a comforting thought coming into an event in which
long lag putts and buckets of 4-footers are considered the keys to
winning. But Duval, through his wraparound shades, sees a cup
half-full.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things are going to change,'' said Duval. ``I think
there are some great things in front of me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
