<HEADER>
A6860 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-DISABILITIES-SURVEY-H     07-19 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABILITIES-SURVEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PEOPLE WITH DISABILITIES STILL LAG BEHIND REST OF SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly 10 years after a law was enacted to halt
discrimination against them, people with disabilities continue to
lag behind the rest of society in employment, income and access to
health care, according to a survey released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``America must do more to release the talents and abilities of
our citizens with disabilities who want to work, participate and
contribute to the nation,'' Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., said at a news
conference here.
</P>
<P>
   But Cleland, a Vietnam veteran who lost both legs and an arm in
the war, said the survey also reflects progress in some areas
especially among younger people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have grown up in a society that tells them that
they are capable of doing anything are beginning to make good on
that promise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans with Disabilities Act was signed into law July 26,
1990, by President George Bush. The law was aimed at easing access
to the everyday world at a time when people with mental or physical
disabilities were often institutionalized. Some 54 million
Americans are considered disabled today.
</P>
<P>
   Since the law went into effect, hundreds of technical guidelines
have brought wider aisles, lower counters and drinking fountains,
automatic doors and more accessible restrooms in stores and other
places of public accommodation. Many restaurants, hotels and office
buildings have installed ramps and more elevators to accommodate
disabled guests. Movie theaters have listening devices for deaf
people, and 80 percent of public buses now are equipped with
wheelchair lifts.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by the National Organization on Disability
(NOD), a Washington-based advocacy group, and the New York-based
Harris Poll found that 56 percent of people with disabilities who
are able to work currently hold full- or part-times jobs, compared
with 80 percent of those without disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   But Brewster Thackeray, NOD's communications director, said the
employment picture for people with disabilities who are able to
work has improved since 1986 when only 46 percent held jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these changes (will take) a generation or two to
really set in and alter the way society looks at people with
disabilities and the way people with disabilities look at
themselves,'' Thackeray said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed a significant income gap between people
with and without disabilities. Twenty-nine percent of those with
disabilities live in households with incomes of $15,000 or less.
Ten percent of people without disabilities live in such households.
Conversely, 16 percent of people with disabilities live in
households with $50,000 or more annual income. But 39 percent of
those without disabilities live in such households.
</P>
<P>
   Thackeray said much of the income gap stems from the fact that
people with disabilities lag in education, with more than one of
every five failing to complete high school, compared with fewer
than one of 10 people without disabilities lacking a high school
diploma. Twelve percent of people with disabilities have graduated
from college compared with 23 percent of those without
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   However, Thackeray said the education gap may be closing. He
noted that 77 percent of people with disabilities have graduated
from high school today compared with 61 percent in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of health care, people with disabilities are just as
likely to have health insurance as their non-disabled counterparts.
However, the disabled are much more likely to postpone seeking
needed health care because they cannot afford it. Twenty-eight
percent put off doctor visits, versus 12 percent of non-disabled
people.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, people with disabilities are four times as likely
as their non-disabled counterparts to have special needs that are
not covered by their health insurance, 28 percent compared with 7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll was conducted between May 25 and June 11 with
a nationally representative sample of 1,005 people ages 16 and
above with disabilities and 1,000 people ages 16 and above without.
The survey's margin of error is plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   NOD President Alan A. Reich said the survey also showed that
people with disabilities do not go to restaurants or vote as
frequently as people without disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that 40 percent of people with disabilities go
to restaurants at least once a week, compared with 60 percent of
people without disabilities. In addition, 62 percent of people with
disabilities were registered to vote in the 1996 election compared
with 78 percent of people without disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the continuing problems, Reich said people with
disabilities have a ``very positive'' outlook on the future.
According to the survey, 63 percent said life has improved for them
over the past decade and nearly 50 percent said they believe things
will get better in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
