<HEADER>
A6873 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     07-19 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV06-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., AUG. 6, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I poured my concrete driveway in several sections about three
years ago and now the surface of the concrete has started to flake
off and also seems to be crumbling in numerous places.
 &HT;    Without actually breaking up and pouring a whole new driveway,
can you tell me what I did wrong and what I can do to level off
this concrete?
 &HT;    A: The flaking condition you speak of is usually the result of
adding too much water to the concrete mix, or not allowing the
concrete slab to cure properly.
 &HT;    It's not easy, but you can resurface the driveway by adding a
new 1/2-inch layer of concrete on top, covering one half-width
section at a time.
 &HT;    Wash the surface with a degreasing solution (sold for use on
garage floors) and a pressure washer.
 &HT;    Then install 1x2 furring strips edgewise along the side of the
driveway so that the top of the strip sticks up 1/2 inch above the
concrete.
 &HT;    Lay a strip of 1/2-inch plywood down the center of the driveway,
then coat the old concrete between these strips with an acrylic
masonry adhesive.
 &HT;    Before this dries spread on a mix of one part Portland cement
and three parts fine sand with enough water added to form the
consistency of thick oatmeal.
 &HT;    Level this off by dragging a 2x4 edgewise across the top of the
wood strips, then trowel smooth with a long wood float.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I stained and varnished some solid mahogany cabinets, but
after applying three coats of varnish and sanding between coats the
finish still does not have that mirror-smooth, glossy look I have
seen on similar pieces.
 &HT;    There are still tiny indents or pores showing in the wood, even
though I sanded the wood smooth.
 &HT;    What did I do wrong?
 &HT;    A: Mahogany is an open-pored wood and the pores tend to show
through when varnish or paint is applied without filling these
pores first.
 &HT;    The pores are filled by applying a wood filler paste before the
first coat of paint or varnish.
 &HT;    Sold in most paint stores, and normally applied before the
stain, this filler comes in a thick, paste form that must be
thinned with solvent then brushed on across the grain.
 &HT;    Before it has a chance to dry the excess must be rubbed off with
a coarse cloth by wiping in a circular motion. After this dries,
sand smooth with fine paper before the first coat of varnish is
applied.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Our kitchen ceiling was painted with a semi-gloss enamel and
now needs repainting. However, there is grease on the area over the
stove and in several other places.
 &HT;    Cleaning all this grease off will be very difficult for us, so
can you suggest any type of paint we can use over this greasy
surface?
 &HT;    A: I would not advise painting over the grease; it's bound to
cause trouble later on. You really should wash the grease off
first.
 &HT;    Even after washing the ceiling I recommend you play safe and
apply a first coat of a primer such as BIN, Kilz, or similar
stain-killing sealer before you apply your regular paint.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My vacation house is in the mountains and has oak floors. In
several places this hardwood flooring has dark colored small dents
_ almost like pit marks that have shown up recently.
 &HT;    Most of these marks are in the middle of the floor, not around
the edges.
 &HT;    What explanation can you offer for the source of these dark
dents or marks?
 &HT;    A: Impossible to say for sure, but I suspect that they are
caused by gritty materials that are being brought in from the
outside on people's shoes after they have walked over sandy or
gravelly areas.
 &HT;    Particles of sand or pebbles get caught in the soles of their
shoes and these gouge or scratch the floor.
 &HT;    It's also possible that small amounts of road tar or dirt have
been caught in people's shoes before they come in and this could be
leaving the dark appearance.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``RESURFACING CONCRETE DRIVEWAY'' goes
with this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: New layer of concrete is leveled off by dragging a 2x4
edgewise across top of temporary form boards on each side.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
