<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-MIRER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RICK MIRER, BACKUP QUARTERBACK, SUDDENLY FINDS THAT HE'S A
VET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. - Rick Mirer is not sure where the time has
gone. One day he was a rookie with the Seattle Seahawks. Now he's a
well-traveled veteran coming into 49ers training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the old guy,'' he said with a sense of wonderment.
</P>
<P>
   Moving around will do that. This is the quarterback's fifth team
in five years and he's tired of the days of ``if this is a yellow
helmet it must be Green Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get things turned around,'' Mirer said.
``Hopefully this is the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirer has been in the league for eight years. He got off to a
promising start in Seattle, where he was named rookie of the year
in 1993 after setting three NFL rookie passing records.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't follow up on that brilliant beginning in his next
three seasons and was traded to the Chicago Bears in `97. Then it
was the Packers in `98 and the New York Jets last year. At each
stop he was mostly a backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard for me to get comfortable anywhere _ settling
in, feeling good about my role,'' he said. ``It's been tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Mariucci plans on going through camp with four
quarterbacks, probably keeping just three for the regular season.
Second-year man Jeff Garcia comes in as the starter. Beyond that,
it gets crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Third-round draft pick Giovanni Carmazzi, a rugged, intelligent
quarterback out of Hofstra who just came to terms with the team
Tuesday, has yet to practice but is valued by coaches for his
potential. Seventh-round pick Tim Rattay has been getting a lot of
snaps in early drills, bringing from Louisiana Tech a familiarity
with the pro-style offense.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Mirer, fighting to not permanently be seen as that
NFL cliche of the savvy aging vet usually signed in desperation as
insurance against injury.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer spent much of the spring and early summer dangling while
the 49ers quarterback situation was as unsettled as Steve Young's
future plans. Finally on June 13, the day after Young retired,
Mirer was signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I was waiting for,'' Mirer said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he didn't have any inside information, but he did
feel he'd eventually end up with the 49ers, so it wasn't a
stressful period for him.
</P>
<P>
   Without a proven starter in the style of Joe Montana or Young,
the 49ers find quarterback depth to be a critical issue. While
Garcia is the starter, he is still, in Mariucci's words, ``a work
in progress.'' When he faltered last year, the team briefly turned
to Steve Stenstrom in an effort to spark the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer has a head start on the rookies in learning the 49ers'
complex offense. He said the Packers had a similar scheme, although
his practical experience there was limited because he was behind
Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got to play in it a lot,'' he said. ``I didn't get a
lot of practice time either.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirer, who is comfortable scrambling out of the pocket then
``winging it,'' hopes to get some quality time at quarterback
during the exhibition season. He said playing time as a backup is
precious, and he'd like to be in a situation ``where you're not
living and dying on every play.''
</P>
<P>
   He diplomatically won't compare himself to the other
quarterbacks because he doesn't want to ``confuse the issue.'' He
acknowledges Garcia has the starting job. ``He paid his dues,'' he
said. ``It's his team.''
</P>
<P>
   It's clear Mirer would be very happy to come out of camp as the
primary backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every team in the league has to go in with more than
one guy they think can play,'' he said. ``Usually the second guy
gets a shot at some point. As a competitive person, I want to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirer said he reached one of his goals when he signed with the
49ers. ``I've always wanted to be in this system,'' he said, adding
he felt his style was a good fit with the West Coast offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to be involved,'' he said. ``You don't want to
stand around just rusting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
