<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ESZTERHAS-BOOK-REVIEW     07-19 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESZTERHAS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN RHAPSODY': WILD EMBELLISHMENTS, BUT YOU KNOW THE REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At last we have concrete evidence that during the events leading
up to President Clinton's impeachment trial, the level of national
discourse really did reach the level of a Joe Eszterhas movie.
Because in his new book, Eszterhas, author of the award-winning
``Showgirls'' (jacket copy cites its Sour Apple Award from the
Hollywood Women's Press Association), has brought his screenwriting
skills to bear upon imagining the deepest, darkest, sudsiest
thoughts of this scandalous story's major and bit players. Harry
Potter is the rare contemporary celebrity whose sex life does not
come under lascivious scrutiny here.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways in which even the author's ``Basic Instinct''
pales by comparison to his ``American Rhapsody.'' After all, by
page 5 Eszterhas has the president smoking marijuana while wearing
a girlfriend's dress, and this is quite a long-winded, excitedly
profane book. And his most attention-getting move here is writing
not just a speaking part, but also rap lyrics to be delivered to
the president by the president's chatty penis, in verse that
bespeaks either the author's professional death wish or his
pathological nostalgia for junior high school. Sample rhyme: ``You
want fame, I want a dame.'' Sample couplet: ``For better or worse,
it's me and you/So stop feeling so low-down blue.''
</P>
<P>
   As this may suggest, sex is central to ``American Rhapsody.''
But it's sex as in ``sexagenarian,'' since the author is largely
concerned with the presidential generation now crowding 60, and
since reflections on his own heavily fraught sexual identity
provide the book's galvanizing force.
</P>
<P>
   Something about this presidential scandal has rekindled the
countercultural energy in Eszterhas, who was a gutsy, pioneering
Rolling Stone reporter long before he hit Hollywood (and vice
versa). He is reminded, sometimes ad nauseam, that behaving like a
rock star around groupies was once (to his thinking) the mandate of
the free-spirited male sex-drugs-and-rock 'n' roller, and that a
funny thing happened to those standards on the way to the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   So this loose, rambling sketchbook, which is both personal and
political memoir, becomes the author's effort to understand what
became of the sexual mores of his floridly evoked youth. ``We wore
no underwear, and the funkier our bell-bottoms looked, the hipper
they were, especially if there was a copy of Chairman Mao's Little
Red Book in the back pocket,'' he writes, with a typical taste for
generational slander. ``We swore by our genitals the way Nixon
swore by his `old Quaker mother.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thus predisposed, and ready to embrace Bill Clinton as the
poster president for 1960s culture and idealism, not to mention as
a kindred spirit whose ``mad priapic obsession'' he shared,
Eszterhas found himself obsessed and enraged by recent White House
scandals. In writing this book, he explains, he ``was thinking
about the state of the union and the state of our hearts and
privates as we tried not to stumble and slide on the treacherous
Internet ice of the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   What that means, in more nuts-and-bolts terms, is a book that is
interspersed with clearly fictitious, largely awkward monologues
(ascribed to Bob Dole, Al Gore, Monica Lewinsky, etc.) but consists
mostly of the author's rehashing and embellishing recent, familiar
events.
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas demonstrates, for instance, a sharp ear for dialogue
in choosing telltale taped conversational snippets from Lewinsky
and Linda Tripp, but anyone who followed these revelations as they
unfolded is liable to have heard this material before. And not even
his prodigious research into the writings of Gennifer Flowers has
much news value by now.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has researched this material so thoroughly as to come
up with trivia from Matt Drudge's high school yearbook, the story
he tells is not easily improved upon. It was a bad enough movie
before Eszterhas decided to use a nickname for the presidential
penis (``Willard'') and write White House love scenes with feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Thus one-upped by the awful truth, Eszterhas winds up looking
elsewhere for frissons of scandal. So his otherwise surprisingly
tame account is punctuated by all manner of free-floating slurs,
from Jay Leno's meanest Hillary Clinton jokes to casual asides.
(``Her style was to eat fried chicken in the back seat of the limo
with Bill when he was governor and to leave the chewed bones on the
limo floor.'') And, as he says repeatedly, Eszterhas likes Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He saves the real venom, and the cheapest shots, for those
practitioners of Hollywood ethics whose behavior, as the book
argues, is the model for the sexually exploitative power politics
that real politics have come to mimic. He seems both shocked and
amused to suggest that the distance between Bill Clinton and the
producer Bob Evans (described here as the compleat party animal, in
the book's least interesting revelation) is smaller than it seems.
</P>
<P>
   Beach-book fanciers will undoubtedly gravitate to the freely
flung dirt here, from invidious suggestions that Sharon Stone is
the kind of actress who sexually curries favor with the
screenwriter, even if the screenwriter is Eszterhas, to a
particularly cruel anecdote about Farrah Fawcett, to Larry Flynt's
description of having sex with a chicken. ( Flynt, unlike many of
the more straight-arrow types described here, comes across as a
well-evoked kindred spirit.) But this kind of reference is what
demolishes the book's real passion.
</P>
<P>
   The author's fierce longing for a lost '60s idealism comes
through even when he is not dropping the name of his friend Jimi
Hendrix or noting that he was the only white listener to a speech
given by Stokely Carmichael. But he can't easily rekindle that
generational fire while dragging this memoir through the mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Rhapsody'' is mercifully free of cynicism, though.
It's easy to believe Eszterhas' assertion that he was genuinely
roiled by national events to the point where this was a book he had
to write. It's also easy to hear traces of the (by now) grand old
Rolling Stone tradition of fearless, indignant first-person
political reporting in the youthful outrage that he struggles to
reinvent. Freed of all the excess (and excessive) baggage he piles
onto ``American Rhapsody,'' perhaps that old voice could have been
loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN RHAPSODY'
</P>
<P>
   By Joe Eszterhas
</P>
<P>
   432 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $25.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-WEIGHTS-HNS &LR;      07-19 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WEIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WEIGHTLIFTER, CANCER SURVIVOR, HOPES TO MAKE OLYMPIC TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JERRY BRIGGS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Cancer-surviving Olympic weightlifter Wes Barnett
never will roam a baseball outfield with Jim Edmonds, Andruw Jones
or Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the vision-impaired Barnett even finds it hard to play a
game of catch with his 12-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``My depth perception,'' the two-time Olympian explained
sheepishly, ``is terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing, however, remains clear in Barnett's life: his desire
to win an Olympic medal.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett, waging a battle against choroidal melanoma, will
compete Saturday in the U.S. Weightlifting team trials in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   If he makes the squad, he will be headed to Sydney, Australia,
for a dramatic appearance in the Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep telling people that if I didn't think I could win a
medal, then I wouldn't have continued on for another four years,''
he said. ``It's going to be a matter of staying healthy and getting
some good, quality training in.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett's health became a major issue in August 1998, when tests
revealed he had developed a tumor on the right eye.
</P>
<P>
   This type of melanoma, normally an affliction of the elderly,
struck Barnett at age 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like, 'How can this be?''' Barnett recalled. ``I'm an
Olympic athlete. I'm 28 years old. I'm healthy. There's no way this
could be.'''
</P>
<P>
   But it was true _ the tumor had grown to the point that surgical
radiation treatment was required to save his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a situation where you put your faith in God,'' said
Barnett, a 30-year-old Colorado Springs resident. ``You put your
faith in the doctors, and you hope for the best. Fortunately for
me, it's so far, so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the long-term prognosis for his health is good, his
chances of making the U.S. team are less than certain.
</P>
<P>
   Only two male American weightlifters are assured of competing
for the United States, and Barnett recently dropped to No. 3 in the
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   He will need a strong showing Saturday afternoon to move up into
the top two.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Barnett may have to settle for one of two alternate
roster spots, and hope that the international federation allows all
four American males on the travel squad a chance to compete.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with the national media in May, Barnett brushed
off a suggestion that recent bouts with blurred vision and dizzy
spells might hurt his cause in the trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Barnett, who won a gold medal in San Antonio at the
1993 U.S. Olympic Festival, ``because the bar isn't moving away
from me. You don't have to catch anything, or deal with any moving
objects. I'm real fortunate in that aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning a bronze medal in the 1997 world championships _
the high point of his career _ Barnett has ridden an emotional
roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   First came the cancer, the surgery and radiation treatment,
which caused him to sit out all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Then he launched a remarkable comeback in 1999, when he won his
sixth U.S. championship and placed 15th at the worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, he has struggled.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered a back strain in the most recent U.S. championship
and failed to lift his usual heavy poundage at an exhibition one
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Oscar Chaplin III and Tom Gough have passed him
in the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett has expressed optimism about increasing his lifts by
20-25 pounds between now and September.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said confidently, ``should put me in the medal
range. That is what I'm going to be shooting for.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, Barnett made a name for himself as an
all-state basketball player at Benton High School in St. Joseph,
Mo., a small industrial town north of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of coaches at a nearby recreation center, he
gradually became infatuated with weightlifting and soon started to
win national meets on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett pretty much owned the American weightlifting scene in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, at age 22, he qualified for his first Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   He consistently finished in the top 15 at the world
championships and placed sixth among the 238-pound
super-heavyweights at the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how he fares Saturday, fans can remember him as an
athlete who refused to quit in the face of adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk to kids or groups of people,'' Barnett said, ``I
let them know that if you set your goals and stay focused, then no
matter what your obstacles are, you can overcome them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Jerry Briggs can be contacted via e-mail:
jbriggs &LR; express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
