<HEADER>
A6897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-COLU     07-19 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: TIPS ON INSTALLING A NEW WINDOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, this column focused on selecting new windows. If you
decide to buy one, you will need three measurements before you can
place the order: the rough opening, the outside dimensions and the
thickness of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   To find the rough opening, pry off the interior casing, then
measure the distance between the studs on either side of the window
and the distance between the rough sill and the header. Measure the
height and width of the frame, i.e., the dimensions of the jamb, to
determine the outside dimensions. To find the thickness of the
wall, poke a ruler in the gap between the stud and the window
frame. Take the measurement from the leading edge of the stud
(where the outside sheathing is mounted) to the interior edge of
the wallboard. Take these measurements with you when you buy the
new window; they will help the dealer select the ideal size for
your opening.
</P>
<P>
   Once you buy a new window, you still have to install it. This is
not a particularly difficult task if the size of the replacement is
close to the old window. If it is larger, you will have to open up
the wall. This will require carpentry skill. If the window is much
smaller, you will have to close in the opening. This in itself is
not difficult, but you will have to extend the exterior finish to
the edge of the new window frame without making the repair into an
eyesore.
</P>
<P>
   Before you can install the new window, you will have to remove
the old one. From the inside, pry off all the window trim, the
casings and stop molding, then remove the sashes. Most window
frames are held in place with finishing nails that go through the
inner and outer casings into the wall studs. When you remove the
exterior casing (you already removed the inner when you pulled out
the sashes), the window may be loose. If not, check to see if there
are any finishing nails that go through the jamb into the studs.
Cut these with a hacksaw blade, then pull the frame out.
</P>
<P>
   Working from the outside, use a stiff putty knife to gentle pry
up the siding and insert 30-pound asphalt impregnated building felt
under the edges. Start at the bottom and work around the perimeter
of the window. Staple the pieces in place as you insert them. The
felt will keep moisture from penetrating into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the top of the window opening. If there is no drip cap
in place, install one. Slide the metal flange of the drip cap under
the siding, but do not nail it. When the window is installed, the
trim will hold it in place.
</P>
<P>
   Since the window frame will rest on the sill plate, it is a good
idea to check to see if it is level. If it is not, add shims on the
low end. Place the window in the opening; you may need a helper to
hold it while you insert shims to get the window centered and
leveled. From the exterior, measure around the window frame from
the jamb to the edge of the siding. Use these figures to measure
and cut the exterior trim molding. Remove the window and nail the
trim molding to the jambs. Squeeze a bead of caulk around the wall
opening in the area that will be covered by the overlapping trim
molding.
</P>
<P>
   Put the window back into the opening and tack it in place by
driving finishing nails through the trim into the wall. Do not
drive the nails home. Leave the heads projecting out so you can
remove the nails to make adjustments, if necessary. (It is not
necessary to nail exterior trim molding to aluminum or vinyl
windows because they have nailing flanges attached to the window
frame.)
</P>
<P>
   Use a level and a framing square to check that the window is
level, plumb and square. If not, insert shims to correct the
alignment. Open and close the window to make sure the sashes
operate freely. If they do not, then the frame is probably out of
square and needs adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   When all adjustments are satisfactory, secure the window by
driving 10d galvanized casing nails, spaced 16 inches apart,
through the exterior trim into the wall. Seal the unit by drawing a
bead of caulk around the perimeter of the trim.
</P>
<P>
   Working from the inside, fill the gaps between the jamb and
studs with fiberglass insulation. Do not pack too much insulation
in the gap or it could distort the window frame. Fiberglass
insulation can irritate the skin, so wear long sleeves, gloves and
a dust mask when working with it. Finally, reinstall the old
interior trim or cut new pieces to fit. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
