<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-TITANS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 SPELLING'S CAMPY NEW SHOW HAS tv CRITICS, NOT STARS, LAUGHING  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ ``Titans'' isn't a comedy, but a promotional
trailer for the new NBC series shown this week in Pasadena had
critics laughing so hard that producers might want to reconsider.
NBC executives even recommend it as ``guilty pleasure''
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Spelling, dean of prime-time soaps and very quick on his
feet, seized the opportunity and suggested that ``Titans'' is
indeed campy with tongue-in-cheek humor. But the pilot episode
wasn't shot that way, and cast members were visibly stunned by the
reaction, clearly not sure if critics were laughing with them or at
them.
</P>
<P>
   Yasmine Bleeth, who plays a manipulative vixen wheedling her way
into a moneyed Beverly Hills family, followed Spelling's lead and
suggested that something like ``Titans'' is merely the same sort of
mindless diversion as ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't really reality we're watching,'' she said. ``It's
pumped-up fantasy. It's like, what would happen if? Our types of
shows are what would happen if you just happen to be a trillionaire
family, and you had the kind of people who sleep with everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Titans'' will air on Wednesday nights this fall, leading off a
night of drama that includes ``The West Wing'' and ``Law &AMP; Order.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to feel sorry for Scott Sassa. Here's a guy who 18
months ago said he wanted NBC to bring a little more dignity to a
prime-time schedule that was already the smartest and most
sophisticated in the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Along comes ``Survivor,'' a bona fide success story for CBS, and
Sassa starts second-guessing himself. Next comes ``Big Brother,''
not quite the success CBS had hoped for but still a summertime
force to be reckoned with, and the industry starts up a betting
pool on when Sassa will lose his job as president of NBC West Coast
because NBC doesn't have any viewer-as-voyeur programming to
counter CBS, nor does it have anything in the wings just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa's counterparts at ABC don't feel the same pressure because
they're still riding the crest with ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire,'' which will make up 18 percent of ABC's prime-time
slate this fall. And you'd think Sassa would have learned a lesson
from all the ``Millionaire'' copycats _ including NBC's own
``Twenty-One'' _ that tanked last season. He's a smart programmer,
after all.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, he probably has learned. But network honchos rarely get
to speak _ or act _ from the heart. They are driven by the bottom
line, which now says that ``reality'' programming like ``Survivor''
is attracting top advertising dollars, which is something that
can't be said about the low-brow cheese that has populated the
reality genre for years. Thus, it is incumbent on Sassa and Garth
Ancier, president of NBC Entertainment, to find progamming to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a fad,'' Sassa said Tuesday. ``It's a trend.
... The line of what is acceptable in television has definitely
been blurred. The sensibility of what's right and what's wrong is
different.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. But couldn't there be one commercial network that
stands above it all, that dares to draw the line and not cross it?
</P>
<P>
   Sassa still looks as if he'd like NBC to be that network, but
his words indicate he has been given little choice in the matter:
``One of the problems that we had is that we are so obsessed with
making sure we have the highest-quality shows, the highest-quality
audiences, ... we weren't as aggressive as we should have been in
this (reality) area,'' he told TV critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want new, they want different, they want distinctive.
... Hopefully, we can find something that captures the imagination
of the public the way that `Survivor' did or the way that
`Millionaire' does.''
</P>
<P>
   What might that be?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Sassa and Ancier say they're considering another European
import, this one a ``relationship'' show in which a woman must
decide which of four men she'd rather be with by being chained to
all four at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Beam me up, Scotty. I think I'm ready to be voted off this
island.
</P>
<P>
   Cable isn't immune to the ``reality'' craze. As part of a
Halloween promotion, Fox Family Channel is looking for an extended
``family'' to spend a week in a supposedly haunted castle, all
under the camera's eye. Each 18-plus member of the five-person
family, which can include nieces, nephews, in-laws, etc., will
reside in a different part of the 300-year-old castle and be
required to accept ``physical challenges and ghost-hunting tasks''
without benefit of much sleep. Those who can last a week win a
vacation on a tropical isle, presumably without the ``Survivor''
gang. Think it's your family's turn for their 15 minutes of shame?
Call 877-777-5441 or visit www.scariestplacesonearth.com on the
Web.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
