<SLUG> BC-TV-PBS-SCHEDULE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS TO TEST NEW SCHEDULES IN THE AUTUMN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY HANDELMAN   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif._ Public television is shaking up its schedule
in a test that will send long-running programs to different nights
in an effort to boost viewership.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot schedule project, as it is called at PBS, will begin
in October and run in seven cities through early winter, and will
likely lead to a new national strategy of programming, executives
told TV critics gathered in California.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are part of an ``effort to create a better schedule,
a more viewer-friendly schedule that will make some sense out of
the terrific programs we have and were offering,'' said John F.
Wilson, senior vice president of the PBS Programming Service.
</P>
<P>
   Because PBS is not a network like NBC, CBS or ABC, but rather is
a membership organization made up of affiliated stations, many
national programs do not air at the same time in every city. That
makes it more difficult for PBS to advertise and to promote
programs nationally.
</P>
<P>
   While some local stations air the national schedule, they
frequently pre-empt programs for locally produced shows.
</P>
<P>
   The test sites are Cleveland, Orlando, Fla., Philadelphia,
Pittsburgh, Salt Lake City, San Diego and Atlanta, along with all
of Georgia Public Television.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said the cities were chosen to represent all regions of
the country and the different types of public-television stations,
such as university markets, community licenses and state networks.
</P>
<P>
   With increasing numbers of cable stations offering competition
and the types of programs that have been the staple of public
broadcasting, PBS is more closely looking at other schedules and
programs its shows will face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of being a counter-programmer is increasingly
difficult in a 50-channel environment,'' Wilson said. ``But, you
can take a look at some overwhelming competition to a given genre
or subject matter and get your program out of harm's way, in that
case.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he cited one of the system's signature series,
``Masterpiece Theatre,'' which has aired on Sunday nights for
decades. In the test cities, PBS likely will move the series to
another night, away from the strong competition of
made-for-network-TV movies, mini-series and regular network series.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he also wants to package shows with similar themes,
such as ``American Masters'' and ``The American Experience,'' both
of which are primarily biographical series. ``Nova'' might be
paired with ``Scientific American Frontiers.'' Wilson said the new
schedule arrangement is expected to spread nationally in April,
after some fine tuning. ``It's a case of when, not if,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke along with new PBS president Pat Mitchell, who joined
the system in March, after seven years with Turner networks, and a
long career at several other networks. Mitchell helped to produce
such multi-part documentaries as ``The Cold War'' and
``Millennium.'' One of her first initiatives is to launch a series
of summits with program producers and filmmakers and documentary
producers who will meet in September to discuss a range of
programming possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   All of them, she said, will address the networks new promotional
theme, ``Come to Public Television If You're Curious.'' In talking
with viewers, she said, ``They kept describing themselves as adults
with a big Why?' and that it was the curiosity factor that kept
bringing them back again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is best scheduling a variety of programs that she
call ``an embarrassment of riches.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the programs viewers will be seeing this season are Ken
Burns' 18-hour series ``Jazz'' in January, ``American Masters''
biographies of such subjects as Norman Mailer, Bob Marley, Clint
Eastwood and Lucille Ball, numerous pre-election specials, a Bill
Moyers miniseries focusing on American attitudes toward death and
dying, and a live ``Great Performances'' broadcast of a new
Broadway revival of ``The Man Who Came to Dinner'' starring Nathan
Lane and Jean Smart.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla., is part of The New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
