<SLUG> BC-MRBIG-SPEAKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. BIG RETURNS TO `SEX AND THE CITY'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MIKI TURNER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Noth wants a better dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm the least comedic character in `Sex and the City,'
'' says the man who has played Sarah Jessica Parker's ``Mr. Big''
the past three seasons on the hit HBO series. ``I actually
complained the first season about my role, because everyone was so
wonderfully dysfunctional and I seemed like this rich, spoiled,
self-made man. I was kind of worried. I didn't quite know what to
do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   So Noth, who returns to the show Sunday, cast a longing eye at
the bizarre sexual quirks some of his fellow men on the series have
gotten to offer Parker and her pals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the men _ for better or worse _ have their dysfunction
handsomely served up on the show,'' Noth says with a laugh. ``Those
are delicious things to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but such quirks would be new to Mr. Big, who, so far,
can only claim some rather prosaic dsyfunctions, like being unable
to commit to Carrie (Parker's character).
</P>
<P>
   Which has certainly been enough for Noth to handle. The
Yale-trained actor, who starred on ``Law &AMP; Order'' from 1990 to
1995, says he's often approached on the street by viewers who want
to vent their frustrations with his ``Sex'' character.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask me, `What's wrong with you?' `Why can't you commit to
her?' `You're so bad.' `I've had a Mr. Big. You're terrible, get
lost.' You know, it's just entertainment, for God's sake,'' he
says. ``I hope (the show) isn't becoming a manual for people to
define their dating habits. We have enough trouble as it is. Maybe
people are watching too much TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least too much ``Sex and the City.'' The series, which
last year won the Golden Globe for best comedy (as well as a best
actress award for Parker), is HBO's highest-rated original series,
besting even ``The Sopranos.'' Noth is a fan, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's some honest moments in it about people and
everything else,'' the 42-year-old Wisconsin native says. ``I think
it's more honest in its portrayal of men and women than a lot of
the other shows are in terms of their portrayals of cops and
hospitals. Even when they try to be real, they are grossly
exaggerated and overdramatized and sentimentalized when they're
supposed to be gritty shows. Well, I think this little funny show,
with all its eccentricities, sometimes hits on the truth between
men and women, whether they like it or not. And maybe that's what
people are responding to.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, HBO is also expecting fans to respond to the return
of Big, who was last seen breaking Carrie's heart by taking up with
the waifish Natasha. So, can he give us a hint about whether Big
and Carrie will get back together?
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't do that,'' he replies simply.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can he help viewers grasp his take on his character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really bad when it comes to talking about character,'' he
says. ``I used to say this on `Law &AMP; Order,' too. ... It's hard for
me to articulate how I get into character. It all sounds like
googly-gook. The only actor that I ever knew who talked about
character in print intelligently was Laurence Olivier _ and maybe
something I read'' about Marlon Brando, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very instinctual process and it bleeds into you, but it
doesn't bleed into you. I can separate it, but to articulate how I
do it will make me sound like a raving idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the secret of his characterization, it's hit a chord
with viewers _ as has the whole show. And Noth, who's appeared on
stage in such classic plays as Hamlet and Shaw's Arms and the Man
and has a series-development deal with CBS, was taken by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it would be as big as it has become,'' he
admits. ``The response in New York and LA has been outrageous. It
was pretty unexpected. I really never know what ... is going to hit
and what's not. It took `Law &AMP; Order' five years to really make a
mark.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``Sex,'' it was immediate _ as was the chemistry between
Noth and Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be happier working with Sarah,'' says Noth. ``She's
incredibly supportive and I feel very close to her. My relationship
with Sarah is so healthy and full of fun that I think it helped me
play the character _ especially in the first season when I didn't
know who he was supposed to be. He didn't even have a name.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question, of course, is this: Is Big worth all the
heartache and pain he causes Carrie?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll answer that as Chris Noth,'' Noth says. ``Yeah, sure,
everybody's worth it. He's no different than anybody else. He has
his problems and that relationship has its own particular problems.
They were together and did try to make it. The very things that
attracted them to each other and made them love each other were the
same things that drove them apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, those kinds of questions always make me laugh a
little, and when I read what I said I always barf.'' .MDBO/.MDNM/
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
