<SLUG> BC-THE_GIFT-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOYS WILL BE BOYS?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warning: It takes a willingness to overlook a fair amount of
swinish behavior to appreciate ``The Gift,'' the strangely
charismatic new musical at Hollywood's Tiffany Theater. Building on
the assumption that boys will be boys _ hurrah! _ until something
happens to turn them into actual human beings, co-authors and
cousins Steve and Robbie Fox have constructed a musical tribute to
ye old frat-boy days and the bonds thence erected. This is ``Animal
House'' meets ``Very Bad Things'' as repackaged by Pat Conroy.
</P>
<P>
   Why ``The Gift'' works isn't easy to explain. Steve Fox's
rock/pop score, currently being put on CD by Geffen Records, is a
largely consistent assemblage of drum-heavy numbers that delivers
the play's messages with a decidedly heavy hand. Credit then the
five actors who somehow get underneath the skin of their
occasionally cliched characters and kick the play's credibility
factor up a few notches. They believe these transformable frat boys
are worth caring about, so we can, too.
</P>
<P>
   Representing the female point of view, sort of, is a high-priced
stripper/call girl named Elektra who wears the flimsiest of
clothing and calls herself the ``escort to the truth.'' It's a
silly role and a bad choice for TV star Alicia Witt to have
selected for her stage debut. Elektra's not exactly the play's
conscience, and there comes a point when neither they nor director
Andy Fickman knows what to do with her. More on this presently.
</P>
<P>
   Elektra's the linchpin, the one who delivers a memorable
bachelor party send-off to bridegroom Mark (Burke Moses), and
former Northwestern frat mates Travis (James Barbour), Lance (Larry
Poindexter), Don (Robert Torti) and Teddy (John Kassir). The five
partied hardy through college before growing apart and moving into
unsatisfying relationships and career paths. Now with Mark about to
tie the knot, the bachelor party and an ensuing catastrophe land
all five men back in Don's Malibu home, where they can reassess
their lives and friendships.
</P>
<P>
   Fickman, who directed several of these actors in the
long-running hit ``Reefer Madness,'' has a nice feel for the
guy-guy dynamics and for their interactions with a plethora of
female characters (juggled between Luann Aronson and Shanola
Hampton). He could afford to give the entire piece a bit more
cynicism, but to do so would probably go against the grain of the
play.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Somebody should rethink both what Elektra
is supposed to be and who should be playing her. As easily as she
seems to wear both the character's clothing and attitude, the
statuesque Witt simply doesn't look comfortable on stage. Part of
the problem is the character's status as a non-reactive narrator,
meaning Elektra is permitted to angrily vamp the audience, deliver
the same ``come hither'' glances numerous times and not much else.
Placed next to more seasoned actors like Barbour or Torti, Witt
doesn't just look out of her league. She looks lost.
</P>
<P>
   In a house with the Tiffany's intimacy, it seems peculiar that
all of the actors should be equipped with body microphones (many
don't seem to need them). All the better, I suppose, to compete
with an off-stage band conducted by Dave Manning. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
What:`The Gift.'' &QL; 
Where: Tiffany Theatre, 8532 Sunset Blvd., West Hollywood &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Thursdays through Saturdays, 3 and 8 p.m. Sundays;
through Aug. 27. &QL; 
Tickets: $35 to $40. Call (310) 289-2999. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JAPAN-LOST-ART-NYT &LR;      07-19 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-LOST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKINAWANS HOPE MEETING PUTS FOCUS ON ART MISSING SINCE WAR
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leaders on the Japanese island of Okinawa plan to use the
eight-nation economic summit conference there this week to help
speed the recovery of cultural property that disappeared from
homes, public buildings and religious shrines when U.S. soldiers
seized the island in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   To date, more than 100 artworks _ including ancient Buddhist
temple bells, statuary and sacred manuscripts _ have been returned
by U.S. veterans, their heirs and, in at least one case, forcibly
by the U.S. Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   But one scholar, Peter Kleinen of the German Institute of
Japanese Studies, recently reported finding nearly 800 objects of
Okinawan origin in the holdings of 21 American museums.
</P>
<P>
   Since many of these artworks were put on display after World War
II, scholars believe they were looted during and immediately after
the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most cherished objects still missing is the ancient
headdress worn by the Ryukyu kings who ruled Okinawa until the
island was annexed by imperial Japan in 1879. The headdress is a
silk, helmet-shaped crown studded with pearls, gold, jade and other
precious stones. It has not been seen publicly since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Last month a delegation of six City Council members from Nago,
where the economic meeting is to begin on Friday, flew to
Washington and gave President Clinton and other administration
officials a council resolution calling on the United States to
``investigate the whereabouts of our lost cultural assets and take
relevant steps for their return.''
</P>
<P>
   Mikio Yabu, the leader of the group, said at a stop in New York,
``We hope the summit conferees will pay attention not only to
international economic issues but to the restoration of cultural
losses from Okinawa.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone from Naha, Okinawa's capital, Shizuo
Kishaba, chairman of the semi-official Ryukyu-American Historical
Research Society, who has played a major role in returning stolen
objects to Okinawa, took a more forceful position.
</P>
<P>
   While stopping short of predicting that Clinton would face a
hostile demonstration when he arrives in Okinawa, Kishaba said,
``The president knows what we are seeking, and if he arrives
empty-handed it will certainly sour our relationship with the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department, in response to an inquiry, issued a
statement saying, ``We recognize the deep concern of the people of
Okinawa about artifacts missing since the end of World War II.''
The FBI, the statement said, has offered to list missing items in a
database available on its Web site,
www.fbi.gov/majcases/arttheft/art.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Missing items are also being listed in the national stolen art
file, accessible only to law enforcement officials, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokesman, however, said that it was unlikely
that the U.S. delegation would actually bring any of the artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   In World War II priceless artworks were seized by soldiers in
both the Pacific and European theaters and sometimes justified as
war trophies. The issue of unreturned works still troubles
relations between Germany and Russia. For U.S. troops theft from
conquered territories was prohibited by the Articles of War, No.
93.
</P>
<P>
   Kishaba said that many servicemen who stole objects from Okinawa
in 1945 later sold or donated them to U.S. museums. ``The result is
that Okinawan treasures are scattered across the United States,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Peabody Essex Museum in Salem, Mass., has a group of six
ceramic and pewter objects sold for $75 in 1947 by Cmdr. Carl W.
Sternfelt, an U.S. intelligence officer who served on Okinawa
during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Records of this sale are particularly significant, Kishaba said,
because he and many others believe that Sternfelt, who died in
1976, also took the royal Ryukyu headdress in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Sternfelt's loot was confiscated by U.S. Customs agents
in 1953 and returned to Okinawa later that year in a ceremony
celebrating the centennial of Matthew Perry's historic visit to
Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   Sternfelt's son, Robert Sternfelt, of Scituate, Mass., denies
that his father ever possessed the headdress and said that his
father voluntarily surrendered the booty he brought from Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Hellmich, a spokeswoman for the Peabody Essex Museum,
said, ``If we are presented with evidence that Sternfelt stole the
objects now in our possession, we would repatriate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another point of contention is a 10-inch flat stone from Okinawa
incised so as to suggest that it may have been used as an ancient
sundial or a navigational instrument. It is now in the collection
of the University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and
Anthropology in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Kishaba believes the stone was taken by a U.S. soldier after the
war and wants it returned to Okinawa, but Gregory L. Posschl,
curator of the Asian collection of the museum, said that the
provenance of the object was uncertain and that it could not be
returned unless Okinawa's rightful ownership was established.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no desire to keep things that don't belong to us,''
Posschl said. ``But we have to go through a process that is both
rigorous and fair to determine the validity of these claims.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1945 Okinawa was the scene of one of the largest land, air
and sea battle in history, and the focus of Japan's desperate
resort to kamikaze attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The 81 days of fierce fighting that began on Easter left 12,000
Americans dead or missing and 72,000 wounded, more than twice the
numbers from Guadalcanal and Iwo Jima combined.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese losses were even greater. The Japanese death toll
soared to 120,000 combatants and more than 150,000 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Few structures on the island were left standing, and looting by
U.S. soldiers _ commanders as well as enlisted men _ was
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ``A frenzy of souvenir hunting was part of the terrible
strangeness of that battle,'' said George Feifer, author of
``Tennozan: The Battle of Okinawa and the Atomic Bomb'' (Houghton
Mifflin, 1992). ``The Marines risked their lives to tear a
photograph off of a wall or even to grab a pair of sneakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kishaba said, ``We were in danger of having our culture
erased.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the delegation spoke emotionally last month about
their sense of loss. Kazunori Nagayama said learning to play the
sanshin, a classical Okinawan stringed instrument, had inspired his
interest in Okinawan cultural history.
</P>
<P>
   When he plays his 80-year-old sanshin, he said, he dreams of
ancient court life where such instruments were played in the
presence of the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my dreams are frustrating because we have so little to
remind us of our roots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Morio Kohama, 42, said he had learned about the history of
Okinawa from his father, who is 86. ``But I have no proof, nothing
I can hold in my hands, of the truth of what he is telling me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
