<HEADLINE>
NBC READY TO FACE REALITY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: This is the final version of early draft sent 7/18 and later
killed.) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ It's a network without a ``Big Brother'' or a
``Millionaire'' that's looking for a ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   The peacock network surprised TV critics Tuesday by admitting it
wants to jump into reality television _ despite the controversy
surrounding the shows _ possibly with a woman in chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't ignore this as something that's going to go away,''
said Garth Ancier, president of NBC Entertainment, at the
semiannual TV press tour. ``The public spoke, and they want these
shows. The challenge is not just chasing a clone (of `Survivor' or
`Millionaire').
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find the next genre of this programming that
will have some life. We've heard every variation of putting people
on a bus or train or whatever and have them kicked off one by one.
Nothing we've seen so far is something we're happy announcing (as
being in development).''
</P>
<P>
   It's been reported that NBC was looking at a program developed
in Europe of a woman chained to prospective boyfriends. She must
make a decision who to stay with and who to set free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality programming is definitely here,'' agreed Scott Sassa,
president of NBC West Coast. ``This is not a fad; it's a trend
that's going to be around for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The line of what is acceptable has definitely been blurred.
It's a moving target defined by public tastes and public sentiment.
We weren't as aggressive as we should have been in pursuing that
type of programming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa conceded that the network's success in traditional
fictional series programming such as ``ER'' and ``Law &AMP; Order,''
and its adherence to a concrete schedule contributed to NBC's
flat-footed response to reality TV's explosion on competing
networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our success in story form hurts us in (developing reality
shows),'' he said. ``Because of our stability, we're more
vulnerable because we have none of those shows.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC was second in the network ratings last season for the much-
sought-after 18-to-49 viewers coming in behind ABC, whose success
can be planted squarely on ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Sassa has taken some criticism for not jumping into reality
programming sooner and boosting the network's ratings. He was in
for some good-natured ribbing Tuesday during a skit that introduced
him and hinted at his demise at NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Recent reports had Jack Welch, head of NBC's parent company,
General Electric, and one of the best-known and toughest executives
in the country, pressuring and criticizing Sassa for having missed
the reality programming trend.
</P>
<P>
   Reality programming will likely pop up on NBC next summer,
despite the added costs of generating original programming during
the season when viewers are watching the networks the least. It
has, however, been a success for CBS this summer with its popular
``Survivor'' series and to a much lesser extent with ``Big
Brother,'' which has taken a caning from critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``One smart thing about placing them in summer is that they're
against competition that's not as great,'' Sassa said, admitting
that due to the fact that such programs have such short shelf lives
_ they can't really be repeated or syndicated _ their ostensibly
lower price tag is misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tricky field _ one of the trepidations is that you
don't want to inhibit the brand of quality we've established with
NBC over the years,'' Sassa said.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa suggested that criticisms that series such as ``Big
Brother'' have debased network airwaves are ``not a good thing or
bad thing. It is what it is. Public sentiment and morals have
changed. I'm not comfortable making value judgments of other
people's programming.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
