<SLUG> BC-POKEMON-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POKEMON' CONTINUES ITS MARCH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Warner Bros. to follow up last fall's
hugely popular ``Pokemon: The First Movie'' with another animated
feature foray into the arcane mythology of the Pokemon world.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news for parents is that Pokemon is still a powerful
enough franchise (by a lot, it seems, from my informal survey of
the neighborhood kids) that they'll have little choice about taking
their preteen children to this film.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, though, is that this is a much better film than
the first one, with better animation, less pablum masking as
dialogue and a engaging- enough storyline involving the usual
suspects dealing with an overly enthusiastic collector of some of
the ultimate Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   For those who've been hiding in a pop-cultural cone of silence
for the past two years, Pokemon is a contraction for ``pocket
monsters,'' which originally populated a series of hugely
successful video games for the Nintendo Game Boy and N64 machines.
</P>
<P>
   After several billion dollars, boatloads of merchandise and an
equally successful trading card game, the newest film promises to
further feed the frenzy with a first-week's giveaway of a rare
Pokemon card and the introduction of dozens of new creatures to
fire the collecting _ and collective _ frenzies of fans of the
games.
</P>
<P>
   In ``2000,'' Ash and his Pokemon trainer buddies get mixed up in
the efforts of Lawrence III, a wealthy, wacked Pokemon collector
whose airship (a highlight of the film's animation for its detail
and imagination) is perfectly suited to capture three elemental
Pokemon birds who represent the warring but equilibrous natural
forces of fire, ice and lightning.
</P>
<P>
   In temporarily capturing one, then another of the great beasts,
Lawrence disrupts the planet's balance of forces and sets the birds
fighting against each other and against another, greater,
peacemaking Pokemon, Lugia.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, only Ash, who happens to be in the area on something
of a vacation at an island festival, can help put things to right.
He also gets help from his friends and Pokemon, and even from his
putative nemeses, the comic foils of Team Rocket (think the Harlem
Globetrotters' Washington Generals, or closer to recent context,
Rocky and Bullwinkle's Boris and Natasha).
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket crew have a number of funny lines, and children in
particular will enjoy the enhanced production values of this year's
film, which nicely mixes traditional 2-D Japanese animation
conventions with several excellent 3-D computer-generated pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Parents will like a film with a positive message that is filled
with action, but not blood, where even the losers merely get a conk
in the head and later return to the fray or move on _ wiser for
their failures.
</P>
<P>
   Even the short that proceeds the movie, ``Pokemon's Vacation
Rescue,'' is more comprehensible and adult-accessible than its
hallucinogenic 1999 predecessor, ``Pikachu's Vacation.'' As with
the 1999 short, there is virtually no dialogue involving speech you
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   The short and the feature debut six of the 90 new Pokemon types
that will be featured in upcoming versions of the games. Needless
to say, your children (if they're younger than about 14 or so) will
want to catch them all. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
The film: ``Pokemon the Movie 2000'' with the short, ``Pikachu's
Rescue Adventure'' (G; moderate animated violence between
creatures). &QL; 
The stars: Veronica Taylor, Rachael Ellis, Eric Stuart, Addie
Blaustein, Ted Lewis and Ikue Otani. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Kunihiko Yuyama (Japanese version)
and Michael Haigney (American version). Produced by Norman J.
Grossfeld. Adapted by Grossfeld and Haigney. Screenplay by Takeshi
Shudo. Music by Ralph Schukett and John Loeffler. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 20 minutes; the short is 22 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6920 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-5SENSES-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      07-19 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-5SENSES-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SENSORY EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Five Senses'' is an ambitious, character-based ensemble
movie about the current state of human relations. It's along the
lines of ``Magnolia'' or ``The Decalogue,'' and while it's not as
demanding, insightful or formally audacious as either of those,
Jeremy Podeswa's dour Canadian film possesses a pleasing amount of
emotional sense and sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a nagging obviousness to Podeswa's organizing
theme. The film's five main, intertwining stories are _ you guessed
it _ keyed to acts of touch, taste, sight, smell and hearing.
Whereas you really had to think multilaterally to get
``Decalogue's'' Ten Commandments references and follow feelings
like you would a symphony in ``Magnolia,'' this one connects the
dots much more simply. The circumstances here are, for the most
part, intelligent and moving, but a sense of the schematic
sometimes takes away from the mystery and richness finely detailed
behavior ought to possess.
</P>
<P>
   The film's other central motif is a Toronto brownstone where
several of the characters live and/or work. One is a masseuse and
widowed mother (Gabrielle Rose of ``The Sweet Hereafter''), whose
anti-social teen-age daughter Rachel (Nadia Litz) loses a client's
young child in a nearby park. While the search for the missing
toddler occupies the local news and much of the film's dialogue for
three days, Rachel refocuses her imperfect watchfulness on a young
male acquaintance (Brendan Fletcher), who shares her interest in
dressing up and role playing.
</P>
<P>
   A French eye doctor (Philippe Volter), who also has an office in
the building, is losing his hearing; he's trying to collect a
backlog of aural experiences in his head while he still can. And on
another floor, we've got Rona (Mary-Louise Parker), who bakes
great-looking but bad-tasting party cakes for a living and who
could use the dose of real sweetness Roberto (Marco Leonardi), an
Italian vacation romance come home to roost, would love to inject
into her life and work if she only trusted him enough to let him.
</P>
<P>
   On the olfactory front, Rona's bisexual best friend Robert
(Daniel MacIvor) hires out as an upscale housekeeper and has
convinced himself that he can smell true love. He's busy looking up
old boyfriends and girlfriends in the hope that he might be able to
sniff out that special pheromone he might have missed the first
time around.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, some of these plotlines sound mighty ludicrous; some of
them inarguably are. But there's a straightfaced, measured
sincerity _ call it Canadian if you must _ in Podeswa and his fine
cast's attack that draws credible behavior out of even the
cutesiest script notions.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what all of these folks and the characters who enter
their orbit are longing for is that often elusive sixth sense, the
one that just makes you know you're connected to someone else. In
its deliberate, gray-and-brown, well-mannered way, ``The Five
Senses'' is deliriously passionate about making that connection. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
The film: ``The Five Senses'' (R; nudity, language, sex, children
in jeopardy). &QL; 
The stars: Gabrielle Rose, Molly Parker, Mary-Louise Parker, Marco
Leonardi, Nadia Litz, Brendan Fletcher, Daniel MacIvor, Philippe
Volter. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Jeremy Podeswa. Produced
by Podeswa and Camelia Frieberg. Released by Fine Line Features. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 45 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6922 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-LOSER-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      07-19 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOSER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TITLE SAYS IT ALL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: No stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Loser'' is a sour, inept comedy that tries to wring humor and
pathos from used condoms, cute kittens and college cretins slipping
co-eds the date rape drug. Needless to say, the laughs and
endearing moments are few and far between, as are characters that
remotely resemble human beings. This is a spectacularly bad movie
that not only lives up to its name, but sinks below it to earn the
distinction of being the year's worst movie.
</P>
<P>
   Commercials promoting ``Loser'' like to trumpet that its
writer-director, Amy Heckerling, was the guiding force behind
``Fast Times at Ridgemont High'' and ``Clueless.'' True enough. But
she also made ``Johnny Dangerously,'' ``Look Who's Talking Too''
and ``National Lampoon's European Vacation.'' Consistent she's not.
And after watching ``Loser,'' one begins to question not only her
talent, but her taste as well.
</P>
<P>
   The movie looks as though it has gone through a number of
revisions, and Heckerling has complained publicly that Columbia
studio executives meddled with her film, taking away its edge. My
guess is that they were trying to do what they could to save this
disaster. Some things just aren't worth saving, though, and
``Loser'' should have been sent straight to video or, more
mercifully for its cast members, simply left on the shelf unseen.
</P>
<P>
   The movie stars ``American Pie's'' Jason Biggs as Paul Tannek, a
small- town nerd who wins a full scholarship to an NYU-like
college. Paul worries about fitting in at a big-city university
since he thinks all the people there will have sophisticated
``Seinfeld'' humor. He finds the reality is much worse, which is
too bad, since an appearance by Kramer or George Costanza would
have enlivened the action here immeasurably.
</P>
<P>
   Paul's three roommates are loathsome, obnoxious jerks who
delight in tormenting and belittling him and making him play the
fool. There is not one laugh in all of this unless your idea of a
good time is watching a nice guy suffer through a barrage of
despicable, reprehensible behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Dora Diamond (Mena Suvari from ``American Beauty'' and
``American Pie'') is the only seemingly nice student at Paul's
school. But that's probably because she has her own set of
tormentors. She waitresses at a strip joint to pay for tuition; the
owner there shorts her on wages. And she's involved with a
manipulative professor (Greg Kinnear at his most unctuous), who
inflicts all sorts of cruel mental abuse upon her. (Professor:
``Would you please just quit talking. Just sit there and look
pretty.'')
</P>
<P>
   What Heckerling was thinking is unimaginable. The story is set
up so Dora and Paul will cast off their abusers and find true
happiness, but their characters are so bland that we could not care
less what happens to them. Watching them take punishment after
punishment is a miserable experience, and this lifeless movie
doesn't even give the audience the satisfaction of seeing the jerks
get their comeuppance.
</P>
<P>
   Even more incomprehensible is why Heckerling thought it would be
funny to watch Paul's roommates slip a date rape drug to Dora at a
party. And it's not the only time they do this; a good chunk of the
film revolves around the boys' date-rape ``high jinks.'' You could
possibly understand such misogyny played for laughs if a man wrote
the movie; coming from a woman, it's both sad and shameful.
``Loser'' indeed. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
The film: ``Loser'' (PG-13; drug content, crude sexual material and
language). &QL; 
The stars: Jason Biggs, Mena Suvari, Greg Kinnear. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Amy Heckerling. Released
by Columbia Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 38 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6924 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-CYC-TOUR0720-COX     07-19 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grueling Tour de France nears ends; Armstrong keeps lead
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ With the grueling Tour de France nearing
the end, a regenerated Lance Armstrong of the United States
maintained his lead Wednesday as one of his vocal rivals dropped
out.
</P>
<P>
   Only 130 riders started stage 17, which took the competitors on
relatively flat ground from Evian Les Bains to Lausanne, the first
time the Tour has crossed into Switzerland in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who ran out of energy Tuesday after he bypassed a
feeding station, was revitalized. He finished 35th, but with the
same time as stage victor Erik Dekker. Armstrong maintained his
5-minute, 37-second cushion over Jan Ullrich, the 1997 champion who
is the only rider with a remote chance of catching the Texan.
Armstrong lost two minutes to Ullrich on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He recovered well,'' said Chris Carmichael, Armstrong's
longtime coach. `` He's doing great.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-seven riders shared the same winning time of 3 hours, 24
minutes and 53 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong and the race's eight other top riders passed a
surprise blood test taken Wednesday, the first test of its kind on
this year's Tour. It marked the latest step taken by the
International Cycling Union following a scandal-plagued Tour in
1998, when several top riders were expelled or quit for taking
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong lost two major rivals: Marco Pantani, the 1998 Tour
champion, said he felt too ill after Tuesday's stage to continue
riding. And Alex Zulle, who finished second to Armstrong last year,
withdrew midway through the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani, who had fallen to 14th place overall, blamed intestinal
pains for his decision. Other riders suggested it might have more
to do with his fading performance Tuesday during the competition's
last major mountain-climbing stage _ the last real chance for
Pantani, a poor sprinter, to narrow Armstrong's lead before the
final race to Paris on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who overcame testicular cancer to win the Tour in
1999, exchanged harsh words with Pantani after allowing him to win
a mountain stage. He said he shed no tears about his rival's
departure.
</P>
<P>
   He pointedly referred to Pantani as ``the Elephant,'' a nickname
referring to Pantani's jug ears and a reference the Italian has
sought to shed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elefantino is a different man. I don't think anybody fully
understands his motivations,'' Armstrong said. ``It's his problem.
He's not my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17th stage wound east around Lake Leman and then turned west
toward Lausanne. There was only one climb of any significance, the
1,455-meter Col des Mosses.
</P>
<P>
   Dekker and Erik Zabel, who have combined to win five stages this
Tour, led the charge to the finish line. Dekker was not familiar
with the final six miles of the course, but he darted past Zabel's
left shoulder just as the two caught the emerging shadows of the
finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Dekker crossed the finish line with his arms outstretched as if
to say, ``No problem.'' But moments later, the native of the
Netherlands was holding back tears before he could speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe this. This is impossible,'' Dekker said.
``This is one thing I didn't think of.''
</P>
<P>
   Dekker, 29, turned professional after winning a silver medal in
the 1992 Olympics, but he didn't emerge as a pro star until eight
years later.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Suzanne Halliburton at
shalliburton(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
