<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEERLEADER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUT I'M A FUNNY MOVIE!'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
There's a funny idea buried deep inside the campy
self-congratulation of ``But I'm a Cheerleader'' screaming to get
out.
</P>
<P>
   Heh, heh, we said ``out.'' And while that isn't a very good pun,
it's better than any of the broad, clumsy jokes this satire of
sexual reorientation programs makes. Yes, such operations, which
try to make gay folks straight, are more than ripe for needling.
But first-time feature director Jamie Babbit and screenwriter Brian
Wayne Peterson's cartoonishly cliched approach to the material
takes all the sting out of what could have and should have been a
wicked, angry black comedy.
</P>
<P>
   To put it another way, these filmmakers could use a little humor
reorientation. And that's no joke.
</P>
<P>
   The bright young actress Natasha Lyonne (``Slums of Beverly
Hills'') mostly just pops her eyes in bewilderment as Megan, a
suburban cheerleader who, due to a growing affinity for tofu and
Melissa Etheridge tunes, is judged by loving friends and family to
be at risk. She is henceforth packed off to True Directions, a
Victorian gingerbread mansion/prison run by blatantly
overcompensating dragon lady Mary Brown (Cathy Moriarty) and her
gratefully heteroized assistant Mike (RuPaul Charles, without the
makeup), where Megan is quickly convinced, to her horror, that she
is indeed a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned parents park their embarrassing kids here to be
straightened out. Of course, all except Megan are so obviously,
well, who they are that the whole dithering process is a joke. And
since the filmmakers presume anyone who doesn't wholeheartedly
approve of homosexuality has to be a complete moron, their movie
becomes one long, subtlety-free gag about deceiving both oneself
and clueless authority.
</P>
<P>
   The production's one non-caricature, Clea DuVall's Graham, soon
captures Megan's heart, and ours, too. Wandering in from some good
movie we're not seeing, DuVall projects all the real yearning,
sullen resentment and emotional intelligence that the film's topic
deserves. Unfortunately, DuVall's thoughtful performance looks
about as isolated here as a same-sex couple might at a North Dakota
prom.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the film, you'll be hard-pressed not to imagine ways in
which it could have been funnier and more pointed. One suggestion:
Make it a lot harder for Megan to accept her lesbian tendencies.
Her protests against her incarceration then could have framed a
sharper critique of anti-gay hysteria ... and of course, when she
fell in love with Graham, it would actually mean something
politically and satirically, not to mention representing an
interesting character development or two.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we're expected to laugh at elementary-grade gags about
gender role stereotypes (the girls at True Directions must wear
pink and practice vacuuming, the boys are in blue and chop wood)
and cheer on the kind of by-the-book, star-crossed teen-age romance
that's as overused in gay cinema as it is on the WB. ``But I'm a
Cheerleader'' is all mindless rah rah, backed up by very little hah
hah. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``But I'm a Cheerleader'' (R; language, sex). &QL; 
The stars: Natasha Lyonne, Clea DuVall, Cathy Moriarty, RuPaul
Charles. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Jamie Babbit. Written by Babbit and
Brian Wayne Peterson. Produced by Andrea Sperling and Leanna Creel.
Released by Lions Gate Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 24 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
