A6927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EMMY-VOTES-NYTR     07-19 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMY-VOTES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMMY VOTING CHANGES UPSET `EMMYS' AUTHOR 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAY HANDELMAN   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Thomas O'Neil is worried. For the first time
in decades, the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences has changed
the voting procedures for the Emmy Awards and O'Neil calls it ``one
of the great tragedies in history.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a bit hyperbolic when you consider world wars, famines
and natural disasters. But O'Neil's world is show-business awards,
particularly the Emmys.
</P>
<P>
   He is the author of ``The Emmys,'' a history of the annual
prime-time and daytime television awards. He is also the author of
``The Grammys,'' about the music awards, and a forthcoming look at
13 different major film awards.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the announcement of the prime-time Emmy
nominations at 8:35 a.m. on Thursday, O'Neil said he expected the
changes in the voting to reduce the chances of new shows and
underdogs, while allowing sentimental favorites to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, volunteers gathered over a weekend to view tapes of
all nominees in a specific category, and picked the winners. This
year, volunteers will be able to watch those tapes at home, where
there is no guarantee that they will watch entire episodes before
they vote.
</P>
<P>
   The new system was announced in March in what academy officials
said was an effort to get more people involved in the voting.
O'Neil said the changes were a reaction to the outcry from critics
when ``The Practice'' defeated ``The Sopranos'' for Best Dramatic
Series at last year's awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're all to blame for this,'' O'Neil told an audience of
writers here.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, he said, ratings never mattered. ``Shows that would
have been canceled were saved by winning Emmys in their first
year,'' he said, citing ``Hill Street Blues,'' ``Cheers,'' ``Cagney
and Lacy'' and ``Mission: Impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice in Emmy history, shows that had been canceled won the top
awards, ``The Bob Newhart Show'' in 1962 and ``My World and Welcome
To It'' in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   That will not happen under the new system, O'Neil said.
</P>
<P>
   Academy officials said that the new procedure is in progress and
that it will affect only the 27 awards presented during the
televised ceremony, which airs Sept. 10 on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had triple the number of people agree to participate
as judges in the process,'' said Meryl Marshall, academy chairman.
</P>
<P>
   She said that O'Neil's concerns are unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the members of the television academy take the
Emmy quite seriously,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil said he's keeping his eye on several potential winners as
proof that the system has been diminished. Michael J. Fox has never
won an Emmy Award for his role in ``Spin City'' (he won three times
for ``Family Ties'') but he may be a sentimental favorite this year
since he revealed he has Parkinson's Disease and left the series.
Nancy Marchand, who died last month, could win for her role as
Livia Soprano in ``The Sopranos.'' And Julianna Marguilies could
win again for her final season as nurse Carol Hathaway on ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any of these people could be deserving; we have to see what
tapes they submit and how they compare to other nominees, but they
are more likely to win for sentimentality sake than anything
else,'' O'Neil said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
