<HEADER>
A6932 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-EARNINGS0720-COX     07-19 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke reshaping pays off in profit
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After two consecutive money-losing quarters, Coca-Cola
rebounded to earn $926 million, or 37 cents a share, in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are beginning to see the benefits from the large-scale
reshaping that we started several months ago,'' Coke Chairman Doug
Daft said Wednesday in a statement. ``I think these (results)
demonstrate that our business is moving on plan, and it is moving
in the right direction,'' he added during a conference call with
industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   This is Daft's first full quarter at the helm of the world's
largest beverage company since becoming chairman and chief
executive in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Daft has moved with a sense of urgency to vigorously
manage expenses, while being disciplined in spending marketing
money,'' said Andrew Conway, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Healthier economies in many parts of the world helped drive up
case sales _ a key indicator of performance _ by 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solid business trends in the second quarter are the result
of strong innovation around brand Coca-Cola and improving global
economic conditions,'' said company President Jack Stahl.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders were rewarded by the news as Coke stock climbed $2
Wednesday to close at $61.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there is still uncertainty,'' said Sanford Bernstein
analyst Bill Pecoriello, ``as investors become more comfortable
they are not stepping in front of a train wreck, they will begin to
anticipate the real benefits of the strategic changes ... and the
(stock) valuation should move higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Daft said those changes include a decentralized and
``impactful'' marketing strategy in which 26 different directors
around the globe are rewarded for innovative campaigns that connect
with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's second-quarter performance was a welcome change
from the loss of 2 cents a share it posted in this year's first
quarter, as well as in last year's fourth quarter. Those results
included one-time charges.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's room for improvement. Second-quarter profit was
down 2 percent from a year ago, when it earned $942 million, or 38
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts, however, pay more attention to financial
results that exclude one-time charges because they give a better
picture of a company's ongoing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding nonrecurring items, Coca-Cola earned 42 cents a share,
beating analysts' estimates by a penny a share. Those charges
included 5 cents a share for the massive restructuring the company
announced in late January.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue increased 5 percent to $5.62 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In North America, where beverage prices in supermarkets have
increased about 5 percent during the past year, case sales in the
quarter increased slightly more than 1 percent, which was below
analysts' expectations. It was the poorest performing region for
the company in volume growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pricing actions taken in the last year by our bottlers in
North America have been a necessary step to improve the overall
returns for our customers (retailers) and bottlers,'' Stahl said.
``As we move into the second half of 2000, we anticipate that the
company, our bottlers and our customers will benefit from improving
volume trends at a more profitable level.''
</P>
<P>
   During the conference call, Stahl said the company will soon be
launching new marketing and advertising campaigns to boost North
American sales of Coke Classic and Diet Coke. He acknowledged the
company has ``some work to do'' on Sprite, one of its main brands
that has experienced declining supermarket sales this year.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl also said new brands would be introduced in North America
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, meanwhile, second-quarter case sales jumped 13
percent. In Latin America and Asia, volume rose 8 percent, while it
increased 5 percengrowth in core profit margin countries, such as
Japan, Germany and Mexico, was robust,'' analyst Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   On the cost front, the company said it expects its
restructuring, which resulted in the elimination of 5,200 jobs
worldwide, to save it $150 million this year and $300 million
annually in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
