<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6935 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-GRAVE-DECOR-NEWHOUSE &LR;      07-19 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAVE-DECOR-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEMETERIES STRUGGLE TO DEFINE `APPROPRIATE' GRAVE DECORATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE is
available as a ``separate-buy.'' For information about purchasing
the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate
at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.
This story first moved May 24, 2000.) 
 By DRU SEFTON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day is gray and damp at the small cemetery next to Our Lady
Queen of Poland Church in suburban Silver Spring, Md. The only
noise is the occasional whish of a car rolling past on the wet
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Atop a flat gravestone rests a soaked Mother's Day card. Nearby,
a pottery frog, fuzzy rabbit statue and colorful plastic
hummingbirds with pinwheel wings decorate an elderly man's grave.
The last few years, especially around holidays such as Memorial
Day, cemetery aficionados are noticing an increase in the placement
of these ``grave goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Sentimental objects left at the final resting spot of a loved
one include everything from the simple -- cigarettes -- to the
poignant -- car keys on a young man's birthday, and from the
personal -- a wig -- to the elaborate -- wrapped gifts beneath
fully decorated Christmas trees complete with battery-operated
lights.
</P>
<P>
   This resurgence in the use of grave goods, a tradition since
ancient times, is creating a quandary for modern cemetery
officials. Just what is ``appropriate'' to place on a grave? When
is a display of affection and loss too elaborate or too personal?
Is a mourning family's need to leave these items more important
than the cemetery's duty to keep graves tidy?
</P>
<P>
   It is a controversy pitting the power of grief against the
pragmatic needs of cemetery maintenance and decorum.
</P>
<P>
   -- In Seneca, Fla., a daughter is fighting attempts to remove a
pink flamingo statue from her father's grave. The Seneca Cemetery
Association last month voted to ban such ornaments. The family
insists the flamingo is there to ``remind us of what a jovial
person he was and to give us all something happy to focus on.''
</P>
<P>
   -- At Lakeview Cemetery in Burlington, Vt., Joyce Martin may no
longer put her husband's hunting cap, favorite hunting shirt and a
small plastic deer on his grave. The town's Cemetery Commission
recently passed rules against such items, citing visitor complaints
and maintenance problems.
</P>
<P>
   -- The placement of grave goods also was banned late last year
at Oaklawn Cemetery in Jacksonville, Fla., after ``it had become
out of hand,'' according to a cemetery official.
</P>
<P>
   -- So many items are being left on graves in a cemetery in
Independence Township, Mich., that the assistant director of public
works is considering installing underground, lockable boxes to hold
them.
</P>
<P>
   These grave goods are part of a larger trend toward
personalization in funeral practices, said Travis Cunningham,
associate editor of American Cemetery: The Magazine of Cemetery
Management.
</P>
<P>
   Cemetery personnel ``are struggling with it,'' Cunningham said.
``They want to please everybody, but they have to keep things
looking the way most people want it,'' which is respectful and
dignified.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Fells, general counsel for the International Cemetery and
Funeral Association in Reston, Va., said safety also is a
consideration. ``Workers and visitors could be injured by these
things shooting out of mowers,'' Fells said.
</P>
<P>
   Families see it another way. ``It's part of the grieving
process,'' said Joyce Martin of Milton, Vt., who remains upset that
she can't leave her husband's hunting memorabilia at his Lakeview
Cemetery gravesite. He died in 1996. She understands the need for
families to be able to leave sentimental mementos.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things were important to them, so they're important to
us,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Fells said that there are no uniform rules within the cemetery
industry regarding grave goods. He estimated there are 100,000
cemeteries in America; each sets its own guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Westbrook, Maine, has typical rules for its three
cemeteries: ``Lawn ornaments (such as balloons, wooden crosses,
ducks, fish, etc.) are not permitted. ... All flags and artificial
flowers must be removed by the second weekend in November except
for winter arrangements. ... The director has the right to remove
any objects that do not comply with the cemetery rules and
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   For Thomas Smith at Spring Grove Cemetery in Cincinnati,
communication of the rules is what's important. The cemetery
publishes brochures with cleanup schedules so families will know
when to gather items.
</P>
<P>
   Officials try to be understanding. If individuals ask that
something special be left on a grave for a certain occasion -- say,
a birthday -- that request will be honored, said Smith, senior vice
president at Spring Grove.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the power of memorialization, people leaving things,
and we encourage it,'' he added. ``We try to be really sensitive.
One of our missions is to help create good memories in all we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring grave goods is a huge task at Spring Grove. The
150-year-old cemetery houses more than 200,000 graves on 750 acres.
</P>
<P>
   People feel so strongly about these items that they are seeking
out cemeteries that allow grave goods to be placed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm seeing in increasing numbers is, people want a say in
how they will be remembered,'' said Helen Sclair, who teaches
cemetery appreciation classes and leads tours as the ``cemetery
lady of Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they find out a cemetery doesn't permit people to leave
things, they'll go find one that will'' and plan to be interred
there instead, she said.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   One of the most bittersweet items Sclair has seen at a grave was
for a deceased young man's 30th birthday -- ``General Motors car
keys placed very securely in a little homemade jar; the family
figured out how to attach it to the tombstone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The variety of grave goods ``always surprises me,'' Sclair said
-- cups of tea, money, a bottle of whiskey, a man's cane, a dish of
chop suey.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Katie Karrick, editor of the ``Tomb With a View'' cemetery
newsletter in Cleveland, has seen all kinds of items in her visits
to hundreds of gravesites.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   One grave in Florida struck her as especially poignant. ``A
young man, it was about six or nine months after he died,'' she
said. ``The whole surface of his grave was covered with those bead
bracelets popular with kids; necklaces, packs of cigarettes,
candles, nickels, dimes and pennies.'' The gravestone was ``a very
stylized image of a person on a surfboard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so moved,'' Karrick said, ``I felt that I wanted to
leave something, too. On the way back to the car I saw a penny on
the ground, minted the same year the young man had died. So I left
that on the grave myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Karrick has seen the use of grave goods spread from the
traditional remembrance holiday of Memorial Day to other
celebrations such as Halloween, the Fourth of July and Easter,
along with birthdays and anniversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to do with a period of time, determined solely by the
individual, in which they want to continue sharing with their loved
ones,'' said Karrick. ``Bringing things they enjoyed -- be it golf
balls, golf tees, teddy bears, balloons, toys -- is a way of
keeping their memory alive. With time, memory begins to fade; this
is a way of keeping it a little fresher, keeping the person close
to you.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Karrick leads Ohio cemetery tours called ``Stones and Bones,''
presents lectures on cemeteries and publishes the 1,700-circulation
newsletter. She thinks the baby-boom generation, now coming to
grips with mortality by burying parents, has a lot to do with the
resurgence in grave goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers don't want to be ignored or forgotten,'' Karrick
said. ``Many are trying to leave some kind of a mark that we were
here, that we lived our lives and cared passionately about
something; we don't want people to forget us.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurel Gabel of Pittsford, N.Y., has been seeing more graveside
items made on home computers. She's the research clearinghouse
coordinator for the Association for Gravestone Studies, a nonprofit
group in Greenfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen whole grave plots covered with messages kids have
printed out on computers: `I love you Papa,' things they've done in
school, all strung together on that computer paper with holes on
the side,'' Gabel said.
</P>
<P>
   She notices a lot of wedding invitations and baby announcements.
``I've also heard people play favorite music on tape, then leave
the tape there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these things are a little chronicle of what's going
on,'' Gabel added. ``It indicates this person is still really a
member of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like the Mother's Day card in the Silver Spring cemetery.
It read: ``The weather is nice. Broke my right arm. Had Barbara's
wedding shower -- she misses you so much. Saw her and Stan get
married on the Internet. I told her you, Poppop and Daddy were
right there. I'll come back on Memorial Day ... God knows how much
you're missed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
