<HEADER>
A6937 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-BEGGING-RESPONSE-NEWH     07-19 2195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEGGING-RESPONSE-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS, COMMUNICATIONS INDUSTRY STRUGGLE WITH BIRD KILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE is
available as a ``separate-buy.'' For information about purchasing
the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate
at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.
Story first moved June 15, 2000) 
 ART ADV: With four photos, of Bob Cote (NNS1), David Frost (NNS2),
Brooke Sylvester with Mark Wade (NNS3) and Wade with an
unidentified pedestrian (NNS4). 
 By BRUCE TAYLOR SEEMAN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAU CLAIRE, Wis. _ Charles Kemper has picked up dead songbirds
for 40 years, retrieving their broken carcasses and bloody feathers
from beneath a local TV and radio tower.
</P>
<P>
   More than 120,000 birds have fallen. They've dropped overnight
in the grass, on rooftops, in the street. A recent night's death
toll was 11, including two Tennessee warblers, a species in
decline.
</P>
<P>
   And always the question remains: What makes these nighttime
travelers, some able to navigate mountain ranges and cross oceans,
crash into the lethal latticework of a blinking communications
tower?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know very little more now than I did then,'' said Kemper,
one of the cadre of amateurs and professionals long puzzled by the
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists estimate that more than 4 million migrating
birds are killed each year in tower collisions nationwide. And
together with industry representatives, they're weighing landmark
strategies to keep birds away from the sky-high death traps.
</P>
<P>
   To minimize the slaughter, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service
hopes soon to issue voluntary construction guidelines on tower
height, lighting and location. Compliance would mean considerable
expense to an industry that is racing to expand.
</P>
<P>
   The task is urgent, advocates say. Thousands of towers have
risen during the cellular phone and digital pager booms. And a new,
taller generation will appear with the spread of digital TV.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ornithologists plan a pioneering study to learn why
some towers lure the chirping birds to a grotesque end. Researchers
also hope to reveal more answers to some of nature's most
tantalizing questions: How many birds roam the heavens? What
species goes where? What keeps them on course?
</P>
<P>
   But the priority is to unravel the tower mystery.
</P>
<P>
   While more birds are killed by other hazards -- cats, cars,
office buildings -- conservationists view the towers as a threat
that can at least be minimized. Any gains would be embraced by
ornithologists who fear that pesticides, development and other
factors have sent populations of migrating, neotropical songbirds
into a prolonged slide.
</P>
<P>
   At some towers, including the 1,000-footer in Wisconsin, bird
deaths are dwindling -- and that's not necessarily a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw tremendous casualties in the '60s and '70s,'' Kemper
said. ``But they've gradually been fewer. ... I think there may be
fewer birds. I wouldn't like to think that, but it may be.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird kills have been reported for more than 100 years. Confused
birds have flown into fires, monuments, street lights and airport
ceilometers that measured cloud height.
</P>
<P>
   At communications towers, birds are killed in several ways. Some
crash into girders and wires. Some accidentally spear each other
with their beaks. Disorientation sends others straight into the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath is rarely seen. Towers commonly stand in sparsely
populated areas, and raccoons and other scavengers quickly pick
through the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   It's even more rare that a tower kill is witnessed as it takes
place. ``This happens 100 yards up in the middle of the night,''
said Ronald Larkin, a wildlife ecologist for the Illinois Natural
History Survey.
</P>
<P>
   The kills occur during spring and fall migrations, and at night,
when songbirds travel to avoid the heat and daytime predators. Fog,
mist or other weather increases the odds of trouble. Unlike larger
birds that might climb above the clouds, smaller migrants may try
swooping underneath, into altitudes interrupted by the towers.
</P>
<P>
   The worst kills happen when a flock, perhaps numbering half a
million, flaps toward a lighted tower. Something about the lights
draws the birds closer. They begin to circle closer and closer to
the tower and its steel tethers.
</P>
<P>
   It is unknown what physiological trick is at work. Many
ornithologists believe birds navigate by the stars. In stormy
weather, a tower's lights, intended to warn away airplanes, may
mimic the celestial beacons.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Larkin used a radar dish several years ago to follow a flock of
birds approaching a 1,000-foot tower in Michigan. When the tower,
which was marked by steady and blinking lights, became enshrouded
in descending clouds, ``we noticed that the birds flying inside the
cloud started behaving strangely,'' Larkin said. ``A substantial
number made turns. They were well out from the tower, but the birds
were flying in a slow arc.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin believes that birds caught in bad weather are afraid to
leave a tower's glow. ``They circle, and as they turn, maybe the
circle gets a little smaller, they strike the guy wires and fall to
the ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams Evans, a researcher who has used audio monitors to
study migration for Cornell University, told a workshop of
ornithologists last year about a kill at a 317-foot tower on the
Nebraska plains.
</P>
<P>
   After pointing a monitoring device at the sky near a tower,
Evans said, ``I was very surprised to discover I had recorded some
bird collisions with the tower. You could actually hear the wing
beats of ducks as they approached the tower, then a collision
sound, and in one case, a thud on the ground. ... A blue-winged
teal was found dead under the tower. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But they didn't sound like vocalizations I had recorded in the
past 15 years from other regions of the country. They were alarm
calls. ... These birds were flying along at night in the dark and
they just didn't see the tower until they were right up on it. Many
apparently became aware of the tower right at the last minute and
gave alarm calls as they attempted to swerve.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Among the most vivid accounts of kills are written reports and a
scratchy home movie kept by Kemper in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Kemper became interested in birds during World War II. While
crossing the Pacific, he was captivated by albatrosses that
zigzagged across open sea. After the war he read about bird deaths
caused by ceilometers, skycrapers and towers. While a young doctor,
he began checking a 500-foot tower in nearby Eau Claire.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing turned up for several months. But then a 1,000-foot
tower was erected near the 500-footer. Kemper missed the first kill
while on vacation, but the local paper published a report.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made for interesting reading,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carcasses were ordered buried by a town official who feared
disease. But other kills followed, including one widely recognized
as the largest single kill ever recorded: more than 20,000 dead
birds discovered Sept. 20, 1957.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see, as far as 500 feet from the tower, birds lying on
the highway crushed by passing vehicles,'' Kemper wrote in an
Audubon Magazine article recounting the deaths of warblers,
thrushes and tanagers. ``There were men, employees from the
next-door junkyard and neighboring businesses, raking up dead birds
like leaves into piles.''
</P>
<P>
   An 8-millimeter film, spinning from a dusty Kodak projector,
documents another kill in the late '50s or early '60s. Its
flickering scenes are all the more powerful for being silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are just the injured ones,'' Kemper said, narrating a
segment showing handfuls of birds collected in a net sack. ``Most
of them died.''
</P>
<P>
   The images are wrenching: Kemper's teen-age son walking on the
roof of a nearby body shop, dropping dozens of dead birds into a
plastic bag. His small dog, Tramp, stepping cautiously in the
street among hundreds of feathered lumps. Kemper's daughter sitting
at a table, stacking victims into piles according to species.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Many specimens, preserved in backyard freezers, were shipped to
university researchers. Kemper's yellowed logs tally the species.
On Oct. 1, 1959, for example, among hundreds of victims were 64
Swainson's thrushes, 44 red-eyed vireos and 46 blackpoll warblers.
</P>
<P>
   Kemper understood he was documenting an important phenomenon,
but ``it got so you went out there and you hoped you didn't find
anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another of his accounts documents a 1964 kill of about 4,600
birds. ``You were lucky if you weren't clunked on the head by a
falling bird,'' Kemper wrote. ``Some of the station personnel ...
got out a 1,000-candlepower television spotlight. Aiming it at the
tower, we beheld a tremendous spectacle. Great masses of birds were
buzzing or milling around the tower like swarming bees or moths
around a flame.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, efforts to address tower kills have accelerated. Not only
are there fears about new towers, but on Jan. 22, 1998, up to
10,000 birds, mostly lapland longspurs, were slaughtered at a tower
during a West Kansas snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were birds scattered all around the agricultural fields,
up to a quarter-mile from the tower,'' said Eugene Young, a
visiting ecology professor at Southwestern College in Winfield,
Kan. ``And you could see birds that were impaled on the stubble. It
was milo or wheat stubble. The birds actually flew into the ground
hard enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, the Cornell researcher who helped organize last fall's
workshop, said ``the longspur kill catalyzed everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The actual number of communications towers in the United States
is unknown but estimated at perhaps 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Only towers of 200 feet or taller, which are required by the
Federal Aviation Administration to have safety lighting, are
federally registered. There are nearly 50,400 of those, according
to the Federal Communications Commission. But shorter towers,
controlled only by local zoning, have proliferated with the spread
of cell phones and pagers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, bird conservationists fear that 1,000 so-called
megatowers for digital TV transmission -- including some
approaching 2,000 feet, taller than the Empire State Building --
will be erected in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 federal officials, conservationists, researchers and
members of the private sector have formed a committee, the
Communication Tower Working Group, to launch research into tower
kills.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Fish and Wildlife Service has drafted its interim
measures for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Manville, a Fish and Wildlife Service biologist, said
expanding companies would be asked to locate transmission equipment
on existing towers rather than build new ones. If that's not
possible, companies would be encouraged to build shorter towers
with no supporting guy wires, locate towers outside areas prone to
low clouds, and mark towers with white strobe lights rather than
slowly pulsing red ones, which are believed to be more alluring to
birds.
</P>
<P>
   It follows that tower construction would become more expensive.
A tall tower without supporting guy wires, for example, requires
more concrete and steel. American Tower Corp., with plans to build
1,200 towers this year, would pay an estimated $70,000 extra for
every 300-foot tower without guy wires, said Rebecca DeMoss, a
company official.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Williams, a lawyer for the Cellular Telecommunications
Industry Association, a trade group represented on the working
group, said her organization had not yet adequately reviewed the
proposals. ``We're withholding our support until we can have the
serious dialogue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, federal officials hope the industry will pay for much
of the planned ornithological study, which may run $5 million to
$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most research would probably take place at towers in the eastern
two-thirds of the country, where migration routes are heaviest.
Ornithologists might use radar, acoustical monitoring, night vision
goggles or other devices. Experts in bird vision and navigation
would participate. One expert has suggested measuring dead birds'
body fat and water content to learn what role exhaustion might play
in their fate.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are already brainstorming ways to keep birds away.
In addition to white lights instead of red, they'll try fluorescent
paint, mirrors to shine lights skyward, giant netting, devices that
spin in the wind, horns or devices that broadcast low-frequency
sounds, similar to sonic booms.
</P>
<P>
   The study would take years, but the possible payoffs are
enormous, ornithologists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit like medicine in the Middle Ages,'' said
Larkin. ``You have a symptom, and you have something that might fix
it, but you have no idea what's going on in the body. It's animal
behavior, bird migration and bird vision. There are areas that we
don't understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
