<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6939 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-FED-GENERATION-NEWHOU     07-19 2053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-GENERATION-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GENERATIONS, TWO LEVELS OF CONFIDENCE IN THE U.S. ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE is
available as a ``separate-buy.'' For information about purchasing
the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate
at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.
Story first moved on June 20, 2000) 
 ART ADV: With two photos, of Sonny Collie (NNS1) and of Rob and
Cara Olsen (NNS2); and with a graphic showing changes in economic
indicators over time). 
 By JIM NESBITT  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a difference a generation makes.
</P>
<P>
   When Sonny Collie, a musician from Dallas, considers the six
consecutive interest rate increases approved by the Federal Reserve
Board and the sharply spiking spring and summer price of gasoline,
he shudders with these bad memories:
</P>
<P>
   The gas lines during the energy crises of the 1970s. The
combination of runaway inflation and high unemployment known as
``stagflation.'' The recessions that seemed to undercut every
recovery. And the double-digit interest rates that made it nearly
impossible to buy a home in 1980 and 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Rob and Cara Olsen react without the fearful imagery -- perhaps
because they were mere children when the economy of the '70s and
early '80s whacked huge holes in the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   Both are 31 years old -- Collie's juniors by 17 years. Unlike
the Texan, they haven't lived scared or coped with the notion that
they might not be as prosperous as their parents, let alone surpass
their standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers and today's young adults regard the nation's
longest economic expansion through the eyes of their respective
experiences. The resulting differences may not create the kind of
wall the Great Depression put up between American generations of an
earlier era, but it is still a substantial divide between those who
have lived through economic upheaval and those who have never been
intimate with recession and inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a generation of people used to good job markets and
higher levels of disposable income and easy about carrying a lot of
debt,'' James Schmotter, dean of business at Western Michigan
University, said of the younger set. ``There's a whole generation
that probably understands to some degree what inflation is through
college courses or its impact in other countries, but they haven't
seen friends losing jobs or lost one themselves because of tough
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Olsens. They bought a house in Silver Spring, Md.,
a month ago, braving the interest rate bumps with which Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan has tried to chill the inflation out of
America's boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not losing a lot of sleep at night thinking the economy is
going into the crapper and that I'm going to lose my job,'' said
Rob Olsen, an economist for a public policy research firm. ``The
economy's been pretty good through most of my adult life. ... It
does breed confidence year after year when you don't hit that many
rough spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers like Collie have a tougher time trusting the
current prosperity precisely because of their rocky economic
experiences, their loss of the sense of entitlement created while
growing up in the post-World War II economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was broke and living on Beanie Weenies,'' Collie said of the
'70s. ``I remember being terrified by what was going on. I don't
remember it being an analog to what our parents faced during the
Depression, but it hit me hard. It made me paranoid and destroyed
my notion that this was a great nation that was going to roll
forward no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until that moment, we were a generation that knew no limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments among baby boomers fuel a broad wariness of the
economy that caused consumer confidence to lag well into the
current expansion, said Lynn Franco of the Conference Board, a
research organization that regularly measures Americans' economic
mood. Not until 1995's sharp drop in the unemployment rate did
consumer confidence top the Conference Board's magic 100-point
mark, its indicator that a majority feel good about the economic
future.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, it seems not even the twin golems of rising
interest rates and gas prices can shake the economic faith of U.S.
consumers, never mind their age.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the consumer confidence index shattered its monthly
record, posting a 144.7 mark. It is now at 144.4, its
second-highest level ever, said Franco, director of the Conference
Board's consumer research center in New York. This despite the fact
that 71.2 percent of those surveyed expect interest rates to go
still higher.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's string of boosts, said Franco, hasn't caught
consumers off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've built it into their thinking about the economy,'' she
said. ``It's just not having the big psychological impact and it's
not impacting consumer spending.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Recent Gallup polls conducted for CNN and USA Today suggest
consumer optimism isn't monolithic. And they reveal an ironic twist
in the difference between generations: Many boomers, born again in
their economic faith, are clinging more tightly to it.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to gas prices, the younger generation exhibits the
greater pessimism. Fifty-eight percent of those ages 18 to 29 think
the increases are a harbinger of permanent change, according to a
May survey. Only 45 percent of those 50 to 64 agree with that
position.
</P>
<P>
   As for higher interest rates, a June survey shows a larger
percentage of the 18-to-29 young adults are reacting by adjusting
major spending decisions -- 41 percent, compared with 32 percent of
those ages 50 to 64.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't as contradictory as it first appears.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking a long, more haunted economic view, young adults are
exhibiting a sharp, almost tactical reaction to interest and gas
price increases -- in some cases, accelerating a house purchase to
lock in a good mortgage rate. But their long view of the economy
remains unshaken.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the more bitter economic experience of older
generations helps them take a broader perspective. This may be bad
news, they say, but they've lived through worse.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Collie paints all this in dark tones. Though he is surprised by
polls showing somewhat greater ``price sensitivity'' to gas and
interest rate increases among young adults, his take on that
generation remains unchanged: Youngsters, particularly those who
buy into the notion that technology is creating permanent
prosperity, exhibit the arrogance and naivete of inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a sense of entitlement to all the things that we
know may not be there forever,'' Collie said. ``We know how close
that chaos can be much better than an 18-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara Olsen, a statistical consultant, gives her generation's
outlook a different spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I think the economy's going to keep getting
better and better,'' she said. ``But because of our experiences, we
think we can weather any little ups and downs and don't think too
much about big downs.''
</P>
<P>
   This generational difference echoes an ongoing argument among
economists, historians, financial professionals and business
people:
</P>
<P>
   Are the very fundamentals of economics being rewritten by
technological marvels like the Internet, resulting in immunity from
capitalism's traditional cycle of boom and bust? Or do those old
rules still apply, albeit in an atmosphere of global competition,
greater productivity and instantaneous communication?
</P>
<P>
   The young wizards of the Internet preach the former with
evangelical zeal. Economists are more cautious, but point out some
significant differences between the modern U.S. economy and the
troubled editions of two and three decades past.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Cold War or accompanying economic drag of four
decades of military competition with the Soviet Union. There has
been no tectonic shock like the Arab oil embargo of 1973.
</P>
<P>
   But greater productivity and efficiency are the prime
difference, said Robert Dauffenbach, director of the Center of
Economic and Management Research at the University of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that improvement is driven by technology -- from
computers to robotics to the Internet -- and the dismantling of the
vertically integrated corporate behemoths of the past, Dauffenbach
said. Innovations such as outsourcing and just-in-time supply
deliveries have trimmed payrolls and tailored supply more closely
to consumer demand, lessening the likelihood of the inventory gluts
that triggered previous recessions.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Dauffenbach said, globalization -- aided
mightily by the Internet -- has expanded markets and increased
competition among suppliers. This keeps prices down, punishes
inefficient players and cools inflationary forces despite the
lowest U.S. unemployment levels since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Another key difference is demographic, said Diane Macunovich, an
economics professor at Barnard College of Columbia University who
has studied the baby boomers' impact on the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   As this giant bulge of humanity entered the work force, it at
first stimulated the economy with demand for products, creating an
expansion that helped absorb its numbers. But this mass of young,
cheap labor encouraged companies to hire more bodies instead of
investing in more efficient machinery and plants, inefficiency
exacerbated by the inflationary pressures of the Vietnam War and
the Great Society programs, Macunovich said.
</P>
<P>
   When the first Arab oil embargo hit, consumer spending dropped
off rapidly, triggering a steep recession in 1974 and a glut of
goods. But production costs remained high, resulting in what Collie
remembers as ``stagflation'' -- simultaneous economic sluggishness
and inflation.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   The movement of the baby boom into the work force caused a steep
decline in young workers' wages. From 1970 to 1985, wages of young
white males dropped 40 percent when adjusted for inflation. Young
black males experienced a 60 percent drop. In addition, women began
working in record numbers, ending what economists call the ``family
wage,'' the unspoken extra paid to a married male in the theory
that he was more productive with a wife taking care of chores at
home.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Boomers made all kinds of compensating adjustments as a result,
Macunovich said. They put off marriage and children, prolonged
their education or dependency on parents.
</P>
<P>
   Collie, making his living backing such luminaries of the Austin
music scene as Willis Alan Ramsey, Roky Erickson and the late B.W.
Stevenson, delayed marriage until 1986 and parenthood until 1988.
He and his wife Cathi, a billing manager for a Dallas law firm,
didn't buy a house until 1992. He told himself he was a free
spirit, a musician with a bohemian lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I was totally full of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a strong historic correlation between the number
of 15-to-24- year-olds and the strength of the U.S. economy,
Macunovich said. Even the early edge of the baby boom expanded the
economy until their sheer numbers overwhelmed and overheated a
system soon wracked by inflation and oil shocks.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the American economy has enjoyed yet another surge
in the absolute numbers of this age group, an echo boom of the
boomers' children. But this generation isn't having the same
proportional impact on the work force as its parents did; it's
being easily absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is suffering none of the high unemployment, low
relative wages and high inflation that buffeted the boomers,
Macunovich said. In other words, its members are perfectly
positioned to enjoy the fruits of continued expansion.
</P>
<P>
   But will that sweet harvest be unending?
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Collie doesn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   To his experienced ear, Greenspan's notes sound like the opening
bars of a golden oldie of economic disillusionment and dashed
hopes. It is a classic that has never left his head. ``What our
generation lived through trimmed our sails psychologically,'' he
said. ``It definitely limits my optimism about the economy and the
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
