<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6943 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DIGITAL-PLAYERS-N     07-19 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DIGITAL-PLAYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOTTLENECK BETWEEN THE DIGITAL PLAYER AND THE EAR: THE PC 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CIR-MP3-PLAYERS) 
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Makers of personal digital audio players readily concede that
despite almost two years of gradual improvements, using the
palm-size and smaller devices is still not nearly as simple as
slapping a CD into a conventional CD player and pressing the play
button.
</P>
<P>
   The chief source of all the complication is the personal
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the dozens of models of digital audio players on
the market today, and most scheduled to be available soon, require
a computer to load them with music.
</P>
<P>
   The simplest method is to copy songs from CDs _ called
``ripping'' _ and then store them on the computer in highly
compressed audio formats, or codecs, like MP3 and Windows Media
Audio. The other approach is to use a computer with an Internet
connection to hunt up some of the countless songs available on
various Web sites. Music on the Web is already compressed in an
audio format, and listeners can download it into a computer.
Portable players are not yet able to do this alone.
</P>
<P>
   Once the digital music is in the computer, either stored on the
computer's hard drive or on a removable storage medium like a Zip
disk, the computer needs special programs to best identify the
music, organize it, play it and load it into a portable player.
Those programs are integrated into something commonly called music
management software. And there's the rub.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the music management software that greeted early
adopters of portable players was complex, temperamental and
generally user-hostile. But in recent months, as portable-player
hardware has significantly improved, so has a new batch of music
management software. Some of the programs are included with new
portable players; others are sold separately, like Sonic Foundry's
Siren Jukebox, a standout for its abundance of features and
exuberance of design elements. And still others are being posted on
the Web as shareware.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most improved examples of music management software
can be found in S3's Rio Audio Manager 3, which comes with the Rio
600 portable player, and Microsoft's Windows Media Player 7, which
can be downloaded free at www.microsoft.com/windowsmedia.
</P>
<P>
   These programs are simple to master. And they can be used both
to convert music taken from CDs into music files and to download
music from Internet sites. They also offer features that permit
users to turn digital music collections into custom CDs (if the
computer has a CD-R or CD-RW drive).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, with so much digital media on the Internet these days,
like streaming video and audio (including live radio, concerts and
music videos) in multiple formats, the new Rio and Windows programs
are being marketed as all-in-one solutions. Each easily searches
and categorizes content in the computer, even tracking down music
files users may have squirreled away in some forgotten corner of
their hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   People can use the software to create playlists by artists,
genres or any theme, in much the same way they would name and
organize documents using a word processor program. Once the
playlists are made, the music management software can do one of the
things it does best _ move digital music into portable players.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio Audio Manager is especially well suited to work with
Rio's line of portable players, either automatically recognizing
them when the devices are plugged into a computer's Universal
Serial Bus port (or serial port on older models) or by manually
selecting the player model from a pull-down menu in the software.
</P>
<P>
   Once the portable player is recognized, the program displays two
adjoining windows; the one on the right side lists what is on the
portable player, and the one on the left displays what music is
available for a listener to copy into the attached player. A
playlist can be placed in the left-side window by simply dragging
and dropping in songs or double-clicking them into the window.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio software plays MP3, Windows Media Audio and other
leading audio and video formats.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows Media Player 7 also reads MP3 and, of course,
Windows Media Audio (almost twice as compressed as MP3, with
similar high fidelity), as well as a range of other audio and video
formats. But the Windows player especially excels at ease of use.
Its look and design is sleek and simple. All the buttons and
windows are well placed, well labeled and intuitively arranged so
their function is clear.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows player also has audio sweeteners, sound-enhancing
programs by SRS Labs called WOW and TruBass which, among other
things, create the illusion when music is played through the
computer that the speakers are farther apart than they are likely
to be on a desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Windows and Rio management software feature annoying
visualization programs, windows that fill with a variety of
computer-generated, three-dimensional animations that respond to
whatever music the software is playing. Even at their best, the
light shows hardly seem to justify the heavy demand they make on
the computer's central processing unit, and they can impede music
playback on all but the most robust computers.
</P>
<P>
   Like most audio management software, both also have graphical
equalizers to adjust the audio characteristics of the music.
</P>
<P>
   And there are alternative ``skins,'' fun and fanciful versions
of the interface.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some notable exceptions. Sony's OpenMG Jukebox
software, which comes with the VAIO Music Clip, has a strikingly
unadorned appearance. It does not offer alternative skins. It also
bears only a dash of 2-D animation seen on a thumbnail-size screen
when music is being played back. The animation can be turned off.
</P>
<P>
   However, while the software will recognize and play music
encoded in MP3, it will copy music files from CDs into Sony's own
format, Atrac3, only.This feature, unlike MP3, severely limits the
number of times a music file may be copied. This is one attempt to
prevent wide dissemination of MP3 files without payment to music
companies or artists.
</P>
<P>
   The Sony software is simple and straightforward. A five-minute
song takes about a minute and a half to copy using the highest bit
rate offered, 132 kilobytes per second. The higher the bit rate,
the better the sound quality but the larger the file. Using Atrac3
at 132 kbps limits recording time to an hour. Copying the same
music using a 66 kbps bit rate yields 120 minutes of playback.
</P>
<P>
   With MP3, using a bit rate that will play back music at what is
usually called near-CD quality, the rule of thumb is about 1
megabyte per minute of music.
</P>
<P>
   Transferring music to the portable player is a three-step
process: highlight the song or album, indicate with a mouse click
that the selection is to be transferred and then click a start
button. Three songs of average length can be transferred in about a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Iomega, which is making and licensing portable players with Clik
drives, takes a different approach. Yes, music software, included
with the players, is used to manage music downloads and rip CD
tracks. But the actual process of transferring the music to
portable players using Clik drives involves nothing more than
dragging a desired song from column A to column B.
</P>
<P>
   In Iomega's digital architecture, a music file is nothing
particularly fancy, just another file to be dragged and dropped
from one hard drive to another.
</P>
<P>
   No, it is not as simple as popping a CD into a CD player, but it
is getting easier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
