<SLUG> BC-ELLEN3-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes wire service clients.) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON ... &QL; 
Ellen Wright &QL; 
Age: 60 &QL; 
--Profession: Interior designer/cookbook author. &QL; 
--Hometown: Cambridge, Mass. &QL; 
--Food background: Over the years she has studied with many food
experts including Lydie Marshall, Madhur Jaffrey and the late James
Beard. &QL; 
Cooking style: Casual and stylish. She likes clean food and
uncomplicated tastes. &QL; 
--Most popular dish she makes: Chinese Chicken Salad (recipe
included on this page). &QL; 
--Favorite junk food: Candy spearmint leaves. &QL; 
--Secret food passion: Double cream cheeses (any of various cow's
milk cheese that have been enriched with cream so they contain a
minimum of 60 percent butterfat). &QL; 
--Pet peeve: Long cocktail hours. &QL; 
--Favorite kitchen gadget: Food processor. &QL; 
--Favorite cookbook: All of the Lee Bailey cookbooks. &QL; 
--Worst kitchen disaster: A long time ago, she attempted to make
brioche for 22 people using 36 eggs and six pounds of butter. It
required a lot of kneading, but the recipe didn't work and she had
to throw it all out and start over. ``By the time dinner came, I
could hardly lift a coffee cup, my arms hurt so much.'' &QL; 
--Favorite restaurant: Leo Le Lion in Paris. It's a little bistro
and a tiny jewel of a place. She also likes Caviar Kaspia in Paris,
which serves all kinds of caviar and sturgeon and fabulous
desserts. &QL; 
--Ideal vacation: Any place with good weather, nothing to do, no
pressure and preferably no phone. &QL; 
--What does she do when she's not designing or cooking? She knits
(sweaters) and plays golf and bridge. &QL; 
--If she couldn't be an interior designer, what would she be? A
surgeon. &QL; 
--If she could dine with anyone (current or in history) who would
it be? Jerry Seinfeld. &QL; 
--Family: She resides in Manhattan with her husband, Joe. She has
three grown children and four grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
