A6954 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-BROPEN0720-COX     07-19 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ It might as well be considered one giant
Road Hole.
</P>
<P>
   The famous strip of macadam on golf's most historic hole, the
17th at the Old Course, is little different from the rest of Old
Tom Morris' famous property.
</P>
<P>
   While the pre-tournament talk was how Tiger Woods' length will
allow him to overpower the Old Course with 350-yard drives and
knock-down wedges, it looks now as if Tida or Earl Woods could get
it out there about 250.
</P>
<P>
   The course is so firm and fast that it is going to play more
like the floor of the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the much anticipated British Open at St. Andrews,
the treasured Home of Golf. Woods, a 2-1 favorite, is going for a
career Grand Slam at 24, to join Jack Nicklaus, Gary Player, Gene
Sarazen and Ben Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Open Championship has gone from historical to
potentially hysterical. Somebody must have spiked the fertilizer
with cement: Players are on a search for wedges with less bounce to
slide more easily under the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Royal and Ancient Golf Club officials wanted to return tradition
to the British Open after last year's over-the-top setup at
Carnoustie. Instead of growing the rough so deep that errant drives
were nearly lost, this year they turned the Old Course into a place
where the greens are slower than the fairways.
</P>
<P>
   If the wind blows hard at any point of the week, John Daly's
drives could bounce halfway to Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted a true links test in the year 2000, and they
certainly have,'' Scot Colin Montgomerie said. ``If you did not
have the spikes on, you would slip down the first fairway. It is
incredible. . . . Length might not be the greatest asset that we've
all talked about. Everyone is going to hit it an awful long way
this week. This is as links a golf course as we will ever play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish weather conditions of the past two days have been
as kind as possible. Wednesday was downright balmy, near 70, with
hardly a breeze, allowing the course to bake ever harder. But it
could change by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Scores also could hinge on how harshly the flagsticks are
tucked. If not accessible, with the Old Course's dips and slopes
and giant putting surfaces, three-putts will be common. In the best
of conditions, the Old Course tests the chipping and putting
talents of the world's best players, many of whom are used to
playing target courses where the ball is flown to the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can hit it quite close to some of the greens (from the
tee),'' Scotland's Andrew Coltart said, ``but you cannot play
normal shots to the flag, because they spin and they will catch on
the large slopes.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience is paramount. Players hit to find distant spires or
to avoid mounds. In places, a dead-center 300-yard drive can be
less useful than a 210-yard iron, because of hidden pot bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who haven't played there might see a flag fluttering in
the distance and fire a wood straight at it without realizing there
is no fairway there, that it tends to be off to the left
somewhere,'' Coltart said. ``But the greens are so big and
difficult that you could hit every one in regulation and still
shoot 80.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
