<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-EARNINGS0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS package volume to reveal industry trend
 &HT;    By Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Is United Parcel Service Corp. taking business away
from rivals FedEx and Airborne Express?
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts say they'll be paying close attention to
package volume figures Thursday when UPS announces its
second-quarter earnings at 8 a.m. via its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for market share, they say, will be nearly as
important to them as financial performance. A survey of analysts
predicts the company will earn 60 cents a share for the three-month
period that ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the industry is focusing on package volume,''
said Art Hatfield, transportation analyst for Morgan Keegan &AMP; Co.
``The volume figures will tell us who's winning and who's losing
the market share game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield said UPS and FedEx have been gaining in recent months
at the expense of Airborne Express and the U.S. Postal Service.
FedEx outperformed Wall Street estimates in its most recent
quarter, while Airborne Express warned analysts its volume would be
flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overnight document business is dying,'' Hatfield said.
``Transportation companies need solid ground networks in order to
compete, and Airborne doesn't have one.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS, the world's largest transportation firm, delivers more than
13 million packages a day, and the vast majority of them travel on
trucks and vans _ not airplanes. UPS also operates an online
``document exchange'' designed to drastically reduce or even
eliminate the need for some premium-priced next-morning shipments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day is fast coming when it won't make sense for anyone to
fill up airplanes with pieces of paper in envelopes,'' said Norman
Black, a UPS spokesman in Atlanta. ``That gives us a leg up.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Hatfield said fax machines and secure e-mail are cutting
into a core FedEx business, but the Memphis-based company has
responded by offering a broad range of air and ground deliveries
for high-value goods.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey L. Pittsburg, transportation analyst at Pittsburg
Institutional Services, said the UPS report also will be watched as
a gauge for business-to-consumer Internet sales. About 55 percent
of the consumer items bought and sold online travel via UPS.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS does a lot of business in the B-to-C arena,'' he said.
``The company is a good barometer of that whole side of the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS shares on the New York Stock Exchange closed Wednesday at
$60.75, up 31 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
