<HEADER>
A6961 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     07-19 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HANGING RECALLS THE HORROR OF THE PAST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raynard Johnson is dead. He was found hanging from a pecan tree
in his front yard in Kokomo, Miss. Maria and Jerry Johnson, his
mother and father, are certain he was killed because he dated white
women. I agree. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Acts of racial hatred still occur in the United States.
Authorities sometimes rule such deaths suicides; I prefer to call
them what they are: lynchings. They're no different from the
hangings that occurred during the Civil War and continue still. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was just 17 years old when his father found him hanged
June 15. The Rev. Jesse Jackson has said his death has ``the smell
of Emmett Till all around it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Till, a black Chicago teen, was lynched in 1955 after being
accused of whistling at a white woman while visiting relatives in
Mississippi. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five years have elapsed between the deaths of Till and
Johnson, and little seems to have changed. Black skin can still be
a death sentence in America, even more so when white women are in
the mix. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is not racism on my part. It is not raw emotion. I believe
it to be fact; it's a part of our history that is repeating
itself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gary Flowers, field secretary for the Rainbow Coalition, had
this to say about Raynard's death in a telephone interview: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the belt (around his neck) was not his,'' Flowers
said. ``We know that the climate of racial intolerance was reported
to be a stronghold for white supremacists groups such as skinheads
and the Klan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that Raynard was in high spirits on that day. He had
just received a computer. He was preparing for a family reunion. He
was a rising senior named in Who's Who Among American Students _
the top 5 percent of students in the nation. He was starting on the
football team, and he was a very popular young man.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing in what Flowers said that indicates Johnson was
a distraught teen-ager about to take his own life. Indeed, none of
the classic suicide warnings _ withdrawal from friends and family,
changes in eating and sleeping habits, drug and alcohol abuse _
were apparent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Raynard's full-of-life demeanor lead a reasonable person to
conclude that he would not take his own life,'' said Flowers,
speaking on behalf of the teen's family. ``Given the climate within
Marion County of racial intolerance, he was a victim of a
homicide.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Marion County coroner's office has said Johnson's death is
consistent with suicide because he had no marks or injuries on his
body. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But just months before Johnson's death, Flowers said, a bridge
less than a quarter mile from the Johnson home had racist graffiti
on it. In addition, he said, that bridge is rumored to be a meeting
place for white supremacists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow Coalition is offering a $10,000 award for
information leading to the arrest and conviction of those involved
in Johnson's death. The group has a hot-line number, (601)
583-4943, Ext. 113. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in donating to the Raynard Johnson Memorial
Fund may write to: First Federal Bank, Box 268, Columbia, MS
39429. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flowers said that Jackson has asked the Justice Department to
pursue any and all leads and to broaden its investigation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope investigators will call Johnson's death what it is.
Murder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
