<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-HISPANIC-IMMIGRANTS-H     07-19 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-IMMIGRANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HISPANIC GROUPS LOBBY CONGRESS OVER HIGH-TECH WORK VISAS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The leaders of major Hispanic groups threatened
Wednesday to use their clout at the ballot box to pressure Congress
into including long-standing immigration issues in legislation
expanding the number of visas for skilled technology workers.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are the special work permits, know as H1-B visas, for
computer programmers, electrical engineers and other high-tech
workers. Computer and software companies are pressing Congress to
raise the number of visas issued annually to fill jobs California's
Silicon Valley and other technology centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to bring up immigration legislation, you must
address the needs of the Latino community,'' said Cecilia Munoz,
vice president of the National Council of La Raza, one of the
nation's largest and most influential Hispanic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos are a very critical voting block,'' Munoz said. ``We
potentially hold the keys to the White House and to control of
Congress. Both parties need to step up to the plate and show they
are interested in our issues. The Latino community is watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a Capitol Hill news conference, the Hispanic leaders
called for action on three ``Latino Fairness Issues,'' asking that
they be attached to legislation that would increase the numbers of
visas for high-tech workers.
</P>
<P>
   H1-B visas are capped at 115,000 this fiscal year, but all of
them were issued in the first six months. Under present law, the
ceiling will fall to 107,500 in the next fiscal year, starting Oct.
1, and 65,000 in fiscal 2002.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least three bills before Congress that would raise
the ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Although the H1-B program enjoys high levels of support in
Congress, labor unions and many high-tech workers contend the
industry has used the visas to hold down wages and discriminate
against higher-paid American workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Latino groups said they would help muster support for the
stalled visa legislation only if three issues are attached to it.
They want Congress to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Change from 1972 to 1986 the date by which illegal immigrants
must prove they have lived continuously in the United States in
order to apply for permanent residency. That would apply to about
350,000 illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grant Salvadorans, Guatemalans, Hondurans and Haitians the
same opportunity to apply for permanent residence as was extended
to Cubans and Nicaraguans in 1997. Nicaraguans and Cubans who apply
for green cards, or residency permits, get them immediately while
immigrants from these other countries may wait as long as 11 years
to have their applications processed. Congress granted a speedier
processing for Cubans and Nicaraguans after determining they were
exposed to violence and hardship if they returned to their home
countries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allow immigrants without green cards or visas who are
sponsored by family members or employers to apply for permanent
residence in the United States. Current law requires they complete
their applications at the U.S. Embassy in their home country.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of the high-tech industry urged Congress not
to attach other immigration measures to legislation that would
boost the numbers of visas for foreign high-tech workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support a clean approach to this legislation and urge House
and Senate lawmakers to do likewise,'' said Harris N. Miller,
president of the Information Technology Association of America,
which represents Internet and computer software companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democratic-sponsored amendments related to long-staying
immigrants and Central American immigration have confused and
delayed this legislation long enough,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Mirabel, chairman of the National Hispanic Leadership
agenda, a coalition of 35 groups, said Hispanic groups would keep a
close eye on the positions representatives and senators take on
these key issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any legislative agenda that attempts to frame itself as
pro-immigrant and pro-Latino must address these issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mirabel noted that Vice President Al Gore has stated his support
for these issues, but that Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential hopeful, has not taken a stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe both the candidates have the responsibility to urge
their colleagues to bring it forward,'' Mirabel said, referring to
the Hispanic legislative agenda. ``Bush can't stay quiet on this.
He's got to be on the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Both presidential candidates are investing significant time and
money in courting Hispanic voters. Bush is trying to extend his
broad support among Texas Hispanics to the national arena.
</P>
<P>
   Mirabel said the Hispanic vote would be especially important in
California, Texas, New York, New Mexico, Florida, Arizona,
Illinois, Pennsylvania, Massachusetts and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Sanchez, executive director of the Labor Council for Latin
American Advancement, which has 1.5 million members, urged the
high-tech industry to support Hispanic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without it, the Latino community will do everything it can to
see that H1-B bombs out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gonzalez, director of the National Association of Latino
Elected and Appointed Officials, which has 5,000 members, said this
is a battle about Silicon Valley and new immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about big money versus low-income communities,''
Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
