<SLUG> BC-DOW0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Greenspan to grab attention today
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan is expected to
tell Congress today that the economy is slowing, but that inflation
persists as a threat. Analysts caution investors not to look for
anything that would ignite a Wall Street rally.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed chairman is scheduled to make one of his twice-yearly
appearances before Congress to report on the economy and Fed
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's senior economist Rick MacDonald said he
expects Greenspan to deliver a ``less threatening'' forecast than
he did in February, when the numbers still showed robust economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised short-term interest rates six times since
June 1999 in a move to restrain a growth rate it regards as
inflationary, especially in wages.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe the government's reports released since
May show enough economic slowing to make additional rate hikes less
likely _ with maybe one more to go at most.
</P>
<P>
   But MacDonald looks for Greenspan to reiterate a warning the Fed
issued after its June meeting. While acknowledging evidence of
slower growth, the Fed added that conditions still existed ``that
may generate heightened inflation pressures in the foreseeable
future.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald also cautioned that ``the last thing Greenspan wants
to do is set off a stock market rally'' that might rekindle
consumer spending fueled by the market's ``wealth effect.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bloomberg News survey of economists also concluded that
Greenspan will leave the door open to further interest rate
increases this year while citing evidence the economy is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   In Wall Street action Wednesday, analysts said disappointed
investors dumped Internet stocks that failed to meet overly
optimistic expectations for the second quarter, sending all major
stock averages lower.
</P>
<P>
   The catalysts for the sell-off were quarterly results from two
bellwether stocks: software giant Microsoft, which fell $5.38 to
$73.135 after reporting stagnant second-quarter sales, and Apple
Computer, which fell $4.56 to $52.69 after it beat earnings
forecasts by only a penny.
</P>
<P>
   The falloff in blue-chip stocks came despite a positive earnings
report from Citigroup, the largest U.S. financial services company.
Citigroup said its profits rose 23 percent over the same period a
year ago, and its stock rose $1.31 to $68.
</P>
<P>
   The main economic news was a Commerce Department report that the
U.S. trade deficit jumped to a record $31 billion in May, mainly
due to America's trade imbalance with oil-producing nations.
</P>
<P>
   Total May imports of goods and services dipped 0.3 percent to
$116.8 billion, but exports fell even more sharply by 1 percent to
$85.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
