<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSICIANS-675(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR UNSIGNED MUSICIANS, WEB PROVIDES LISTENERS AND EVEN SOME
PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Conn., Minn., Ga., Pa.)  (See also CIR-MP3-PLAYERS) 
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since his post-punk band put out its first compact disc in
May, Ken Peterson, a guitar player and commercial dishwasher
salesman, has been spending a lot of time on the Internet. The
Lawrence, Kan., band, mi6, has never played outside of the Kansas
City area, and its self-financed CD is only available in local
stores.
</P>
<P>
   But Peterson, determined to attract a wider audience, also
released several of the new tracks for free on Web sites devoted to
music. He has e-mailed anyone who has ever expressed an interest in
mi6 and persuaded several on-line radio stations to give the band
airplay. So far, about two dozen people who otherwise would never
have heard of mi6 have bought the CD _ not bad, Peterson considers,
``for a no-name band.''
</P>
<P>
   But what really has him logging on lately is the rankings on
garageband.com, where one of mi6's songs has claimed the top spot
based on the reviews of visitors to the site. If it remains No. 1
after another round next week, the band stands to win a $250,000
record contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has been very cool for us,'' said Peterson,
adding that he has also been contacted by an executive at a major
record label who came across mi6 on another Web site. ``The thing
about our band is we just want to play. But a record contract _
yeah, that would be awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   As the recording industry and commercial artists like the heavy
metal band Metallica try to stamp out the distribution of
copyrighted music for free in the form of computer files known as
MP3s, tens of thousands of aspiring rock stars are happily using
the technology to give their music away _ and more than a few are
beginning to see some payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Most, of course, are not getting record deals from the major
labels. But for some bands, that may no longer be the ultimate
goal. For these musicians, the Internet's emerging role as an
equal-opportunity jukebox is providing new ways to make a modest
income from a relatively small base of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Ulike most of the MP3s available through popular services like
Napster, it is unquestionably legal to download, play and copy with
abandon those posted by unsigned artists on the growing cluster of
Web sites designed for them.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat to the surprise of the artists themselves _ and even to
the proprietors of these sites _ millions of Internet users are
doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a lot of days the downloads of unsigned artists are right
up there with the name acts in the music videos on our site,'' said
Andy Schuon, chief executive of Farmclub.com, a site owned by
Universal Records. ``And they're not necessarily even looking at
the ones we feature. People like to dig into the jukebox and type
in ``G'' and just see what's there.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com, the largest repository of free music on the Web, said
it receives more than half a million visitors who listen to more
than a million items each day. The company is perhaps best known
for its legal dispute with the record industry over adding
thousands of copyrighted songs to its database, a case that it is
in the process of settling. But its revenues are generated from
advertising sales based on visitors who come to hear almost
exclusively unsigned artists.
</P>
<P>
   Last November it began to pay all artists, signed or not, a
small fee each time someone listens to one of their songs. And
particularly since May, when the company expanded its monthly
``Payback for Playback'' pool to $1 million it has become a source
of significant revenue for those at the top of the MP3.com heap,
and an incentive for the 75,000 or so others to promote their
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been quite a victory for us after having a lot of record
companies close doors on us for years,'' said Chris Geith, a jazz
guitarist in Madison, Conn., whose Chris Geith Group last month
made more than $6,500 from MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those consistently ranking in MP3.com's top 10 said
they have little interest in a record deal. That may be just as
well, since it is hard to imagine a major label promoting them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They include Ernesto Cortazar, a 60-year-old Mexican composer
whose career was spent mostly in piano bars and who has earned more
than $100,000 from his online efforts since last fall, about
$80,000 from nearly 4 million downloads and the remainder from CD
sales; Mikel Fair, a 26-year-old engineer who quit his job at
Compaq Computer and built a home recording studio when he began
earning more than $20,000 a month from downloads of his electronic
music, and Alex Smith, who just graduated from high school in
Stillwater, Minn., and last month earned $10,239.08 from MP3.com's
program.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com, which says its program has safeguards against
ballot-stuffing, has yet to turn a profit, and Michael Robertson,
the company's chief executive, has made no assurances about the
continuation of the payment program. But other sites, such as the
Internet Underground Music Archive (iuma.com) and Audiohighway.com,
have also initiated compensation schemes for unsigned artists.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, few of the 100,000 or so unsigned artists on the
Internet participate in such revenue-sharing. Most say the main
benefit of distributing MP3s of their songs is the ability to
attract an audience that may eventually buy CDs or t-shirts or come
to a live performance.
</P>
<P>
   And the more experienced caution that none of that will happen
without logging plenty of hours on old-fashioned marketing, online
and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I did was ask my father to reply to all his
e-mail,'' said Ernesto Cortazar Jr., who has taken as a full-time
job the promotion of his father's music on MP3.com. ``I am always
motivating him. The first time he appeared on the charts I printed
that paper, I showed it to him, I framed it. I was like, 'you're
going up!' ''
</P>
<P>
   After convincing his father to put his music on the Internet
last year, the younger Cortazar spent weeks scouring the MP3.com
message boards and picking up tips from other artists. He sends out
regular e-mail updates to a growing database of fans, asking in
each one that they tell a friend about the elder Cortazar's talent
for the piano. Since about half of Cortazar's CD sales come from
outside the United States, his son recruited fans to translate his
Web pages into Korean, Spanish, French, Slovenian, Romanian,
Portuguese, Hungarian, Greek, Italian and Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   The result has enabled both Cortazars to devote themselves
full-time to music.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Rubenstein of the Northern California band Headboard
credits the Internet with vastly expanding the band's reach.
Starting with an e-mail list of about 10,000 fans who had attended
gigs over the last three years, Rubenstein doubled the list over
the last year, which he has spent e-mailing fans of other bands
like his own and offering t-shirts to those who drove the most
traffic to his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts won the band a spot on Farmclub.com's television
show on the USA Network a few months ago. But more important,
Rubenstein said, after sending out an e-mail message informing fans
of a new CD, he received 200 checks for $12 in the mail last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The postmaster said there was too much mail to fit in the
box!'' crowed Rubenstein, who holds down a day job as an editor at
an Internet news site.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so enamored of the Internet as a means of
distributing or discovering new music. Traditional record
executives mostly see the Internet as another repository for the
demo discs that pile up unopened in their offices. And even bands
that use all the right Internet marketing tricks can fail to find a
way to get to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Red Delicious, a Pasadena, Calif., band, spent several months on
the top of MP3.com's charts last year. But several nibbles from
record labels fell through.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least in the record industry you have a chance to make
money,'' said Rob King, the drummer for Red Delicious, estimating
that Internet revenues bring in only about $1,200 a month for the
band. ``We got tons of press. We were the Internet band, everyone
knew who we were, but none of it helped us get a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies are also beginning to forge new relationships
with labels and artists. Emboldened by the idea of being able to
obtain demographic information and e-mail addresses of thousands of
potential customers who have become fans of an artist on-line,
companies like Farmclub.com and Garageband.com have already signed
several bands to emerge from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major record labels are interested in artists that are
going to come out of the chute and sell millions of records,'' said
Tom Zito, chief executive of garageband.com. ``That is not really
music that people deep in their gut embrace. Our process really
allows people to find music that is more interesting to music
lovers than the kind of stuff that people who work at record
companies think they're going to like.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the global network has seemed to tap into a
near-universal desire to be a rock star, it appears to have
unleashed the latent record executive in many a music listener.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like with the radio once they get a hit song they
play it over and over and over until you get tired of it,'' said
Lisa Fields, 42, a property manager for an apartment complex in
Fitzgerald, Ga., who cites the unsigned Buzz Poets as her favorite
new band. ``Going on the Internet you can constantly get new music,
new sounds, new groups so you've got something new to listen to all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Shane J. Strait, an accountant in Harrisburg, Pa., explains his
hours on MP3.com and other Internet music sites another way: ``It's
always better to find bands when they're just forming,'' he said.
`That's when they care more about their fans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
