<HEADLINE>
WEB INVESTOR COMPANY GARNERS $24.8 MILLION IN VENTURE FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three months after tabling its IPO plans, CCBN.com
Inc., a Web-based investor relations company, has landed $24.8
million in venture capital from some big Wall Street players.
</P>
<P>
   That's roughly half the $58 million CCBN.com had aimed to raise
in its initial public stock offering, filed in February but yanked
when stocks tanked in April. The company had already completed its
European road show when it canceled the stock sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting fabulous feedback, but it didn't matter what
you were selling at that time,'' said chief executive and founder
Jeffrey Parker _ best known for having launched First Call, the
well-known clearinghouse for analyst reports.
</P>
<P>
   It's a familiar saga for many start-ups lately: going back for
more venture money when the public markets are unwelcoming. Some
have been turned away.
</P>
<P>
   But CCBN.com in this third round tapped deep pockets, as is
expected to be announced Thursday. Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. leads the
deal and will become CCBN.com's biggest outside investor. Others in
the round include brokerage Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Boston's
HarbourVest Partners, Trident Capital, and America Online Inc.,
which also invested $1.5 million in December.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the three-year-old company had raised $11 million in
venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   CCBN.com builds and hosts investor relations Web sites to help
publicly traded companies handle communications with their
shareholders. It claims 1,500 customers for the service, including
FleetBoston Financial Corp., Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., and Akamai
Technologies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   It also runs a site called streetevents.com, where institutions
and individuals can track the events that can affect a public
company's stock, from earnings releases to analyst calls and CEO
speaking engagements. CCBN.com helps investors hook into public
companies' conference calls at earnings time, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Parker sees the Internet as a disclosure tool, the best way to
deliver to individual investors the same information that Wall
Street gets about public companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're helping companies use the Internet to level the playing
field between institutional and retail investors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Taylor, a partner with HarbourVest, said the investments
from Goldman and Morgan are significant: ``The money means
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, 57, sold First Call and a group of other firms he
started to Boston's Thomson Financial Corp. in 1986. Thomson was
the first investor in CCBN.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
