<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-UNION0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilots at Delta regional subsidiaries seek merger with main
union
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The pilots' unions at Delta Air Lines' two regional
subsidiaries want to be merged into the parent carrier's pilots'
union, a change they say is needed to gain fair representation for
their members.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the Air Line Pilots Association units at Comair and
Atlantic Southeast Airlines comes a little over a year after Delta
bought full ownership of the two regional carriers, which feed its
hubs in Cincinnati and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's pilots also are represented by ALPA. But the three
unions continue to operate as separate chapters of the national
union, with separate contracts and elected leaders. On certain
issues that affect pay and career advancement, the larger chapter
has more clout and can negotiate terms that hurt the smaller units,
merger advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a two-tier system within the Air Line Pilots
Association,'' said J.C. Lawson, chairman of the Comair ALPA
chapter. ``This is a very big issue and one the national union has
got to address.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comair and ASA unions on Wednesday petitioned ALPA's
national headquarters to merge the three units, which would entail
putting all pilots onto a single seniority list for pay and
promotion purposes. Details of how that would be done would come
later, but Lawson said it would likely raise pay rates for pilots
at the subsidiaries ``somewhat.''
</P>
<P>
   ALPA's national leadership council will consider the request at
a meeting in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Duncan, a spokesman for Delta's ALPA unit in Atlanta, said
the smaller unions ``didn't consult us'' before filing the
petition.
</P>
<P>
   Delta management views the petition as ``an internal union
matter,'' said John Kennedy, a Delta spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Lawson said the mushrooming use of regional jets at the
subsidiaries has brought the issue to a boil. The Delta pilots'
union, like those at other major airlines, views regional jet use
as a form of ``outsourcing'' in which the parent airline uses
lower-paid subsidiary crews to fly routes once reserved for bigger
jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta union, which is in contract talks, has said it will
seek tighter limits on how many regional jets ASA and Comair can
operate. The smaller unions' petition argues that such limits
result in subsidiary pilots' careers being ``unilaterally and
egregiously restricted.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
