<SLUG> BC-SPRING-TIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS. COMPANY TO HELP BUILD WIRELESS NETWORK FOR AT&AMP;T 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring Tide Networks of Maynard, Mass. has won a big chunk of a
$250 million contract from AT&AMP;T Wireless to build a nationwide
fixed-wireless broadband network delivering telephone service and
high-speed Internet access, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies, with which Spring Tide has a lucrative
comarketing arrangement, won the deal to build out fixed-wireless
systems in 180 US markets over the next two years to help AT&AMP;T roll
out broadband and local calling services in areas where it does not
own cable television franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of privately held Spring Tide's share were not disclosed.
But based on a list price of $80,000 to $700,000 for its
Internet-protocol switching devices, based on how many features
they have, $50 million or more of the $250 million could be flowing
to the 2-year-old start-up.
</P>
<P>
   As it aims to become a nearly nationwide provider of local phone
service and Internet access, AT&AMP;T is looking to fixed wireless to
fill coverage holes where it has not obtained cable television
franchises as part of its $100 billion acquisition of MediaOne and
TCI.
</P>
<P>
   Already launched in Fort Worth, the fixed wireless service will
be added starting in September in Houston, Los Angeles, San Diego,
and Anchorage, AT&AMP;T said Wednesday. Areas with 15 million more
homes are to be added by 2002, but AT&AMP;T spokesman Richard Blasi
said it has not been determined whether any New England markets
will be eyed for fixed wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Tide is providing its IP Service Switch 5000 to
complement Lucent gear being used in the first phase of the service
rollout.
</P>
<P>
   With fixed wireless systems, homeowners attach a small dish-like
device to the side of their house aimed at a neighborhood antenna
to get telephone service and 516-KBS Internet access. That is about
12 times faster than a dial-up modem but only one-third as fast as
a cable modem. AT&AMP;T plans to boost the fixed-wireless Net access to
1 megabit by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Tide marketing vice president Bob Sullebarger said the
AT&AMP;T deal easily exceeds in value the company's three other
announced contracts, all with small competitive local phone
companies using Spring Tide gear to offer high-speed Internet
access such as digital subscriber line services. Spring Tide late
last year reached a deal with Lucent to sell its gear under a
cobranding arrangement, opening big markets for the start-up.
</P>
<P>
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, AT&AMP;T stock fell $1.4375 to
$33.9375. Lucent rose $1.4375 to $64.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
