</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMC-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMC CITES E-COMMERCE GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMC Corp. said second-quarter earnings vaulted 50 percent to
$429 million as orders from e-commerce companies helped the data
storage maker meet its ambitious growth targets.
</P>
<P>
   EMC Corp. faces a host of fresh challenges from competitors, but
keeps reporting strong results. Wednesday, the Hopkinton, Mass.
company said sales climbed 30 percent to $2.1 billion for the
quarter, marking the first time it has taken in more than $2
billion in a three-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Sales were driven by rising demand for its products from
companies such as American Family Insurance Group and State Street
Corp., which must keep track of vast amounts of data as they move
more business onto the Internet. As a result, EMC boosted revenue
targets for this year and said it is still on track to sell $12
billion worth of devices, software and services in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   EMC's software and services business lines have grown rapidly.
Software revenue nearly doubled to $350 million in the
April-to-June period, a faster growth rate than rivals such as
Veritas Software.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's primary business continues to be building
refrigerator-sized cabinets containing arrays of hundreds of
computer disk drives, and in recent months it has faced new threats
from competitors like IBM and Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   To counter them, EMC introduced new hardware in April, and its
gear has sold so briskly that even traditionally skeptical analysts
were left echoing the EMC line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find any fault with any part of the way they
executed in the quarter,'' said analyst Gary Helmig of the Wit
SoundView Group in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The company itself was clearly satisfied with its performance.
``This was our strongest quarter ever, marked by superior
execution,'' said EMC chief executive Michael Ruettgers.
</P>
<P>
   EMC's profit was 19 cents per diluted share, up from 13 cents a
year ago. The numbers were adjusted to reflect an EMC stock split
in May. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thompson Financial had
expected EMC to earn 17 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   EMC shares sprinted up $5.4375 in New York Stock Exchange
trading Wednesday to close at $84. Shares have more than doubled in
the past year to give the company the highest market valuation of
any in Massachusetts, more than $170 billion based on Wednesday's
closing price.
</P>
<P>
   EMC also said sales rose 30 percent to $141 million during the
quarter for the midrange storage products it took on when it
acquired Data General Corp. last year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its rapid growth, some industry watchers have
expressed concern that EMC might have trouble obtaining all the
parts it needs. In a conference call with reporters Wednesday,
Ruettgers acknowledged that might become an issue later this year.
Component shortages ``may keep us from accelerating the
acceleration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Employment growth is also a concern, as EMC tries to keep up
with orders. EMC had 20,700 people worldwide at the end of June,
1,900 more than at the end of March. In Massachusetts, it now has
7,600 employees, 400 more than three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Despite low unemployment rates, Ruettgers said the company faces
no talent shortage. ``The difficulty hasn't been candidate flow,''
he said. ``The challenge is to make them productive.''
</P>
<P>
   The supply and work force constraints mean EMC isn't likely to
exceed expectations in the third quarter, said Phil Rueppel,
analyst for Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown. But Rueppel said EMC is
likely to meet its $12 billion goal next year.
</P>
<P>
   EMC Wednesday said it had boosted its overall revenue target for
this year to roughly $8.7 billion from $8.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   SoundView's Helmig said his main concern for EMC is the
competition. For instance, IBM and Compaq earlier this month
announced an agreement to jointly market their equipment.
</P>
<P>
   EMC executives, Helmig said, go ``out of their way to say
competition's not an issue, and it may not be now. But the users
are all rooting for competition to come along, if only to keep
prices under control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
