<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-MONEY-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PENNSYLVANIA CANDIDATE FUND RAISING HEATS UP
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Melissa Vogt  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (July 19)--Candidates for Pennsylvanian Congressional
seats are stepping up their fund-raising efforts as the November
election nears, according to campaign finance reports from the
Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Area incumbents held a definite fund-raising edge over their
challengers for the second quarter of this year - April 1 through
June 30. Federal law requires all campaigns that raised or spent
more than $5,000 to submit a finance report to the FEC by last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates without challengers seemed to raise money as if they
were in a hotly contested race.
</P>
<P>
   Running unchallenged, Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Altoona, led the pack
in fund raising and holding onto his cash. By the end of the
three-month period he raised $105,850 and had $221,613 in the bank.
Rep. John Peterson, R-State College, also without a challenger,
took in $55,015 and had $88,483 in cash for the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Pitts, R-Lancaster, second in fund-raising efforts and
liquidity drew in $56,094 and had $165,118 in cash on hand. Pitts'
challenger Bob Yorczyk of Exton, who started with empty pockets on
April 1, raised $747 and had $72 in the bank by June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Harrisburg's Republican Rep. George Gekas raised the least among
the area's incumbents but continued to bring in more than his
Democratic opponent Leslye Herrmann. Gekas took in $9,851 during
the recent quarter, raising $54,634 since the year's start. He
spent $7,034 and had $87,941 on hand at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Gekas gave $2,925 to the Republican committees in Dauphin,
Lancaster and Cumberland counties in May. Other major expenditures
included $1,451 paid to campaign treasurer Raymond Bucks for
accounting and $1,129 for a petition party.
</P>
<P>
   Herrmann spent $1,398 more than she raised during the second
quarter. Contributions to Herrmann's campaign totaled $2,314 for
the quarter and $6,875 since Jan. 1. She had $592 cash on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Goodling's retirement leaves open the 19th district
House seat, which covers Adams, York and Cumberland counties.
Contenders for the seat showed markedly different approaches and
goals for campaign fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic contender Jeff Sanders, a professor at Towson
University, Towson, Md., spends six to eight hours a day calling
possible donors, said his campaign finance director Jaime Fleet.
Fleet said the campaign is gaining momentum and he expects to meet
the $250,000 fund-raising goal by election time.
</P>
<P>
   Sander's campaign coffers swelled to $13,469, up $13,136 or 390
percent from the $333 in the bank on April 1. Of that sum, $7,740,
came from contributions and $7,567 in loans.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Todd Platts, R-York County, said he is keeping things
low-key with ham and cheese submarine sandwich sales each month and
a refusal to accept money from political action committees. He used
the same tactics to win and keep his state seat since 1992. Platts
said the strategy can work for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Platts won the five-way April primary race for his party's
nomination in spite of the fact he came in fourth in fund raising.
Sandwich sales brought in more than $5,000 during the primary
period, Platts said.
</P>
<P>
   Platts said he expects to raise $175,000 for the fall election.
For the first six months of the year Platts' campaign receipts
totaled $83,942. Platts brought in $22,729 during second quarter
2000 and had $6,174 in the bank. Platt said postage has been a
major expense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
