u i BC-RUSSIA-CONTROL-BOS &LR;      07-19 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CONTROL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUMA BOOSTS PUTIN'S POWER OVER PROVINCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In what many called the biggest overhaul of Russia's
government since the fall of Communism, the Kremlin Wednesday
rammed legislation through parliament that stripped the country's
provincial leaders of much of the power and independence they had
won over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The new laws give President Vladimir V. Putin the right to fire
any governor accused of breaking the law. In addition, they take
away the governors' automatic membership in the Federation Council,
the upper house of parliament, and the blanket immunity from
prosecution that went with it.
</P>
<P>
   The upper house had rejected the bill allowing Putin to fire
governors, but the State Duma, the lower house, of parliament voted
363-35 to override the Federation Council's veto.
</P>
<P>
   By a veto-proof margin of 308 for and 88, the Duma also passed a
compromise version of a second bill depriving governors of their
seats in the Federation Council. The upper house must still approve
that bill.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said the changes are necessary to fight corruption in the
far-flung provinces and establish what he calls a ``dictatorship of
law.'' But critics said the measures threaten Russia's shaky
democracy and could pave the way for a dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal lawmaker Boris Nemtsov said granting the president the
right to remove elected governors ``goes against the will of the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be the first step toward an authoritarian regime,''
said Nemtsov in televised comments Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Few here dispute that many of the governors of Russia's 89
provinces have abused their power and run their regions like
personal fiefdoms. From St. Petersburg in the west to Vladivostok
in the far east, critics have accused them of stomping on civil
liberties, suppressing dissent, fixing elections, and enriching
themselves and their cronies at the public's expense.
</P>
<P>
   But the question that hung in the air Wednesday was: Will a more
powerful Kremlin solve the problem and bring good government to
Russia?
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts were skeptical, not least of all because most of
the accusations against regional leaders _ corruption, cronyism,
and creeping despotism _ have also been levelled against the
Kremlin as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a bad choice between the centralized authoritarianism
of the Kremlin and the local authoritarianism of the governors,''
said Vladimir Pribylovsky, a Moscow-based political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, Putin can only remove governors accused of
committing a crime. But politicians and analysts pointed out that
Russia's federal prosecutors and courts are beholden to the
Kremlin, meaning Putin could easily use his new power to pressure
uncooperative regional leaders to get in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``A road has been opened wide for unbridled arbitrariness by
prosecutors,'' Nemtsov told reporters after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Some regional leaders said the changes could result in unrest.
``This poses a threat of the collapse of the Russian Federation,''
said Nikolai Fyodorov, governor of the Chuvashia region in central
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Business magnate Boris Berezovsky, who has bitterly attacked
Putin's proposals, formally resigned from the State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, to protest the expected vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of people already understand that the actions of the
authorities are absolutely dangerous for our society, brazen and
dangerous,'' Berezovsky said. ``We must try to stop them, hold them
in check.''
</P>
<P>
   Yury Korgonyuk, a political analyst with the Moscow-based INDEM
think tank, said the laws would do little to improve how Russia is
governed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just gives federal bureaucrats a weapon to pressure local
bureaucrats. None of the bureaucrats are under the control of
citizens, and nothing will change until they are,'' Korgonyuk said.
``In America you have the mentality toward bureaucrats that: `I am
a taxpayer, I pay your salary, you work for me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In Russia you never hear this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
