u a BC-KY-ALCOHOL-TEMPERANCE     07-19 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KY-ALCOHOL-TEMPERANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVE TO GO WET IN ONE KENTUCKY COUNTY HAS AN UNLIKELY SOURCE 
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRY RIDGE, Ky. _ Almost seven decades after the end of
Prohibition, 75 of Kentucky's 120 counties remain dry by local
choice, but the pressures to go wet _ or ``moist,'' the new limited
imbibing option devised by frustrated state legislators _ are
mounting against the state's temperance leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The question of going wet will be back before voters on Tuesday
in dry Grant County, once rural but now rapidly suburbanizing.
Civic leaders have been wondering what mysterious force conducted
the discreet petition drive that put the issue on the ballot with
1,115 signatures, something of a local shock. Was it, as many
townspeople speculate, a cabal of business executives wary of being
denounced in this rigorously Christian bluegrass community?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it was just me,'' said Dara Florek, a 29-year-old native
of these rolling hills. ``I've done it all by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   An office worker impressed by the booming growth and arrival of
young people, Florek said she just decided it was time that the
options of modern life be fully faced in the county. ``I kind of
kept this hush-hush because I wanted to sneak up on the dry side,''
she said in an interview after being identified as the organizer of
the petition in the fine print of a pro-wet advertisement in the
weekly newspaper, The Grant County News. She collected 300 more
signatures than required.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot question of permitting the sale of alcoholic
beverages in Grant County is of no small moment, as only 30 of the
state's 120 counties have opted to go wet since Prohibition was
repealed in 1933. But the pro-dry ramparts recently appear to be
weakening, as indicated by close margins in various county votes.
Over the years, 15 other counties have evolved as mixed, or moist,
with the largest cities authorized to go their own way within dry
counties.
</P>
<P>
   But a new state law, quietly passed in the closing hours of this
year's Legislature, is designed to promulgate the ``moist'' option
down to small jurisdictions and might considerably liberalize life
in dry counties. The law permits even the smallest communities to
vote on whether to end the alcohol ban in local restaurants with
100 or more table settings, even if the surrounding county stays
dry. The House speaker, Larry Clark, said he moved the measure as a
relatively conservative response to complaints that various regions
were losing out in the competition for tourism and convention
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Progress can be a wild ride,'' said the Rev. David Tucker,
pastor of Sherman Baptist Church here and one of the leaders of
KIDS (Keep It Dry and Safe), the anti-wet coalition hurriedly
organized by local church and civic leaders when the ballot
petition surfaced last month. He denounced the ``moist'' law as an
end-run by the Legislature to foil what is one of the few important
direct-voice options still in county hands, one that he and other
pastors are urging their flocks to reaffirm on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a crossroads,'' Tucker said of Grant County's growth
rate, one of the state's highest. Grant's population has more than
doubled in the last decade to close to 25,000, with a flood of
newcomers from Lexington, 50 miles south, and Cincinnati, 35 miles
north. ``If we set the tone now for raising our children, we'll
grow into that community,'' he said, of the importance of setting
high standards.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, 35, insisted the issue was a modern one of family values
and nuisance-free neighborhoods, and not that of the old-fashioned
pulpit-thumping denunciation of drink that once resounded in the
area's hilltop churches.
</P>
<P>
   But Florek, flatly denying that she is fronting for any business
conglomerate, says the issue is one of convenience, not morality.
Florek started her petition drive before the new moist option took
effect on July 14. ``Why should I have to drive 20 miles out of my
way to Florence to buy a reasonably priced bottle of wine for
dinner guests?'' she asked, contending that the nearest liquor
stores in Kenton County, a wet oasis to the north, were not only
fueling Grant County's rate of drunk driving but price gouging as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Intent to the last, Florek worked this week on a
5-foot-by-8-foot sign calling for residents to vote on Tuesday. She
planned to put the sign up across from the local Wal-Mart. All the
while, she worried that with the birth of her first child four days
overdue, she might find herself bedridden and unable to vote
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot of guts for her to do this,'' said her husband,
Jeff, describing a low-key, six-month, one-woman petition drive.
``And, no, we're not naming the baby `Jack Daniels' or anything
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   A raft of elected officials and local business leaders are
firmly opposed to going wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very safe livable county, with almost no crime
rate,'' said County Judge-Executive Darrell Link, predicting a dry
victory, although with perhaps a smaller margin than the last such
vote 15 years ago when wet forces were turned back by a 2-to-1
margin. Dry Ridge, he noted, is a name that predates Prohibition
and was coined in the days of early railroading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life here is slow, it's wholesome, it's safe,'' Link said,
emphasizing that this is a community of new housing developments
sprouting in old farm fields, not of glasses clinking in the sort
of new strip club that opponents point to in nearby Gallatin
County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of put my head on the chopping block, but it's worth
it,'' declared Mrs. Florek, saying she simply grew fed up with the
inconvenience and political passivity on the subject. ``People talk
around here,'' she said, describing some rough and righteous
letters she said she had received after her name surfaced in the
newspaper advertisement that she said cost her $500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for truth,'' read the headline on the advertisement,
which noted that drunken driving rates were higher in Grant County
than in three neighboring wet counties.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Mrs. Florek's stealth and industry, some voters will
go to the polls on Tuesday convinced that a larger wet force has
been at work in raising the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the business community is somehow behind this,'' said
the Rev. Willie Ailstock of the Dry Ridge Baptist Church. ``And in
a small town like this, nobody wants to be known as a
troublemaker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
