<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-SCIENTIFIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNGRADING CUTS INTO BOSTON SCIENTIFIC TRADING PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston Scientific Corp. shares fell 28 percent Wednesday after
nine Wall Street analysts downgraded the stock following the
company's lower-than-expected second-quarter sales and a gloomy
outlook for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Natick, Mass. medical device company saw its shares fall
$7.3125 _ its largest one-day drop _ to close at $18.5625 as more
than 11.7 million shares were traded.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, Boston Scientific said its second-quarter sales
were down 4.3 percent, to $695 million, from $726 million a year
earlier. And while cost-cutting moves improved earnings, the
company warned that revenue in the second half of 2000 would be
about the same as last year, with lower earnings estimates due to
lackluster sales.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts cut their Boston Scientific stock rating to
``hold,'' while Merrill Lynch downgraded the company to
``accumulate'' Wednesday from ``buy'' just eight days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The lower rating is due, in part, to the increasing friction
between Boston Scientific and Medinol Ltd. of Tel Aviv, Israel, its
key supplier of advanced coronary and peripheral stents, noted
Daniel T. LeMaitre, first vice president at Merrill Lynch in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Surgical stents are tiny devices used to prop open once-clogged
arteries. Boston Scientific owns 25 percent of Medinol and
reportedly has been unsuccessful in trying to acquire the Israeli
company.
</P>
<P>
   LeMaitre and other analysts said the animosity between the two
companies is resulting in delays for product launches, which are
negatively impacting SCIMED and Meditech, Boston Scientific's two
largest divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its rival Guidant Inc. of Indianapolis, which makes its
own advanced coronary stents, Boston Scientific is dependent on
Medinol under a 10-year contract that requires buying hefty
inventories of stent products.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a disconnect in research and process engineering of
new stents between the two companies that is not turning around
very soon,'' said David A. Gruber, senior vice president of equity
research at Lehman Brothers. ``And that has put Boston Scientific
at a disadvantage with Guidant.''
</P>
<P>
   On a conference call with Wall Street analysts late Tuesday,
James Tobin, company president and chief executive, said the
relationship with Medinol has gone from bad to worse. Many
analysts, however, praised Tobin, who joined Boston Scientific last
year, for taking steps to improve the company's internal
efficiencies while struggling to iron out difficulties with
Medinol.
</P>
<P>
   Those proposed improvements include Friday's announcement that
Boston Scientific was dismissing 1,900 manufacturing people in
three states, including 850 in Watertown over the next 18 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1928EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6982 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-CHOICE-HNS &LR;      07-19 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CHOICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOP PLATFORM CHAIR PLEDGES OPENNESSS TO PRO-CHOICE SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, who chairs the
Republican Platform Committee, assured GOP pro-choice advocates
Wednesday that their views will get a full airing next week when
the committee meets before the party's national convention begins.
</P>
<P>
   After a closed-door meeting that Thompson held with several
pro-choice groups, Susan Cullman, co-chair of the Republican
Pro-Choice Coalition, said, ``What was newsworthy to us is that we
continue to have a dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the groups' efforts to have the strict anti-abortion
plank modified or removed altogether at earlier Republican National
Conventions, Cullman said, ``In 1996 and 1992, no one would return
our calls. So this is a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Thompson told the pro-choice advocates that
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee, does
not want the plank changed and that it will be virtually impossible
for them to succeed in their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Stone, chair of the Republicans for Choice Political Action
Committee, which funnels campaign contributions to pro-choice
Republican candidates, said the meeting with Thompson ``went about
as well as could be expected.'' Stone said Thompson asked the
advocates ``to think creatively'' about how to get their message
across without throwing a wrench into the convention.
</P>
<P>
   With the convention opening July 31 in Philadelphia, the
abortion plank represents one of the few areas of debate among the
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 abortion plank does not allow for any exceptions _ such
as in cases of rape, incest or where the woman's life is at stake _
to its opposition to the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   It says, ``The unborn child has a fundamental individual right
to life which cannot be infringed. We support a human life
amendment to the Constitution and we endorse legislation to make
clear that the Fourteenth Amendment's protections apply to unborn
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purpose is to have legislative and judicial protection of
that right against those who perform abortions. We oppose using
public revenues for abortion and will not fund organizations which
advocate it. We support the appointment of judges who respect
traditional family values and the sanctity of innocent human
life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past Bush supported the rape, incest and
life-of-the-mother exceptions. He has declined to apply an abortion
litmus test to judicial appointments. But in an effort to win
backing of Republican conservatives during the primary season
earlier this year, Bush pointedly endorsed the 1996 plank's
language. ``This is a pro-life party,'' he said, adding, ``We need
to say, `Life is precious.'''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans fear that an open squabble over the plank would hurt
the party in a year when its presidential candidate is strong in
the polls. But they also fear that an appearance of being
heavy-handed with pro-choice Republicans could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have a fair opportunity to try to get their
views expressed,'' said Kevin Keane, Thompson's spokesman. ``It
will be a fair playing field, but the governor was also up front
about strong support for the pro-life plank among delegates too.''
</P>
<P>
   The 107-member Republican Platform Committee meets in
Philadelphia next Friday and Saturday, and the four-day convention
opens two days later. The Platform Committee's Family and Community
Subcommittee will take up the abortion plank, which is likely to be
a carbon copy of the 1996 plank, a Republican National Committee
official said.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
