<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONAIRE-ABUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEALTHY YACHTSMAN CHARGED IN DOMESTIC ASSAULT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT AND STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARNSTABLE, Mass. _ Millionaire yachtsman William I. Koch is
facing criminal charges after he allegedly punched his wife in the
stomach and threatened to kill her and his son with a belt in their
luxurious Osterville home.
</P>
<P>
   Barnstable police were summoned to the sprawling estate in a
gated community around 11 p.m. Monday by Angela Koch, who told
arriving officers of her 60-year-old husband's attack, according to
police. She also told police that Koch threatened ``to beat his
whole family to death with his belt,'' Barnstable Deputy Police
Chief Michael J. Martin said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Koch was arrested at the house. He has pleaded not guilty to
charges of domestic assault and battery, and threatening to kill,
and was released on personal recognizance.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Koch, 42, has obtained a restraining order against her
husband under which he must live in the estate's guest house or
beach house while she is in the main house and he cannot be at the
couple's West Palm Beach, Fla. house when she is there.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Koch, whose fortune has been estimated at $650
million, observed: ``Every marriage has its problems and my
marriage to Angela is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my wife and have every confidence that with the help of
competant professionals we will be able to work out our problems
and enjoy a long and happy marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela has been a wonderful wife and mother and has brought me
much happiness,'' said Koch, who won the 1992 America's Cup,
skippering America3 to a victory over Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Koch, who is Koch's second wife, could not be reached for
comment Wednesday. A Koch spokesman, Brad Goldstein, said Wednesday
that Angela Koch has not filed for divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said the couple hopes the media will respect their
privacy and allow them to work through their problems quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Koch's vast wealth and history as a playboy -- which was
documented in a bitter legal fight with a former mistress in 1995
in a Boston courtroom -- has made his private life grist for the
media in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Koch has a total of four children from three women, including a
3-year-old son and one-year-old daughter with Angela Koch. Koch's
second oldest child lives with his mother, a former girlfriend of
the yachtsman, in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Koch's oldest child, Wyatt, is from his first marraige to Joan
Granlund. Wyatt is the inspiration for what neighbors here have
dubbed ``Wyatt's World'' -- an amusement-park-like section of the
estate with a paved go-cart track, tennis and basketball courts and
a soccer field.
</P>
<P>
   According to Barnstable court records, Koch threatened to kill
Angela and 14-year-old Wyatt during the domestic violence incident.
Goldstein said that neither Angela, Wyatt nor the other two
children required medical attention after Koch was removed by the
Barnstable police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Koch and Angela negotiated a detailed restraining order that
includes language that no part of the agreement can be the basis
for any subsequent divorce or custody action.
</P>
<P>
   One provision bans Koch from drinking alcohol for 24 hours
before he visits with his children, who will be accompanied by
their nannies at that time, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   The order, which is to remain in force until Sept. 11, requires
Koch to stay 100 yards away from Angela. But it also allows Koch to
attend social events or parties they host without Koch being found
in violation of the order, which carries a 2 1/2-year prison
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it allows the couple to attend therapy together
without violating the order and permits Koch to contact his wife by
telephone or letter. Usually, all forms of communication between
estranged couples are banned by restraining orders.
</P>
<P>
   During last week's Tall Ships events in Boston Koch was
frequently on local television offering commentary on the ships and
sailing techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, Koch was probably best known in Boston for his
eviction of his former mistress, Catherine de Castelbajac, from a
$2.5 million condo he owned at the Four Seasons Hotel. The Boston
Housing Court trial featured steamy faxes the couple had exchanged
during their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Koch's arrest for domestic violence stunned Koch's friend,
George Regan, the Boston public relations executive, who said
Wednesday both Koch and Angela Koch are friends of his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just really surprised,'' Regan said of the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Regan said Koch was devoted to his family and that he showed
that as recently as Sunday when he brought his 2-year-old son to
Boston while he hosted a Tall Ships party and appeared at a
Metropolitan District Commission press event.
</P>
<P>
   Regan said Koch left in the late afternoon because he promised
to be home for dinner with Angela by 5 p.m. Sunday. Koch joked that
if he was late, ``he'd be in hot water.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch is a native of Kansas whose father struck it rich in the
oil business. Over the last decade, Koch has sued two of his
brothers who run the family corporation for a greater share of the
company in court in that state.
</P>
</TEXT>
