<SLUG> BC-G7-MEETING-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S DILEMMA: HIS LEGACY VS. A GLOBAL ROLE
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID E. SANGER and MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton was a president caught between two
summit meetings Wednesday, one in Camp David dealing with the
oldest and thorniest problems in diplomacy, the other in Japan
approaching the newest and vaguest issues of global inequity.
</P>
<P>
   The Middle East peace talks kept Clinton's attention overtime.
And for him, the meeting in Okinawa, in southern Japan, has less to
recommend itself _ save for the fact that he would be the star and
the issues, from bringing the Internet to developing nations to
funding a global battle against AIDS, resonate with the themes he
has tried to place on the international agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The other one half a world away on Okinawa, has less to
recommend itself _ save for the fact that Clinton would be the star
and the issues, from bringing the Internet to developing nations to
funding a global battle against AIDS, resonate with the themes he
has tried to place on the international agenda.
</P>
<P>
   With his concentration on Middle East diplomacy, Clinton has yet
to be briefed on his role at the meeting beginning Friday of
leaders of the world's seven largest industrial nations, and with
Russia's new president, Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers preceded Clinton to Japan to
warm the president's seat and reassure the Japanese that he would
be there eventually. Traveling with him was the chief person
organizing the U.S. part in the talks, Lael Brainard, who was to
have briefed Clinton on Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we'll wing it,'' said one White House official. ``It won't
be the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Meetings of the group are notoriously disjointed, but the agenda
for this session is particularly scattered. Leaders will discuss
the ``digital divide'' between those nations taking advantage of
the information revolution and those that are not; coordinated
approaches to the spread of AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria; and
even a U.S.-backed proposal to create an international school lunch
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say the issues are unimportant but they are a
laundry list and some of them don't meet my criteria for being the
top global concerns,'' said C. Fred Bergsten, director of the
Institute for International Economics.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, for example, the leaders promised to focus on
remaking the international financial system until safeguards were
in place to prevent another economic crisis like the one that
struck Asia in 1997, from radiating around world markets. But a
recovery shortened the group's collective memory, and while modest
progress has been made, one would have to dig far into the fine
print to find that discussion on this year's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   On the national security front, the summit meeting will grapple
with more traditional issues _ from terrorism and nonproliferation
to the turmoil in Africa, Chechnya and the Balkans. But those
conversations tend to be as scripted as the meeting's communique,
one reason Clinton appeared far less anxious to meet his fellow
leaders than to play out his role as potential Middle East
peacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   That forced Clinton to postpone a one-on-one meeting with
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori in Tokyo, but it should be
noted that Mori's days are considered numbered because of his
party's poor showing in an election last month.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also skipped one of the unique aspects of this
meeting _ a gathering of the leaders of developing countries such
as Algeria, Nigeria, South Africa and Thailand, all of whom have
long complained that they are excluded from the elite club of large
economies. Summers will see them instead, but the smaller nations
are bound to view Clinton's no-show as a snub.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to arrive in time, however, for meetings with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and a session with Putin that is
expected to address Clinton's looming decision on a national
missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president, I'm sure, will want to take advantage of having
the leaders there to discuss the issues that are facing him and the
decision that he will be making in the coming weeks,'' said James
Steinberg, the deputy national security adviser. ``I think that he
will indicate that he is going to take into account the concerns
that have been addressed and all of the factors that we've
previously identified, the four basic variables of cost, threat,
technical feasibility and the impact on overall security.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton's late arrival demonstrates how muc has changed since
he took his first steps on the stage of global diplomacy, also in
Japan. It was July 1993, and other world leaders took turns beating
up on Clinton for the size of the U.S. deficit and Washington's
failure to stabilize the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the U.S. economy reins supreme and Clinton
arrives as the indispensable peacemaker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
