<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ANTIMETRIC-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S SHOPKEEPERS DRAG THEIR FEET ON METRIC CONVERSION 
</HEADLINE>
   bY SARAH LYALL  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROTHERHAM, England _ Over the years, Keane Fletcher has
dutifully, if unenthusiastically, complied with every new directive
imposed on him by the European Union. A third-generation butcher,
he even agreed to take a course last year in which he was taught,
among other things, how to tell when food is not altogether fresh
(one suggested method: check the expiration date).
</P>
<P>
   But in March, when the local government threatened to seize his
late grandfather's antique porcelain scales because they violated
Europe's metric measurement requirements, Fletcher briefly forgot
that he was a serious-minded family man with his own business and
two sons to raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Make sure you send big men, because as sure as there
are eggs there on that counter, I'll break their jaws,''' recalled
Fletcher, 37, a onetime amateur boxer who keeps the old scales in
his shop, in a housing development in this gritty South Yorkshire
town, for sentimental reasons. ``I said, `You can put me on death
row, but I'm not removing those scales.'''
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying that people like Fletcher, who weighs his meat
in pounds and ounces with an electronic scale, have not had ample
warning about the government's metrification program. Britain first
talked about going metric back in the mid-19th century.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, when it joined the Common Market, the European
Union's predecessor, Britain pledged to replace its old imperial
system, which uses pounds, yards, pints and the like, with the
Europe-wide metric system, based on grams, meters and liters.
</P>
<P>
   Britain duly converted, selling its gasoline in liters and, more
recently, its supermarket goods in grams. But small shopkeepers
like Fletcher remained exempt until Jan. 1 of this year. It was
then that new government regulations took effect, requiring every
seller of loose goods _ things like fruits, vegetables, carpets,
window shades, loose candy and meat _ to begin selling in metric
units.
</P>
<P>
   The point, of course, was to harmonize with the rest of the
European Union, a concept that is dear to the government of Prime
Minister Tony Blair. But a healthy percentage of the country's
96,000 or so small shopkeepers do not feel much like harmonizing,
especially not with the Germans and the French.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've been through the war, you don't want French people
telling you what to do,'' said Muriel Kemp, 78, defiantly buying
half a pound of liver at Fletcher's shop. ``I think we're quite all
right on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to say exactly how many shopkeepers have
refused to go metric, but Donna Webb, a spokeswoman for the U.K.
Weighing Federation, which represents scale manufacturers,
estimates that some 30,000 small shopkeepers have not replaced or
converted their imperial-measurement scales.
</P>
<P>
   Webb lays much of the blame on what she called ``this little
problem we're having with the U.K. Independence Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The Independence Party has three members in the European
Parliament, whose dedication to persuading Britain to leave the
European Union tends to leave them eating alone when everyone
breaks for lunch. But while they have had trouble engaging the
public's imagination in many cases _ it is hard to explain abstruse
European regulations to ordinary Britons and expect them to remain
alert _ they have had no such problem with the metric issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to now, the English have gone along with the European
stuff, allowing these kinds of idiocies to mount,'' said Tony
Bennett, who is running the party's anti-metrification campaign.
``Finally it's gotten to be too much.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Britain's populist, vehemently anti-Europe press has weighed in
too. The Sun, which uses the word Eurocrat the way others might use
the word Nazi, has started a ``Save Our Scales'' campaign in which
it is regularly features small shopkeepers who have run afoul of
the metrification program.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outshone, The Daily Mail, which has long enjoyed
printing articles about how the European Union is supposedly
forcing Britain to give up things like its traditional toilets (in
fact, the toilets are safe), has named its first ``metric martyr.''
</P>
<P>
   He is Steven Thoburn, a greengrocer who achieved a degree of
fame in the Southwick Market in Sunderland when local officials
came in and noisily confiscated his imperial scales.
</P>
<P>
   While Thoburn faces a $7,500 fine and the destruction of his
scales, in other parts of the country shopkeepers have gotten off
with warnings. The disparity reflects widespread confusion among
local governments, which are supposed to be enforcing the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a battle between central government and local
government,'' said Vivian Linacre, director of the British Weights
and Measures Association, which maintains that the British
metrification law is not legally binding. ``Brussels said to
Westminster, `This is the law _ now you've got to enforce it.'
Westminister said to the local government, `This is the law _ now
you've got to enforce it.'''
</P>
<P>
   All this puts the country's 2,500 Trading Standards officers in
an awkward position indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have every sympathy with the government,'' said Alan
Charlesworth, chief executive of the Trading Standards Institute,
which helps the Trading Standards officers negotiate the
vicissitudes of their jobs. ``We're harmonizing with Europe and
we've been subject to a lot of directives, and we're doing our best
to comply. For people in the business profession to say that
metrication suddenly happened _ they must have been on another
planet or buried in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is perfectly understandable that his members do not
much want to go door to door threatening people with jail for the
crime of selling half a pound of jelly beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for the offices of various local authorities to get
involved in all that,'' Charlesworth said. ``But we've gone through
a process of education, and the next step of issuing warning
notices, and there comes a stage where you've got to say, OK, if
you're flouting the law, then you need to comply.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does this leave Fletcher and his scales? He was willing to
go metric, Fletcher said _ he had even bought a new set of scales,
for $450 _ until the local government so insulted him that he
changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   His customers like the old way too. ``If people want to sell in
pounds and ounces, why shouldn't they?'' said Chris Hartley, 32,
pointing out that Americans do not much want to use the metric
system either, no matter what their politicians say. ``It's not as
if it's an obscure system of weighing things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
