<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, July 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An area of rain will brush southeastern New England as low
pressure moves south of Cape Cod. In the wake of the low, mostly
cloudy and cool conditions will linger over much of the Middle
Atlantic states. Farther north, sunshine and clouds will be mixed.
Despite the sun, afternoon temperatures will be several degrees
below average.
</P>
<P>
   Very hot and humid weather will linger over the South. A few
strong thunderstorms will erupt from the eastern Carolinas to the
eastern Gulf Coast, however most of the region will be dry with
ample sun.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of clouds and thundershowers will form in the central
Plains where sultry air is forced to rise over cooler air to the
north. Large hail and strong wind gusts will attend some storms in
Kansas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TWO-FACED JULY
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the temperature touched 100 degrees in Tuscaloosa,
Ala., for the 14th consecutive day as searing heat persists in the
South. Meanwhile, Green Bay, Wis., in the midst of a chilly month
across the Great Lakes and Northeast, set a record for its coolest
July afternoon as the mercury struggled to reach 58 degrees.
Mid-summer temperature trends are often influenced by the
longer-term rainfall patterns that precede them. Damp soil
conditions in the upper Middle West have helped to limit day
temperatures. In the South, the dry ground from recent drought has
been promoting additional heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
