<HEADLINE>
AS THE WAIT LENGTHENS, JERUSALEM MULLS THE POSSIBILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a city heavy with possibility and buzzing with
apprehension, Israelis and Palestinians waited for word from Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   After eight days of talks, both sides were left to wonder if an
historic agreement was imminent, or if the two sides would
ultimately fail to bridge their differences, particularly on the
status of Jerusalem, which both sides claim as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout a long day of waiting, analysts and insiders on
both sides seemed to believe that even if the summit were to fall
short of producing a final agreement, or even a framework for one,
there had nevertheless been an important shift in the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis have refused to compromise on its position that
Jerusalem is the ``eternal and indivisible capital'' of the Jewish
state. Reports here said Israeli leaders were willing to grant
Palestinian president Yasser Arafat administrative control over
East Jerusalem, but not full sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have insisted that under the UN Security
Council resolution 242, East Jerusalem and the West Bank, which
were captured by Israel from Jordan during the 1967 Six Day War,
must be turned over to them. They maintain that they would accept
nothing short of full Israeli withdrawal and full Palestinian
sovereignty over the area.
</P>
<P>
   Both Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak know they face
stiff political opposition at home if they abandon these positions,
analysts said, making it quite possible the talks would end without
any resolution of the Jerusalem question despite President
Clinton's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But even if that happens, said Menachem Klein, a senior
researcher for the Jerusalem Institute for Israel Studies and part
of a team that helped brief the negotiators who accompanied Barak
at the talks, ``What happened over these days is very important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak raised the issue of Jerusalem and the sky did not fall
down. That should not be forgotten,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man on the street is talking about details'' of how to
resolve the future of Jerusalem, said Mahdi Abdul-Hadi, director of
the Palestinian Academic Society of the Study of International
Affairs. ``That never happened before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The street _ Palestinian and Israeli _ is being prepared for
the possible'' on an issue that until now had been impossible even
to discuss, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both parties put their cards on the table,'' said Abdul-Hadi.
``Everything is in the open.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the talks, Barak kept his positions on Jerusalem a
tightly held secret even as his government virtually collapsed on
the night of his departure for Camp David with the resignation of
right wing and religious parties in his coalition. saying they
opposed to concessions he might make.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said Barak, a former general known for isolating
information and making decisions without building consensus, ``did
not even allow his ministers to prepare for the possibility on
Jerusalem because he feared there could be a leak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept it as a secret until the last minute, and he wanted
that the details only be discussed in a summit,'' said Klein.
``This was a groundbreaking move he made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
