<HEADER>
A7011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-REC-ROOM-COX     07-19 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REC-ROOM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All work, no play? Rec rooms cure workday blues
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _If Dan Dykstra plans on climbing the ladder at his
company, he'll need to brush up on his office skills.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-year-old mechanical engineer at Radiant Systems, a
technology company, Dykstra isn't sweating about his career: He's
already turned down job offers at bigger, better-known firms,
including Ford Motors.
</P>
<P>
   But Dykstra's pingpong game? That's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   His lackluster serve and choppy backhand have kept him from
ascending the pecking order known as ``the ladder,'' which ranks
the skill level of employees competing in intraoffice tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   So this week, smack-dab in the middle of a workday, Dykstra and
two co-workers spent 15 minutes whacking the ball across the table
in Radiant's downstairs rec room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may look like it, but we're not lollygagging,'' Dykstra
said. ``Sometimes you just have to come down here and forget what
you're doing at your desk. If you're working too hard it becomes
monotonous and you lose interest. Taking a break keeps you fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   And what a break room this is. Besides housing a pingpong table,
it has a tournament-quality dartboard, a '50s-style cafeteria, with
vinyl LPs hanging on the walls and a sprawling fitness center with
a bank of color TVs, that stays open 24 hours a day. And, hidden
behind a sliding panel where Dykstra and his buddies were playing,
is an open space for Radiant's in-house rock band to practice and
perform for employees.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, the rock band.
</P>
<P>
   Rec rooms like this are becoming the rage among Internet and
other high-tech firms scrambling to attract young employees for
whom work and play aren't separate worlds. Many of these techies
have grown up with computers, toggling between work and play with
the click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms have another purpose as well: Companies are trying to
gain a competitive edge by creating office homes _ places where
employees are encouraged to spend more time with their co-workers,
socializing but also conducting business.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Dave-and-Buster-ization of the workplace. Like
Radiant, companies are investing in arcade games, Foosball tables,
interactive computer games, gas grills, wet bars, Frisbees and
other distractions aimed at keeping their employees entertained _
and productive.
</P>
<P>
   During a post-lunch workout, Radiant executive Carlyle Taylor
was polishing off a set of leg presses in the company's weight
room. ``You never know what's going to drive the next creative
business idea,'' he said. ``Sometimes you hear people in here
talking about business while they're lifting free weights. That's
what we want to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   At eTour.com, a personal Web-search service in downtown Atlanta,
employees are still unpacking boxes after moving into their new
offices in Peachtree Center.
</P>
<P>
   Even before they arrived, company executives opened the brightly
colored rec room with a tabletop shuffleboard, two pool tables,
arcade-style games, a tropical aquarium and models of vintage prop
planes hanging from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to our Romper Room,'' said Clare Gordon, a company
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Geltzer, an eTour employee, considers rec rooms a welcome
departure from company-sponsored picnics and softball games
traditionally used to create a sense of camaraderie and loyalty
among employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man in the gray-flannel suit, that's just not who we
are,'' said Geltzer, 29, who works in marketing. ``In this
industry, people are more communal. You can talk about a project
just as much over a Foosball table as you can over a conference
table.''
</P>
<P>
   Geltzer's co-worker Mallory Roth said she got burned out working
in traditional workplaces, ``the world of pantyhose and business
suits'' where employees are judged by how much time they spend in
their cubicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so unhappy working in stuffy environments, I could never
go back,'' said Roth, 26. ``To be more effective at your job, you
need to play at your job. People expect that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Howe, chief marketing officer at eTour, said in addition to
the rec room, he has earmarked $1,000 of his department's monthly
budget to increase what he called ``the fun and craziness
quotient.'' The marketing staff will decide how to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   Not all high-tech companies in metro Atlanta are joining the
rec-room boom.
</P>
<P>
   At Hallman Interactive Productions, a Internet-based marketing
and Web-site design firm in Poncey-Highland, the company founder
and CEO isn't a sockless, 30-something Gen-Xer who grew up playing
Quake.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Hallman is 56, graying and wears bifocals. He worries that
some tech companies are going overboard with extravagant
recreational facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no goal to hire a physical-fitness instructor,''
Hallman said. ``As soon as the Internet economy is not hot anymore,
those kinds of perks are going to be the first things to go, and
people will be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Hallman is an all-work-and-no-play kind of
boss. He realizes to attract the workers he wants, he's got to keep
things loose.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting atop a digital scanner is a pump-action Nerf gun. A
closer look reveals that there's at least one toy weapon on
everyone's desk. Some Hallman employees have as many as three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill bought these for us,'' said Rob Mathea, a Web designer
</P>
<P>
   A yellow dart with a sucker attached whizzed past Mathea and
landed on a wall near a co-worker's head. Retaliation was
immediate, and suddenly the narrow office was filled with a volley
of foam projectiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our business it's more important to make sure having fun is
part of our personality and culture,'' said Hallman. ``You don't
need rec room to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
