<P>
   COLOMBIA-AID-$ADV23 _ BOGOTA, Colombia _ The U.S. Congress has
passed a $1.3 billion aid package for Colombia, but many wonder if
the money will be too
</P>
<P>
   little too late to save a country beset by violence, civil war
and a powerful leftist guerrilla army. Some critics fear the U.S.
is stepping into a Vietnam-style quagmire by sending military
advisors and sleek new helicopters to help battle Colombia's drug
lords, who along with Marxist guerrillas control vast areas in the
countryside. Meanwhile, Colombian President Andres Pastrana is
battling plummeting public support, a deep recession, icy relations
with the national congress, corruption charges and stalled peace
talks. (Williams, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With COLOMBIA-FARC-$ADV23 _ SAN VICENTE, Colombia _ Fueled by
tribute from coca-growers and drug lords, the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia or FARC has become one of the most potent
leftist insurgencies in Latin American history. Ceded a
Switzerland-sized chunk of territory last year by Pastrana, the
FARC shows no signs of compromising in peace talks as they
consolidate their control. Profile of the group, its leaders,
origins and history, set in San
</P>
<P>
   Vicente, the capital of the rebel-held territory. WITH PHOTOS.
With map of map of Colombia and areas controlled by rebels and
coca-growing regions; chart of U.S. aid to Colombia over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move in advance by noon Wed., July 19, on the NYT
Wire.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DIVORCE-$ADV23 _ BEIJING _ The southern province of
Guangdong, one of China's most prosperous, has seen a resurgence of
a feudal practice the Communists eliminated 50 years ago:
concubines. Affairs and divorces have been on the upswing for years
in China, but men in Guangdong have taken marital
</P>
<P>
   infidelity to a new level _ they are known to take a mistress ?
or even two or three _ set tlem has become so serious, the province
issued anew legal directive that
</P>
<P>
   makes it easier for wives to get a share of what their husband
bought for the other woman. (Chao, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BRUNSWICK _ BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ When Kendra McCrae stormed into the
Brunswick city manager's office recently and demanded an audience,
it was another sign of the continuing unrest in the coastal city
that has spawned violence, marches and calls for change. McCrae, a
28-year-old secretary, was upset over mistreatment she says she and
other blacks received at the hands of police during a July 4th
altercation. That holiday weekend confrontation, which eventually
turned violent, led to a subsequent protest march on Monday (July
17) with others planned. It has also revealed a wider set of
grievances. A loose coalition of residents and ministers is now
calling for sensitivity training for police, a community-wide forum
to discuss racial differences and better economic opportunities for
the city's black population. We examine the continuing evolution of
a city in transition. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BARTON-VICTIMS _ The lives that were changed by Mark Barton's
rampage; the woman who was robbed of her sight by Barton; the widow
who wakes up each day alone; the day traders who can't help but
shudder when they walk into their Buckhead office ... For this
story the reporters initially assigned to keep in touch with the
survivors and the families of the dead will go back and chronicle
how they have coped in the year since the shooting. (Judd, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GROWING PAINS FOR THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Eds: The following two stories, about growing pains for the
Internet in a period of rapid worldwide growth, are suitable for
twinning or use as a series.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-HARDWARE _ WASHINGTON _ Even as the Internet is hailed
for expanding the horizons of millions of users and energizing the
world economy, there's concern it could become the victim of its
own success. Rapid growth of sites and users poses the very real
nightmare that this massive online structure,
</P>
<P>
   representing a $650 billion investment, could come crashing down
in gigantic cyber-traffic jams. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HARDWARE-DATA _ For a graphic, growth in number of computers
attached to the Internet. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Moved Monday on NYT wire in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, Business, Technology.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SOFTWARE _ WASHINGTON _ WWW.any-site.com. To American
ears, this familiar pattern identifies a World Wide Web site on the
Internet. The system seems simple and settled, but a global battle
is being waged this summer over how addresses will be assigned to
keep pace with rapid Internet growth. The
</P>
<P>
   stakes are enormous. If plans to establish private control over
the Internet's address system founders on technical details and
political disputes, the global
</P>
<P>
   expansion of the online community could become gridlocked. But
if it succeeds, Americans will have to get used to having the
Internet governed by an international body that may be located in
Switzerland (Geewax, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TAKEN _ Pity the late-arriving entrepreneur who decides
to take his business on line. Suppose a fisherman creates a fly
that catches trout like magic. He decides to create a Web site to
market it. But he'll find the waters are nearly fished out.
</P>
<P>
   With an Atlanta-produced 2-column cartoon due at 4:30 p.m. EDT
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With INTERNET-DOMAINS _ WASHINGTON _ There's pressure on the new
Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers to expand the
number of ``top level''
</P>
<P>
   Internet domains. (Geewax, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   With INTERNET-ICANN _ ICANN at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   With logo.
