<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7018 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-TASTE-OFHAWAII-TEX     07-19 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-OFHAWAII-TEX </SLUG>
 
EDS: Has a sidebar, TASTE-OFHAWAII-RECIPES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAHAINA, Maui _ In the dimly lit dining room of Roy's Kahana
Grill, one of a dozen stylish restaurants overseen by star Hawaii
chef Roy Yamaguchi, we are sitting down to dinner: light, crisp
spring rolls served with black bean sauce and hot-sweet mustard; a
tower of skewered tiger shrimp, fried in coconut batter and
perfectly balanced over a pool of cocktail sauce spiked with hot
Thai chiles.
</P>
<P>
   Next, sea bass crusted with macadamia nuts; seared sea scallops
sided with wasabi mashed potatoes and a champagne mango salsa; a
blackened ahi (yellow-fin tuna) and a lemon grass-crusted shutome
(swordfish) seared but still nearly raw at the center, as tender
and silky as the finest sashimi. Finally, cake glazed with an icing
of deep Hawaiian chocolate, and coffee brewed with rich Kona beans,
grown on the Big Island.
</P>
<P>
   If you come to Hawaii looking for faux-Polynesian fare _ pu-pu
platters, Blue Hawaiians and sweet-'n'-sour pork with pineapple
chunks, served in garish rooms lit by tiki torches _ you're in the
wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a decade after the original dozen chefs created the
concept of Hawaiian Regional Cuisine, the dining scene on the
islands has been altered for good. From the finest restaurants to
tourist-oriented spots to fast-food joints, more chefs are
following the mantra of the original regional-cuisine gurus:
Fresher ingredients. More locally grown produce and meat. More
locally procured or farmed fish and seafood. And a bold fusion of
the cuisines long found on the islands: Japanese, Chinese, Thai and
Filipino, with European flavors and traditional Hawaiian fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened here is really an offshoot of what happened in
California and across America, with the whole notion of eating
fresher foods and taking regional flavors and making them more
upscale,'' says Joan Clark, food editor of the daily ``Honolulu
Advertiser.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's best Hawaiian food features ``the local flavors and
dishes that have been upscaled and refined by chefs who have been
trained, usually elsewhere, in American and French techniques,''
Clark says. ``They've taken these mostly Asian flavors and come up
with some really great food.''
</P>
<P>
   That might mean the ahi katsu _ tuna sushi rolled in Japanese
bread crumbs, flash-deep-fried so it remains rare, and served with
a butter-based sauce _ served by Russell Siu at his trendy 3660 on
the Rise on Oahu.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the quesadillas stuffed with kalua pork, or traditional
Hawaiian roast pig, at Alan Wong's eponymous restaurant in
Honolulu, named the most popular on the island in the 2000 edition
of the ``Zagat Survey.''
</P>
<P>
   Or it might be something as simple as a soft taco stuffed with
fresh fish marinated in pineapple, lime juice and local spices, one
of the bestsellers at the Maui Taco fast-food chain, with locations
all over Hawaii and now on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Hawaii, you see all these different cultures,
and along with their culture, they brought their food. As chefs,
we're like kids in a candy shop,'' says chef Sam Choy, a native
Hawaiian who oversees an empire of a dozen restaurants, several
cookbooks and an eponymous line of sauces, salad dressings,
marinades and other prepared foods set to debut in Price Club
stores nationwide this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hawaiian food has finally come of age, and what's happened is
that we've taken the local cuisine and taken it out of the
closet.''
</P>
<P>
   The food of Hawaii has always been an interesting polyglot,
shaped by the large immigrant populations from China, Japan,
Thailand, the Philippines, Korea and Portugal, among others. Most
Hawaiians, no matter their ethnic background, grew up eating dishes
found nowhere else, says Clark, a native of Hawaii whose booklet,
``Local Food: What to Eat in Hawai'i'' describes many of those
dishes and ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   This old-school Hawaiian cuisine includes such dishes as
``saimin,'' a Japanese-style broth with Chinese egg noodles, lunch
meat and green onions; ``lomi lomi salmon,'' a salad of raw salted
salmon, tomatoes and sweet onions; ``loco moco,'' a breakfast dish
of white rice topped with brown gravy, hamburger patty and a
sunny-side-up egg; and ``poke,'' morsels of raw fish marinated in
salt, seaweed and ground candlenuts.
</P>
<P>
   Island specialties are widely available in local restaurants.
Even McDonald's serves a Hawaiian version of its Egg McMuffin,
using linguisa, a garlicky Portuguese sausage, instead of Canadian
bacon. But for years, finer restaurants wouldn't think of serving
anything like these dishes.
</P>
<P>
   When John Heckathorn, restaurant critic of ``Honolulu''
magazine, moved to the islands 25 years ago, he found the ``best''
restaurants serving the same kind of heavy, Continental/American
food served on the mainland: steak Diane, chicken Cordon Bleu,
smoked salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the feeling that they had to give the tourists the
kind of food they were used to, on the grounds that local food
didn't have high enough status for them,'' Heckathorn says. ``But
then, 25 years ago, American tastes were not as adventurous as they
are now. Honestly, you couldn't put raw fish in front of people
from the mainland. They just wouldn't eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the problem was the difficulty in getting fresh
ingredients, says Beverly Gannon, a former Dallas resident who
opened her Haliimaile General Store on Maui in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetables and fruits shipped from the mainland were often three
to four weeks old; fresh fish was shipped abroad while Hawaiians
had to make do with frozen products; and local farmers seemed to
send most of their crops to the mainland. So in 1991, Gannon and 11
other Hawaiian chefs formed the Hawaiian Regional Cuisine Council,
which began making deals with local farmers to grow _ and sell to
them _ baby lettuces, eggplants, sweet potatoes and other produce.
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, 80 percent of our produce was imported. Today,
80 percent is produced here,'' Wong says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've really created an awareness of fresher foods, on an
island where a lot of us grew up eating a lot of canned foods and
frozen foods because everything had to be shipped in,'' Clark says.
``Where I grew up eating frozen mahi-mahi, now I'm eating fresh
mahi-mahi, and there's a big difference in flavor and texture.''
</P>
<P>
   Given access to better ingredients, chefs who already understood
local food _ like Yamaguchi and Wong _ were able to create foodie
versions of dishes islanders knew and loved, or tweak other
cuisines with a Hawaiian flavor.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one of Gannon's signature dishes is a towering
sashimi napoleon, featuring smoked salmon, sashimi and ahi tartare,
layered with crisp wontons; Gannon calls it a twist on a fish taco.
</P>
<P>
   Wong's restaurants serve such island-inspired specialties as
``poki-pines'' _ crispy ahi poke balls, served on avocado with
wasabi sauce, and a Hawaiian-style Caesar salad with warm kalua
pig, poi vinaigrette and lomi tomato.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Wong's food, like many of the other chefs' fare, defies
categorization. Much Hawaiian cuisine has a strong Asian flavor, in
ingredients and presentation. But Gannon, whose book of Haliimaile
General Store recipes will be published by Ten Speed Press this
fall, sees Hawaiian cuisine shifting again, to a more global
sphere, with more Italian and American and Mexican-style
restaurants coming in vogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not losing the (Hawaiian) influence, it's just backing
off a little,'' she says. ``When you come to Hawaii, you really do
have food options now.''
</P>
<P>
   And far better ones than in the days of Steak Diane and the
pu-pu platter.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
