   Given access to better ingredients, chefs who already understood
local food _ like Yamaguchi and Wong _ were able to create foodie
versions of dishes islanders knew and loved, or tweak other
cuisines with a Hawaiian flavor.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one of Gannon's signature dishes is a towering
sashimi napoleon, featuring smoked salmon, sashimi and ahi tartare,
layered with crisp wontons; Gannon calls it a twist on a fish taco.
</P>
<P>
   Wong's restaurants serve such island-inspired specialties as
``poki-pines'' _ crispy ahi poke balls, served on avocado with
wasabi sauce, and a Hawaiian-style Caesar salad with warm kalua
pig, poi vinaigrette and lomi tomato.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Wong's food, like many of the other chefs' fare, defies
categorization. Much Hawaiian cuisine has a strong Asian flavor, in
ingredients and presentation. But Gannon, whose book of Haliimaile
General Store recipes will be published by Ten Speed Press this
fall, sees Hawaiian cuisine shifting again, to a more global
sphere, with more Italian and American and Mexican-style
restaurants coming in vogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not losing the (Hawaiian) influence, it's just backing
off a little,'' she says. ``When you come to Hawaii, you really do
have food options now.''
</P>
<P>
   And far better ones than in the days of Steak Diane and the
pu-pu platter.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
