<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0720-C     07-19 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON WORKING TO SALVAGE MIDEAST SUMMIT TALKS ON BRINK OF
COLLAPSE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Struggling to rescue marathon Mideast peace
talks from the threat of collapse, President Clinton led Israeli
and Palestinian leaders Wednesday through a tumultuous day of
brinkmanship and heated negotiations that ground into the night.
</P>
<P>
   After nine days of talks at nearby Camp David, though, Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
spent much of the day threatening to walk out on the summit, while
Clinton shuttled between them and urged them to stay.
</P>
<P>
   With the two sides at loggerheads over the thorny territorial
and security disputes that divide them _ and, in particular, vexing
questions about the future of Jerusalem _ Clinton set a Thursday
morning deadline for Barak and Arafat to break their impasse and
move toward a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   At day's end, though, White House spokesman Joseph Lockhart
conceded that the prospects for a peace accord hung very much in
the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've obviously reached a pivotal moment in these talks, and I
can't predict how they'll come out,'' a grim Lockhart told
reporters gathered in this town of 4,400, five miles from the
secluded presidential retreat at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is working very hard to see if there's some way we
can get from where we are now to an agreement,'' Lockhart insisted.
``The problem is the structure and the substance of that
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   As the three leaders and their negotiating teams met into the
night, Air Force One was standing by at Andrews Air Force Base
outside Washington to take Clinton early Thursday to Okinawa,
Japan, where he plans to attend a weekend summit of leaders from
the Group of Eight democratic powers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had earlier scratched a Tokyo leg of the trip, delaying
his departure by 24 hours, but Lockhart said there was a limit to
how long the president could fruitfully remain at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone understands we don't have an unlimited
time-clock here,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking outside support, Clinton telephoned at least four
Mideast leaders from the Camp David retreat where the summit is
being held, asking them over secure lines to add the weight of
their influence to his own efforts to broker peace between Arafat
and Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart would not name the leaders Clinton called, nor would he
say whether those leaders followed up with calls of their own to
Arafat or Barak.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan's state news agency Petra said Clinton telephoned
Jordan's King Abdullah on Wednesday and briefed him on the Camp
David talks. Petra quoted the king as thanking Clinton and his
administration for their efforts to push the Middle East peace
process forward and expressed hope the summit would yield the
results they were seeking.
</P>
<P>
   The Reuters new agency also quoted Egyptian presidency sources
that Clinton called Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Wednesday to
discuss progress at summit. But the sources said that Clinton did
not ask Mubarak for his help in securing an agreement at the Camp
David talks during their telephone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   As tensions ran high throughout the day, both Barak and Arafat
delivered letters to Clinton. Lockhart would not comment on their
contents, but Israeli and Palestinian media widely reported that
each side had threatened to quit the talks, blaming the other's
intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinians arrived at Camp David lacking a true
commitment, and are not ready to have a substantive discussion
about a lasting peace and to make historic decisions,'' Israel
radio quoted a Hebrew translation of the letter as saying. ``Unless
there are last-minute changes, the Palestinians will have to
envision the tragic consequences of an opportunity they missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Abdel Rahman, who heads the Palestine Liberation
Organization's office in Washington, told the Associated Press the
Palestinians went to Camp David to achieve a just and lasting peace
that the Israeli and Palestinian people could live with for
generations.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Associated Press, Rahman emphasized
that Palestinian control over East Jerusalem was a bottom-line
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no agreement without total Palestinian
sovereignty over East Jerusalem,'' Rahman told the AP. ``This is a
basic condition for achieving peace.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
