<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-MARKEY-RESIDENCY-BOS &LR;      07-19 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKEY-RESIDENCY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKEY FACES RESIDENCY DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN JOHNSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The death of Representative Edward J. Markey's
father last week was a personal loss for his family, but it also
puts the Massachusetts Democrat in a ticklish political position.
</P>
<P>
   Markey lives with his wife, Dr. Susan J. Blumenthal, in an
$800,000 house in Chevy Chase, Md., but for years he has claimed
his political residency in his childhood bedroom at his parent's
home in Malden.
</P>
<P>
   Markey's mother, Christina, died in 1998, and with the death of
his 89-year-old father, John, last Thursday, the disposition of
their house will fall to Markey; his brother John, who lives in
Belmont, Mass.; his brother Richard, a resident of Charlestown,
Mass.; and his aunt, Marguerite Markey of Stoneham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed intends to continue to maintain his residence at 7 Townsend
St.,'' Markey's spokesman, David Moulton, said Wednesday without
elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the house were sold, there is no law that requires
Markey to be a resident in his district, but the issue has been a
nettlesome one for Markey in the past. His failure to own a house
in the 7th Congressional District over his 24 years in Congress
flared up during his 1994 reelection campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are about being a voice for the people we hope to
represent, not a Washington insider that's removed and has no
contact or connection with the district,'' said then-challenger
Brad Bailey, who lost his campaign but later served an appointment
as Middlesex County sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Residency is a prominent issue this year in the US Senate race
between Hillary Rodham Clinton, an Illinois native and longtime
Arkansas resident, and Representative Rick Lazio, a Republican who
was raised on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said recently: ``For me, New York isn't just a mailing
address; it's my home.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts election law does not require members of Congress
to live in their districts, only that they be an ``inhabitant'' of
the state when elected. The Constitution says only that candidates
live in the state where an election is held.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, members of Congress keep an apartment or share living
quarters in Washington while maintaining a primary residence in the
area they represent. They are paid $141,300 per year, a sum they
often justify because of the expense of keeping two homes.
</P>
<P>
   All other members of the Massachusetts congressional delegation
_ including Senators Edward M. Kennedy and John F. Kerry _ own
property in Massachusetts except for Representative Barney Frank.
The Massachusetts Democrat, who had been living with his widowed
sister the past five years, began renting his own apartment in
Newton, Mass. in May.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Jim McGovern, who serves the Worcester area in
Congress, bought a house there two years ago. He also has a home on
Capitol Hill with his wife, Lisa, an employee of the federal
General Services Administration, and their 2-year-old son, Patrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's up in Worcester, that's where they stay,'' said
McGovern spokesman Michael Mershon, referring to the family's house
on Burncoat Street. ``When Congress is in session, they live
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Watanabe, a political science professor at the University
of Massachusetts at Boston, said any effect of such residency
criticism depends on the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think on these kind of issues, one can't talk about them in
the abstract. They are more of a problem for some candidates and
not for others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be an issue for a candidate seeking an open seat or a
candidate who is fighting against a seat held by an incumbent, but
if you are an incumbent who has held the seat for a long time, it's
not a problem,'' Watanabe added. ``In Markey's case, it's an
irritant for some, but it's not enough to change the outcome of an
election.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Markey is unopposed for reelection this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
