<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7027 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-BRITISH-DIRECTOR     07-19 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BRITISH-DIRECTORS-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GENERATION OF REALISTS SCRAPS THE KITCHEN SINK 
</HEADLINE>
   By GRAHAM FULLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I once asked John Schlesinger if he would ever return to
making the kind of small, authentic English films, like ``A Kind of
Loving'' and ``Billy Liar,'' that made his name in the early '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? We've done all that,'' he growled, speaking for himself
and his fellow so-called kitchen sink realists, and we returned to
talking about what was then Schlesinger's latest film, the slick
American espionage thriller ``The Falcon and the Snowman.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. Artists don't grow if they retrace their steps. The
kitchen sink, too, is no longer a handy symbol for the social
inequities and domestic pressures of British life. Britain has
changed irrevocably in the 40 years since Schlesinger, Lindsay
Anderson, Jack Clayton, Karel Reisz and Tony Richardson, inspired
by the literary example of the Angry Young Men and offended by the
bourgeois values of the staid national cinema, made a brief series
of socially aware films that depicted regional working-class life
in all its grim (and occasionally funny) verisimilitude.
</P>
<P>
   The welfare state has metamorphosed, by way of Margaret
Thatcher's privatization imperatives, into Tony Blair's
post-industrial Cool Britannia. Mobile-phone realism, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   The rhythms of British life, however, do not alter as quickly as
the political landscape, and in the last few years several talented
directors have emerged with pain-infused realist dramas that get to
the heart of working- and middle-class Britain. They include Gary
Oldman's ``Nil by Mouth,'' Tim Roth's ``War Zone,'' Carine Adler's
``Under the Skin'' and two that will open here this fall, Lynne
Ramsay's ``Ratcatcher'' and Shane Meadows' ``Room for Romeo
Brass.'' Another, ``Wonderland,'' directed by Michael Winterbottom,
opens on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   These directors do not belong to any manifesto-issuing group
like the Danish Dogma 95 collective with its back-to-basics agenda,
or, for that matter, the Free Cinema documentarists of the '50s,
whose work led to the kitchen sink movement. Unlike that tireless
agitator Ken Loach, they are driven by polemical concerns only in
passing. Although Winterbottom and Meadows, for example, have shown
they are not limited to particular themes, all the films just
mentioned are linked by a realist or quasi-realist style and a
preoccupation with the psychological legacies of parental abuse or
absence, or, as in the case of ``Wonderland,'' parental warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Loach's work has always rooted the political in the personal,
and it is impossible to ignore the influence of domestic dramas
like his ``Ladybird, Ladybird'' on ``Nil by Mouth'' and ``The War
Zone'' (particularly since the actor Ray Winstone portrayed brutal
father figures in all three). There are traces of ``Ladybird,
Ladybird'' and earlier Loach films like ``Up the Junction'' and
``Family Life'' in ``Wonderland'' and ``Under the Skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether directly or through osmosis, Roth and Oldman are
indebted to Mike Leigh and especially Alan Clarke, directors they
both worked for as actors. After many years as an eloquent
director-for-hire in British television, Clarke capped his career
with a series of pulsating dramas, including ``Scum'' (starring
Winstone and banned by the BBC, which had financed it), ``Made in
Britain'' (with Roth) and ``The Firm'' (with Oldman), that offered
a caustic critique of the British social order. Since Clarke's
death in 1990, his films have grown in critical stature, and he
stands alongside Loach and Leigh as one of the seminal figures of
British social realism.
</P>
<P>
   Winterbottom's ``Wonderland'' unfolds over a November weekend in
contemporary London, which it depicts as a locus of alienation,
loneliness and despair. Laurence Coriat, the film's London-based
writer, was a psychology student in her native France and,
accordingly, her script lent itself to psychological rather than
social realism. It focuses on three sisters and their brother, and
their codependent parents (Kika Markham and Jack Shepherd), whose
wretchedly antagonistic relationship implicitly indicates why their
son is estranged and not one of their daughters seems capable of
forging a relationship based on trust.
</P>
<P>
   Of the sisters, the shy cafe waitress Nadia (Gina McKee, who
played a similar role in Leigh's ``Naked'') dates men from the
personal ads and ends up being seduced and rejected by one of them;
the willfully promiscuous Debbie (Shirley Henderson), a
hairdresser, parks her son on her irresponsible ex-husband, who
promptly loses him; and the pregnant teacher Molly (Molly Parker)
cold-shoulders her live-in boyfriend for quitting his job, causing
him to walk out. Their younger brother, Darren (Enzo Cilenti),
agonizes over whether to call home as he passes through the city
with his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Thematically, Winterbottom's films, which also include ``Jude''
and ``Welcome to Sarajevo,'' deal with people who are trapped in
some kind of prison, whether psychological or physical;
stylistically, they have little in common. In ``Wonderland,'' he
adopted a casually observational approach, filming the quotidian
routines and mishaps of his characters with a hand-held camera as
they struggle through the weekend, making a hash of their attempts
to communicate with each other. Winterbottom was loath to
acknowledge specific realist influences on ``Wonderland'' when we
spoke in January at the Sundance Film Festival, where the movie had
its American premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't consciously trying to emulate '60s kitchen sink
realism,'' he said. ``The fact that `Wonderland's' characters
happen to be living mainly in council estates in South London and
struggling economically isn't the heart of the film. I was more
interested in exploring the emotional connections between people in
a family who rarely meet, and in capturing the noise and excitement
of London and the exhaustion of trying to keep your head above
water in a place where you've got seven million people around you
whose lives you don't know. You sit next to them on the tube, live
next door to them in a block of flats and walk past them on the
street, but you never expect to have any connection with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Superficially, ``Wonderland'' resembles Loach's films _ a
``Riff-Raff,'' say, or ``Raining Stones'' _ but a closer
examination reveals that its style is heightened above and beyond
Loachian documentary realism. Like ``Nil by Mouth'' and ``Under the
Skin,'' ``Wonderland'' is carried along by a fly-on-the-wall look,
charged with an unsettling lyricism. Scenes of Debbie's son and his
dad leaving a soccer match, and in Soho, where Nadia and Molly's
boyfriend each gloomily wander, render the metropolis as a
threatening human jungle. It is not entirely faceless: Winterbottom
had Sean Bobbitt, his cinematographer, pick out lonely individuals
in the crowd, making us wonder about their stories. But he did
something Loach would never do: using time-lapse photography, he
turned Soho's hordes into an inhuman tumult moving at warp speed,
overlaid by an alternately plaintive and mournful Michael Nyman
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, a film's realistic if it somehow expresses something
that's truthful,'' Winterbottom said. ``But I don't think there's
an objective way of saying one film is truthful and another isn't.
`Wonderland' is a naturalistic film in most respects. One thing I
wanted to do stylistically was have moments in it where we weren't
just observing details but somehow trying to evoke a sense of the
characters' inner lives, their aspirations and dreams. That's why I
used the time-lapse photography and Michael Nyman's score.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Ramsay's ``Ratcatcher'' is set in and around a decrepit
housing project and a polluted nearby canal in Glasgow in the '70s;
a national refuse workers' strike (also seen in the recent Sex
Pistols documentary ``The Filth and the Fury'') has led to an
infestation of rats in the neighborhood. In the film's first few
minutes, a boy drowns in the canal. The story then follows
12-year-old James (William Eadie), who shoved the boy into the
water. James befriends a hapless teen-ager, Margaret Anne (Leanne
Mullen), who is picked on by a local gang, then he feels betrayed
when he sees her having sex with her persecutors. James' father is
beaten up and takes it out on his wife. James himself jumps into
the canal.
</P>
<P>
   From such human squalor, Ramsay, who grew up in a similar
Glasgow environment, has fashioned a movie that is equal parts
realism and impressionism. Unlike Winterbottom, she sought out and
framed details _ the scab on Margaret Anne's knee, her spectacles
at the bottom of the canal, James protectively pulling his mother's
ripped nylon stocking over her bare toe _ that are stark in their
realness but more than three-dimensional. ``I tried to think of the
emotional core of every shot,'' Ramsay said recently. ``I wanted to
get details that trigger a memory. A lot of people like the scene
in which James looks at Margaret Anne's scab because it's quite
sensual and reminds them of when they constantly had scabs on their
knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Ratcatcher'' often looks and feels like real life,
any notion that it is a ``realistic'' film is confused by the fact
that it appears to operate on two intersecting planes of reality,
the conscious and the unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   When James follows his sister out of town on a bus, he drifts
off to a new housing estate situated among wide fields that might
have been photographed in Nebraska: the sequence has the quality of
a reverie. Then later, in a Magritte-style scene, James' family
carries its furniture through the fields to the estate to claim
their little slice of heaven _ but there's a sense that this is
only a visualization of James' futile wish for a life that isn't
brutish and disease-ridden.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the film, council inspectors visit James' family's
untidy flat and deny them a new home _ a typically Loachian
intimation of how the working class is habitually betrayed by the
authorities who are supposed to help them. The runtish James is
also reminiscent of the unloved schoolboy who finds solace in the
company of a kestrel in Loach's ``Kes.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Loach, Ramsay primarily works with nonprofessional actors.
Stylistically, however, the British filmmakers who most affected
her were Bill Douglas (``My Childhood,'' ``My Ain Folk''), Clarke
and Nicolas Roeg, while she also credits the influence of the
American avant-garde director Maya Deren and such European
heavyweights as Fellini, Bergman, Fassbinder and Truffaut.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think `Ratcatcher' is part of the tradition of British
social realism because of the working-class world in which it's
set,'' she said. ``If it offers an alternative view of British
culture compared with most of the films that are made these days,
then, yeah, it is connected to that kitchen sink tradition, but I
never sat down and said, `I'm going to make a social realist film.'
When I make my films, I go off on a different planet, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay, who previously directed highly regarded shorts (``Small
Deaths'' and ``Gasman''), added that she did not wish to be thought
of as a Scottish filmmaker. The regionalist spirit of the '60s
kitchen sink films, however, survives in the work of Shane Meadows,
whose grass-roots cinema is based in and around the Midlands _ not
that his stories about the vicissitudes of emotionally or
economically disenfranchised teen-agers and young adults aren't
universally applicable. Meadows' films, both jaunty and poignant,
share with Mike Leigh's a fascination for quirks of personality.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows was about to start work on a Welsh western when a
conversation with his writing partner Paul Fraser steered them
toward an autobiographical story about a temporary break in their
long friendship during adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Room for Romeo Brass'' depicts a crisis in the life of
pugnacious 12-year-old Romeo (Andrew Shim). He not only deserts his
next-door-neighbor, Knocks (Ben Marshall), when the latter is
hospitalized but, angered by his itinerant father's decision to
return home, takes up with the 30-ish misfit, Morel (Paddy
Considine), who has been courting his sister.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows' first feature, the black-and-white ``TwentyFourSeven''
(1997), was shot in an uneasy blend of realist and impressionist
styles, but ``Romeo Brass'' returns him to the vibrant naturalism
of his short films, ``Small Time'' and ``Where's the Money
Ronnie?,'' which were shot on video. Of all the films by new
British directors about real-life situations, Meadows' have the
strongest tang of verisimilitude.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Winterbottom and Ramsay, Meadows candidly admits he was
directly influenced by the Loach-Leigh-Clarke era, which achieved
its apotheosis in television drama during the '70s and '80s, a time
when the British film industry was enduring one of its periodic
slumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear Martin Scorsese talking about the first time he went
to see great movies in these huge cinemas in New York,'' Meadows
said, ``but to me a cinema was some seedy place in the back streets
of Stoke-on-Trent where you went twice a year at the most to see
films like `Grease.' Except for the likes of `Chariots of Fire' and
`Absolute Beginners,' there was no cinema culture in England when I
was growing up. And yet I would come in from the youth club on
Thursday night and on the telly there would be a film about a
pregnant woman and the guy who has come round to read the gas meter
and who obviously fancies her, and they'd sit in a room in a block
of flats and not talk. And you'd think, `Who the hell made this?'
You wouldn't know if it was a story or a documentary but you'd sit
there glued to it.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``The one thing I felt was missing from these
incredibly hard-hitting dramas was comedy. They were very real but
they seemed to take themselves too seriously, and I remember that
although life was tough where I grew up, people's humor came
through, and that's what I thought I could bring to my films when I
started making them. You see it in the cruel way the two boys treat
Morel when they think they can take advantage of him in `Romeo
Brass.' Even if a film's based on reality, it doesn't have to be a
depressing state of affairs.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
