<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSIC-JARRE &LR; - &UR; $ADV23-     07-19 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-JARRE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUBERT PLAYS A ROLE IN A CLEVER FILM SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
 - $ADV23-NYT   For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By MICHAEL BECKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   One of the cleverest moments in
the clever score for Istvan Szabo's film ``Sunshine'' occurs toward
the end, when old Uncle Gustave Sonnenschein returns home to
Budapest from abroad. He goes to the piano, ostensibly to play the
opening of Schubert's four-hand Fantasy in F minor, which has
served as the movie's leitmotif. To remind us that he is a
socialist, the tune immediately turns into the ``Marseillaise.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   This kind of thematic metamorphosis is at the core of the music
of ``Sunshine.'' From the first bars, there is something oddly
familiar about the score, and this for a reason. To create the main
theme, the composer Maurice Jarre starts with Schubert's first five
notes, which are just like those of the ``Marseillaise'' except
that the fifth note returns to the first instead of repeating.
Schubert, after a pause, reiterates the ``allons enfant'' pattern
several times before ending the phrase with a seductive dip. Jarre
goes right to the dip, in effect skipping a measure. To this torso
he adds a new, expansive gesture reminiscent of his score for
``Lawrence of Arabia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schubert fantasy is a particularly compelling choice for
``Sunshine.'' Written at the end of the composer's life, it is a
remarkable piece, which goes against the grain. What begins simply
as a kind of Biedermeier serenade turns into a work of great
mystery and astonishing profundity, concluding, like Mozart's
``Jupiter'' Symphony, with a double fugue.
</P>
<P>
   As Mozart did in his F minor Fantasy for mechanical organ,
written 30 years earlier and also arranged for four hands, Schubert
takes the genre into uncharted territory. In tone, his fantasy
shares something with Mozart's 40th Symphony, yet the dotted rhythm
recalls a march, with aspects simultaneously childlike, military
and funereal. The opening is riddled with grace notes, suggesting _
appropriately for the film _ an exotic, Hungarian Gypsy origin. The
phrases are irregular, and the seemingly wistful opening idea is
immediately repeated with an unusual insistence. There is something
inscrutable about this work.
</P>
<P>
   It projects a strangely ominous quality, a component of the film
as well. When two characters perform the piece at the beginning, it
seems to signify refined upper-middle-class contentment. Yet the
paradise of the Sonnenscheins is threatened from inside (a
quasi-incestuous love affair, various character flaws) and out
(world wars, revolutions, anti-Semitism). Maternal curses abound;
china cups break symbolically. Family members change their name
from the German-Jewish Sonnenschein to the Hungarian Sors. (Hmm,
now whose name does that sound like?) The family frolics, fights
and flees for generations, from Franz Joseph's Vienna to Stalinist
Budapest, with various progeny _ all played by Ralph Fiennes _
serving as an imperial court judge, an Olympic gold medalist and an
interrogator for the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is more music than the Schubert fantasy and its
offspring to back all this up. The score brilliantly weaves
together many kinds of sounds. The first third of the film is
particularly rich in musical variety, reflecting _ as Schubert's
work does in microcosm _ the polyglot shimmer of the Hapsburg lands
with a dazzling combination of Gypsy bands, Hungarian patriotic
music, Strauss waltzes, Jewish liturgical chants and, as a kind of
subsidiary theme, a glorious Hungarian love song, ``Spring Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the musical score, there is a subtler blend of
sounds. Chimes ring; clocks tick. Time is a major force in the
movie, and the slightly metronomic aspect of the Schubert fantasy
suggests that it may also be understood as a symbol of fate. In
fact, it is only when the youngest Sonnenschein loses his watch
(and fails to learn the piano) that he can begin his move toward
freedom. At this point, music teachers, we get the major-key
version of Schubert's theme.
</P>
<P>
   The film has a message: to be free, you must be true to who you
really are. This is linked to a pervasive distaste for
assimilation. (A Hungarian officer says to a Sonnenschein: ``I told
you to assimilate. I was wrong.'') Though not itself complex, this
mandate has darker, unexplored implications. On one hand, it seems
entirely positive: stand up for who you are; honor your traditions;
do not give in to changing fashion. On the other hand, in Central
Europe and elsewhere, such attitudes have quickly led to
collections of armed camps with devastating results.
</P>
<P>
   The film, as marvelous as it often is, has no room for such
ambiguities. It is, after all, a Hollywood-style epic, ultimately
more concerned with family drama and fornication than it is with
metaphysical complexity or illuminating the great wash of history.
So, if the untutored cannot really distinguish between the 1953
``doctors' plot'' in Russia and the 1956 Hungarian revolution, that
hardly matters.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is hard to avoid the conclusion that the nuances
that have been bleached out of history in ``Sunshine'' have their
perfect counterpart in the missing measure from Schubert's Fantasy
in F minor. In this way, too, the film and the score are
compatible, sharing a tone that tends to favor a certain
sentimentality over more troubling and painful visions.
</P>
<P>
   My coda is just the sort of thing the ``industry'' probably
expects from ivory-tower types, even those who live and work in
Southern California and should know better. We are all aware by now
that the movie business is about fame and illusion, but shouldn't
Schubert get some credit for the score?
</P>
<P>
   Neither the soundtrack album (from BMG/Milan) nor the
15-seconds-of-fame Web zines that have provided reviews of it seem
to know that Jarre's score owes a great debt to a rough
contemporary of the first Sonnenschein we meet (who almost
immediately gets blown up in the family's distillery): a short,
curly-haired composer from the Hapsburg Empire, who had his own
problems. (One data base says that the soundtrack ``starts with a
piano minuet that quickly develops a Beethoven feel.'')
</P>
<P>
   I am rooting for Maurice Jarre to win an Oscar for his terrific
score. But I hope he shares it with Schubert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
