 PERSONALS: Many Varieties on Bush Family Tree 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The hottest Bush of all, says Elle magazine, which has an eye for
beauty, is  &UR; George Prescott &LR;   &UR; Bush &LR; . This 24-year-old hunk, nephew
of presidential candidate  &UR; George W. &LR; , was ``my little brown one''
in 1988, when his grandfather introduced him to the public.
</P>
<P>
   George P. works as a paralegal and plans to enter law school in
the fall, but he meanwhile helps out in his uncle's campaign, says
Elle, where Bushites realize his `` &UR; Ricky Martin &LR;  appeal gives his
white-bread clan a touch of ethnic chic.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine says that George P. is well aware of his sex appeal
and ``uses his Lothario looks to open doors once closed to Bushes _
witness Vanity Fair's Oscar party, where he drooled over
 &UR; Salma Hayek &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for a balance,'' he says, ``between working hard
and succeeding and just having fun. I need that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Parties of the First Part &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At last week's Judiciary Committee hearing on Napster, Sen.
 &UR; Patrick Leahy &LR; , D-Vt., recalled that his ``beloved Grateful Dead
allowed anyone to tape their live shows and then trade tapes,
without ever demanding a nickel for the rights,'' reports Roll
Call.
</P>
<P>
   Sen.  &UR; Orrin Hatch &LR; , R-Utah, didn't have anything to say about
that precedent, but he wasn't going to let the Dems wear the sole
Deadhead crown. ``I like the Grateful Dead, too,'' he said, ``but
I'm not a slavish devotee.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The West Wing'' is adding a pair of Republicans ( &UR; Peggy &LR; 
 &UR; Noonan  &LR; and  &UR; Marlin Fitzwater &LR; ) to its list of Democratic
consultants ( &UR; Dee Dee Myers &LR; ,  &UR; Patrick Caddell &LR;  and  &UR; Lawrence &LR; 
 &UR; O'Donnell &LR; ), says the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; LUXURY HANDBAGS &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; FROM ITALIAN PRISONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A line of  &UR; Giorgio Armani &LR;  purses that sell for about $240 each
are being manufactured by inmates at the San Vittore prison in
Milan, says the Sunday Mirror of London. The workers are paid a few
dollars each.
</P>
<P>
   The handbags, display at Fashion Week in Milan, ``are official
Giorgio Armani products and are sold as part of our Armani Jeans
label,'' a spokesman for Armani told the paper. ``The aim is to get
the prisoners used to working again. Some have been inside a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the prisoners are Mafia members serving life terms.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Brooke Shields &LR; , 35-year-old former wife of &UR; Andre Agassi &LR; , is
engaged to be married to  &UR; Chris Henchy &LR; , 37, who produced the
canceled TV series ``Battery Park.''
</P>
<P>
   _ An IHateFinancialPlanning.com survey reported by the online
news service Wireless Flash found that 67 percent of people would
stoop to pick up a penny from the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm partial to my Web site, www.michaeldouglas.com. I do all
the e-mails and chats. There's a fan club you can join and see
pictures of me and Catherine _ stuff the tabloids would love to
have, so I figure it's worth $39 a year. The money goes to
supporting issues like disarmament with the U.N.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Michael Douglas  &LR; in Movieline magazine, as mined by &UR; Chris &LR; 
 &UR; Jehle. &LR;  A peek at the site reveals, in Douglas' bio, that although
he attended UC Santa Barbara, he had been accepted at Yale.
