<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7039 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-BEER-ART-2NDTAK     07-19 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BEER-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 QINGDAO, China: hard enough. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Our sales agents tended to focus on fancy restaurants, while
ignoring the needs of the common drinker,'' said Peng, a
plainspoken man who wears short-sleeve shirts and admits that he
does not really like beer.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, 70 percent of China's consumers fit the
definition of common drinker. They make enough money to buy beer,
but will not pay for a premium brand. So Tsingtao was squeezed on
both ends of the market: at the high end by Budweiser and Foster's,
and at the low end by the likes of Yintang.
</P>
<P>
   While China's beer market grew tenfold in the 1990s, Tsingtao's
production increased just 20 percent. From 1994 to 1996, the
company lost money.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to Qingdao in 1996, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, who
was then a cabinet member, became alarmed that China's flagship
beer seemed to be fading. Qingdao's leaders plucked Peng out of a
successful state-owned food company and sent him on a rescue
mission. Peng promptly got rid of most of the senior managers and
set about overhauling the brewer.
</P>
<P>
   He set up a new sales network, with 45 branch offices, to
promote Tsingtao more aggressively. And he started buying breweries
to produce the flagship brand, as well as lower-cost local brands.
Buying breweries in the hinterland enabled Peng to avoid one of the
pitfalls of the Chinese industry: protectionism by local
authorities who jealously guard their home brew.
</P>
<P>
   Tsingtao, which reclaimed the No. 1 position last year, has
acquired 22 breweries from Shenzhen in the south to Beijing in the
north. Owning more breweries has allowed Peng to bypass China's
clotted distribution channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect, he's consolidating the industry,'' said Jack
Perkowski, the chief executive of Asimco, an Asian investment
company that owns two small Beijing beer companies, Five Star and
Three Ring. ``They want to be the first Chinese company to have a
truly national presence.''
</P>
<P>
   While Peng was whipping Tsingtao into shape, the foreigners
began discovering some hard truths about the Chinese market. The
premium segment, in which the non-Chinese producers compete,
accounts for barely 7 percent of overall sales. As price deflation
has rippled through the Chinese economy, consumers have been more
reluctant than ever to pay extra for an upscale brand.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign companies also made heavy upfront investments.
Burrows said Anheuser-Busch paid $52 million for its brewery in the
central city of Wuhan. The company spent millions more to upgrade
the factory, not to mention on advertising and marketing. Although
its main brand, Budweiser, is quite popular here, the sales are too
small and costs are too high to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get enough volume,'' Perkowski said, ``particularly
if you set up a brewery that looks like a brewery in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Burrows said sales of Budweiser improved this year, after two
lackluster years. He predicted that Anheuser-Busch would turn a
profit in China in five years. Burrows said that with 200 sales
agents in 31 Chinese cities, Anheuser-Busch was determined to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Other foreign brands, however, are sounding a retreat. Foster's
of Australia sold two of its Chinese breweries last year, keeping
one in Shanghai. Lion Nathan, a New Zealand brewer, said it may
leave altogether. By the end of August, Tsingtao will announce
three acquisitions of foreign-invested breweries _ two in Beijing
and one in Shanghai. Peng declined to name the companies.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Peng, though, is looking beyond the breweries to a partnership
with Anheuser-Busch. He said a deal would cut Anheuser's costs
because it must now transport all its beer from its Wuhan brewery.
It could avoid those long trips by using Tsingtao's plants in
Beijing and Shanghai. In return, Tsingtao would brew its beer in
Anheuser's factories in the United States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An alliance with Anheuser-Busch would be rich in symbolism. Five
years ago, Anheuser bought a 5 percent stake in Tsingtao, and the
two companies discussed ways to cooperate. But the American company
was put off by the Chinese company's balky managers. Coming back to
the table to make a deal would send a clear signal that Tsingtao is
a global player.
</P>
<P>
   It would also help Peng realize his dream of making Tsingtao one
of the world's top 10 brewers by 2003, its 100th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top leaders of China were worried that Chinese beer would
collapse because of all the competition,'' Peng said. ``But five
years later, it turns out the Tsingtao has succeeded. Our attitude
has changed from fear of the foreigners to driving them out of the
market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
