<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HOLOCAUST-AUSTRIA-ART     07-19 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-AUSTRIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST RESTITUTION GROUP PLANS TO PRESS AUSTRIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD WONG   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An international organization that seeks compensation
for Holocaust survivors said Wednesday that it planned to pressure
the Austrian government to acknowledge complicity during the Nazi
regime and to improve financial reparations to Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty delegates at a two-day annual meeting of the Claims
Conference in New York voted unanimously to approach the Austrian
government with three requests: to acknowledge that it had a role
in the Holocaust; that it make payments to survivors even before a
final accounting report is completed, and that it make some sort of
restitution for property taken from Jews during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've solved so many issues except for the Austrian issue that
it sticks out like a sore thumb,'' said Israel Singer, chief
negotiator for the group. ``This is an obligation on their part.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Claims Conference, which started in the 1950s,
distributed $239 million to survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The group, officially known as the Conference on Jewish Material
Claims Against Germany, was instrumental in pressuring the German
government and companies to create a $5 billion fund for Nazi-era
slave laborers and forced laborers. That agreement came to fruition
in March. Since its founding, the group has helped to get Germany
to set aside $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The group also lobbied the Swiss banks that decided in 1998 to
pay $1.5 billion to survivors because the banks were storing money
that Nazis had seized from Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Austrian government agreed to give 70,000
schillings, just under $5,000 today, each to Jews from Austria who
survived the war.
</P>
<P>
   It is also completing an agreement to make reparations for slave
and forced laborers, in exchange for the United States' dropping
all lawsuits filed on behalf of those victims. But the Claims
Conference said Wednesday that it disapproved of that agreement
because it did not address the issue of seized property.
</P>
<P>
   The group estimates that 70,000 apartments and up to 30,000
businesses were taken from Jews living in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   When Germany took over Austria in 1938, scholars say, about
180,000 Jews lived in the country. About 50,000 were sent to
concentration camps, mostly in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more than a financial problem, it is a psychological
problem,'' said Moshe H. Jahoda, the group's representative in
Austria. Jahoda said 23 members of his family were killed in camps,
including his parents and younger sister. Their apartment and
printing business were taken from them, he said, and all he has
received is the 70,000 schillings.
</P>
<P>
   George Kilzer, an Austrian consul in New York, said that his
government had not heard of Wednesday's vote by the Claims
Conference. ``We know, of course, these are issues, but so far it
has not been brought officially toward us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the slave labor reparations, he said that ``is more or
less settled already.''
</P>
<P>
   Austria has long said it was a victim of German aggression. But
the government's agreement in 1990 to pay $200 million in benefits
to Jews who suffered there during the Nazi era suggested to some
Jewish groups that Austria had begun to accept responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Chancellor Wolfgang Schussel of Austria sent a
letter to Singer expressing his interest in settling quickly on
reparations. ``I fully understand the concern that in view of the
age of the Holocaust survivors quick solutions are asked for,''
Schussel wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, Austrian officials appointed a special envoy,
Ernst Sucharipa, to negotiate with the Claims Conference on
speedier reparations and property restitution. Sucharipa is
officially unaffiliated with the coalition government, because the
Claims Conference has refused to negotiate with a government that
includes Joerg Haider's far-right Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   So far, representatives from both sides have met only once,
indicating Austria's reluctance to negotiate, Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Austrians just keep trying to delay the issue,'' Singer
said. ``They just need the willingness to deal with this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
