<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-BAXTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stakes are high in race for open seat
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Rep. John Lewis' expression of interest Wednesday in
the U.S. Senate seat vacated by the death of Paul Coverdell was the
earliest, but it certainly won't be the last we can expect in the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting the memory of Coverdell's taciturn nature, some of the
other possibilities are waiting until after the funeral to make any
public comment.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, several of those who might figure in this unexpected
Senate race are men of Coverdell's generation, who are genuinely
mourning the man they knew and perhaps taking stock of the length
of their own days.
</P>
<P>
   But with only four months before the November election, next
week should be a fast-paced period of decision, with the capacity
for not a few surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The interests of the two national parties will strongly
influence how things play out. The race could change the chemistry
of the presidential contest in Georgia, which gives Al Gore an
interest in Barnes' choice.
</P>
<P>
   With a few Republican-held seats already in jeopardy, this race
also presents the Democrats with the opportunity to significantly
narrow the GOP's 55-45 Senate majority this year and have a
realistic chance of winning back the majority another election down
the line.
</P>
<P>
   So there isn't going to be any sentiment from Washington for
Barnes to appoint a caretaker for the next four months. The
Democrats want a candidate who can win and hold this seat.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of national Democrats would like to see former Gov. Zell
Miller, a name they associate with success, express interest in the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Either Lewis or former U.N. Ambassador Andrew Young also would
spark national interest because of their potential to increase
black Democratic turnout this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Moving down the generational ladder, Michael Coles could make an
argument for the job based on his showing against Coverdell in
1998, and former Secretary of State Lewis Massey might have an
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes likes and has confidence in current Secretary of State
Cathy Cox _ but the interesting question here might be whether he
wants to risk a promising protege in what could be a difficult
race, depending on what shapes up among the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's the big name to watch on the Democratic side, although
the likelihood that he will make himself available isn't great.
Among the Republicans, it's the man Miller beat in the 1990
governor's race, Rep. Johnny Isakson.
</P>
<P>
   If Isakson _ now the best-known and most experienced Republican
holding office in the state _ shows a strong interest in
challenging the Democratic appointee this November, the GOP
struggle could be short and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't, the next name that comes to mind is Rep. Jack
Kingston, who has gone to some trouble to get his name known
outside his coastal district and has the youth and ambition to go
for the job.
</P>
<P>
   But more names come to mind only shortly after his. Five of the
eight Republican House members have war chests over $600,000, and
one who doesn't, Mac Collins, has resources he might put into play.
Then there's Newt Gingrich and Guy Millner, but that's blue-sky
speculation http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
