<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID SUMMIT CROSSFIRE, CLINTON REACHES OUT TO MIDEAST LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Taking ``every step imaginable'' to rescue
Middle East peace negotiations as they carried on well past the
original deadline, President Clinton contacted the leaders of
several key Middle East nations late Wednesday, struggling to reach
a compromise before leaving early this morning for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials denied that the Israeli-Palestinian talks
were in crisis, or that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak was on
the verge of walking out, despite a letter Barak issued accusing
his opponents of ``squandering an opportunity.'' Trying to sound a
note of optimism, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Wednesday
the parties had ``reached a pivotal moment in these talks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked very hard to find a path to an agreement. At
this point in time, we have not reached that,'' Lockhart said
shortly after 5:30 p.m. ``But the priority for the president right
now is to make sure every possible avenue toward an agreement is
explored.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant a ninth long day of meetings among the negotiators,
including two between Clinton and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
inside the rain-drenched confines of the Camp David retreat.
Clinton also spoke via telephone with several Mideast leaders _
including Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, King Abdullah II of
Jordan, and Crown Prince Abdullah of Saudi Arabia _ in what US
officials said was an effort to place pressure on the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   One US official who has been involved in previous talks said the
calls appeared to be aimed at encouraging Barak and Arafat, but
particularly Arafat, to show the courage and fortitude to find a
compromise. It may also have been an effort to get Arafat to step
back from the September 13 deadline he has set to unilaterally
declare Palestinian statehood, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, meanwhile, said the calls were simply ``to give them
(the other leaders) some sense of where we are in this process and
where it stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Accusations flew throughout the day, with news of a breakdown
ricocheting from Camp David to the Middle East and back again in a
series of phone calls. Amid reports that Barak was leaving and had
sent a letter to Clinton accusing the Palestinians of negotiating
in bad faith, a Palestinian official thousands of miles away
charged the Israeli leader with exploiting the talks for political
gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak did not go to the summit to make peace,'' said
Palestinian cabinet minister Freih Abu Meddein. ``He went there to
prove to his people that he could stick to Israeli red lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, whose coalition government fractured before he left,
faced criticism from hawkish conservatives that he was willing to
cede too much. He had hoped to return home with an agreement that
he could then sell directly to the Israeli people, who according to
polls support a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides arrived at the negotiating table focused on four
core issues: The fate of Palestinian refugees; territory and
borders; Israeli security; and control over Jerusalem, the holy
city that both sides claim as their capital. The issues were so
intractable, and, in the case of Jerusalem, so freighted with
symbolism, that Israeli and Palestinians had previously avoided
discussing them through seven years of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, the increasingly hostile remarks by
officials on all sides seemed to reflect the mood inside the
presidential retreat, where a week of cautious optimism rapidly
deteriorated in the summit's final hours.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of possible failure followed fast on the heels of
Clinton's decision to postpone his trip to Japan, which he
announced shortly after midnight Wednesday. By morning, Israeli
officials were telling reporters traveling with the prime minister
to pack their bags and prepare to go.
</P>
<P>
   Barak informed Clinton of his decision via letter, angrily
writing that the Palestinians were negotiating in bad faith. It was
interpreted as brinkmanship at first; Abu Mazen, a senior
Palestinian negotiator who left Camp David Wednesday morning to
attend his son's wedding in Ramallah, said as he left the country
that ``serious talks'' were continuing into the early afternoon,
suggesting Barak had not given up right away.
</P>
<P>
   But the verbal crossfire outside the talks suggested that both
sides had hardened their positions. Some critics began questioning
whether either leader had been willing to make concessions at all.
The harshest words came from Barak, who began making his
displeasure public just 12 hours before the talks were supposed to
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my sorrow, I have come to the conclusion that the
Palestinian side is conducting negotiations insincerely and is not
willing to negotiate in a serious and practical manner for a
permanent peace between us,'' Barak's letter said, according to
Israel's Army radio, which broadcast the declaration soon after it
was sent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinians will witness the tragic consequences of
squandering an opportunity,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs taken the night before showed a weary Clinton
sitting on an outdoor patio with Barak, who was taking notes on a
legal pad. Another picture from Tuesday night, of Clinton and
Arafat deep in conversation, contrasted starkly with many shots
taken the previous week, in which the leaders were seen smiling and
strolling through the surrounding woods.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned to leave sometime after midnight Thursday for
Japan, where the G-8 summit of industrialized nations begins
Friday. He delayed the trip early Wednesday, postponing a meeting
with the Japanese prime minister until later in the week. And
according to one US official, the decision to press beyond the
original deadline made sense, given the personalities Clinton was
working with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Middle East is the land of miracles,'' the US official
said Wednesday. ``You never say die. You don't know what's going to
happen before (Thursday) morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ann Scales of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
