<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COLOSSEUM-OEDIPUS-NYT     07-19 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOSSEUM-OEDIPUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMAN COLOSSEUM COMES ALIVE AGAIN, WITH A MORE DIGNIFIED ROAR OF
THE CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Colosseum, the infamous arena of combat and
slaughter, is back in business for the first time in 1,500 years.
Only instead of cheering for gladiators and hungry lions,
contemporary Romans are paying to see a more ancient and somewhat
more high-minded form of entertainment, ``Oedipus Rex.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's world premiere, a new production of the
Sophocles tragedy performed by the National Theater of Greece, was
a daring experiment in putting Rome's most famous ancient monument
in the service of culture. Just building a stage over the yawning
pit of ruins required five years of study and restoration work by
an international team of archaeologists and engineers, who
reconstructed a wood floor over a portion of the ruined corridors
and underground tunnels where gladiators, stagehands and caged
beasts once waited for the show to begin.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment also required a leap of faith by Greek actors,
accustomed to performing in smaller, more accommodating and
acoustically correct theaters. ``The Colosseum was a place designed
to kill people,'' said Grigoris Valtinos, the actor who plays
Oedipus, somewhat nervously before Tuesday's dress rehearsal. ``And
now it is killing us.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, however, the actors were clearly audible and
visible Wednesday night on a stage and narrow wooden crossing set
like a bridge along the length of the Colosseum. But the VIP
audience had more difficulty. The lighting was too dim for the
audience to read the Italian translation that was distributed. A
few hardy souls fired up cigarette lighters in an effort to follow
the plot. But just being inside the ghostly walls provided its own
theatrical thrill.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of staging a performance at the Colosseum during 2000,
a Holy Year of the Roman Catholic Church, came from Italy's
Istituto Nazionale del Dramma Antico, an organization dedicated to
staging classic works in ancient settings, including plays,
translated into Italian and staged in the Greek theater of Syracuse
in Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sophocles,'' performed in modern Greek, is not the usual
summer fare, however. ``We wanted to break away from the usual and
stage something that would represent the voyage of mankind,''
explained Walter Le Moli, president of the institute. When he and
his colleagues first talked of using the Colosseum, they didn't
know its floor was being restored, serendipity that made Wednesday
night's performance possible.
</P>
<P>
   For Italy's millennium celebrations, the institute selected what
it calls the ``Sophocles Project,'' a series of plays by the Greek
playwright starting with ``Oedipus Rex,'' which runs through
Friday. Le Moli said it made thematic sense to have a Greek company
perform what he described as ``man's search for identity _ the
first play from which all other drama descends.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be followed by ``Antigone,'' to be performed in late
July by an Iranian theater company, the Dramatic Arts Center of
Tehran. The play stresses, as Le Moli put it, ``the conflict
between religious and civil authority.'' The cycle ends in August
with ``Oedipus at Colonus,'' an operatic version of Sophocles' play
with music by Mendelssohn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oedipus at Colonus,'' a play that deals with Oedipus' death in
exile, was originally supposed to be performed by the Kameri
Theater of Tel Aviv. The organizers hoped to link the play's theme
with the Jews' search for a promised land. Those ambitious
cross-cultural notions ran aground, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian government resisted committing to the project,
apparently unwilling to have its players perform if Israelis were
included in the program. The point became moot, however, after the
Israeli company was forced to pull out because of translation
delays and scheduling conflicts. Instead, Italian actors,
accompanied by an Italian orchestra and chorus, will perform the
play.
</P>
<P>
   The National Theater of Greece, which in past years has brought
``Medea'' and ``Electra'' to New York, will take ``Oedipus Rex'' to
City Center in Manhattan in October. There, instead of relying on
translations printed in librettos, audiences will be able to follow
the play by reading English supertitles. That concession to
American convenience puzzles some of the performers. ``Like a pop
music show,'' said Jenny Gaitanapoulou, who plays Jocasta, the
mother of Oedipus. ``Only I am not Celine Dion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaitanapoulou, who usually works at the National Theater of
Cyprus, nevertheless displayed a shrewd sense of contemporary
American culture. To prepare for her role as a powerful and at
times ruthless matriarch, the actress explained, ``I based my
interpretation of Jocasta on Elizabeth I, Queen Gertrude in
`Hamlet' and Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The stage, set atop the new wood flooring that covers only
one-seventh of the Colosseum's arena, is small and dwarfed by the
vast marble and brick curves of the ruins beyond it. The
archaeologists' concerns limited seating to 300 people. Another 400
spectators were allowed to stand. The set will come down at the end
of the summer, but the floor will stay, and there is the
possibility of staging more small cultural events. Government
officials, however, rule out a large rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's performance was a theatrical debut for the
Colosseum, which was begun under Emperor Vespasian in A.D. 72 and
finished under Titus in A.D. 80, built to awe and entertain more
than 50,000 spectators. The Colosseum last saw a Roman-style
spectacle _ wild animals being slaughtered _ in A.D. 523.
(Gladiator fights were ended in 407.) A series of earthquakes badly
damaged the building, and at times it was used as a quarry, , its
stones carried off to build Renaissance palaces and churches. In
the 18th century Pope Benedict XIV, who had a conservationist
streak, put an end to such scavenging by consecrating the Colosseum
to the passion of Jesus, which helped feed the legends of the
Colosseum as a site of Christian martyrdom. Even now, the pope, on
Good Friday, reenacts the last passion of Christ at its walls,
starting inside.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say there is no evidence that early Christians were
martyred there, let alone fed to the lions. Many, however, are
reluctant to rule it out. ``It was a prime place for public
executions, and there is no reason to believe Christians were
excluded from the slaughter,'' explained Adriano La Regina, Rome's
superintendent of archaeology, who oversaw the reconstruction work.
``It may not show up in the texts because Romans took it for
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago the restoration unearthed a marble plaque with an
inscription that had been covered over centuries ago. Scholars
discovered that the plaque originally explained that the
construction was paid for with booty taken from the sack of
Jerusalem in A.D. 70.
</P>
<P>
   Vassilis Papavasiliou, the director, said that while it was
challenging to stage ``Oedipus Rex'' in the Colosseum, it was also
oddly fitting. ``Oedipus is a deeply human story, the story of all
of us, and we are all children of this society,'' he said. ``The
Colosseum used combat as entertainment. Our chosen form of combat
here is Sophocles, an effort to restore meaning to entertainment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
