<HEADER>
A7053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ATL-HOT-COX     07-19 0298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-HOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wednesday heat hits summer high
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ These are the times that fry men's soles.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature hit 99 degrees at Hartsfield International
Airport about 3 p.m. Wednesday, according to the National Weather
Service. It's Atlanta's hottest temperature this year, matching the
high on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the sidewalks have been sizzling all month, reaching 92
or better for 18 consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures today are expected to climb to the high 90s in
South Georgia, the low 90s in the mountains, and somewhere in
between in metro Atlanta, according to Robert Beasley, a Weather
Service meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday or Monday, Atlantans could enjoy highs that only reach
the upper 80s, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be in a cooling trend by then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some parts of the state could see a few scattered showers in the
next several days, Beasley said.
</P>
<P>
   With temperatures up, Atlanta's air quality is down.
</P>
<P>
   Today has been declared a Code Orange smog alert day by the
Partnership for a Smog-Free Ga., meaning ozone levels will be
``unhealthy for sensitive groups.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the demand for electricity prompted Georgia Power
Co., for the second time this year, to order power curtailed to 160
large industrial customers.
</P>
<P>
   The businesses, mostly manufacturing plants, purchase
electricity under reduced rates year-round with the provision that
the utility can ask them to reduce consumption when demand soars.
However hot it is here, it's even hotter farther west.
</P>
<P>
   Heat has been blamed for 12 deaths in Texas; five more deaths
are being investigated in Louisiana as possibly heat-related.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
