<HEADER>
A7057 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ART-TINTORETTO-$ADV23     07-19 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-TINTORETTO-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TINTORETTO REAPPEARS IN RURAL PENNSYLVANIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By KEN SHULMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WERNERSVILLE, Pa. _ The Jesuit
Center here stands in a lush, rolling, Gainsborough-like landscape
some seven miles west of Reading. Opened in 1930 as a novitiate,
the imposing, slightly incongruous red brick building now serves as
a Jesuit retirement home. As in most small, contained communities,
the residents are not accustomed to seeing strangers. When the
elderly priests look up from their dinners to watch the Rev. J.A.
Panuska, who directs the Jesuit residence, lead a visitor into the
refectory, they already know what has brought the outsider here.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You're here for the Tintoretto,'' says an unshaven priest
leaning on a cane. The stranger nods. ``It stinks,'' the cleric
says. ``The scripture tells how Jesus was repulsed by Lazarus'
rotting flesh, how Jesus withdrew before the sight of death. The
passage foreshadows his own death, and his triumph over death. Here
Tintoretto gives us a milky white Lazarus, a muscular movie star
whose nudity is covered by a paltry little cloth. He got it all
wrong. All wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting under discussion is ``The Raising of Lazarus,'' one
of seven existing Tintoretto treatments of the subject. In 1998,
the 42-by-58-inch oil painting was rediscovered during a general
inventory at the Wernersville residence. At the time, it was
hanging, unlighted and unlabeled, in a first-floor corridor across
from the chapel entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when they came from the museum to examine it with
their special lighting,'' said Father Panuska, who was a novice at
the residence from 1948 through 1950 and has been the superior
since 1998. He also recalls seeing the Tintoretto over the entrance
to the third-floor library during his novitiate. ``I said, `Oh my
Lord, what is this that we have?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jacopo Robusti Tintoretto (1518-94) was one of the great
painters of the late Italian Renaissance. ``The Raising of
Lazarus'' is a staged tableau done primarily in soft reds, pinks
and flesh tones. In it, a placid Jesus resuscitates a nude,
athletic-looking Lazarus. Mary and Martha, Lazarus' sisters, and a
third witness kneel rapt and spellbound before Jesus, their heads
pitched to the right in a gesture of adoration.
</P>
<P>
   Behind them, five additional witnesses, their faces concealed
behind handkerchiefs or rendered in hidden profile, stand in an
almost conspiratorial huddle beneath the now blackened leaves of an
olive tree. An idealized view of Jerusalem from the hills of
Bethany in the upper left section of the painting completes the
composition.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt about the painting's authenticity. ``The
Raising of Lazarus'' is listed in Rodolfo Pallucchino's 1982
Tintoretto catalog, the most authoritative source on the Venetian
artist. The entry lists it as ``missing.'' Sarah Lidsey, the
old-master specialist at Christie's in New York, expressed no doubt
about the painting's authenticity after she was invited to inspect
it last year. Tentatively dated 1556-57, ``The Raising of Lazarus''
is an early Tintoretto in excellent condition. Franco Mormando, a
Jesuit and professor of Italian literature at Boston College who
did extensive archival research on the painting, said it was
probably commissioned as an ex-voto during a minor outbreak of the
plague in Venice.
</P>
<P>
   From an art-historical standpoint, the discovery of the
Tintoretto in Wernersville is not quite as significant as the
discovery of Caravaggio's ``Taking of Christ'' in a Jesuit
residence in Dublin in 1990. Yet the story of the Tintoretto
painting is intriguing and involves several figures of
ecclesiastical and historical prominence.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest document that mentions ``The Raising of Lazarus''
places the painting in Nottingham, England, in 1872. It
subsequently traveled to Munich, Berlin and then to Rome, where
Nicholas and Genevieve Brady, a pair of wealthy and devout American
Roman Catholics, saw the work in the collection of Pietro
Galleazzi. Galleazzi was a close confidant and aide to Cardinal
Eugenio Pacelli, who served as papal nuncio in Berlin in the second
decade of the 20th century and later became Pope Pius XII.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bradys spent their winters in Rome,'' Mormando said.
``They were part of that elite social ecclesiastical circle that
would meet frequently in Rome and at the Vatican.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1928, Nicholas Brady purchased the Tintoretto from Galleazzi
for $35,000, a high price for an artwork at that time. The bill of
sale was witnessed by Frank Spellman, a young priest from Whitman,
Mass., who had fallen out of favor with his local archdiocese and
gone to test the ecclesiastical waters in Rome. He would later
become Cardinal Francis Spellman, archbishop of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Brady, who had expanded a considerable family fortune through
utility-company mergers, died in 1930. That same year, his wife
donated the Tintoretto and 94 other artworks to the newly opened
Wernersville novitiate, which had been paid for entirely by Brady
at a cost of more than a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradys were not collectors; they purchased the artworks as
objects of contemplation for the novices and teachers at the
novitiate. Their gift was of uneven quality. It included a
miniature watercolor copy of Pinturicchio's Madonna and Child
fresco in the Vatican and a small oil copy of Luca Signorelli's
``Overthrow of the Anti-Christ'' in the Duomo at Orvieto, along
with several religious paintings by unknown 19th- and 20th-century
painters and portraits of the Bradys. There was also a splendid
Arts and Crafts Movement needlepoint series depicting the stations
of the cross by Lilly Yeats (sister of the poet W.B. Yeats),
several medieval ivory statues and a terra cotta angel head
attributed to the school of Luca della Robbia. Still, the
Tintoretto is the only work of real note.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Raising of Lazarus'' hung in the Jesuit Center from 1930
onward, first in the upstairs library and then in a corridor
outside the main chapel. ``I believe that the Jesuits simply forgot
about it,'' Mormando said. ``Or that they thought the attribution
was a sort of wishful thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Since last December, just after the discovery of the painting
became public, it has hung in the European gallery on the third
floor of the Reading Public Museum and Art Gallery. The museum was
founded in 1904 in the classroom of Dr. Levi Mengel, a Reading
educator and explorer who participated in Admiral Perry's 1891
expedition to the Antarctic. Its core collection consists of 1,700
natural-history specimens that Mengel acquired for his classroom at
the 1903 St. Louis World Exposition. On the second floor of the
museum, a life-size plastic replica of Mengel inspecting a
butterfly through a magnifying lens sits behind his desk,
surrounded by specimen bottles and neatly organized wooden
cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   Before the arrival of the Tintoretto, the museum's top
attractions were the armor of a Samurai warrior, three shrunken
heads from the Jivaro people of Ecuador, a mummified Egyptian
female from 550 B.C. and, upstairs, a large 19th-century landscape
painting by Julien Dupre titled ``The Balloon.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have nothing of this quality in the entire museum,''
Robert Metzger, the director, says of the Tintoretto. ``We have
some great masterpieces from several periods. But having a work
from one of the great masters of the Italian Renaissance is of
tremendous importance to us. We are very fortunate that the Jesuit
center saw fit to loan it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The Tintoretto has attracted visitors from New York, the West
Coast and Europe. Panuska and Mormando are currently examining
proposals from conservators for a minor restoration. After the
conservation, the painting will travel selectively for several
years. Although ``The Raising of Lazarus'' has been valued as high
as $2 million _ a smaller version of the same subject by Tintoretto
sold at Sotheby's for $950,000 in 1994 _ the Jesuits have no
intention of selling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy is that if something is given to an institution,
they should use it for that purpose,'' Panuska said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That purpose now is sharing this beautiful painting with the
world, and with our local community,'' he continued. ``I'd like for
this museum to be its home base. Then I would like to see it
travel, but to smaller museums, perhaps near other Jesuit
communities, where it would really be something special. So many
museums are so gifted with wonderful paintings. I'd like this
painting to travel to places where people would want to come and
look at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
