u s BC-BBN-LARKIN0720-COX     07-19 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LARKIN0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Larkin feels asking price is fair
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Anybody can get traded.
</P>
<P>
   They traded Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   They traded Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   They traded Hank Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cincinnati Reds are likely to trade Barry Larkin. Soon.
The dodgy question remains, though. Will Larkin accept a trade and
are there more than subtle hints from his camp that he won't. When
it was suggested Wednesday that general manager Jim Bowden might be
requesting approval on a trade with the New York Mets in the next
48 hours, Larkin smiled and said, ``He can save his breath.''
</P>
<P>
   A Yankee-like package may be offered to the Reds by the Mets,
some minor-league prospects similar to the three minor-leaguers the
Bronx Bombers sent to the Reds for pitcher Denny Neagle. The Mets
might part with 20-year-old Class AA pitcher Pat Strange, their No.
2 draft pick in 1998, plus 23-year-old pitcher Grant Roberts and
21-year-old outfielder Alex Escobar.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Operating Officer John Allen said Wednesday that the Reds
want Larkin to finish his career in Cincinnati, become one of the
few modern-day players to stay his entire career with one team, but
that Larkin's non-negotiable, three-year, $27.9 million asking
price was too steep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not tell Barry that we were not interested in keeping
him in Cincinnati,'' Allen said. ``I simply informed him that we
were not able to sign him for the amount of money he has
demanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin agreed that what Allen said is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did tell me he wanted me to stay in Cincinnati and I don't
want to get into a war of words,'' Larkin said. ``All I'm asking
from Cincinnati right now is to be paid at below fair market.
Below. That's simply it. They've informed me they can't do that.
That's it. I asked John about deferring money, the way they did for
Junior Griffey, but that was not an issue because they said we are
too far apart, not even in the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Far apart is $18 million over three years, which the Reds might
be willing to kick up to $20 million, but because Larkin and his
agent, Eric Goldschmidt, believe $27.9 million is below the going
rate, they aren't in a negotiating mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking for them to take care of me because I signed
for less money when I signed my contracts in the past,'' Larkin
said. ``I caught a lot of grief from guys around the league and
other agents for signing for under value. And I'm not trying to
recoup that now. It's just I'm asking for fair market value and
that's it. I'm not asking for them to bend over backwards or do me
any favors. I could see it if my game has deteriorated, but it has
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin began Wednesday night's game against Houston with a .327
batting average with nine homers and 33 RBIs. Defensively, he
remains more than competent, although he is tied for the club lead
with 10 errors, same as Gold Glove second baseman Pokey Reese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a realist, man,'' Larkin added. ``I deal with good news
and I deal with bad news. This is just one of those things _ a
business decision . . . and that's the first thing Allen said to
me. He told me it was nothing personal and they appreciated
everything I've done. He did use the past tense. It's unfortunate
and I'm disappointed by it, but my career is not over by any
stretch of anybody's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go somewhere else if the Reds choose not to sign me. The
COO said they aren't going to sign me, so I'm looking at it like
they aren't going to sign me. I haven't talked to the GM (Bowden)
and I'm surprised by that. If he is working on anything, he needs
my approval and I have not yet talked to him and I find that odd.
They are running out of time (July 31 trade deadline).''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Larkin will accept a trade. He could refuse
all trades and stay the rest of the year, then declare free agency,
making certain the Reds get little in return for him.
</P>
<P>
   Why would he stay when he isn't wanted? It is Cincinnati, where
he has played his entire career, where he was born, where he went
to school. One of the reasons Griffey signed with the Reds is
Larkin, and they are close.
</P>
<P>
   It's an ugly mess out of which can come no winners.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
