<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7078 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-IACOCCA19-COX     07-19 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IACOCCA19 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 -COX &HT;    Auto icon Iacocca has his thumb in another pie
 &HT;    By Paul Owers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Asking Lee Iacocca what kind of car he drives is like
asking a priest about the prayers he prefers.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Iacocca, the dean of the American auto industry,
skips around town in several models, but DaimlerChrysler's new PT
Cruiser might be his favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very practical,'' he said Wednesday from the second-floor
study of his suite at the Hotel Inter-Continental in downtown
Miami. ``And it's cute as a bug.''
</P>
<P>
   As in insect _ not VW, which he quickly dismisses for lack of
room. You'll see Jeeps and minivans in Iacocca's Bel Air, Calif.,
garage, along with a mint condition MG.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of great specialty cars out there,'' said the
man who gave us the Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   Iacocca, former head of Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp., was
in South Florida briefly this week to promote Olivio Premium
Products, a Boston-based company that has been one of his many
business interests since leaving the top post at Chrysler in 1992.
He also has been involved with electric bicycles, casinos, and
investment banking ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Olivio makes Olivio Premium Spread, a butter substitute made
with olive and canola oils. The salty spread is cholesterol-free
and contains 85 percent less saturated fat than butter, the company
said. Health magazine has named the spread one of its 10 tastiest
low-fat foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people think of Lee Iacocca, they think of cars,'' Olivio
spokeswoman Karren Walsh said. ``But what most people don't know is
that his lifelong passion is food.''
</P>
<P>
   Iacocca, 75, the son of Italian immigrants, developed the idea
for a butter substitute more than 10 years ago when he and his
son-in-law, Ned Hentz, were taking an after-dinner stroll on
Iacocca's 25-acre estate in Tuscany. Iacocca, who cooks frequently,
wanted a spread that was healthy and began to hire food experts.
The spread first went to market in 1995 in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Hentz, a former advertising executive married to Iacocca's
daughter, Kathi, is president and chief executive of Olivio Premium
Products. The company's chief operating officer is Vincent Auty,
who helped create the ``I Can't Believe It's Not Butter'' brand of
margarine.
</P>
<P>
   Hentz and nutritionist Dr. Walter Willett are developing other
good-for-you products and are planning to roll out Olivio
mayonnaise and cooking and salad oils.
</P>
<P>
   The Olivio spread is manufactured in Baltimore by a division of
European food giant Unilever, which this year bought Slim-Fast
Foods Co. of West Palm Beach for $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The spread generated about $3 million in sales last year _ a
decent number considering it's available in only about 20 percent
of the nation, Hentz said. Publix, Albertson's and Wal-Mart are
among the retailers that now carry the spread in Florida, with
one-pound containers selling for $1.69.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you gave 10 people the product, I can't imagine fewer than
four would not make it their brand,'' Hentz said. ``It's really
about sampling. It's getting there. It's starting to round the
corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at his Miami hotel suite overlooking Biscayne Bay, Iacocca,
who owned a house in Boca Raton for 21 years, touched on other
topics before catching a flight back to California to continue his
semi-retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He said he doesn't mind America's reliance on technology _ as
long as it works. He opposed air bags in cars because he said they
initially were unsafe. But once the feature was perfected, he
embraced it and was the first to put air bags on the passenger
side.
</P>
<P>
   As for the looming presidential election, Iacocca said he's
unsure what will happen. An independent who was asked to run in the
1988 presidential race, he said he has never met candidates George
W. Bush or Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's for what anymore,'' Iacocca said. ``Whoever
comes across as the most human will win.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why (President) Clinton has done so well. He thinks
fast on his feet, plus he was in the right place at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
