<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-COWBOYS0720-COX     07-19 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CBy Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ At what price can someone regain honor
and peace of mind?
</P>
<P>
   After quarterback Randall Cunningham accepted the 1998 most
valuable player trophy as the NFL's best player, he wasn't worth a
case of beer last year in Minnesota. He became a forgotten man
early in the season, booed by fans, treated like yesterday's
newspaper by teammates. The best way to save face was to get out of
town before the snow melted.
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic he would land with the Dallas Cowboys, the team he
hated most during his first 10 seasons in the NFL. Yet Dallas
offers Cunningham an opportunity to complete his career on his
terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good situation for me, playing with the best in
front of you,'' said Cunningham, towering over a group of visitors
after practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy's the best. Who's still playing in the league who has won
three Super Bowls?''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham was referring to Troy Aikman, of course, who has no
plans to let the newest Cowboy play this year. That's what makes
the acquisition of Cunningham so intriguing. Why would someone who
has been a hallmark player for 14 years want to be someone's caddy?
A three-year, $3 million deal makes the former Viking and Eagle an
expensive understudy.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but team owner Jerry Jones saw something in Cunningham when
they met early this year. Jones is convinced Cunningham's skill
level is closer to his 1998 season than 1999's meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something happened to Troy, we'd have a player who not only
could protect us from losing the game, but someone whose unique
skills could win the game,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   A QUICK DOWNFALL
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham won a lot of games in 1998, the year Minnesota
practically rewrote the NFL record book. He played target practice
with Cris Carter and a young man named Randy Moss, the runaway
choice for Rookie of the Year honors. Despite missing the first two
games of the season, Cunningham threw an amazing 34 touchdown
passes, averaging 270 yards passing a game.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham was the toast of Minneapolis after the Vikings came
within one field goal of representing the NFC in the Super Bowl.
That hardly diminished the stature of the Vikings' leader, who
resurrected a career that had many peaks and few valleys during 10
seasons in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   If 1998 was an indication, 1999 would certainly bring more
fortune to Minnesota and more fame to Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings broke from the gate at 2-4, with Cunningham
struggling. He was benched after Minnesota was shut out in the
first half of the seventh game, and would never return. With Jeff
George playing well in the second half of the season, Cunningham
was left to kick Gatorade cups on the stadium floor, quietly
pondering what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Why was the MVP pulled so quickly?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still searching for the answer to that,'' Cunningham said
during a 103-degree afternoon. ``I just think maybe it was God's
will for me to be in Dallas. I can go out and ask (Vikings coach)
Dennis (Green), but he might not have the solution or the reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, 37, speaks with a calm, soothing tone when he
reflects on those troubling times. He says he holds no animosity,
but his piercing eyes suggest there are unsettled issues that might
never be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Again, what happened last year?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, offensive coordinator and Cunningham favorite
Brian Billick left Minnesota to become the head coach of the
Baltimore Ravens. When the ship began to sink in '99, no one wanted
to save him from drowning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, I think if Brian had been there with me last
year, I don't think I'd have been sitting down,'' Cunningham told
the Minneapolis Star Tribune last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The finger got pointed a lot of ways,'' he said this week.
``I'm sure some of it was my fault since so much was expected of
our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST FIT
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham had no intention of retiring this year, not after his
MVP trophy had been blemished with humility. Detroit and Tampa Bay
called him. Detroit's Charlie Batch is injured, and Tampa Bay
quarterback Shaun King remains an NFL neophyte who has not proven
himself during a full season. Certainly someone of Cunningham's
caliber would look good in a Lions or Buccaneers jersey.
</P>
<P>
   He said no to both teams.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, he said, has a better chance to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has great coaches, first of all,'' Cunningham said.
``They have a great owner. Jerry wants to win. That the No. 1 thing
for him. It's not the money thing. He just wants to be successful
at whatever he does. That flows down from him to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only can Dallas be a playoff contender again, Cunningham
believes the Cowboys are comparable to the 1998 Vikings who were
considered the best team in football before falling to Atlanta in
the NFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have had the most powerful offense in the history of
the league, but this team has a more rounded offense,'' he said.
``Every position here is stacked. It makes a big difference because
when backups have to play, they have to go in and get the job
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham enters camp as the No. 2 quarterback, an insurance
policy for Aikman, whose history of concussions makes him
vulnerable for another. In Aikman's 11 seasons, he has played in
all 16 games just three times.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman still gets the majority of snaps in practice and aims for
starting wideouts Joey Galloway and Rocket Ismail. Cunningham,
whose improvisational skills makes him ill-suited for the Cowboys'
timing-based offense, has thrown to the likes of Chris Brazzell and
Jeff Ogden.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cunningham is an icon to many of the young faces in Cowboys
camp. Many of the current players remember him as one of the
league's most exciting players, someone whose daring moves became
the rage of the league. Someone who was MVP just two years ago must
have something left in the tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Randall steps into the huddle, he automatically deserves
respect because of what he's accomplished,'' said Cowboys assistant
Bill Bates, who played against Cunningham many times during his
15-year career in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what Randall has done against us,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Cunningham is with the Cowboys. Dallas is one
city where his desire and talent were never questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
