<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7085 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-COPYSIDE-AZR &LR;      07-19 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPYSIDE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-COPYSIDE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DECENTRALIZED FREENET OPEN TO EXPLOITATION(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING: Sidebar to COPYRIGHT) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By MONTY PHAN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ian Clarke's vision is the entertainment industry's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   In developing a program called Freenet, designed to allow the
anonymous, free trade of information, Clarke was hoping to help
further the notion that free speech is fundamental by giving
residents of restrictive countries a tool to speak their minds
without fear of censorship.
</P>
<P>
   It is a decentralized network - no one controls it, so no one
can shut it down. Napster is centralized; shut it down, and the
network goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   Like other file-sharing programs, Freenet (available at
freenet.sourceforge.net) lacks the ability to distinguish between a
top-secret CIA file and a dog photo. This means that if users want
to exploit Freenet by trading copyrighted material (or even child
pornography), they can. No one controls Freenet; no one can stop
them.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke says that it wasn't designed for that, but that he can't
do anything about it. After all, Freenet was built to resist
attempts to remove information from it. But it also was designed so
that the most requested information remains in the network.
Information few are interested in - say, an anonymous missive about
your controlling boss - will die out, replaced by other files.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if the entertainment industry suffers, Clarke fails
to sound that broken up about it. His opinion is that technology
will improve to the point that it will be impossible to control
what kind of information is shared. All information will be free;
nothing will be copyrighted.
</P>
<P>
   Absurd? Perhaps. But look at Napster: Even though such irate
bands as Metallica have identified users who trade copyrighted
files, its popularity persists, despite the threat - however remote
- of legal action. Gnutella, a less-popular program that, like
Freenet, is decentralized, offers near-anonymity. So what happens
when a program achieves perfect anonymity?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be that the idea that you can kind of prevent
people from copying and sharing information will just seem
ridiculous,'' Clarke says from his London home.
</P>
<P>
   Censorship is a hot topic for Clarke, especially now that the
British government is considering laws allowing police to view
private e-mails. As countries attempt to legislate the Internet,
Freenet could be a way to skirt those laws.
</P>
<P>
   But although Freenet allows for anonymity, such technology as
digital signatures could allow for some type of accountability. It
would be comparable to receiving a series of anonymous letters all
in distinguishable handwriting; the person is recognizable, but not
identifiable. That's important in differentiating between a dingbat
and Deep Throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody posts allegations without any kind of support,
then anyone who believes it is really kind of an idiot,'' Clarke
says. ``Why not let the people reading it decide what's the truth?
You can't really trust any information that is completely
anonymous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HAMPTONS-DAYWORKERS-N     07-19 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMPTONS-DAYWORKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 TRADESPEOPLE KEEP THE HAMPTONS HUMMING 
</HEADLINE>
   By TRACIE ROZHON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. _ On a hectic Friday morning, the first stop
for the white plumbing van was . . . the beach. ``Sometimes it
helps to pay a visit to the waves before I start dealing with the
people,'' said Bob Donohue, one of a handful of veteran
air-conditioner repairmen in the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   But on this particular morning, Donohue found no time for
reflection.
</P>
<P>
   There was a knock on the van's door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, but are you a plumber?'' asked a kind-looking
middle-aged man, out walking his springer spaniel. ``I'm having a
problem with the _ what do you call it? _ thermostat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, this must be summer. And in the summer here, it is not the
homeowners who reign. Underpinning almost every house is a network
of people, a veritable phalanx of well-paid but indefatigable
workers. These are the heroes of the Hamptons: the air-conditioning
workers, the electricians, the rose pruners, the hedge trimmers,
the house watchers and the rest of the men and women who keep every
weathered shingled cottage _ owned or rented _ ticking away like a
gold Rolex.
</P>
<P>
   Tree man, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have a tree guy,'' said Jeffrey Fisher, the
homeowner who knocked on Donohue's van door. ``Then there's the
hot-pot person _ the one who plants your pots on the terrace. Now,
who else do we have? The plumber, the boiler man, the house
watcher, the house cleaner, the pest control guy, the lawn mower
guy, the turf guy, the irrigation guy, the pool person and the pool
heater person.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher questions the competence of a plumbing company that did
recent work, but he's afraid to say anything negative. The savvy
homeowners know that money can't buy everything, even in the
Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   ``One very well-known man arrived here to find his air
conditioning wasn't working,'' said Diane Saatchi, a local real
estate broker. ``He called up the air-conditioning man and started
screaming. When he stopped, the repairman, without raising his
voice, said: `Listen, pal, there are hundreds of millionaires like
you out here. There are only two air-conditioning repairmen.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then the repairman hung up, she said. ``He didn't need the
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Nan Noel, a jacqueline-of-all-trades, often turns down clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just this week, someone called who had been referred by
someone else and asked if I could come over,'' said Noel, who
arranges for house cleaning, car washing, dog grooming and just
about anything a lord or lady of the manor could need. ``These
people wanted me to stay there _ right then _ while the movers
came.'' She declined the job. ``I could see in advance what they
would expect. These people had no boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, however, she provides a big chunk of the good life.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman is an editor in New York and she doesn't get here
until 2 or 3 in the morning; she likes to sleep until 11:30
Saturday morning so I never disturb her,'' said Noel, who, among
other things, boards the editor's dog during the week. ``But on
Saturday afternoon, I arrive with her dog, her newspaper _ and her
strawberry muffins.''
</P>
<P>
   Noel charges $35 an hour for her own time, and works mainly with
regular clients. Then she passes on the charges of the maintenance
people she employs. Hamptonites like their grass to be perfect.
</P>
<P>
   One oceanfront cottage was surrounded by swaths of ferns and
naturalistic plantings. But there was something odd _ too perfect _
about the lawn on the hillside. ``It's all sod,'' said Craig Socia,
a garden designer, who supervises the maintenance of 33 houses in
the Hamptons. ``We had it laid this spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Just mowing the lawn on the most palatial of these estates can
run $500 a week, Socia said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory P. Kirwan, a partner in Casual Water, charges $49.95 a
week to service an average pool. ``When I visit my parents in
Florida, my relatives in Arizona, I check out the prices,'' he
said. ``For what we charge for one week here, they can get a whole
month of service there.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, after the quick stop to look at the waves, Donohue,
an avid surfer, headed for his first service call.
</P>
<P>
   There, up a curving gravel driveway, stood the shingled home of
Steve and Diane Jacobson. Steve Jacobson came out of the side door
to greet Donohue, who works for Schenck Fuels here. Donohue bustled
into the basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a problem in the basement and I was trying to find the
fuse box,'' Jacobson explained. ``And I walked through some water.
A puddle, on the floor.'' He laughed. ``There's no way the city
slicker can do without these guys. It'd be better to sell the house
and buy a condominium. This company responds right away, but most
of the time, they say, `See you in two weeks.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the basement, Donohue adjusted the thermostat on the boiler,
which someone had turned up to 240 degrees. ``It wasn't me,''
Jacobson insisted, with a laugh. ``There are spider webs down
there; it's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, eight Hamptons houses sold for $2 million to $3
million in the first three months, according to Cook Pony Farm Real
Estate. In the first three months of 2000, 20 sold in that price
range.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new homeowners are first-time owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so young,'' Noel said. ``One woman said: `What do I
know about a house? The last place I lived was a dorm.'''
</P>
<P>
   What was the problem?
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a fly in her refrigerator,'' Noel said.
</P>
<P>
   The young homeowner _ she just closed on her house last week _
was anxious. ``She also was saying her fiance couldn't sleep in the
bedroom because it was bright. Well, any hardware store sells
blackout blinds. But how would she know that?'' Noel said. ``I
asked her where the entrance to the basement was and she said: `I
don't know. Is there a basement?'''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the maintenance people dislike is homeowners who try
to do their pools _ or anything else _ themselves. ``One client
tried to do it himself,'' Noel said. ``And he stored all these
chlorine tablets in the basement; it says right on the bucket
you're supposed to store it outside.''
</P>
<P>
   After struggling with possibly toxic fumes and an unopenable
plastic bucket, she gave up and told him to hire a pool service.
``It's people like him who give customers a bad name,'' she said.
``Here he is trying to save $1.50 on this multimillion home.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirwan, the pool man, said he gets most of his angriest calls
when new homeowners receive their first bill. ``They call up
screaming, because they've gotten a bill for $500 to open their
pool,'' he said. ``They don't realize how many chemicals we use.
They think we're making money on all these chemicals and they don't
really need them.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a cup of coffee at the Golden Pear here, Rodney Herrlin and
Christopher Schenck, whose great-grandfather started Schenck Fuels,
assessed the ways things have changed. ``It used to be that we knew
a lot of our customers, 25 or 30 years,'' Schenck said. ``Now, it's
two or three years, they're selling their homes and moving; they
aren't setting their roots. It used to be, you'd say, `You need a
new furnace,' and they didn't ask why and run around getting other
estimates.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's customers are apt to be more impatient, too. ``It gets a
little vicious,'' Herrlin said. ``Especially in the midst of the
summer. People just keep calling: `I called 25 minutes ago and
nobody's here yet.'''
</P>
<P>
   But those people may be cutting their own throats,
maintenance-wise.
</P>
<P>
   They may not know that it takes several seasons to cultivate a
crew. ``Until the tradespeople know you're going to pay the bills
and not be abusive to their staff,'' Saatchi, the real estate
agent, explained, ``they may be a little tough to find out here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
