<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE CRIME FIGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An important but frequently overlooked factor in the nationwide
decline in crime over the past few years has been the corresponding
decline in the unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive policing and long prison sentences get most of the
attention. Credit is also belatedly being given to the often heroic
and usually unheralded crime-fighting efforts of local groups and
individuals in poor neighborhoods, and to the many young people who
have stepped back from the lure of drugs and antisocial behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have a study by a pair of Washington economists that
appears to confirm a point that has seemed like common sense to a
lot of people, but that politicians have never pushed vehemently
enough: A job is one of the most effective weapons in the nation's
crime-fighting arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just common sense but longstanding economic theory that
suggests a link between lower rates of joblessness and lower rates
of crime. The new study by the Economic Policy Institute looked at
crime rates and employment statistics in several regions of the
country between 1989 and 1998 and found evidence to support that
theory.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, ``An examination of unemployment, wages,
and crime rates by region shows unemployment and crime rates
falling together, and rising wages and crime rates moving apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking specifically at unemployment rates for young men, the
study found that since 1992 the jobless rate had fallen by at least
four percentage points in each region, with the largest decline in
the Northeast, which is also where crime rates fell most quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the study, Jared Bernstein and Ellen Houston,
wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor market conditions are not, of course, the only or even
necessarily the prime determinant of crime rates. Over the 1990s,
the U.S. sharply increased its expenditures on prisons,
incarcerating a growing number of the population and passing `get
tough' crime prevention legislation. These interventions have
undoubtedly played a large role in lowering crime rates. But the
link between crime and labor market opportunity is too often
ignored in the current policy debate over crime, which focuses
almost solely on longer sentences and prison expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   The people at highest risk for engaging in crime are young men,
primarily from ethnic minority groups, ``with low levels of
education and a weak attachment to the labor market,'' the study
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the overwhelming employment obstacles faced by
individuals in that group, many have found work as a result of the
current long-running economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, in an interview, said, ``As unemployment fell below the
level of 5 percent over the last couple of years, you can see that
real economic opportunities are being expanded for those who are
probably the most disadvantaged low-wage workers in society.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a hunger among Americans everywhere, including the poor
and the otherwise disadvantaged, for meaningful employment. The
benefits to be gained from putting people to work are endless, and
one of those benefits is a safer society.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, Houston and Bernstein felt it was important
when looking at the problem of crime to pay more attention to labor
market policies and the value of employment.
</P>
<P>
   They say in the study, ``The Federal Reserve can play a decisive
role here by focusing on its full-employment mandate with at least
the same fervor it devotes to interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are other issues _ for example, the importance in a
time of unprecedented prosperity of approving a boost in the
minimum wage; and the need for no-nonsense education and training
for low-wage workers, and for ex-criminal offenders, many of whom
are released into communities across America each and every day.
</P>
<P>
   When you consider the factors crucial to building a safe and
secure society, employment is right there at the top. The idea is
to get as many people working for a decent wage as is humanly
possible, rather than searching for excuses as to why this person
can't be paid a living wage and that person can't be allowed to
work at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
