<SLUG> BC-STROGANOFF-THEFAMILY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RISE AND FALL OF RUSSIA'S NOBLEST FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 
 EDS: Accompanies STROGANOFF-EXHIBITION  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By WAYNE LEE GAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were at center stage of Russian life for nearly five
centuries, always willing to devote their immense wealth and
political clout to the Russian Empire. From generation to
generation, right up to the revolution in 1917, the Stroganoffs had
a knack for betting on the winning horse, staying on the good side
of the czar and sensing historical trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were earthy people,'' says the Baroness Helene de
Ludinghausen, the surviving scion of the centuries-old dynasty.
``The most important thing is, they knew how to move and diversify.
... And they helped people who needed it. Every time they built a
village, there was always a school, a church and a hospital,'' she
said in a recent telephone interview with the Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   Like many great families, the Stroganoffs had rough-and-tumble
beginnings. Some sources say they originated in the Moscow region,
but other historians suggest that the Stroganoffs descended from
the semibarbaric Asiatic tribes of eastern Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its genesis, the family showed a talent for wheeling
and dealing as early as the 1300s, and it rose to political
prominence in 1445 when Luka Stroganoff paid the ransom for Prince
Vassily the Dark, who had been captured by the Tatars.
</P>
<P>
   In the 16th century _ about the same time Henry VIII was wading
through his marital difficulties in England _ the Stroganoffs,
savvy and tough, diversified the fortune they had made with
saltworks in northern Russia into ironworks, fur-trading, fishing
and agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
   The Stroganoffs translated their financial clout into political
power by paying for the Russian Empire's first forays into Siberia
_ hiring the infamous bandit Yermak to organize an army of
mercenaries to fight their Tatar cousins _ and in the process
gaining the gratitude of Czar Ivan the Terrible. By 1600, what
would today be called ``Stroganoff Family Enterprises,'' employed
6,000 workers and owned almost everything of value in Russian
Siberia, including 8.5 million acres, held tax-exempt.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th century brought a new heyday for the family. Realizing
that the new capital city of St. Petersburg was where things were
happening and that Russia was becoming more Eurocentric, the
Stroganoffs shed their rural ways, learned French (with the rest of
the Russian upper crust), built a palace and settled into court
life. This was when a clever chef invented a mixture of beef and
spices in a rich sauce and named it for Count Pavel Stroganoff,
ensuring the immortality of the family name in cookbooks and on
menus worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Stroganoffs traveled to Western Europe, where one
temporarily wayward son of the dynasty shocked Catherine the Great
by joining the French Revolution. She called him back to Russia,
where he and his family, the revolutionary bug cured, continued to
build palaces and churches and to collect great art through the
19th century. Despite such opulent living, they were known for
their piety, and for a tendency to urge reform and modernization of
the political system while remaining firmly entrenched in the power
structure.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stroganoff luck finally ran out, as did the luck of the
entire imperial ruling class, when the guns of revolution swept
across Russia in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their friend the czar and his family, who were fatally
shot in a basement in Siberia, the Stroganoffs managed to escape
Russia with their lives and a few items that could fit in
suitcases, leaving behind their vast land holdings, the palaces and
churches they had built and their fabulous art collection in St.
Petersburg, which the communist government dispersed in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   Baroness Ludinghausen's mother, Xenia, fled from St. Petersburg
by train in 1919 at age 7 with her mother, Princess Sonia, and
escaped from southern Russia in a boat supplied by the queen of
Italy. As with most Russian aristocrats, there was no secret Swiss
bank account. ``Former generals ended up working as chauffeurs,''
the baroness says.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the heirs of one of the world's great dynasties, stripped
of their wealth and privilege, did what they had always done: They
moved ahead, and went to work. Born in Paris in 1942, during the
German occupation, Baroness Ludinghausen spent much of her
childhood in Brazil, where her father worked for an American
company. She graduated from a high school in Denver, and currently
works as director of salons at Yves Saint Laurent Couture in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, with the tables once again turned in Russia and
communism toppled, Baroness Ludinghausen founded the Stroganoff
Foundation for the reunification and preservation of the Stroganoff
artistic legacy. She raised the money for the foundation not from
any family fortune, which is gone forever, but from leading tours
to St. Petersburg and from donations. Because of her efforts, the
name Stroganoff once again means more in the cultural lexicon than
noodles and beef. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``Encyclopedia Britannica;'' ``Stroganoff: the Palace
and Collections of a Russian Noble Family;'' ``The Romanovs,'' by
W. Bruce Lincoln; ``A History of Russia,'' 4th edition, by Nicholas
V. Riasanovsky.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
