<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7092 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-STROGANOFF-EXHIBITION     07-19 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROGANOFF-EXHIBITION-2400(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIMBELL EXHIBIT RECALLS THE GLORY DAYS OF A FABLED RUSSIAN FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 
 EDS: Has a sidebar, STROGANOFF-THEFAMILY  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ANDREW MARTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Stroganoff school technique.
</P>
<P>
   Icons are not the only vestiges of the Stroganoffs' religious
interior design to shine in the exhibit. What one might dismiss as
prosaic, mid-17th-century embroidered textiles in fact encapsulate
a luxuriant style of gold and silken interlocking threads forming
distinctive geometric shapes. Deserving close attention is ``The
Entombment,'' a shroud dating from 1592 that measures 6 feet long
and is a model of highly involved needlework. And as for overt
luxury in the unexpected guise of a textile, little can compare
with the bejeweled ``Our Lady of Kazan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stroganoffs' collection of religious objects is hardly
restricted to those reflecting the Orthodox church. Mining the
medieval periods of France and Italy, the Stroganoffs emerged with
such startling works as a casket-shaped, 12th-century Limoges
``reliquary chasse'' to hold and display religious relics, with its
carefully engraved metalwork and Romanesque relief. These Limoges
works are easily matched in quality by two Italian objects, one a
13th-century crook of ivory, carved into the shape of a ferocious
dragon's head, and the other a 15th-century gilt and rock-crystal
cross that would have led any procession proudly. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a preface to the Stroganoffs' impressive holdings of
masterpiece paintings, many of which once formed the central focus
of the Stroganoff Palace interior in St. Petersburg, the exhibit
offers a series of paintings depicting the palace's picture
gallery. Many of the watercolor works, done by the famed architect
and interior designer Andrei Voronikhin and others, are something
of a letdown, in part because of their surfeit of detail.
</P>
<P>
   What the watercolors do accomplish is to whet one's appetite for
the real masterworks of the exhibition. This is ``Stroganoff'' at
its most inspiring. The two portraits by Anthony Van Dyck hypnotize
through their capture of personality. ``Portrait of a Young Man''
grasps the innocent glint in the eye of what may be a Spanish
aristocrat, his lacy collar spread like a butterfly's diaphanous
wing over his black coat. But it is Van Dyck's ``Portrait of
Nicolaas Rockox'' that is a miniapotheosis of Flemish portraiture.
Van Dyck has planted a slightly perturbed expression on the
subject's otherwise implacable face, framed by the classic
accordion ruffle of a high collar over a jet-black tunic imbued
with a velvet texture.
</P>
<P>
   In Luca Giordano's ``The Battle of Lapiths and Centaurs,'' the
exhibit has a master canvas that all but leaps off the wall with
its melee pitting salvation against perdition. Acquired by
Alexander Stroganoff, this 17th-century work roils humanity with
mythic centaurs whose sense of anarchy must be quelled by arriving
deities. The painting splits a viewer's attention, forcing one to
stare at the brawl on Earth even as one looks skyward toward the
celestial intervention riding on a chariot of clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Sergeievich Stroganoff (1823-1911) felt an inexorable tug
toward two works by Sandro Botticelli, completed in 1500, that
personify so much of the painter's ecclesiastic leanings. ``Saint
Jerome'' and ``Saint Dominic'' are both models of moral rectitude,
with one penitently kneeling, his roseate robe gathered in one
hand, while the other subject's gaze is aimed at the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Alexander Stroganoff's predilection for 17th-century
French masterworks, the exhibition also contains some powerfully
expansive canvases from Claude Lorrain and Nicolas Poussin.
Lorrain's ``Landscape With Dancers'' spins a buoyant mood among
friends set against a pastoral setting rendered with surgical
precision. Poussin's ``Rest on the Flight Into Egypt'' bursts with
biblical symbolism set against a meticulously stage-managed
classical backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   As a welcome relief from the mammoth stage sets of these French
works, ``Stroganoff'' presents Antoine Watteau's ``La Boudeuse,''
with its pointillist accumulation of filigreed detail devoted to a
silken gown and veined leaves. Another subtle treat for the eyes is
the delicately fetching ``Self-Portrait'' by Marie-Louise Elisabeth
Vigee-Lebrun, one of the art world's most groundbreaking female
painters and a specially appointed Stroganoff family portraitist. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the exhibit's examples of classical
antiquities, collected by the peripatetic Alexander Stroganoff on
his travels to Italy, some tend more toward models of accomplished
restoration than unique examples of classical art. However, the
Stroganoff's fifth- and sixth-century terra-cotta Etruscan works
are exceptional, with one sixth-century vase cover notable for its
carefully engraved headdress and the expression of bonhomie on the
good citizen's visage.
</P>
<P>
   Showing little geographic parochialism, the Stroganoffs played
an active role in the emerging popularity of pre-Columbian art in
the mid-1800s. The collection thus includes an exceptional Mexican
jade mask dating from somewhere between the fifth and the eighth
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Not stopping at Mexican art, the Stroganoffs felt drawn to the
adroit use of enamel in Chinese art. The collection includes a
series of robin's-egg-blue vases dating from the early 16th
century, all festooned in red and white blossoms and gilt. Although
a tad redundant, this style of Chinese decorative arts was
certainly versatile, as it was also applied to an altar set and the
everyday hat stand.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, it may be the relatively underexplored work of the
French artist Hubert Robert that serves as the best summation of
the Stroganoff exhibit's representation of the family role as
patron, cultural taste arbiter, and integrator of monumental art
into a domestic setting. Alexander Stroganoff commissioned not one
but six architectural landscapes from Robert. The result is a
series of works transporting the viewer to St. Peter's in Rome, to
an obelisk encircled by a classical sculptural arcade, and to
verdant and rocky vistas featuring cypresses and waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Each one of Robert's windows into a classical past is 10 feet
tall. Each one is an ultimate example of how great art could
elevate a palace interior to near-mythic levels of refinement. It
was the way the Stroganoffs habitually decorated their lives and
the cultural landscape of their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
