<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7093 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-STROGANOFF-EXHIBITION     07-19 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROGANOFF-EXHIBITION-2400(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIMBELL EXHIBIT RECALLS THE GLORY DAYS OF A FABLED RUSSIAN FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 
 EDS: Has a sidebar, STROGANOFF-THEFAMILY  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ANDREW MARTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A curious little paradox resides at the core
of the Kimbell Art Museum's latest exhibition, ``Stroganoff: The
Palace and Collections of a Russian Noble Family.'' Massive in
scope, even daunting in the variety of works displayed,
``Stroganoff'' still generates an improbable glow of domestic
approachability.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, the ``home'' of this collection is
definitely a palace. How could it not be, considering that 2,000
works were whittled down to the 230 on display for the exhibit,
which will end October 1. And considering that those pieces include
icons and textiles, Greek and Roman antiquities, palace
furnishings, old-master paintings, Middle Eastern silver, medieval
crosses from Italy, pre-Columbian objects from Mexico and examples
of Chinese decorative works?
</P>
<P>
   Such varied art objects accomplish two distinct goals for the
exhibit. On the one hand, by dint of their almost uniformly
superior quality (many of them justify that shopworn descriptive,
``masterwork''), the Stroganoff pieces are marvels of their
mediums. In addition, the exhibit stands as a lavishly decorated
scrapbook, recounting the Stroganoffs' involved family history, one
filled with a nonpareil legacy of wealth, collecting and
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   History must linger over any tour of this family's riches. The
Stroganoffs were the Medicis of Russia, spending 500 years
accumulating individual fortunes based on that most primary of
minerals _ salt _ only to translate that business acumen into a
private collection of such vast, eclectic taste that it easily
competed with that of the czars. But perhaps the exhibit's ultimate
mark is that it demonstrates how a single family can become
synonymous with what it accumulated, and how this family and this
vast store of art helped mold the cultural development of an
empire.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, visitors are immediately greeted by twin
portraits of Catherine and Peter the Great, along with a delicately
etched tea service and a heavily inlaid wooden chest. This
introductory gallery sets the tone of the entire exhibit,
attempting to mitigate the staidness of a museum by replicating a
vestibule to a private residence.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit makes it all but unavoidable to receive a crash
course in Russian imperial politics and Stroganoff family lore.
This is either fascinating or tedious, depending upon one's level
of curiosity. Although it's tantalizing to inspect the minute
Cyrillic script that forms an exceptionally rare charter signed by
Ivan the Terrible, the subsequent painting of the Cossack leader
Yermak, and the spiked helmet Yermak presumably wore, pale as
arresting works of art.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic furnishings will soon bring you back to life,
however; little can top two works that act as robust homages to the
baroque ideal. The Stroganoffs selected from the French atelier of
Jean-Francois Dubut a desk that seems to erupt in floral detail.
Mother-of-pearl and ivory of varying pigments frolic among the
various shadings of wood inlay as polychromatic flora sprout along
the desk's front.
</P>
<P>
   But this ``secretary'' seems monastically ascetic compared with
a nearby cabinet that is all baroque flourishes. An amalgam of
tortoiseshell and tiny sculptures wrought from pliant silver, the
cabinet is painted the kind of Caribbean green that immediately
distinguishes it from its Danish counterparts of the same epoch.
</P>
<P>
   The Stroganoff exhibit successfully links not just the
masterworks but even the smallest home objects to the family's
storied history of collecting. Alexander Sergeievich Stroganoff's
(1733-1811) tastes, for example, occasionally ran to delicate
beauty over clunky, if pragmatic, form. Some of his favorite
snuffboxes are thus layered in enamel and pearls and frame
Lilliputian glass-covered gouache paintings. One Parisian snuffbox
even has his involved plans to renovate many of his family's
properties incorporated into its design.
</P>
<P>
   On a larger scale are the exhibit's palace tabletop designs,
specifically its decorative stonework; the subtle and the dramatic
live side-by-side. One can bypass the uninspiring gray jasper tray
and vodka cups and fixate on the selection of lapis lazuli
``perfume burners,'' a cushion shape of purple-flecked
cobalt-colored stone cradled by golden dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   But easily one of the most extraordinary examples of stonework
acting as mesmerizing domestic decoration is the ``coupe'' or basin
formed from the emerald-green and black-veined malachite, widely
considered to be Russia's most coveted stone. This great bowl rests
on a tripod of three heavily gilded angels, their feet digging into
an equally imposing bronze stand. This malachite creation remains a
grand piece of decorative art, a felicitous marriage of art and
engineering.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For generations, the Stroganoffs devoted enormous time and
energy to building churches and monasteries almost everywhere they
settled. These places of worship demanded a plethora of
iconography. The exhibit allows one to wade into the gradual
progression of Russian icon artistry, such as the 16th century's
``The Virgin Hodegetria of Smolensk'', a clear precursor to the
Russian iconic style. One can then appreciate the arrival of the
Stroganoff school of icon painting, marked by its groundbreaking
attention to detail, especially of the face and hands. This
burgeoning Stroganoff school is amply represented in a portrait of
``Saint Dmitry the Tsarevich,'' the son of Ivan the Terrible.
Though 5 feet tall, this grand icon doesn't forgo careful
rendering, making it more human, less ideally conceived.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful not to let size considerations influence which pieces
of iconography to examine. The Kimbell should signal its visitors
that four of its smaller icons, ``The Baptism,'' ``The Raising of
Lazarus,'' ``The Entry Into Jerusalem'' and ``The Descent Into
Limbo,'' are exceptional demonstrations of Stroganoff school
technique. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
