<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-UTENN-WHISTLEBLOWER-2     07-19 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTENN-WHISTLEBLOWER-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE WHISTLE-BLOWER WORRIES ABOUT HER FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.J., Ore., Ill.)  (Eds.: Buuck in 2nd graf if 2nd take is cq) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The whistle-blower finds comfort in her
office these days, surrounded by books about Renaissance drama, her
speciality. So long as Linda Bensel-Meyers can keep her mind in the
past, she can forget about the lawsuits against her, the damage to
her marriage, the anger of University of Tennessee officials and
coaches, the threats by local fans who curse her as a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   But she is reminded of the present by the fat leather briefcase
leaning against a leg of her desk. It is stuffed with what she
calls her evidence, the paper trails that always lead back to the
altered grades, ``friendly'' courses and plagiarized papers that
she says the athletic department uses to keep varsity players
eligible.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the evidence is being used against her; one suit
implies she has publicly released confidential student information,
which she denies. After some five years of being ignored by the
administration, she talked to ESPN last September after it began
its own investigation of the athletic tutoring system.
</P>
<P>
   Four football players were suspended for a game pending the
school's investigation, and Bensel-Meyers became a well-known
pariah on campus. Students taunt her, teachers turn away. She says
her office has been broken into, mostly as intimidation, she
thinks. She is sitting now with her back to the office window that
overlooks the 107,000-seat football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never feel sorry for myself,'' she says, just a bit too
stoutly, ``because I am responsible for my own decisions. I am not
a victim. I hate it when people look at me with pity. Sometimes,
however, I despair.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the righteousness of this 47-year-old Methodist church
organist pops up. ``It is hard for one good person to live among
those who are not good, and to try to make the right choices,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers is not alone these days as the American
Association of University Professors and another national group of
faculty members convened last year at Drake University in Iowa and
considered reforms in intercollegiate sports. The Drake Group, in
particular, has declared that big-time college sports is basically
a corrupting influence on the academic mission of the university.
And the Rutgers 1000, a group of professors and students, is
calling for that university to divest itself of varsity sports.
</P>
<P>
   At Tennessee, a 44,000-student university, most members of the
administration and the athletic department who speak on the record
say Bensel-Meyers has made all the wrong choices, attacking a
source of state pride. The Volunteers were national football
champions two seasons ago. And, as officials point out, the NCAA
conducted an investigation for months on her charges and found no
violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campus is just weary of reading about all her charges,''
said the university president, J. Wade Gilley. ``We've had nine, 10
investigations in the 11 months I've been here, by the faculty
senate, the conference, the National Collegiate Athletic
Association, the Federal Bureau of Investigation _ what have I left
out? _ and nothing was found that violated rules or laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilley says he thinks Bensel-Meyers may have an agenda, a ``big,
pregnant idea,'' about de-emphasizing college sports. If that's it,
he chuckles, then there's no better place to start than at a place
that ``epitomizes the system, like Notre Dame or Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Her voice is low. ``This is not my cause,'' she says. She talks
into her hand. Her eyes rarely make contact. ``I'm a company
person. I thought I'd be here forever. I went through channels. But
my options have been limited because no one would listen to what
I've been saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when they did hear me, the attitude was, just fail the
athlete who plagiarized. How can I do that, when the plagiarism was
institutional, when the athlete thinks he's supposed to turn in a
paper written by one of the hired tutors? How can I sacrifice some
poor guy who bought into the dream just like me, to get off the
farm.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers left the family chicken farm in Pendleton, Ore.,
30 years ago for a scholarship to the University of Chicago. She
always loved sports, she says, the third of four children who all
became teachers. She roughhoused with her brothers. She ran track
in high school and continued to play basketball and volleyball at
the University of Oregon, where her Ph.D. dissertation was on ``The
Duchess of Malfi,'' a bloodthirsty revenge tragedy, written by John
Webster circa 1613.
</P>
<P>
   At Tennessee, where she began her first tenure-track teaching
job in 1986, she says she has rarely missed a Volunteers football
game on television. But she has never taken her three teen-age sons
to the stadium because she is afraid of crowds and heights.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, she became director of composition, a job she loved,
she said, because the required first-year writing course gave her a
chance to shape a curriculum that would teach critical thinking and
``empower'' the many ``provincial, religious, concrete thinkers,''
who, as she had been, were the first generation in their families
to attend college. She borrowed from the great books courses
created at Chicago and from her own scholarship. She sees parallels
between the Age of Gutenberg, when the printing press helped
replace ethical reasoning with scientific thought, and the Age of
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Among her early tasks was hiring and training the tutors who
would help athletes, particularly male football and basketball
players. Slowly, over the years, she began to realize, she says,
that the athletes were being exploited by a system that did not
deliver a real education in return for the millions of dollars the
university made from their time and energy. Tutors came back with
stories of being sexually harassed by athletes, not to mention
having to write their term papers.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers, with access to transcripts, began to notice
patterns of grades being altered, of clusters of unusually high
grades for athletes in certain courses, of special privileges. She
thought there was abuse in the labeling of certain athletes as
having disabilities, which could excuse them from having to read or
write. She began to send memos to her superiors. She was ignored.
She began sending e-mail messages, first to foreign colleagues whom
she had met at Renaissance conferences, then with almost anyone who
seemed to understand and would respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda is naive, a straight arrow who never understood the
power she came up against,'' says Jeffrey Kovac, a 51-year-old
chemistry professor and one of Bensel-Meyers' few public supporters
at Tennessee. Last week, he quietly announced a legal defense fund
to which faculty could contribute anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
