A7096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-UTENN-WHISTLEBLOWER-2     07-19 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTENN-WHISTLEBLOWER-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 KNOXVILLE, Tenn.: contribute anonymously. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Most faculty are cynical about sports,'' Kovac said.
``Athletes get away with murder, so what, just let me concentrate
on neutron scattering. But I've also been a professional soccer
referee for 20 years, and I've always thought, all we have is our
integrity and a whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovac's fund-raising is welcome news to David L. Buuck, a
graduate of Tennessee and its law school who finds himself shunned,
as well as underpaid, while defending Bensel-Meyers. The libel suit
against ESPN.com and a former head of the tutoring service, by a
former player and a former tutor, does not even name Bensel-Meyers,
but she had promised to pay for any of her teachers who were sued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't let them be punished because someone's trying to get
at me,'' she said. ``I worry about my seven doctoral students,
working on dissertations, mostly on the Renaissance. What if after
all this, my letters of recommendation are poison?''
</P>
<P>
   An injunction to keep his records private was filed by Spencer
Riley, the center on last year's football team who is now trying
out for the Buffalo Bills. The university's failure to defend her
along with itself sent a chill through the faculty; would this be a
precedent to punish anyone out of favor who became a target of
litigation?
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers finds herself more and more isolated, with fewer
responsibilities. She thinks she may be fired. She is afraid of
going to her car at night in the campus underground garage. Her
children hear remarks about her at school. Her husband, who thinks
she is hurting the family, rarely talks to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for my kids to see what I'm doing,'' she
says, not sounding absolutely certain. ``Or it will be someday. We
can't teach people abuse of the law and not expect it will lead to
more crime. We're losing values in this country, and the university
may be the only place left to preserve these values.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to teach kids there's a reason to be on earth and it's
not just grabbing off pleasure. I believe if people have all the
information they'll choose the right thing. That's why I talk to
the media, why I send out all these e-mails. But then I have this
image of myself doing cartwheels along the edge of a cliff,
blindfolded. I think I'll be all right as long as I don't see where
I'm going.''
</P>
