u f BC-FORD-EARNINGS-NYT     07-19 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD BLAMES ONE-TIME CHARGES FOR QUARTERLY LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ The Ford Motor Co. said Wednesday that brisk
sales of luxury cars and sport utility vehicles and growing profits
from auto loans and leases lifted its operating earnings in the
second quarter, but a pair of one-time charges caused the automaker
to post its first quarterly loss since the fourth quarter of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the one-time charges, which were announced last week,
Ford's after-tax earnings from operations rose 8.5 percent, to
$2.69 billion. Earnings per share rose 10 percent, to $2.20,
beating by 12 cents the consensus forecast of financial analysts,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   After relying heavily on profit from sport utility vehicle sales
in the United States over the last several years, Ford managed a
somewhat more diverse blend of earnings in the second quarter.
Strong sales of the Focus small car, the Taurus and Mercury Sable
midsize sedans and the Mercury Grand Marquis large sedan meant that
cars accounted for a growing percentage of overall profit, said
Henry Wallace, the chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Credit, a wholly owned subsidiary that issues auto loans
and leases, posted a 16 percent gain in profit, to $388 million,
continuing a turnaround that began late last year. And Ford's
results improved in Latin America and East Asia, although profit
eroded at the company's European operations.
</P>
<P>
   But the strong operating earnings were more than offset by
one-time charges totaling $3.27 billion. Ford took a $1.02 billion
charge for writing down the value of many factories and buildings
in Europe to reflect their actual value and for covering the cost
of early retirement incentives and other programs to reduce
employment in Europe, where Ford's market share has been falling.
Ford also took a one-time charge of $2.25 billion for the spin-off
on June 28 of the Visteon Corp., its auto parts division, because
Visteon's parts factories had been carried on Ford's books at a far
greater value than the market value of the division when it became
an independent company.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace contended that the Visteon charge was purely a
bookkeeping change that did not reflect on the company's financial
health and had no cash implications. ``The Visteon thing is just a
paperwork exercise to get our books in order,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Including the one-time charges, Ford reported a loss of $577
million, compared with a profit of $2.34 billion a year earlier,
when Ford's only one-time charge was $146 million related to the
acquisition of Volvo Car.
</P>
<P>
   Ford shares rose 50 cents Wednesday to close at $47.438, even as
broad market measures fell.
</P>
<P>
   The company is wallowing in cash, reporting that it had $25.56
billion in cash and marketable securities. It plans to distribute
$10 billion of that cash to shareholders next month in a complex
recapitalization of the company. Though some institutional
investors have suggested that the plan is more advantageous to the
Ford family, which holds a special class of stock, than to other
shareholders, Wallace rejected the criticism, saying that the plan
was fair and would not be reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   The robust results announced on Wednesday by Ford Credit
confirmed the growing perception in Detroit that the lending
division has recovered from its difficulties two years ago, when
decades of profit growth came to an abrupt halt. Ford Credit, like
many other companies in the auto-leasing business, overestimated in
the mid-1990s how much money it could make by selling vehicles
returned by customers at the end of their leases.
</P>
<P>
   In response, it created its own system for predicting the value
of automobiles at the end of their leases, instead of relying on
published figures. The lending subsidiary's executives said in
interviews Wednesday that the problems of the mid-1990s had been
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know a lot more than we did then,'' said Elizabeth Acton,
the chief financial officer of Ford Credit. ``We have developed
much more sophisticated computer modeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Lapidus, an auto analyst at Goldman Sachs, said that the
Federal Reserve's repeated increases in short-term interest rates
over the last year had hurt other auto lenders, making Ford
Credit's improvement particularly impressive. ``It was a good
result, especially with rates going up,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
