<HEADLINE>
IN GEORGIA, TOUGH FIGHT FOR CRUCIAL U.S. SENATE SEAT LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT14,15,17 were sent July 18 with OBIT-COVERDELL
to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The death of Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., gives
Democrats an unexpected chance to pick up a crucial seat in their
uphill fight to seize control of the Senate this fall, political
analysts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a genius to see this is a very competitive
two-party state, and that this race will be very competitive,''
said Chuck Clay, chairman of the Georgia Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes of Georgia, a Democrat, is expected to appoint a
temporary successor after Coverdell's funeral on Saturday, ensuring
that a Democrat will hold the seat until a special election on Nov.
7. That will at least temporarily cut the Republican majority in
the Senate to 54-46. .
</P>
<P>
   State and national party officials said it would be unseemly to
publicly handicap the special election less than 24 hours after
Coverdell's death from a stroke on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, politicians were already jockeying, however
respectfully, for what Democrats and Republicans agree will be one
of the nation's most hotly contested races. The term runs through
2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hearing from a lot of mourners,'' said one Georgia
Democratic Party aide. ``The phones are ringing off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic and Republican strategists said that with less than
four months to campaign, a candidate must have deep pockets or good
fund-raising skills, statewide name recognition and experience
running a statewide campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious choice for Democrats is the popular former governor,
Zell Miller. But Miller rebuffed repeated entreaties by Democrats,
including President Clinton, to run against Coverdell in 1998.
Democratic aides said Barnes and others will try again to persuade
Miller, who is 68, to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' short list is said also to include Michael Coles, a
cookie mogul who lost to Coverdell in 1998; former Rep. Buddy
Darden, a close friend of Barnes; Rep. Cynthia A. McKinney; Charles
Walker, majority leader of the state Senate; Thurbert Baker, the
Georgia attorney general; and Cathy Cox, the Georgia secretary of
state.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, at least three House members are
potential candidates: Reps. Jack Kingston, Saxby Chambliss and
Johnny Isakson. Isakson, who took Newt Gingrich's House seat when
he stepped down as speaker last year, would seem to be the early
favorite, having run competitive races for Senate and governor in
the 1990s. But he supports abortion rights, and is likely to draw
opposition from the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Waving off speculation that he would run, Isakson said, ``Now is
the time to pay tribute to Paul, not talk about this other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss and Kingston also have potential problems, because
Democrats have a good shot at winning their House seats, Chambliss'
in particular, if they were to run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Neither party holds a majority in Georgia, which is a
battleground state in this year's presidential election. In recent
years, Georgia has been leaning Republican, but Democrats say they
believe they have stanched Republican in-roads, particularly in the
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats control the governor's mansion, both chambers of the
Legislature and one Senate seat, Max Cleland's. But Republicans
hold 8 of the state's 11 seats in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said that Democrats would rally behind
Barnes' choice, but that state Republicans are more fractured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with Republicans is that they don't have a
structure of leadership to unite around a candidate,'' said Merle
Black, a professor of politics at Emory University. ``Democrats may
be able to unite around a single candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Georgia election laws, the winner of a special election
must garner 50 percent of the vote, said the Georgia secretary of
state's office. If no candidate reaches that level, there would be
a runoff shortly after the special election.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington and Atlanta on Wednesday, flags flew at half-staff
at the Capitol buildings. Lawmakers from both parties paid tribute
to Coverdell, and Barnes said that Coverdell's body would lie in
state at the Georgia Capitol on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor Wednesday, Phil Gramm, R-Texas, recalled
going to help Coverdell in his first Senate race in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was doing an event in this dingy old steel mill about
industrial renewal,'' said Gramm, who broke down in tears several
times during his tribute. ``I got up and spoke, and
}Y%9!%M!9MM &QC; %QI%Q &QC; 1% Q1e]!%screened by colonoscopy. One study, with
more than 3,000 patients, is the largest study to date of the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Both studies show that it is not safe to assume that the upper
colon is healthy just because the lower third looks normal. On the
contrary, the studies found that half the patients who had
precancerous lesions in the upper colon had nothing abnormal lower
down. If those patients had had only sigmoidoscopy, they would have
mistakenly been given a clean bill of health and left with
dangerous, undetected growths high in the colon.
</P>
<P>
   The new studies confirm many doctors' suspicions about
sigmoidoscopy, said Dr. Daniel K. Podolsky, chief of
gastroenterology at Massachusetts General Hospital, who wrote an
editorial that accompanied the two articles. Podolsky said many
experts think sigmoidoscopy makes about as much sense as screening
women for breast cancer by doing mammograms on only one breast. He
urged that doctors recommend a colonoscopy to all patients 50 and
older, and that insurers pay for the more thorough procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Medicare and most insurers do not cover colonoscopy
as a screening test, and pay for it only for high-risk patients. A
sigmoidoscopy costs about $200, a colonoscopy $1,200 to $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the insurance industry, Dr. Donald Young,
medical director of the Health Insurance Association of America,
said that the new findings mean that current guidelines for
coverage should be re-examined, but that it would be premature to
change the rules until medical experts can assess all the
information.
</P>
<P>
   Colorectal cancer kills 56,000 Americans a year, and is the
second leading cause of cancer death, after lung cancer. But
despite their potential to save lives, the screening tests for
colon cancer are not popular: All adults 50 and older are
candidates for a screening, but fewer than a third actually are
tested.
</P>
