u s BC-GLF-WMNOPEN-ADVANCE19     07-19 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WMNOPEN-ADVANCE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sorenstam hopes to have the right numbers for the Open
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, ILL. _ A self-proclaimed ``statistical nerd,'' Annika
Sorenstam has all of her scores on a computer. She keeps track of
fairway hits, greens in regulation and putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's just the way I play,'' said Sorenstam, who will
shoot for her third U.S. Women's Open title today at the Merit Club
outside Chicago. ``I have a feeling in my game, but I don't play
with my heart. I don't just go out there and rip the driver hoping
it's going to be okay.''
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish star keeps track of Karrie Webb, too, checking the
Australian's scores. Webb's success spurred her to practice more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always think that she's one of the best,'' Sorenstam said,
``and if you want to be the best, you've got to beat the best.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Sorenstam has won five tournaments, including
the last two on the LPGA Tour. Webb won four of the first five.
Webb leads the point standings, 197 to 175.93, while Sorenstam is
tops on the money list, $985,635 to $963,742. Sorenstam won
back-to-back Opens in 1995-96; Webb's best finish is fourth in four
tries.
</P>
<P>
   So who has the edge at the 55th U.S. Women's Open? It could be a
matter of which way the wind blows. The Merit Club, which at 6,540
yards is the longest U.S. Women's Open course, is notoriously wide
open. And the wind often changes direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as suiting my game,'' Webb said, ``I tend to enjoy
playing in the wind and I think that's going to be a big factor
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb, who is working on her patience, said wind makes the
players concentrate more. ``I think when you have perfect
conditions, you sometimes tend to lose your creativity,'' she said,
``but when it is windy, you really have to think about things.''
</P>
<P>
   In the back of their minds is the largest purse in women's
history, $2.75 million, with $500,000 going to the champion.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam said money doesn't add any extra pressure. In fact,
she's feeling extremely relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the confidence, I have the game, so I'm looking for a
good outcome,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nancy Lopez is still seeking the Women's Open title
that has eluded her, defending champion Juli Inkster thinks another
Georgian, Atlanta's Rosie Jones, could do well here.
</P>
<P>
   Jones agrees. She said that the U.S. Golf Association's methods
of toughening the course by growing the rough, tightening the
fairways and hardening the greens is ``almost like punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added, ``It's right up my alley. The harder the golf
course, the better I play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution HHHHHH Thursday, July 20, 2000
E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
