<SLUG> BC-APPLE-PRODUCTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE TRIES TO KEEP ITS REVIVAL GOING
</HEADLINE>
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Apple Computer Inc. introduced several new products
on Wednesday from a restyled mouse to an overhaul of its popular
iMac desktop computers, whose sales have stagnated in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has enjoyed a remarkable corporate revival in the last
three years under the leadership of Steven P. Jobs, who returned to
take the helm of the company he helped found in 1975. But lately,
industry analysts have pointed to signs that Apple's momentum may
be slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Apple, based in Cupertino, Calif., reported strong quarterly
profits on Tuesday on a 17 percent increase in revenues, though the
increase in sales was less than Wall Street had anticipated. And
sales of its iMac consumer desktops slipped to 450,000 machines in
the June quarter, down from 487,000 in the year-earlier quarter,
according to analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question some people have had about Apple is, Can we keep
it up?'' Jobs, the chief executive, said. ``Well, we've answered
that question here today. Innovation keeps coming from Apple.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcements at the company's biannual Macworld exhibition,
which began on Wednesday in New York, continue the game plan Apple
has followed since Jobs took over in 1997: to combine arresting
industrial design, homegrown hardware and software technology,
competitive pricing and performance.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's software engineers focus not only on the Macintosh
operating system, but also video imaging software. Apple introduced
a version of its iMovie software, which enables people to import
and edit home digital video clips on an iMac or a Power Mac.
</P>
<P>
   During his two-hour presentation, Jobs pointed to iMovie as an
indication of the company's direction and of ``Apple's DNA.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, he said, is ``not just about making spreadsheets
run faster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Apple to stand at the intersection of art and
technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most visually striking innovation was a new line of
Power Macintosh called the G4 Cube. The new model packs the power
of Macintosh machines used by graphics artists and Web designers
into a white plastic cube, eight inches on a side, or about
one-fourth the space of most similarly powered computers.
</P>
<P>
   Apple hopes that the G4 Cube will both expand its sales among
media and arts professionals, as well as encourage home users who
have Apple's more expensive line of iMac to trade up to the G4
Cube.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac line has been refurbished with more aggressive pricing,
faster processors, more storage capacity and new colors including a
white machine _ a color Apple calls ``snow.'' The least expensive
iMac will be priced at $799, or $200 less than the previous
entry-level machine.
</P>
<P>
   Apple also introduced a line of Power Mac desktop machines with
two microprocessors. The dual-processor machines are Apple's
response to concerns that the company could not keep pace with
industry-standard PC's using Intel microprocessors. Apple
demonstrated that its machines far exceeded the performance of the
fastest Intel machines, whose processors have higher raw
calculating speeds measured in megahertz, as both machines did the
same multimedia editing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just megahertz, it's the architecture,'' Jobs
explained.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Apple introduced new versions of all its desktop
machines, which represent 75 percent of its sales. And all of them
will come with a redesigned keyboard and a new elongated computer
mouse, designed by Apple, which uses optical technology for
positioning and requires no mouse pad.
</P>
<P>
   The new mouse's entire housing depresses to click, dispensing
with the traditional mouse button. It replaces the round Apple
mouse, which was derided by reviewers variously as ``an ergonomic
nightmare'' and a ``hockey puck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our failings at Apple, but we do listen to
customers,'' Jobs observed.
</P>
</TEXT>
