<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7114 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WOMAN-CHASER-REVIEW-L     07-19 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMAN-CHASER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A LITTLE STYLE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From way, way out of Nowheresville comes a kicky little indie
item that should warm the heart of any true movie buff. ``The Woman
Chaser'' is a film noir spoof done with real cockeyed commitment to
its eccentric premise, wit that won't quit and a surprisingly
sophisticated understanding of psychosis, Hollywood-style.
</P>
<P>
   That's Hollywood 1960 style, to be precise. Not only set in
tailfin era Tinseltown but shot (in scruffy black-and-white) like
it was actually made then, this satiric adaptation of a hardboiled
novel by Charles Willeford (``Miami Blues'') boasts precise
approximations of the bad acting, loony behavior and hothouse
sexuality B movies of the period traded on, getting the wacky
details down right to the Yma Sumac number on its great retro
soundtrack. The difference is that adapter-director Robinson Devor
is thoroughly conscious of his movie's cheesiness; he actively
aestheticizes it here, while missing no opportunity to let the
audience in on the joke.
</P>
<P>
   That we come to really identify with, and in some ways even
admire, the story's cracked, misanthropic protagonist is perhaps
the best evidence that Devor, who makes his feature film debut with
this project, has a gift for storytelling that's as prodigious as
his sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the filmmaker is incalculably aided by his star,
Patrick Warburton. The actor does a more soulful variation on the
impacted, inelegant hostility that made him so funny as
``Seinfeld's'' Puddy, and it's a marvelous fit for the character.
Richard Hudson is a crooked used car salesman and mother-fixated
misogynist who, suddenly desperate to give his life meaning,
decides to write and direct a movie about a renegade, child-killing
truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Richard has no filmmaking experience barely daunts
him (there's some coy business about writer's block, amusingly
overcome). After all, Mom's umpteenth husband Leo (Paul Malevitz)
is a washed-up director, and Richard's ego and piggishness know no
bounds, so what have those other guys got that he doesn't? What's
really funny is, he apparently has talent, too; we're not shown
much of the movie within the movie, but everyone who sees it thinks
it's quite effectively disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, even, too effective that way. When studio guys start
suggesting ways to make the project more commercial, the
uncompromising artist in Richard comes out.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a pretty sight.
</P>
<P>
   But Mr. Auteur is just one of the character's many unattractive
aspects that Warburton fearlessly displays. Whether browbeating car
lot underlings, oafishly practicing ballet with his teasing mom
(Lynette Bennett) or seducing and abandoning females as diverse as
his teen-age stepsister and a widowed Salvation Army officer,
Warburton lets no shame slip past his mask of deadpan earnest, yet
is somehow convincing when he cries, too.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Richard is also narrating the story for us, and Devor
and Warburton do a masterful job of camouflaging the extent of his
unreliability until the very last scene.
</P>
<P>
   Made for a reported $800,000, ``The Woman Chaser'' did the film
festival circuit before landing the limited commercial release
that's brought it to the Nuart for a week. But don't confuse the
project's modest circumstances with limited achievement or
entertainment value; it's as accomplished a first film as we're
likely to see all year.
</P>
<P>
   And it should certainly be the kookiest. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
The film: ``The Woman Chaser'' (NR; nudity, language, sex). &QL; 
The stars: Patrick Warburton, Paul Malevitz, Emily Newman, Lynette
Bennett, Ernie Vincent. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Robinson Devor, based on
Charles Willeford's novel. Produced by Soly Haim. Released by
Inwood Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 27 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
