<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: IT'S TIME FOR CAPTAIN McENROE 
By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTANDER, Spain _ With daylong sun to stoke his fire and a
coastal breeze to cool his jets, John McEnroe's decision to deploy
himself as a Davis Cup doubles player remains a point in progress,
a mental rally in which his brazen side is attempting to reach the
net for a winning volley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closer to 50-50, maybe a little more,'' McEnroe rated his
chances Wednesday of teaming with somebody, anybody, for Saturday's
doubles against heavily favored Spain, smack dab in the middle of
the Davis Cup semifinals in this beach-endowed resort city.
</P>
<P>
   For the third leg of his maiden voyage as skipper of the
U.S.team, McEnroe finds himself in a typically tormented place,
only without the enviable options to hit his way out. He has no
Pete Sampras, no Andre Agassi and no fountain of youth from which
to drink.
</P>
<P>
   This may not be The Perfect Storm that Captain McEnroe finds
himself in. It could be worse, much less dramatic, a topspin
torture under a broiling sun on thick, red clay. It could be death
by indifference, with only Ma and Pa McEnroe, and maybe brother
Patrick, caring enough to watch back home.
</P>
<P>
   From the U.S. point of interest in sporting events playing out
in Europe this week, this Davis Cup event can rate no better than
third, behind the unparalleled golfer and the inspirational biker.
McEnroe surely won't change that from a courtside chair and
probably not from a doubles alley either.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is against the man's nature to compete in anything less
than a cacophonous state and, for the life of him, he hasn't been
able to think of two better U.S. doubles players or one good reason
he absolutely should not put himself in.
</P>
<P>
   When McEnroe played four sets of doubles with three different
partners Tuesday evening at the beachfront club alongside the
temporary stadium that looks like a giant erector set, he won three
and the other was called at five-all.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, the practice drew fans away from the nearby
Spaniards, a diverse crowd of sunbathers and celebrity worshipers
who rabidly supported every angled winner off McEnroe's racquet.
</P>
<P>
   Even Juan Balcells, one of the Spanish doubles players, said it
would be ``great, a thrill'' to play against the cranky legend.
Never the most artful ambassador, McEnroe was unfortunately on
record already regarding the quality of the likely doubles
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, doubles are our best bet, on paper,'' he said. ``I'm
not saying we'll do it but if we win the doubles and lose 4-1, I
don't consider that a victory just because I stepped on the court
and beat Balcells and, you know, somebody. I mean, who the hell is
Balcells?''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever he is, Balcells and his probable partner, the rock-solid
Alex Corretja, will be about 15 years younger and likely to make
McEnroe miserable with those heavy ground strokes that are the
foundation of the clay court game.
</P>
<P>
   When McEnroe looks in the mirror, he still sees the
serve-and-volley genius, the short-point artist, more than the
gray-haired 41-year-old who in his prime bragged about a
conditioning program that began with his self-titled ``Haagen-Dazs
diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he would only have half the court to cover; points in
doubles are shorter and the Spaniards are not going to serve and
volley anyone off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what he saw of McEnroe on Monday night, Todd Martin,
the most experienced U.S. singles player here, said: ``The only
thing keeping him from being a real viable candidate to play is his
second serve. His first serve is still very effective and his play
at the net is superb. But you have to make your second serve
penetrate on clay and I don't think that was easy for him even in
his prime.''
</P>
<P>
   At Wimbledon, Martin said he did not think McEnroe should vacate
his captain's chair but Wednesday admitted that he had to
``hedge,'' now that Sampras and Agassi are injured and out, putting
Martin in a position to play two singles matches.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is 30 and has fought off various ailments the last few
years. To play doubles with Jan-Michael Gambill would mean three
straight days in the sun, on the clay.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe might have brought another doubles player, an Alex
O'Brien, a Jared Palmer, but he played it straight in Zimbabwe and
Los Angeles, resisted the temptation to nominate himself and lost
the doubles in both events.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, with a career 18-2 record in the Davis Cup doubles,
can't do any worse and there is nobody to make a case for who is
certain to do better.
</P>
<P>
   When he assumed the captaincy, McEnroe's stated goal was to
raise the visibility of the Davis Cup, which he has done to a
degree. On the other hand, he already sounds frustrated by the
bailouts of the stars and he knows that, with the possible
exception of Gambill, there are none on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   He holds the job on a year-to-year basis, and said that he would
have to assess his availability for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has not worked out the way I planned it but I still
believe that Davis Cup is an event worth fighting for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He should take the fight to the court, one more time. He should
put himself in, go to the net, strike a few winners for the sport
that he loves. If he drowns under a tidal wave of topspin, well,
disasters sell at the box office, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
