<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huffins laments lost shot at rival
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, CALIF. _ Protocol has its place, and no event on the
track has a deeper sense of tradition than the decathlon. It is
considered the cathedral of sporting perseverance, the Olympic
stage its altar. Ruled by high priests down through the years like
Bill Toomey, Rafer Johnson, Bruce Jenner and, most recently, Dan
O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Huffins has waited four years for the chance to formally
unseat O'Brien as the country's best all-around athlete. But as the
Olympic trials resume this afternoon with first-day competition in
the decathlon, Huffins is left chasing a ghost of a rival _ with
O'Brien returning to his desert haunt in Scottsdale, Ariz., to
nurse a bruised heel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been preparing a long time for this day, hoping the best
decathlete in world would be at his best and we'd go at it,'' said
Huffins, dejected by the absence of O'Brien. ``It stinks. It's like
reading a book and the ending is stupid. Everything is building
towards this magnificent crescendo and it doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   This neatly captures Huffins' personality _ blunt, eloquent and
honest. He carries an air of supreme confidence, alongside fierce
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   While other competitors pay homage to O'Brien, Huffins speaks
openly of beating him. O'Brien still owns the American record of
8,891 points; Huffins has a personal best of 8,694. But with
O'Brien competing just once since the Atlanta Olympics, Huffins won
the last two U.S. championships and a bronze medal at last summer's
World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, Huffins evolved into America's best decathlete while
O'Brien lived off his Atlanta glory. That's why he wanted O'Brien
and no excuses in the trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I don't think the victor will be any different
than it was going to be before,'' said Huffins, sporting a gold
Georgia Tech visor.
</P>
<P>
   Huffins, 30, expects to be the last man standing when the
10-event decathlon ends Friday. Then, he'll head off to a second
Olympic Games and, if all goes well, return to Atlanta with a medal
and perhaps the title of the world's greatest athlete.
</P>
<P>
   As of July 1, Huffins went on the Georgia Tech payroll as an
assistant track coach. Head coach Grover Hinsdale, however, made
the hire knowing Huffins might be involved with the Olympics until
the early fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK, we'd be glad to have an Olympic medalist on our
staff,'' Hinsdale said.
</P>
<P>
   After adopting the decathlon in 1992, and even leading the
trials competion in New Orleans later that summer after the first
day, Huffins finds himself now at the peak and a serious threat to
Czech star Tomas Dvorak for an Olympic gold medal. Huffins says
he's at the point O'Brien was between 1992-95, searching for
consistency in all events.
</P>
<P>
   He excels in the 100 meters (10.22 seconds) and long jump (26-5
3/4), which explains why he scores well the first day. Ever so
steadily, Huffins has improved in the other eight events and has
managed to conquer his fear of the event-closing 1,500 meters in
his pursuit of a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Huffins, a California/Berkeley graduate, first knows he has to
earn his way onto the U.S. team, cognizant of steamy temperatures,
dicey pole vault conditons and other pitfalls that could be ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what, no regrets,'' he said. ``I only wanted track
to pay for my college. I'm a '96 Olympian and on the cusp of
another team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
