A7118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-     07-19 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following
entertainment/arts articles for release Sunday, July 23, 2000. If
you have questions about stories, call 888-346-9867 or
212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `e' category
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-VENICE-BIENNALE (Venice) _ The Venice Biennale's
Seventh International Architecture Exhibition features the latest
strain to emerge in architecture in recent years: ``blob'' design,
produced with the aid of animation software. Biomorphic and
invertebrate, blobs look like things you would expect to see rising
from an electronic version of the primordial ooze. But a small
floating park set within the cargo hold of a rusting freight barge
is the favorite of Herbert Muschamp, the Times critic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LECONTE (Paris) _ Patrice Leconte has averaged one feature
a year since his debut in 1975, and in the time it has taken for
``The Girl on the Bridge'' to reach the United States, he has
completed one feature _ the period piece ``The Widow of
Saint-Pierre,'' with Juliette Binoche and Daniel Auteuil _ and is
filming ``Felix et Lola'' with Charlotte Gainsbourg and Philippe
Torreton. In his spare time, he makes commercials. ``The Girl on
the Bridge,'' which opens Friday in New York, is a love story.
``All films are love stories,'' he says in an interview in Paris.
By Dave Kehr.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BRITISH-DIRECTORS (Undated) _ The kitchen sink is no longer
a handy symbol for the social inequities and domestic pressures of
British life and the so-called kitchen-sink filmmakers of the '60s
have gone on to other projects. But in the last few years several
talented British directors have emerged with pain-infused realist
dramas that get to the heart of working- and middle-class Britain.
Lynne Ramsay's ``Ratcatcher'' and Shane Meadows' ``Room for Romeo
Brass'' open in New York this fall. ``Wonderland,'' directed by
Michael Winterbottom, opens on Friday. Graham Fuller interviews the
directors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-JARRE-FILM (Undated) _ Michael Beckerman says he is
rooting for Maurice Jarre to win an Oscar for his brilliant score
of ``Sunshine.'' Then, Beckerman says, he hopes Jarre gives it to
Schubert. To create the main musical theme, Jarre has played the
first phrase of the Schubert Fantasy in F Minor without notes 6-15,
then added a new expansive phrase. The Schubert fantasy is a
particularly compelling choice for ``Sunshine'' because the opening
suggests a Hungarian Gypsy origin, appropriate for the film set
over three generations of one family in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MAVERICKS (San Francisco) _ So what if some of the
participants were not really mavericks; more like an in-group of
outsiders. So what if the concerts had their ups and downs; the ups
were amazing and the downs were mostly good enough at the
``American Mavericks'' festival at the San Francisco Orchestra last
month. Richard Taruskin writes that he had never heard such a
catholic barrage of not-to-be-missed programming. Also not to be
missed in this unusually colorful music story was the sight and
sound of Michael Tilson Thomas directing the audience, who had been
invited to bring instruments. Taruskin says he looked like Jerry
Springer with a stick and the music sounded like a clambake, but a
good time was had by all. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ART-RIJKSMUSEUM (Amsterdam, the Netherlands) _ ``The Glory of
the Golden Age'' at the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam celebrates the
museum's 200th anniversary and offers a reminder that the 17th
century was a special moment of creative boom in Dutch history. In
other parts of Europe, art was still reflecting the power of kings
and popes; in the Netherlands, it mirrored the emergence of a new
mercantile society. With still lifes decorating every
self-respecting home, it was an enviable time to be an artist.
Several million paintings were produced by several thousand
artists. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ART-TINTORETTO (Wernersville, Pa.) _ Since 1930, ``The Raising
of Lazarus'' hung, unlighted and unlabeled, in the Jesuit Center in
Wernersville, Pa. Two years ago, it was authenticated as one of
seven existing treatments of the subject by Jacopo Robusti
Tintoretto, one of the great painters of the late Italian
Renaissance. There is little doubt about its provenance. The story
traces its travels to England to Berlin and back to Italy where it
was purchased for $35,000 in 1928 by an American couple. The sale
had an exceptionally credible witness, Frank Spellman, a young
priest who went on to become archbishop of New York. By Ken
Shulman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-COPS-RUSSIA (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ In the last two years,
St. Petersburg has become the hottest location for the hottest
trend on Russian television: gritty, tell-it-like-it-is cop shows.
The boom began in early 1998 with ``The Street of Broken
Streetlights,'' a St. Petersburg version of ``Hill Street Blues.''
Now, in its wake, half a dozen mini-series are being shot or are on
the drawing boards in St. Petersburg, starring counter-intelligence
agents, mafia dons, tough female investigators and other heroes and
villains. The choice of St. Petersburg echoes real life. In recent
years, the city has become infamous for a string of contract
killings. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BURNETT-SURVIVOR (Undated) _ Mark Burnett may not be liked by
everybody, but he has survived the entertainment world. The
40-year-old British native landed in Los Angeles in 1982, moved
from au pair work to telemarketing, insurance and credit card sales
before being inspired by a Tony Robbins motivational seminar and
turning to television. He has since developed two winning
entertainment vehicles in remarkably little time by Hollywood
standards, the ``Eco-Challenge Expedition Race,'' and now
``Survivor.'' ``Survivor'' is the latest in what he promises will
be a stream of adventure-related businesses and programming
combining a blend of drama and reality. Burnett calls it
``dramality.'' By Alica Ault.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-MONNIER (Paris) _ Choreographing ``Pour Antigone,''
Mathilde Monnier went for inspiration to the last place one might
associate with Greek mythology, Africa. She held auditions and
hired one dancer from Mali and four from Burkina Faso. By the time
she was finished it was a turning point for her and the dancers and
for the Greek story which, in her version, unfolds on a minimalist
African landscape with a car seat and corrugated-tin siding as
decor. By Amy Serafin.
</P>
