<P>
   TRAVEL-BRAZIL-SOCCER (Undated) _ How you play the game of soccer
does matter. So Annasue McCleave Wilson accompanied her 14-year-old
son, John, to Florianopolis, Brazil, for training sessions and
matches planned by his coach, Paulo Barreto. In between games, John
and his teammates had time for sandboarding and exchanging e-mail
addresses with Brazilian teenagers and parents had time for
enjoying lime drinks on the hotel veranda, ecological walks and
watching games played on sand as white as baby powder.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TEENS (Undated) _ Based on first-hand experience from
five trips, Jill Abramson has advice for parents traveling with
teen-agers. In London, avoid the British Museum and Parliament, but
visit the Tower of London and war rooms because teen-agers like
gory stuff and they have seen enough World War II movies to make
Whitehall interesting. In Paris, she reports that her daughter took
in the Louvre in less than two hours, but loved going to a movie
without a chaperone. Other advice: rent a ``sweet'' car, don't
share rooms with teen-agers because vacation for them means not
being neat and finally, don't insist on little adults, be a big kid
instead.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) How young is too young for a child
to fly? It depends on whom you ask. Continental will not accept an
infant younger than 7 days. American Airlines sets a 3-day limit,
but in fact, a spokesman says the airline doesn't ``inspect''
babies. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta
recommends 6 weeks. Another expert asks if a postpartum mother is
ready for a long trip and still another says a good criteria might
be, Is this trip really necessary? By Betsy Wade. &QL;
</P>
