<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7121 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COVERDELL-STROKE0720-     07-19 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-STROKE0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bad headaches a warning sign, neurologists say
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The type of stroke that killed U.S. Sen. Paul
Coverdell presented doctors at Atlanta's Piedmont Hospital with two
major challenges: It is very rare and highly fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's senior senator died Tuesday evening in Piedmont's
neurological intensive care unit of a massive intracerebral
hemorrhage. He had been brought in by ambulance Saturday night
complaining of a severe headache.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the 61-year-old lifelong politician died as a
result of bleeding from a vein in the left side of his brain that
led to uncontrollable swelling and pressure on areas vital to
breathing and consciousness. Surgery was performed Monday morning
to remove a blood clot and relieve the pressure. His wife, Nancy,
and other family members made the decision to remove him from life
support when tests showed no brain activity, a Piedmont spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's family has instructed the hospital to release no
further information on the specifics on the senator's death, said
Nina Montanaro, director of public affairs, so the exact kind of
hemorrhage he suffered was not made public.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said he had been complaining of bad headaches recently.
</P>
<P>
   Cerebral hemorrhages, or bleeding into the brain, comprise about
20 percent of the 750,000 strokes that occur every year across the
country. They can be caused by a sudden rupture or slow leakage of
a blood vessel, or a weakening of the wall of an artery that forms
into an aneurysm, a balloon-like collection of blood that can clot
or rupture.
</P>
<P>
   The most common strokes _ and the ones that can be treated with
new clot-busting drugs called tissue plasminogen activators _ are
called ischemic and are caused by a lack of blood getting to the
brain. These are commonly triggered by high blood pressure and
atherosclerosis, or fatty deposits in the arteries that break off
and cause clots that block blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   While getting immediate treatment for any kind of stroke is
vital, people suffering ischemic strokes have a higher survival
rate than those stricken by the hemorrhagic variety.
</P>
<P>
   Treating a cerebral hemorrhage depends on which type of bleeding
is occurring and where it is occurring. Brain hemorrhages generally
fall into three categories: venus thrombosis, where the major vein
in the brain clots and then blood backs up into the brain, causing
a hemorrhage and potentially fatal pressure on the brain stem; an
aneurysm, which is a bulging out from a weakened wall in an artery
in the brain; or a hemorrhage within an artery of the brain that is
usually caused by high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   A brain scan is the standard first test done to see if a
disturbance is occurring and which type, said Dr. Keith Sanders, a
neurologist and director of the Stroke Center at Saint Joseph's
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have said Coverdell did not suffer from high blood
pressure, and Montanaro said he was not diagnosed with an aneurysm.
Piedmont Hospital is known for its successful treatment of brain
aneurysms using a nonsurgical technique called interventional
radiology, which uses X-ray imaging and balloon angioplasty to plug
the bleeding with small hair-thin wires.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping bleeding within the brain that is caused by a ruptured
vein is considered one of the most difficult types of stroke to
treat, doctors said. It also is listed as having the highest
mortality rate among all the possible stroke events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've had an hemorrhage in the brain, you're really tied
as to what you can do,'' said Dr. Lou Jacobs, a Piedmont
radiologist who specializes in treating brain aneurysms with
interventional radiology. ``If the hemorrhage is on the venus side,
surgery is limited and you have to be extremely careful in what is
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Local neurologists said patients suffering from venus thrombosis
probably account for less than 1 percent of their stroke patients.
While hemorrhagic stroke victims have a 50 percent chance of dying
_ and a great chance of some type of disability if they survive _
catching the bleeding in the brain before irreparable damage occurs
is key, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who experience sudden, severe headaches need to get to
a hospital immediately,'' advised Dr. Michael Frankel, chief of
neurology at Grady Health System and an Emory School of Medicine
associate professor of neurology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors have a acronym for them _ WHOL _ worst headache of
their life. Obviously, the vast majority of headaches are not due
to stroke symptoms, but they can be a warning sign that shouldn't
be ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
