<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7124 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CHEATING-NYT &LR;      07-19 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOU JUST CAN'T BEAR TO DIE, CHEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE HUTSKO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am not a cheater by nature, but when my life depended on it,
for the 20th time, I caved in. I cheated. The game that caused me
to cross over to the dark side was the aptly named Perfect Dark,
for the Nintendo 64.
</P>
<P>
   I had fairly, honestly and exhaustedly reached the final level,
where my alter ego, Joanna Dark, was instructed to blow up an alien
temple's target system, activate an access bridge and assassinate
the diabolical space invader responsible for wreaking so much
interplanetary havoc.
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done. After multiple defeats at the scabrous
claws of the so-called final boss, I gave in. I used a Game Shark,
a piece of hardware the size of a Nintendo 64 cartridge that plugs
into the cartridge port on the top of the console.
</P>
<P>
   The device lets players choose built-in codes that give them
special powers on existing games or add codes for new games, using
the controller pad to tap in alphanumeric sequences that can be
saved to the console's memory.
</P>
<P>
   The cheat I used fooled Perfect Dark into believing that I had
played the game all the way through, which unlocked the elusive
infinite life code. I took out not only the big boss, but also his
minions, with nary a virtual scratch.
</P>
<P>
   After it was over, my feelings were mixed. I felt both good and
bad. But mostly, I felt guilty. Or, as the game itself, which
recognizes whether you played honestly or not, reported in the
final level's summary screen: ``Disgraced.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheating is not new. Programmers have always built in ways to
cheat because testers need to play every level hundreds of times to
make sure the game works.
</P>
<P>
   With so many variables besides just beating the bad guys _ level
design, conversations with other characters, how the bullet holes
look when they pierce the wall _ testers install cheats that allow
them to bypass certain phases. The programmers sometimes leave the
cheats in the finished game or forget to take them out.
</P>
<P>
   The cheats are not always easy to discover. So many gaming sites
and magazines try to cull cheats from inside sources and beta
testers, or by experimenting with games. Many video games have
basic cheats that can be activated, without a Game Shark, by
pressing an often thumb-numbing series of buttons on the console's
controller.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a cheat involves nothing more than typing in a secret
password to a certain level, instead of the password the game gives
you after completing the level fairly. In either case, once the
cheat or cheats are in place, the game becomes easier to play,
whether it is because you have better and stronger weapons and
ammunition or, in the case of Perfect Dark, unlimited life.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other games, Perfect Dark assigns the ``Disgraced''
status to make sure you do not forget that while you may have
conquered the level, you went about it dishonestly, according to
the game's code of ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the subject of video game cheats, for me and other
gamers discussing them online, seems to frequently revolve around
the issue of saving games.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike PC games, which often let you save your game at any
point, video games, also called console games, do not.
</P>
<P>
   So in games like Perfect Dark, dying means you must start the
level over. But in games like Unreal and Quake II for the PC, you
can save your game as you go, and should you get mowed down around
the next turn, you can return to the spot you saved.
</P>
<P>
   But that has been changing. Last year, when Fox Interactive
released Alien vs. Predator for the PC, players cried foul when
they discovered that the game could be saved only after completing
a level.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, the company released a fix that allowed
limited saves. The recently released PC shooter game Soldier of
Fortune offers the best of both worlds: an easy setting, for
unlimited saves at any time in a level, or a more difficult setting
that limits the number of saves per level.
</P>
<P>
   Another game, Daikatana for Windows PCs, takes a slightly
different approach, by requiring the player to collect ``save
crystals'' to save the game's progress. The catch is that only
three save crystals can be carried at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Players can get around some of the game's challenges by
activating many of its not-so-secret cheats, revealed on popular
gaming sites like Gamespot.com and DailyRadar.com. The most common
cheat for shooter games is the so-called God cheat, which, as in
Daikatana, makes your alter ego invincible.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not into playing God; I only want to be able to save at any
point. So it's only a matter of time before Daikatana's maker
presumably releases a patch that lets a player do that. Even so,
since Daikatana has received several scathing reviews, it is not
likely to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a game is so good _ and available only for video game
consoles _ that it is worth playing, despite the many deaths you'll
suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Metal Gear Solid for the PlayStation is one. A spy game in which
stealth is always preferred to shooting, the game casts the player
in the role of a secret agent with a mandate to _ what else? _ save
the world. Considered ancient in video game years (it was released
in 1998), the game continues to appeal to PlayStation users.
</P>
<P>
   As with Perfect Dark, Metal Gear Solid's inability to save the
game at any point can be frustrating. So a little cheating to slip
on a bulletproof vest and load up with unlimited ammunition got me
through a few levels.
</P>
<P>
   But then I stopped cheating and put the game aside because a
more appealing alternative is waiting: a higher-resolution version
of the game for Windows that will be published this summer by
Microsoft. It will let you save the game anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Will I ever cheat again? I'm sure I will, as long as the game
doesn't allow me to save at any time. I'd rather live (infinitely)
as a disgraced agent than forever die trying.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites with game cheat codes: GAME SHARK: www.gameshark.com
CHEAT CODE CENTRAL: www.cheatcc.com
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT.COM VIDEO GAME STRATEGIES: vgstrategies.about.com/games
/vgstrategies/mlibrary.htm
</P>
<P>
   ZDNET GAMESPOT: www.gamespot.com DAILY RADAR: www.dailyradar.com
THE ADRENALINE VAULT: www.avault.com IGN.COM: www.ign.com GAMEPRO:
www.gamepro.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
