<HEADER>
A7125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COVERDELL-MEDIA0720-C     07-19 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-MEDIA0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hospital defends Coverdell
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera and Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The confusion surrounding initial reports Tuesday
evening of Sen. Paul Coverdell's death weren't intentional, says a
Piedmont Hospital spokeswoman whose comments caused some
broadcasters to retract reports that later were proven to be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most difficult time I've ever had dealing with the
media. But I told the truth as I knew it to be,'' Nina Montanaro,
director of public affairs at Piedmont Hospital, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers, listeners and reporters were still wondering Wednesday
how reports of Coverdell's death, which occurred in the middle of
the evening news, could get so confused.
</P>
<P>
   WXIA and WSB as well as radio stations WGST (640 AM and 105.7
FM) and WSB (750 AM and B98.5 FM) reported shortly after 6:15 p.m.
that Coverdell had died. A few minutes later, Montanaro _during a
briefing _ said such reports were ``false.'' Some stations
immediately retracted their stories while others reported
Montanaro's conflicting statement.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:55 p.m., the hospital announced the state's senior senator
had died at 6:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Montanaro, a 25-year Piedmont veteran, said she was with about
15 of Coverdell's relatives and longtime staff members in a
hospital conference room watching TV reports shortly after 6 p.m.
The conference room is near the intensive care unit room where
Coverdell was with his wife, Nancy, Senate Chaplain Lloyd Ogilvie,
other relatives and ICU staff, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know he was dead. The family members I was with did
not know he was dead,'' Montanaro said. ``They said to me, `Would
you do something? It's not correct.' So I did that. I went
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   After denying the reports to the media, Montanaro went back to
the ICU conference room. A few minutes later _ at 6:35 or 6:40 p.m.
_ Nancy Coverdell came out of her husband's room to say the senator
had died, Montanaro said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital then prepared a written statement that was
distributed to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Montanaro said she did not intentionally lie when she denied
those first reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, the senator had passed, and it had been 20 minutes
since he had passed, when I said he had not. But I told the truth
as I knew it to be,'' she said. ``There were minute-by-minute
decisions being made in the patient's room that I was not privy to,
or the rest of the family outside the room were privy to.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, she says she probably denied the reports too
strongly _ she really did not know whether they were true _ but
that the only way to confirm the information was to interrupt the
family in the ICU room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not appropriate, in my opinion,'' Montanaro said. ``They told
me they would let me know as soon as they could.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the hospital's view, even though an individual's clinical
death may occur at a particular time, the family has the
prerogative to pronounce the death publicly according to their own
timetable, regardless of whether you are a public figure or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Events show how tricky things can be for a hospital spokesperson
charged with respecting a family's privacy while providing a
competitive media with information during a sensitive time. So was
it a rare instance of everyone trying to do the right thing, only
to have things go completely wrong?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a right or wrong answer to this,'' says Tom
Rosenstiel, director of the Project for Excellence in Journalism in
Washington, D.C. ``Journalism is all about weighing different
values: the right to privacy versus the right to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's better not to confuse people _ you should be
authoritative when you declare someone dead,'' he added. ``Either
someone is dead or not dead _ you can't be a little bit dead. These
are interesting issues that show just how tricky journalism can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
