<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-VOICESTREAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE TELEKOM OFFERS TO BUY VOICESTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a move that advances the ambitions of Europe's
largest telephone company in the United States, Deutsche Telekom
has offered to acquire the VoiceStream Wireless Corp. in a deal
that values the U.S. company at about $53 billion, according to a
person close to the bid.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom this week offered an exchange ratio of 3.2
shares of its stock plus $30 a share in cash, for a valuation of
about $205.60 a share for VoiceStream. With other large
telecommunications interested in VoiceStream, including Nippon
Telegraph &AMP; Telephone of Japan, the offer raises the stakes for
control of the wireless carrier based in Bellevue, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   While global telecommunications players need to make
acquisitions to provide a complete array of services for clients,
Deutsche Telekom's valuation of VoiceStream is sure to raise
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   If the bid is accepted, it would value VoiceStream at more than
$20,000 per subscriber, or more than three times the average for
wireless carriers. Verizon, the largest wireless carrier in the
United States, is valued at about $4,000 per subscriber, while a
smaller, but faster-growing carrier like Sprint PCS, the wireless
unit of the Sprint Corp., is valued at about $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very expensive,'' said Frederick Moran, a
telecommunications analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``You have to ask how
they would get a return on an investment like that.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Deutsche Telekom is betting on the potential for
growth by pushing to acquire VoiceStream, a company which has been
on an acquisition tear of its own. Last year VoiceStream bought two
wireless carriers, Omnipoint and Aerial Communications, for a
combined $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valuations are extremely difficult to quantify when a company
knows it has to grow and have pockets deep enough to do so,'' said
Steven Yanis, an analyst at Banc of America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of VoiceStream rose 93.75 cents on Wednesday, to $145.50,
while American depository receipts of Deutsche Telekom fell 87.5
cents, to $54.875.
</P>
<P>
   Operating on the GSM standard, for global system for mobile
telecommunications, the same standard in use in Europe where
Deutsche Telekom is a power, VoiceStream has ample room to grow in
the United States, with licenses to cover roughly three-quarters of
the population, or more than 200 million people.
</P>
<P>
   For other carriers, the possible merger of VoiceStream into
Deutsche Telekom's empire would give them greater incentive to
arrive at similar deals. Sprint's wireless arm, which has been a
target for Deutsche Telekom, is left particularly vulnerable after
its parent company's $115 billion merger with WorldCom unraveled
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good side and a bad side to deals like this,'' said
Jeffrey Kagan, an independent analyst. ``At least it means that the
psychology involved makes the deal ahead more expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is the possibility that Deutsche Telekom may
not stop if it succeeds in acquiring VoiceStream. The German
company has previously tried to buy Qwest Communications of Denver,
and might do so again. Or it could be eyeing Sprint PCS, the
fourth-largest wireless carrier, as some analysts have suggested.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Deutsche Telekom will probably face a fight in any
large acquisition it attempts in the United States after opposition
emerged in Congress to the acquisition of American
telecommunications by companies controlled by foreign governments.
The German government owns more than 50 percent of Deutsche
Telekom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
