<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7130 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SNAKE-RIVER-DAMS-ART-     07-19 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAKE-RIVER-DAMS-ART-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION TO POSTPONE PLANS TO BREACH SNAKE RIVER DAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a decision highly sensitive in the Pacific
Northwest, the Clinton administration will postpone by at least
five years a plan that could have led to the breaching of four
major Snake River dams for the benefit of wild salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the administration will propose a menu of smaller steps
intended to protect the salmon and other fish that comprise a dozen
endangered species, in part by placing logs along riverbeds to
provide the fish with an illusion of home.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which is to be made public next week, was outlined
Wednesday by senior administration officials. It was portrayed as
an alternative to more severe measures that face strong opposition
by elected officials in the Northwest. But the new proposal will
also reverberate across the politically important region.
</P>
<P>
   The dams, in Washington state, are part of a cluster on the
Snake and Columbia river that interrupt the fishes' migratory flow.
But they also generate enormous quantities of electricity, and in
the debate over their fate, the potential cost to consumers of
electricity in the Pacific Northwest has weighed heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumed Republican
presidential nominee, had already declared his opposition to any
breaching of the dams. By contrast, Vice President Al Gore, the
presumed Democratic nominee, has refused to comment directly about
the issue, despite repeated questions about it during campaign
stops in the region.
</P>
<P>
   An administration move to put off any decision about breaching
the dams could insulate Gore from criticism from environmentalists,
who have argued that more needs to be done sooner to repair the
damage to the habitat of the endangered fish.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions about the fate of the dams are being weighed by a
collection of federal agencies, including the Army Corps of
Engineers and the Bureau of Reclamation, with the ultimate decision
being made by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has cast himself as an environmentalist, but
a decision made in the name of federal agencies might help to
shield him from attack by those who might seek to portray the
administration as an enemy of economic development.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday morning about the administration's decision,
Gore told reporters in Missouri that he was ``going to bring all of
the parties together to come up with a solution that respects the
environment and does not cause an upheaval in the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he agreed with the administration's decision, Gore
side-stepped the issue. ``I'm going to review it carefully. I think
that what's needed is to bring all of the stakeholders together.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, the Gore campaign released a statement from the
vice president that said, in part, ``I feel it provides a solid
foundation for restoring the salmon while strengthening the economy
of the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also says that ``if sufficient progress toward
recovery is not being made, we may then have no choice but to
pursue options such as dam breaching. But we must first exhaust all
reasonable alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, news of the postponement prompted concern from Ralph
Nader, the Green Party nominee, who is running well in Washington,
Oregon and other Pacific Northwest states where polls have
indicated a tight race between Gore and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Nader made clear that he was eager to
join the debate. ``Everybody knows the dams cannot be removed
overnight, but you have to move toward that goal,'' Nader said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to postpone any breaching of the Northwest dams was
reported in Wednesday's editions of USA Today. Details were
discussed by administration officials who cited testimony that was
to have been delivered before Congress on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks prepared for those sessions, which were postponed,
George Frampton, chairman of the White House Council on
Environmental Quality, tried to explain why the administration had
elected not to recommend that the dams be breached as soon as
possible. Frampton said such efforts ``may not be essential'' to
recovering salmon habitat ``and may not be sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, at least for now, the proposal by the White
House calls for several other measures, including steps aimed at
making it easier for fish to overcome the Snake River dams.
</P>
<P>
   Under the strategy, the progress made by the salmon and other
fish toward recovery is to be monitored over the next five years.
If it is not sufficient to remove the fish from the list of
endangered species, other actions would have to be taken, including
a renewed review of whether to breach the dams.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for American Rivers, an environmental advocacy
group, said it would be watching closely to see whether the
administration's final plan provides adequate guarantees both now
and in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science shows that the dams need to be removed to save
salmon,'' said the spokesman, Justin Hayes. ``And if we delay too
long, salmon runs, and even extinction, are at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, administration officials have signaled that a
preferred course might have been a move that would have directed
that the dams be breached.
</P>
<P>
   But such a step would require the approval of Congress,
including members of the Northwest delegations who have been
steadfastly opposed to such an overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Without such support, administration officials said Wednesday, a
plan to push forward now with breaching would have been politically
foolish, and could have resulted in years of legislative battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to decide, `let's breach,' you would be setting
yourself up for an enormous fight. So isn't it better to focus your
energy on concrete measures that will have real benefits in the
near term?'' asked an administration official who has played a key
role in the decision-making process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
