<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKONE-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: BANK ONE'S QUARTERLY LOSS FAILS TO SCARE AWAY
INVESTORS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ill.)  By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A quarterly loss of much more than $1 billion was not enough to
scare investors away from the stock of the Bank One Corp.
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they bought shares of the bank, which is based in
Chicago, after its new chief executive, James L. Dimon, announced a
$1.91 billion restructuring charge that wiped out the company's
second-quarter profit and left it with a loss of $1.27 billion, or
$1.11 a diluted share. The bank also slashed its dividend in half.
</P>
<P>
   Though the charge was much bigger than analysts had predicted,
Bank One's stock rose $2.625, or 8.8 percent, to $32.625, in
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. More than 12 million shares
of Bank One changed hands, making it one of the most active issues
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   After a briefing by Dimon, several analysts increased their
estimates of the bank's future earnings and some raised their
ratings on the stock. Most of them expressed confidence in Dimon's
ability to turn around the troubled bank he took over earlier this
year after he was forced out of the No. 2 job at Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody was convinced. Michael Mayo, an analyst at
Credit Suisse First Boston who has been advising clients to sell
Bank One's stock, did not change his rating Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie Dimon gave a good presentation today,'' Mayo said. ``But
you have to realize that this is a battleship to turn around and
Jamie Dimon is not Hercules.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayo raised his estimate of how much Bank One would earn next
year by about 4 percent, to $2.90 a share. At Wednesday's closing
price, that translates to a price-earnings ratio of 11.2.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of Chase Manhattan, a consistently profitable and
growing financial-services company, trades for about the same
price-earnings ratio, 11.34. That contrast shows that ``Bank One's
gotten a little ahead of itself,'' Mayo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we'd like to see is that the smart ideas that start from
the top translate into progress from the business lines,'' he said.
``The best laid plans don't always translate into sustainable
earnings growth.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Dimon said he had taken the first step toward a
turnaround by writing down the value of some of the bank's assets
and setting aside money to cover future losses. Before taxes, the
charge amounts to $2.94 billion, with $777 million attributed to
the bank's First USA credit card division.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon said he was ``pretty confident'' that the bank would not
have to take more charges to cover the costs of the restructuring,
``but it's not a promise yet.'' He added: ``I've only been here for
three or four months. But I really do feel confident that we
scrubbed pretty hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimon said he did not anticipate having to lay off significant
numbers of the bank's 82,500 employees, nor did he intend to sell
the credit card business or Wingspan.com, an Internet-based bank.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon said the bank would reduce employment mainly through
attrition and would focus on reducing nonemployment expenses. He
said the bank hoped to cut those costs by about $500 million a
year. He also announced plans to conserve cash by cutting the
quarterly dividend by 50 percent, to 21 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The bank will try to combine the resources of Wingspan, which it
has run as a freestanding unit, with the online operations of Bank
One and ``try to grow both of them aggressively,'' Dimon said. He
believes Wingspan ``can be positioned differently'' to take better
advantage of Bank One's branch network and other resources, but ``I
can't tell you that strategy will definitely work.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Flannigan, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., said she
had always thought Bank One should hang onto First USA because it
was such a big player in the credit card business and because there
were synergies between it and the bank's other consumer businesses.
``I think Wingspan is a bigger question mark,'' she said,
expressing doubt about the wisdom of having two bank brands on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Flannigan, who kept a ``near term neutral'' rating on the stock,
said Dimon and his team had taken steps that should ensure smooth
profitability in the short run. ``Certainly big upfront charges
have the ability to pave the way for a nice bounce,'' she said.
``But in the long run, can they position this company to be a
standout in an industry that is increasingly competitive?''
</P>
<P>
   May added: ``They face a long haul in getting there. Investors
better be ready for more bumps in the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
