<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TRIP DELAY ANNOYING TO JAPAN 
 

</HEADLINE>
 TRIP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's decision to cut short a planned
trip to Japan to stay on at the Camp David peace talks will bolster
sentiments this administration does not take its Asian ally
seriously, Japan watchers say.
</P>
<P>
   And by shuffling his schedule at the last minute, Clinton is
doing little to help the political fortunes of his Japanese host,
embattled Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton originally was scheduled to fly to Tokyo Wednesday to
confer with Mori today ahead of Friday's meeting of the Group of
Eight, the seven major industrial powers and Russia on the southern
island of Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also was slated to meet in Tokyo with leaders from a
group of Third World nations to discuss issues such as poverty,
AIDS and access to computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   But with peace talks between the Israelis and Palestinians at a
critical juncture, Clinton chose to remain at Camp David _ at least
for a day.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers filled in for Clinton
at the economic session with the developing nations. And the White
House announced the session with Mori would be rescheduled during
the summit in Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president made a judgment that the issues here are
important enough, and the stakes are high enough, that he would
take the extra day to see what additional work could be done,''
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Wednesday at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult decision, because he had an important day
planned in Tokyo,'' Lockhart said. But he noted: ``I think those
who are involved in international affairs in a way like the
Japanese are, as a leader of the world, understand the
responsibilities that international leaders take upon themselves
and the difficult decisions that sometimes have to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at the Japanese Embassy in Washington declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   However, the delay generated some comments in Japan, the
Washington Post reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before the summit has begun, it feels like we are being
swept aside'' by the United States, complained Fuji Television.
``It is clear where (Clinton's) priority lies,'' TV Asahi added,
noting Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori ``has been studying hard for the
summit. He is disheartened at the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Few outside observers ever expected the summit in Japan would
produce an agreement of truly great consequence. Camp David,
meanwhile, has the potential for lasting import.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Japanese and U.S. trade negotiators reached a deal
to lower the connections American and other foreign telephone
companies would have to pay to compete in the Japanese market.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin wants to hammer Clinton on a
U.S. proposal to build a missile defense system, but the
administration is not ready to negotiate a final deal on that
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the modest expectations, there has been great interest
in the summit in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese take these summits much more seriously than we
do,'' said Michael Green, a senior fellow at the Council on Foreign
Relations in Washington and an expert on Japan. ``They don't have
as many areas to present their diplomatic prowess as we do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The general impression in Japan is the Clinton administration
does not take Japan seriously as an ally,'' Green said. ``And the
Japanese are at least half right.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton irked many Japanese in 1998 when he made an extended
trip to China but failed to stop in Japan, while U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright failed to attend a Group of Eight foreign
ministers meeting earlier this month in Miyazaki, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese press has dubbed the phenomenon ``Japan passing,''
Green said. Clinton, however, did manage to assuage Japanese
sensibilities somewhat in June, when he attended the funeral of
former Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mann, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution here
in Washington, said there has been some friction between Japan and
the Clinton administration. But, he believes ``the relations are in
reasonably good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's successor _ Mori _ is now fighting for his political
life.
</P>
<P>
   With public approval ratings in the single digits, Mori is
widely viewed as a caretaker prime minister, only holding onto
power until after the summit, Mann noted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
