<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OPEN TIP FROM A SAGE ... NOT TIGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ He is 68 now. He doesn't caddie anymore,
but every day shortly before noon he is in the Dunvegan Hotel bar,
perched next to the door. With a mischievous smile, he said, ``I
try to get here eight days a week,'' and behind him was a small
brass plate attesting to his stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This chair,'' it read, ``reserved for Tip and his friends.''
</P>
<P>
   In front of James (Tip) Anderson was a glass of dark rum and a
glass of beer. He sipped each occasionally as he talked about the
Old Course at St. Andrews, where he caddied since he was a lad and
where the 129th British Open begins on Thursday with Tiger Woods a
9-to-4 favorite in the local Ladbrokes betting parlor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Tiger will win,'' this sage of St. Andrews said.
``It's precision here. If you go in the boonker, it's bye-bye
Delilah.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go into some of the 167 boonkers, you have to blast out
sideways, if not backward. And for all his talent, Woods will be
vulnerable to the most dreaded bunkers _ the Coffins on the 13th
hole, the Beardies and the Hell on the 14th, the Principal's Nose
on the 16th, and the Road bunker, shaped like a mine shaft, on the
17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger should keep the driver in the locker room,'' the sage
said. ``He only needs it at 5, 14 and 17. If you drive it too far,
you run out of fairway and you're in the rough.''
</P>
<P>
   When Woods was asked later where he will spurn his driver, he
said: ``It's dependent on the wind. If the wind is blowing on the
first hole dead in your face, I'm going to go driver. Other times
I've hit a chip 3-iron down there and a little sand wedge to the
green.'' And the first, like the 18th, doesn't have even one
boonker.
</P>
<P>
   Tip Anderson, whose nickname was handed down from his father,
Tipper, who put tips on snooker cues, subscribes to the Scottish
tenet, ``If it's nae wind, it's nae golf.'' And it's seldom nae
wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the wind is from the east off the North Sea, the course
is more difficult,'' the sage said. ``When it's from the west, it
makes the course easier because then the back nine is downwind.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' caddie, Steve Williams, has been here before, usually
with Raymond Floyd, for both the British Open and the Dunhill Cup
matches. He knows the course. But none of the touring pros' caddies
know it like Tip Anderson, who has collaborated with Desmond
Muirhead to write ``How to Play the Old Course'' (Mainstream,
$23.50).
</P>
<P>
   Anderson caddied in the British Open for 36 years, notably here
for Arnold Palmer in 1960, when Palmer lost to Australia's Kel
Nagle by one stroke, and also when Palmer won at Royal Birkdale in
1961 and Royal Troon in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be another Arnold Palmer,'' the sage said.
``He listened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Old Course's sixth green during a 1960 practice round,
Palmer had a five-foot putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `It's one ball on the right, sir,''' the sage
recalled. ``He missed and said, `Throw it back, Tip.' He missed
again. `Throw it back, Tip.' He missed again. He said, `You gave me
the wrong line, Tip.' I said, `It took me 28 years to find that
out.' He said, `There's no way I'll beat you, Tip,' and I said,
`You got that right.'''
</P>
<P>
   When Palmer didn't enter the 1964 British Open here, he told
Tony Lema to hire Tip, and Lema won.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Tip Anderson, with a tiny Arnold Palmer
umbrella pin on his white Dunvegan Hotel cap, was inducted into the
Professional Caddies Association Hall of Fame at a dinner,
fittingly, at Rusacks Hotel overlooking the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived in St. Andrews all my life except I didn't remember
the first two weeks,'' he said with that smile. ``I forgot to
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he doesn't think Tiger Woods will win here this week, who
will be able to master the Old Course's wind and boonkers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick Price,'' he said. ``He's a very consistent golfer. He
hits the ball far enough and if he holes a few putts, which
everyone's got to do, he'll win. That's just a matter of opinion,
of course.''
</P>
<P>
   The Old Course is only a block away from the Dunvegan, but Tip
Anderson will watch the Open on the telly there from his chair in
the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've seen enough golf,'' he said. ``It took me a long
time to know all this and I still don't know what I'm talking
about, but I can read all the putts on the telly. The third green
is the fastest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
