<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-SERVICE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Services scheduled to mark the passing of Sen. Coverdell
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The body of Sen. Paul Coverdell, who died Tuesday of a
cerebral hemorrhage at the age of 61, will lie in state at the
Georgia Capitol on Friday, his family said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell will be memorialized Saturday at Atlanta's Peachtree
Road United Methodist Church in a ceremony that will draw many of
his Senate colleagues, dignitaries from around the country and much
of the state's political leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell will be cremated after Friday's public viewing and his
ashes laid to rest in a private family ceremony after Saturday's
memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after his death, members of Congress eulogized
Coverdell in both the House and the Senate in an outpouring of
remembrance and grief.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate chamber, the sergeant at arms draped a black cloth
over Coverdell's desk and placed a bouquet of white roses, lilies
and freesia on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a heavy cloud hanging over the Senate chamber
today,'' said a somber Arlen Specter (R-Penn.).
</P>
<P>
   And the flood of condolences continued. Peace Corps Director
Mark Schneider called Coverdell one of the agency's finest
directors. ``We thank him for service to our country and his
immeasurable contributions to the cause of peace and freedom around
the world,'' said Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, state flags flew at half-staff. Officials at Georgia
College &AMP; State University in Milledgeville erected a small
memorial to Coverdell at the entrance to the library, where
Coverdell's official papers are housed.
</P>
<P>
   And at the University of Georgia and Morehouse School of
Medicine, officials praised the state's senior senator for his help
in securing federal grants for their institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Jockeying for Coverdell's Senate seat also began behind the
scenes Wednesday as Democrats and Republicans scrambled to develop
short lists of viable candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes, who offered the Capitol to Coverdell's family
for the public viewing, declined comment on whom he might name to
succeed Coverdell pending a Nov. 7 special election.
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia Sen. Richard Russell lay in state at the Capitol
after his death in 1971 and former secretary of state Ben Fortson
was the last person so honored, in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
