<SLUG> BC-ZIFFDAVIS-CNET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNET TO BUY ZIFF-DAVIS FOR $1.6 BILLION IN STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GREG WINTER and ALEX KUCZYNSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ CNET Networks said Wednesday that it would acquire
Ziff-Davis Inc., a trailblazer in the technology magazine industry,
and its Internet subsidiary, ZDNet, for $1.6 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at both companies characterized the deal as an
outgrowth of their ``shared common vision'' to provide online
consumers with critiques of the latest technology, a niche CNET has
exploited to become one of the more profitable Internet companies.
The combined company is expected to be the Internet's
eighth-largest property, with 16.6 million users, roughly 22
percent of the U.S. audience.
</P>
<P>
   The deal signals the degree to which CNET, an upstart in the
days when Ziff-Davis was a formidable presence in the technology
industry, has managed to surpass its main rival, from which it took
many of its cues.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis, the one-time owner of PC Magazine and MacWorld, had
an online presence a decade before CNET. In 1985, long before most
Americans started going online, PC Magazine introduced an
interactive reader service, which evolved into ZDNet by the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   CNET, by contrast, began with a television program on USA
Networks in 1995, followed by its first foray onto the Web a few
months later. But the company quickly went public in 1996, becoming
one of the first Internet companies to do so and beating ZDNet by
three years.
</P>
<P>
   That early offering, analysts say, helped CNET raise the money
to buy 10 companies over the last year alone, including the $700
million purchase in January of MySimon.com, an online
comparison-shopping company.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring ZDNet would give CNET a way to increase its audience
at a time when the Internet is fast approaching saturation,
analysts say. In addition to a widely recognized name, ZDNet is a
leading technology portal in Europe, especially in France, Germany
and Britain, where CNET wants to expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're buying additional customers rather than trying to
steal them away,'' said Robert Martin, senior Internet analyst at
Friedman, Billings, Ramsey &AMP; Co. ``It's a good way of extending
their lead in market share.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, CNET would exchange 0.3397 of a share for each
share of Ziff-Davis and 0.5932 of a share for each share of ZDNet,
a separately traded company in which Ziff-Davis is the majority
owner.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis was particularly ripe for acquisition, having become
a shell of the company known for magazines like PC Magazine and
MacWorld, and for putting on Comdex, the computer trade show. Last
year, Softbank, the Japanese investment group that owns a majority
stake in Ziff-Davis, said it intended to sell or spin off the
company's non-Internet components, pursuing its strategy to become
the world's largest Internet investor.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a piecemeal breakup of Ziff-Davis has ensued,
starting with the $204 million sale of its cable television
channel, ZDTV, in November. One month later, the company announced
the sale of its magazine division to Willis Stein &AMP; Partners LP for
$780 million. Then, in March, Ziff-Davis executives disclosed plans
to spin off the company's trade show business in an initial public
offering scheduled for August.
</P>
<P>
   If the offering goes through, Ziff-Davis' remaining assets would
include ZDNet; two technology magazines, Computer Shopper and a
stake in Red Herring; and a Web site, SmartPlanet, all of which
would be included in the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Because many investors see ZDNet and CNET as both catering to
computer consumers, the deal raised concerns that advertisers would
have less incentive to buy space on two Web sites owned by the same
company. Advertising represents about two-thirds of CNET's revenue
and more than 70 percent of ZDNet's income.
</P>
<P>
   The companies tried to assuage these concerns by pointing out
that only 25 percent of their top advertisers overlapped and that
they shared a relatively small percentage of the same users.
Whereas ZDNet provides product information to technology-savvy
computer users, CNET caters to a less sophisticated audience that
is often uncomfortable with highly technical terms.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts raised objections to what appeared to be a
deviation from CNET's effort to wean itself of conventional
advertising, like banner ads, a staple in ZDNet's revenue stream.
In recent years, CNET has focused on building its capacity to link
its customers directly to sales of the products it reviews, an
income strategy that many regard as integral to its future, but one
that ZDNet has been slow to adopt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, Ziff-Davis was what CNET was trying to get away
from,'' said Matthew Finick, an analyst at Thomas Weisel Partners
LLC. ``They're taking a step backward right now.''
</P>
<P>
   One potential sticking point on the deal is content for ZDNet.
When Willis Stein &AMP; Partners bought the magazine division, which
then became Ziff-Davis Media Inc., the companies negotiated a
three-year contract through which the magazines supply content for
ZDNet exclusively. But Wednesday, executives for Ziff-Davis Media,
the sixth-largest magazine publisher in the United States, said
they were still in the dark on what provisions had been made to
extend that contract to CNET once it takes over.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Estroff, a spokeswoman for Ziff-Davis Media, said:
``We have not seen the details of the deal and so it is difficult
to comment about specifics right now. But for now, it's go forward,
business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   But James D. Dunning Jr., one of the partners in the acquisition
of the Ziff-Davis magazines, said, ``We had no contact in this
transaction.'' He added that Dan Rosenzweig, the chief executive of
ZDNet, who will become CNET's president, and Shelby Bonnie, the
chief executive of CNET, both called him Wednesday and had asked
for a meeting to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis executives said they expected Dunning, who has a
reputation as a tough negotiator, to press the two executives for a
better deal. Ziff-Davis Media will receive at least $7 million this
year for letting ZDNet use its content, at least $9 million next
year and at least $11 million in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Ziff-Davis Media executives said they must sign
off on the final agreement between CNET and ZDNet, so their
satisfaction with the terms is vital to the deal's closing.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of CNET fell $2.5625, or 8 percent, to $29.625 on
Wednesday. Ziff-Davis rose $2.0625, or 18 percent, to $13.4375,
while ZDNet climbed $4, or 31 percent, to $16.875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
