u w BC-CONGRESS-PENSIONS-NYT     07-19 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-PENSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO RAISE LIMITS ON RETIREMENT-PLAN SAVINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By a surprisingly lopsided margin, the House voted
Wednesday to strengthen retirement savings plans by permitting
larger contributions to them and making it easier to transfer
savings in employer-sponsored plans from job to job.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, passed by 401-25, is intended to encourage
Americans to save more for retirement. Many Democrats objected to
it, saying it would benefit high-income employees but do little to
help low-income workers. Still, just 24 Democrats voted against the
measure, an indication of its broad appeal to voters.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's future appears uncertain, though. For one thing, it
is unclear whether the Senate will have time to take it up before
the end of the current Congress. And the Clinton administration,
sharing the concerns of House Democrats, strongly opposes it. The
administration instead wants legislation that would help those of
more modest income _ many of whom are among the 75 million
Americans not covered by employer-sponsored retirement plans _
rather than those financially able to make contributions above the
current limits.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the House bill, which has the strong backing of some
trade unions, said they hoped its resounding approval Wednesday
would better its chances both in the Senate and at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly I didn't expect such a strong vote,'' said Rep. Rob
Portman, R-Ohio, who co-sponsored the bill with Rep. Benjamin L.
Cardin, D-Md. ``That was an extraordinary vote of confidence. A
strong message is being sent to the Senate and the president that
this House is committed, on a bipartisan basis, to provide more
retirement security this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would raise the amount of money that workers can
contribute to 401(k)'s, individual retirement accounts and other
retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, workers can set aside no more than $2,000 a
year in individual retirement accounts. That amount, applying to
both the traditional IRA and the newer Roth IRA, would rise to
$5,000, in phases, by 2003. An exception would be made for those
older than 50, who would be permitted to make a $5,000 contribution
beginning next year. The exception is meant as a catch-up tool for
older workers who may not have saved enough for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   In 401(k) plans, which permit workers to set aside savings from
their pay and allow employers to take tax deductions for adding to
those amounts, the annual limit on employee contributions would
rise in phases to $15,000 by 2005, from the current maximum of
$10,500. Again an exception would be made for those older, who
would be permitted to save an extra $5,000 a year. And employers
could contribute as much as 20 percent of a worker's salary, up
from 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of frequent job-hopping, the legislation would also
make it easier for workers to transfer their savings in
employer-sponsored plans from one job to the next. One provision,
for example, would speed employees' ability to become fully vested
in 401(k) plans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bill would address a longtime concern of
carpenters, plumbers and other trade workers, whose wages often
fluctuate from year to year, leaving many with less in pension
benefits than they would otherwise receive. Under a 1974 law,
multiple-employer pension plans for trade workers calculate
benefits on the basis of the three consecutive years of highest
pay; the bill would change the basis to the three highest-paid
years, regardless of whether consecutive.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the broader legislation are a desire to spur an
American savings rate that is now at Depression-era lows, and
lawmakers' concern that more needs to be done to supplement Social
Security benefits, particularly since only half of all workers in
the private sector have pensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we must save Social Security, we must remember that
Social Security was never intended to meet all the financial needs
of retirement,'' Cardin said Wednesday. ``Employees need to
understand that they need to take greater responsibility in saving
for retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Democrats, even those who support some aspects of the
bill, complained during the debate that the legislation should do
more to help low- and moderate-income workers. They are the ones
who have the hardest time setting money aside for the future,
Democrats said. As it is, few workers with IRA's and 401(k)'s save
the maximum permitted by law, a point Democrats used to illustrate
that the bill favored the affluent.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing that concern, Democrats offered an amendment, based
on a White House initiative, to provide tax credits to workers of
modest income. For every $2,000 those workers saved, the government
would match it with $1,000. That proposal was rejected Wednesday on
a vote of 221-200.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they also worried that the increased contribution
limits could prompt small businesses to abandon their pension
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is significant data that indicates that the
problem with IRA's is they tend to reward those who already have
the ability to save for retirement,'' said Rep. Richard E. Neal,
D-Mass. ``We want to extend this benefit to low- and
moderate-income workers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
