A7141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COVERDELL-LEWIS0720-C     07-19 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-LEWIS0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    John Lewis quits majority whip race
 &HT;    By Melanie Eversley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Georgia Congressman John Lewis announced Wednesday
night that he is dropping out of the race for majority whip and
acknowledged that he would accept an appointment _ if offered _ to
the Senate seat vacated by Tuesday's death of Sen. Paul Coverdell
(R-Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   It is up to Gov. Roy Barnes to appoint Coverdell's successor.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who led the Georgia House delegation in emotional
remembrances Wednesday on the floor about Coverdell, stressed that
his announcement about the whip race and his interest in the Senate
appointment were not related. Lewis, in fact, stressed that he and
other members of Congress were still reeling from the sudden loss
of their colleague, who had suffered a stroke over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But, when asked whether he would accept an appointment to the
Senate post, Lewis responded that he would do so ``gladly.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who emerged as an icon during the civil rights struggles
of the South and whose seven terms in Congress have made him dean
of the Georgia House delegation, broke the news of his withdrawal
from the whip race in a letter sent to House Democratic colleagues
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout my life, from my earliest days growing up on a farm
outside of Troy, Alabama, to my days and my service in the civil
rights movement through the present day and my service in Congress,
I have always tried to be true to myself. Regardless of the odds, I
have always done what I believe in my heart to be right, to be
just, and to be fair,'' Lewis wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``After several months of campaigning for the post of majority
whip, I have concluded that the votes are simply not there for me.
Therefore, I am writing to inform you of my decision to withdraw
from the contest,'' the two-page letter continued.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Lewis said he had made the decision
several days ago to withdraw from the race and had planned to make
his formal announcement today as a House Democratic Caucus meeting
had been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was in the common good,'' Lewis said, explaining he
did not have the votes to win the race. ``I felt that I should get
out of the race and concentrate on helping take back the House,''
he said of democrats' hopes to regain a majority in the body.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the whip race, Lewis said he would instead place his
support behind candidate Steny Hoyer, a Democratic congressman from
Maryland. Rep. Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.), also is running. Hoyer
could not be reached Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he believed that he and Pelosi took votes from each
other, both sharing many of the same philosophies, and that Pelosi
simply entered the race earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said she was gratified that Lewis would say they both
share the same philosophies because she respects Lewis, and she
predicted that many of his supporters would now stand behind her.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Lewis is highly respected in the Congress, so well-liked,
he was a worthy contender and I wish I had his support,'' Pelosi
said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats took back control of the House in the November
general election, the majority whip would be the third in command
in the House, behind the Speaker and the majority leader. It is the
whip's job to round up votes for legislation being pushed by the
majority party.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis were appointed to the Senate, he would become only the
fifth African-American Senator in U.S. history and only the third
in recent history. Edward Brooke of Massachusetts served in the
Senate from 1967 to 1979 and Carol Mosely Braun of Illinois served
one term, from 1993 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, when pressed about the possibility that he could become
one of the few African-American senators in history, said it would
be high time for someone - even if not him - to serve in such a
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time long passed for there to be an
African-American in that body,'' Lewis said. ``The body is 99 white
and one Native American and I think that the time has long passed
for this country to have some African Americans in the U.S.
Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
