<HEADER>
A7142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COVERDELL-SENATE0720-     07-19 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-SENATE0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Members of Congress shaken by Coverdell's death
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ With tears and heavy hearts, members of Congress
mourned Sen. Paul Coverdell on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate business came to a virtual standstill for most of the day
as senator after senator _ some struggling to compose themselves _
took the floor to praise their deceased colleague.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, members adopted a resolution eulogizing
Coverdell's nearly 30 years of public service after delivering
speeches recalling his life, dedication and friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate today is a very sad place, and it's a shaken place
because of the suddenness of Paul's death,'' said Sen. Joseph
Lieberman (D-Conn.), capturing the mood of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's death is the second death of a senator in less then
a year after the passing of Republican John Chafee of Rhode Island
in October, and many senators appeared to take Coverdell's sudden
demise especially hard.
</P>
<P>
   Normally polished speakers suddenly found themselves struggling
for words or choking back tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often feel something about people _ we often love people _
but _ but we don't often tell them that,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm
(R-Texas), his eyes red with tears. ``It's especially hard for men
to tell other men that they love them. But what I am happy about _
I can't quite get to it _ is . . . that I realized over a year ago
that Paul Coverdell had become an indispensable member of the
Senate, that he was the greatest senator from Georgia since Richard
Russell. And so I always went to great lengths to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate colleagues praised Coverdell for his civility, his
boundless enthusiasm, his skill at helping move complex bills to
passage and his ability to mediate disputes in a body of 100
oversized egos. Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) said Coverdell reached out
to help him when he joined the Senate in 1997, just as they had
tried to help each other when serving together in the state Senate
nearly 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on different sides of the aisle, different sides of
the issues, but he helped me learn,'' Cleland said. ``He helped me
because he was a good man and a great friend, and because he knew
what was good for Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats praised Georgia's senior senator for the courtesy and
good will that he extended to them during the many difficult
political battles they faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of too many times he and I found ourselves on
the same side of a debate,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle (D-S.D.), ``but I can't think of a single time that he was
not fair, that he was not decent, and that he was not honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer (D-Calif.) said Coverdell possessed the rare
quality of being able to disagree ``without being disagreeable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a time when we see our legislative branches becoming more
and more partisan, more and more separated by imaginary aisles that
separate, we can think back and remember that Paul Coverdell was a
person who was willing to work with anyone who was willing to work
with him in order to accomplish legislation that was in the
interest of this whole country,'' said Sen. John Breaux (D-La.).
</P>
<P>
   Senators quoted Scripture, the Romantic poets, former presidents
and statesmen as they searched for ways to express their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms (R-N.C.) said he preferred to visualize
Coverdell on Cloud Nine, standing with St. Peter: ``So, Paul, if
that's you who I think I'm looking at on Cloud Nine, you know that
we're missing you and that we are so dearly grateful for the years
that we had to enjoy working with you. I have a notion that the
Lord will be blessing you for being his good and faithful servant
while you were amongst us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
