<HEADER>
A7154 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-R-BUSH-LOYALTY-2TAKES     07-19 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BUSH-LOYALTY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN POLITICS, AS IN EVERYTHING ELSE, BUSH PLACES PREMIUM ON
LOYALTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Walk through Gov. George W. Bush's campaign
headquarters here and you encounter a remarkable sight: virtually
the same lineup of senior advisers that he had a year ago and, at
the uppermost echelon of the operation, an inner circle of trusted
friends that is wholly intact from the days when Bush won his first
race for Texas governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to these advisers and you hear something equally
arresting: unvarying, self-effacing odes to the governor's talents
that attribute all credit for the campaign's successes to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly acknowledged disagreements? Leaks? These are almost
nonexistent in Bush world, because most of the people who are
allowed to enter it have declared or demonstrated their loyalty, an
ethos as precious to Bush as any other, the coin of his political
realm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loyalty is the No. 1 criterion for him,'' said one Republican
official who has known Bush for more than a decade. ``He would have
loyalty over any other skill or characteristic in the people around
him.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bush, the de facto Republican presidential nominee, nears the
announcement of who his running mate will be, unanswered questions
continue to swirl around what type of political and professional
pedigree that person will have. But Bush and his advisers have made
clear that one of the litmus tests the person will have passed is
that he or she can be utterly faithful to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, most Republican operatives chalk up Sen. John
McCain or Arizona, a political maverick who loves the spotlight, as
an improbable selection, even if his publicly stated lack of
interest could be overcome and even though his presence on the
ticket could be a powerful lure for independent and swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma has maintained his
position as one of the most-talked-about contenders largely because
his mild manner and long friendship with Bush suggest that he would
never try to contradict, usurp or eclipse the Texas governor,
Republican officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Even by the standards of politics, where discretion is always
desired, Bush places an extremely high premium on loyalty, and it
drives many of his important decisions, helping to determine who
gets his ear, who gets the top jobs around him and the terms of
their relationships with him. Many of the senior people in his
campaign had proven their commitment to Bush by forswearing other
political allegiances or taking low salaries. Others had long
histories with the Bush family.
</P>
<P>
   At Bush's request, his chief strategist, Karl Rove, sold his
independent consulting business so that his attention to the
candidate would be undivided. Maverick Media, the advertising firm
that produces Bush's television commercials, was brought into
existence solely for the purpose of the Bush campaign and has no
clients other than Bush, an unusual arrangement in presidential
politics.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview aboard his campaign plane on Tuesday, Bush said
that what he had tried to do was build an efficient team, and that
loyalty was its glue, binding people together so that they could
focus on common goals without fear that colleagues would work
against their interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``A disloyal person in the wrong position can undermine an
administration,'' said Bush, seemingly alluding to the lessons that
his friends and advisers said he learned from watching his father,
former President George Bush, prevail when the lieutenants around
him were true and struggle when they were not.
</P>
<P>
   But several political analysts said that there was a potential
downside to Bush's penchant for loyalists. One Republican
strategist questioned whether Bush received advice that was tough
and critical enough and whether he exposed himself to a wide enough
range of opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen a single decision made by this campaign that
looked to me like they had to force the candidate to do it,'' said
the strategist, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``That's not
necessarily a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican official, describing Bush's closest advisers,
observed: ``I've never seen a campaign where people don't sit
around and psychoanalyze the guy. They never do that, even if
you're having a drink with them. They never call him anything other
than governor, and they never say anything even remotely close to
disparaging.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers say that their united public front should never
be mistaken for a private acquiescence to his wants and whims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel absolutely free to disagree with him,'' said Karen P.
Hughes, the campaign's director of communications. Other advisers
said that they, too, spoke their minds around Bush, but that the
vigorous debates behind closed doors stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes and other advisers said that Bush had earned their
loyalty, supporting them as strongly as they support him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we lost New Hampshire by 20 points,'' Hughes said,
referring to the Republican primary, ``the easy thing for him to
do, to silence the critics, would have been to give them a
sacrificial lamb. He didn't do that. He said, `We're in this
together.'''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters aboard his campaign plane recently, Bush
said, ``There was never any question in my mind'' about replacing
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are friends,'' he said. ``I know they're there for the
right reason.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
