<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7156 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-R-BUSH-LOYALTY-2NDTAK     07-19 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BUSH-LOYALTY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 AUSTIN, Texas: right reason.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Bush struggled in the primaries to turn back the
insurgency of McCain, some analysts speculated that he would turn
to a conventionally seasoned political operative to supplement the
so-called iron triangle _ Rove, Hughes and Joe Allbaugh, the
campaign manager _ who had also guided Bush's career in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush asked one of his best and oldest friends, Donald
L. Evans, an oil and gas company executive, to be the campaign
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The tightness and endurance of Bush's advisers stand in contrast
to the gyrations in Vice President Al Gore's operation, which Bush
has monitored with a disapproving eye. During a taping of the
television news program ``Hardball with Chris Matthews'' a month
and a half ago, Bush predicted that Gore's campaign chairman, Tony
Coelho, would not survive Gore's persistent disadvantage in most
polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to dump him,'' Bush told Matthews during a
commercial break. ``Mark my words. Oh, they'll dump him. There's no
loyalty in those guys.'' (Coelho later stepped down after being
hospitalized with an inflamed colon.)
</P>
<P>
   The unity of the Bush team differs as well from the revolving
door that afflicted Bob Dole's presidential campaign four years
ago, and it has enabled Bush to keep the news coverage of his
campaign focused on the policies he is unveiling or the voters he
is courting.
</P>
<P>
   It also reflects Bush's lingering ire over the behavior of some
aides and allies during his father's failed re-election effort.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that when the going got tough, ``I saw them jumping
out the windows in 1992, looking for the next campaign. And that
influenced me. Yeah, that influenced me. I worry that some may be
wanting to be involved in my campaign to enhance their consulting
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends said that Bush also learned to value loyalty from the
example of his father, who swallowed ideological differences with
Ronald Reagan to serve as his vice president from 1980 to 1988. In
1988, after his father was elected to the presidency, George W.
Bush was asked to head a committee with the task of making sure
that people who had helped his father win were not overlooked for
jobs in the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. opened the meeting by saying, `The purpose of this
occasion is not to punish our enemies but to identify our
friends,''' recalled Chase Untermeyer, who became the director of
personnel in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   And friends are not being forgotten _ or forgetting the Bushes.
Condoleezza Rice, a Russia specialist on the National Security
Council during the Bush administration, is George W. Bush's chief
foreign policy adviser. Richard B. Cheney, the defense secretary
under former President Bush, is supervising the process by which
his son selects a vice president.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Texas governor discusses these teammates, the words
loyal or loyalty are bound to pop up, as they do even when he talks
about the less political people in his life.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent interview about his wife, Laura, Bush said:
``The other thing about Laura is that she's fiercely loyal. She's
loyal to me. She's loyal to my dad. She's loyal to her children.''
It was clear, in the tone of his voice, that there was no praise
any higher. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
