<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-TEXAS-470&AMP;ADD-NY     07-19 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEXAS-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING BUSH VULNERABLE ON STATE BUDGET, GORE WILL VISIT TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: this story, held earlier, is now restored) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE with JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAYTOWN, Mo. _ Seizing what he views as a golden chance to
pierce the heart of Gov. George W. Bush's campaign, Vice President
Al Gore said Wednesday that he would ride into Bush's backyard in
Texas on Thursday to highlight the state's budget woes.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore entourage had planned to travel from Cedar Rapids,
Iowa, back to Washington, but Wednesday morning Gore announced that
he was diverting his campaign to San Antonio for the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign can hardly contain its glee over the daily
headlines out of Texas describing a budget shortfall and its
attendant problems. It campaign can be expected to hit the air with
television commercials on the subject soon, and will exploit the
budget problems for maximum publicity for some time to come,
particularly as a competing story line with the Bush campaign in
the days leading up to the Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that how the governor runs Texas says important
things about how he'd run the country,'' said Mark Fabiani, a
spokesman for the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Fabiani said the Gore team perceives the Texas budget shortfall
as politically devastating for Bush as the pollution of Boston
Harbor was to Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts when he ran for
president in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a surprising weakness,'' Fabiani said. ``The thing that
hurt Governor Dukakis the most is that people thought a Democratic
governor ought to be strong on the environment, and when questions
were raised about the harbor it undermined one of his strengths. If
a Republican governor can't effectively manage his state budget in
a period of tremendous prosperity, it is just as bad. This is his
Boston Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters Wednesday night that the Boston Harbor
comparison ``never crossed my mind.'' But when asked whether he
hoped his attacks on Bush would be as effective as the attacks on
Dukakis, he did not answer directly. Instead, he criticized the
administration of Bush's father, which he said ``squandered'' money
on a tax cut that could have been used on a cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   There is a special irony for the Gore campaign in being able to
turn the Boston Harbor strategy so forcefully against Bush since
his father, in seeking the presidency in 1988, had turned Boston
Harbor into a weapon against Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has already been using bits of this strategy
by pointing to a variety of problems in Texas, but the vice
president's advisers said the budget offered a graphic opportunity
to bring various threads of the Texas story together. These
threads, as Gore described them Wednesday, run from Bush's
``unaffordable tax cuts for powerful interests, coupled with vague
promises that the numbers will somehow add up in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   One Gore aide exclaimed, ``It's a metaphor for everything!''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The announcement of Gore's trip to Texas comes amid growing
fights among Texas lawmakers and public officials over the state's
budget. Earlier this week Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander
announced that the state would see an estimated $1.1 billion
surplus _ more than enough, she said, to pay for the estimated $610
million in cost overruns that has pushed the state over budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a shortfall,'' said Rylander, who will release a
final figure for the surplus on Friday. ``There are budgeting
adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she made the announcement to reassure Wall Street
investors. But Democrats questioned the timing of Rylander's
announcement of the surplus, noting that the comptroller usually
projects revenue at the end of the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a bunch of bull,'' said state Sen. Mario
Gallegos, D-Houston. ``I think she released it early not because of
ratings from Wall Street, but because of the ratings that George W.
Bush is getting.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy became public last week when state budget
officials confirmed that unanticipated cost overruns, particularly
in Medicaid and in state prisons, had thrown the state $610 million
over budget. Bush's aides quickly responded that cost overruns were
routine during any two-year budget cycle, and that the surplus
would more than make up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   But several Texas Democrats are pouncing on the issue, blaming
the $1.7 billion in tax cuts championed by Bush for the shortfall,
and portraying the governor as having put short-term political
interests ahead of the state's fiscal stability.
</P>
<P>
   An internal memorandum leaked from the Texas Department of
Health has only fueled the controversy by predicting that Medicaid
shortfalls alone could reach $633 million by Aug. 31, 2001.
Ultimately, the Legislature must approve an emergency appropriation
next year to keep the state in the black.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden scrutiny of the Texas budget has also focused
attention on the $84 million in the state's Rainy Day Fund, an
account established in the 1980s after the oil boom ran out of
steam. Dick Lavine of the Center for Public Policy Priorities in
Austin said the Rainy Day Fund, as it stands, could pay for state
government services for about 16 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spokesman, Dan Bartlett, said that the Rainy Day Fund had
only $8 million when Bush took office in 1995 and that the account
has since grown tenfold.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been mentioning Bush's budget problems every day since
the issue emerged last Friday, although his main focus has been
another set topic.
</P>
<P>
   At the City Hall in Raytown, where he announced a proposal to
help local communities hire 10,000 more prosecutors, Gore began
with a minor tutorial on the Texas budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several days ago, we learned that under Governor Bush's
leadership, Texas has suddenly gone from its biggest budget surplus
ever to a budget shortfall, the most serious budget problem in
almost a decade,'' Gore said in a speech at the City Council
chamber here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we learn at a time of national prosperity _ indeed, the
longest economic boom in the history of America _ that Texas has
saved less for the future than almost every other state in
America,'' Gore continued. ``The state's so-called Rainy Day Fund
could barely withstand a drizzle. It's now so small that by this
fall there will be only enough money to run the Texas state
government for a single day. You know, there'd be a real problem if
Texas had a rainy season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
