<HEADER>
A7164 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-NYT     07-19 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATORS RACE AGAINST DEADLINE TO REACH MIDEAST ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story will be updated as necessary) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ and DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Hurtling toward a tension-crackling midnight
deadline, the Camp David peace summit seemed on the verge of either
a final breakthrough or a final breakdown as President Clinton kept
the Israeli and Palestinian leaders at the presidential retreat
well into Wednesday evening, determined to press for an agreement
until it was no longer worth trying.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was expected to address the nation before boarding a
plane for Japan sometime in the early morning hours of Thursday.
After a high-tension day of rapidly shifting moods, it remained
until the end unclear whether he would be pronouncing an end to a
bitter, 52-year conflict, announcing a partial solution or
proclaiming an impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Making an all-out effort to retrieve what looked like a failing
meeting, Clinton shuttled between the Israeli and Palestinian
leaders, fended off an Israeli initiative to leave early and
returned repeatedly to his advisers and to the negotiators in
search of a formula that would save the summit.
</P>
<P>
   During the nine-day summit, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel
and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, dealt with every issue
at stake in their conflict _ from borders and the fate of Jewish
settlements to the right of return of Palestinian refugees and the
status of Jerusalem. But it was unclear on Wednesday whether the
ultimate stumbling block was a single issue, like Jerusalem, or the
trade-offs needed to fashion an overall agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Each side was gearing up to lay the blame for a failed summit
squarely on the purported bad faith of the other party. Each leader
appealed privately to Clinton in letters written in the last 48
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The mood of the high-stakes day see-sawed. At midday, it seemed
certain that the talks were fizzling out. By early evening, when
the parties were still entrenched at Camp David and a tentatively
scheduled final press conferences were postponed, it seemed
possible that Clinton would be able to pull out an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The day started out with a tension-crackling midnight deadline,
which would allow Clinton to depart for Japan by early Thursday
morning, a departure he had already delayed by a day in a final bid
to rescue the summit.
</P>
<P>
   But it built to an unexpectedly quick first climax, when the
Israeli journalists accompanying Barak were ordered in the
afternoon to rush to their hotels for a security check so that
their luggage could be shuttled to Andrews Air Force Base for an 8
p.m. departure for Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   As the clock ran down, expectations were rife that there had
been a breakdown. Israeli television revealed, and an American
official later confirmed, that Barak had sent a letter to Clinton.
The letter, Israeli television said, announced the prime minister's
departure and laid the blame for the summit's failure on the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian side is conducting negotiations insincerely
and is not willing to negotiate in a serious and practical manner
for a permanent peace between us,'' an Israeli reporter cited as a
direct quotation from the letter.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed a done deal or non-deal but a senior Palestinian
negotiator, Abu Mazen, who himself was heading to the airport to
fly home to his son's wedding, brushed off what he saw as an
eleventh-hour Israeli tactic to increase pressure on the
Palestinians. Talks were ongoing, he said, and the fate of
Jerusalem, a seemingly intractable issue, was still on the table.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington reporters were told that Clinton, by himself,
might address reporters at the White House at 6 p.m., and that
Barak, by himself, would speak shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a 5:30 briefing at the Thurmont Elementary School some
five miles from Camp David, an announcement by Joe Lockhart, the
White House spokesman, gave the final day an extended lease on
life.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than confirming that the hopes for an agreement had
pretty much faded away, Lockhart told reporters instead that the
summit had reached a ``pivotal moment.'' Clinton, he said, was busy
``exploring every possible avenue'' for an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been going at this now non-stop for nine days in this
session,'' Lockhart said. ``I think we've obviously reached a
pivotal moment in these talks and I can't predict how it will come
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that as he spoke, Clinton was sitting down at the
retreat's Birch Cabin to his second face-to-face session on
Wednesdaywith the Arafat. Clinton had met with Barak earlier in the
day, but in what observers considered a sign of trouble, the two
Middle East leaders remained apart all day as the American
president shuttled between them.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the changing dynamic of refreshed momentum, Israeli
journalists returned to the press filing center, where one, Keren
Neubach, announced breathlessly that their bags were being returned
from the Air Force base to the Hampton Inn where they were staying.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that Clinton also received a letter from Arafat,
which arrived first, on Tuesday. He did not characterize its
contents, but Palestinian officials said that Arafat had reached a
peak of frustration on the eighth day.
</P>
<P>
   If news of the letters lowered expectations of a deal, Lockhart
reported that Clinton had managed by late afternoon to keep the
leaders from walking out. ''They are still there, they are all
still talking,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   When Lockhart described Clinton's last-dash effort to save the
situation, he made clear that the two leaders were having trouble
making concessions on deeply emotional issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders both want to go home with an agreement,'' Lockhart
said. ``The problem is the substance and structure of the
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the extended deadline would have to stand.
``There comes a time when you have to put a time limit on
discussions,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
