<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TRIES TO SALVAGE PEACE TALKS 
 

</HEADLINE>
 TALKS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton made a last-ditch effort
Wednesday to salvage a Middle East peace deal at the Camp David
summit, as the Israeli and Palestinian delegations prepared to
leave for home without an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton planned to
negotiate through the night if necessary. But he acknowledged that
neither Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak nor Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat were speaking to each other, a signal that there
would likely be no comprehensive deal struck before Clinton leaves
today for the Group of Eight economic summit in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked very hard to find a path to an agreement. At
this point in time, we have not reached that,'' Lockhart told
reporters during an evening briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Describing Clinton's 11th hour efforts as a ``pivotal moment in
these talks,'' he said the president still hoped to fashion some
kind of pact addressing the thorny issues of Palestinian statehood,
the final status of Jerusalem, the fate of refugees and Israeli
settlers.
</P>
<P>
   But he indicated that Clinton would likely declare the talks
``over'' around midnight if both sides rejected a final round of
U.S. proposals dealing with the division of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian sources reportedly told Reuters new service that one
of those proposals called for shared control in one part the Old
City of Jerusalem. The Palestinians would also win sovereignty over
some areas outside the city boundaries. But Israel would maintain
sovereignty over the remaining areas of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Reuters report, Arafat was given a deadline of
midnight Wednesday by Clinton to make up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart went on to describe the negotiations unfolding at the
presidential mountain retreat five miles from here as ``very
difficult'' and said Clinton had no plans to delay his trip to the
economic summit any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to have left on Wednesday for Japan, but he
postponed the trip by one day in hopes of persuading both sides to
compromise on their hard-line positions.
</P>
<P>
   Given the apparent intransigence of both sides, a grim-looking
Lockhart said, ``I don't think anyone sees any value in staying on
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   He also appeared to dismiss suggestions that Clinton might try
to reconvene meetings with the two leaders when he returns from
Japan on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our point, we've certainly made it clear that this is the
summit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton struggled to hold things together, he made a series
of telephone calls to other leaders in the Middle East to update
them on the talks and to sound them out on possible avenues left
unexplored that might convince Arafat and Barak to strike a deal.
But by late Wednesday night, there was no evidence that any of his
conversations had yielded a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, both Barak and Arafat spent most of the day
threatening to walk out, as Clinton shuttled back and forth between
them trying to convince them that a deal was still possible.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his best efforts, it appeared late Wednesday night
that he would be unable to convince the two sides to settle the key
issue that has confounded the negotiations all along _ whether the
Palestinians will be allowed to reclaim the areas of East Jerusalem
that were captured and annexed by the Israelis in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians are demanding that they be given sovereignty
over East Jerusalem, which they plan to designate as the capital of
a future Palestinian state. But the Israelis have insisted on
maintaining sovereignty over the entire holy city while granting
limited control of certain areas of East Jerusalem to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, neither Barak nor Arafat seemed ready to budge from
their stands. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
