<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS TRYING TO FIND TWO CORNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ You notice it most as the players make their
post-practice walk to the locker room, and the fans stacked 10 deep
behind a chain-link fence begin their daily ritual of begging for
autographs. And if not a signature, just a glance or a wave.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The frenzied screams of ``Emmitt ... Emmitt'' and ``Troy ...
Troy'' haven't changed in a decade of summers.
</P>
<P>
   But what's been very different this week are the quick pauses of
near silence as the adoring public hurriedly scans roster sheets,
trying to match names with jersey numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, star power is on the decline for the Cowboys.
Suddenly gone are a Michael, a Deion and a Moose, all of whom could
touch off near-riot conditions on the other side of the fence at
Midwestern State University.
</P>
<P>
   You still hear a lot of ``Dat,'' as Dat Nguyen remains extremely
popular, but a puzzled ``who's that?'' has now become a constant
and daily end-of-practice buzz by the fandom. The face of the
Cowboys is changing drastically, and so is ring-finger jewelry.
Only nine players remain from the last Super Bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to this new era of metallic-blue mystery men,
Mike Zimmer will be dealing with it constantly this summer, and
into the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer is the new defensive coordinator under Dave Campo, and
the former long-time secondary coach. The one most up-for-grabs
position on the team is cornerback. The Cowboys are looking for not
one, but two starters, and this duo must be found from a list of
Brand X candidates.
</P>
<P>
   For many, this will be considered the logical fallout from the
departure of Deioness. For many, replacing the Nine-Toed wonder
will be impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But on that note, consider one comment yesterday from Zimmer:
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely don't want to be helping our cornerbacks on every
snap. We've had to do it for the last two years, and it just takes
away so much from your overall defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. Deion and his do-rag were in that secondary the past two
seasons, although two years ago he missed nearly half the season
with various ailments, real and imagined.
</P>
<P>
   But the point here seems to be that the Cowboys were having the
same kind of cornerback woes with Deion. And if he were still here,
counting $8 million against the salary cap, a prevalent theme of
this camp would center on his health, his obvious slippage in
coverage last season, his availability for the 16-game season, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have a healthy Deion than anybody who plays the
position,'' said Zimmer, who remains a large fan of Nine-Toed.
</P>
<P>
   With him or without him, however, questions hang over both
corners. Owner Jerry Jones, another Deion lover, decided it was
time to move on minus Sanders, as the salary costs were not worth
the health risk. It was the most logical subtraction Jones has made
in years.
</P>
<P>
   But now what?
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, at a Valley Ranch minicamp, Zimmer offered the
possibility of rotating six cornerbacks, highly unusual to say the
least. It was mentioned that if he had to play six corners, that
might mean he couldn't find two, prompting a smile from Zimmer, and
a reply of ``now that's a negative outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there aren't two. And maybe not one. But the seven
leading candidates include veterans Kevin Smith and newcomer Ryan
McNeil, a spunky yet limited veteran, Charlie Williams, last year's
rookie free agent surprise, Duane Hawthorne, and three rookie draft
picks: Dwayne Goodrich, Mario Edwards and Kareem Larrimore.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Smith continues to be hobbled by injuries, and Zimmer was
frank yesterday in saying: ``Kevin has got to be better than what
we've seen thus far. I love Kevin Smith and his competitive nature,
but if he can't do the job, it would be unfair to the other 10 guys
on defense to put him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Zimmer lists McNeil as a starter at one corner,
with the other side posted as TBA. McNeil slid into free agency in
the off-season, and his career has been on the slide since he made
nine interceptions for St. Louis in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The key at cornerback is if and how quickly the three rookies
develop. Larrimore, the fourth-round pick out of West Texas A&AMP;M, is
Zimmer's early pick as the most likely to make an impact: ``He's
ahead of the others in speed and quickness. I think he has a chance
to be a great player in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   If shaky cornerback play continues, it would give Zimmer less
options in allowing safety Darren Woodson to come up in run
support, and in calling blitz packages. ``The most important part
of training camp is what we come out of here with at cornerback,''
Zimmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Deion is gone, and the worries continue. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
