<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TRADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TRADE LOAIZA FOR TWO MINOR-LEAGUERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Unwilling to go to arbitration with a $2.65
million middle reliever, the Rangers traded pitcher Esteban Loaiza
to the Toronto Blue Jays yesterday for minor-league pitcher Darwin
Cubillan and shortstop Mike Young.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Loaiza, who was sent to the bullpen earlier this week, is
eligible for arbitration in the off-season and the Rangers knew
that at some point they would have to trade him or release him.
They decided now was the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to decide if at the end of the year we could get better
value than what we could get now,'' Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin said. ``We didn't think we could. We felt now was the right
time because there were a number of teams interested. Toronto was
the most aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, acquired two years ago from the Pittsburgh Pirates ,
said: ``I can't say I'm happy. I was here two years, and I liked it
here. I'm disappointed, but what can you do. I loved the players,
the team and the atmosphere in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said trading Loaiza does not signal the start of a fire
sale for the Rangers, who went into last night's game having lost
five of seven. They were 9 1/2 games back of the Seattle Mariners
in the American League West, but Melvin said the Rangers' focus
should be on winning games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers might have to make changes if they don't start
making up ground on the Mariners and wild-card contenders, but
Melvin said: ``I don't think we're at that point. We've been
playing pretty good baseball. It's not like we're getting blown out
or playing poorly, like in 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are still trying to win, but they feel they have a
better chance with second-year pitchers Ryan Glynn and Matt Perisho
in the rotation. That made Loaiza expendable.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers wanted Young, the Blue Jays fifth-round pick in 1997
out of the University of California-Santa Barbara, who played in
the Double-A All-Star game this year. The deal was done when the
two sides settled on Cubillan as the second player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young was the guy we wanted all along,'' Melvin said. ``He's
got good athleticism, he's someone who can play on both sides of
the bag at second, he runs well, has a strong arm. We like the way
he plays the game; he's a real intelligent player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays used Young at shortstop and second base. The
Rangers plan to use him at shortstop with the Double-A Tulsa
Drillers to go with two of their other top prospects: first baseman
Carlos Pena and second baseman Jason Romano.
</P>
<P>
   Young was hitting .275 (95-for-345) at Double-A Tennessee with
24 doubles, five triples, six homers and 16 stolen bases. He was a
Florida State League All-Star at Class-A Dunedin last year, hitting
.313 with 36 stolen bases and 83 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash said: ``It's a seller's
market. Given the dearth of pitching, there's a price you have to
pay. From a purely scouting point of view and a development point
of view, we probably overpaid.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubillan, a native of Venezuela, was signed by the Blue Jays as
a minor-league free agent in the off-season. The Rangers also had
interest at the time. He was 3-1 with a 0.55 earned-run average and
six saves in 24 appearances for Triple-A Syracuse. He also appeared
in seven games for the Blue Jays, going 1-0 with an 8.04 ERA,
walking 11 batters in 14 2/3 innings. He has a combined 55
strikeouts in 48 1/3 innings this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a good arm,'' Melvin said. ``He throws 90 to 93
\Rmph\S, has a good changeup and pretty good command of his
pitches. He just needs to gain consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubillan is being sent to Triple-A Oklahoma. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
