<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 19, 2000 -- CIR-MP3-PLAYERS-3 --
Less than two years ago, the first handheld MP3 player was
introduced. That first player, the Rio 300 PMP, has now spawned its
third generation, the Rio 600, as sleek and curvy as its predecessor
was boxy and bland. And it is only one of a new wave of
consumer-friendly digital players, aimed not at the early adopters,
the tech-hungry minority who will buy anything, but at the mass
market. The Rio 600 by the S3's Rio division, priced at $169, which
plays MP3 and Windows Media Audio, upgradable to include AAC and
Audible. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- July 19, 2000 -- CIR-MP3-PLAYERS-2 -- Less
than two years ago, the first handheld MP3 player was introduced.
Now, new MP3 devices are challenging tape and CD players. From left
to right: The Nomad II by Creative Technology priced at $329,
available now and plays MP3 and Windows Media Audio and is upgradable
for more formats; The Yepp by Samsung, priced at $249.95, available
now and plays MP3; The Personal Sport Audio Play 120 by Nike priced
at 279, to be released in late August and plays MP3 and Windows Media
Audio, upgradable to include AAC and Audible. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- July 19, 2000 -- CIR-MP3-PLAYERS-1 --  Less
than two years ago, the first handheld MP3 player was introduced.
Now, new MP3 devices are challenging tape and CD players. Left, the
Rave MP 2300 by Sensory Science priced at $299 which plays MP3 and
Windows Media Audio. Center, a player not yet named by Iomega to be
released in the fall, which plays MP3 and Windows Media Audio and is
upgradable for additional formats. Right, Rush by Philips Electronics
priced at $299 to be released in August and plays MP3, Real Audio and
Audible. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BEIJING, China -- July 19, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. JULY
23 -- CHINA-DIVORCE-COX -- Divorce rates in China have more than
tripled, domestic violence has increased, and marriages now are based
more on individuals' feelings rather than the old standard of
political or familial ties. While many men with modern-day concubines
are from Hong Kong and Taiwan, plenty of mainland men are indulging
as well. Liu Donghua, a lawyer at the Center for Women's Law Studies
and Legal Services of Beijing University, believes mistresses should
be made to pay for breaking up marriages. (Julie Chao/Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 19, 2000 -- POE-HOUSE-DEMOLITION-2 --
To make way for a new law school building in New York University's
Washington Square Campus, this house, where Edgar Allen Poe once
lived, would be demolished. Residents of the area in downtown
Manhattan, known as Greenwich Village, have criticized the
university's construction projects which they considered to be
insensitive to the scale and historic character of the area. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 19, 2000 -- POE-HOUSE-DEMOLITION-1 --
