<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7172 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-hkn-STARS-LEMIEUX-TEX     07-19 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-hkn-STARS-LEMIEUX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEMIEUX CONSIDERS STARS' BID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Bargain hunters thus far in the free-agent
market, the Stars appear in position to land the last major
acquisition available.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Claude Lemieux, who has been a Stanley Cup champion with three
teams, is inching closer to signing a multi-year contract with the
Stars, possibly as soon as today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talks are continuing in a very amicable basis,'' Lemieux's
agent, Michael Barnett, said yesterday of his negotiations with
Stars general manager Bob Gainey. ``He [Lemieux] is approaching
this like the veteran that he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year veteran right winger, who helped the New Jersey
Devils knock off the Stars in six games last season to win the
Stanley Cup, is seeking a three- or four-year deal that would take
him to the end of his career. He also wants a raise from the $2.47
million he earned last season.
</P>
<P>
   Money might be the pivotal barricade to finalizing the deal to
this point. Barnett and Gainey spoke yesterday, but were unable to
strike a deal. Barnett said he will discuss yesterday's
negotiations with Lemieux and expects to be in contact with Gainey
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of problems associated with it that at this
point [we] haven't been able to find solutions for,'' Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux, who turned 35 Sunday, whittled his wish list down from
nine to six and finally to four teams: the Stars, New York Rangers,
New Jersey Devils and St. Louis Blues. Barnett said all four teams
remain in contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He [Lemieux] is taking his time to discuss the various
proposals,'' Barnett said. ``He's looking at rosters over a
three-year period. He is taking a very logical approach to where he
wants to end his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett said Lemieux, one of the game's top antagonists, is
evaluating his options on several levels. Foremost, he wants to
ensure his final years will be spent playing for a contender. He is
also looking ahead, seeking a destination that might provide him an
opportunity to remain in the NHL beyond retirement and provide a
long-term home for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett said Lemieux is also weighing issues such as state
taxes. Texas is the lone state of the four on Lemieux's wish list
that does not have a state income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux, 6-foot-1, 225 pounds, has won the Stanley Cup with
Montreal (1986), Colorado (1996) and twice with New Jersey (1995,
2000). As a rookie in '86, he was Gainey's teammate on the Stanley
Cup-champion Canadiens. After playing in 10 regular-season games
that season, Lemieux scored 10 goals and had six assists in 20
playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   While he has posted outstanding regular seasons, including
scoring 30 or more goals five times, the postseason cemented his
reputation as a hard-nosed, abrasive instigator and a premiere
clutch goal scorer. He won the Conn Smythe Trophy as the playoff
MVP with the Devils in 1995 when he scored 13 goals, scoring on 20
percent of his shots.
CANADIENS PURSUE CARBONNEAU Former Stars center Guy Carbonneau
might be headed back to Montreal, where he played for 12 seasons
and enjoys hero status. Stars general manager Bob Gainey said the
Canadiens have offered Carbonneau, who retired earlier this month,
a position within their organization.
</P>
<P>
   Gainey said Carbonneau phoned him from Montreal after receiving
the offer to discuss specific opportunities with the Stars and
where they might lead in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Gainey said he will speak with Carbonneau next week to further
discuss Carbonneau's possible future within the Stars'
organization. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
