<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CLINTON-DEM-VP-NYT &LR;      07-19 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEM-VP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PRIVATE, CLINTON MAKES HIS CHOICES KNOWN FOR V.P. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Maine, Ind., S.D., R.I., Nev., Conn.)  By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has told friends and associates
that two of his favorite choices for Vice President Al Gore's
running mate are former Sen. George Mitchell and Sen. Bob Graham,
both of whom he considered picking eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has gone out of his way to stay clear of the selection
process, people close to him said, because he wanted to avoid
appearing as though he was imposing his preferences on Gore _ or
injecting himself into his vice president's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton is regarded by many Democrats as his party's most
brilliant strategist. And when he is questioned privately at party
functions about who he thinks would make sound choices, he has not
been reluctant about offering his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is a political brain attached to a body,'' said
a Democratic lobbyist who has heard Clinton rattle off vice
presidential possibilities recently. ``He can't help himself. It's
how he's wired.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to Clinton said he sounds most animated when he is
discussing Mitchell, the former Senate Democratic leader from Maine
whom he picked to preside over the peace negotiations in Ireland.
Clinton has told people that Mitchell would bring a weight and
dignity to the ticket, has no skeletons in his closet and would be
particularly appealing because he is Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks it would be great,'' said one person who has talked
to Clinton about Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton loves him,'' said a Democratic strategist close to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had considered Mitchell as a potential running mate in
1992, but he was not on the final short list, according to people
involved in the process then.
</P>
<P>
   The president also tells people he has quite high regard for
Graham of Florida, who, according to aides at the time, he came
quite close to selecting eight years ago. The president has long
been deeply interested _ some of his aides say obsessed _ in
winning Florida for the Democrats and has told people that could
happen if Graham were on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   One person who worked closely with Clinton eight years ago said
he remembered that the then-governor of Arkansas said more than
once that Graham, who had been governor of Florida, ``was the best
governor I served with.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Graham said that after undergoing the
background checks and interview with Clinton in 1992 he was not
sure whether he would be picked. But he said he had been
``anxious'' because he was seeking re-election that year and wanted
the matter settled. In Florida, candidates cannot run
simultaneously for the Senate and on the national ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I feel as if I was going to get a call to join the ticket
or definitely not going to get one? I didn't know,'' Graham
recalled. ``I was uncertain as to what Governor Clinton's decision
was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he discussed his prospects for helping Clinton win
Florida that year, Graham said: ``I'm sure we did. He has told me
personally that he feels one of the major mistakes that was made in
'92 was that they gave up on Florida too early.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Clinton said he is also intrigued with Sen. Evan Bayh
of Indiana because of Bayh's involvement with the Democratic
Leadership Council _ a centrist group that Clinton once headed _
and because he would evoke an energetic and vibrant image, similar
Gore's when he was picked in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to Clinton said the president spoke positively
early on about Defense Secretary William Cohen, a former Republican
senator. But Cohen is not discussed much anymore by people close to
Gore. Some Gore loyalists said they had been disturbed about nice
things Cohen said about Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in a
television interview in May.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can be considered an expert on the selection of a
running mate. He sometimes says that his choice of Gore will be an
important part of his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The president's musings are very sensitive in Gore's circles.
People who have discussed the No. 2 slot with the president said he
has been careful not to push one prospect above another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's smart enough not to say, `My first choice is ...''' said
one Democratic official who has talked with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   That official also said he believed that Gore was so concerned
about being viewed as independent from the administration that he
might change his mind on a choice if it looked like he was
following the president's counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Like his vice president, Clinton seems to enjoy keeping up the
suspense. At a fund-raising reception last month for Sen.
Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, Clinton joked about the selection
process in a hotel ballroom full of senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing crowd of people here tonight,'' Clinton said.
``And not all of them want to be vice president. But a lot do.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the audience were Sens. Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, Jack Reed of Rhode Island
and Harry Reid of Nevada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-UTENN-WHISTLEBLOWER-1     07-19 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTENN-WHISTLEBLOWER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE WHISTLE-BLOWER WORRIES ABOUT HER FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.J., Ore., Ill.)   (ADDS that Bensel-Meyers is a tenured associate professor in 8th
graf) 
 (Eds.: Buuck in 2nd graf if 2nd take is cq) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The whistle-blower finds comfort in her
office these days, surrounded by books about Renaissance drama, her
speciality. So long as Linda Bensel-Meyers can keep her mind in the
past, she can forget about the lawsuits against her, the damage to
her marriage, the anger of University of Tennessee officials and
coaches, the threats by local fans who curse her as a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   But she is reminded of the present by the fat leather briefcase
leaning against a leg of her desk. It is stuffed with what she
calls her evidence, the paper trails that always lead back to the
altered grades, ``friendly'' courses and plagiarized papers that
she says the athletic department uses to keep varsity players
eligible.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the evidence is being used against her; one suit
implies she has publicly released confidential student information,
which she denies. After some five years of being ignored by the
administration, she talked to ESPN last September after it began
its own investigation of the athletic tutoring system.
</P>
<P>
   Four football players were suspended for a game pending the
school's investigation, and Bensel-Meyers became a well-known
pariah on campus. Students taunt her, teachers turn away. She says
her office has been broken into, mostly as intimidation, she
thinks. She is sitting now with her back to the office window that
overlooks the 107,000-seat football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never feel sorry for myself,'' she says, just a bit too
stoutly, ``because I am responsible for my own decisions. I am not
a victim. I hate it when people look at me with pity. Sometimes,
however, I despair.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the righteousness of this 47-year-old Methodist church
organist pops up. ``It is hard for one good person to live among
those who are not good, and to try to make the right choices,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers is not alone these days as the American
Association of University Professors and another national group of
faculty members convened last year at Drake University in Iowa and
considered reforms in intercollegiate sports. The Drake Group, in
particular, has declared that big-time college sports is basically
a corrupting influence on the academic mission of the university.
And the Rutgers 1000, a group of professors and students, is
calling for that university to divest itself of varsity sports.
</P>
<P>
   At Tennessee, a 44,000-student university, most members of the
administration and the athletic department who speak on the record
say Bensel-Meyers who is a tenured associate professor, has made
all the wrong choices, attacking a source of state pride. The
Volunteers were national football champions two seasons ago. And,
as officials point out, the NCAA conducted an investigation for
months on her charges and found no violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campus is just weary of reading about all her charges,''
said the university president, J. Wade Gilley. ``We've had nine, 10
investigations in the 11 months I've been here, by the faculty
senate, the conference, the National Collegiate Athletic
Association, the Federal Bureau of Investigation _ what have I left
out? _ and nothing was found that violated rules or laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilley says he thinks Bensel-Meyers may have an agenda, a ``big,
pregnant idea,'' about de-emphasizing college sports. If that's it,
he chuckles, then there's no better place to start than at a place
that ``epitomizes the system, like Notre Dame or Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Her voice is low. ``This is not my cause,'' she says. She talks
into her hand. Her eyes rarely make contact. ``I'm a company
person. I thought I'd be here forever. I went through channels. But
my options have been limited because no one would listen to what
I've been saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when they did hear me, the attitude was, just fail the
athlete who plagiarized. How can I do that, when the plagiarism was
institutional, when the athlete thinks he's supposed to turn in a
paper written by one of the hired tutors? How can I sacrifice some
poor guy who bought into the dream just like me, to get off the
farm.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers left the family chicken farm in Pendleton, Ore.,
30 years ago for a scholarship to the University of Chicago. She
always loved sports, she says, the third of four children who all
became teachers. She roughhoused with her brothers. She ran track
in high school and continued to play basketball and volleyball at
the University of Oregon, where her Ph.D. dissertation was on ``The
Duchess of Malfi,'' a bloodthirsty revenge tragedy, written by John
Webster circa 1613.
</P>
<P>
   At Tennessee, where she began her first tenure-track teaching
job in 1986, she says she has rarely missed a Volunteers football
game on television. But she has never taken her three teen-age sons
to the stadium because she is afraid of crowds and heights.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, she became director of composition, a job she loved,
she said, because the required first-year writing course gave her a
chance to shape a curriculum that would teach critical thinking and
``empower'' the many ``provincial, religious, concrete thinkers,''
who, as she had been, were the first generation in their families
to attend college. She borrowed from the great books courses
created at Chicago and from her own scholarship. She sees parallels
between the Age of Gutenberg, when the printing press helped
replace ethical reasoning with scientific thought, and the Age of
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Among her early tasks was hiring and training the tutors who
would help athletes, particularly male football and basketball
players. Slowly, over the years, she began to realize, she says,
that the athletes were being exploited by a system that did not
deliver a real education in return for the millions of dollars the
university made from their time and energy. Tutors came back with
stories of being sexually harassed by athletes, not to mention
having to write their term papers.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers, with access to transcripts, began to notice
patterns of grades being altered, of clusters of unusually high
grades for athletes in certain courses, of special privileges. She
thought there was abuse in the labeling of certain athletes as
having disabilities, which could excuse them from having to read or
write. She began to send memos to her superiors. She was ignored.
She began sending e-mail messages, first to foreign colleagues whom
she had met at Renaissance conferences, then with almost anyone who
seemed to understand and would respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda is naive, a straight arrow who never understood the
power she came up against,'' says Jeffrey Kovac, a 51-year-old
chemistry professor and one of Bensel-Meyers' few public supporters
at Tennessee. Last week, he quietly announced a legal defense fund
to which faculty could contribute anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Most faculty are cynical about sports,'' Kovac said.
``Athletes get away with murder, so what, just let me concentrate
on neutron scattering. But I've also been a professional soccer
referee for 20 years, and I've always thought, all we have is our
integrity and a whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovac's fund-raising is welcome news to David L. Buuck, a
graduate of Tennessee and its law school who finds himself shunned,
as well as underpaid, while defending Bensel-Meyers. The libel suit
against ESPN.com and a former head of the tutoring service, by a
former player and a former tutor, does not even name Bensel-Meyers,
but she had promised to pay for any of her teachers who were sued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't let them be punished because someone's trying to get
at me,'' she said. ``I worry about my seven doctoral students,
working on dissertations, mostly on the Renaissance. What if after
all this, my letters of recommendation are poison?''
</P>
<P>
   An injunction to keep his records private was filed by Spencer
Riley, the center on last year's football team who is now trying
out for the Buffalo Bills. The university's failure to defend her
along with itself sent a chill through the faculty; would this be a
precedent to punish anyone out of favor who became a target of
litigation?
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers finds herself more and more isolated, with fewer
responsibilities. She thinks she may be fired. She is afraid of
going to her car at night in the campus underground garage. Her
children hear remarks about her at school. Her husband, who thinks
she is hurting the family, rarely talks to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for my kids to see what I'm doing,'' she
says, not sounding absolutely certain. ``Or it will be someday. We
can't teach people abuse of the law and not expect it will lead to
more crime. We're losing values in this country, and the university
may be the only place left to preserve these values.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to teach kids there's a reason to be on earth and it's
not just grabbing off pleasure. I believe if people have all the
information they'll choose the right thing. That's why I talk to
the media, why I send out all these e-mails. But then I have this
image of myself doing cartwheels along the edge of a cliff,
blindfolded. I think I'll be all right as long as I don't see where
I'm going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-680&AMP;A     07-19 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD LIFT BAN ON IMPORT OF U.S. DRUGS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Vt., La., Mich., N.D.)  By STEVEN A. HOLMES and ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Wednesday overwhelming voted to
permit pharmacies and wholesale distributors of prescription drugs
to import and sell U.S.-made medicine that originally had been
exported to foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   But in voting 74-21 to overturn the ban on such imports, the
lawmakers also unanimously adopted an amendment requiring the Food
and Drug administration to certify that the action would pose no
risk to public health and safety and would significantly reduce
costs to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment sponsored by Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., could
delay lifting the ban by tying up the food and drug agency in an
extensive rule-making exercise to determine precisely how it would
guarantee the safety and low cost of imported drugs that are
reimported.
</P>
<P>
   Given the possibility of delay, supporters of the measure
emphasized its symbolic importance. Regardless of whether it
becomes law, the measure's backers say the vote in the Senate,
along with a vote approving a similar measure in the House last
week, sends a strong signal to the pharmaceutical industry that it
must do something about its prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a shot across the bow,'' said Sen. James Jeffords,
R.-Vt., who is the chief Senate sponsor of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Jeffords' legislation becomes law, drug manufacturers
said, consumers might not see any savings because there was no
assurance that pharmacists and wholesalers would pass on the lower
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's action in the Senate and the similar action last
week in the House came on amendments to a bill to finance the
operations of the Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   The amendments vary slightly, but would have the same effect.
The differences are to be reconciled in a Senate-House conference.
</P>
<P>
   Because the legislation is an amendment to a spending bill, even
its supporters acknowledge that it could be dropped in the give and
take of negotiations with the White House at the end of the fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures cover the importation into the United States of
prescription medications that have been produced here or in foreign
pharmaceutical plants approved by the Food and Drug Administration.
Proponents of the measure have argued that pharmaceutical companies
often get tax breaks for developing drugs, then charge much more in
the United States than in foreign countries for the same drug.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say that ending the ban would result in a flood of
cheap, counterfeit imports because there is no way the food and
drug agency can police the way drugs are stored, transported or
produced abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's coming from Canada, that's not a bad deal,'' said Sen.
John Breaux, D-La. ``But this amendment is not limited to Canada.
We'd be importing from third world countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate action responds to pleas by the elderly, the
country's most politically active demographic group, which has in
recent years expressed concern about the high cost of prescription
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Because countries like Canada subject prescription medicines to
price controls, popular drugs like Lipitor, the anti-cholesterol
medication and Prozac, the anti-depressant, cost much less there _
in some cases half as much. Federal law says that a prescription
drug made in the United States and exported may not be reimported
except by the manufacturer. The law, adopted in 1988, sought to
choke off a ``gray market'' for drugs that were counterfeit,
adulterated or too old to be used safely.
</P>
<P>
   The 1988 measure, introduced by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., was
widely seen as a consumer protection measure. Congressional
investigators documented many cases in which counterfeit drugs,
including birth control pills, had been imported.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Congress last year, Dr. David Kessler, the former
commissioner of food and drugs, said, ``The dangers of allowing
reimportation of prescription drugs may be even greater today than
they were in 1986.'' With the rise of Internet pharmacies, he said,
``the opportunities for illicit distribution of adulterated and
counterfeit products have grown as well.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jeffords tried to address such concerns. His amendment says that
the Department of Health and Human Services, in allowing
pharmacists and wholesalers to import prescription drugs, must
establish safeguards to protect public health and to guarantee the
safety and effectiveness of the imported products.
</P>
<P>
   Support for such legislation has increased along with the cost
of prescription drugs. In an interview, Rep. Bernard Sanders,
I-Vt., said, ``Safety is a legitimate issue, but because of the
high price of drugs, hundreds of thousands of elderly sick people
cannot afford to fill the prescriptions they receive.'' Sanders has
been pushing legislation to allow access to low-cost foreign drugs
since May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper advertisements in the last few days, the
Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America, representing
major drug companies, expressed alarm at Jeffords' proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., denounced the advertisements. ``The
pharmaceutical industry wants to scare people into believing the
legislation is bad for consumers,'' he said. ``We would assure the
safety of the drug supply, but we would also assure consumers they
can have access to drugs that are priced reasonably.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jennings, the health policy coordinator at the White
House, said Wednesday night that the administration had not opposed
Jeffords' amendment. But Jennings said Congress ought to provide
money to the food and drug agency so that it can assure the safety
and purity of imported drugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
