<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTRACEPTIVE-SUIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT CLAIMS LACK OF CONTRACEPTIVE COVERAGE IS DISCRIMINATORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SCHUBERT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A pharmacist at Bartell Drugs, shocked that her
medical plan doesn't cover prescriptions for contraceptives, on
Wednesday filed a lawsuit arguing that the lack of coverage amounts
to sex discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court here, is backed by the
legal and financial resources of Planned Parenthood and is the
latest tactic in the organization's push to make coverage for
prescription contraceptives as universal as coverage for
vaccinations.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first known federal case to challenge the lack of
prescription contraception coverage on the basis of Title VII, the
federal Civil Rights Act, which prohibits discriminatory employment
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sex discrimination when male employees get their basic
health care needs covered by insurance, but women are forced to pay
for theirs,'' said Gloria Feldt, president of Planned Parenthood
Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff is Jennifer Erickson, a pharmacist in Seattle. But
court papers ask that it be made a class-action lawsuit, covering
women enrolled in Bartell's self-insured prescription plan who use
contraceptives. The goal is an order requiring Bartell to cover all
FDA-approved prescription contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Class action is a mechanism that allows people to challenge
the status quo,'' said Roberta Riley, staff attorney for Planned
Parenthood of Western Washington.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the suit could have broad implications for
private employers and their female employees across the country.
Three out of four American women of child-bearing age rely on
employer-provided insurance plans, according to the Alan Guttmacher
Institute, a New York-based research organization that studies
reproductive issues.
</P>
<P>
   But half of all fee-for-service plans do not cover any
reversible contraception, and only 15 percent cover all five
prescription contraception options: the birth control pill, IUDs,
diaphragms, Norplant implants and the drug Depo-Prevera.
</P>
<P>
   Bartell has not yet been served with the lawsuit, but a company
official said Wednesday that the firm's comprehensive health
benefits, provided at no cost to the employees, are lawful and
non-discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``No medical benefit program covers every possible cost,'' said
Jean Bartell Barber, the company's chief financial officer, at a
press conference Wednesday. ``For example, we do not cover
prescriptions for Viagra, infertility drugs, drugs for weight
reduction, immunization agents, drugs for cosmetic purposes and
various other items.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug store chain reviews its health plans once a year,
Barber said, but cost dictates how much the company can add.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we add something to the plan, we have to take something
away from the plan,'' Barber said.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson, 26, started working for Bartell in February 1999. It
is, on the whole, a great company to work for, she said. But she
was surprised to find that contraceptives were not part of her
prescription health care benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson, who is married, currently pays more than $300 a year
out-of-pocket for birth control pills, but she said other women
can't always afford that. As a pharmacist, Erickson said every day
she tells many women who come in to fill prescriptions that
contraceptives aren't covered under their health plans either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see women actually walk away from the counter when it's
not covered,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson questioned the policy and wrote a letter to the
benefits department asking that the coverage be changed. In
December, she filed a complaint with the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission, a legal prerequisite to filing a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until today, no one has asked a court to stop this form of
discrimination that blocks a woman's access to basic health care,''
said Roberta Riley, staff attorney at Planned Parenthood of Western
Washington and lead attorney for this case.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is the first lawsuit of its kind, advocacy groups
have been pushing to have prescription contraceptives covered in
health plans for a number of years.
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood of Western Washington has been waging a
campaign urging employers to voluntarily add prescription
contraceptives to their health-care plans. As a result, Microsoft,
Swedish Medical Center and Darigold have all extended their
prescription benefits to include contraceptives. Some said they
didn't realize contraceptives weren't included in their health
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lack of awareness for many companies,'' said Chris
Charbonneau, president and CEO of Planned Parenthood of Western
Washington. ``There are some companies, however, that are really
recalcitrant.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen states have laws that require contraceptive coverage;
Washington is not among them. Federal legislation that would
require all health plans nationwide to cover contraception has been
stalled in Congress since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely an issue that all the people who are
concerned with reproductive rights are concerned about,'' said
Louise Melling, associate director of the ACLU's Reproductive
Rights Project. ``Reproductive rights include the right to have a
child _ and the right not to have a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Belle Taylor-McGhee, executive director of the California
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, argues that the
reproductive health services have been segregated from overall
health care for too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it interesting that insurers will pay for
pregnancy-related services, but they won't pay for services related
to making sure that a woman doesn't have an unwanted pregnancy?''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those involved in the lawsuit don't buy the argument that
contraceptions are an elective drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without contraception, the average woman would have 12 to 15
pregnancies in her lifetime,'' said Riley, the lead attorney.
``This is basic health care for women.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
