<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBASUMM-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALWAYS THERE TO HELP OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAMES MELROY  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ For those who venture to the 2000 NBA
Summer Pro League at the Pyramid, there are many familiar faces
competing on the court, hoping to leave an impression on those who
are watching.
</P>
<P>
   One such face is familiar to fans of Southern California
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Cooper has been a part of local basketball for 15 years,
playing at Lakewood High school before continuing his education
(and playing days) at USC.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike a majority of the athletes remaining at the Summer
Pro League, he has played in the NBA, having stints with teams such
as the Lakers and the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, Cooper has been a mainstay at the
Pyramid during the summer, hoping to showcase his skills enough so
that another NBA team would decide to add him to their roster.
</P>
<P>
   At 31, he continues to maintain the ultimate trait of a good
point guard: unselfishness. In fact, some of the younger athletes
playing with Cooper come to the 6-1 guard, looking for some
guidance from someone who has been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got guys that look to me for advice, but I think it's just
because I am getting old,'' Cooper said half-jokingly. ``I've been
around the block a little bit. As far as the NBA goes, those teams
are looking for new faces. I think that's a shame, but at the same
time I can understand that. So, if I can help a young guy out, I'll
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping younger players out might be something Cooper ends up
doing for a long time. He said that after his playing days end, a
new endeavor might be on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'd like to buy and sell real estate, but I think my
calling is to coach, to be a college coach,'' Cooper said. ``I've
been offered a few coaching jobs since I've graduated from college.
Southern Illinois, Northern Arizona and Loyola Marymount are a few
of the schools I could help out with.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Cooper takes great pride in improving, not only himself,
but others that come in contact with him. For instance, the
Lakewood graduate joined a struggling college program in the
Trojans. But along with Harold Miner and head coach George
Raveling, Cooper helped lead USC to an NCAA Tournament berth in his
senior year.
</P>
<P>
   And now, almost 10 years later, Cooper is showing that his will
to win and ability to lead hasn't waned one bit.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Coopers' Anaheim Roadrunners trailed the Supreme
Court All-Stars by nine midway through the fourth quarter. But with
less than 6:30 remaining in the game, Cooper ran off eight
consecutive points, including a pair of 3-pointers, in a span of
just over a minute. The run by Cooper, who finished the game with
17 points, sparked the Roadrunners to a 107-100 victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
