<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED AND AMERICAN BEAT EARNING EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Earnings at the nation's two largest airline
companies, UAL Corp., the parent of United Airlines, and AMR Corp.,
owner of American Airlines, handily beat Wall Street expectations
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news was tempered by United's warning of weaker
earnings in the current quarter, sparking a large selloff of
airline stocks, led by UAL.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, US Airways, the No. 6 carrier, said its profit
plunged 41 percent, excluding one-time gains, while TWA, which has
continued to elude profitability despite the travel boom, narrowed
its losses more than analysts had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The strong showing by United and American came after similar
reports by Continental Airlines and the low-fare leader Southwest
Airlines on Tuesday. ``If the economy is slowing down, we don't see
it in the airline business,'' said Tom Horton, AMR's chief
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profit at UAL rose 17 percent, to $408 million, or
$3.47 a share, compared with $349 million, or $2.86 a share, in the
period a year earlier. Revenue rose 13 percent, to $5.11 billion
from $4.54 billion in 1999. Analysts had expected the company to
earn $3.24 a share, according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   United said that it benefited from higher fares and a 6.8
percent increase in passenger traffic during the quarter, led by a
21 percent increase in the Asia-Pacific region. That more than made
up for the surge in fuel prices, which is an airline's
second-biggest expense after labor, thanks to an aggressive hedging
program that locked in fuel costs before the big price increases.
</P>
<P>
   But United also suffered from several operational headaches
during the quarter that gave it the poorest on-time record and most
flight cancellations of the major airlines. Executives blamed
unusually poor weather, the air-traffic control system and the
refusal of many of its pilots, who are angry about the slow pace of
contract negotiations, to fly overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Rono Dutta, UAL's president, said that the pilot action cost the
company $50 million during the quarter. United has cut thousands of
flights and is adding more time into its schedule to try to reduce
cancellations and delays.
</P>
<P>
   Dutta said that revenue would continue to be strong in the
current quarter but that the reduction in capacity along with
higher fuel and wage costs would result in earnings between $2.60
and $3.20 a share, lower than analysts were expecting.
</P>
<P>
   The news caused shares of UAL to plunge $6, or 10.1 percent, to
$53.25 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   AMR reported a 32 percent surge in profit, excluding
extraordinary items, to $285 million, or $1.75 a share, compared
with $216 million, or $1.36 a share, in the quarter a year earlier.
Revenue rose 10.4 percent, to $5 billion from $4.5 billion last
year. Analysts had expected AMR to earn $1.57, according to First
Call.
</P>
<P>
   American also benefited from hedging its fuel costs, saving $105
million during the quarter, Horton said. He said that the airline
also gained $10 million to $15 million in additional revenue by
attracting passengers displaced by cancellations at United, its
main competitor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, American faced an easier comparison with results in
the quarter a year earlier, when its bookings were weakened by the
aftermath of a pilot sickout that crippled its operations. And a
recent decision to remove seats from most of its airplanes to give
passengers more legroom helped increase its average fare.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue at US Airways rose 6.4 percent during the quarter, to
$2.43 billion from $2.28 billion in 1999. But profit fell to $80
million, or $1.17 a share, compared with $136 million, or $1.83 a
share, in 1999, excluding one-time gains. Analysts were expecting
US Airways to earn $1.36 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger demand was strong at the airline, which agreed in May
to be acquired by UAL for $4.3 billion, but it was hurt more by the
rise in the cost of fuel than were United and American. US Airways
said that its fuel costs rose nearly 63 percent during the quarter,
or $102 million, whereas American said its fuel costs rose only 37
percent. In addition, US Airways lost some lucrative business
passengers who shied away from the airline because of the threat of
a strike by its flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Rakesh Gangwal, the chief executive of US Airways, told analysts
that the airline was focusing on winning back business travelers.
But he predicted a further decline in unit revenue during the third
quarter and another hit from higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   TWA also had record traffic during the quarter. Revenue rose
10.3 percent, to $954.9 million from $866 million. But the
struggling airline, which does not aggressively hedge its fuel
costs, was still in the red. TWA said that it lost $4.2 million, or
8 cents a share, compared with a loss of $5.3 million, or 17 cents
a share, in the quarter a year earlier. Still, analysts had
expected the airline to lose 33 cents a share during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's last profitable quarter was two years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
