<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SALES SLUMP, IBM'S EARNINGS RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite declining sales, IBM managed to surprise Wall
Street on Wednesday with earnings of $1.9 billion for the second
quarter, up 12 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   That works out to $1.06 per share, well above the $1.00 Wall
Street expected.
</P>
<P>
   The company compensated for weak sales, especially of personal
computers and mainframes, through strict cost controls. It also
bought back $1.8 billion of its stock, increasing the per-share
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts dismissed the share buybacks and cost cutting as
necessary evils.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM has not been getting credit for beating the earnings
estimates,'' said Laura Conigliaro, an analyst with Goldman Sachs.
``Their revenues are so sorry looking, you wouldn't want to give
them the wrong idea. The truth of the matter is that the market
needs to see revenue turn around and they know it.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts took heart that IBM, did not back off its
optimistic forecasts for the second half of the year, despite more
negative assessments in recent weeks by services companies like
Electronic Data Systems and software companies like Computer
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors were nervous that IBM would back off from the second
half and they didn't do that,'' said Steven Milunovich, an analyst
with Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   In after-hours trading, IBM's shares rose to $109, after closing
at $104.16, up $1.28, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In a long conference call with analysts, IBM detailed signs of
improvement in most of its business lines.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, IBM's fast growing Global Services division, which
designs and operates computer systems for other companies, signed
contracts worth $20 billion over the next several years, far more
than analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the company reduced the loss in its personal computer
business to $69 million, from $100 million a year earlier, and John
R. Joyce, the company's chief financial officer, told analysts the
unit should break even by the end of the year. He said that in the
second quarter, 24 percent of the company's PC sales were direct to
customers, rather than through dealers, up from 19 percent in the
previous three months. By the end of the year, he said, direct
sales, the technique used to great effect by Dell Computer, should
be 35 percent of IBM's PC sales.
</P>
<P>
   Other strong areas included Unix servers and storage systems,
both in increasing demand by companies operating Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, IBM said the rise in the dollar reduced sales
overseas by 1 percent in dollar terms. And it said it was having
continued difficulty with its hard disk drive business.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, hardware revenue fell by 4.9 percent to $9.2 billion.
Services revenue increased by 2.4 percent to $8.2 billion. Software
revenue increased by 1.7 percent to $3.2 billion. And financing
revenue increased by 10.1 percent to $819 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its services revenue actually grew by 10
percent when it excluded figures for its network services unit,
which IBM sold to AT&AMP;T last year, and for services related to the
Year 2000 computer bug, demand for which has fallen off sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Sales declined in the Americas and Europe, but increased sharply
in Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
