A7188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BANK-EARNINGS-NYT     07-19 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIGROUP AND CHASE REPORT HIGHER EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Citigroup, the nation's largest financial services
company, earned more than $3 billion for the second consecutive
quarter, despite a sharp drop in the performance of its Salomon
Smith Barney securities unit. At Chase Manhattan Bank, the No. 3
United States bank, the drag on earnings came from its investments
in private companies.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies reported second-quarter earnings on Wednesday
that were higher than a year earlier and exceeded analysts
expectations. Citigroup shares rose $1.3125, to $68, while Chase
shares slipped 25 cents, to $50.6875.
</P>
<P>
   Strong growth in its consumer businesses helped Citigroup
increase its net income 23 percent, to $3.005 billion, or 87 cents
a diluted share, from $2.45 billion, or 70 cents a share, in the
second quarter of 1999. That profit was down significantly from
Citigroup's first-quarter profit of $3.6 billion, which was the
biggest quarterly profit any company has reported, according to
First Call/Thomson Financial. Analysts expected earnings of 83
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings at the Salomon unit were down 33 percent from the first
quarter and up just 5 percent from the period a year earlier, at
$641 million. Salomon was hurt by the downturn in stock market
activity and a slowdown in bond trading, caused in part by rising
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford I. Weill, Citigroup's chairman and chief executive,
noted that the Smith Barney brokerage unit took in $24 billion in
new money from U.S. customers in the quarter, surpassing the $11
billion its bigger rival Merrill Lynch reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at what some of our competitors did, relative to the
size of our sales force, we did excellent,'' Weill said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Merrill, which said that it would cut 1,800 jobs in its
brokerage unit, Smith Barney has no layoffs planned, Weill said.
``We run a very efficient retail brokerage business,'' he said.
``We like to run it on a steady-as-you-go basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Weill said that rising interest rates had not posed a problem
for Citigroup's consumer lending businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to see in the U.S. very strong credit quality
trends with delinquencies continuing to decline,'' he said.
``Writeoffs are at the lowest level in five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup said it would split its shares 4 for 3 next month.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away at Chase headquarters, executives sounded
upbeat even though Chase's earnings fell 22 percent, to $1.09
billion, or 85 cents a diluted share, from $1.39 billion, or $1.06
a share, a year earlier. Excluding one-time charges, Chase earned
95 cents a share, beating analysts estimates by 12 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Chase officials attributed most of the decline in profit to the
falling value of its private equity investments. Chase had private
equity gains of just $298 million, down from $513 million a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real reassuring number that showed that even in a
tough, dislocated market, they can protect their reported
earnings,'' said Judah Kraushaar, an analyst at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are more concerned about the bank's expenses rising
faster than its revenue, Kraushaar said. Chase has spent a lot of
money hiring people and buying companies to add heft to its
investment banking business and, he said, the ``question for
investors is can they stay on top of the investments and turn it
around quickly?''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Shapiro, Chase's vice chairman, tried to reassure investors
that spending would not outpace revenue growth for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have what I call a field of dreams strategy that says
we will spend all of this money and hope that one day the revenues
will come in and pay for it,'' he said. ``We intend to pay for
things on a pay-as-you-go basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
