A7189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-19 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Ga.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS: GETTING PERSONAL WITH BUSH
</P>
<P>
   For voters who were not feeling up close and personal enough
with the candidacy of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the campaign
Wednesday unveiled a redesigned Web site, www.GeorgeWBush.com, with
a new feature, ``My George W.'' It allows users to receive e-mail
messages from the campaign about issues of specific interest to
them.
</P>
<P>
   The revised site, which has a less cluttered look than its
previous incarnation and includes sections like ``GWB TV,'' which
is devoted to video clips of Bush, is being promoted in a novel
way, too. The campaign says it is running the first political
television commercial designed solely to advertise a candidate's
Web site. The unnarrated, 30-second spot scans the campaign's home
page and supplies the address of the Web site, where users can also
answer a daily trivia question and win Bush campaign souvenirs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE ISSUES: ANTI-ABORTION PLANK
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of abortion rights said Wednesday that they had told
Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin, the chairman of the Republican
platform committee, that they had not ruled out a floor fight to
change the platform's strong anti-abortion stance. The exchange
occurred in a meeting with Thompson in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has said repeatedly that he is under instructions from
party leaders to make no changes in the platform's abortion plank,
which calls for a constitutional ban on the practice without
exceptions. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumed nominee, has
said he favors keeping that language.
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Cullman, co-chairwoman of the Republican Pro-Choice
Coalition, said she and her colleagues told Thompson that their
struggle would not end with the vote of the platform committee.
Cullman said simply that her group was reviewing its options _ one
of which is to try to assemble a majority of six state delegations,
necessary to make a motion to suspend the rules and try to bring
the issue to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSE: DEMOCRATS TAKE AIM AT SEAT
</P>
<P>
   None of the three candidates in Tuesday's Democratic primary in
Georgia's 7th Congressional District took more than 50 percent of
the vote, so a runoff will be held on Aug. 8 to decide which of the
top two finishers, Roger Kahn or Jim Williams, gets to challenge
the incumbent Republican, Rep. Bob Barr, in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES:
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: No public events.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: San Antonio, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
