<HEADLINE>
MINIMED REPORTS SECOND QUARTER EARNINGS UP 77 PERCENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ MiniMed Inc., which makes microfusion systems for
the delivery of drugs, on Wednesday said second-quarter earnings
grew 77 percent, fueled by strong demand for the company's insulin
pump.
</P>
<P>
   The Sylmar-based company also said its board had set a
two-for-one stock split.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed's income climbed to $8.6 million, or 26 cents a share,
compared with $4.9 million, or 16 cents a share, for the 1999
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues grew about 41 percent, to $69.4 million, over the $49.1
million reported in the comparable quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did pretty well,'' said Alfred E. Mann, chairman and chief
executive officer at MiniMed. ``We have been on a roll now for 21
quarters, ever since we went public, and every quarter we either
meet or exceed expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann said the company was set to introduce a number of new
products over the next couple of years, including a disposable
infusion system for Type 2 diabetes and a prefilled insulin
cartridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of new products that should accelerate our
growth,'' he said. ``Our strong revenue increase continues to be
driven by worldwide insulin pump placement growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The results exceeded Wall Street forecasts for 24 cents a share,
according to a survey of industry analysts by First Call/Thomson
Financial. Despite the strong earnings report, shares of MiniMed
fell $4.938, or 3.7 percent, to close Wednesday at $113 on heavy
volume of 534,700 shares traded on the Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are great numbers,'' said Kevin Kotler, an analyst with
ING Barings in New York. ``This is a company that is starting to
see an acceleration in its earnings story, which is fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With new products for 2001 and 2002, including their consumer
glucose censor and its Type 2 (insulin) pump, it should add to
estimates on Wall Street,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the stock split would be effective Aug. 2 for
holders of record at the close of business on that date and will be
distributed Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board's decision to approve another stock split
demonstrates continued optimism and confidence about the company's
future,'' Mann said.
</P>
