<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOTORISTS USING LESS GAS; SUPPLY OF HEATING OIL IS LOW
</P>
<P>
   Facing higher fuel prices, motorists are using less gas _ but
only slightly less. The American Petroleum Institute said that
deliveries of gasoline in the first half of 2000 were down about
0.7 percent, ending a long period of growth.
</P>
<P>
   The data also showed that supplies of home heating oil were far
lower than usual, but Bill Richardson, the energy secretary, said
he was making progress toward establishing a heating oil reserve in
the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   GIVEAWAY MUSIC PAYS OFF FOR SOME
</P>
<P>
   As the recording industry and commercial artists try to stamp
out the distribution of copyrighted music for free in the form of
computer files, tens of thousands of aspiring rock stars are
happily using the technology to give their music away _ and more
than a few are beginning to see some payoff.
</P>
<P>
   TOP TWO AIRLINES BEAT EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Earnings at the nation's two largest airline companies, UAL, the
parent of United Airlines, and AMR, owner of American Airlines,
handily beat Wall Street expectations. But United also warned of
weaker earnings in the current quarter, touching off a large
sell-off of airline stocks, led by UAL, which fell $5.9375, or 10
percent, to $53.3125.
</P>
<P>
   IBM POSTS 12 PERCENT GAIN IN PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Despite declining sales, IBM managed to surprise Wall Street
with earnings of $1.9 billion for the second quarter, up 12 percent
from results in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE PASSES RISE IN 401(k) LEVEL
</P>
<P>
   In the latest action on big tax bills, the House overwhelmingly
passed a measure that would increase the allowable level of
tax-deductible contributions to individual retirement accounts and
401(k) programs.
</P>
<P>
   BROAD SELL-OFF SENDS GAUGES DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Investors sold technology shares to lock in profits, sending the
Nasdaq composite down 121.54 points, or 2.9 percent, to 4,055.63.
The Dow Jones industrial average declined 43.84 points, or 0.4
percent, to 10,696.08, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
slumped 11.78 points, or 0.8 percent, to 1,481.96.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE OVERHAULS SOME PRODUCTS
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer introduced a flurry of products from a restyled
mouse to an overhaul of its iMac desktop computers, whose sales
have stagnated recently. Apple has enjoyed a remarkable revival the
last three years under the leadership of Steven Jobs. But lately,
industry analysts have pointed to signs that Apple's momentum may
be slowing.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTIVES URGE CLOSING DIGITAL GAP
</P>
<P>
   A group of high-technology executives urged the wealthiest
nations to take action to erase a growing digital divide separating
the developed and developing worlds.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE DEFICIT WIDENED IN MAY
</P>
<P>
   The trade deficit widened slightly more than expected in May, to
a record $31.04 billion, as both exports and imports declined.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA TO LOOSEN CONTROL OF BANKS
</P>
<P>
   China's central bank chief said banks would be empowered to set
their own lending and savings deposit rates within the next three
years, an important step toward opening the tightly controlled
Chinese financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   EFFECT OF THE ONLINE JOB SEARCH
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is rapidly changing the way workers search for jobs
and employers recruit workers. The resulting speed and ease of
filling jobs have significant implications for unemployment, pay
and productivity.
</P>
<P>
