u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT &LR;      07-19 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT ST. ANDREWS, THERE'S WOODS AND THERE'S EVERYONE ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Either Tiger Woods will win the career
Grand Slam, or someone else will have a grand weekend.
</P>
<P>
   When the British Open begins Thursday, Woods will chase history,
trying to become the youngest player, at 24, to win all four
majors. But there are other reasons the 2000 British Open is
certain to be remembered. Jack Nicklaus, at 60, could be playing
his last Open, and he is probably competing in his last tournament
at one of golf's most treasured sites, the Old Course at St.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, Nicklaus, nostalgia and a world-class field _ a blend
certain to produce excitement. While Woods enters the tournament as
the clear-cut favorite, how can anyone be certain what will happen?
Who expected Paul Lawrie to win last year at Carnoustie, Scotland?
And who can predict how players will react to the changes at St.
Andrews, including rock-hard fairways that are faster than some
greens and refaced bunkers that can take several strokes to escape?
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the Open, some of the world's best players can be
grouped into two categories _ those who are in a groove and those
with something to prove. Meanwhile, beware of long shots, like
Lawrie last year, who could make a surprise move.
</P>
<P>
   Of those who are in a groove, Woods, Ernie Els, Lee Westwood and
Notah Begay III head the list.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has won 14 of his last 26 starts worldwide, and he won the
U.S. Open last month by a record-setting 15 strokes. Woods is a
presence, not only on the course, but inside the heads of his
competitors. He tees off at 9:20 a.m. local time, and almost
everyone else in the clubhouse will be tracking his score.
</P>
<P>
   If Woods opens with a 65 or better, and if he putts well early,
some of his competitors will be demoralized. But if Woods struggles
in the first round, as he did at the Masters this year when Vijay
Singh won, the tournament will suddenly feel much more wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not win the Western Open a couple of weeks ago,''
Westwood said. ``He is clearly the best player in the world. He is
not going to win every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Westwood is Europe's most torrid player, winning two consecutive
starts and three of his last six. But Westwood only has one
top-five finish in a major, and he does not care for St. Andrews.
Yet, after taking last week off, Westwood felt well rested and
confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two tournaments have been wins, so results-wise, it
could not be much better,'' Westwood said. ``Stay out of the
bunkers. That will be the main point this week.''
</P>
<P>
   After Woods, Els is the player being mentioned most often as the
next favorite. Els has finished second this year at both the
Masters and the U.S. Open. He has won the U.S. Open twice, and he
is not intimidated by Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ernie Els is going to win the tournament,'' said Gary
Player, who will be playing in his 45th British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Begay has won his last two starts _ the FedEx St. Jude Classic
and the Canon Greater Hartford Open. But Woods did not play in
either of those events. And Begay is playing in his first British
Open.
</P>
<P>
   The list of those with something to prove is headed by five
players ranked among the world's top 10 _ David Duval, Colin
Montgomerie, Phil Mickelson, Davis Love III and Jesper Parnevik.
Duval, Mickelson, Montgomerie and Parnevik have never won a major,
while Love has not won any event in more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who has not won anywhere since April of last year, will
have to improve his putting and bunker play to contend this week.
But he is still a great driver of the ball and he insists he has
not lost confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've gone backward,'' Duval said. ``Truthfully,
I think I'm better. The putting has been lacking.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, a native of Scotland, seems to put even more
pressure on himself when the Open is in his homeland. But it may
help that with Woods, Els and Westwood playing so well, Montgomerie
enters this event far from the main attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, the weight of expectation is not so great,''
Montgomerie said. ``I believe I am more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson turned 30 last month, so there is a sense of urgency
to win a major. Parnevik, who has three top-four finishes at the
Open, is 35 and still has not won a major.
</P>
<P>
   Love, who won the 1997 PGA Championship, has been a poor Sunday
player recently, doing what it takes to finish second, not first.
Love has six top-five finishes this year, but no victories.
</P>
<P>
   Among the long shots to watch are: Loren Roberts, who won at
Milwaukee on Sunday, finished third at the Masters and eighth at
the U.S. Open; Padraig Harrington, who tied for fifth at the 1997
British Open and also tied for fifth at this year's U.S. Open; and
John Huston, who finished fourth at the U.S. Open and tied for
fifth at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   But as the tournament begins, Woods is in a familiar position _
the focus of attention, with his mind focused on winning. One day,
Woods expects to complete the career Grand Slam. And he hopes that
day is Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are any two tournaments you want to win, it's the
U.S. Open at Pebble Beach and the British at St. Andrews,'' Woods
said. ``I get the chance to complete the slam on the most historic
golf course ever designed. It's just a wonderful opportunity.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
