<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAKS-SPLIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAKS FIFTH AVENUE SPLITS FROM PARENT
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs 10th graph to reflect that earning estimates were for fiscal
2000 and the second quarter ending July 29) By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The answer to the question of whether a country
peasant can marry a Park Avenue swell and live happily ever after
appears to be no.
</P>
<P>
   Saks Inc., previously called Proffitt's, with headquarters in
Birmingham, Ala., announced late Wednesday that less than two years
after it acquired Saks Fifth Avenue and renamed itself, its board
had approved a plan to split again into two separate public
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The spun-off entity will be called Saks Fifth Avenue Enterprises
Inc. and will include the luxury-oriented stores of Saks Fifth
Avenue; the Saks Direct, which includes catalog and Internet
operations; and Saks Off Fifth, its upscale outlet business. Saks
Inc. will retain the rest of the department store business _
including regional department stores like Proffitt's, McRae's and
Parisan _ and will eventually be renamed. Shareholders are expected
to receive one share of Saks Fifth Avenue Enterprises common stock
for every three shares of Saks Inc. stock they own.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Proffitt's-Saks merger in September 1998, skepticism
abounded about the logic of combining mid-market department stores,
which rely on staple brands like Liz Claiborne and Levi's, and the
tony retailer, best known for such offerings as Prada and Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts and consultants argued that the businesses were
too dissimilar to produce real benefits and accused the company
chairman, R. Brad Martin, of being blinded by his desire to own a
upscale property _ with the opportunities to hobnob with socialites
and celebrity designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mistake to buy Saks Fifth Avenue,'' said Robert F.
Buchanan, a retail analyst at A.G. Edwards, ``and it makes sense to
undue the mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Designers who counted on Saks stores to showcase their newest
creations also worried that the corporation was running the upscale
emporium like a mundane department store _ starving it of necessary
resources for inventory, remodeling and staff training to hit its
financial targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger went off because there was a lack of understanding
on what it takes to run a first-class luxury operation,'' said
Arnold Aronson, a former Saks Fifth Avenue chief executive. ``It is
better that the realization came late rather than never.''
</P>
<P>
   The spin-off is clearly a bid to improve Saks Inc. sagging stock
price. Before acquiring Saks Holdings and changing its name,
Proffitt's was an industry leader in buying businesses at a rapid
pace and making them profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the purchase, it became apparent that the former
Proffitt's had hit a block in integrating the disparate parts of
its empire. Last summer, the company said it would miss earnings
estimates for the fiscal year 1999 by a mile, in part because of
disappointing growth in its credit business and because of
lower-than-anticipated revenue growth at Mercantile Stores, a chain
of bargain-priced apparel stores that it bought from Dillard's Inc.
in 1998. Then this spring, sales were lower than anticipated in the
department stores, and the company on Wednesday forecast an
operating loss for its fiscal second quarter, ending July 29.
</P>
<P>
   Saks Inc. had already missed earnings estimates for three
quarters in a row, and its stock price has crumbled by more than 50
percent since the merger was announced. The stock gained 68.75
cents, to $12.50, on Wednesday ahead of the spinoff announcement,
which came after the financial markets had closed.
</P>
<P>
   The company stopped just short of saying that the purchase had
been a mistake but acknowledged that winning Wall Street's favor
was a motivating factor in the plan announced on Wednesay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will let others critique whether I lost my focus,'' Martin
said, but this deal was necessary ``to get the appropriate focus on
each business as well as the appropriate capital structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the two new companies, Saks Fifth Avenue Enterprises appears
to be in stronger shape, stock analysts said. Because of a booming
economy, the luxury market has been soaring, and sales at Saks
Fifth Avenue have been growing at roughly 10 percent a year. The
prospects for Saks Inc. and the midlevel department stores in
general seem grimmer, reflected Wednesday in the news that Martin
will eventually relinquish his position with the department store
group to remain on as chairman of Saks Fifth Avenue Enterprises,
although he will continue to own a stake in both.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Miller will continue as chairman of Saks Fifth Avenue,
and Christina Johnson will continue as president and chief
executive of the Saks Fifth Avenue stores division. The department
store group will start a search for a new chief executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
