<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-U.S.-TELECOM-NY     07-19 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN AND U.S. REACH TRADE PACT ON TELECOMMUNICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ With its ownership of nearly all telephone lines that go
into Japan's homes and businesses, the Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone Corp. has long enjoyed a virtual monopoly in this
country. On Wednesday, however, a U.S.-Japanese trade agreement was
reached that is likely to make telecommunications services in Japan
far more affordable, competitive and diverse.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came after nine days of intense negotiations and
averted a major trade battle between Japan and the United States on
the eve of a global summit meeting in Japan. American trade
officials, who have been pressing loudly for increased American
telephone industry access to the $140 billion Japanese market,
called it a huge victory.
</P>
<P>
   Its central feature is cuts in the fees that NTT charges other
telecommunications companies to use its domestic network, which
covers 98 percent of the lines to all customers.
</P>
<P>
   For other telephone companies, the agreement will lower the
costs of linking up with NTT by an average of 35 percent in two
years and by at least 40 percent over three years, said Charlene
Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative.
</P>
<P>
   Those charges have been consuming roughly 40 percent of the
revenue of NTT's competitors, stifling competition to provide
telecommunications services in the world's second-largest economy,
U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan has been placing a tax on the Information Age by the way
it regulates NTT,'' said Richard W. Fisher, Barshefsky's deputy, in
an interview. ``It's therefore a tax on competition, and that tax
is going to come down substantially now.''
</P>
<P>
   While Japanese officials said the agreement was only modestly
different from a proposal they made in January, their American
counterparts noted that it provided for significantly deeper cuts
than the 17 percent reduction Japan had offered previously. The
agreement also accelerates the timing of the cuts so that most of
them take place over two years instead of Japan's original offer of
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Japan also agreed to reconsider its methods of setting the fees
paid by NTT's competitors to use its network, which U.S. officials
said should have a more widespread effect on reducing fees and
enhancing competition in 2002 and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most significant element of the deal is how it
came together. That process ruptured long-standing relationships
among regulators, politicians and NTT, and those rifts may lead to
sweeping changes in regulatory structure here and in the structure
of NTT itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``By how many percent interconnection fees are cut and whether
it takes place over two or three years is not really very
important,'' said Harumasa Sato, a professor at Konan University in
Kobe and a telecommunications policy expert. ``The important thing
is that it may lead to fundamental reform of regulation that will
create fair competition in this market.''
</P>
<P>
   The broader scope of the agreement came about in part because of
the way the U.S. trade representative's office fought for it. US.
negotiators moved the debate out of the confines of the Ministry of
Posts and Telecommunications, which regulates telecommunications,
and into a broader public view.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, while past U.S.-Japanese trade fights over issues like
film distribution, car parts and flat glass failed to capture the
imagination of ordinary citizens, the public took a major interest
in this fight, and Japanese politicians noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher embarked on a calculated campaign to make the issue
relevant to consumers in Japan, giving numerous interviews to the
Japanese media and using easily understood examples of why high
connection fees hurt Japan's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   He repeatedly bemoaned the fact that only 10 percent of Japanese
elementary and middle school students could connect to the Internet
because charges were so high. He asked why his daughter paid less
than $9 a month for Internet service in the United States while her
Japanese friend in Tokyo paid eight times that amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should a Japanese girl be at such a disadvantage to an
American girl?'' he asked over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   He apparently made his case, because with the exception of one
newspaper known for its strong conservative editorial view, Japan's
major dailies all supported sharp reductions in connection fees.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese industry also spoke out. The business federation known
as Keidanren, which represents Japan's giant blue-chip
organizations, argued for lower connection fees, and Hiroshi
Mikitani, the founder and president of Japan's biggest e-commerce
site, Rakuten Ichiba, commissioned a study about the impact of the
fees on Japan's ability to harness the information technology
revolution, which he then used to advocate lower charges.
</P>
<P>
   NTT's Japanese competitors weighed in on the side of lower
rates, as did European and American companies attempting to break
into the market. Even some of the companies under the NTT umbrella,
which also pay fees for connecting with the lines owned by the
regional telephone companies that are their cousins, complained.
</P>
<P>
   The concerted effort worked, and around the beginning of the
year, influential politicians began to question the postal
ministry's arguments for only modest reductions in the connection
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that its position on fees was now politically
unacceptable, NTT officials offered to accede to U.S. demands in
exchange for pledges from sympathetic politicians that they would
work to abolish the NTT Law, which restricts the company from
entering other types of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal appealed to Hiromu Nonaka, who is perhaps the most
powerful politician in Japan and the secretary-general of the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party. Among his many roles, Nonaka
serves as the chieftain of the ``postal'' tribe in the Parliament,
a large group of politicians with strong ties to the postal
ministry and to NTT.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, Fisher said, it was Nonaka who struck the deal
on connection fees that emerged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said the breakthrough came when Nonaka invited him and
other U.S. officials, including Ambassador Thomas Foley, to a
Tuesday morning meeting. It began with a 20-minute monologue by
Nonaka.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me a very erudite and extremely thorough discussion
about how Japan needed to come into the IT age and needed to
restructure NTT to do that,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   One hour after the meeting ended, Fisher said, the postal
ministry called the embassy and asked for a meeting that resulted
in the agreement.
</P>
