<HEADLINE>
BOEING POSTS SECOND QUARTER GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. offered fresh evidence it has bounced
back from an engineering strike as well as some production woes
Wednesday, posting a 26 percent jump in second quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The gains don't reflect one-time charges that took away the
profits on paper.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of the company's aircraft deliveries _ 167 in the
second quarter _ demonstrates a healthy demand for aircraft and
continuing productivity improvements at Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the aerospace giant recorded $654 million in adjusted
net earnings during the second quarter, up from $520 million a year
ago. However, those figures don't include a one-time charge in 2000
and a windfall in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have recovered from the depths of despair, but there is
still a lot of upside by going to new levels of efficiencies,''
said William Fiala, an analyst at the investment firm Edward D.
Jones &AMP; Co. ``It was a lot of good news on all fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all good news. The company suffered a one-time $34
million loss tied to the launch a mock payload on a Delta III
rocket next month. Boeing also enjoyed a one-time $181 million gain
the year before thanks to a tax settlement. When the items are
added to Boeing's performance the company's earnings fell 11
percent in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors welcomed the company's latest financial
snapshot, pushing Boeing shares up $.75 to close at $45.88 in
trading Wednesday. Over the past two days, Boeing shares rose
$1.91.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most encouraging signs of the quarter was a jump in
operating margins, a key barometer of profitability, at Boeing's
commercial airplane division. Operating margins hit 8.9 percent at
the unit, up from 4.4 percent during the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The improvement was driven, in part, by the fact that many of
the 167 airplanes delivered in the quarter were essentially built
in the first quarter, according to Boeing Chairman Phil Condit.
Boeing delivered just 75 planes in the first quarter as it
struggled with a 40-day engineering strike.
</P>
<P>
   The company also raised its revenue estimates to $51 billion
from $50 billion in 2000 and to $53 billion from $51 billion in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The increase was built, in part, on the back of the company's
expectation that commercial airplane deliveries will jump between 5
and 10 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pretty stable market,'' Condit said during a
telephone briefing with reporters and financial analysts. It's a
``period that we have not really seen before ... relative
stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the aircraft market, Boeing and rival Airbus Industrie
continue to battle over new orders. In recent months, Boeing has
landed a series of high-profile orders, including one for 94
single-aisle 737s from Southwest Airlines Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not seeing big shifts on the pricing side. (It's)
fairly stable and remains an ... aggressive market,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also delivered some bad news. The company's military
aircraft and missile unit reported problems in its helicopter work.
Executives didn't identify the issues, saying they expect to fix
the problems in the coming months. Overall, the military unit
posted $250 million in operating revenues in the second quarter,
down from $368 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Chief Financial Officer Michael Sears also said the unit
is seeking international customers for its F-15 fighter. But he
characterized the line as ``warm'' as the company waits for
additional congressional funding.
</P>
<P>
   And the Space and Communications unit posted an operating loss
of $38 million, down steeply from $94 million in earnings a year
ago. Boeing blamed the loss on research and development costs and
the expense of launching the Delta II mock payload.
</P>
<P>
   The financial report offered few details about the question on
the minds of many Boeing employees: where and when executives may
decide to sell another plant, operation or asset.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have been swirling around the company's Auburn, Wash.,
fabrication plant and other units about an impending sale. Condit
didn't discuss possible sales, but he said Boeing has several
options to handle underutilized assets as it reviews its
operations. Executives could sell a unit outright, consolidate its
work or free up space and sell the real estate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be looking at our business and trying to
maximize asset utilization. Where we have a plant that is
underutilized we are going to address that issue,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also reported that its research and development budget is
growing. The company spent $375 million on research in the second
quarter, compared to $350 million in the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the spending is now flowing to Boeing's new Connexion
project, which will offer airline passengers access to e-mail, the
Internet and computer networks during their flights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
