<SLUG> BC-LATIMES-EDITOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES EXECUTIVE JOINING LOS ANGELES TIMES AS MANAGING
EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dean Baquet, the national editor of The New York Times, was
appointed by the Los Angeles Times on Wednesday as managing editor
and its No. 2 newsroom executive.
</P>
<P>
   Baquet, who won the Pulitzer Prize for investigative reporting
in 1988, is the second top editor appointed by the Los Angeles
Times from outside since March, when the Tribune Co. announced its
purchase of the newspaper's parent, the Times Mirror Co.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the Chandlers, the Los Angeles Times' controlling
family, agreed to sell their holdings to the Tribune Co., which is
based in Chicago, Tribune executives appointed John S. Carroll,
editor of the Baltimore Sun, to replace Michael Parks as editor in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun was part of Times Mirror and is now owned by Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the Los Angeles Times has been a site of
controversial and continually revised experiments with newsroom
management. Most memorable was a deal to split profits from a
Sunday magazine, whose coverage was devoted to a new downtown
sports arena, with the arena's management.
</P>
<P>
   Baquet, 43, has a low-key, informal management style that
matches Carroll's. Baquet will oversee all the newsroom
departments. Newsroom executives at the Los Angeles Times said that
in the past three months, Carroll had shunned meetings, preferring
to leave his door open for reporters and editors to drop by.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said the newsroom was reverting to ``a more traditional
management structure'' and jettisoning the top-heavy structure of
the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Until early this year, the Los Angeles Times had four managing
editors; it now has two _ Karen Wada and John Arthur _ and an
executive editor, Leo Wolinsky. Their new titles and roles ``will
be worked out over the next several weeks,'' Carroll told his staff
in a memorandum Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Baquet won the Pulitzer as leader of a team of reporters for the
Chicago Tribune that uncovered self-dealing and waste in the
Chicago City Council. At the time, the Tribune's No. 2 editor was
Jack Fuller, who is now president of the Tribune Co.'s newspaper
division. Baquet joined The New York Times in 1990 as an
investigative reporter and has been national editor for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York Times is a hard place to leave,'' Baquet said
Wednesday. ``I just think that the Los Angeles Times would be a
fun, exciting place to be right now. It has a lot of talent. The
thought of working with John Carroll and going to a paper that was
good but was also about to take on new leadership was
irresistible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
