<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WHO DIED IS CHECKED FOR WEST NILE VIRUS
</HEADLINE>
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal health authorities are analyzing the blood of
a 71-year-old man who died Wednesday on Staten Island to see if he
was infected with the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   The man, whom hospital and government officials did not
identify, was taken to St. Vincent's Medical Center on Staten
Island on July 5 complaining of a headache, fever and confusion.
Those symptoms are sometimes associated with encephalitis, which
can be caused by West Nile, a mosquito-borne virus. The man, who
was visiting from South Carolina, died early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said it was just as likely that the man died of
an illness other than West Nile. ``It is highly premature for
people to assume this gentleman was infected with West Nile
virus,'' said Dr. Neal L. Cohen, the city health commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, several viruses peak in July and August and cause
encephalitis, especially among children and the elderly, health
officials said. And the Staten Island patient, Cohen said, ``had a
number of debilitating health conditions that may have been
responsible for his illness and his deterioration.''
</P>
<P>
   But because crows infected with the virus were found on Staten
Island earlier this month, Health Department officials took blood
and spinal fluid samples from the man Tuesday to be sure that he
was not New York's first human case of the virus this year. Last
year, the virus sickened 62 people, killing 7 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said that test results from the federal
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta were expected
on Thursday or Friday. ``At this point there are several competing
hypotheses for his illness,'' Giuliani said. ``In other words, West
Nile is not the only possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, 32 mosquitoes with evidence of the virus have been
found in Westchester and Suffolk Counties, and 25 birds with
confirmed infections have been discovered on Staten Island and in
Rockland, Westchester and Suffolk Counties in New York and in
Bergen County in New Jersey. But there have not been any confirmed
cases in humans.
</P>
<P>
   The finding of dead birds and animals has led to the resumption
of pesticide spraying in several counties, many of which had
already taken preventive measures to kill mosquitoes since the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Staten Island was scheduled to be sprayed with insecticide on
Wednesday night and Thursday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0469 </DOCNO>
