<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 FORD, SUED IN AIR BAG CASE, SAYS VICTIM WAS STRANGLED  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ford Motor Co., accused by a New Jersey man of killing his
wife when her air bag inflated during a car crash three years ago,
is defending itself by asserting that the woman was actually
strangled.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's assertion has enraged the man and his lawyers, who are
seeking to expand a lawsuit to include defamation charges against
the automaker. Ford, the lawyers said Wednesday, should pay heavy
punitive damages for trying to avoid taking responsibility for a
faulty product by tacitly suggesting that their client murdered his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Kruzel, a Ford spokeswoman, said the company merely
wanted to bring evidence in the case to the prosecutor's attention.
``Our goal is to defend our product,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The case dates from Feb. 9, 1997, when Tracy Thomas, 37, a
former ballet dancer who was six months pregnant, died after the
Ford Explorer she was driving skidded into a utility pole at a
speed of about 15 miles per hour, not far from her home in Cape May
Courthouse, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Dr. Eric Thomas, is suing Ford in U.S. District
Court in Camden, N.J., claiming that his wife was killed by the
force of an air bag deploying at 200 mph. Dr. Thomas was riding in
the passenger seat, and the couple's young daughter, who also
survived, was in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is seeking unspecified compensatory damages for the loss
of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Thomas' death was ruled an accident by the Cape May County
prosecutor's office, which administered a lie detector test to Dr.
Thomas at his own lawyer's request. He passed the test.
</P>
<P>
   The accident is among 60 low-speed traffic deaths that the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration has investigated
since 1990 and found to have been caused by air bags. Tim Hurd, a
spokesman for the highway safety agency, said the cause in the
agency's file is taken directly from the coroner's report, and
reads, ``Blunt trauma to neck with asphyxia.''
</P>
<P>
   But among the evidence presented by Ford during the pretrial
discovery phase is a report by a pathologist it hired who concluded
that Tracy Thomas was not killed by the air bag. ``In my opinion,
Thomas died of compression of the neck by the hands of another,''
wrote the pathologist, Dr. Michael M. Baden.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mellon, a lawyer for Dr. Thomas, said Baden's conclusion
conflicted with findings of the county prosecutor, the coroner and
the highway safety agency. He also said Ford tried to persuade the
county prosecutor to reopen the case as a criminal investigation in
an attempt to intimidate his client into dropping the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has hired Floyd Abrams, a well-known specialist in First
Amendment cases. Abrams appeared at a pretrial hearing on Tuesday
to oppose a motion to expand the suit to include the defamation
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams argued that lawyers should be given broad latitude to say
and do things in their clients' defense, even if, in other
circumstances, those things might be grounds for defamation or
other charges. If the judge allows the defamation charge, Abrams
said, it could set a precedent that ``would chill the bar from
doing its job of representing clients.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0470 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-19 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINE TOP RIDERS PASS SURPRISE BLOOD TESTS
</HEADLINE>
  By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ At no time was the D-word uttered during
the Tour de France Wednesday. On a day when Lance Armstrong
maintained his lead while two other well-known racers dropped out
of the event, a handful of the 20 teams were tested for drugs.
Armstrong and the race's eight other top riders passed the surprise
blood test taken in their hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The D-word was not voiced thereafter, so at least verbally in
this 87th Tour de France, drugs are nonexistent. But in the next
few months, urine samples that have been taken daily from the stage
winner, the overall leader and two riders selected at random will
be subject to a new examination developed at the French national
drug testing laboratory. The samples, which are flown daily to the
laboratory outside Paris, have been frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Once the new testing technique is medically, and thus legally,
approved _ as it was not before the Tour started on July 1 _ the
names of those detected using such illegal performance-enhancing
drugs as EPO will be announced and the riders will be stripped of
their honors, if any.
</P>
<P>
   The testing is the latest step in an understated official effort
to prove the goodwill and integrity of the Tour and the cycling
union after the drug scandal that plagued the race in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday the focus was on Erik Dekker. A Dutchman with the
Rabobank team, Dekker won his third stage in a mass sprint finish
into Lausanne, easily beating Erik Zabel, a German with Telekom, in
second place, and Fred Rodriguez, an American with Mapei, in third.
</P>
<P>
   The way Dekker was rolling Wednesday, he might even win the
customary sprint on the Champs-Elysees on Sunday. He completed the
155-kilometer (96.3-mile) run from Evian les Bains in 3 hours 24
minutes 53 seconds, a speed of 45 kilometers an hour (28 mph).
</P>
<P>
   The stage began and ended on opposite sides, French and then
Swiss, of Lake Geneva, which was dotted with sail and motorboats,
their wakes shimmering in a hot sun.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, the U.S. leader of the U.S. Postal Service team,
continued in the yellow jersey of overall top dog, 5:37 ahead of
Jan Ullrich, a German with Telekom, and 6:38 ahead of Joseba
Beloki, a Spaniard with Festina.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-seven riders among the 130 left in the Tour finished in
the same time as the leaders, with the rest left behind to admire
the nearby vineyards climbing the hills on stone terraces in the
Swiss manner.
</P>
<P>
   There were two significant dropouts: Marco Pantani, the Italian
leader of Mercatone Uno, the winner of two mountain stages, the
Tour champion in 1998 and the highest name on Armstrong's hit list,
failed to start because of a reported case of dysentery. He faded
badly in the mountains Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The other casualty was Alex Zuelle, a Swiss with Banesto, who
finished second overall to Armstrong last year. Seeking to move up
a notch, he changed his entire training regime for the Tour and has
been invisible since the start. As the stage passed Swiss alpine
meadows where newly cut hay scented the air green, Zuelle
apparently thought of his nearby home and dropped out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
