<SLUG> BC-NJ-TORRICELLI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRICELLI SAYS HE IS EAGER TO RUN FOR GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Saying he alone could repair his party's deep
wounds and sweep Democrats back to control of both houses of the
Legislature, U.S. Sen. Robert G. Torricelli said Wednesday for the
first time that he was eager to run for governor of New Jersey and
boasted that he had already won the backing of most of the county
Democratic organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign that last month's bitter U.S. Senate primary might
merely be replaced with another bloody intraparty conflict,
Torricelli and Mayor James E. McGreevey of Woodbridge, the man who
until a week ago had been the lone front-runner for the Democratic
nomination, dispensed with intermediaries and sniped at each other.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two weeks, Torricelli has been jockeying for
support behind the scenes, but not acknowledging his intentions
publicly. Wednesday, he still shrank from officially declaring
himself a candidate, but nonetheless said he was frustrated by the
slow pace of change in Washington and had reached ``the point in
life where I would like to actually achieve something.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, he said the governor's office had been
a lifelong ambition and denied that he saw it merely as a
steppingstone to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   For McGreevey, who has described Torricelli as a close friend,
the senator had only faint praise Wednesday. He said McGreevey had
a ``tremendous future in elective or appointive office.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli also made several pointed references to perceptions
that McGreevey was too dependent on a few powerful state
legislators for support. ``I've made it clear that people should
understand that if I become a candidate for governor, there'll be
no deals, no arrangements, no winks, no nods,'' he said. ``There'll
be no Rasputins, no one whispering through side doors.''
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey, meanwhile, responded tersely with a reference to past
questions about Torricelli's ethics. ``Considering Senator
Torricelli's track record, that indeed is a remarkable comment,''
he said, refusing to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said he would run only if he could unify the
Democratic Party's northern-central and South Jersey factions,
which exploded into all-out warfare during the Senate primary
between Jon S. Corzine and former Gov. Jim Florio. But in the next
breath, he said, ``Most of the counties in northern Jersey and
almost all in southern New Jersey have come together of a common
mind'' to support his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   He added that his supporters included Florio and former Rep.
William Hughes in South Jersey; Reps. Frank E. Pallone of Monmouth
County and Bill Pascrell of Passaic County; and Michael Murphy, a
former Morris County prosecutor. The last three, he said, are
interested in challenging McGreevey themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can unite almost all of them,'' he said. ``Otherwise
I think there's likely to be a Democratic primary of four or five
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey, who has refused to abandon his own candidacy,
dismissed the senator's claims of overwhelming support as
``rhetoric'' and maintained that he would prevail in a primary with
Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   But McGreevey said the senator was putting his ambitions ahead
of the party's goals in the presidential and congressional
elections. ``The irony is that while Bob Torricelli allegedly
discusses unity, his actions will inevitably produce a very
divisive primary,'' McGreevey said. ``The self-serving actions of
Senator Torricelli are not premised upon electing a Democratic
majority on the federal level, but only serving his personal
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said he had been approached for months by Democrats
in New Jersey but became interested only after the Senate primary.
``If these wounds are not healed, the next gubernatorial election
is going to be lost,'' he said. ``There are Democrats in the
southern and northern Assembly caucuses who will not go in the same
room.''
</P>
<P>
   He even went so far as to outline the makings of a campaign
platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States Senate has been enormously rewarding, and I
feel I've made a real difference, but we're not making a difference
on a large enough scale,'' he said. ``The point I've made is, can
we actually win a sufficiently convincing victory to do things like
establishing statewide day care, mandatory school instruction at
age 4, buying enough open space to limit suburban sprawl, expanding
our prescription drug program to include middle-income people, and
establishing clinics in the state where pregnant women can get care
in rural and urban areas?''
</P>
</TEXT>
