<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISCOPAL-DEFIANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH CHURCH OFFICIALS SAY THEY WON'T EVER ACCEPT FEMALE
PRIESTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JIM JONES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Defiant officials of the Episcopal Diocese
of Fort Worth say they won't bend to the national church's demand
that they accept women as priests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stay and fight for the right to believe what we
believe,'' said the Rev. Canon Charles Hough, a close associate of
Fort Worth Episcopal Bishop Jack Iker. ``They are asking us to do
something we can't do. It's a matter of conscience for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Iker, who is on vacation, could not be reached to comment
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Iker has been one of the leading challengers to ordaining
female priests, saying it goes against his understanding of church
tradition and biblical teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Fort Worth proponents are taking heart from the
national ultimatum and are saying it is time for the 23-county
local diocese to comply with a 26-year-old church law opening the
priesthood to women.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are living in the dark ages,'' said Peter Tringham, a
member of Trinity Episcopal Church and a longtime proponent of
women in the priesthood. ``It's a done deal. We have 1,700 female
clergy now across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But none is in Fort Worth _ or is likely to be anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   More pressure was put on Iker and bishops of two other dioceses
to accept female priests during final sessions of the Episcopal
Church U.S.A.'s general convention, which ended Friday in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates approved a much-debated resolution calling for a
``task force'' to visit and assist the dioceses of Fort Worth,
Quincy (Ill.) and San Joaquin (Calif.) to develop an action plan to
make sure they accept female priests by Sept. 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The task force will make semiannual reports to the Episcopal
Church Executive Council on how the dioceses are progressing.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 100 U.S. dioceses, three were targeted for oversight. The
resolution notes a lack of progress in accepting female priests in
Fort Worth and in Quincy, Ill., where the Right Rev. Keith Ackerman
is bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Some progress is being made in the Diocese of San Joaquin, based
in Fresno, Calif., the resolution states. But Michael Adari, a
parishioner in that diocese, said he does not see any progress.
</P>
<P>
   Like Fort Worth, the diocese has no female priests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop John David Schofield ``has vowed never to allow a woman
priest here,'' Adari said.
</P>
<P>
   Adari's wife, Maryly, is being assisted by an Episcopal bishop
in Sacramento in her quest to become a priest, her husband said.
Schofield refused to help her meet the requirements to become a
priest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schofield could not be reached to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Iker and retired Fort Worth bishops before him _ Donald Davies
and Clarence Pope _ have been leading Episcopal traditionalists who
say ordaining women contradicts Scripture and church traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Parishes select their priests, but the bishop has input. Iker
and his predecessors have encouraged conservative priests to take
positions in the diocese and promoted them to leadership roles. The
diocese covers 23 counties and has about 19,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   But many Fort Worth Episcopalians, and some priests, are
strongly supportive of women in the priesthood. Some female priests
have been brought into the Fort Worth diocese as visiting clergy.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Fred Barber, rector of Trinity Episcopal Church,
allowed a visiting female priest to assist in celebrating Mass with
him two weeks before the general convention, said Katie Sherrod, a
leader of the national Episcopal Women's Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Barber informed Iker that he might invite a woman to help
celebrate Mass, Sherrod said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is kind of a `Don't ask, don't tell arrangement,'
'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth diocese has adopted a ``Dallas plan,'' which Iker
says complies with requirements that the priesthood be open to
women.
</P>
<P>
   Women in the Fort Worth diocese who are called to the priesthood
are put under the supervision of Bishop Jack Stanton of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   If a woman becomes a priest, Stanton _ not Iker _ would issue
her priesthood license. And, she would be under the spiritual
direction of Stanton even though the church would remain part of
the Fort Worth diocese in terms of finances and organization.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrod said the Dallas plan is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our diocese is 17 years old, and during that time any woman
who wanted to be ordained had to leave,'' she said. ``All the
Dallas plan does is say she must go to the diocese in Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   If Iker stands firm in not complying with church laws, he faces
the possibility of undergoing a church trial and the potential of
being ousted as a bishop under a long, complicated process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, that could happen,'' Hough said. ``But there are
bishops in the church who are allowing the blessing of same-sex
unions (which is prohibited under Episcopal Church teachings), and
no one is stopping them from doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishops are rarely removed. During the Episcopal General
Convention, bishops strongly approved the resolution on pushing
dioceses to accept women as priests, but they also approved a
``mind of the house'' resolution calling for a pastoral approach
and for respect of bishops who hold minority views.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Durham, a member of All Saints Episcopal Church, said he
favors the national church's decision to speed up acceptance of
female priests in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would not seek out a female priest personally,'' he
said. ``But I don't think the diocese should deny women the right
to be a priest.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, he would like the leadership of the Fort Worth diocese to
be more in line with the national church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I feel more like a Fort Worth Episcopalian than a
national Episcopalian,'' Durham said. ``I love Fort Worth, but I
want to be part of the whole church.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
