<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATORS RACE AGAINST DEADLINE TO REACH MIDEAST ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs to lead with Lockhart's comments; adds Israeli TV
reports on Barak's letter; tightens, minor changes throughout; adds
optional 2nd take with background.) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ and DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton waged an all-out effort
Wednesday night to salvage the nine-day Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks at Camp David, shuttling between the two sides against an
early morning deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Briefing reporters at 5:30 p.m., Clinton's spokesman, Joe
Lockhart, said that the talks were at a ``pivotal moment'' and that
the president was ``exploring every possible avenue'' for an
agreement. The talks then returned to the secrecy which has
surrounded them from the outset, and the hours ticked on.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton was still planning to leave by early
morning Thursday on a trip to Japan already delayed by one day.
Officials said the president would probably make a statement before
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   But after a high-tension day of rapidly shifting moods, it
remained unclear to the final hours whether he would be pronouncing
an end to a bitter, 52-year conflict, announcing a partial
solution, or proclaiming an impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Clinton shuttled between the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders _ fending off an Israeli initiative to leave
early and returned repeatedly to his advisers and to the
negotiators in search of some formula that would save the summit
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   During the summit meeting, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel
and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, apparently dealt with
every issue in their conflict _ from borders and the fate of Jewish
settlements to the right of return of Palestinian refugees and the
status of Jerusalem. But it was unclear on Wednesday whether the
ultimate stumbling block was a single issue, like Jerusalem, or the
trade-offs needed to fashion an overall agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Each side was gearing up to lay the blame for a failed summit
meeting squarely on the other, and each leader appealed privately
to Clinton in letters written in the last 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The mood of the high-tension, high-stakes day see-sawed. At
midday, it seemed certain that the talks were fizzling out. By
early evening, when the parties were still entrenched at Camp David
and tentatively scheduled final news conferences were postponed, it
seemed possible that Clinton would be able to pull out an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The day started out with the declaration of a midnight deadline,
which would allow Clinton to depart for Japan by early Thursday
morning _ a departure he had already delayed by a day in a final
bid to rescue the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But the day built to an unexpectedly quick first climax, when
the Israeli journalists accompanying Barak were ordered in the
afternoon to rush to their hotels for a security check so that
their luggage could be shuttled to Andrews Air Force Base for an 8
p.m. departure for Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   As the clock ran down, expectations were rife that there had
been a breakdown. Israeli television reported, and a U.S. official
later confirmed, that Barak had sent a letter to Clinton announcing
the prime minister's departure and laid the blame for the summit
meeting's failure on the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian side is conducting negotiations insincerely
and is not willing to negotiate in a serious and practical manner
for a permanent peace between us,'' an Israeli reporter cited as a
direct quotation from the letter.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Palestinian negotiator, Abu Mazen, who himself was
heading to the airport to fly home to his son's wedding, brushed
off what he saw as an eleventh-hour Israeli tactic to increase
pressure on the Palestinians. Talks were ongoing, he said, and the
fate of Jerusalem, a seemingly intractable issue, was still on the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli television reported that Barak sent Arafat a message
that he was willing to return to Camp David for another round of
talks but that he might not still be prime minister by then.
Palestinian officials reported, in turn, that Arafat, seeing this
as a threat, retorted that if he made too many concessions, Sheik
Ahmed Yassin, spiritual leader of the Islamic fundamentalist Hamas
group, would be taking his place.
</P>
<P>
   Washington reporters were told that Clinton, by himself, might
address reporters at the White House at 6 p.m., and that Barak, by
himself, would speak shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at 5:30, in a briefing at the Thurmont Elementary School
some 5 miles from Camp David, an announcement by Lockhart gave the
final day an extended lease on life.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been going at this now nonstop for nine days in this
session,'' Lockhart said. ``I think we've obviously reached a
pivotal moment in these talks and I can't predict how it will come
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that as he spoke, Clinton was sitting down at the
retreat's Birch Cabin to his second face-to-face session Wednesday
with the Arafat. Clinton had met with Barak earlier in the day, but
in what observers considered a sign of trouble, the two Middle East
leaders remained apart all day.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the changing dynamic of refreshed momentum, Israeli
journalists returned to the press filing center, where one, Keren
Neubach, announced breathlessly that their bags were being returned
from the Air Force base to the Hampton Inn where they were staying.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that Clinton also received a letter from Arafat,
which arrived on Tuesday, before Barak's. He did not characterize
its contents, but Palestinian officials said that Arafat had
reached a peak of frustration on the eighth day.
</P>
<P>
   If news of the letters lowered expectations of a deal, Lockhart
reported that Clinton had managed by late afternoon to keep the
leaders from walking out. ''They are still there, they are all
still talking,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart made clear that the two leaders were having trouble
making concessions on deeply emotional issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders both want to go home with an agreement,'' Lockhart
said. ``The problem is the substance and structure of the
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the extended deadline would have to stand.
``There comes a time when you have to put a time limit on
discussions,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
