<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7219 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-W     07-19 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THURMONT, Md.: discussions,'' he said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the day, Clinton telephoned other leaders in the Middle
East to brief them on the developments, the first such contacts
since the summit meeting began.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that an ultimate sticking point concerned the future
status of Jerusalem, the most divisive issue and one that has never
before been negotiated by Israeli and Arab leaders. It was seen as
the make-or-break issue, but it is possible that other stumbling
blocks remained, too.
</P>
<P>
   After conquering East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967
Arab-Israeli war, Israel declared that the city would ``eternally''
remain united and under exclusive Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The visit of the Egyptian leader, Anwar el-Sadat, to Jerusalem
in the fall of 1977 was interpreted by the Israelis as recognition
of Jerusalem's status as Israel's capital. But a year later, at the
first Camp David summit meeting between Sadat and Israeli Prime
Minister Menachem Begin, the question of Jerusalem threatened to
scuttle the entire conference.
</P>
<P>
   President Carter tried to find some sort of symbolic solution _
such as flying Muslim flags on the Temple Mount _ but the
suggestions were rejected by the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   In the Oslo agreement of 1993, under which Israel recognized the
Palestinian Liberation Organization and the Palestinians renounced
all violence against Israel, the future of Jerusalem, along with
the fate of Palestinian refugees, final borders and some other
issues, was left for ``final status'' talks. The official position
of the United States has been that the fate of Jerusalem must be
negotiated between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last seven years, diplomats, professors, demographers
and officials from both sides have tried to come up with various
arrangements that could satisfy the demands of both sides,
including ideas that involved ``autonomy'' for Palestinian
neighborhoods in Jerusalem and allowing the Palestinians to claim
the neighboring village of Abu Dis as their Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But these ideas were dismissed by the Palestinians as a ``Jewish
solution.'' Abu Dis, they argued, is not Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have watched Arafat over many years say that he always
set a benchmark: He would not be the Palestinian who went down in
history as the one who gave up Arab claims to East Jerusalem as the
capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, they point out, was not asking for a divided city but
rather shared sovereignty in an open and undivided city. Offering
municipal control over some neighborhoods, they said, fell far
short.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, for Barak, making concessions on a city that many
Jews regard as their capital by divine fiat was extremely
difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
