<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ADDS TEXAS STOP 
TO CHALLENGE BUSH 
 

</HEADLINE>
 BC- GORE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAYTOWN, Mo. _ Sensing a breach in George W. Bush's Texas
battlements, Vice President Al Gore abruptly changed travel plans
Wednesday and will challenge the Texas governor's budget priorities
not far from the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's troops can't wait till he gets there.
</P>
<P>
   Before touting a crime-fighting initiative in this Kansas City
suburb, Gore said Bush should justify his decision to cut taxes for
the wealthy in Texas while the state's budget surplus dwindled. He
said he plans to spotlight the issue in San Antonio this afternoon
along with the states' approach to children's health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Governor Bush's leadership, Texas has gone from its
biggest budget surplus ever to a budget shortfall,'' Gore told
police at the Raytown City Hall. ``Now we learn that at a time of
national prosperity _ indeed, the longest economic boom in the
history of America _ Texas has saved less for the future than
almost every other state in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state's so-called rainy day fund could barely withstand a
drizzle,'' Gore said, adding that by this fall, there may only be
enough money to keep the state government running for a single day.
``There would be a real problem if Texas had a rainy season.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer issued a statement
saying: ``If Al Gore wants to talk about progress and prosperity
there is no place like Texas, where taxes are low, budget surpluses
are high and we even have a bipartisan patient bill of rights.''
</P>
<P>
   And Texas Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander, who will announce
in Austin Thursday that Texas is in good financial shape, asked
Gore for the opportunity to brief him ``on the facts about our
state budget and our current surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Rylander's invitation were state Sen. Bill Ratliff,
R-Mount Pleasant, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, and
state Rep. Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's trip is the latest development in a growing debate over
state budget overruns, projected to be about $610 million, but
expected to be covered by an unexpected surplus in sales tax
revenue. Gore, the likely Democratic presidential candidate, has
charged that his GOP rival has irresponsibly put $1.7 billion in
tax cuts for the wealthy ahead of providing health insurance for
the state's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major issues of this whole election is, what will
our priorities be for the next four years,'' Gore told reporters.
``Will we be for the people or for the powerful? If we have a
budget surplus, what will we do with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Democratic state Sen. Mario Gallegos has accused
Rylander and Republican leaders of cooking the state budget books
to make Bush look good in the final months of the presidential
campaign. Gallegos has demanded an independent audit, while others,
including the state's highest ranking Democrat, Texas House Speaker
Pete Laney, have praised the governor's efforts in working with the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bush's record in Texas matters. The fate of the
federal government's surplus would be in his Republican rival's
hands if he is elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Governor Bush has run Texas is relevant to the judgment
the American people will make as to how he would run the country if
they gave him the chance,'' Gore said, ``especially when he is
calling for the same priorities that gave Texas its budget
shortfall in a time of unprecedented prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's spokesman, Chris Lehane, said the Gore campaign had been
considering the diversion to Texas for several days and Wednesday
was finalizing plans. The goal, he said, was to reinforce the
differences between the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Later, reporters asked Gore about the comparisons that would be
drawn between his new strategy of trying to attack and define his
opponent on his home turf and an earlier presidential campaign:
Bush's father, former President Bush, buoyed by 1988 polls that
showed him closing on Democratic challenger Michael Dukakis,
blasted the Massachusetts governor on his home turf for neglecting
polluted Boston Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never crossed my mind,'' Gore said of the comparison ``It
really didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was on a four-day tour through Tennessee, Missouri and Iowa
to promote his crime-fighting proposals. He told police officers
Wednesday that he would fund an additional 50,000 positions to
continue the efforts of the Clinton-Gore administration to put more
officers on the street.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
