<HEADER>
A7352 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF--BRITISH-HNS &LR;      07-19 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF--BRITISH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
At St. Andrews, it's more than a game
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ He is in his usual seat at the wee table
to the left of the door as you enter the bar of The Dunvegan Hotel,
which if not the heart of the Open, at least houses its soul.
</P>
<P>
   James ``Tip'' Anderson lifts his half-empty glass of McEwan's
bitter, says ``Cheers!'' and won't you pull up a chair to hear a
few quick stories from one of the great golf heroes in all of
Scotland. It will only cost you the price of another pint, laddie.
</P>
<P>
   And faster than you could pull a 3-wood out of your bag, he's
off and running down fairways of the past, telling of the six-year
stretch in the '60s when he won the Open three times and finished
second once, though it was actually Arnold Palmer and Tony Lema who
hit all of the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is a caddie, retired now, a tall, 1-iron slim,
distinguished gentleman in a powder-blue sport coat, a white cap
and sneakers, as much a fixture in the cradle of golf as the
clubhouse of St. Andrews and The Dunvegan itself, a five-room hotel
run by a former Texas Aggie from Liberty named Jack Willoughby and
his sweeter-than-shortbread Scottish lass wife Sheene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the walls of the place, look at the photographs,''
Anderson says. ``There's Arnold over there. And there's Elk (Steve
Elkington) tending bar one evening. And Jack Nicklaus and Peter
Jacobsen and Ian Woosnam and Payne Stewart and all the rest. See,
there's the young lad, Tiger, and there's one of Sheene out by the
17th hole with your American president George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the game that brings them all together. It's
this place.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Andrews has been called the birthplace of the game, harking
back to centuries when men flailed at a feather-stuffed ball with
hickory sticks, and the confessional of the game, for the way it is
so often talked about in hushed terms and pulls out players' sins.
</P>
<P>
   It is a place where the champions and the never-weres, the
legends and the caddies, the former presidents and the innkeepers
can pay quiet homage or give loud, rowdy toasts to this intriguing,
addictive and incredibly frustrating game.
</P>
<P>
   It is the charming seaside town of 20,000 that could swell to a
temporary population of 1 million this weekend _ roughly one-fifth
the population of Scotland _ as the 129th British Open moves in to
paint more stories, more memories, more images.
</P>
<P>
   There is the Road Hole and the Swilken Burn. There is the
Principal's Nose and the Hell Bunker and the Valley of Sin and so
many other names that say this isn't country club golf the way you
know it back home.
</P>
<P>
   A wedge shot away from the 18th green is The Dunvegan, which is
just down the hill from the center of town, where the spectacular
rosebushes that adorn the public areas and the odd-sounding items
on the menu that confirm it is an entirely different place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haggis, Neeps and Tatties'' is one recommendation for lunch at
Littlejohn's restaurant. ``Scotland's national dish served the
traditional way with mashed tatties and neeps. Served with Scottish
oatcakes and a complimentary nip of fine whiskey. O' what a
glorious sight _ warm, reekin and rich!''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   There is Hal Sutton admiring a perfect drive on No. 17, the Road
Hole, and there is Lee Trevino taking several frustrated whacks out
of the gorse on No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   It is a cloudless day when the temperature soars to 76 degrees,
enough to wilt the spirit of even the stoutest Scot. So they tromp
slowly around the Old Course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe this heat?'' asks a woman.
</P>
<P>
   And the man simply nods, his face is so slathered with white sun
block that it looks as if he had gone headfirst into a bowl of
mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   A threesome of Nicklaus, John Daly and Jean Van de Velde
finishes up a practice round and it is the affable Frenchman _ who
self-destructed on the final hole to lose the Open title last year
at Carnoustie _ that gets the biggest applause.
</P>
<P>
   The sea wind blows strong and cool _ the mark of links golf _ in
the face of 88-year-old former champ Sam Snead as he stands over a
putt on the second green. Just 100 yards away, across the road, a
strip of beach called the West Sand is filled with would-be sun
worshippers, all pale, but soon to be pink. A toe into the North
Sea finds it surprisingly pleasant, while a bagpiper in full
regalia, surely sweating under his kilt, stands at the water's edge
playing a tune.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus chips close to the pin. Snead makes his putt. Back at
The Dunvegan, Anderson raises his glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Tis a slice of heaven if you're a golfer,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Still a sizable chunk of paradise if you're not.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
