<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NAZIS-PAINTING-NYT     07-19 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZIS-PAINTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LOSES SECOND ATTEMPT TO SEIZE PAINTING NAZIS TOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A painting by Egon Schiele that was taken from its
owner by the Nazis during World War II cannot be seized by the
federal government as stolen property, a federal judge in Manhattan
ruled this week.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time the painting, ``Portrait of Wally,'' has
been released by the courts. The New York state courts rejected an
attempt to hold it and another Schiele painting, ``Dead City,'' as
stolen goods in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney's office subpoenaed the two
paintings when they were on loan to the Museum of Modern Art in
early 1998. ``Dead City'' was released, but prosecutors have been
battling the owner of the paintings, a private Austrian museum,
over ``Wally'' ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's subpoena was quashed by the New York
State Court of Appeals in September 1999. In a ruling that avoided
questions of ownership, the court ruled that the state's
30-year-old Arts and Cultural Affairs Law prevented seizure of
artworks on loan to museums.
</P>
<P>
   But immediately after that ruling, the office of Mary Jo White,
the U.S. attorney, moved to seize ``Wally'' under a federal law
that forbids transporting stolen goods in foreign commerce. Lawyers
for the museum, the Leopold Museum of Vienna, argued that the
paintings were not stolen goods.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision released Wednesday, Judge Michael B. Mukasey of
federal District Court ruled that the paintings could not legally
be considered stolen because they had been recovered by U.S. armed
forces after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Mukasey wrote that under the law, a person cannot be convicted
of receiving stolen goods if he received them after they were
recovered by the original owner or the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wally'' was the possession of a Jewish art gallery owner in
Vienna before World War II. After the Nazis came to power, they
confiscated the gallery. Later, the owner, Lea Bondi Jaray, was
also pressured by the Nazis to surrender ``Wally,'' which was part
of her private collection, Mukasey wrote. Her heirs are seeking its
return.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the painting was seized by American forces in
Austria. The judge wrote that the military mistakenly returned the
painting to someone thought to have owned it before the war. It was
later sold to the Austrian national gallery, to a private owner and
then to the Leopold.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, the U.S. forces were charged with recovering
stolen items and acting on behalf of the items' true owners,''
Mukasey wrote. ``This recovery purged the painting of the taint it
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the military made an error in the return, the judge
wrote, ``in the eyes of the law, it was no longer stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, a spokesman for White said the office was
reviewing the decision to determine whether to appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
