A7345 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-TOY-KAN &LR;      07-19 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH LAUDS KC TOY STORES FOR NONVIOLENT ITEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID KLEPPER and KATIE HOLLAR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Julie Crnkovich, with her three sons in tow,
strolled past the chemistry sets, plastic dinosaurs and
kaleidoscopes in the Store of Knowledge that a church study found
to have a low-violence quotient.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City mother on Wednesday shopped the Country Club
Plaza store because of its absence of toy guns, military action
figures and brutal video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for that kind of realistic, gory violence,''
she said. ``At this age, they get desensitized. They don't realize
that in real life, that could really hurt someone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Store of Knowledge was happy with the seal of approval it
earned from the Church of the Brethren. Church members recently
visited more than a dozen local stores looking for violent toys and
games. The church picked Kansas City for its first toy survey
because the denomination wrapped up its annual meeting here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey comes a year after several school shootings left
Americans wondering what was wrong with children. The search for
answers prompted Congress to look at the effects of video games on
youngsters. Earlier this year, a Senate committee heard conflicting
testimony about the possible dangers of children battling and
blasting virtual opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Combating youth violence is high on the church's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, we played cowboys and Indians,'' said Margie
Polhamus, a church member who helped conduct the survey. ``But we
knew it was a game. It didn't change us. The toys we found are a
lot worse than cowboys and Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   The Church of the Brethren has about 140,000 members and its
headquarters is in Elgin, Ill. Church members describe their
denomination as pacifist. The church's survey teams found that
small, independent stores offer fewer violent toys and games than
the larger retailers such as Toys R Us and Kay-Bee Toys.
</P>
<P>
   Stores were judged on a 100-point scale that docked outlets for
toy weapons, soldiers and grisly video games. The four stores that
scored 98 and higher were: Ingenious Toy Store; Adventure Store at
Science City; Noggin Noodle; and the Store of Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Moy McIntosh , manager at the Store of Knowledge, was proud of
her store's score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it shows you can have success with a company that
sells educational toys,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the larger toy chains said their stores
offered the toys and games children wanted. If a parent thought a
toy was too violent, they shouldn't allow their child to purchase
it, they said.
</P>
<P>
   A Kay-Bee outlet in Independence was criticized by the church
for some video games, and a spokesman objected to the ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be carrying them if they weren't selling,'' said
Kay-Bee spokesman John Riley. ``We respect (church members') views,
but we think they're in the minority.''
</P>
<P>
   FAO Schwarz was rated a 75 _ ``tolerable,'' by the church's
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The store's personal shopper, Thomas Cander, said he thought the
store lost 25 points because of a water-gun display.
</P>
<P>
   ``These water guns are bright yellow and aqua. They certainly
don't look too authentic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the link between toy guns and mayhem is doubtful, said one
Brooklyn, N.Y., child therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the toy makers make things they shouldn't? Probably,'' said
Meri Wallace. ``But will a toy gun make a child into a killer? No.
Parenting is a lot more significant to a child than a particular
toy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said no scientific studies proved that violent toys
produced violent children. But she said studies indicated that
young children who watched violent movies were more aggressive. She
said parents should select age-appropriate games and toys for
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents need to guide children _ especially younger
children,'' she said. ``Younger children might not understand the
difference between a real gun and a toy. The same goes for movies
and video games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
