<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-WILLIAMS-NY     07-19 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: WILLIAMS IS UNEASY WITH MVP WHISPERS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Originally skedded BBA-YANKS-WILLIAMS) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The discussion inadvertently sent Bernie Williams
time traveling, causing him to recall what it was like to be a
struggling rookie with the New York Yankees nine years ago.
Williams provided the flashbacks, when petty teammates like Mel
Hall called him Bambi, when manager Buck Showalter had him work out
with minor leaguers in spring training and when every day could
have been his last in the majors. Or at least that is what Williams
thought.
</P>
<P>
   All it took was one mention of the past for Williams to
instantly digress and remind himself of the uncertainty. Williams
is one of the elite players in baseball, he owns three World Series
rings and he has an $87.5 million contract, but he took a few
minutes Wednesday to ground himself. Remember when?
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember those days,'' Williams said, shaking his head. ``I
don't ever want to go back to that. How many people have had great
starts and then you never hear about them again?''
</P>
<P>
   That Williams seized upon the flimsiest of opportunities to
recall when he was not an All-Star center fielder is a sign of his
humility. But Williams is humble, not dense. He is having another
splendid season and knows that he is a prime candidate for the
American League's most valuable player award. Because he plays a
demanding position, he should be the leading candidate. That makes
him uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong, it would be great to have one of those in
your trophy case,'' he said. ``It's one of those things you dream
about. The attitude here is team-oriented. That's worked, so I'm
not going to change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill was more direct about Williams and said, ``I'd say
that he is as important to us as any other player is to his team in
the American League.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Williams squirmed. Some Yankees have teased him about
winning the award because he was batting .334 with 21 homers and 87
runs batted in before Wednesday night's game against Detroit. There
is no doubt Williams is improving, but he quickly mentioned other
players who are having terrific seasons: Nomar Garciaparra, Carlos
Delgado, Darrin Erstad, Frank Thomas, Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams is on pace to drive in 160 runs, so he added, ``If
this isn't the year for me to go off like this, I don't know what
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was referring to the explosion of offense in the
majors, but he could have also been referring to the aging of the
Yankees. While Williams is only 31, the Yankees are growing older
around him, and they have sputtered this year as they have not
since early 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder O'Neill is 37, the same age as pitchers Roger
Clemens and David Cone. Maybe, deep down, Williams knows that these
Yankees could be approaching their finale.
</P>
<P>
   He was reflective enough to remind himself of 1991. He is surely
reflective enough to know that winning a third straight title is a
gargantuan task. Just getting to the postseason is not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got guys breathing down our necks,'' Williams said. ``We
can't really relax.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been customary to call Derek Jeter the MVP of the
Yankees, but Williams is the MVP this year. Even though Williams
has won three Gold Gloves, he does not always get good jumps on fly
balls, he pulls up on others and he has an average arm. But
Williams has not been charged with an error this year, and his
offensive output has obscured the listless defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we need a big hit, Bernie gets it,'' O'Neill said. ``He's
got so much confidence, you know he's going to do it. Without him,
our offense would be less than mediocre.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre is enamored of and amused with Williams, who
is usually the last Yankee on the field for stretching exercises
and the first player to hustle out of the clubhouse after games.
After Williams smacked a two-run triple off Curt Schilling in a 3-1
victory over the Phillies on Tuesday night, the only person who
asked him about it was a security guard because Williams bolted
again.
</P>
<P>
   Before Clemens faced the Florida Marlins last Friday in a game
that was more critical for him than anyone else, Torre told
Williams, ``I need you.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams looked at him and softly said, ``I know.'' Torre loved
Williams' response, which was part playful and part serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably think I'm the goofiest player on the team,''
Williams said. ``I'm always giving them weird answers to make them
think. But I took what Joe said seriously. It was an important
game. I think the whole season will be like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The goofy, great center fielder is right. This has been an
arduous season for the Yankees, and they need a much more stable
starting rotation to get them to October. They do not have to worry
about Williams, who admitted, ``If I'm not the goofiest one here,
I'm one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Goofiest? Probably. Most valuable? Definitely.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
