<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7346 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-GORE-KAN &LR;      07-19 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ATTACKS BUSH'S HANDLING OF TEXAS BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Wednesday was Al Gore's time for some real
heavy lifting.
</P>
<P>
   On day two of his visit to the Kansas City area, Gore took on
George W. Bush over a possible budget crunch in Texas, unveiled a
plan calling for the hiring of 10,000 prosecutors and acknowledged
that his campaign had gotten off to a slow start.
</P>
<P>
   He also found time for some physical exertion by tossing about a
dozen YMCA pre-schoolers _ one at a time _ into the air at the
Raytown YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do that to me, do that to me,'' the youngsters shouted at the
Richard C. Green Sr. Family Center YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   And the vice president, mindful that he was offering television
and newspaper cameras a nifty picture, dutifully complied, tossing
one squealing youngster after another into the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't they want autographs instead?'' a red-faced Gore moaned
at one point, sticking his tongue out to emphasize his effort.
``That's a workout.''
</P>
<P>
   At the playground, the Democrat did something else unexpected.
He announced that he was junking his schedule for today to fly into
Bush's Texas. The objective: to highlight the governor's new budget
woes.
</P>
<P>
   The move is reminiscent of former Vice President George Bush's
1988 campaign cruise of the dirty Boston Harbor aimed at
embarrassing Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a Texas newspaper reported that the state's
rainy-day fund designed to help lawmakers overcome future
recessions had been drained to less than two-tenths of 1 percent of
the state's $49 billion annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now so small that, by this fall, there will be only
enough money to run the Texas state government for a single day,''
Gore said later at Raytown City Hall. ``You know, there would be a
real problem if Texas had a rainy season.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer tagged Gore's Texas trip a
``distort and destroy'' mission. He emphasized that Texas still has
a $1.1 billion budget surplus. The point of contention, however, is
over how much of that money will remain after the state pays out at
least $610 million in Medicaid and prison cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al Gore wants to talk about progress and prosperity, there
is no place like Texas, where taxes are low, budget surpluses are
high and we even have a bipartisan patient bill of rights,''
Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore clearly appeared to be relishing the prospect of a hot
new issue to use against the Republican. For the second day in a
row, he appeared confident and upbeat, perhaps buoyed by several
new national polls that showed the race virtually deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States of America has now built up the biggest
surpluses in our 211-year history,'' Gore said. ``And how Governor
Bush has run Texas is relevant to the judgment the American people
would make as to how he would run the country if they ever gave him
the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore then shifted his attention to his main initiative of the
day _ his call for 10,000 new prosecutors across the nation, an
idea modeled after the Clinton administration's 1994 proposal for
100,000 new police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to talk tough on crime,'' Gore said. ``But let's be
honest: You can't be tough on crime if you're cheap on
crime-fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not stick a price tag on his plan, but said communities
would have to compete for grants and provide a local match to the
federal investment.
</P>
<P>
   The dearth of prosecutors nationwide results in too many plea
bargains and ``wrist-slaps'' because prosecutor's office are
stretched too thin, Gore said. Statistics from 1996 show that only
one in four prosecutors' offices nationwide employ even a single
full-time prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``New police are essential,'' Gore told law enforcement and
community leaders at Raytown City Hall. ``But it's not enough just
to catch criminals if our justice system is so overloaded that it
cannot even try them.''
</P>
<P>
   On another front, Gore renewed his call for the hiring of 50,000
new police officers. Those officers would join the 60,000 now on
the job that were hired under Clinton's plan to bring on 100,000
more.
</P>
<P>
   Raytown Police Chief Larry Overfield applauded that idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll ever reach a point where there are too
many police officers out there on the streets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also pledged to segregate federal law enforcement funds in
a so-called ``lock box'' so that communities could plan ahead
knowing that money for new officers would be there.
</P>
<P>
   And he also proposed a plan to focus on ``hot spots'' where high
concentrations of crime occur. Gore wants to hire additional police
and prosecutors who would bear down on such districts.
</P>
<P>
   Overfield said he thought his department could benefit from the
initiatives. Raytown police have hired several officers through the
federal COPS program, which partly subsidizes an officer's salary
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he picked the Democratic stronghold of Raytown to make
his appearance because of the success the eastern Jackson County
community has had in battling crime. Raytown claimed a 45 percent
cut in major crimes last year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he had a goal in mind for his weeklong focus on crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is my commitment: the toughest, most effective anti-crime
strategy this nation has ever seen,'' he said. ``More police and
more prosecutors, to widen the thin blue line between order and
disorder. Smarter prevention to stop crime before it starts.''
</P>
<P>
   That can't happen, Gore said, if the money is set aside ``to cut
taxes for powerful interests and the wealthy,'' a reference to
Bush's tax-cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Gore stuck around City Hall for several hours
conducting media interviews and preparing for future events. He
didn't fly out of Downtown Airport until about 4:30 p.m., a
departure that resulted in tied-up rush-hour traffic along
westbound Interstate 70 from the Blue Ridge Cutoff to the Broadway
extension.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Kansas City Star, Gore admitted that
his campaign had started slowly, partly because he was still
thinking and acting like a vice president instead of the Democratic
standard-bearer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the process (of being vice president), I developed a kind
of habit of responding to every question and every challenge by
thinking first of all, how can I help the administration with this
answer, how can I move the ball down the field for the team here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started for president I was still very much thinking
that way, like I was a vice president running for a promotion. It
took me awhile to break through that and realize...it's not a
question of following somebody's team plan, it's a question of
speaking directly from your own heart, spontaneously and directly
to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he made the shift, he said, ``things began falling into
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
