<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT WOULD REMAIN BRIDESMAID IF DEUTSCHE AND VOICESTREAM DECIDE
TO MARRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Deutsche Telekom AG reportedly has made a bid
to buy VoiceStream Wireless Corp. A deal would all but rule out any
Deutsche bid for Sprint Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal's Web site, citing unnamed sources,
reported Wednesday that Deutsche's bid for VoiceStream values the
U.S. company at about $205.60 a share in stock and cash, or about
$53 billion. Both Deutsche and VoiceStream declined comment on the
report.
</P>
<P>
   It VoiceStream accepts the offer, Deutsche is expected to ditch
any idea of making a run at Sprint. The area's largest
private-sector employer long has been seen as juicy target for the
cash-rich German telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche owns 10 percent of Sprint through an earlier
international joint venture. In theory, at least, a Sprint
acquisition would give Deutsche a big presence in U.S.
telecommunications with land lines, wireless, Internet and data
transmission, and long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say there is no logic in Deutsche's pursuit of
both.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make a bid for VoiceStream, it makes no sense to make a
bid for Sprint,'' said Steven Hanson, senior analyst for Merger
Insight, a research firm for institutional investors. ``The
antitrust issues for Deutsche to buy both would probably be
insurmountable.''
</P>
<P>
   When rumors circulated two weeks ago that Deutsche was sniffing
around Sprint, it raised the hackles of some U.S. senators, who
didn't like the idea that a company that is majority-owned by the
German government might get its hands on a vaunted domestic
telecommunications company. The German government's ownership stake
is down to about 58 percent and would be diluted further if
Deutsche gives up stock to buy VoiceStream.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche might still covet Sprint's other assets, Hanson said,
but if you have VoiceStream, you don't need Sprint's prized
wireless operations. Moreover, he said, it would be ``stupid'' to
buy Sprint and sell off what many see as its best asset.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sprint's digital wireless operations, Sprint PCS, that
WorldCom Inc. most desired when it offered $129 billion to buy
Sprint last October. The deal with WorldCom, which antitrust
regulators filed suit to stop because it would have combined the
nation's second- and third-largest long-distance carriers, was put
to rest by both companies last week.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing termination of the WorldCom deal last week, Sprint
Chief Executive William T. Esrey declared, ``Sprint is not for
sale,'' in pieces or as a whole. He said that the WorldCom deal had
been a unique opportunity and that Sprint was not interested in
being partners with anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint officials had no comment Wednesday about reports that
Deutsche had made an offer for VoiceStream. Last week, Esrey said
the company had not had any conversations with Deutsche.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not talking to anybody, haven't talked to anybody and
aren't looking to talk to anybody,'' Esrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in a telecommunications market where many think a
company must be able to offer all services to all clients to
compete, what you want and what you get can be two different
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone offers you enough money, the Sprint board would be
hard-pressed to turn it down,'' said Hanson, who thinks there are
plenty of other companies, particularly foreign companies, that
would be interested in Sprint. NTT DoCoMo, the publicly traded
wireless unit of Japan's Nippon Telegraph &AMP; Telephone Corp., and
France Telecom might be interested.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Sprint's stock closed at $45, down $2.25. Sprint
PCS closed unchanged at $69.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nespola, chief executive of the consulting firm The
Management Network Group and a former Sprint executive, agrees
there are plenty of companies that would like to own his old
employer. There is no question that Sprint remains ``the prettiest
girl at the dance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report by The Journal, notably, indicates there is no
guarantee a deal with VoiceStream will be concluded.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Journal, VoiceStream has had discussions with
several potential partners in the past few months. Telekom's offer
could set off a bidding war with NTT DoCoMo, which has been looking
at VoiceStream and is expected to make a bid for the firm, people
familiar with the situation said.
</P>
<P>
   The interest in Bellevue, Wash.-based VoiceStream stems from the
fact that it is the only independent national wireless carrier left
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Many foreign firms that want access to the U.S.
telecommunications market are turning to wireless first as a way to
get a foothold. That's because wireless is a quicker way to offer
service in local markets. Wireless firms don't have to go through
the same regulatory hurdles as wireline companies, which are
strictly regulated by states and must have rates and tariffs
approved by state regulatory bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Another big factor in the fate of VoiceStream is the opinion of
Finland's Sonera Ltd. and Hong Kong's Hutchison Whampoa Ltd., two
companies that hold large stakes in VoiceStream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
