<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFF-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACE OF THE LAW IS CONSTANTLY SHIFTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A potential client asked for names of previous clients at a
career counseling center. Oh, we can't tell you that. It's illegal,
came the response.
</P>
<P>
   Hogwash. Revealing names might be a violation of individual
privacy agreements, but reputable companies can and do get previous
clients' permission to include their names on reference lists.
Nothing in the law forbids that.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to know what's legal and what's not in the work
world. Workers who have never gone through certain experiences
before have no idea whether the responses they get are correct. In
fact, labor lawyers and human resource professionals have trouble
keeping up.
</P>
<P>
   A slew of regulatory agencies, legislative bodies and court
decisions adapt and reinterpret workplace law on a daily basis.
What's ``legal'' is refined case by case, in response to individual
complaints and lawsuits, and subject to lengthy appeals and
reversals.
</P>
<P>
   For example: A divided National Labor Relations Board last week
rejected a 12-year-old precedent. It ruled that a nonunion employee
had the right to have a representative present when he was called
in by his supervisors for what he expected to be a disciplinary
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Previously the labor board had guaranteed that right only to
union members.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's case involved an employee who, with another
employee, wrote a memo to his top boss, asking that their
supervisor be removed. The boss responded by calling the employee
to meet with her and the supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   The employee refused to attend unless he could meet with the
boss alone. Or, if the supervisor had to be present, the employee
wanted to be accompanied by his co-worker who also signed the memo.
Both requests were denied, and the employee was sent home and then
terminated the next day for gross insubordination.
</P>
<P>
   A majority on the NLRB board decided that, unionized or not,
employees have the right to act in concert and that ``an employer
may not mask the obstruction of employee efforts to exercise rights
by asserting a right to deal on an individual basis.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the board ruled that the employee was wrongly
dismissed for insisting that his co-worker attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   So, is this the ``law'' now? Can any worker who suspects he or
she is being taken to the woodshed demand to have a co-worker
present?
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it. The NLRB decision may be appealed by the
employer. The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals may rule on it. Other
appellate courts may rule differently in other cases. The case
could work its way to the highest court in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Left unclear, too, is whether an employer even has to call a
disciplinary meeting or whether an employee has a right to demand
one.
</P>
<P>
   The process of determining workplace rights is arduous. It takes
time and money _ things that most workers aren't able to give.
They're too busy earning paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   The process also is piecemeal. Sweeping legislation may set
guidelines, but interpretations are incremental. And that's partly
why it's so hard to know what's ``legal'' and what's not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
