each other for not yielding on the intractable issue of the future
of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat came into the talks vowing not to accept any accord
unless it guaranteed Palestinian control over East Jerusalem, the
site of some of the holiest shrines in the Muslim, Christian and
Jewish worlds. Israel captured it in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, for his part, had pledged that an undivided Jerusalem
would remain the eternal capital of Israel, fully under Israeli
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was unable to bridge those differences, and largely upon
the shoals of that ancient dispute the talks apparently foundered.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome constituted a deep and potentially dangerous setback
for the region, where analysts have warned that factions of
Israelis and Palestinians opposed to the peace process might try to
foment unrest in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a bitter disappointment for Clinton, who has
invested seven years of diplomacy in the quest for a comprehensive
Mideast peace agreement and had sought an accord as a final grand
foreign policy achievement before he leaves office next January.
</P>
<P>
   With hope for reviving the process on Clinton's watch all but
extinguished, the president was left with a record of limited
accomplishments in the Mideast, despite the leverage of
unprecedented American influence and might in the aftermath of U.S.
victories in the Cold War and the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also been thwarted in his efforts to broker peace
between Israel and Syria, a second component of his objective of
closing the elusive circle of peace in a region that is the cradle
of Western civilization, home to three of the world's major
religions and the reservoir of two-thirds of the world's known
crude oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to go early Thursday morning to a
Washington area airport, where he was to board Air Force One for
the 15-hour flight to Okinawa, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   There, far from the crucible of Mideast summitry and even
farther from the flesh-and-blood issues the talks were designed to
address, Clinton was to assume the role of elder statesman at his
farewell session of the annual summit of leaders from the so-called
Group of Eight democratic powers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned at the outset of the talks that failure could
trigger renewed ``hostility and . . . perhaps even more violence,''
in the volatile Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   He had also cautioned that ``there was no guarantee of
success,'' at the Camp David summit, where he spent nine days and
nights, interrupted only by a day of activities in Baltimore and
Washington last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
