<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-RECRUITS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU LOSES TWO RECRUITS, FINDS TWO; OTHER NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ The jewel of TCU's 2000 football recruiting
class, All-American running back Tyson Thompson from Irving, has
been declared academically ineligible.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Horned Frogs coach Dennis Franchione confirmed yesterday that
Thompson and Galveston Ball defensive back Derrick Pope failed to
achieve the minimum requirements mandated by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Though losing Thompson and Pope are major hits, the 2000 class
received a boost with the signing of Dunbar twins Jerome and Jerrod
Braziel, both 1999 commitments.
</P>
<P>
   The Braziels, both cornerbacks, signed with TCU last yearbut
failed to qualify academically. They decided to sit out a year and
retake the standardized tests needed to gain their eligibility.
They met the qualifying scores recently and were on campus
yesterday afternoon signing their scholarships offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire them for what they've done,'' Franchione said. ``It's
not easy to go through what they went through. It's a real credit
to those kids, their parents and their coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braziels had stellar football and track careers at Dunbar,
both earning All-District 9-4A honors at cornerback and running
legs on the state champion 4x100-meter relay team.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione said Thompson could still be a partial qualifier or
travel the same path as the Braziels. As a partial qualifier,
Thompson could enroll at TCU this fall and practice with the team,
and, should he make satisfactory academic progress, would be
eligible to play next season.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was a first-team ``Parade Magazine'' All-American and a
``Star-Telegram'' National Top 100 selection. As a senior, Thompson
rushed for 2,933 yards and 32 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Pope played linebacker and tailback at Ball, but was expected to
be a defensive back at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   Though Franchione was unsure of Pope's plans for the immediate
future, he said Pope and Thompson remain in TCU's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way, we want to put something together to make sure
both get into Horned Frog purple,'' Franchione said.
TENNIS COACH LEAVING According to sources, TCU men's tennis coach
Michael Center has accepted the head-coaching position at Texas and
an announcement could come as soon as tomorrow. Center was out of
town yesterday and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Center coached the Frogs to a 36-12 record the past two seasons,
including a 22-5 mark and trip to the NCAA Division I quarterfinals
last season. Before coming to TCU, Center coached the men's and
women's teams at Kansas, and served as a volunteer assistant at
Stanford.  &LR; subheds:Wagner update Keith-Ann Wagner, who suffered
partial paralysis in a car accident July 4, continues to make
steady progress, according to her mother, Shirley Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's starting to feel real good and her spirits are high,''
Shirley Wagner said. ``Her arms are getting strong and she has more
feeling in her legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith-Ann Wagner has begun occupational and physical therapy at
Baylor Medical Center in Dallas, and doctors have set Sept. 28 as
her tentative release date. Wagner, TCU's starting goalkeeper the
past two seasons, had surgery to repair her broken sixth vertebra.
FOOTBALL ON TV The TCU football team could have up to eight of its
11 regular-season games televised this season.
</P>
<P>
   KSTR/Channel 49 has agreed to broadcast three Frogs games,
including the season opener at Nevada on Sept. 9. The network has
also picked up the Tulsa (Oct. 21) and Rice (Oct. 28) games.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports Net, which is already televising Northwestern (Sept.
16) and Navy (Sept. 30) nationally, is close to picking up Fresno
State (Nov. 11) and SMU. The SMU game is scheduled for Nov. 25 but
would probably be moved to Nov. 24, the day after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports Regional might add the Hawaii game (Oct. 7). nn
</P>
</TEXT>
