<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-IBF-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTION WRAPS UP ITS I.B.F. CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Asserting that boxing is a ``dying sport that has
lost the trust of people,'' the prosecution in the federal
racketeering and bribery trial of the president and founder of the
International Boxing Federation laid much of the blame for that
state of affairs Wednesday on a scheme of bribes in exchange for
favorable rankings and matchups that the defendants are accused of
running.
</P>
<P>
   In a daylong summation of the prosecution case, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Marc A. Agnifilo painstakingly sketched out the details of
the 32-count indictment against Robert W. Lee Sr., 66, the
president of the IBF, and his son, Robert F. Lee Jr., 38, who
served as liaison to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The Lees are accused of extorting $338,000 over 15 years from
managers, promoters and fighters in exchange for rankings and
sanctioning that were crucial to boxers getting shots at lucrative
televised championship bouts.
</P>
<P>
   Agnifilo said that in each of the alleged bribes, the pattern
was the same, with the elder Lee using go-betweens to arrange and
collect the money and then launder it so he would never be ``at the
messy place'' where it all took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no doubt who is in charge of this organization,''
Agnifilo said. ``It's Bob Lee Sr. He runs the IBF, and particularly
the criminal acts of the IBF.''
</P>
<P>
   While highlighting the strengths of the prosecution case,
Agnifilo also tried to shore up its weaker points: the absence of
direct testimony that Lee or his son solicited or accepted
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the evidence linking them to payments from promoters,
managers and fighters was provided by Colin Douglas Beavers, a
former rankings committee chairman of the IBF, based in East
Orange, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers cooperated with the prosecution, secretly videotaped and
audiotaped conversations and testified that he was a bagman for the
Lees.
</P>
<P>
   Agnifilo reviewed many of those taped conversations, culling
excerpts of comments by the elder Lee which, Agnifilo said,
incriminated Lee in spite of his tendency to talk guardedly and in
a clipped, coded manner.
</P>
<P>
   Those excerpts were printed in large type on 10-inch-square
placards, which were attached by Velcro strips to an 8-by-4-foot
chart that dominated the wall of the courtroom of U.S. District
Judge John W. Bissell.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day there were more than 40 placards arranged
like tiles on a Scrabble board.
</P>
<P>
   The defense summation was expected Thursday, and there was a
chance that jurors would begin their deliberations as soon as
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the trial, which began April 11, was nearing its
conclusion, Bissell indicated that he was still considering defense
motions that would limit the mail and wire fraud charges that the
jury could consider. That part of the government's case pivots on
defining a fair ranking by the IBF as a thing of value and a right
due to the boxers the organization served. But the judge said he
was still researching case law for guidance.
</P>
<P>
   The case has dealt a blow to boxing and particularly the IBF,
which became the first private sports organization that the federal
government has taken over and monitored under provisions of the
Racketeering Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Robert J. Cleary, the U.S. attorney for New
Jersey, persuaded Bissell to wrest control of the organization from
its leaders and appoint a monitor to oversee it, a move that has
usually been limited to corrupt labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   The trial has in addition seen boxing's image tarnished by a
parade of promoters including Robert Arum, the powerful owner of
Top Rank, and Cedric Kushner, who have testified to paying bribes
to Lee and the IBF and who could eventually face prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
