 - LADN 
LOS ANGELES TO REROUTE TRAFFIC AROUND DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV and ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A traffic plan released Wednesday for the
Democratic National Convention sharply restricts traffic for
several blocks around Staples Center, forcing some businesses to
consider closing for that week in August.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown business owners _ many still reeling from rioting after
the Lakers' NBA championship victory _ fear workers will get caught
in traffic and that protesters will destroy property or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the Lakers game forward, it's been a horrible experience
_ and it's going to get worse before it gets better,'' said Steve
Auth, whose Kaiser Bros. Honda and Oldsmobile dealership sustained
more than $100,000 in damage during the Lakers unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan said he is confident the plan will
minimize traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared for anything that can happen and will give the
Democrats the best convention they ever have held,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said he hopes downtown businesses cooperate by changing
employee work shifts, if possible, for the week of Aug. 14-17, as
they did during the 1984 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working to see that people go on a staggered work
schedule and carpool to ease some of the traffic,'' Riordan said
during a news conference. ``And it will allow people like me to
ride our bikes to get in and out of downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan, an ardent bicyclist, said he plans to help by riding
his bike one day during the convention to get around downtown.
</P>
<P>
   One boost for planners is the time the convention will be held:
4 to 8 p.m. each day. Most traffic will come before or after rush
hour _ unlike the Olympics, which had events at all times of the
day and throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic restrictions will be in place by Aug. 12 and some
will be instituted several days earlier, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Some highlights of the plan:
</P>
<P>
   _The immediate area around the Convention Center and Staples
Center, including their parking lots and adjacent streets, will be
restricted to only those people with credentials.
</P>
<P>
   _Near Staples Center, traffic on Figueroa and Flower streets
will detour to Grand Avenue for southbound travel and northbound
vehicles will detour to Hope Street, except from 6 to 11 p.m., when
Olive Street will be used.
</P>
<P>
   _Metropolitan Transportation Authority bus lines will be
modified to avoid the Staples Center perimeter, where 35,000
convention visitors are expected, as well as up to 50,000
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   _Bus-only lanes will be created on some streets, new turning
lanes will be created and traffic signals will be altered.
</P>
<P>
   _A tour guide has been published to advise delegates about
places to visit around Los Angeles and how they can use public
transportation, from buses and cabs to the Red Line subway and Blue
Line rail systems.
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes hospitality booths at all the airports and
hotels _ staffed by the convention's local Host Committee _ to
provide information to the delegates on sites to see and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put together a pretty solid plan, given our experience in
dealing with large volumes of people here in downtown,'' said
Francis Bannerjee, general manager of the city Department of
Transportation. ``We plan more than 1,500 major events a year and
whenever anyone throws a major party, we are involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, she said the number of people attending the convention is
small considering the Figueroa Corridor is used by more than 2
million people a week.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners are not impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about the security of the employees and myself,
also,'' said Tony Alfaro, manager of Winston Tires, where vandals
smashed plate glass windows during the Lakers celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Auth said he has not decided whether to close his doors, but he
doubts any customers will come in and is planning to do ``spring
cleaning'' during that week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending upon the traffic, depending upon the kind of
activity the protesters are doing that week will determine whether
we close or stay open and for what hours,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Schatz, president of the Central City Association, said
her group is trying to reassure business owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is concern _ there has to be any time you are inviting
thousands of people to your home,'' Schatz said. ``Whenever you are
talking about huge crowds and events, it is foolish not to be
prepared for any eventuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schatz and city leaders say they are optimistic that the
week will go smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are preparing for a joyous, peaceful celebration for a week
and to showcase the heart of our city that we've worked very hard
to make vital,'' Schatz said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis O'Neill, general manager of T.R. King Co., which sells
gaming supplies south of Staples Center, said he likely will close
his shop to business but stay there to try to protect his property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still recovering from that riot. Our business was
destroyed and we were broken into,'' O'Neill said. ``I think it
could very well happen again. It just takes anything to spark these
people off, any excuse to loot and riot.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of the plan are available by visiting the city's Web
site at www.lacity.org and clicking on the Democratic National
Convention icon. The city also has a telephone hotline to provide
information at (888) 356-4661.
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
