<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN MAY BE SHOWDOWN FOR SORENSTAM AND WEBB
</HEADLINE>
  By BILL FIELDS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. _ Golf rivalries are an elusive commodity, often
more hype than reality. But the women's game has a real one, and
when the 55th U.S. Women's Open begins Thursday, much of the focus
will be on Annika Sorenstam and Karrie Webb.
</P>
<P>
   The two young, dominant LPGA stars have done almost everything
but have a showdown in a major championship, but the stage is set
for that possibility this week at the Merit Club, a course about 40
miles north of Chicago that opened in 1992 and is playing host to
its first national championship.
</P>
<P>
   In a 150-player field with elite players of all ages, from
14-year-old Nare Wongluekiet to the Hall of Famer Nancy Lopez, who
after 23 tries and at age 43 is still looking for her first Women's
Open title, a Sorenstam-Webb battle could raise the profile of an
event in the unenviable position of being played the same week as
the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam, a 28-year-old Swede, is coming off two consecutive
victories and leads the LPGA Tour with five victories for the
season. Webb, a 25-year-old Australian, has four victories this
year, including a 10-stroke triumph in the Nabisco Championship.
They are one-two on the LPGA money list by a wide margin over No. 3
Juli Inkster, the defending champion this week. Already this
season, each golfer has beaten the other in a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really talk about the rivalry,'' Sorenstam said.
``But I can't deny it. I check her scores whether I'm playing or
not playing. She's one of the best, and if you want to be the best,
you've got to beat the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam has won 18 times since taking her second consecutive
U.S. Open title in 1996, but none of those victories have come in
majors, and she missed the 36-hole cut at the Open in 1997 and
1999. ``I think I've been in my own way mentally,'' she said,
reflecting on her recent record in majors.
</P>
<P>
   Motivated by the success of Webb, who eclipsed her as the
world's No. 1 player, Sorenstam was determined to improve. With a
combination of more practice and less worry, she said she ``wanted
to get back to the No. 1 spot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After last year I was a little disappointed with the way I
played,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Merit Club, built on the site of a former cattle farm, is
known for its most famous member, Michael Jordan. At 6,540 yards,
the layout is the longest in Women's Open history, and the fairways
are firm. Only a few holes are tree-lined and the wind often blows
across the layout.
</P>
<P>
   Webb and Inkster, who successfully defended her McDonald's LPGA
Championship last month, have between them won the last five
women's majors. Webb was in position to thwart Inkster at the LPGA
Championship but she pressed down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest hurdle that I have to overcome is my patience,''
Webb said. ``I go so long and keep everything in and then just one
bad break or one bad swing and I lose it. And that's what I have to
work on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
