<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PAROLE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PAROLE OFFICER TALKS OF PRESSURE TO RELEASE FELON
</HEADLINE>
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A former state parole official testified on Wednesday
that his supervisor had gotten ``a tremendous amount of pressure''
from the Pataki administration to release a violent felon whose
family had contributed thousands of dollars to the governor's 1994
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The former official, Ronald Hotaling, also testified that he
received a request from an official in the state's Community
Affairs office to report back to her about whether the prisoner had
been released.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony by Hotaling was in Federal District Court in
Brooklyn on Wednesday at the trial of Yung Soo Yoo, a New Jersey
businessman who was often tapped by the Republican Party to raise
money among Koreans in the New York area. Yoo, 63, has been charged
with telling three Korean families in Queens that he would use his
influence to obtain parole for their sons if they donated thousands
of dollars to the campaign of New York Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution of Yoo stems from a two-and-a-half-year federal
investigation into accusations that Pataki officials used the
promise of early parole to help fill the governor's campaign
coffers. The prosecutors overseeing the case have repeatedly said
there is no evidence that Pataki participated in or had knowledge
of the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also introduced a letter they said was written in
November 1996 by Yoo addressed to Patrick Donohue, who at the time
was Pataki's campaign finance director. The letter said that two
contributors were furious that their sons had not been released and
were threatening to go public. Donohue has not been charged, and
his lawyer, Thomas Puccio, did not respond to phone calls seeking
comment. The defense said on Wednesday that it planned to call him
as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Hotaling also testified that Brion D. Travis, the chairman of
the parole board, received a message in April 1996 from the
governor's office advocating the release of John Kim of Queens, who
was serving time for armed robberies. Two years earlier, Kim's
family and their supporters contributed about $7,000 to Pataki's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Hotaling said Travis then told him to relay the interest of the
governor's office in the case to two of the three parole
commissioners charged with deciding on Kim's release. The two
commissioners, Sean McSherry and Leo S. Levy, voted to parole Kim
after he had served the minimum of his 4-to-12-year sentence, the
first opportunity he was eligible for release. Hotaling also said
Grace Koh of the Community Affairs office asked him to call her
after a ruling on Kim's parole was made. She has not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Hotaling, 53, pleaded guilty last year to lying to a grand jury
to cover up his dealings with Travis and the two parole
commissioners. McSherry was convicted in August 1999 of lying to
the same grand jury, and Levy was charged last month with
misleading investigators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000719.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7371 &Cx1f; tad-z
b i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0720-1     07-19 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0720-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: writes thru to update with collapse of talks
 &HT;    CLINTON UNABLE TO PREVENT MIDEAST SUMMIT TALKS FROM COLLAPSE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Nine days of U.S.-led Mideast peace talks
collapsed in failure late Wednesday, as President Clinton was
unable to broker a resolution to the thorny territorial and
security disputes at the heart of half a century of
Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to cast the marathon effort as at least a partial
success, White House officials claimed that Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat had narrowed their
differences and set the stage for further negotiations at a time
yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat left the Camp David summit, however, at an
acrimonious impasse that threw a pall of uncertainty over a
seven-year Mideast peace process less than two months before the
leaders' self-imposed deadline _ Sept. 13 _ for settling their
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summit has come to an end without reaching an agreement,''
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said in a prepared statement
read to reporters just before 11 p.m. (ET) by National Security
Council spokesman P.J. Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to leave shortly after that by motorcade for the
hour-long drive from the cloud-shrouded presidential retreat in the
Catoctin Mountains in western Maryland to the White House, where he
was expected to make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last three hours, he's been shuttling back and forth
between the two leaders,'' Crowley said, ``but was unable to help
them make an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   As the talks faltered through a final tumultuous day of
brinksmanship, high drama and heated negotiations, both sides
blamed each other for not yielding on the intractable issue of the
future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat came into the talks vowing to reject any accord that
didn't guarantee Palestinian control over East Jerusalem, the site
of some of the holiest shrines in the Muslim, Christian and Jewish
worlds. It was captured by Israel in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, for his part, had pledged that an undivided Jerusalem
would remain the eternal capital of Israel, fully under Israeli
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was unable to bridge those differences, and largely upon
the shoals of that ancient dispute the talks apparently foundered.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome constituted a deep and potentially dangerous setback
for the region, where analysts have warned that factions of
Israelis and Palestinians violently opposed to the peace process
might try to foment unrest in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a moment of opportunity that will not re-occur,''
Barak had warned at the outset of the talks. ``It is accompanied by
major risks. And if, God forbid, we should fail, then the risks,
and not the opportunities, will come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Those failings were a bitter disappointment for Clinton, who has
invested seven years of diplomacy in the quest for a comprehensive
Mideast peace agreement and had sought an accord as a final grand
foreign policy achievement before he leaves office next January.
</P>
<P>
   With hope for reviving the process on Clinton's watch all but
extinguished, the president was left with a record of limited
accomplishments in the Mideast, despite the leverage of
unprecedented American influence and might in the aftermath of U.S.
victories in the Cold War and Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also been thwarted in his efforts to broker peace
between Israel and Syria, a second component of his objective of
closing the elusive circle of peace in a region that is the cradle
of Western civilization, home to three of the world's major
religions and the resevoir of two-thirds of the world's known crude
oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to go early Thursday morning to a
Washington area airport, where he was to board Air Force One for
the 15-hour flight to Okinawa, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   There, far from the crucible of Mideast summitry and even
farther from the flesh-and-blood issues the talks were designed to
address, Clinton was to assume the role of elder statesman at his
farewell session of the annual summit of leaders from the so-called
Group of Eight democratic powers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned at the outset of the talks that failure could
trigger renewed ``hostility and . . . perhaps even more violence,''
in the volatile Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   He had also cautioned that ``there was no guarantee of
success,'' at the Camp David summit, where he spent nine days and
nights, interrupted only by a day of activities in Baltimore and
Washington last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat and Barak left Camp David shortly after Clinton for long
flights to their home region, where both faced the political
challenges of balancing the costs of failure here against the
virtues, however those might be calculated, of not having given in
on issues fundamental to their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat walked away from a deal that would have given him a shot
at carving out an independent state of Palestine, though not,
apparently, on terms he regarded as essential to building a viable
state.
</P>
<P>
   Barak pushed off from a chance to forge a framework for Israeli
security, though he upheld his pledge to retain full Israeli
sovereignty over all of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
