<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7373 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-POLICE-PROFILING-SPI &LR;      07-19 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-PROFILING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN AMERICAN TRAFFIC CITATIONS DISPROPORTIONATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KERY MURAKAMI  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A disproportionate number of black drivers were given
traffic citations by Seattle police last year, the department
acknowledged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The acknowledgment before a City Council committee immediately
raised the prospect of racial profiling _ the practice of making
traffic stops based on the race of the driver.
</P>
<P>
   But Capt. John Diaz said the study does not explain why the
disparity exists, and called for an independent study.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said a group examining racial disparities in policing
analyzed 86,000 traffic citations written in the city last year.
Blacks were given 16.8 percent of the tickets, even though they are
estimated to make up only about 9 percent of all drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're past the point of saying `is there disproportionality?'
There clearly is,'' he told the council's Public Safety Committee.
``The tough question is `is there racism?'''
</P>
<P>
   The study was ordered by Interim Police Chief Herb Johnson in
March amid controversy over racial profiling. The review of
departmental data was done in conjunction with the Building Blocks
Coalition, a group chaired by King County Councilman Larry Gossett
that has a diverse membership that includes state Supreme Court
Justice Bobbe Bridge and Mothers for Police Accountability leader
Harriet Waldron.
</P>
<P>
   Though in some minds the numbers verify what the already
believed _ that minorities are pulled over because of their color _
Diaz said, ``Finding out the reasons why is going to be extremely
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he noted that about 20 percent of the citations
given to blacks were for driving with a suspended license.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's clearly an economic issue,'' Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz and others said police do not keep data that would clearly
explain if racism is a factor. For example, the department does not
track instances where officers make a traffic stop but do not write
a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Boruchowitz, president of the Washington Defenders
Association, which represents public defenders around the state,
said that if minorities are disproportionately stopped, without
being cited, it might indicate they are being pulled over as a
pretext.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Murray, a policing consultant who works with King
County, said a further study could examine if a disproportionate
number of tickets given to blacks are dismissed in court as lacking
merit. He said that could also suggest blacks are being pulled over
unnecessarily.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Jim Compton, chairman of the committee, said that as
a first step he will prepare a council resolution declaring racial
profiling ``reprehensible and intolerable.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he was quick to note the data do not
necessarily mean blacks are targeted because of race. Racial
profiling has become a nationwide issue in recent years. Just last
year, New Jersey State Police acknowledged that troopers took into
account the race of drivers in determining who to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle police have repeatedly said they do not practice racial
profiling, and Compton said that he's ``satisfied we have nothing
like that kind of racial profiling in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that ``racial disproportionality is a fact,''
whether it happens because of improper training, prejudice or other
factors. He urged further study to find out why.
</P>
<P>
   Compton said the council should urge the department to begin
collecting more data that would shed more light onto why the
disproportionality exists.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Peter Steinbrueck, like Diaz, said the city shouldn't
wait. He called for an independent study _ perhaps by the
University of Washington _ based on the information the city
already collects.
</P>
<P>
   James Kelly, executive director of the Urban League of
Metropolitan Seattle, also called for a more detailed study. He
said the city needs to find the reason for the disproportionality
to restore trust in police among people of color.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Eason Jr., president of the Seattle branch of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, echoed the call
for a more detailed study.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of racial profiling, Eason said, is that ``it doesn't
just stop with writing tickets and putting people in jail. ... It
goes into the court system, it gets into the judging, and from
there it goes into the prisons. That's why you have such a
disproportionate number of blacks in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if a person is just being stopped because of who they are,
that is going to manifest itself in more (minority) people being
sentenced, more people locked up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
