<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-19 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SOBE-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-19 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOBE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOBE NICHE IN DRINK MARKET KEEPS EXPANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since it first appeared on store shelves a mere four
years ago with its lineup of unusual flavors and a distinctive
double-lizard logo, Sobe has grown into a Godzilla of the
alternative-beverage business.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the company expects to post $250 million in sales, up
from $167 million last year and $67 million in 1998. Its products,
which it prefers to call ``healthy refreshment,'' have names like
Zen Blend, Tsunami and Strawberry Carrot Elixir, featuring
ingredients like bee pollen, ginkgo and something called kava kava.
It has established a customer base that ranges from middle-age
women to radicalized teen-agers, and its official alliances run the
gamut from Wal-Mart to Biker Sherlock, a demigod of the
extreme-sports racing circuit. Its marketing has been mostly grass
roots, with sampling from old buses and milk trucks, and
advertising has been mostly on the radio and in print.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, with giants like Coca-Cola taking an interest in
drinks beyond their traditional brands, pressure is growing to
develop a more sophisticated advertising campaign and, to go with
it, a more aggressive business plan. Many analysts say Sobe has to
push itself to the next level, to become less a phenomenon than a
permanent player in the highly competitive nonalcoholic beverage
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The company, founded by John Bello and Tom Schwalm in 1996, has
plans to put at least $12 million into advertising and sports
sponsorship this year and will introduce several products in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   It has also announced plans to sell a two-thirds stake to the
Boston-based investment firm of J .W. Childs Associates, a
development that many think will lead to an initial public offering
of the company before long. Sobe's archrival, Snapple Beverages, is
planning to go public later this year in an offering estimated at
$115 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sobe right now is at a critical point,'' said John D. Sicher,
publisher of Beverage Digest, an industry newsletter. ``It is on
its way to becoming a very successful brand. How fast and whether
that happens will be known in the next year or two.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Bello said his company had succeeded ``because
we have a product that consumers want,'' and added that he planned
to expand distribution in the coming year with a variety of
products and packaging.
</P>
<P>
   Among those is a sports drink, like Gatorade but with additives
like D-ribose, packaged in a reusable plastic sports bottle. There
are also plans to introduce a chocolate drink, named ``Love Bus
Brew,'' and a high-energy blend called Adrenaline. Child-friendly
packages, containing a vitamin-fortified juice drink tentatively
named Lizardade, are on the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   Distribution now includes mass merchandisers like Costco and
Wal-Mart. And this week was the official introduction in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're everywhere, but we are not everywhere we need to be,''
Bello said. ``We have had some difficulty penetrating the major
cities, like New York, Philadelphia and Washington, where there are
not a lot of distribution options.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobe's competitors, which include Snapple, Nantucket Nectars and
Mistic, tend to be handled by the same distribution network, he
added. ``Where do they put their focus?'' he said. ``That's the
game we are playing at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Many industry experts praise Sobe's development so far, saying
it has carved out a particular place in the crowded beverage aisle.
``The marketing, the use of the lizard, and the innovation have all
been first rate,'' Sicher said. ``I really think the U.S. consumer
is fascinated by a beverage that claims to do more than taste good
and refresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobe has so far avoided television ads because Bello thinks they
would be too defining for the brand. An ad aimed at teen-agers
could alienate other Sobe loyalists, or so the thinking goes. Too
much emphasis on the ingredients, and there might be a whole other
set of problems to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone mainstream with a product that has all these
nutrients and herbal additives and tastes great and has mystique,''
Bello said. ``The last thing we want to be is a medicine, or a
castor oil, or something that doesn't taste good.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, television ads may not be as effective for
Sobe as its fleet of buses and trucks and armored cars, all bearing
the lizard logo, have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to spend so much to cut through the clutter,'' he
said. ``Our sampling really works to create a buzz around the
product in local communities. We are trying to maintain the common
touch.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick going forward, particularly with a new majority
shareholder, will be to maintain all that. ``What John has done
with the positioning, with his grass-roots marketing, has been to
build a very dedicated following,'' said Michael Bellas, chief
executive of Beverage Marketing, a consulting company that tracks
beverage sales. ``He has to not lose that as he gets more broad
based.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the success of Sobe has not gone unnoticed by
Coca-Cola and PepsiCo, the giants of the soft-drink business, which
have declared their intentions to get involved in all kinds of
beverages. ``Coke is going to be looking at that category very
strongly,'' said Andrew Conway, a beverage stocks analyst for
Morgan Stanley. ``They will look at developing brands on their own
and at equity investment or ownership of existing brands.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
