<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBS DELIVER LIKE HEROES AS THE METS RALLY TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The New York Mets' bench is largely a collection of
players who were never part of the team's original plans.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Johnson played in Japan last year and signed a minor league
contract. Joe McEwing is the player the Mets took from St. Louis
when they had to find someplace to trade Jesse Orosco. The Mets
thought pitcher Bill Pulsipher could succeed; when he did not, they
traded him to Arizona for Lenny Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Harris has become a starter, but Johnson and McEwing have had
few opportunities to contribute. All played important roles
Wednesday night when the Mets beat the Montreal Expos, 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   McEwing singled in the tying and the go-ahead runs in the eighth
inning off Montreal closer Steve Kline, who had allowed singles to
Jay Payton and Benny Agbayani leading off the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani eluded the throw from center fielder Milton Bradley by
sliding to the right of home plate and tagging the plate with his
left hand.
</P>
<P>
   McEwing _ who scored the Mets' final run on a single by Derek
Bell _ was batting for Johnson, who had a pinch-hit single in the
seventh and scored on a triple by Harris. Harris' hit tied the
score, 2-2, and though Vladimir Guerrero doubled off Pat Mahomes in
the seventh to regain a one-run lead for Montreal, McEwing's
heroics gave the Mets the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets won their third game in a row after losing nine of 12.
Armando Benitez recorded his 22nd save, matching a career high set
in 1998 and equaled last year.
</P>
<P>
   Expos pitcher Tony Armas Jr. arrived at Olympic Stadium on
Wednesday night with a strained rotator cuff, and the Expos
announced that Felipe Lira would start in his place. But Lira is a
reliever.
</P>
<P>
   That forced the Expos into a spring training arrangement, with a
tag team of pitchers working a few innings each.
</P>
<P>
   Lira pitched three innings and allowed only a homer to Todd
Zeile leading off the second. Scott Strickland followed with two
scoreless innings. Anthony Telford came on for the sixth, but he
got into trouble in the seventh when Johnson had a pinch-hit single
with one out. Harris followed with a line-drive triple to the
left-center field gap, scoring Johnson to tie the game, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Glendon Rusch had gone 341/3 innings without giving up a walk
until he walked Jose Vidro and Vladimir Guerrero in the first
inning. The Expos used three singles to get their first run, in the
second, and a two-out walk to Lee Stevens led to their third-inning
run, when Stevens scored on Chris Widger's triple.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch worked six innings, allowing two runs, six hits and three
walks. It was the 12th time in 17 starts he has lasted at least six
innings and allowed no more than three earned runs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his final inning, he was aided by center fielder Payton, who
has impressed the Mets with the routes he takes, which maximize his
fine range. Lately, Payton has put every inch to use.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the ninth in a tie game at Toronto Monday,
Payton sprinted back and to his left to chase a drive by Homer
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   If the ball had dropped, the speedy Bush probably would have had
a triple.
</P>
<P>
   But Payton got there, cradling his glove over his shoulder as
Bush's fly dropped in for an out.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning Wednesday night, Payton was playing in on
Mike Mordecai in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The third baseman sent a liner over Payton's head, but Payton
hurried back and leaped to spear it, the ball peeking out of the
webbing of his glove.
</P>
</TEXT>
