A7388 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-19 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS COMPETING HAS RAFER SWEATING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SACRAMENTO _ Rafer Johnson lit the torch during the opening
ceremony at the 1984 Olympics, his ascent of the L.A. Coliseum
steps eyeballed by 100,000 mesmerized spectators and a worldwide
television audience.
</P>
<P>
   That was soothing _ a veritable deep-tissue massage on his
nerves _ next to this. Tonight, Johnson will sit in Cal State
Sacramento's Hornet Stadium and watch his son Josh try to qualify
for the 2000 U.S. Olympic Track and Field team in the javelin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not even close,'' Johnson said Wednesday. He fidgeted
fretfully in his seat. ``There's no comparison. It's way more
nerve-racking watching Josh compete.''
</P>
<P>
   The qualifying round of the event Monday was unadulterated agony
for the elder Johnson, a two-time Olympic medalist in the
decathlon. The Sherman Oaks resident is here to tell you there is
an event even more grueling than his 10-event specialty.
</P>
<P>
   It's called offspring gazing.
</P>
<P>
   Watching his son post the fifth-best throw in the first flight
and then waiting helplessly to see how many of the 19 throwers in
the second flight surpassed it gave Rafer Johnson a worse case of
cotton mouth than the pole vault ever did. His stomach was churning
more than it would down the stretch of the 1,500 meters, the
decathlon's fitting finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is much different than when I was competing,''
Johnson said. ``Then I could work out or find some way to burn that
nervous energy.''
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, all he can do is sit and pray. Oh, Johnson could
hold up sign boards with silly sayings like another proud papa,
Richard Williams. He could stand up and shout instructions to his
son, thus assuring the television cameras, which were largely
absent in his heyday, found him.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not Johnson's style. The way he sees it, he has had
his day on sport's center stage. It's his kids' turn now, and so he
sets up in the shadows and stalwartly supports his children (his
daughter Jenny Johnson Jordan is inching ever closer to securing a
U.S. Olympic berth with partner Annett Buckner-Davis in beach
volleyball).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was ``holding his breath'' Monday as the second
javelin qualifying flight wound down. Seven throwers surpassed
Josh's best throw of 226 feet, 9 inches, leaving him the 12th and
final qualifier for tonight's final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone came up to me afterward and said, `Your son just made
it by the skin of his teeth,' '' Johnson said. ``My reply was,
`Doesn't matter. All that matters is he made it.' Everybody starts
with a clean slate now. If he catches one, he can be right there.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke of his son's prospects, Johnson's chiseled features
softened; it was obvious that seeing the soft-spoken, statuesque
Johnson as a father is catching him in his most flattering light.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson shed his athletic past when his children were young,
boxing up and putting aside all his sporting mementos as though his
storied athletics career was a sweater that no longer fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt when we had children, it was their time,''
Johnson said. ``So from the time they were very young, we tried to
make the house theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was you could walk into the Johnson's Sherman Oaks home
and see Jenny's soccer trophies prominently displayed and Josh's
track ribbons but neither Rafer's silver medal from the 1956
Olympics nor his gold medal from the 1960 Summer Games in Rome.
Jenny and Josh Johnson would get to ogle their father's Olympic
hardware once a year like Fourth of July fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go to their schools on a yearly basis and bring my medals
and speak,'' Johnson said. ``They could hold them and rub them
then, along with their classmates. I think they learned a little
bit about what I'd done from the appearances I made and the talks I
gave.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a parent, of course, is an ongoing revelation. Johnson
experienced the pressure of competing for an Olympic gold medal as
the world-record holder in Melbourne, Australia, in 1956. He
suffered the disappointment of finishing second to teammate Milt
Campbell there and the thrill of winning four years later. And yet
nothing from his athletic past prepared him for his children's
sporting pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it goes well for them, I have great weeks,'' Johnson
said. ``When it doesn't go quite the way they want it, I'm bothered
just like they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Johnson was feted along with other former U.S.
Olympians at a lavish dinner at the Convention Center. Earlier in
the day, he admitted that even as he was enjoying the company of
former U.S. teammates and good friends such as Glenn Davis, his
mind would be with his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a flash of a thought, definitely,'' Johnson
said. ``The flash will come when I look around and think it would
be so great if Josh and Jenny could make an Olympic team and
someday have this same experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
