<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WELCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE WELCH MYSTIQUE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 20:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a magazine like Fortune or Forbes conducts a survey to
determine who is the most admired businessman of the year, decade
or even the century, Jack Welch of General Electric invariably
finishes at or near the top of the list. In his 20 years as GE's
chief executive officer, Welch has generated enormous wealth not
only for the company's stockholders but for hundreds of companies
that do business with GE. But is Welch worth $7.1 million as a
writer? That is what Time Warner Trade Publishing has agreed to
advance him for a book about his career, his business philosophy
and whatever else Welch chooses to write about when he retires next
year. It is the biggest advance in publishing history, exceeding
the up-front money paid to Colin Powell and the pope.
</P>
<P>
   Paying off a $7.1 million advance will require North American
hardcover sales of 1.6 million books. Only one or two titles a year
sell more than a million copies. A recent best seller by
Microsoft's Bill Gates sold about half a million. So this is a
gamble, but to some publishing executives, not nearly the gamble it
seems to be. The reason is that whatever Welch writes is going to
be perceived as the bible of American business.
</P>
<P>
   People are not going to buy it for its plot, character
development or sex appeal. Unlike Chrysler's Lee Iacocca, whose
story sold an astonishing 2.6 million hardcover books, Welch did
not rescue a large American company from bankruptcy, nor does he
have Iacocca's promotional flair. People will buy Welch's book
because it will be marketed as the definitive text of modern
American business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Does he have enough managerial wisdom to write such a bible?
Welch himself would say no. But a lot of people think he has all
the answers, and Time Warner is betting that that there are at
least 1.6 million people willing to pay good money to find out what
they are. There may be other factors at work here, too, including
America's growing obsession with business and the stock market. But
the real come-on is Welch and his mystique.
</P>
<P>
   That mystique is grounded in some hard realities. He took a
company with a market value slightly in excess of $12 billion and
turned it into a company worth $500 billion. Along the way he sold
off underperforming divisions and fired about 100,000 people, thus
earning himself the name ``Neutron Jack.'' He also introduced
simplicity to an excessively cumbersome system of checks and
balances. GE was famous for, even admired for its layers of sector
managers, department managers, unit managers and supervisors, all
of whom were thought to be essential to strategic planning and
quality control. Neutron Jack threw some ordnance at this system,
and when the dust cleared he had eliminated all but four of nine
hierarchical levels _ and, more important, made sure that the
bosses of each of GE's various businesses reported directly to him.
</P>
<P>
   Freed of fuzzy paternalism, the people who remained were
encouraged to think for themselves and question the corporate
culture, resulting not only in technological innovation but in huge
cost savings. At the same time, Welch was not at all shy about
borrowing good ideas when he came across them. Companies like
Hewlett-Packard and Toshiba gave him tips on productivity and
customer relations, and from Allied Signal and Motorola he lifted
an entire system of quality control.
</P>
<P>
   Welch is not without his critics. But in an era when CEO's seem
to hang around for only two or three years (see Coca-Cola, or
Mattel) before the directors decide they have made a mistake,
Welch's 20 years of virtually uninterrupted success inspires
curiosity _ enough, Time Warner hopes, to sell 1.6 million books.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
