</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SNOWMOBILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: INFERNAL SNOWMOBILES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont., Idaho, Wyo., Nev.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, July 20:
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday afternoon, the subject on the Senate floor turned
to snowmobiling in the national parks. ``You will see very little
variety in wildlife in Yellowstone in the wintertime,'' Sen. Conrad
Burns of Montana remarked. ``If you have been there, you know that
about the only thing you will see is bison. Let me tell you, you
don't bother them with a little old snowmobile.'' Sen. Larry Craig
of Idaho agreed. ``Somehow,'' he mused, ``the wildlife of
Yellowstone is going through some emotional problem as a result of
snowmobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns and Craig were not alone in making fun of the Interior
Department's sensible and long-overdue ban on snowmobiling in the
national parks, which was announced in April. And Sen. Craig
Thomas, R-Wyo., offered an amendment to the Interior Department
appropriations bill that would have torpedoed the administration's
ban by ordering up one of those endless ``studies'' of the
situation and by denying Interior the funds it needs to carry out
the ban. Thomas later withdrew his amendment. But the clear threat
was that it would resurface later this summer when the House and
Senate meet in conference to resolve their differing versions of
the appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   This is a typical example of the legislation-by-stealth employed
by anti-environmental senators. The senators who oppose an end to
snowmobiling in the parks know that the ban enjoys widespread
public support and is buttressed by careful, conscientious science.
Their only hope to scuttle the ban is to do so out of sight. The
Interior Department's rule is and has been open for public comment.
That is a far more democratic procedure than the device of sneaking
a piece of substantive legislation into an appropriations bill
without hearings, which is what the Westerners clearly intend to
do.
</P>
<P>
   As for the proposed ``study,'' the issue has already been fully
investigated by the Air Resources Division of the National Park
Service, which concluded that snowmobiles create a
disproportionately large amount of atmospheric pollution in
Yellowstone. But there are other compelling reasons to ban
snowmobiles. Their numbers, their noise and their ability to
disrupt wildlife contradict the National Park Service's mandate to
maintain, unimpaired, the natural resources of the parks.
</P>
<P>
   One lone Westerner, Sen. Harry Reid of Nevada, made yet another
telling argument. He pointed out that of the 130,000 miles of
designated snowmobile trails in the United States, only 600 are in
national parks. That leaves 129,400 miles for the machines. That
seems sufficient.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
